</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SILAS REFUSES VAN GUNDY'S HANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The young man's name is Eddie Robinson, out of Flint,
Mich., and off a trail of small-college basketball outposts not
likely to appear on Dick Vitale's itinerary any time soon. He is 6
feet 8 inches, with a 43-inch vertical leap and a jump shot that
belies the general state of bricklaying in the modern game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A special talent,'' Paul Silas said on Monday, leaving a
morning rehearsal for Monday night's 112-109 overtime loss at
Madison Square Garden to the Knicks. ``But he's just a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie raw, in other words, but another potential superstar for
Jeff Van Gundy to marvel over during his weekly homage to
Charlotte's budding dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets didn't make the playoffs last spring but Van Gundy,
coach of the defending Eastern Conference champs, has been touting
Silas' team as the most talented in the East. Silas, whose Hornets
had been living up to Van Gundy's expectations until their
eight-game winning streak was snapped on Monday night, has not been
flattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to talk to him about it,'' Silas said with
the same steeliness that led him to more than 12,000 career
rebounds. ``What Jeff's been saying is a whole lot of. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   He edited himself, letting us fill in the blank.
</P>
<P>
   What Silas was saying was that coaching a National Basketball
Association team is difficult enough without having a peer publicly
inflate the quality of a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he thinks if we do well, it'll make people think that's
the way it was supposed to be,'' Silas said. ``Jeff keeps talking
about all our talent, but I could ask him, would he trade a bunch
of his players for mine? Would he trade Houston, Sprewell and Camby
for a bunch of my guys?''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not after Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston _ finally
paired in the backcourt _ put 61 points on the board, Marcus
Camby's defense helped shut down the lane and the Knicks recovered
from 17.9 percent first-quarter shooting with a 57-38 domination of
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to use Paul's team for motivational
purposes,'' Van Gundy said afterward. ``I have too much respect for
him. When I first came in the league, he looked out for me. I've
only been saying that I believe he has a good club and he's done a
great job.''
</P>
<P>
   The underlying issue here is that six years after Van Gundy
joined the organization in 1989, as a walk-on with no pro
experience, he became head coach. One of sport's most fierce and
respected players, Silas' first head coaching job was with the old
San Diego Clippers, as inept a franchise as Los Angeles' new
Clippers. His three-year run ended in 1983. For 16 years, he sat as
an assistant on numerous NBA benches, including New York's, and
watched other men pass him by for the league's choice jobs.
</P>
<P>
   From Pat Riley to Van Gundy, Rick Adelman to Mike Dunleavy, Paul
Westphal to Danny Ainge. A white player _ Scott Skiles last week in
Phoenix _ can dream of building his reputation with first-class
talent. A black player _ Lionel Hollins last week in Vancouver _
can hope to be named interim coach of a desperate team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't changed much,'' Silas said. ``You look at Lionel up
in Vancouver. Hopefully, he'll do better than the other guy but
what are the chances?''
</P>
<P>
   Silas, at 56, replaced Dave Cowens last season, before the
slumping Hornets traded for Elden Campbell and Eddie Jones. Under
Silas, they won 22 of 35. Only then did he have the interim collar
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Perception of coaches is part of an NBA mythology that is old as
Red Auerbach. When Riley won big with the 1980s Lakers, he was
hailed as a well-groomed genius. Over with the Celtics, K.C. Jones
was credited for sitting back and letting Larry Bird run the show.
It's hard to believe that Van Gundy would try to set Silas, or
intentionally use him as a motivational prop. But, given the way
things work and the way Silas waited, it is understandable why he'd
be sensitive to the hint of the old stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I have known each other long enough to not even go
there,'' Silas said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Van Gundy, Silas doesn't go to work in paradise. The
Hornets' owner, George Shinn, was recently involved in a sordid
public fiasco. Van Gundy, meanwhile, has a pretty good idea what
it's like to coach Anthony Mason. Charlotte's other starting
forward is the always endearing Derrick Coleman, who strolled into
Monday's shoot-around 30 minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I said, they are the most talented team in the
East,'' an unsmiling Silas said after the game. Van Gundy may not
want to argue this point anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
