<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-PIPPEN-ROCKETS-HN     12-21 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PIPPEN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He's back.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that has been woefully short on highlights,
tonight's game has likely been circled in red on many a Rockets
fan's calendar.
</P>
<P>
   That's because former Rocket (for however brief a period)
Scottie Pippen returns to town with his new team, the Portland
Trail Blazers, who meet the Rockets tonight at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's exit from Houston has been pretty well-documented _ a
calculated barrage of insults directed at teammate Charles Barkley
designed to hasten Pippen's departure. His intended landing spot
was Los Angeles, where Pippen had hoped to be reunited with former
Bulls coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pippen wound up in Portland, where the Blazers were
immediately dubbed the NBA's next juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   But in an apparent case of ``that was then, this is now,''
Pippen now regrets how he left town. He admits that he had a
personality conflict with Barkley, but
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a little bit of everything,'' Pippen said of
his disagreements with Barkley. ``We didn't handle things _ and
maybe myself more than anybody _ the way we should have. We
probably should have spoken person-to-person and handled it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally like Charles, and I enjoyed being around him.
He's a character. He's like being with a comedian or something. But
he's a good-hearted person. I hate that things got ticked off like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And suffice it to say that things got very ``ticked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way he left town, the Pippen story has taken on
the proportions of a Shakespearean tragedy. Or at least a soap
opera.
</P>
<P>
   But it's probably more like the Dr. Seuss tale How the Grinch
Stole Christmas. And all the Hous here in Hou-ville are still
crying boohoo over the departure of Pippen, who was dealt to
Portland in the offeseason for six players, among whom were keepers
like Carlos Rogers and Kelvin Cato.
</P>
<P>
   And very much like the Grinch, many Rockets fans studied
Pippen's play and figured that his heart was two sizes too small.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though Pippen's heart has grown in the past couple
of months, though. Perhaps seeing Barkley's career end with a torn
quadriceps tendon has mellowed Pippen somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said that whatever his disagreements with Barkley,
watching him being carried off the court in Philadelphia was no way
for such a great career to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're human, and things like that can be very emotional, not
being able to walk away from the game,'' Pippen said. ``Charles was
looking forward to playing this season. No matter how you look at
it, he was looking forward to going around and being taunted (by
the fans) _ all those things he's really going to miss. People hate
him so much that everybody loves (to taunt) him. Everybody loves to
hear what he has to say, get a laugh from him or get him talking
about whatever. It would be tough for any athlete to go that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wanted to walk away from the game (on his own
terms). I think he's been put in a tough situation right now where
he has to go out and rehab and all those things, knowing that he's
not coming back to the game, which sort of brings the challenge
down a little bit for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really have to fight to bring himself back to where
he's been competitive, like he has his whole life. So I'm sure it's
pretty tough for him. You hate to see that happen to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   What Houstonians hate is that Pippen so nicely landed on his
feet in Portland. The Los Angeles Clippers would have been nice. Or
Vancouver. Chicago would have been perfect, even though there was
no way that was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   And if the reaction last Saturday is any indication, the
Rockets' marketing people missed out on a great opportunity for a
corporate tie-in by not getting the folks at Sucrets to sponsor
some sort of giveaway tonight. Saturday's announcement of the
Rockets' next home game, against the Trail Blazers, drew a
protracted round of boos from the 15,000-plus who attended that
game.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be worse tonight, and Pippen is expecting just
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look forward to it,'' Pippen said. ``That's just part of
the game. It's going to be an incentive for me to just go out and
do the things that I know I can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the game. It always has been, and it always
will be part of the game. The only game they don't allow that in is
golf. So you have to be able to deal with the fans and just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said he doesn't expect a reception similar to what Steve
Francis received in Vancouver, where fans hurled tomatoes, lemons
and eggs at the rookie point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they need to be throwing anything on the
court,'' Pippen said. ``If it's that personal, then they need to
come down on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have already played the Blazers once, losing in
overtime at the Rose Garden (91-88 on Nov. 26), but Pippen doesn't
think that, or the fact Barkley and Olajuwon will be out, takes the
edge off tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going out there and competing against Charles and
Hakeem anyway,'' Pippen said. ``It's about me beating the Rockets.
We still feel like we're a better team. I don't think that takes
any edge off it. I think they still feel like they should have won
the game when they came to our building, so it's going to make
(today's) game that much tougher for us because they're going to
come out with the mindset that they can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Which seems to be a pretty prevalent sentiment these days when
the Blazers take the floor. After starting the season 13-2, the
Blazers have since gone 5-5 and have won three of those games by a
total of 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done some great things, but we've had some slippage here
of late and not played very consistently,'' Pippen said. ``But our
ballclub is still learning each other, and we're still trying to
better ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night that we go out on the court, we're capable of
beating some people. But we haven't hit that dominance that we need
to be the good team that people are saying that we are. It hasn't
come together yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither have he and Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen admits he hasn't contacted Barkley since the
career-ending injury, and isn't sure if such a move is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Pippen said. ``I'm sure we'll run across each
other somewhere in life. Maybe I'll get invited to his retirement
party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
