<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA </SLUG>
 -KAN  
 Woman who used `Viagra defense' sentenced in man's death   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At her sentencing Monday, Mary Frost
recounted for a Jackson County Circuit Court judge the night in
June 1998 that she says her 77-year-old housemate went from asking
for sex to trying to rape her.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Fingers' use of Viagra had made him increasingly
aggressive, her defense attorney had argued in trial, and Frost was
defending herself when she killed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I protected myself,'' Frost, 33, told the judge Monday after
spending about 20 minutes explaining how Fingers chased her
throughout the house during their struggle. ``This man wouldn't be
dead if he hadn't done this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, Judge Jay A. Daugherty sentenced Frost to 18
years in prison, less than the 20 years prosecutors had requested
but more than the 10 to 13 years her attorney had sought.
</P>
<P>
   In October a jury convicted Frost of second-degree murder and
armed criminal action after deciding that, even if Frost's story
was true, she could have escaped without stabbing Fingers to death.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Kate Mahoney argued that Frost should receive a long
sentence because her criminal record showed a pattern of
increasingly violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said Frost pleaded guilty to second-degree assault in
1996. When Fingers was killed, Frost was on probation stemming from
an aggravated assault charge in a February 1998 stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   While on probation, Frost was supposed to attend anger control
classes and maintain steady employment. She did neither.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think, as we've seen here today,'' Mahoney concluded,
``she shows no remorse for her actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost's attorney argued that the jury was not allowed to hear
about her background.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jarrett Johnson said a family member raped Frost
repeatedly when Frost was a child. She also was the victim of a
random abduction and rape and domestic abuse, he said.
Nevertheless, Frost was able to get a technical degree in the
nursing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``She tried to become a productive member of society,'' Johnson
said. ``I think Mary Frost is a person who has repeatedly found
herself in a situation where she is a victim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
