<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K17-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Don't blame every techno-glitch on Y2K, White House Y2K czar says (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ For about 12 hours, U.S. Army Maj. Eric Van
Vliet was a computer-glitch multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics instructor at Fort Leavenworth's Army Command and
General Staff College, in Kansas, moved $18,950 into a Charles
Schwab Roth IRA account and found that his investment had
done...well, pretty darn good.
</P>
<P>
   When Van Vliet received the Dec. 8 letter confirming the new
account, his ``credit cash balance'' was $84,281,186.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck, major. A clerical mistake caused a computer
glitch. Your $18,950 transfer was worth...well, about $18,950.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a month until 2000, Van Vliet assumed it was a
Y2K problem. It wasn't. And that's the point.
</P>
<P>
   For those dealing with technology, stuff just happens, says John
Koskinen, the White House's Y2K czar. And stuff will happen, as
usual, this New Year's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So don't assume every techno-glitch is sparked by Y2K, Koskinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glitches at electric generating plants knock out power to an
average American home for about 13 hours every year _ in addition
to longer outages every year caused by major storms.
</P>
<P>
   A railroad accident happens somewhere in the United States every
5 hours on a typical New Year's Day. On average, low-level
emergencies involving nuclear power plants happen more than twice a
day between Dec. 28 and Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   And about 8 percent to 10 percent of all ATM transactions fail
the first time _ most often because people hit a wrong key when
typing in a pass code or try to take out more money than they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day things go wrong, and nobody pays much attention to
them, nobody thinks twice about it,'' Koskinen said in a news
release. ``But any of those things that happen on Jan. 1st will
immediately be presumed to be the indication of a Y2K problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In short? Sure, have a little extra food, cash and even water on
hand Jan. 1. But don't worry. Go party.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen's comments last week were the latest attempt by the
Clinton administration to make sure undue panic does not cause more
problems than Y2K itself.
</P>
<P>
   A ``fact sheet'' put together by Koskinen's office shows how a
variety of problems go unnoticed by consumers every day:
</P>
<P>
   - On a bad day, 1 percent of the nation's traffic signals
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   - More than 400 commercial flights are delayed by 15 minutes or
more on a normal New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   - An average, large 911 emergency system experiences one
disruption every week.
</P>
<P>
   As for Van Vliet, well, he knew when he received the letter that
he was not a multimillionaire. But it makes for a good tale.
</P>
<P>
   Van Vliet had moved some Roth IRA funds from another brokerage
to Schwab. The Dec. 8 letter confirming the transaction was
straightforward enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transfer...to your Charles Schwab account is now
complete....Below is a listing of the assets that have been
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit cash balance...$84,281,186.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for moving your assets to Charles Schwab,'' the
letter concluded.
</P>
<P>
   A responsible investor, Van Vliet called Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was kind of speechless. He kind of chuckled and said,
`Just don't do anything until we call you back,' '' Van Vliet said.
``They basically said they had some problems with automation.''
</P>
<P>
   The $84 million mistake was all on paper. A Schwab spokesman
said the money was never really in Van Vliet's account. It was an
error in a letter that did not affect the account.
</P>
<P>
   How does Van Vliet feel about Schwab?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely pleased with my initial balance,'' Van Vliet
said. ``The gains over that period were like an Internet IPO,'' he
said, referring to the hot-market dot-com stocks that skyrocket
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is a prelude, I'm extremely excited about Y2K,'' Van
Vliet said. ``I can't wait for the beginning of the new year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
