<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKEEFFE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION SHOWS KEMPER MUSEUM'S WATERCOLORS NOT O'KEEFFE'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE THORSON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A collection of watercolors bought for $5
million by Kansas City banker and philanthropist R. Crosby Kemper
Jr. are not the work of noted American artist Georgia O'Keeffe.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper purchased 24 watercolors thought to be early works by
O'Keeffe in 1993. In 1994, he presided over a much-publicized
showing of the paintings as an inaugural exhibit at the Kemper
Museum of Contemporary Art, which he founded and presented with the
watercolors as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit featured 28 watercolors in all, including four
valued at $500,000 that were a gift to the museum from Gerald
Peters, the well-known New York art dealer who sold the 24 works to
Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Kemper learned that the paintings, known as ``The
Canyon Suite'' and most recently shown at the museum in 1997, are
not the work of O'Keeffe.
</P>
<P>
   In an all-day meeting last Wednesday with Kemper Museum
officials, experts from the National Gallery of Art shared
information that caused them to conclude that the ``Canyon Suite''
watercolors are not authentic. The age of the paper on which the
works were painted was not consistent with the 1916-18 dates
attributed to the watercolors; moreover, the types of paper were
different from those O'Keeffe normally used.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about the works' authenticity have swirled since early
November, when it became known that they were among 210 works on
paper omitted from a new scholarly catalog of the artist's complete
works written by Barbara Buhler Lynes.
</P>
<P>
   Lynes, an O'Keeffe scholar, was one of the experts who traveled
to the Kemper Museum last week. Joining her were Ruth Fine, curator
at the National Gallery; Judith Walsh, the National Gallery's
senior paper conservator; and Elizabeth Glassman of the O'Keeffe
Foundation. They presented their findings to Kemper at a meeting
also attended by the Kemper Museum's director, Dan Keegan, whom
Kemper has designated as his spokesman in ``The Canyon Suite''
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance were the museum's deputy director, Walter
Dietrich, and a conservator, Mark Stevenson, whom the museum hired
to look into the matter when doubts first surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Keegan said that the museum has accepted the experts'
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've concluded that these works are not authentic, '' Keegan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Ziska, National Gallery press officer, said Monday her
museum would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the works belong to the Kemper, they're the ones making
the statements,'' Ziska said. ``We provided the information to them
and we're leaving it in their hands to discuss specifics about the
works of art.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kemper bought the works from Peters, he was told that they
were created by O'Keeffe from 1916 to 1918, while she was living in
Canyon, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Research for the scholarly catalog, called a catalogue raisonne,
showed that some of the papers dated from the 1930s and some as
late as the 1960s, which threw into question just when the works
were made.
</P>
<P>
   The later dating of the papers also raised doubts about the
works' provenance, the chain of possession after they left
O'Keeffe's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently it was thought she had given the works to her
friend and lover, Ted Reid, in 1918 and that Reid held onto them
until 1975, when he gave them to a friend. The friend, Emilio
Caballero, reportedly accepted the gift in a packet, not knowing
what it contained.
</P>
<P>
   Caballero supposedly forgot about the packet until 1987, when he
rediscovered the works and gave them to his son, who was married to
Reid's granddaughter, Terry Lee Caballero. After O'Keeffe's
assistant, Juan Hamilton, authenticated the rediscovered
watercolors, the couple sold them to Gerald Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown at the time, Keegan said, was that O'Keeffe did not use
a wide variety of papers, a fact which emerged during research for
the catalogue raisonne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they realized this,'' Keegan said, ``they understood they
had a really good baseline to judge all of O'Keeffe's works on
paper and to judge their authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper used in the ``Canyon Suite'' watercolors was compared
by researchers with vintage sample books from paper manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Facts about the age and types of paper were unknown in 1993 when
Kemper bought ``The Canyon Suite,'' Keegan stressed. In fact,
Kemper did so partly at the urging of some of the very experts who
have declared the works unauthentic.
</P>
<P>
   After the works surfaced in the late 1980s, Ruth Fine and
National Gallery directors J. Carter Brown and Rusty Powell
declared them a ``national treasure'' and urged Kemper to buy them
and donate them to the National Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing years the works were accepted by leading O'Keeffe
scholars. Now, Keegan said, the ``five million dollar question'' is
whether the watercolors were deliberately forged or were mistakenly
attributed to the artist.
</P>
<P>
   When questions about the watercolors surfaced in November,
Gerald Peters promised he would buy them back, but he could not be
reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expecting a full refund,'' Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum plans to use the refunded money to create a $5
million permanent collection endowment for the purchase of new art.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan expects the endowment to generate $300,000 to $400,000
per year for the purchase of art created within the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   He is glad, he said, to have closure on ``The Canyon Suite''
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the outcome we would have hoped for,'' he said, ``but
one we were prepared for, after having done our own research.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
