 2nd TAKE-KAN  
 Hot market for new technology stocks provides benefits for KC  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new generation of wealth in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1990s, the hot market for new technology stocks
has created vast fortunes for entrepreneurs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A few Kansas Citians jumped on that golden road this year and
have brought some of the nation's technology riches to town.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Fraser, chairman of National Information Consortium
Inc., for example, has seen his personal stake in the Internet
company grow in value from $364.8 million to $976.6 million in just
five months.
</P>
<P>
   National Information Consortium, based in Overland Park, helps
state and local governments set up Internet pages to provide
services to businesses and citizens.
</P>
<P>
   National Information Consortium is one of three local companies
that offer a peek at how going public can have a profound effect on
the operations of a company and on the finances of the people who
work there.
</P>
<P>
   Management Network Group Inc., also based in Overland Park, has
been another star performer in the stock market. The company sold
stock to the public in late November, and already the stock's price
is 74 percent higher than the offering price.
</P>
<P>
   That performance has boosted the net worth of Chief Executive
Richard Nespola's stock from $83.2 million to $144.3 million in
less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Not every technology company is a way for executives to get rich
quick, especially biotechnology companies, where ``overnight
successes'' can take years to develop. But when a biotech company's
time comes, as it apparently has for Avax Technologies Inc. of
Kansas City, the results are similarly sweet.
</P>
<P>
   At Avax, which develops cancer-treatment therapies, Jeffrey
Jonas has 372,205 shares. In December 1998, those shares were worth
$837,461. Last week, the stock was worth $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at National Information Consortium, Avax Technologies
and Management Network Group described what it's like to manage
companies with so many people knocking at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a vice president at Upjohn, it would be unthinkable to take
calls from the public,'' said Jonas, who is Avax's president and
chief executive officer and who previously worked at the
pharmaceutical giant.
</P>
<P>
   At Avax, Jonas has taken hundreds of calls from shareholders who
want to know more about the company.
</P>
<P>
   For Avax, going public has been about raising awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to develop a treatment for cancer and you can't
open a Web site and sell ads to make money,'' Jonas said.
``Although I'd be delighted if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Avax has been a public company for three years, and its stock
has recently regained ground it had lost since the original public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   When a biotechnology company offers its stock in an initial
public offering, the company usually still has a long road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a company like ours, an IPO is really a tool,'' Jonas
said. ``I think most people have the idea that you issue stock, you
get rich.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jonas, his stock holdings in Avax are relatively modest
compared with executives at some other companies. Jonas owns about
2.26 percent of the company's stock, according to filings with
federal securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of going public is to raise awareness about the
company's research, to give the company credibility with its
research partners and to give Avax a currency it can use to buy
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 29, the company announced results that its vaccine,
called M-Vax, had a high long-term success rate.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, BusinessWeek noted that Avax would start
marketing its vaccine in Australia early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price jumped from 2 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company has yet to turn a profit, executives are
still in the early stages of building the company through research
and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be conscious of the fact that you are there to
increase the value of the company,'' Jonas said. ``And you can't do
that by watching the stock go up and down every day.''
 &LR; brk:Management Network Group
</P>
<P>
   Watching that stock price can be a gratifying distraction,
conceded Nespola.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not all it's hyped up to be,'' he added. ``You think,
`Wow.' But you know what? It's all paper.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be money in the bank, but people still notice.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Nespola's paper _ his stock in Management Network
Group _ was worth as much as $171.8 million when the stock hit a
per-share peak of 35. The company, which provides management
consulting to telecommunications companies, went public less than a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nespola said his 22-year-old son was shopping at Hall's
department store when a clerk cornered him with this greeting:
``That's a great IPO your dad had. You must be able to get anything
you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not anything.
</P>
<P>
   Nespola, a former Sprint Corp. executive, said he hasn't traded
in his car and he hasn't noticed any co-workers showing up to the
office in fancier clothes.
</P>
<P>
   But Nespola is proud that the stock offering has spread the
wealth throughout the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many consultants have stock options, so I am sharing the
equity upside with the people who work for the company,'' Nespola
said. ``In this particular case, a full 10 percent of the company
is dedicated to the employees.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
