<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9 IN TEXAS FAMILY KILLED IN TRAFFIC ACCIDENT IN MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ and MARISA TAYLOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six children and three adults from the same Fort Worth family
were killed in a traffic accident last weekend while traveling to
visit family in Mexico for the Christmas holidays, Mexican
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A 10th relative survived the accident, which Mexican police said
was caused by a truck driver who was speeding. The truck driver
fled after the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The family members, with the last names Carvajal and Delgadillo,
ranged in age from 1 to 30 and had been living in Fort Worth for at
least two years, friends said. They lived in three different homes
in south Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were good people and we will remember them that way,''
relative Patricia Delgadillo said Monday night at a rosary inside
one of the homes.
</P>
<P>
   The dead children were identified as Javier Delgadillo, 1;
Cecilia Delgadillo, 4; Cindy Delgadillo, 6; Maria Carvajal, 11;
Silvano Carvajal, 13; and Eva Carvajal, 16. Also killed were Noel
Carvajal, 21; Sofia Carvajal, 30; and Filiberta Carvajal
Delgadillo, 26. All of the Carvajals were siblings.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as a chilly December wind blew outside, about 40
people gathered inside a small, sparsely decorated house on
Laughton Street, home to five of the dead. They propped photographs
of some of the victims on a small wooden coffee table and burned
five religious candles in a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, school teachers and the family priest, the Rev. Francis
X. Fernandez, pastor of Immaculate Heart of Mary Church, described
the family as respectful, hard-working and reserved.
</P>
<P>
   The family was originally from a town in the state of Zacatecas,
in northern Mexico, and were making the 10-hour trip from Fort
Worth to share the holidays with relatives. Jose Carvajal, 24, had
driven a Chevrolet Suburban from Zacatecas to Fort Worth to pick
them up. He survived the crash with a broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   The Suburban was hit by a truck owned by a steel mill as it
traveled on Highway 54 about six miles north of Concepcion del Oro,
said Fernando Lugo Martinez, an investigator with the district
attorney's office in Zacatecas.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the accident was reported at 5:30 a.m. Sunday, but
family members in Fort Worth said it occurred about 10 a.m.
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, who reportedly works in Monclova, Coahuila,
could face manslaughter charges, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a horrible tragedy,'' said Gloria Sandoval, a
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths have devastated family and friends in Fort Worth, and
last night the mourners remembered the victims in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offer this rosary in honor of the Carvajal and Delgadillo
families,'' said Carmen Avila as she clasped a turquoise-colored
string of rosary beads.
</P>
<P>
   Children fussed in their mothers' arms, and many kneeled
somberly on the hard wooden floor, heads bowed, while Avila
murmured traditional Roman Catholic prayers. After the hourlong
prayer session ended, teary-eyed mourners hugged one another,
shaking their heads in apparent disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Next-door neighbor Rosa Murguia said the Carvajal family kept to
themselves. But Murguia said she always knew when they were home,
because the music of Juan Gabriel, a Mexican singer, would blare
from the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I thought about telling them to lower the music,''
Murguia recalled in Spanish. ``Now I'm glad I never told them
anything. I would feel too guilty now.''
</P>
<P>
   Murguia said the loss of nine people in one family is too
devastating to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel awful when you lose one or two,'' she said. ``But
nine? I can't even imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Murguia's 9-year-old son, Osvaldo, said the news came as a shock
to him because he used to play Pokemon with Silvano Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad,'' Osvaldo said quietly. ``I was sad when I heard
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Moreno, who was Cecilia's prekindergarten teacher at
Worth Heights Elementary, said that on Friday, the day the family
left, Cecilia was ``so excited because they were going to Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very quiet. But when something would interest her, she
would just light up,'' Moreno said. ``She couldn't wait for me to
open the present she brought me. It was a really nice address book
with a pen and an angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave her a big hug and said thank you,'' Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia was supposed to be an angel in the school play, but she
got sick and had to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Filiberta Delgadillo would bring Javier with her to eat lunch
regularly with Cecilia at school.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Fuentes, a teacher at Worth Heights, said Maria was a quiet
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an excellent student, very hard worker. She had a lot
of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Irma Flores-Brothers, the principal of Richard J. Wilson
Elementary, said Cindy Delgadillo was a bright first-grader who had
just been referred to the gifted and talented program. She was in
bilingual classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our school is such a close-knit community. We'll do everything
we can for that family,'' Flores-Brothers said.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the victims were turned over to relatives in
Mexico Monday, officials said. Family members said a burial service
is planned for Tuesday in the Mexican state of Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Michelle Melendez contributed to this report.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
