<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET A WEARY WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tired legs met hyper bodies Monday night, and the
results were predictably chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' fourth game in their fourth city in five nights _
against a frantic, full-court Boston Celtics attack _ looked a lot
like a coach's classroom videotape, the one with all the oddball
mishaps that make players cover their eyes on second viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Loopy inbounds passes were picked off. Inbounds passers were
called for five-second violations. Simple drives up the court
became adventures in ballhandling as the Celtics applied their
collegiate full-court pressure and drove the weary Lakers to the
edge of insanity. And to a season-high 24 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   And to the edge of a streak-stopping loss. But only to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers pulled back, relaxed and calmly pushed through
their own fatigue and the Celtics' frenzy to pull out a 99-90
victory at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Four games in five nights became four wins and no losses. And no
doubt the Lakers will be a holly, jolly bunch on the flight back to
Los Angeles this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a good feeling,'' Derek Fisher said after the
Lakers extended their winning streak to seven by coming back from a
13-point second-half deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much we should read into it. We've been in
these situations before... but I think the only other time was in
Sacramento, and we failed to come back and get that one. To close a
trip out in this fashion, with a win, really feels good. We felt
like this would be a test road trip, and we finished up 4-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The last piece fell into place behind an impressive tag-team
effort from Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, who played 46 and 45
minutes respectively, defying any notion of road-trip fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal powered through the Celtics' frontcourt for 34 points and
20 rebounds, his performance marred only by a season-high eight
turnovers. Bryant skipped and glided to 27 points, four rebounds,
four assists and four steals.
</P>
<P>
   With Glen Rice (nine points) held back by early fouls and
limited minutes (23), Fisher provided a lift off the bench with 13
points.
</P>
<P>
   It was another measure of the Lakers' newfound resilience and
confidence as they won for the 14th time in 15 games and improved
their league-best record to 22-5.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Celtics' press _ which O'Neal derided as ``(coach) Rick
Pitino's `Outbreak' monkey defense'' _ made the Lakers ever appear
road-weary. Otherwise, they played sharply, shooting 52.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were more mentally tired than physically tired,''
coach Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Celtics cashed in the turnovers for 26 easy points
and could have had much more.
</P>
<P>
   Boston scored 12 unanswered points to open the second half and
took a 55-44 lead _ ``We got completely out of whack there for
about two minutes,'' Jackson said. Then the Lakers, with Fisher and
Rick Fox subbing for Ron Harper and Rice, settled down and went on
an 11-0 run, leaving them down by two to start the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Bryant did the rest, combining for 21 points on
7-of-10 shooting in the final period, while Celtics stars Antoine
Walker (24 points), Kenny Anderson (21 points) and Adrian Griffin
all fouled out trying to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had called this trip, the Lakers' longest of the season
so far, a big test. He's still reserving a final grade after
watching his team dispatch with Atlanta, Minnesota, Toronto and
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be pleased with what we've done,'' he said. ``We
didn't beat the top teams in the East, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the defending champion San Antonio Spurs await
the Lakers on Christmas night, no one was overly impressed with
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we're a good basketball team,'' Fisher said,
``but I think there's still some mystery, even amongst ourselves,
as far as how good we can be. I believe that's a good thing,
because we really don't know. So each night we just have to go out
there and try to do it, and tonight was an example of that. Since
we really still don't know exactly who we are, we just continue to
just play, fight and try and win. And we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
