<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO </SLUG>
 2ND TAKE-KAN  
 Hot market for new technology stocks provides benefits for KC  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That means about 90 people share about $80 million worth of the
company as of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of smiles on people's faces,'' Nespola said.
``I've had a few employees say, `Other people may not tell you
this, but I take out my calculator at night and add up the value of
my stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Nespola said he doesn't focus on the day-to-day value of his
holdings. In fact, on the first day of trading, he was on a plane
and didn't check the opening performance until he was on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was elated at the positive market response,'' Nespola said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the hard work begins. Management Network is in a competitive
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I don't see the stock offering as an end,'' Nespola
said. ``I think my job has just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   Management Network Group raised about $78 million in its stock
offering, giving it money to pay off debt, expand overseas and
establish a Web site.  &LR; brk:National Information Consortium
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that make this work are companies that are focused
on making a great company, not watching the daily movements of the
stock,'' said James Dodd, chief executive of National Information
Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   For National Information Consortium, that means expanding a
niche that has enormous growth potential. NIC designs and operates
Web pages for state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are a convenience for citizens and government
officials. The Web pages aim to improve government efficiency and
reduce the hassle for citizens trying to renew licenses, apply for
permits or obtain other government services.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow focus of the company was a huge benefit when the
company went on the road to raise money through an initial stock
offering, Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an Internet company that was 9 years old,'' Dodd said.
``That gets you down to about 5 percent of the Internet companies
out there. And we had a management team that was all over 40 years
old. Now you're down to 1 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   When the NIC team would stop at a potential investor's office,
it wasn't unusual to see ``seven limos waiting in front of the
building and several groups of three in the office lobby, all
waiting'' their turn.
</P>
<P>
   NIC executives could explain, simply, that their company
provides Internet services for eight states, including Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The hard work and the focus paid off.
</P>
<P>
   When NIC went public in July, it offered 13 million shares at
$12 apiece. Last Friday, the stock was 32. The stock hit a peak of
44 earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   That ride has created a fortune for Fraser, the company's
founder. Forbes ASAP magazine pegged Fraser's wealth at $526.2
million, ranking him 53rd on a list of technology's 100 richest
people.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees also are basking in the stock's glow.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, who left a 15-year career at Sprint to join NIC, holds
shares that are now worth $9.4 million, up from $3.5 million in
July. He also received options in December 1998 that would be worth
in excess of $40 million based on Friday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said the experience of taking a company public has been
exhilarating, but the celebration doesn't end with a successful
sale of stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great because we've built a great company and the
market was ripe for us,'' Dodd said. ``It was not built by a bunch
of folks who wanted to make a lot of money, but by people who
wanted to improve the quality of government services.'' (30)
 &LR; tag1:To reach Mark P. Couch, development reporter, call (816)
234-4289 or send e-mail to mcouch &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
