<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE ILLUSION TO DISTRACT FANS GOING INTO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Maybe this is OK, the Seahawks presenting a sobering
picture for these final weeks of the year, of the century, of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in some cosmic way this December swoon is a public
service.
</P>
<P>
   There is no promise of a month-long bout of giddiness to
distract us from what is really important.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, there is something excruciatingly human about what
keeps happening to the Hawks _ a reminder that we can't depend on
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us could not stand to have this lesson reinforced?
</P>
<P>
   With their dramatic loss to the Broncos in Denver Sunday, it now
appears the Seahawks could be playing their final game in the
Kingdome this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Hawks, with four consecutive losses, vs. the Kansas
City Chiefs, with four consecutive victories, in an AFC West
showdown for all the marbles.
</P>
<P>
   What an ending for the concrete cave, where professional
football and baseball were born in the Pacific Northwest. Yet, the
do-or-die, regular-season game is not the finale originally
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were supposed to deliver bigger and better things
than this, especially after all the money, hype and grand illusion
pumped into the team. Mike Holmgren was courted to Seattle by one
of sports' richest owners to rescue a flailing franchise. The new
coach and a new attitude were supposed to set the Hawks on a
winning course just in time to swell public sentiment in
anticipation of the Seahawks' move to its
soon-to-be-under-construction outdoor palace.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Seattle was supposed to be a football town.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, despite a move to their alleged franchise
re-invigorating designer ballpark, the Mariners were swooning and
Ken Griffey Jr. was batting .255 and the funk around the M's was
thick as fog. That's when, short on patience for the way baseball
was making us feel, thoughts turned to the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   With so much riding on the new coach and the new football
stadium and the need for this team to be a juggernaut to justify
its new money/power base, the Hawks were hyped to be on the verge
of being better than ever, even superhuman.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone who watched Sunday and witnessed the Hawks
looking as meekly human as Tiny Tim, almost all hope for that
one-season transformation is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Any November anger from season ticket-holders over the steep
price of playoff seats now seems to have been premature. So was our
nutty euphoria over an 8-2 record that made it appear the Seahawks
would fulfill their prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks ago, Hawks success seemed as easy and inevitable as
closing your eyes and having your dot-com stock options split three
times. Dreaming of instant wealth is a sign of our times.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a lesson in all of this losing, one would have to
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   As Seattle approaches the end of '99, reality has been harsh
from all corners. From the violence surrounding the World Trade
Organization protest marches to the arrest last week of a suspected
terrorist attempting to smuggle explosives into Port Angeles, the
action in Seattle has been monumentally sobering.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, has been the realization that sports does not always
serve as some sort of great unifier. And no matter how much hope we
heap on high-paid athletes and price-gouging teams to supply us
with a steady roll of good tidings, the system can't deliver with
nearly the regularity promised.
</P>
<P>
   As this year, this century, this millennium comes to a close,
Seattle has two new sports stadiums. Safeco Field already sits on
the city's skyline, and the football stadium is on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Both were in part sold on the expectation that with bigger and
better and more expensive venues, the actions of the players and
the results of the seasons would mirror the enormous investments _
both financial and emotional.
</P>
<P>
   The new-era, big-spending Hawks were going to go out in '99 with
a bang, just before the Kingdome went down in a bang of dynamite.
Instead, the Hawks are not much different from last year or the
year before, nor are they much different from most other NFL teams
mired in expansion-era mediocrity. That's reality.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were going to turn from small-market, small-focus,
perennial underachievers into boys of summer, basking in the
natural light of an outdoor wonder well suited for a World Series
contender. Instead, the M's are starting a new Safeco Field era
with the tearing down of the franchise's most enduring and
important star. Griffey, now vilified in many corners, wants out of
town because the new ballpark is too far away from where he chooses
to live and is too big for his brand of home run hitting.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the best of times. But that's OK. At least, we
perhaps can face this holiday season with a bit more clarity.
</P>
<P>
   There are few distractions. There are no instant highs in our
sports palaces. The tension-fraught game that the Hawks will play
Sunday won't be the gushing, gonzo going-away party we thought the
Seahawks would give the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   But this reality seems fitting for these times.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
