<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKADAISICAL SONICS DOWN BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ That they have a key player, Rusty LaRue, whose first
name basically describes his game tells all you need to know about
the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the bottom of a tin NBA barrel and you will certainly
find corrosion in a team formerly known as champions throughout
most of the Michael Jordan era.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently the Sonics either forgot or did not bother to read the
current scouting report. They also took their time before deciding
to play Monday night. It took three twilight zone quarters before
the Sonics woke up and beat the Bulls, 93-84, at United Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at their record and said, `Ah, we don't have to play
defense tonight,''' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``In the
fourth quarter everybody got mad and we shut the Bulls down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics actually trailed 72-71 heading into the final period.
Then, Gary Payton took over, attacked the basket and scored 9 of
his 22 points in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Payton also led the defense. The Sonics knocked an otherwise
hot-shooting Bulls team off balance. Chicago (2-20) missed 16 of
their 18 shots in the final frame and the Sonics (18-7) ended the
game with a 22-12 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have an excuse for that,'' Payton said of the Sonics'
performance. ``We're supposed to get up for any team. For us to go
through that was ridiculous. If we do that (Tuesday against
Indiana) we're looking at another blowout (loss).''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were mortified, then pulled out the victory. The
Bulls had just nine players available because of a rash of
injuries. Still, the Sonics allowed the Bulls to shoot 52 percent
through three quarters. Chicago entered the game shooting just 40
percent while allowing opponents to make 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they talked about taking the game seriously, the
Sonics' effort spoke volumes. The Sonics were careless and
lackadaisical. They settled for outside shots and gave the Bulls
the advantage in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago trailed the Sonics 57-53 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics center Horace Grant did not have a single point or
rebound at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very scrappy team even though their record is
poor,'' said Grant, who finished with two points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were ever in a situation where we were
worried about the game,'' said Vin Baker, whose 25 points on
7-of-12 shooting led the Sonics. ``They played hard. But all we had
to do was play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he gave the team his shortest halftime speech
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `They haven't scored 100 points all season. They have
53. You do the math,''' Westphal said. ``Then, I threw something.
... I think it was a pen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls even impressed themselves by staying with a team with
one of the league's best records.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we're hanging around in a position to win games,''
said Bulls forward Elton Brand, the NBA's No. 1 draft pick this
year. ``We have a lot of young guys out there getting run down. We
are definitely undermanned physically so it's great to see us
hanging around.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having Brand and rookie Ron Artest, the Bulls are still
the same hapless team Sonics guard Brent Barry played for last
season. Barry actually was part of a subplot to the game because of
comments he made upon arriving in Seattle after the Bulls swapped
him for Hersey Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   Barry basically said the Chicago team he played on could not
chew gum and walk at the same time. Bulls starting center Dickey
Simpkins took offense and was quoted in yesterday's Chicago
Sun-Times that Barry should be careful driving the lane
</P>
<P>
   So Barry did not hesitate. He went hard to the basket a couple
of times early in the first quarter. On one play Simpkins whacked
Barry across the chest with a hard foul.
</P>
<P>
   Both players bumped into each other after the contact but did
not get into a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was my dad (Rick), I would have gotten kicked out,''
Barry said. ``He did it. The referee probably should have taken a
longer look at it. ... Off the court, I don't have a problem with
Dickey. On the court, it's kind of nonsense. But I was going to see
what he was going to bring at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 17-12, the Sonics had to fight off the energy the Bulls
brought.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Patterson took off after a Sonic rebound and beat everyone
down court for an uncontested dunk. That ignited a 14-0 run. The
Sonics led by as many as 13 points in the first half before the
Bulls made the game interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they're going to compete,'' Barry said. ``The two
games they won, they won at home. I was on the other side last
year. You want to come out and play as hard as you can. Sometimes
the talent doesn't match up but the effort is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics learned that lesson Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
