r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HOPE-TEX     12-21 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HOPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE FLOATS: IF COWBOYS WIN 2, THEY'RE IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys know about the gift that
keeps on giving.
</P>
<P>
   They just received it.
</P>
<P>
   It showed up on their Valley Ranch doorstep Monday in the form
of an interpretation of the NFL's convoluted tiebreaker system
which favors _ or rather ``resuscitates'' _ the Cowboys in their
quest to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league office, the Cowboys are assured of
making the playoffs simply by winning their remaining two games to
finish 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what anyone else does, no matter how many NFC teams
also finish 9-7 ... if the Cowboys win, they're in.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many times they keep shooting themselves in the
foot, i.e., Sunday when they blew a fourth-quarter lead for the
fifth time this season and lost at home to the already
playoff-eliminated New York Jets, the Cowboys still control their
own destiny, albeit a complicated destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Tampa Bay and Washington go on to join St. Louis as
division champions, that would leave six teams vying to finish 9-7
or better and secure one of the three remaining wild card spots.
</P>
<P>
   But:
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys finish 9-7, the Giants won't because they finish
the season at Texas Stadium, where a loss would eliminate them from
that six-team hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina can finish 9-7, but if the Panthers and the Cowboys
both finish 9-7, the Cowboys will have a better conference record,
which would be the tiebreaker between those two teams.
</P>
<P>
   If Detroit, Minnesota and Green Bay each finish 9-7 or any two
of them finish 9-7, teams within the same division tied for a
wild-card spot must break that tie before breaking ties with teams
from other divisions. That would leave the Cowboys and two NFC
Central teams as the wild-card teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys still have a chance to defend their NFC East crown,
although Washington, 8-6, holds a one-game lead over the Cowboys,
7-7, and New York Giants, 7-7, with two games to go. Dallas does
hold the tiebreaker edge against the Redskins because of
head-to-head (2-0) results.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys learned Monday is that they're still assured of
getting at least an NFC wild-card berth by winning their remaining
two games, although that would mean putting together their first
two-game winning streak since opening the season 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   They play at New Orleans on Christmas Eve. And while the Saints
are 2-12, the Cowboys will be taking a six-game road losing streak
this season into the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys then come home for a Jan. 2 game against the Giants
at Texas Stadium. And while the Cowboys are 6-1 at home this
season, they lost to the Giants two months ago, 13-10, at Giants
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hurt now,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Monday,
``but if we sit around feeling sorry for ourselves (at 7-7) rather
than go out and play these last two games (to win), just think how
bad we'd feel later knowing that 9-7 would've gotten us in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd really be sick then.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a computer inside the league office in New York on
Monday, the Cowboys have been assured a chance of feeling ``really
sick.'' All they have to do is stub their toe one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective now is to go fight,'' said Gailey. ``OK, it
hurt. OK, it's over. Now let's go fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Both remaining games for Dallas are against NFC opponents, which
plays into the Cowboys' favor of controlling their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Giants, the Saints defeated the Cowboys in their
last meeting, 22-3, just over 12 months ago. In that game, the
Cowboys were held to 182 yards total offense. Emmitt Smith finished
with 15 carries for 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets actually have a lower-ranked offense (25th) and defense
(23rd) in the NFL than either the Saints (20th in offensive, 21st
in defensive) or the Giants (17th in offensive, 11th in defensive).
So there are no easy opponents for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made too many penalties at critical times,'' said Gailey,
whose team made four of their eight penalties in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But while mistakes and penalties cost the Cowboys the Jets game,
Gailey stopped short of putting his players on notice that some of
them are playing for their jobs next season in these final two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily think it's a big deal to make that a point
with them, or with anybody,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year coach was asked how he justifies some so-called
``questionable'' penalties, such as Sunday's pass interference
against cornerback Kevin Smith, which led to a Jets touchdown, or
tripping on center Mark Stepnoski, which wiped out a first-down run
by Emmitt Smith and led to a Dallas punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to justify it to the team because there's no way
you can justify it,'' said Gailey. ``The way you justify it to
yourself is to say (that) all that evens out, if you stay employed
long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he allows himself to think about his own job
security, Gailey replied, ``No, I don't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey emphasized that the focus is on beating the Saints, then
beating the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are fortunate enough that they still can.
</P>
<P>
   And, more important, it still matters. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
