<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS DEFEAT PACKERS, 24-20 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Randy Moss loves big games and, with the exception
of the postseason, none is bigger than the stage on ``Monday Night
Football.'' As he has done many times in his short career, Moss
stole the show on Monday night, as only a great thespian can do.
</P>
<P>
   It began late in the second quarter, when quarterback Jeff
George sold a great run fake to running back Robert Smith, freezing
the Green Bay cornerback Tyrone Williams, who was guarding Moss on
the right side. Moss executed the subterfuge brilliantly, jogging
like a disinterested tourist, then sprinting and galloping past
Williams for the 57-yard touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   Big game. Big play. Big man.
</P>
<P>
   That touchdown tied the score at 10. Moss finished the day with
two touchdown catches and was the biggest reason Minnesota beat the
Packers, 24-20, before 64,203 at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's record is 8-6 and tied with Detroit for first place
in the National Football Conference Central Division. The Packers'
playoff chances were dealt a serious blow as they fell to 7-7. They
will visit Tampa Bay on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Moss' second touchdown came with just under two minutes left in
the third quarter. George, despite some risky throws that could
have been intercepted, engineered a solid 59-yard drive to the
Green Bay 1-yard line. The Vikings love to go to Moss near the goal
line because he can use his 6-feet-4-inch frame and post-up
defensive backs like it is basketball instead of football.
</P>
<P>
   Moss' second victim was safety Darren Sharper. It was no
contest. Moss ran maybe a half-yard inside the goal line. George
delivered a strike to him, and the Vikings led, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not a perfect day for the star wide receiver. His
sophomore season has had its highs and lows, with dropped passes,
and in this game he fumbled a punt return. Moss was hit hard by
Basil Mitchell, and the ball was recovered by Tod McBride.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers were stopped on third down at Minnesota's 9-yard
line and lined up for the field goal. Then Green Bay Coach Ray
Rhodes made a great call. The Packers ran a fake field goal, with
holder and backup quarterback Matt Hasselbeck picking up the
football and throwing it to tight end Jeff Thomason. Green Bay led,
20-17, with 12 minutes 19 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But Moss, who finished with five catches for 131 yards, made up
for his mistake. He outran double-coverage, getting behind both
safeties, for a 36-yard completion to the Green Bay 1-yard line.
Leroy Hoard ran it in and the Vikings again led, 24-20, with just
under nine minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre (18 of 32 for 178 yards), still the most dangerous
comeback quarterback in football, got the ball back but was
intercepted on third-and-20 with 3:19 left. Favre got another shot
with 45 seconds remaining at his own 22-yard line, and worked his
way to Minnesota's 28-yard line, but was intercepted in the end
zone with no time left on the clock by Robert Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   This game was the most important of the season for both teams.
Griffith put it best when he said that the loser, realistically,
would miss the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   For the Vikings, that would be rare. Dennis Green's teams have
missed the postseason only twice in his eight years as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has struggled, but it is not a team in turmoil, which
might have described the Packers this week. Defensive coordinator
Emmitt Thomas has come under fire for not finding ways to put
pressure on opposing quarterbacks. What the Packers did against
Carolina was an embarrassment to a proud organization. The Panthers
scored on all four of their second-half possessions and Steve
Beuerlein threw for 373 total yards, the most Green Bay has given
up in two years. That forced the Packers defensive coaches to
rethink their defensive schemes, especially against the powerful
offense of the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Green Bay coaching brain trust did worked. The
Packers were much more aggressive, blitzing from the corners, and
constantly putting pressure on George, who was rattled early.
</P>
<P>
   Both Favre and George struggled until late in the second half.
The Packers' first three possessions were a fumble followed by two
punts, and the Vikings were plagued by a George fumble and blown
blocking assignments by the line. The first quarter was scoreless;
early in the second Minnesota kicker Gary Anderson connected from
43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-yard run by Dorsey Levens and a 26-yard field goal by Ryan
Longwell gave Green Bay a 10-3 lead in the second quarter. Then
came Moss's first touchdown catch. When he went streaking down the
field and into the end zone, it was still early in the game and
there were more fireworks to come from Favre. But watching Moss is
like seeing a young Jim Brown or Jordan or Gretzky perform.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Moss makes it look too easy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
