<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND-MARKET ANXIETY HELPS DRAGS DOWN THE DOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to adjust closing numbers for Honeywell, J.P. Morgan,
Citigroup, Chase Manhattan and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.)  
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A bad day in the bond market hurt some segments of
the stock market Monday as concerns mounted about what Federal
Reserve policy-makers might do about interest rates at a meeting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks seen as sensitive to rising interest rates, like
financial-services companies, suffered after bond traders lifted
the yield on the 30-year Treasury to 6.44 percent, its highest in
27 months, from 6.37 percent on Friday. The bond's price, which
moves in the opposite direction, fell 25/32, to 95 29/32.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in stocks like J.P. Morgan and Citigroup helped to
pull down the Dow Jones industrial average by 113.16 points, or 1
percent, to 11,144.27.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy continuing to be quite strong, the assumption
is that the Fed will definitely move, and possibly on Tuesday'' to
raise short-term interest rates, said David Mead, chief investment
officer at Harris Bank in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt they will move that rapidly,'' he added, ``but the
fear is they may tighten by half a percentage point at their
meeting in February.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, demand for technology stocks remained intense, and
the Nasdaq composite index set a third consecutive record and its
55th of the year. It rose 30.81 points, or 0.8 percent, to
3,783.87.
</P>
<P>
   The continued rise in technology and Internet stocks ``is very
frustrating for anyone who has any sort of value orientation,''
said Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer at Fleet Boston
Investment Advisors. ``This is a market that is driving anyone who
wants to do old-fashioned analysis to question their existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The other main market gauges were narrowly mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed at 1,418.09, down
2.94 points, or 0.2 percent. But the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies gained 0.98 point, or 0.2 percent, to 467.19.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among analysts is that the central bank will leave
short-term rates unchanged Tuesday and continue with its neutral
stance toward any future rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, that view is based on the fact that the Fed,
which has been injecting liquidity into the banking system as a
precautionary measure before the turn of the century, does not want
to roil financial markets because of the uncertainty about how
potential Year 2000 computer problems will affect the economy.
</P>
<P>
   At this juncture, a move to raise rates would come as a
definite, negative surprise, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they tightened again and said they are not afraid of Y2K,
then that could set the stage for a big year-end sell-off,'' said
Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Although financial-services stocks were losers, Honeywell
International was the biggest single contributor to the decline in
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The stock fell 7 1/8, to 56 5/8, after Honeywell said it had
agreed to buy Pittway, the maker of burglar alarms, for $2.2
billion, a 57 percent premium to its closing price on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial-services company stocks, J.P. Morgan was down 2
9/16, to 125 9/16. Citigroup closed at 53 7/16, down 1 1/16. And
Chase Manhattan dropped 1/8, to 72 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, share prices of both Monsanto and Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn
both fell after the rival drug makers agreed to merge. Monsanto
closed at 36 5/8, down 5 1/8, while Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn fell 3 1/8,
to 47 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies did better after announcing stock splits.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle gained 5 5/8, to 96 5/16, after the world's largest maker
of database software said it would split its shares 2 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat, a developer of a computer operating system that
competes with Microsoft's Windows, gained 15 1/16, to 267 15/16,
after it said it would split its stock 2 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   And Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's stock also gained after the
financial- services company announced fourth-quarter earnings that
were well above Wall Street estimates, as well as a 2-for-1 stock
split. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter stock closed at 128 5/16, up
15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
