   SCI-FUL-MOON (Undated) _ High tides, not cosmic levels of
illumination, may be the most noticeable effect tomorrow night when
an unusual combination of celestial events will produce one of the
largest and brightest full moons in recent memory. By Robert A.
Saar.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BETHLEHEM-STAR (Undated) _ The Star of Bethlehem has been
called many things by many people: a comet, a conjunction of
planets, a supernova, a miracle, a myth. With just one biblical
account, in the book of Matthew, of the star and how it caused the
wise men to come to Judea in search of the newborn Jesus, exactly
what it was, if indeed it was anything at all, remains an open
question. That question has attracted yet another answer, one that
is gaining attention from historians of astronomy for its unique
approach. Dr. Michael R. Molnar, an astronomer and physicist and
former teacher at Rutgers University, proposes that the star was
the planet Jupiter, seen in the constellation Aries, the ram. By
Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-CANCER (Undated) _ Terry Hoddinot, 36, has been blind
since the age of 3. His son, Riley, 3{, lost his left eye a month
ago. And the same rare eye cancer, retinoblastoma, was diagnosed in
his baby daughter, Katie, while she was still in the womb. But
doctors say there is a good chance that they may have saved Katie's
vision with a bold new procedure: delivering her prematurely, then
treating the affected eye before the cancer had a chance to grow
and blind her. The approach has important implications for the
treatment of retinoblastoma, a potentially fatal genetic disorder
that afflicts 1 in 20,000 North Americans. By Mark Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
