<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-ALCORN-WHITNEY-HN     12-21 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ALCORN-WHITNEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DEAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PRAIRIE VIEW _ Before Davey Whitney coached at Alcorn State, he
replaced Ernie Banks at shortstop, employed Wilma Rudolph as his
children's baby sitter and, as a teen-ager, sneaked into University
of Kentucky basketball practices to watch Adolph Rupp.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's a lifetime of conversation pieces right there, but
there's also the matter of his 500 coaching victories.
</P>
<P>
   No. 500 came Monday night as Alcorn State defeated Prairie View
A&AMP;M 91-72 at the William Nicks Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real ride,'' said Whitney, in his 29th season of
college coaching. ``Being a poor black kid coming from a small
(Kentucky) town, nothing better could have happened to me except
what has happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching basketball is only part of what has happened for
Whitney, who has amassed a 500-307 record in two stints covering 24
years at Alcorn State plus five years at Texas Southern. His Alcorn
teams have won 10 Southwestern Athletic Conference regular-season
championships and five conference tournament titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to coach. I never wanted to teach school,''
said Whitney, the SWAC's winningest coach, who as a player earned
more athletic letters than anyone in Kentucky State history.
</P>
<P>
   What Whitney, who turns 70 on Jan. 8, wanted to do was play
baseball. He was able to do that for a time in 1952 for the Kansas
City Monarchs of the Negro League. With the Monarchs, he replaced
future Hall of Famer Banks, who was en route to the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a pretty good baseball player,'' said Whitney, who began
his college coaching career at TSU (1964-69) and, while at Alcorn,
has won SWAC Coach of the Year honors nine times. His record with
the Braves is 446-235. ``Things didn't pan out like they should.
Like I would have liked. That's when I went into coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   And went on to become a coaching legend.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there 500 victories and five NCAA Tournament
appearances, but some of the wins have had historic significance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Alcorn State became the first historically black
institution to compete in the National Invitation Tournament. The
Braves beat Mississippi State 80-78 in Starkville, Miss., before
losing in the second round to eventual champion Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn State also became the first historically black
institution to win an NCAA Tournament game, beating South Alabama
70-62 in 1980, a season in which the Braves finished 28-2.
</P>
<P>
   Under Whitney, the Braves have won three NCAA Tournament games
and had some memorable, close losses _ to Kansas in 1984 by one
point and to Georgetown in 1983 by three.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney is still going strong: The Braves are the defending SWAC
regular-season and conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win,'' said Whitney. ``I never had any idea,
any thought of winning awards. Never thought about them.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly wasn't thinking of being a college coach when, in
his teen years from 1944-48 while attending high school in
Lexington, Ky., he and a friend would slip into Kentucky practices
and watch Rupp in action.
</P>
<P>
   Rupp didn't sign a black player until 1971 and had a reputation
as a racist in his 41-year Kentucky tenure. But Whitney said he had
no problem with Rupp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Rupp let us come in,'' said Whitney, who grew up in tiny
Midway, Ky. (population 547). ``I'd watch (Ralph) Beard, Wah Wah
Jones (two of Kentucky's stars).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a learning experience for me because he (Rupp) did
everything by the stopwatch. Everything was planned meticulously,
and I realized that when I was 14, 15 years old out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the all-time great coaches. I don't care about the
other stuff. I know what I got from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney's coaching career began in 1955. His teams compiled a
217-72 record with two state championships at Burt High School in
Clarksville, Tenn. It was there that he met Rudolph, who gained
fame by winning three gold medals in the 1960 Summer Olympics in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three girls, and we needed a baby sitter,'' said
Whitney. ``We stuck with her all through her career and when she
went to Rome. Everywhere. Even after she stopped running, we kept
in contact all the years. We went to her funeral (in 1994). We were
pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the coaching milestones, it hasn't all been a bed of
roses for Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 seasons from 1973 to 1985, the Braves won 20 games or
more 12 times. But after winning the SWAC championship in 1986, the
Braves stumbled to 5-23, 8-21 and 5-23 records.
</P>
<P>
   And a change was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got fired,'' said Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   But Alcorn was 57-135 in six years under two head coaches, so
the school brought Whitney back for the 1996-97 season. The Braves
have gone 11-17, 12-15 and 23-7 since.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn State is 4-5 following Monday's SWAC-opening blowout of
Prairie View.
</P>
<P>
   Six Braves scored in double figures with Walter Harper getting
12 points and 12 rebounds. Terrance Cameron and Marcus Fleming also
had 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ironic part about the whole situation: The guy that fired
me named the building after me,'' said Whitney, whose Braves play
at Texas Southern on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Also ironic is that Prairie View coach Elwood Plummer was
recruited by Whitney when Whitney was coaching at TSU and Plummer
was the leading scorer in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known coach Whitney since he was coaching at Texas
Southern,'' said Plummer. ``I was coming out of high school, but I
had already made up my mind to go to Jackson State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been around a long time. He's been an asset and credit to
the conference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
