<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WINS, BUT BIBBY ISN'T HAPPY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ A 33-point USC victory over anybody seems a minor
cause for celebration, so what was coach Henry Bibby doing keeping
his team in the locker room for more than 20 minutes after the game
Monday night?
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't to congratulate each of the Trojans
individually after their 87-54 rout of lowly San Diego State before
3,402 at Cox Arena.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat disturbed Bibby instead lectured USC about its
uncanny ability to let a team back into a game.
</P>
<P>
   USC seemed to put the Aztecs away by taking a 28-9 lead 11
minutes into the contest. But then the Trojans went to sleep, and
San Diego State scored 23 of the next 33 points and trailed 38-32
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   USC (6-5) got hot again, as point guard Brandon Granville hit
four 3-pointers in the second half en route to a career-high 24
points. But the final score didn't do much to soothe Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a win,'' Bibby said. ``I thought we turned the ball
over. We were careless and unorganized. The second half, we got
organized. One player played in the first half, Brian Scalabrine.
In the second half, Sam Clancy and Granville stepped it up. But we
need to have four to five guys play every night.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no argument from the Trojans, who realized that they
won't see many teams like San Diego State (2-5) when Pacific-10
Conference play begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him,'' said Scalabrine, who scored 21 points.
``If we play like this, these eight-minute lulls where we don't do
anything, that's what makes it hard. It can kill you in the
Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine had just four points in a loss to Long Beach last
week, but against San Diego State he decided the answer was to
shoot more frequently, taking 15 shots and making eight. He also
grabbed a career-high 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bit of redemption after obsessing over the loss to Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough,'' Scalabrine said. ``I was still thinking
about it until the game started. It was a devastating loss, losing
to a rival. They wanted to win more than us, and it was on ESPN.
That was a tough game to bounce back from.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Two-sport star quarterback/forward Teyo Johnson of Mira
Mesa High in San Diego attended the game. ``I'm really high on
USC,'' Johnson said. ``I had a great visit. I still need to visit
Stanford and Miami.'' Johnson said he is also considering UCLA, and
may not make a decision until after the prep basketball season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
