<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-PACKERS-VIKINGS-H     12-21 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-VIKINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ In a classic confrontation between bitter NFC
Central rivals, Minnesota and Green Bay provided Monday Night
Football with one of its best and most exciting games of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   There were enough lead changes and mood swings to satisfy even
the most casual fan. When time ran out in the Vikings' 24-20
victory, players and coaches on both sidelines were mentally and
physically drained.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's victory before a Metrodome crowd of 64,203 wasn't
secured until safety Robert Griffith made an end-zone interception
of quarterback Brett Favre's desperation pass as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to make the playoffs, and this win puts us
closer to it,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said. ``Our guys were
put in a tough situation at the end, but Robert made the big
interception.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings snapped a two-game losing streak to improve their
record to 8-6, leaving them one game behind Tampa Bay. Minnesota
visits the New York Giants and hosts Detroit in its last two games.
The Packers fell to 7-7, but they aren't out of wild-card
contention. They travel to Tampa Bay and host Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay had no answer for the Minnesota combination of
quarterback Jeff George and receiver Randy Moss. George completed
16 of 29 passes for 258 yards and two touchdowns, both to Moss. He
wasn't intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moss made some great plays,'' Packers coach Ray Rhodes said.
``I thought we blitzed them a little too much at times. There were
a couple of situations where Randy got some room and made some
plays. And we missed some tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not surprising that Favre, who completed 22 of 39 passes
for 229 yards and no touchdowns, lost at the Metrodome. His record
here dropped to 1-7, but the Vikings had to earn every yard and
point to win the game and split the season series.
</P>
<P>
   After losing its last two games, Minnesota was desperate for a
victory. After a scoreless first quarter, the Vikings and Packers
exchanged leads in the second, which ended with Green Bay leading
13-10.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Anderson's 42-yard field goal gave the Vikings a 3-0 lead
that lasted until the Packers moved 75 yards in nine plays. Running
back Dorsey Levens, returning to Green Bay's lineup after missing
two games because of a cracked rib, scored on a one-yard run, and
Ryan Longwell kicked the extra point for a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Longwell's 26-yard field goal boosted the Green Bay lead to
10-3, but Minnesota tied it when George found Moss for a 57-yard
touchdown pass. Moss got behind cornerback Tyrone Williams with
4:17 left in the first half. Anderson's extra point tied it.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers retaliated by going 69 yards to set up Longwell's
22-yard field goal with three seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   There were four punts in the third quarter before the Vikings
regained the lead with a 10-play, 60-yard drive. With
second-and-goal at the Green Bay one, George and Moss collaborated
for their second touchdown, which provided Minnesota with a 17-13
lead that lasted into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With Green Bay's offense unable to get untracked in the second
half, the Packers had to resort to trickery to score their other
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   When Longwell lined up for a 26-yard field goal early in the
fourth quarter, holder Matt Hasselbeck threw a nine-yard touchdown
pass to backup tight end Jeff Thomason. Longwell added the extra
point to give Green Bay a 20-17 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' much-maligned defense played about as well as it
could, but the Vikings' offense was just too good. Once again, it
was the George-to-Moss combination that did most of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   George threw deep over the middle to Moss, who made an
outstanding 36-yard catch. It appeared to be a touchdown, but the
officials called him down at the one, further delaying the Packers'
agony.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Leroy Hoard scored what proved to be the winning
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   With Green Bay trailing by four, Favre led the Packers into
Minnesota territory. His pass for Antonio Freeman was intercepted
by rookie cornerback Kenny Wright at the Minnesota 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings used all but the last 45 seconds. The Packers got
the ball back at their 22. With no timeouts remaining, Favre took
them to the Minnesota 28 with six seconds to go. With time for one
last play, Favre threw for the end zone, where Griffith made a
leaping interception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     12-21 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A COUPLE OF REAL SWINGERS WHO DESERVE A RAZE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the movie I'm writing about a psychotic
wrecking-ball operator, titled ``Swing Shift,'' the bad guy's reign
of terror ends (if you plan to see the movie, don't read the rest
of this paragraph) when he tries to knock down an occupied
children's hospital, but the good-guy scientist places a giant
magnet behind the crane and the wrecking ball swings right back
through the cab.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe nobody's made this movie yet. Nothing is quite
as cool as a wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   Four and a half tons of steel in the shape of a teardrop, swung
with the lazy arc of a hypnotist's watch fob, bringing mighty
structures to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Bob Sparks, who is not a deranged maniac, is swinging
a wrecking ball at a large office building at Third and Howard. As
fast as Willie Brown builds the city, Bob and his ball-swinging
brother Bill knock it down.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sparks seems like a good name for a wrecking-ball operator,
but in my movie his name is Buster Downs. Announcer's voice in the
preview: ``Power corrupts. Absolute power corrupts absolutely. So
don't blame Buster Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sparks says his father wanted him to become a doctor, and I
think maybe Bob is pulling my leg, but that is what he became _ a
doctor of destruction. A master of structural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Bob's father was a wrecking-ball operator. As a kid, Bob would
sit on his dad's knee as William Sparks turned buildings to
tangled, smoking rubble.
</P>
<P>
   You might say Bob took a crash course at Wreck U.
</P>
<P>
   When a kid is raised in the cab of a wrecking-ball crane, he
does not say to himself, ``When I grow up, I want to be a computer
software management consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   I ask Bob if his job is as fun as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be fun,'' he says. ``Now it's just a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing my disappointment, he adds, ``It's got its moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the time a couple years ago when he dropped his 8,600-pound
ball from its 160-foot-high boom onto a couple of junk cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gave 'em a sunroof pretty quick,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're talkin'.
</P>
<P>
   I see a TV show, called ``Wreck This.'' A wrecking ball can be
dropped straight down, or swung. Viewers send in requests. ``My
ex-husband's beach cottage.'' ``An above-ground swimming pool
filled with Pokemon toys.'' ``A 50-foot-high pyramid of paint
cans.''
</P>
<P>
   I see a civic fund-raiser. Donate $100, take a swing of the ball
at a Muni bus. Empty, of course.
</P>
<P>
   I see an ESPN event to replace the boring Lumberjack Games.
``The Wreckin' Games.''
</P>
<P>
   I see me climbing into the cab to take a couple swings at the
office building at Third and Howard. The demolition company does
not share my vision. Insurance problems and blah blah blah.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly the kind of modern b.s. that attracted me to the
wrecking ball in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   THERE IS something primitively satisfying about a wrecking ball.
Even the name. It's so bad that even the bureaucrats can't mess
with its name. It is not called a ``kinetic spheroid disassembly
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world grown increasingly delicate and fragile and
technical, the wrecking ball is a throwback to the days when men
arranged high-speed, head-on locomotive crashes for sport.
</P>
<P>
   There is an awesome, Grim Reaper aspect to the ball's work.
Watching Bob break buildings is like watching Mark McGwire take
batting practice, only with better sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   Bob swings the boom to the right, stops it on a dime and starts
it back left. Lazily, like a kid in a park swing, seemingly in slow
motion, the ball-on-chain stops, hangs in the air, then begins to
swing slo-o-o-wly back to the left.
</P>
<P>
   What damage can it do, moving so slowly? And it's not that big,
about the size of Danny DeVito.
</P>
<P>
   The ball slams into the sixth-floor wall, chunks of debris
clatter down with an enormous roar, the entire side of the building
sways and wobbles like a prizefighter battling to stay on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   With each blow, the wall wobbles more. Finally, blam, there it
goes, six stories of offices collapsing helplessly, a 50-foot-long
steel girder flying through the air like a matchstick, sticking
point-first into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the artist,'' says demolition company president Wayne
Evans, watching Bob Sparks work. ``He and his brother are about the
best I've seen. It really is an art form, not a lot of guys can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob works four stick-like levers and two brake pedals, a
puppeteer in a hard hat.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bob's target is a free-standing, upright steel beam.
Precision is required. He nestles the wrecking ball softly against
the beam, like a golfer addressing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The backswing, and whammo, direct hit. The beam topples.
</P>
<P>
   I ASK BOB about the therapeutic aspects of his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, this takes out pretty much all my frustration,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   I can't tell if he's joking. Bob is a friendly, easygoing guy.
Of course, so was Buster Downs when he first walked onto the
demolition site and asked for a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing Shift,'' by the way, opens with Buster doing his thing,
making the ball dance, to the sound of Emmylou Harris singing a
Neil Young song, ``Wrecking Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet me at the Wrecking Ball, I'll wear something pretty and
white, and we'll go dancing tonight. . .''
</P>
<P>
   BOOM!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
