<HEADLINE>
REDESIGNED GLOBE TO DEBUT NEXT YEAR, PUBLISHER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston Globe's publisher, Richard H. Gilman,
announced Monday that the newspaper will undertake a complete
redesign next year that will include printing the paper on a
slightly narrower page.
</P>
<P>
   The one-inch reduction in the width of the page, from 13 1/2
inches to 12 1/2 inches, will be introduced in some papers in
January. The Globe will convert each of its seven presses to a
50-inch web to accommodate the new format, a process expected to
take one month per press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use less newsprint and ink,'' Gilman said, ``and thus
reduce our expenses as well as be more gentle on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also aim to be more appealing to readers, in an
easier-to-handle size with a more attractive design and graphic
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several newspapers, including The Washington Post, The
(Cleveland) Plain Dealer, and The Denver Post, have converted to
the smaller size in recent years, and others are in the process of
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The redesign, to be introduced in September, is the first
significant change in the Globe's look in a decade. It's expected
to feature updated typography and graphics and some reorganization
of the content of the paper. The redesign, Gilman said, will offer
``an improved product with the editorial quality that readers have
come to expect from the Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe is a wholly owned subsidiary of The New York Times Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
