<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GOODEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX OFFER GOODEN ONE-YEAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox, who already boast two Cy Young Award
winners in Pedro Martinez and Bret Saberhagen, have made an offer
to another, though one whose best days are long past.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight ``Doc'' Gooden, who in 1985 became the youngest pitcher
to win a Cy Young Award, at the age of 20, but this season was left
off Cleveland's postseason roster when the Indians met the Sox in
an American League division series in October, has been offered a
contract by the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox proposal was a one-year deal with a modest base
salary and performance bonuses that could lift the total value in
excess of $2 million. There also would be a club option for a
second year.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's agent, Lee Rosenblum, has sent the Sox a counteroffer
asking for a higher base salary and total package, but he was
confident the sides could reach an agreement this week. Rosenblum
was awaiting a response Monay night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dwight is very enthusiastic about pitching for the Red Sox,
especially since they are a contender,'' said Rosenblum, who also
has been in contact with a couple of other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, who turned 35 Nov. 16, became a free agent when the
Indians decided not to exercise the $3 million option they held on
his contract for 2000, electing to give him a $400,000 buyout
instead. Gooden had signed a two-year deal for $5.6 million with
the Indians in 1997 but won a total of just 11 games in two
seasons. He was just 3-4 with a career-worst 6.26 ERA for Cleveland
this past season, when he made 22 starts but gave up 127 hits and
67 walks in 115 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox battered Gooden in his three starts against them in
1999, scoring 12 earned runs in 13 1/3 innings and beating him
twice, with one no-decision. Gooden also faced the Sox in Game 2 of
the 1998 division series, when he was ejected after just a third of
an inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox, with Saberhagen out until at least midseason after
undergoing shoulder surgery, are scrambling for some veteran help
in the rotation and apparently feel Gooden has something left.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1996, when he made a comeback with the Yankees
after being suspended for the 1995 season because he violated the
terms of his drug aftercare program, Gooden tossed a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He would join Saberhagen and Ramon Martinez as Sox pitchers who
have thrown a no-hitter in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden ranks fourth among all active pitchers in wins with 188,
one more than Tom Glavine, though the last time he won as many as
13 games in a season was 1991, when he went 13-7 for the Mets. He
also ranks fifth in career strikeouts among active pitchers with
2,238.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also are talking to lefthander Jeff Fassero, as general
manager Dan Duquette has indicated he'd like to add at least one
starter and a reliever to the staff entering the 2000 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
