<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compulsion to clean cost me plenty o' green
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're feeling a little down in the
mouth because you didn't win the big lottery last Wednesday, for
heaven's sake set aside your selfish worries for just one minute
and start obsessing about something that actually matters in this
wild, whacked-out world of ours.
</P>
<P>
   Me.
</P>
<P>
   I think I won $6.3 million in the lottery back in 1993 and never
collected.
</P>
<P>
   I can't be sure, and laugh if you must, but I have this really
bad feeling and it began this week when I read about all these
winning lottery tickets that were never cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   $9 million in 1997. $2.8 million in 1995. And a single ticket
worth $6.34 million back in September of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   How could I, or anyone, hit the Lotto and not know it? Well,
these tickets don't exactly have the shelf life of Spam. They're
only good for 180 days. And I distinctly _ OK, vaguely _ remember
driving through Broward County in the early 1990s and buying a
ticket. Then I cleaned out my wallet in 1994 or '95 or '96, and I
found that Lotto ticket and I thought, What's this old thing? And I
threw it out.
</P>
<P>
   I do that.
</P>
<P>
   Throw things out.
</P>
<P>
   My husband has part of a wooden railing from his Ohio college
days. I don't have the letter I got yesterday from Ed McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Leftover pork roast, broken toys, love letters, newspapers,
resumes from pathetic job searches. Who needs that stuff? Catalogs,
birthday cards, half-done craft projects, an old bag of corn in the
freezer. In the trash.
</P>
<P>
   This obsession I have for tidiness _ pause a moment and let my
family and friends chuckle _ has gotten me into a heap of trouble
even before this $6.34 million debacle. I've been known to throw
away outgoing mail, story ideas, even my wedding hat. Once I even
threw out an old Sports Illustrated magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Now this.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I can't be certain. But when I close my eyes, I have this
very vivid image of the following sequence of numbers:
1-17-29-36-37-39. I'm pretty sure I remember them as the numbers
printed on the ticket that I'm pretty sure I bought seven years ago
at a little store that I believe could have been in Broward County.
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or I just copied them directly from the newspaper
clipping that happens to be right here on my desk.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering how I can be so chipper. WELL I'M NOT!
I'm schlepping children and carrying in my own groceries when _ in
the name of all that is fair in this world _ I should be soaking in
a bathtub, calling out, Calgon, take me away, in a voice as lovely
as the late Miss Madeline Kahn's.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, here I sit, not a box of Calgon in sight, waiting for
that no-good Jerry Springer to call. They're talking about booking
me for their Money in the Millennium show. It's called, How her
tidiness cost him millions.
</P>
<P>
   It's always about the man, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Wait just a darn a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Somebody called yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Where's that message?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for Pete's sake.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it was from Jerry Seinfeld, and I just threw it away.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
