<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN22-COX     12-21 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heller was a well-loved grumpy guy
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Joseph Heller is my favorite living
author,'' I began a 1980 column about the author of Catch-22. This
was 19 years before his death last week at 76. ``If he were dead,
he'd be among my top five or six dead authors.''
</P>
<P>
   In that column I went on to explain that far from looking
forward to meeting Heller, who was in South Florida visiting family
and publicizing his recently released paperback ``Good as Gold,'' I
dreaded the meeting. For one thing, Heller was my hero, and I was
afraid I wouldn't like him. Second, his publicist had gotten his
book to me only a day before Heller's visit, and I had barely
cracked it.
</P>
<P>
   When I begged to postpone our interview until I finished the
book, he wouldn't hear of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're on page 80?'' he asked. ``It'll go so fast from now on,
you won't be able to put it down.''
</P>
<P>
   That relaxed me. And when he further assured me that it was a
great book and that I would love it, I correctly guessed that a guy
with that kind of ego was going to be a loosey-goosey interview.
</P>
<P>
   What I saw when we met at the Holiday Inn was a 56-year-old
novelist ``of medium height, slender, with coils of unruly gray
hair good for wrecking combs. If he were any more collegiate, ivy
would grow on him. He looks like your English Lit prof should have
looked, and indeed has taught at New York City College long enough
to know he doesn't particularly care for it.''
</P>
<P>
   I told Heller up front that I had read ``Catch-22'' three times
and still didn't know whether it was anti-war or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me either,'' said Heller. ``I still can't tell anybody what
``Catch-22'' is about. People ask me if Yossarian got away. I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take a chance and tell Heller that his second
novel, ``Something Happened,'' depressed me and that I probably
wouldn't have finished it if it weren't for his recurring teenage
flashback of a ravishing older woman who used to take him to the
stock room.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about writing a depressing, serious novel when
people are expecting ironic slapstick is that people take you
seriously as a writer. The downside is that his long-awaited second
novel, 12 years in the writing, took some of the anticipation out
of his third novel, four years in the incubator.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Good as Gold' was just awaited,'' he noted dryly.
</P>
<P>
   And it also proved the mother lode for zaniness fans looking for
more nuggets from the author who gave the language ``Catch-22,''
the notion of a loophole that self-destructs the second you ask for
it. In ``Gold,'' the insanity built into bureaucracy blooms anew
when author Bruce Gold gets a job as a White House flack for the
Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   When I pointed out that in ``Gold,'' he dealt very kindly with
an abrasive father who gave him nothing but grief, Heller shrugged
and insisted that ``I almost never offer answers. I don't have a
solution for these family problems. I put my own mother in a
nursing home and I didn't feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller wrote that medical science had created something terribly
portentous, ``a long life span, with a larger and larger number of
old people who were unneeded by society, had nothing to do and were
not revered. How much longer would grown children hope their
parents going into surgery would come out alive?''
</P>
<P>
   Within five years of asking that question, Heller himself was
stricken with Guillain-Barre syndrome, a nerve disease that left
him paralyzed and bedridden. For a year, he could not change
position, swallow or clear his throat, although he could talk with
slurred speech. His recovery was almost complete, leaving him with
a slight speech impairment, immense gratitude, and the makings of a
book, ``No Laughing Matter,'' co-authored with his friend, Speed
Vogel, a sculptor and herring taster who managed his personal
affairs during his convalescence.
</P>
<P>
   I interviewed Heller after his recovery, again at a Holiday Inn,
where he told me that if you're going to be laid up in a hospital
for a year, you had better have friends and money. He was $250,000
in the hole when his health returned, and learned through his
co-author that Vogel and friends such as Dustin Hoffman and Mel
Brooks loved Heller despite the fact that they often commiserated
with one another about his ``impatience, rudeness, insensitivity,
selfishness, arrogance, duplicity, obstinacy, malevolence,
insincerity, negativity and general unpleasantness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked him,'' Vogel wrote, ``but we were extremely hard-put
to explain why.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Vogel reflected, Heller came out of his illness ``so
much nicer in every way that we, his friends, pondered how we could
manage to give him another foreign ailment _ I am still working on
it, for my sake as well as humanity's.''
</P>
<P>
   One day when Heller was at his lowest, Mel Brooks strode to the
novelist's side, placed his hand on the patient's head, rolled his
eyes toward the ceiling and screamed:
</P>
<P>
   ``For Jesus! Stand! Walk!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Heller was unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks shrugged and said: ``I thought I'd give it a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without people,'' said Heller, No. 2 after Mark Twain on my
list of dead authors, ``I would have been in an awful situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
