r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX     12-21 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One of AIDS' biggest tragedies is all who remain nameless
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ They call it the NAMES Project, but it can't
always be true to that.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of hand-made sections make up the immense AIDS quilt
that travels the country. Most have names. Then there are squares
like the one dedicated to John Doe, or to many of them _ ``actor,''
``artist,'' ``teacher,'' ``nurse.'' It signifies death certificates
falsified to protect someone's identity.
</P>
<P>
   We must ask ourselves why it is that our society has made it
necessary for people with such an important story to need
anonymity. We must realize that people's need to remain nameless
compounds the AIDS tragedy in more than one way.
</P>
<P>
   On the NAMES quilt is a square dedicated to ``Raymond,'' a gay
man who would not have allowed even this much information out while
alive, not even his first name, ``because his family would have
been deeply disturbed to have Raymond identified publicly in a gay
context . . . Ray himself never came out of the closet. Ray was
alone in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Family. Friends. Alone. Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the way people die in a society that cherishes life.
</P>
<P>
   But dwell not on Raymond, and not on the closet that confined
him. By now everyone should know that AIDS is not a ``gay
disease.'' Certainly the sample in today's paper will attest as
much.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it strikes people in all walks of life. Unfortunately
almost all get routed into a common canyon _ity, secrecy,
shame, stigma.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Allen, former president of the Southern Baptist
Convention, is one with no shortage of family or friends, but one
who found himself harboring a terrible secret through his darkest
days.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's daughter-in-law contracted HIV from a transfusion in the
early days when AIDS lurked in the blood supply. Her two sons got
it. All three died. In the early stages of this tragedy, Allen's
son, a pastor in a Colorado church, lost his job because the
congregation feared rubbing elbows with his family.
</P>
<P>
   One of Allen's biggest challenges was, sadly, finding a church
where his grandchildren could go to Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me hard when I realized that the church as an
institution has so failed that it could not summon the cleansing
touch of Jesus for a 4-year-old child,'' he wrote in his memoir,
``The Burden of a Secret.'' Allen tells of the years when this
terrible family secret was known only to a few.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we want to perceive AIDS as someone else's problem, so
too do we deceive ourselves that keeping such secrets is a burden
only on those who suffer. In fact, it is an impediment to curbing
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Valdiserri, a medical pathologist who lost his twin
brother to AIDS, writes in his book ``Gardening in Clay:
Reflections on AIDS,'' ``When we look at HIV infection as a threat
to our own, we accept as valid the prevention needs of those of us
who are at risk, and we willingly share our resources to meet their
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But when we see AIDS as someone else's problem, we limit
ourselves to preaching ``don't do this'' and ``don't do that.'' We
wouldn't consider for a moment something that might save lives like
needle exchanges for drug abusers who might risk their lives for a
high. Because they're faceless. They're ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   The shame is ours in their anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Herald-Tribune, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
