<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN22-CO     12-21 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Focused funds depend on manager
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Suppose you could pick an accomplished mutual fund
manager and concentrate your investment on his very best stock
selections.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about index funds and giant funds, those familiar names
that spread your money among hundreds of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   You can indeed take the first option by picking from a growing
number of mutual funds that invest in 30 or fewer stocks.
</P>
<P>
   They are called focused funds, or concentrated funds, and there
are scores of them. The number is growing now, as mutual fund
families elbow their way into yet one more investment niche.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is easy to understand: The fund manager can
concentrate on a handful of companies, and you get the benefit of
his very best work.
</P>
<P>
   The chart at right shows how attractive the returns can be, at
least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   But it also shows that focused funds are not a
one-decision-for-all-time way to beat the market. Among the
longest-lived funds, not a single one did as well as the S&AMP;P 500
index over a 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is the volatility that goes with
owning fewer stocks. If one goes bad, the impact is greater on a
less-diversified portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving the manager more freedom and making stock
picking more important,'' explained analyst Russ Kinnel of
Morningstar, a leading fund research company. ``That's great if you
have a great stock picker. But in the hands of an average stock
picker, it's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Focused funds tend to cluster among the best performers _ and
the worst. ``What happens is that people notice the ones at the
top,'' Kinnel said.
</P>
<P>
   You can get some very good years with a focused fund. But if the
market has a bad year, a focused fund may well have a very bad
year. That suggests that risk-averse investors probably ought to
stay away from focused funds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a focused fund may be interesting for investors who
already own larger, more diversified funds. ``If you've got a
couple of those, a focused fund isn't really taking on much risk,''
Kinnel said. ``And if you're going to bet on active management
rather than indexing, why not really do it? Why not tack on a
focused fund, where stock picking really does matter?''
</P>
<P>
   If you're picking a focused fund, there are plenty of choices.
Morningstar now follows 132 focused funds that specialize in stocks
and that have been around for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   There are two selection techniques: Stick with established funds
that have a long track record, or go for the top performers in the
last year or two.
</P>
<P>
   I favor the old hands. Like Kinnel, I don't believe short-term
results mean much. If you go for the hot hands, it's important to
examine the fund manager carefully. Look for past performance at
other funds. Check out the manager's investment strategies and his
or her reputation. Don't forget to check the fund's investment
criteria _ large or small companies, growth or value companies,
U.S. or foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnel cites Tom Marsico and Bill Nygren as managers with good
records. Marsico runs the 2-year-old Marsico Focus Fund (46.1
percent return over the last year, 1-888-860-8686). Nygren is boss
of the 3-year-old Oakmark Select Fund (19.5 percent,
1-800-625-6275).
</P>
<P>
   Those two didn't make the chart below because it focuses on
one-year returns.
</P>
<P>
   Does that matter? Probably not. Remember, the best choices here
are the best managers.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
