r l BC-CIVIL-DIVORCE22-COX     12-21 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-DIVORCE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A healthy divorce? Approach minimizes anger, costs
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Remember the 1989 black comedy that
pitted a determined and irate Kathleen Turner against a brutal
Michael Douglas in a near-battle to the death?
</P>
<P>
   ``War of the Roses'' told the tale of a couple who became locked
in such a ruinous divorce that they thought nothing of destroying
their belongings and, eventually, each other.
</P>
<P>
   Time out.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants to come out punching when a divorce is on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that never leaves you,'' says Boca Raton lawyer
Valerie Kanouse of her own difficult divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Her marriage ended in 1987, two years after her husband left
her, but years before custody battles and appeals ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't understand the psychic damage that you
suffer going through this trauma. I thought there has to be a
better way.''
</P>
<P>
   She found it, she says, in an emerging movement toward a kinder,
gentler divorce.
</P>
<P>
   It's called collaborative divorce, and it means that lawyers for
both parties sign a contract promising not to go to court, but to
try to settle amicably.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no settlement, the lawyers withdraw from the case.
</P>
<P>
   The concept, which binds the lawyers through the agreement, was
developed in 1996 by Stuart Webb, a Minneapolis lawyer who tired of
seeing clients pull each other apart, especially during divorces.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're suggesting is, let's not file anything in the
courts. Let's start working on the agreement right off. When we
come up with an agreement, than we file a dissolution with the
agreement attached. Both sides file that,'' Kanouse said.
</P>
<P>
   The object is to minimize anger and save money by avoiding a
prolonged court battle. Initially, you eliminate ``the psychic
satisfaction out of filing for divorce,'' Kanouse said, but you
also eliminate _ or at least postpone _ the vitriolic war that can
scar both the couple and any children involved.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is this approach won't work for everyone.
Certainly, it doesn't work for people who want revenge, where
assets are thought to be buried by a spouse, or where there is
domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   And failure to get an agreement would mean starting over with
new lawyers for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   But those supporting this approach say it's worth a try for
couples who are motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can kick butt like you never saw it kicked,'' says Don
Dowling, a Delray Beach lawyer who is one of two male attorneys to
join the fledgling Collaborative Divorce Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not the approach to take in all cases.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wouldn't ``push it'' on anyone seeking a divorce, but
would offer it as an option.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach lawyer Robin Roshkind says, ``Psychologically,
it makes the parties more committed to settle. The couple has said
they don't want to fight about it, get it over with. There's a
spirit of cooperation because they have the same goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the process is new, none of the 16 lawyers who has so
far joined the association has handled such a case yet.
</P>
<P>
   Kanouse, however, sees it increasing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to encourage you to get a Rambo lawyer. The whole
family gets hurt, but the lawyers make money. With this, clients
and attorneys should be aligned.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Susman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: carolynsusman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
