A5188 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX     12-21 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fat cat's my aspiration
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLIS, Fla. _ Just in case reincarnation is an option, I've
made up my mind to come back as a fish-camp cat because from what
I've seen lately, it's a pretty good life. In exchange for racking
up an occasional mouse, there is the promise of warm nights and
endless fresh fish. Best of all, there are tourists to shmooz.
</P>
<P>
   Fish camp, for the benefit of those who have never experienced
it, is a place where folks go to get away from their comfortable
beds and user-friendly plumbing. It's a place with roach motels
under the sink and Red Dog beer bottle caps under the sofa. There
are bare bulbs overhead, no closets, and the showers are straight
out of Bates Motel.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I go, I wonder why. I don't enjoy fishing because I'd
feel lousy about killing a perfectly healthy fish when I could buy
one that's already in the can. And I find the great outdoors most
appealing when I'm on the inside looking out at it.
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason that has not yet made itself clear to me,
about twice a year I wind up in a fish-camp cabin on the edge of a
lake in central Florida, frying bacon, boiling grits, and catering
three squares a day for Big Tom, the fish-camp cat.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tom, as his name indicates, is an oversize beauty built like
maybe he's just recently retired from the Packers starting lineup.
He moved into my cabin the same night I did. All I had to offer him
was some half-and-half that I'd picked up for my morning coffee. I
poured two fingers in a bowl and set it beside the door.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tom sniffed the cream then looked up at me with that ``Is
this the best you can do?'' look cats do so well. I found myself
making excuses, late flight, closed stores, and promising to do
better in the morning. Big Tom thought it over and then, just to be
polite I guess, lapped enough cream to coat his whiskers. While I
unpacked, he sat on the sofa washing up.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Big Tom stayed long enough to help me make the bed
and check out the bathroom. I let him go in first, just in case.
While I showered, Big Tom sat on the toilet lid and talked to me of
the cabbages and kings of the fish-camp kitty world. He told me of
the granddaddy gator who lives in the boat inlet, and filled me in
on a family of pileated woodpeckers who hang out in the cypress
tree beside the dock. I paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   While I dried, Big Tom preened and purred and stretched out on
the carpet to be admired. He even let me stroke his lush black coat
a couple of times before wandering out into the night. I asked if
he'd be coming back to sleep. He didn't answer so I closed the door
and turned in.
</P>
<P>
   The early morning fog muffled the slapping of the waves against
the dock as the fishing boats churned down the inlet and headed for
the lake. Big Tom wandered in from his nightly prowl and while I
rustled us up some bacon and grits, he fell into a deep sleep on
the sofa. Pretty soon he was dreaming _ whiskers twitching, paws
waggling. Guess maybe the gator was chasing him.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, Big Tom curled up on my pillow as I dressed to
go to the store. He never stirred when I tiptoed out the open front
door or when I came back in.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it went for the week. In exchange for kitty treats
and cozy napping places, Big Tom allowed me to scratch behind his
ears and tell him what a fine fellow he was. Once I even asked who
he might have been in his previous life. Of course, he didn't
answer. All he did was break into one of those enigmatic grins that
cats do so well and blink several times, quite deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tom, I suspect, has been around for many moons. I just wish
I could figure out how to get his job when we both move on.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431; E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
