<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SINGLE-BUT-HAPPY22-CO     12-21 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-BUT-HAPPY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe for happiness: good neighbors, time, energy
 &HT;    By Mara Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's not quantity of dates that does it. It's not
money, or education, or even the boyfriend or girlfriend of the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The single people who are happiest with Dayton, Ohio, and with
their lives, find these things: a neighborhood where they have
friends, not just vaguely familiar faces; the time to follow their
interests; and the energy to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mahan, 33, loves his neighborhood. He moved there with his
former partner, with grand plans to renovate a Victorian home and
only a small hammer for hanging pictures and no clue of how to
start.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the architecture that captured his heart. It's the
friendships in historic McPherson Town that keep him tethered to
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton's not the largest, most cosmopolitan city we know,'' he
said. ``You seek out the people that you have things in common with
and the things you like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To newcomers having trouble finding their place, he advised
moving into a historic neighborhood. ``I think all of the historic
neighborhoods, you just have an immediate sense of camaraderie, and
they truly are neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied singles make peace with their past, which makes them
open to the present's possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Caren Ostendorf is a woman at ease in her own skin. You'd know
that if you saw her out salsa dancing this summer or fall, her
heels rapping against the dance floor, her hips rocking in time.
She had tiny brown braids all over her head and a delighted smile.
</P>
<P>
   She's 35, but sort of feels like she's 25 and could easily pass
for twentysomething. She wears swoopy scarves, clunky heels and
short skirts, and her nieces _ she's from a six-kid Catholic family
and is the last single left _ ask why their moms can't dress as
cool as she does.
</P>
<P>
   She pokes fun at her dating track record _ frequently with
foreigners, people of different faiths and one boyfriend 20 years
older. ``My mother says I date people that I cannot marry,'' she
said. She thinks her mother might be right.
</P>
<P>
   It's been several years since she's had a serious relationship,
and she's only had a handful in the last 15 years. She'd like to
find a husband and have children, but it's mostly on her mind when
she's dating again. Is he the one? Can I imagine 40 years with him?
Would he be a good dad?
</P>
<P>
   A year or two ago, she put an ad in the personals and loaded it
with humor, touting her great teeth (like a thoroughbred's) and
good genes. The calls just didn't stop. For six months, response
after response. Many she didn't even bother to meet. And those she
did, she said she wished she hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met so many guys _ so many times I thought I'd rather be
home reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``That taught me a lot. I realized that I was just really happy
with my life. An addition would be great. (But) the energy and time
you take to look for somebody _ you feel like it's such a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Her neighbor just down the block in St. Anne's Hill became her
latest boyfriend. He's a foreign graduate student, studying
biology. They've only been seeing each other a few months, and
she's not sure where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   That uncertainty defines single life and has to be accepted to
feel OK about being single.
</P>
<P>
   Rick figures he'll have a life partner at some point. Since he
and his boyfriend of eight years split a year ago, dating hasn't
become serious, and he doesn't mind. He has a friendly face, a
confident manner, a sense of style _ he's rarely at a loss for
companionship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at myself as eligible and not single,'' he said.
``Single sounds so lonely, and I'm far from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does he meet men? Where doesn't he, is more like it. At
the gas station, (''We had good eye contact''), at a restaurant
(his waiter), through friends, at bars. ...
</P>
<P>
   He won't meet them through the antique/architectural salvage
store he owns. ``There's business and there's pleasure, and never
the two shall meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And he hates matchmaking. ``I don't want my mother choosing
partners for me, and I don't want you choosing my partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he laughs at some of the flaky things dates have
said to him, he said he gets something out of every date and
doesn't regret any of his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Ju-an Norvell, 27, of Trotwood, also easily meets new
acquaintances everywhere _ at stoplights, in grocery stores. ``I
cannot look at someone in your face and not speak,'' he said. ``I
just enjoy people, period. I guess I have a friendly spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ju-an said the hardest thing about dating isn't finding dates _
with an impish grin, he said the longest he's gone without a date
might be three weeks, maybe a month. It's finding women who are
secure in themselves so they can be secure with you.
</P>
<P>
   While Ju-an also describes himself as very happy with his single
life, he's still a little uncertain about the future and the
relationships it may hold. His parents are divorced, his divorced
sister just moved back in with their mom, and many of the married
couples he sees don't seem too happy.
</P>
<P>
   When his girlfriend Monica got pregnant two years ago, after
four months of dating, he refused to marry her _ and she was not
pleased, he said. They're moving toward marriage now, he said, but
he's still anxious _ even with an adorable daughter in the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone goes into it with some kind of fear,'' he
said. ``How are things going to turn out?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all these happy singles were always pleased with the Dayton
area as a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   Rick hated Dayton when he moved here eight years ago from
Cincinnati, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I whined about Dayton being too small of a town, that it was
too blue-collar of a city,'' he said. ``It was a culture shock for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the neighbors he met introduced him to more people, and he
found his comfort zone. Meeting people builds on itself. Networking
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Keller, 34, moved here from Charlotte, N.C., in 1989 to
work at Emery Worldwide, and he likes Dayton much better than that
fast-growing city. In Dayton, he said, ``you meet a lot of people
through other people. Decent people, anyway.'' In Charlotte,
``There are so many people that you can't even get around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mara Lee writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio. John
Keilman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
