</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, December 22, 1999 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're feeling a
little down in the mouth because you didn't win the big lottery
last Wednesday, for heaven's sake set aside your selfish worries
for just one minute and start obsessing about something that
actually matters in this wild, whacked-out world of ours. Me. I
think I won $6.3 million in the lottery back in 1993 and never
collected. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The United Nations has no standing in the
Israeli-Syrian or Israeli-Palestinian peace talks but there's a way
the U.N. could be helpful even so. It could get off Israel's back.
In more diplomatic but still firm language, that was the message
from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in a recent speech. (Teepen,
Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ This subject is, in the coinage of the
recently late Joseph Heller, a Catch-22. It is about where in
automobiles children ought to be sitting _ or, rather, where they
should not be sitting. For some time, it was judged that children
should not be sitting in the front seat because of erupting air
bags in an accident. Now, according to a study done by the Los
Angeles Times, they also should not be sitting in the back seat,
this based on unsubstantial front seats that pitch backwards.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ INGLIS, Fla. _ Just in case reincarnation is an
option, I've made up my mind to come back as a fish-camp cat
because from what I've seen lately, it's a pretty good life. In
exchange for racking up an occasional mouse, there is the promise
of warm nights and endless fresh fish. Best of all, there are
tourists to shmooz. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIGGINS-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Joseph Heller is my
favorite living author,'' I began a 1980 column about the author of
Catch-22. This was 19 years before his death last week at 76. ``If
he were dead, he'd be among my top five or six dead authors.''
(Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ They call it the NAMES Project, but
it can't always be true to that. Thousands of hand-made sections
make up the immense AIDS quilt that travels the country. Most have
names. Then there are squares like the one dedicated to John Doe,
or to many of them _ ``actor,'' ``artist,'' ``teacher,'' ``nurse.''
It signifies death certificates falsified to protect someone's
identity. We must ask ourselves why it is that our society has made
it necessary for people with such an important story to need
anonymity. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
