<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHRISTIANITY-WORLD26-     12-21 2193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-WORLD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Mission fields yield a rich harvest
 &HT;    (Eds: This is part of the final installment of Cox's
Christianity at 2000 series. The series, written by Gayle White of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with
feeds from Cox religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run
since January. This package looks at the present state of
Christianity and its growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa
and Asia. Art is available including charts/maps on Christianity's
growth. This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for Dec.
26. A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication. This package includes the
following slugs: CHRISTIANITY-WORLD, CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA,
CHRISTIANITY-ASIA, CHRISTIANITY-LATIN, CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA. All are
moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Walk into any church in metro Atlanta at Christmastime
and you're likely to hear the same carols _ the wistful strains of
``O Come, O Come Emmanuel,'' the invitational ``O Come, Let Us
Adore Him'' and the effusive ``Joy to the World.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the tunes are familiar at the chapel at Shallowford
Presbyterian Church, you probably won't recognize the words. The
chapel is the home of Hanbit Korean Presbyterian Church, one of the
fastest-growing congregations in the Presbytery of Greater Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hanbit (a transliteration of the Korean words for ``one light'')
represents the completion of a circle that began more than 110
years ago when Presbyterian men and women from America traveled to
the mission fields of Korea. Today, there are almost twice as many
Presbyterians in Korea as in the United States, and South Korean
Presbyterian churches are sending out more missionaries than their
American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the United States now is a mission field for the Korean
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of Korean churches, we first received the gospel
through American missionaries,'' said the Rev. Sung Joo Park,
Hanbit's pastor. ``Now the case is reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of all major Christian denominations talk in similar
terms as they survey the Christian world today: the ``center of
gravity'' has shifted from Western Europe and North America, and
the future of the faith is in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some evidence:
</P>
<P>
   _ One in three Roman Catholic cardinals is from the so-called
Third World, and both Asia and Africa have more members of the
College of Cardinals (15 and 14, respectively) than the United
States (12). An African cardinal is considered one of the top
contenders to be the next pope.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Archbishop of Canterbury, presiding cleric of Anglicanism,
opened the once-a-decade Lambeth Conference in England last year by
greeting the congregation in Swahili. Of the 736 bishops
registered, only 316 _ less than half _ were from the United
States, Canada and Europe combined. Africa sent 224 and Asia 95.
</P>
<P>
   _ Today, 58 percent of Protestants and two-thirdsistians
in Charismatic and Pentecostal churches _ a movement that began in
the United States in the early 20th century _ live in Africa, Asia
and Latin America. ``The gospel is no longer in western
captivity,'' says David Garrison, a vice president at the
International Mission Board of the 15.9 million-member Southern
Baptist Convention. ``It's every bit as at home in Beijing or
Shanghai as in Atlanta or Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   As Christians from China, Korea, Nigeria and Kenya relocate,
they are changing the face of the church in the United States and
sustaining some traditional denominations. In Georgia, for
instance, Southern Baptists have services in 37 languages, from
Arabic to Urdu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally for Southern Baptists, without the growth of the
ethnic and African-American congregations in the last number of
years, we would not have seen the positive growth we have been able
to report,'' said Jerry Baker, a specialist in non-English
ministries with the Georgia Baptist Convention. Until a slight loss
in 1998, the Southern Baptist Convention had increased in
membership every year since 1926.
</P>
<P>
   If the 2.6 million-member Presbyterian Church (USA) successfully
adapts to Asian and African immigrants, it will have a
``significant racial-ethnic majority'' by 2050, predicts Edwin
Albright, executive presbyter of the Presbytery of Greater Atlanta,
where the fastest-growing churches are international. ``If we
don't, I think the consequences are severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptizing the nations
</P>
<P>
   According to the gospel of Matthew, Jesus told his disciples,
``Go therefore and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in
the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   Christians through the ages have regarded the verses, known as
the ``Great Commission,'' as their marching orders. They have
spread the faith _ sometimes through violence, as during the
Crusades, but often through compassionate work. Church history is
full of accounts of martyrs who gave their lives telling others
about Jesus, beginning with St. Paul, whose epistles make up much
of the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   From the Middle East to the Roman Empire to the New World,
Christianity spread.
</P>
<P>
   By the 20th century, North Americans represented about
two-thirds of all Protestant foreign missionaries. Many spent years
in the field, establishing hospitals and schools, drilling wells
and building dams, and taking part in every phase of life from
delivering babies to caring for the dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who gave their lives to mission work and were
greatly revered by the people who were there,'' said Stephen
Gunter, professor of evangelism at Emory University's Candler
School of Theology. ``Some died while they were in their late 20s
and early 30s. Other people lived all their lives in another
cultural context, spending only a few years back in North America.
You look at the economic levels at which those people retire, and
people with 30, 40 or 50 years in missionary service could not
afford to buy a house in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, their efforts generated academic disciplines such as
anthropology and linguistics, said Darrell Guder,
secretary-treasurer of the American Society of Missiology and
professor of evangelism and church growth at Columbia Theological
Seminary in Decatur. ``Scholarship in these areas was profoundly
shaped by the missionary enterprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the United States, missionary efforts proved to be an
outlet for the creative energies of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women medical doctors were not accepted in America,'' said
Dana Robert, professor of world mission at Boston University.
``They went way out of proportion to their numbers as missionaries.
For years, women couldn't be ministers in most churches, but they
could be missionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Through correspondence from missionaries, American women began
to care about the spiritual and physical welfare of women in other
countries and raise money to help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to work for the upward lift of women in other
lands, American women also liberated themselves, tested their
skills and proved their competence,'' said Catherine Allen, a
25-year veteran of the Women's Missionary Union of the Southern
Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, women took the lead in funding mission work. The
Lottie Moon Christmas Offering of the Southern Baptist Convention
is a case in point. In 1888, Southern Baptist women initiated the
gift campaign in honor of a pioneer female missionary to China to
send more women to do mission work there. ``It didn't take but
about 10 years before even Lottie herself was saying the money
could be used for outreach to men, too,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   The offering is still a Southern Baptist tradition. This year it
will bring in more than $100 million to help support missions in
150 countries that have helped make Christianity the global
religion it is today.
</P>
<P>
   In the churches that grow out of mission efforts, women are the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see in African indigenous churches at least 70 percent of
the members are women,'' Robert said. ``In China, 80 percent of the
house church members are women. In Korea, most leaders of cell
groups in the largest church in the world are women. In Latin
America, over 70 percent of the new Pentecostals are women. It's a
global phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   The women who have flocked to those churches are taking
responsiblity for their missionary efforts at a time when the role
of women in missions in traditional American denominations is
diminishing, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is going to be different as leadership emerges from
other places,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sojourning missionaries
</P>
<P>
   With the end of colonialism and the development of indigenous
churches in the far reaches of the globe, international ecumenical
relationships have changed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Christianity and Western culture sometimes became
intertwined on the mission field, at times perpetuating the image
of the ``Ugly American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain process of deculturation that happens to
the local people when they, because of the power, wealth and status
of western Christians, tend to devalue their culture and take upon
western ways of doing things,'' said Thomas Thangaraj, professor of
world Christianity at Emory University's Candler School of
Theology.
</P>
<P>
   Although it still occurs, that is less likely to happen today,
experts say. And, in many areas where local communities establish
churches in their own cultures, Christianity is exploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at the way Africans are adapting rituals and customs
to their local culture, I think can encourage people in the United
States to think about how we should adapt rituals and customs to
our culture today,'' said Thomas Reese, a Jesuit scholar and editor
of America, a national weekly Catholic magazine. ``When we see
Africans dancing up the middle aisle of St. Peter's in Rome to
bring up the gifts at Mass, and hear them using drums and African
music, it shows us that, well, maybe we could do something from
American culture in our liturgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern American missionaries are more likely to serve as
consultants to native church leaders than to set up institutions
and run them. And while every major denomination still has career
missionaries, many groups now also have Peace Corps-like programs
that allow people to serve for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much different than it used to be,'' said Bonnie Jensen,
executive director of the division for global missions of the 3.8
million-member Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
``Missionaries are much more likely to be sojourners. They stay for
a time until they're not needed any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, American denominations fund the education of
natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years, we have had 350 international
scholarship recipients who have worked on master's or doctoral
degrees,'' Jensen said. ``They've gone back to their churches and
filled positions that decades ago would have been filled by
missionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   More American congregations are also sponsoring mission trips or
funding individual mission volunteers. Among United Methodists in
the Southeast, for example, more than 25,000 people traveled last
year to mission sites, most outside the United States, for periods
of a few days to two or three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a phenomenal thing,'' said Allan Kirtin, director of
the Mission Resource Center for the 8.5 million-member United
Methodist Church. ``It's happening without too much structure. It's
happening as the spirit moves.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have worked abroad are likely to gain a new
appreciation for the global scope of the faith. In metro Atlanta,
having Christian neighbors who speak other languages and worship in
different styles also sharpens awareness.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta's Roman Catholic Archbishop John F. Donoghue
traveled to Nigeria last year, he came home with enthusiasm for the
worship and commitment of poverty-stricken Catholics there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The churches on Sunday are packed with people,'' he said.
``The homilies go on forever. The music is great. They have a lot
of joyful celebration. It's really humbling to go to a place like
that and see so much faith despite the conditions in which they
live.''
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop traveled with the Rev. Martin Kalu, a Nigerian
priest whose mother's family was converted to Christianity by
missionaries who entered Nigeria in 1885. Now Kalu has been
assigned by his Nigerian bishop to be a missionary to the Atlanta
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Here on his own mission field in April, Kalu was one of hundreds
of Catholics of all colors and nationalities who filled the
Cathedral of Christ the King to see Cardinal Francis Arinze, the
Nigerian priest many people think may be the next pope.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican visitor's prominence speaks well of the coming of
age of African Christianity, Kalu said, ``but whether they pick him
or not, the church in Africa will be flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
