<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHRISTIANITY-LATIN26-     12-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-LATIN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Catholic church trying to stop erosion of
popularity in Latin America
 &HT;    (Eds: This is part of the final installment of Cox's
Christianity at 2000 series. The series, written by Gayle White of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with
feeds from Cox religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run
since January. This package looks at the present state of
Christianity and its growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa
and Asia. Art is available including charts/maps on Christianity's
growth. This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for Dec.
26. A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication. This package includes the
following slugs: CHRISTIANITY-WORLD, CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA,
CHRISTIANITY-ASIA, CHRISTIANITY-LATIN, CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA. All are
moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Susan Ferriss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Nearly 500 years ago, fervently Catholic priests
captured the spirit of this country and the rest of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Vatican is trying to reconquer this hemisphere by
fighting the spread of secularism and Protestantism in a region
that now represents the largest bloc of Catholics in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is a 90-percent Catholic nation that has been bloodied by
civil war over the power and influence of religion. Earlier this
year, during a visit here Pope John Paul II bestowed Mexico a
special role in cementing Catholic faith in this hemisphere for the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is sort of like Poland for the Pope,'' said Bernardo
Barranco, president of the Center for Studies of Religion in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Catholic Poland gnawed at the communist Soviet Union,
Barranco said, Pope John Paul II considers Mexico a bulwark against
the secularism and Protestant influence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is also a country where Catholicism has sunk deep roots
in popular culture. Everyone in Mexico from traditional village
housewives to gay activists embrace the brown-skinned figure of
Mexico's Virgin of Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   The church in Mexico has thrived despite more than a century of
laws that conflict with Vatican doctrine. Limited divorce was
available in the late 1800s and was offered in full in 1917. With
the exception of abortion, the government has eagerly pushed birth
control since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mexico re-established diplomatic relations with the
Vatican, which had been severed in 1861 by reformist President
Benito Juarez. In the wake of the 1910 Mexican Revolution, the
church was stripped of vast land holdings and relegated to
non-legal status. Priests, who were viewed as allies of an
oppressive upper-class, were barred from voting or even wearing
vestments publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, devout rebels attempted to defend the church by
waging a civil war in central Mexico. It wasn't until 1991,
however, that Mexico restored the church's legal status.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Catholic Church has gained political ground this
decade. Politicians feel freer to profess their faith and meet with
clergy, and the church is attempting to overturn bans on church
access to television and public education.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Mexico, Chile and Argentina only recently began
to dismantle some laws based on a conservative Catholic identity.
Until 1994 Argentina's constitution required that the president be
Catholic. In Chile, divorce is still outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic concern shared throughout the Americas is the advance
of Protestantism, including evangelical faiths. Some rough
estimates put the Protestant population in Latin America at 12 or
13 percent, up from 4 percent in 1960 and 1 percent in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala might be as much as 20 percent Protestant. Protestant
missionaries have made inroads into the Mexican state of Chiapas,
where poor indigenous women especially have embraced teachings that
eschew spending money on alcohol and village festivities. Brazil,
the biggest Catholic country in the world, is also seeing a surge
in Protestantism and beliefs rooted in African traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church has tried to stem desertions by
incorporating Indian or other local cultural practices into
services. A trend called ``renovation,'' which includes speaking in
tongues and spirit possession, is also ``a shot in the arm for
Catholicism in Latin America,'' said Virginia Burnett, a religious
studies expert at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the Vatican punished some priests for practicing
so-called liberation theology, which borrowed from Marxism and was
strong in Brazil and Central America. Since the collapse of
communism, the church has tried to show concern for Latin America
by condemning a widening gap between rich and poor and calling for
a mass forgiveness on the region's huge foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is an institution that finds it hard to be
dynamic,'' said sociologist and religion specialist Oscar Aguilar
of Mexico's Iberoamericana University. ``The challenge of the
church is to find its place in modernity and democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
