<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA26     12-21 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Orthodox Church carves out new role in
post-Soviet Russia
 &HT;    (Eds: This is part of the final installment of Cox's
Christianity at 2000 series. The series, written by Gayle White of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with
feeds from Cox religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run
since January. This package looks at the present state of
Christianity and its growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa
and Asia. Art is available including charts/maps on Christianity's
growth. This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for Dec.
26. A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication. This package includes the
following slugs: CHRISTIANITY-WORLD, CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA,
CHRISTIANITY-ASIA, CHRISTIANITY-LATIN, CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA. All are
moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Golden-domed and imposing, the lavishly reconstructed
19th-century Christ the Savior Cathedral, near the Kremlin, stands
as a striking symbol of just how far religion has come since the
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolsheviks blew up the original church and built a swimming
pool in its place in their effort to demean the Russian Orthodox
Church and its imperial past.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the nation's new post-Soviet royalty _ powerful
politicians and capitalists _ resurrected the church on the same
site, with the help of small contributions from countless
churchgoers across Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Moscow and the rest of Russia, sparkling new
onion-domed churches are rising from the rubble of the Soviet Union
_ some 9,000 new parishes since Communist rule fell in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   As Christianity enters its third millennium, the Russian
Orthodox Church is back, though in Soviet times it never really
went away. The church was a survivor and, evidence suggests, a
Soviet collaborator that has now emerged as a powerful political
and economic force in the new Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communism collapsed and there was nothing there to replace
it,'' said Vladimir Pravotorov, editor of Science and Religion, a
scholarly journal, explaining the sudden surge of popular interest
in the church in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The decades-long taboo lifted, it was cool to be religious.
President Boris Yeltsin publicly embraced the church's Patriarch
Alexy II. A parade of politicians, writers and rock stars became
churchgoers, along with crowds of ordinary Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Even godless Communists found religion. Communist Party leader
Gennady Zyuganov looked for photo ops with the church hierarchy in
the 1996 national elections, and his party two years ago pushed
major legislation bestowing special status on the church.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Orthodox Church remains among the most trusted
institutions in Russia, no small feat in a country battered by
economic problems and apathetic toward their corruption-riddled
government.
</P>
<P>
   But the allure of churchgoing has worn off. The church remains
an important symbol of nationalism and new church buildings are
going up, but attendance is down.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to recover properties it lost during Soviet times,
the church has diversified in the new free-market economy, dabbling
in banking, oil and tobacco imports among other enterprises it
operates tax-free. The church does not disclose its finances.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russians view the church as just another powerful and
wealthy institution not to be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Orthodox Church would like to play the role of state
church in the same way Islam operates in Iran,'' said Katya
Smyslova, an attorney for the non-profit Institute of Religion and
Law. The group has challenged a 1997 law pushed by the Orthodox
Church, which restricts the activities of other religions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics saw the law as an attempt to enshrine Orthodoxy as the
national religion, a status it held for nearly a millennium under
royalty that ruled Russia until the revolution of 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the Russian Orthodox and other major Christian
churches have been rocky for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Orthodox leader, Alexy, has rejected repeated
proposals for a papal visit to Russia, frustrating the efforts of
John Paul II. The Roman Catholic leader made improving relations
among Christians a key goal of the papacy in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Russian church lent its qualified support to
Russia's war in Chechnya, disappointing international and Russian
human rights groups who had hoped the church would use its moral
authority to denounce the war.
</P>
<P>
   But controversy has never been the church's strong suit. In
imperial Russia, the church acted at the whim of the tsars. In
Soviet times, some priests were persecuted, while others served the
KGB and the church quietly survived.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the church is a national icon, representing continuity
and stability in a country that has lived through a century of
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is an important symbol, but does not have a
practical influence on daily life,'' said Yuri Levada, director of
the Russian Center for Public Opinion and Market Research.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
