<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHRISTIANITY-ADVISORY     12-21 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN NEWS, FEATURES, RELIGION EDITORS: Final installment of
Christianity series
</P>
<P>
   The final installment of Cox's Christianity at 2000 series is
now available. The series, written by Gayle White of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with feeds from Cox
religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run since January.
</P>
<P>
   This package looks at the present state of Christianity and its
growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa and Asia. Art
includes charts/maps from the Atlanta Journal-Constitution on
Christianity's growth.
</P>
<P>
   This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for the weekend
of Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories. All have moved, in the (l) Lifestyle and
(i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   For the weekend of Sunday, Dec. 26
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-WORLD _ The spread of Christianity transformed the
Western world. As the third millennium approaches, the movement is
far removed from what it was as its inception. Today, almost one
third of the world's population is Christian. For believers, Jesus
is the hinge of history. But even by secular standards, Jesus is
the dominant figure of Western culture. In this last installment of
a yearlong project, we explore the growth of Christianity around
the world, especially its impact in Asia and Africa and
re-emergence in Russia. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 50.
WITH PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS .
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Across Moscow and the rest of
Russia, sparkling new onion-domed churches are rising from the
rubble of Communism. The Russian Orthodox Church is back, though in
Soviet times it never really went away. The church was a survivor,
and some say collaborator, that has now emerged as a powerful
political and economic force in the new Russia. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 45.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-ASIA _ SEOUL, South Korea _ This region of the
world has been one of the more painful ones for Christians and
their beliefs. They face persecution everywhere. Vietnamese police
have raided a number of Christian gatherings across the country in
recent months, detaining and harassing scores of worshipers.
Vietnam's Christian population is unclear, although the country of
79 million has 8 million Catholics, the largest community in
Southeast Asia outside the Philippines. But in secular South Korea,
the number is growing and becoming one of the most active churches
in East Asia. (Kirk, Cox News Service) 40.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-LATIN _ MEXICO CITY _ In this fervently Catholic
country, they build shrines by the thousands and crawl on their
knees to honor the Virgin Mary at her own special basilica. The
main purpose of the pope's trip to Mexico earlier this year _ his
fourth trip to this country _ was to address challenges to the
Catholic Church in the Americas, the most Catholic region in the
world. Mexico is considered a geographic powerhouse for the Vatican
because it is a bridge between South America and North America,
where the church is concerned about the spread of materialism and
secularism. And Mexico, whose Catholic population is second only to
Brazil in number, is home to the Basilica of the Virgin of
Guadalupe, the second-most visited Catholic sanctuary in the world
after St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
40.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA _ KUMASI, Ghana _ Christian missionaries
began pouring into Africa in the late 19th century, saving souls
and offering a Western worldview that dramatically changed the
ideas that shaped this continent in the last century. Today
Christians are part of the fabric of this land. And missionaries
continue to come. Mike Mozley, a missionary from Marietta, Ga.,
moved his wife and three children to Ghana this year. We take a
look at the growth of Christianity through his mission. (Melvin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday, Jan 1
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-FUTURE _ For thousands of years, Christians in
Europe and the Americas have led the faithful. In coming years
there's a chance that the growth of the religion will be centered
in Asia and Africa. In fact, the largest Christian church in the
world today is in Korea, not the Bible belt of America. In this
last installment of our yearlong report on the millennium and
Christianity, we look into the future and explore the direction the
church seems headed in the next century. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
