<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA26     12-21 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: Flourishing under African skies
 &HT;    (Eds: This is part of the final installment of Cox's
Christianity at 2000 series. The series, written by Gayle White of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with
feeds from Cox religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run
since January. This package looks at the present state of
Christianity and its growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa
and Asia. Art is available including charts/maps on Christianity's
growth. This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for Dec.
26. A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication. This package includes the
following slugs: CHRISTIANITY-WORLD, CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA,
CHRISTIANITY-ASIA, CHRISTIANITY-LATIN, CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA. All are
moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (WITH PHOTOS.)
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACCRA, Ghana _ The Rev. Mathias Forson has prepared a special
sermon for Christmas, one that celebrates not only that special day
but his special congregation.
</P>
<P>
   To the 400 or so residents of Accra who manage to squeeze their
way into the Bethany Methodist Church in the Dzorlu area of Ghana's
capital, Forson will try to explain the meaning of Christmas in the
context of Africa. He will take as his text John 1:14 _ ``And the
Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Forson, a native Ghanaian who earned a master's degree from
Emory University in Atlanta 10 years ago, believes that, contrary
to the teachings of some early missionaries, Christianity and
Africanism are complementary and not at all at odds. One need not
expunge from people all traces of native culture for them to become
Christians, he says. Instead, the word of Christ can dwell among
the people of Africa and find the culture to be very fertile soil
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The facts bear him out. Africa, which had 9.9 million Christians
at the beginning of this century, has 203 million as the century
ends. Each year, the continent has 6 million more Christians than
it had the year before, and 1.5 million of those are converts,
according to a new study by David Barret, a British clergyman who
edited the first-ever world Christian encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   And the rate of growth seems only to be increasing. In 1970,
about 12 percent of Africans were Christian. Now, nearly half are.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, in 1970, one-tenth of all the Christians in the
world were Africans. Now the continent is home to more than a fifth
of the world's Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is growing faster in Africa now than
anywhere else. In 1968, there were about 29 million Catholics in
Africa; by last year the number had nearly quadrupled, to 114
million.
</P>
<P>
   And the total number of Protestants during that period grew much
faster, from 8 million to nearly 108 million _ a 13-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
   That phenomenal growth is reflected in Forson's church. Two
years ago, when he became pastor at Bethany Methodist, the
congregation numbered about 200 members. Now, though the church
seats only 350 people comfortably, the congregation has swelled to
700. Forson must hold two services each Sunday and sometimes he
must broadcast the service through loudspeakers to those sitting
outside.
</P>
<P>
   He is building a new church next door. When it is finished the
new church will seat as many as 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   Faces of faith
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Mathias Forson exemplifies the new African
Christians. Not only is he making converts, he is one. He wears the
collar of a cleric, but his face bears the scars of traditional
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Now 49, Forson grew up in central Ghana in a family whose
spiritual relationship to the world was based not on Christianity
but on beliefs native to Africa. His parents believed strongly in
evil spirits that cause everything from disaster to disease,
spirits from whom potent protection was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Before Forson was a year old, a practitioner of traditional
medicine cut inch-long diagonal slices in his cheeks. Medicine was
rubbed into cuts to ward off the spirits and protect the child.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached high school, where he was a boarding
student, Forson was drinking, smoking and chasing girls _ and his
efforts to reform had come to naught. Then a British missionary
came to the school to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that someone would come all this way to share this
message with us, that meant a lot to me,'' Forson said.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted Christ, he said, and joy flooded into his life. He
dropped his old habits and found a better way to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started sharing with my friends, who were really
surprised,'' he said. ``I made quite a number of converts, because
my life was a testament. They knew me.''
</P>
<P>
   But if his friends were accepting, his family was not. When
Forson refused to go to a practitioner of traditional medicine, his
father became angry. Forson was practicing the religion of
outsiders, the religion of Westerners, his father complained.
</P>
<P>
   We have our own religion, his father, Kweku Seidu, argued. Let's
not give up what we have.
</P>
<P>
   Forson persisted in his Christianity, and, after several years,
his father changed his mind and converted to Christianity, changing
his name to Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Forson eventually traveled to Atlanta, where in 1989 he earned a
master's degree in theology at Emory, followed by a Ph.D. at Asbury
Theological Seminary in Wilmore, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw the lifestyle lived by many people in the United
States _ opulent, compared to that of many Ghanaians _ he
appreciated even more what Western missionaries left behind when
they came to Ghana to preach the word. And that made their message
even more meaningful to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a missionary to my own people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch export
</P>
<P>
   Christianity in sub-Saharan Africa dates from 1652, when
officials of the Dutch East India Co. arrived in Table Bay, on the
southern tip of the continent, near the current site of Cape Town,
South Africa. They brought with them plans to found a settlement _
and Dutch Reformed beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist faith was introduced to the continent 141 years
later, in 1792, when David George, a former slave from South
Carolina, reached Sierra Leone on Africa's west coast.
</P>
<P>
   But for many more years, Christianity remained limited to the
fringes of the continent. It was not until the latter part of the
19th century that the religion began to penetrate the interior of
Africa, following the call by the explorer David Livingstone to
stamp out the slave trade inside Africa by opening the continent to
the three C's _ civilization, commerce and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   In the 126 years since Livingstone died, frozen in prayer at his
bedside near Lake Bangweulu in what is now Zambia, thousands of
missionaries have worked this vast territory with, overall,
considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for that success, though, can sometimes be difficult
to determine.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Joseph, a professor of political science at Emory
University, attributes much of the growth to the ``prolonged period
of economic difficulties that most people in the continent have
been experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph spent time this year in Nigeria, the most populous
country in Africa, where he witnessed ``phenomenal'' growth in
revivalist-style sects _ growth that has paralleled the country's
economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is plain is the churches are really becoming a very
public sanctuary for many people,'' Joseph said. ``You can't help
but sense that the churches are providing some meaning for lives
that on the face of it are pretty desolate.''
</P>
<P>
   And many people see yet another reason for the recent remarkable
growth of Christianity in Africa. In many cases, Africans are no
longer being told that they have to deny their Africanism in order
to be good Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is major work going on by Africans in
interpreting Christianity against an African background, and that's
something that Westerners are not going to be able to help with
very much,'' said Mark Noll, the author of ``Turning Points:
Decisive Moments in the History of Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern missionaries
</P>
<P>
   Some of that work is being done by Mathias Forson. He deeply
believes, contrary to early missionaries, that African culture and
Christianity can co-exist, and even complement each other, in the
same person.
</P>
<P>
   But Westerners can still help somewhat. Forson, for example,
receives help from Mike Mozley, with the Mission Society for United
Methodists, who moved his family from suburban Atlanta to Kumasi,
Ghana, this summer to work with Ghanaian Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The techniques many modern missionaries bring to Africa differ
from those of earlier Christians, who would sometimes go so far as
to set up villages in which they could isolate potential converts
from all African influences.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Mozley favors ministries that attend to all
people's needs, that work to improve their physical as well as
their spiritual health.
</P>
<P>
   And he is spending his first year doing little besides settling
in, acclimating himself and his family to the culture, and doing
more learning than teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the Ghanaians I came with big ears and big eyes and a
small mouth,'' Mozley said. ``I affirm the African people.''
</P>
<P>
   A sermon in three languages
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly of God church in Gueckedou, Guinea, has a dirt
floor, mud-brick walls and a tin roof. But it vibrates with music,
singing and joy.
</P>
<P>
   The church is packed to overflowing, and here, as at Forson's
church in Accra, church leaders are building a new, larger church
to accommodate the growth in the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Gueckedou is dominated by the green minarets of a hilltop
mosque. The streets are crowded with men in boubous, the
shimmering, ankle-length robes worn by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Religions are spread not only by missionaries but by the
movement of people. The neighboring country of Sierra Leone, where
freed slaves from the new world introduced Christianity, has been
racked by civil war. Hundreds of thousands of refugees have fled
across the border to Guinea, adding a dollop of Christianity to the
heavily Muslim city.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation is made up largely of those refugees, but some
Guineans have been attracted to the church, too. The service is
conducted in three languages simultaneously _ English, the language
of Sierra Leone; French, the national language of Guinea; and
Kissi, the local tribal language.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims here argue bitterly that Christianity is a western
religion, not one for Africans, but Pastor David Kondiano
disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the church is not only for white men,'' Kondiano
said. ``We believe that the Bible is for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Forson's central belief. Christianity is growing so fast
in Africa, he said, in part because Africans begin as very
spiritual people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The African by nature is religious,'' Forson said. ``Atheism
is the belief that there is no God. That is not an African problem.
An African is born with a knowledge of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My major thesis has been: How can we become truly African and
truly Christian?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Forson will not tell his congregation in his sermon today
that the evil spirits in which they believe do not exist. He will
say instead that the church offers more powerful protection against
those spirits.
</P>
<P>
   He will say that Christmas reminds us that God is no longer to
be seen as transcendent and far removed. He has come down in the
person of Jesus Christ to be involved in our struggles, to identify
with our needs and bring joy and peace to our world.
</P>
<P>
   Forson will discuss what the message of Christmas means for
people who live on a continent rife with ethnic conflicts, wars and
rumors of war. And he will appeal passionately, he said, for
Africans to allow Christ to rule in their hearts so that they can
experience his peace and the protection he offers from the forces
of the evil one who fights against them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
