<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHRISTIANITY-ASIA26-C     12-21 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIANITY-ASIA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: History, influence throughout Asia
 &HT;    (Eds: This is part of the final installment of Cox's
Christianity at 2000 series. The series, written by Gayle White of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and edited by Ron Feinberg with
feeds from Cox religion writers and foreign correspondents, has run
since January. This package looks at the present state of
Christianity and its growth areas in South America, Russia, Africa
and Asia. Art is available including charts/maps on Christianity's
growth. This package is available as a CoxNet Focus page for Dec.
26. A final article, on the future of Christianity, will move the
week of Dec. 27 for Jan. 1 publication. This package includes the
following slugs: CHRISTIANITY-WORLD, CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA,
CHRISTIANITY-ASIA, CHRISTIANITY-LATIN, CHRISTIANITY-AFRICA. All are
moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Don Kirk
 &HT;    c. 1999 Special to the Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, Korea _ Parents awake early to pray at churches
throughout the country for the success of their sons and daughters
in college entrance exams. Labor activists camp out in tents in the
sanctuary of the driveway leading to the Myongdong Cathedral, the
center of the Catholic Church in Korea. Protestants stage services
for people still held in prison on charges of violating the
national security law.
</P>
<P>
   These separate scenes dramatize the powerful roles of
Christianity in a country where more than 10,000 people were
executed in the 19th century for refusing to abandon the faith
inculcated in them by French Catholic priests.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-dawn of the third millennium after the birth of
Christ, Christianity is not only fully accepted in South Korea but
flourishes as a social force unrivaled in any country in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea is unique,'' says Horace G. Underwood, grandson of
Presbyterian missionary Horace Underwood. The elder Underwood
arrived in Korea in 1885 and founded the college that formed the
basis for Yonsei University, one of Korea's leading educational
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the rest of Asia, the church was tainted as the religion of
colonialists, but in Korea the colonialists were the Japanese'' who
wound up ruling Korea as a colony for 35 years until their defeat
in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Christianity is the basic faith of roughly 12 million of
the country's 46 million people. Nine million are Protestant,
including 5 million Presbyterians splintered into several different
sub-groupings. Three million are Catholic, including the country's
president Kim Dae Jung, who succeeded a Presbyterian, Kim Young
Sam. Buddhists rank as the second largest overall grouping with
more than 10 million adherents, while nearly half of Koreans claim
no formal faith at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity before World War II was the religion of the poor
people,'' says Underwood, still active as a Presbyterian lay
leader, ``but the Christian community has prospered more than the
rest of the country. It's now upper-middle class and middle
class.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has confidence in Christianity's role in the rest of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity is growing in all countries,'' said Underwood.
``Militants are anti-Christian because it's growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The foothold that Christianity gained in Korea in the waning
days of the Lee dynasty more than 100 years ago contrasts with the
problems confronting Christians in almost every other country in
Asia. The only real exception is the Philippines. There, explorer
Ferdinand Magellan planted the Christian cross in 1521.
</P>
<P>
   While Christianity in the Philippines is not as diverse as in
Korea, Catholicism may penetrate deeper into society. Nine out of
every 10 Filipinos are Catholic. And Cardinal Jaimie Sin, who loves
to pun on his last name, is a dominant figure whose influence
helped to bring down Ferdinand Marcos in 1986 _ and prevented Fidel
Ramos from running for a second six-year term as president last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Catholicism exerts a similar but far less pervasive influence in
Vietnam, where nearly five million Catholics among a population of
78 million practice a faith introduced during the era of French
colonialism. The Catholics were some of the staunchest fighters
against the Vietnamese communists before the communist defeat of
the French in 1954, and again before the communist government in
North Vietnam gained control over all of South Vietnam in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Vietnamese Catholics, along with members of other faiths _
notably the Hoa Hao, who worship God but not Christ, and the Cao
Dai, who worship figures including Christ, Buddha, Confucius and
Victor Hugo _ face stringent controls. Police have raided places of
worship in a campaign to force members of all faiths to join
government-sanctioned organizations of Catholics, Hoa Hao and Cao
Dai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now worshippers are protesting against these organizations,''
said Duong The Tu, a Vietnamese refugee living in California. ``The
religious movement is very tense now. Catholics, Hoa Hao and Cao
Dai are uniting to strike against the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Christians face problems of different sorts in the two most
populous countries of Asia _ China and India _ as well as the
richest country in Asia, Japan. Since the communist authorities
authorized worship at state-approved churches in the early 1980s,
millions of Chinese have flocked to worship in a reaction to
oppressive communist rule under former leader Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
   The regime, however, has cracked down on worship at ``house
churches,'' homes where underground services are held. In early
November, the police arrested Li Dexian and six of his followers
near the southern city of Guangzhou, according to the British
group, Christian Solidarity Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In India, where Christians compose 2.3 percent of a population
of nearly 1 billion, Hindus have attacked Christians in the capital
of New Delhi and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The World Hindu Council, based in New Delhi, accused Pope John
Paul II of a breach of hospitality for praising missionary work in
Asia during a visit to India last month. Hindu fanatics killed four
members of a Christian family in the eastern state of Bihar and
have staged a series of attacks in the state of Gujarat.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where Christians make up less than one percent of a
population of 124 million, church groups criticized the government
for ordering schools and offices to fly the rising sun flag on the
10th anniversary in November of the reign of Emperor Akihito.
Religious leaders said they feared a renaissance of the nationalism
that led Japan into World War II while Akihito's father, Hirohito,
was emperor.
</P>
<P>
   For many Japanese, Christian as well as non-Christian, the
rising sun flag evoked memories of the days when the emperor
himself was viewed as a god _ a state that Hirohito specifically
renounced after surrendering at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
