<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CANAL-SECURITY-$ADV26     12-21 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANAL-SECURITY-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME SAY PANAMA CANAL REMAINS VULNERABLE TO TERRORISM
 &HT;    With PANAMA-CANAL and CANAL-WORKERS
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ It's a glorious sight: huge freighters dot
the Pacific horizon, waiting their turn to slip into the giant
locks that will lift them through one of the world's greatest
shipping short-cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the awe it inspires as an engineering achievement,
the Panama Canal is also notably vulnerable, especially in this day
of globe-trotting terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   American conservatives warn that a couple of bad guys armed with
a suitcase of explosives could probably put the canal out of
business for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few places where you could have a more dramatic
impact on U.S. military and commercial interests than the Isthmus
of Panama,'' said Frank Gaffney(cq) of the Center for Security
Policy, who noted that the Panamanian army was disbanded after the
U.S. invasion of 1989 and the country now boasts only an
18,000-member police force.
</P>
<P>
   Canal administrators and Pentagon officials insist the canal is
in safe hands despite the closure of the dozen U.S. military bases
that once defended it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, U.S. soldiers haven't been the primary security force
for the canal since World War II, said Deputy Canal Administrator
Joseph W. Cornelison(cq), a retired U.S. Army officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary responsibility has always been that of the canal
commission,'' he said. ``We have an adequate security force
augmented by the very sophisticated use of the latest technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelison declined to discuss specifics, but said a recent
review by a top Pentagon official drew praise for the canal
security set-up.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the assurances, concerns remain because the canal is so
clearly vital to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Although it handles only 4 percent of world shipping, about 12
percent of U.S. shipping passes through the waterway. Some 65
percent of the canal's traffic is bound to or from U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives say the canal is simply too important to be left
in the hands of another country _ especially one with Panama's
spotty record for honest, democratic government. They were appalled
when talks on retaining a U.S. military presence in Panama
collapsed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   They worry that Colombian drug lords or leftist guerrillas could
make the canal a target, and point to several recent attacks along
the Panamanian-Colombian border. While the U.S. retains the right
to intervene if there is a threat, that's not enough, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll do us damn little good to send in the Marines after some
terrorist has already blown the thing up,'' said Howard Phillips of
the Conservative Caucus, who opposed the canal hand-over.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also fume over a contract allowing
Hutchinson-Whampoa (cq), a Hong Kong company they allege has close
ties to the Chinese military, to run ports at either end of the
canal. The Chinese could use the facilities for spying, smuggling
or as a base for sabotage, they warn.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pentagon officials and Cornelison dismiss the worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no relation between the operation of those ports and
the operation of the canal,'' said Cornelison, who will retire soon
after the canal is turned over to Panama. ``As a retired military
officer and the senior U.S. official on the ground in Panama, I
know a national security threat when I see one and would be
obligated to report it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
