</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV26-C     12-21 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STORMY RELATIONSHIP UNDERLIES PEACEFUL U.S.-PANAMA CANAL
TRANSFER
 &HT;    With CANAL-SECURITY and CANAL-WORKERS
 &HT;    EDS NOTE TIME ELEMENT: Panama Canal will officially change hands
on Dec. 31
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Marcos Vargas(cq) wheels his taxi toward
his nation's most famous landmark, passing on the way through
Chorrillo(cq), a poor but teeming district of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his countrymen, the 25-year-old taxi driver is
proud that on Dec. 31, Panama will finally take full possession of
the canal that has been so closely tied to his nation's identity.
</P>
<P>
   But the stormy nature of Panama's relationship with the canal's
builder, the United States, underlies everything here, even on a
simple taxi ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the invasion of 1989, many buildings in Chorrillo were
destroyed,'' Vargas said, referring to the U.S. incursion that
ousted Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega. ``Many people here
don't like the Americans because they lost their houses or their
relatives were killed. And they feel the Americans have never
respected us at the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Military intervention, secret deals, coups and wounded pride
have checkered the U.S.-Panamanian relationship from the very
beginning. It started out something like a shotgun wedding, and
produced plenty of fireworks over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the union also produced one of the marvels of the 20th
Century, a 50-mile-long canal slicing across a low mountain range
to connect the Caribbean Sea and the Pacific Ocean. Opened in 1914,
the waterway became a powerful symbol of American ingenuity and
might, ushering in ``the American Century.''
</P>
<P>
   At 85 years old, the canal is still an awe-inspiring sight:
massive locks and gigantic steel doors mesh with the intricacy of a
Swiss watch.
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely why American conservatives are so outraged
that the U.S. is giving the canal to the Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built it. We paid for it. It's ours and we're going to keep
it,'' Ronald Reagan said in 1976, summing up the view of opponents
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But President Jimmy Carter felt the turnover was only fair, and
in 1978 managed to get the U.S. Senate to approve the transfer _ by
a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline for the turnover approached this fall, critics
insisted the U.S. must keep a military presence in Panama to
protect the canal. They fear the Panamanians will forsake the
waterway's upkeep, jack up ship tolls or allow it to fall victim to
corrupt internal politics.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates say the turnover does more than anything to
counterbalance a tradition of U.S. domination of its smaller Latin
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right thing to do,'' Carter said at a Dec. 14
ceremony marking the transition. ``Americans didn't understand
clearly enough the feelings of the Panamanian people, that (the
original canal treaty) implied an element of colonialism.''
</P>
<P>
   History does much to explain the intense feelings surrounding
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Panama in 1903 when a U.S. warship just happened to
steam over the horizon right as a band of rebels declared their
independence from Colombia. The rebels had sent an envoy to
Washington before the uprising, obtaining American promises to
block any Colombian counter-offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, a representative of the fledgling government signed
a treaty granting the Americans the right to build the canal, and
to occupy ``in perpetuity'' a 10-mile-wide canal zone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the document that would shape Panama's destiny wasn't signed
by a Panamanian.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Philippe Bunau-Varilla(cq), a French engineer who had
been part of a failed effort to build a canal in the 1880s _ and
who had a large financial stake in the effort's revival _
frantically pushed through a deal before an official Panamanian
delegation arrived in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heady time for the young United States. Having just won
the Spanish American War, the canal was seen as a vital trade and
military link that would expand U.S. power. Succeeding where the
French had failed would also prove U.S. superiority over the
European colonial powers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But success was far from assured. The 10-year French effort to
dig a canal _ led by Ferdinand de Lesseps(cq), builder of the Suez
Canal _ collapsed in scandal in 1889 after finances faltered and
tropical diseases killed 20,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The engineering challenges facing the Americans were extreme.
They had to deal with 20-foot tidal surges in the Pacific and 10
feet of annual rainfall that triggered frequent floods and
mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   But the American engineers proved equal to the task. Giant new
steam shovels were imported, and engineers designed an ingenious
system for hauling away the unbelievable amounts of excavated dirt.
</P>
<P>
   They also came up with innovative systems for mixing and pouring
the massive amounts of cement needed for the gigantic locks, which
at 1000 feet long, 110 feet wide and 80 feet deep dwarfed any
previous construction project.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge was cutting through the spine of the
500-foot-tall continental divide. Working nonstop, the giant
shovels tore away the earth, filling enough railroad cars to circle
the globe several times.
</P>
<P>
   A huge dam was built across the Chagres(cq) River, creating the
world's largest man-made lake, which controlled the torrential
rains and provided enough water that the locks could run on gravity
flow, without pumps to move the ships.
</P>
<P>
   The medical challenges were just as severe as the engineering
ones. At the turn of the century, malaria and yellow fever were
terrifying diseases that could sweep through a community, killing
thousands within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Following the groundbreaking work of others, U.S. Army Dr.
William Gorgas proposed killing the mosquitoes suspected of
spreading the diseases. His bosses scoffed, but eventually his
sanitation and hygiene programs proved successful and enabled the
canal to be built.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those programs, some 5,000 workers died from accidents
and disease. About 4,500 of the victims were black West Indians,
who did the backbreaking hand labor needed to keep the giant
shovels working.
</P>
<P>
   The canal opened in 1914, its untested systems quickly working
perfectly. Soon the massive construction force was replaced by
thousands of Americans running the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   They lived separated from the Panamanians by fences surrounding
the canal zone, enjoying subsidized housing, low-cost imported
goods and the protection of American troops at a dozen U.S.
military bases within the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Their work was hard and far from home, but their lives were
rich. There were social clubs, recreation leagues, dances, scout
troops, American schools, a July 4 celebration.
</P>
<P>
   All of which stuck in the throats of the Panamanians, who were
paid less, kept out of the American stores and banned from the
canal zone except for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created a country within a country,'' historian David
McCullough said in a televised C-SPAN forum. ``It had its own
police force, laws, courts and stores which the Panamanians didn't
have access to. That was very difficult for the Panamanians to
accept.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocky relationship spawned violence in 1964. American
officials, mindful of the tension, ordered the Panamanian flag
flown beside the U.S. flag at all installations. American students
in the canal zone protested, triggering a counter-protest by
Panamanian students.
</P>
<P>
   Riots broke out, leaving three U.S. Marines and 24 Panamanians
dead.
</P>
<P>
   A succession of U.S. presidents promised to renegotiate the
canal treaty, but nothing was done until Carter took office in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood...that of all the issues that I could possibly
address as president, the relationship between the United States
and Latin America would be predicated on...whether or not we had a
(new) Panama Canal treaty,'' Carter said in a 1998 interview. ``It
was a moral issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The final deal phased out the U.S. presence over a 22-year
period. Along with the waterway operations, the U.S. agreed to turn
over the 360,000 acres within the canal zone _ including all U.S.
military bases. America retains the right to intervene if the
canal's security is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two decades, Panamanians gradually took control
of the canal's day-to-day operations. Today, about 97 percent of
the 9,000 canal workers are Panamanian.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several military coups, the scandalous Noriega years and
the 1989 U.S. invasion, the Panamanian government passed a
succession of laws designed to insulate the canal from domestic
politics. An independent board now runs it, with a blue-chip
international advisory panel overseeing the operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panama understands extremely well the responsibility we have
with this waterway,'' said Alberto Aleman(cq), the canal's
administrator. ``We understand that we are in the marketplace, that
we have to compete, and that we must maintain the confidence of our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panamanians have already begun a $1 billion modernization
program, and hope to turn the canal zone into a bustling center of
trade, tourism and international investment. Cruise ship terminals,
shopping complexes and an eco-tourism resort are going up.
</P>
<P>
   But everybody acknowledges the Panamanians must still prove
themselves. Skeptics will be watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be proud of the economic development the canal can
bring,'' Carter said. ``We want to see Panama become the Singapore
of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
