<P>
   FULL-MOON (San Francisco) _ The world probably won't end
Wednesday night, but the sky should be a bit brighter _ and the
Earth's inhabitants may act a little goofier. It's the last full
moon of the century, and the sun, moon and Earth are in a rare
alignment, unseen since 1866. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   NEURALGIA-RELIEF (Albany, N.Y.) _ His pain is so intense that
the Rev. Paul Tartaglia can't chew, talk, brush his teeth or even
touch his face. He has a disorder called trigeminal neuralgia, and
he traveled last week to New York University Medical Center to
undergo an operation that he hopes will stop the misery. Thanks to
medical advances, most sufferers like him are now finding some
relief. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   JAIL-CUISINE (Houston) _ A 21-year-old chef from Seattle who
works at a Houston restaurant that counts former President Bush
among its visitors will cook up a gourmet Christmas meal for the
hungry souls in the nearby Trinity County Jail. ``It's been a
tradition in our family to adopt people who don't have families,''
she said. The chef is a graduate of the Western Culinary Institute
in Portland, Ore. By KATHY WALT. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   NORTH-POLE (Wilmington, N.Y.) _ Nestled in the Adirondack
Mountains of upstate New York, the North Pole village has been
entertaining children for 50 years. But Bob Reiss, the man who owns
Santa's satellite home, is selling the attraction. ``Don't be sad.
Be glad,'' Reiss, 73, tells a worried visitor. ``For the park to
continue, someone else has to take over.'' By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
