<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-NORTH-POLE-HNS &LR;      12-21 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTH-POLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A VETERAN SANTA FINDS THE NORTH POLE NEEDS YOUNGER BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.Y. _ Bob Reiss, owner of the North Pole village
near Lake Placid, had trouble walking through the park on a recent
Sunday. Visitors to the tourist attraction kept stopping him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, are you Mr. Reiss?`` asked Jerry Devoe, from Lake
George. ``I've been coming here since I was a little boy. I respect
you a great deal for sticking to your convictions and not just
looking for the almighty buck.`` Reiss just smiled, as the sleigh
bells that hung from his red hat jingled, and shook his hand. He
had been hearing words like that a lot recently. It was only a
month ago that the 73-year-old businessman announced he was selling
the village. Asking price: $650,000, including the reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   He had been running the North Pole, fictitious home of Santa
Claus, only a few years after his father built it in 1949. For five
decades, Reiss has been at the helm of what some say is the
nation's first theme park. And while similar attractions in the
Adirondack Mountains have been largely abandoned, the North Pole is
still going.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, it will be going without him. That prospect
saddens some visitors. Melissa Giesin, who also stopped Reiss to
thank him, said she felt bad he was leaving. Reiss told her not to
worry. He sees his departure as a way for someone to take a
struggling park and make it thrive, at a time when Santa Claus has
to compete with PlayStation, Pokemon and the Internet for a child's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be sad. Be glad,`` he said. ``For the park to continue,
someone else has to take over.`` When Julian J. Reiss opened the
North Pole in the summer of 1949, the idea was so unique it made
headlines around the country. The story told to children was that
Santa Claus knew the children wanted to visit him, so he had some
Adirondack businessmen build a second home for him on the shoulder
of Whiteface Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Julian Reiss, who bought a home in the Adirondacks
after living here to recover from tuberculosis, got the idea while
driving his daughter to the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened, the North Pole attracted more adults than
children. It consisted of eight colorful log buildings where
visitors met with Santa, fed reindeer and looked at an actual North
Pole (coolant was pumped through a vertical pipe, causing it to ice
over year-round). There was even a post office branch, where
visitors could have their letters postmarked ``North Pole.`` In
1951, two years after the park opened, more than 14,000 attended on
the Sunday of Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Walt Disney, which sent a team to visit the North Pole
before he opened Disneyland, forever changed the world's definition
of a ``theme park.`` These days, places with roller coasters
flourish while places like the North Pole _ where the closest thing
to a ``thrill ride`` is the merry-go-round _ struggle to stay
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   In the Adirondacks of upstate New York, similar parks have all
fallen into ruin. ``Tourist-traps`` like Land of Make-Believe, Home
of 1,000 Animals and
</P>
<P>
   Gaslight Village have all closed. The owners of Frontier Village
hung up their coonskin caps for the last time a year ago.
Meanwhile, the former Storytown in Lake George has ditched its
fantasy-land mystique, put up roller coaster rides and is now known
as The Great Escape.
</P>
<P>
   The North Pole did well until the early 1970s, attracting an
average of around 180,000 people every year. Then came the problems
_ first the oil embargo, when the high cost of gasoline kept people
from making long trips, then another gas crisis in 1979, then the
recession of the 1980s. By the time the economy improved, visits
were down to about 65,000 to 70,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Reiss was sure that, once times got better, people would start
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Times got better. Business didn't. A lot had changed since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now your children grow up so much faster,`` Reiss said.
``Twelve-year-olds are not into Santa Claus like they used to be.
It's been a challenge for us to live with that.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reiss willingly admits the park needs someone with younger ideas
_ and younger blood _ to take over. But when he was ready to sell
(he says his wife said it was time to grow up and get a real job)
he did it in a rather unique way.
</P>
<P>
   He invited the QVC home shopping channel to do a broadcast from
his village. ``It's not everyday you get to purchase your very own
theme park,`` the announcer said as they toured the park. A window
on the left-hand side of the screen advertised the price: $650,000,
with no shipping charge. From the dozens of calls, Reiss narrowed
it down to eight people who were serious about running a park. He
hopes the deal will go through as early as March, so he can start
on his hobbies of sailing and being with his grandchildren. But it
may not be so easy for him to leave. ``Even though I live half my
life in a fantasy, I think I'm a realist,`` he said. ``When you
have a business like this, you don't just walk away and forget
it.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
