<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-HOLIDAY-DICOR-HNS &LR;      12-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-DICOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAMILY TAKES PRIDE IN HOLIDAY TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENS FALLS, N.Y. _ Holidays are a time for creating new
traditions and carrying on old ones. For 30-plus years, Louis and
Carol Whitney have celebrated their family Christmas with three or
more Christmas trees among their holiday decorations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the holidays and started this tree tradition when we
were first married,'' said Carol Whitney, as she wiped artificial
snow from her tailored brown trousers and matching Chanel shoes.
``Our children continue to love it. It's a lot of work, but we
wouldn't dream of using an artificial tree. The trees, greens and
flowers always have to be fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the public rooms in their gracious
French-chateau-style residence feature a tree, but so does the
billiard/home theater room and their master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the ceiling-high trees features ornaments that the
couple has collected over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The tree in the walnut-paneled living room is
traditional-looking, with the feeling of a sparkling jewel box.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one has loads of tinsel on it and colored lights,''
Whitney said. ``Many of the glass ornaments are new, several that
we have collected over the years and several from family and
friends. Almost every ornament has a memory attached to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ornaments vary in size from jumbo orbs to tiny glass figurines.
There also is a collection of mouth-blown and hand-painted
ornaments done in the Old World, European tradition of the 19th
century designed by Christopher Radko. Each is produced in a
limited edition.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney decorates the living room tree with friends at a party
she and her husband give after Thanksgiving but she puts the
ornaments on the other three trees in the following weeks herself.
</P>
<P>
   The large evergreen in the foyer is decked out with white
lights, bows and ornaments and a crown of blue bows with matching
streamers down to the gaily wrapped presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first one you see when you enter the house,''
Whitney said. ``It also picks up the colors of the foyer and cloak
and powder room.''
</P>
<P>
   Since purchasing the house nearly eight years ago, the Whitneys
have been slowly and carefully bringing harmony to the interior of
this eye-catching home with its 16 rooms, seven baths and former
maids' quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Set on 15 acres in upstate New York, the 8,400-square-foot
creamy stucco-and-brick house was built in the 1960s by attorney
Louis P. Brown, who was also a president of the Glens Falls
National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Brown incorporated many unique features into the house, from
four French marble fireplace mantles to antique French fruitwood
doors that enclose the built-in home entertainment equipment and
television set; Rococo paneling in the formal dining room with
fireplace; elegant French door windows; slate and red Spanish tile
floors; fountains in many of the rooms and a working faience stove.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also had a large depression in back of the house where he
kept his pet bears and other animals. It has since been filled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually the pond, which runs into Halfway Brook, and
the walkway through the woods that attracted me to the house,''
recalled Carol Whitney, who is a native of Pennsylvania. ``Then
when I saw the large gourmet kitchen, I was really sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Whitney is the grandson of Charlotte Pruyn Hyde, the
founder of the Hyde Collection art museum in Glens Falls and
daughter of one of the founders of the Finch, Pruyn &AMP; Co. paper
mill in Glens Falls. Although Carol Whitney tackled some of the
projects herself, such as wallpapering the powder room, she has
been working with interior designer Edmond DeRocker of Glens Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house basically decorates itself by demanding period
furnishings,'' DeRocker said. ``Carol has achieved a warm mostly
Country French look with fun touches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabric and tents and ornate brass coat hooks decorate the cloak
room. Pieces from her former home have been reupholstered and
incorporated into the house. ``Carol has a very good eye and knows
what she likes when she sees it,'' DeRocker said.
</P>
<P>
   The first project Carol Whitney tackled was the den. It has a
rich palette of
</P>
<P>
   forest green plaid wallpaper, built-in bookcases, comfortable
burgundy leather furnishings and a fireplace. According to Whitney,
it is her favorite room in the house, where she does most of her
reading, knitting and needlepoint.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the color scheme, Whitney adds only decorative
touches here, such as placing fresh greens and candles on the
fireplace mantle and an arrangement of fresh boughs beside it. A
decorated tree sits outside the floor-to-ceiling French doors.
</P>
<P>
   All of the interior fountains have been removed except the one
in the main hallway, which is a classical three-tiered
cream-colored marble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to landscape the fountain with poinsettia plants and
candles,'' Whitney said. ``We like to entertain during the holidays
and so the dining room is often set up buffet-style.''
</P>
<P>
   For a festive and dramatic centerpiece, she uses an antique
child's sleigh in the center, filled with fresh flowers. Greens,
flowers and candles are arranged formally over the fireplace
mantle.
</P>
<P>
   The tree in the second-floor home theater room ``has inherited a
lot of old odds-and-ends ornaments,'' she said. ``I've used campy,
colorful bubble lights on the tree, which seem to fit better than
solid-colored lights.''
</P>
<P>
   The master bedroom tree adorns the cream-and-peach-colored room
with its fireplace and pale mint carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fingers are sore from spraying the tree with artificial
white snow,'' Whitney said. ``It took a couple of days and 24 cans
of spray to get it covered before the pale gold ornaments could be
put on.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and son put the lights on all the trees, but they
draw the
</P>
<P>
   line there when it comes to putting on all the ornaments,'' said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Come Christmas morning, all of the packages are rounded up from
beneath the other trees and brought to the living room, where they
spill out into the room beyond the abundance of wrapped presents
already under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't open them now until around 10 a.m. or later in the
morning,'' Whitney said, as she rid her trousers of the last few
flecks of artificial snow. ``It was always at the crack of dawn,
before the children grew up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
