<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION'S HURTADO BRINGS IT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eduardo Hurtado went from the MetroStars, the worst team in
Major League Soccer, to the Revolution, another team more known for
floundering than flourishing. But in between stops, Hurtado has
found success in Ecuador, his home country.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado scored two goals as Liga Deportiva Universitaria
defeated Nacional, 3-1, in the championship game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Hurtado was especially convenient for Ecuadoran
headline writers, since his nickname is ``El Tanque'' (The Tank)
and the vanquished opposition represented the nation's armed
forces. The victory also gave residents of Quito a diversion from
the effects of Guagua, the volcano ``which is still raining ashes
onto the city,'' according to a wire service account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eduardo is very fit, at the top of his game,'' said his agent,
Eric Manasse. ``He is playing at 2,700 meters above sea level and
it is hard to breathe, so it is a real test of fitness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado's good form has made him a certain candidate for the
national team. Coach Hernan Dario Gomez has called in Hurtado and
former Revolution striker Ariel Graziani for training camp next
month, and hopes to use them for three preparation games before the
start of World Cup qualifying March 28. Revolution coach Fernando
Clavijo could also lose Giovanni Savarese, who could join Venezuela
for qualifying games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was being interviewed all the time,'' Manasse said of
Hurtado, ``and said he is very content with going to the Revolution
because of his rapport with Fernando, plus going to a new city
after the problems he had in New York. He is really into it and he
wants to win with the Revolution. He likes playing with Giovanni
Savarese, and he knows if they get an expert central defender, they
can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado, whose wife is expecting their third child, will likely
arrive in Boston early next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Central casting
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manasse is offering the Revolution three experienced central
defenders: Stefano Nava, a member of two European Championship
teams with Milan, who is on a free transfer; Colombian Evereth
Palacios; and Byron Tenorio, who is from Hurtado's hometown,
Esmeraldas, and has been a regular on Ecuador's national team. Nava
and Tenorio are tall and bring a strong physical presence _ Tenorio
was also a member of Ecuador's national team in basketball. All
three are 30 years old. Clavijo has been scouting in Portugal for a
central defender . . . If the Revolution want to start laying the
foundation for the future, they should consider local prospects
Ebbie Kodiat, 20, and Bruno Schneider, 17. Kodiat has a chance to
be invited to spring training in Florida, and Schneider could be a
Project 40 candidate, according to Clavijo. Kodiat has performed
well at recent tryout camps, but Schneider was prohibited from
attending because of his age. But Schneider, a 6-foot-1-inch,
160-pound striker, is among the most ambitious young players in the
area. He scored 74 goals in 48 games at Winthrop and Dom Savio high
schools but believes he must move to the professional level to
develop his talent. He plans to skip his senior year in high school
to pursue opportunities either in Europe or MLS. Meanwhile, he is
with Juventus of Worcester and playing in indoor leagues. The last
Massachusetts product to play for a US national team was Matt
Thompson, of Roxbury Latin High and Wellesley, with the Under-17
team. Thompson, 21, a central defender, performed briefly at
Indiana University and transferred to Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His home fires still burn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Francis Okaroh, the Revolution's defensive player of the year in
1996 and '97 before being claimed by the Chicago Fire, said he
hopes to conclude his career playing for New England. But Chicago
coach Bob Bradley does not seem eager to let Okaroh depart. Bradley
quickly moved to change the Fire's foreign flavor, waiving Polish
veterans Roman Kosecki and Jerzy Podbrozny, and now must reinforce
the midfield. Okaroh, who is recovering at his Woburn home after
hernia surgery, missed the Fire's final playoff game and his team
squandered a two-goal advantage in being eliminated by Dallas.
``You have to have that fire and some of our guys didn't have it
last year,'' Okaroh said. ``We are ready to start over. We have the
nucleus. The key thing is we still have the defense, and if you
have your defense set you can plug guys into the offensive roles.''
. . . Javier Pedro Saviola has become the youngest player to lead
Argentina's first division in scoring since Diego Maradona in 1978.
Saviola converted his 15th goal of the Apertura season in River
Plate's 2-2 tie with San Lorenzo, just eight days after his 18th
birthday. Maradona was 17 when he scored 22 goals in '78. River
Plate's other goal went to 19-year-old Guillermo Pereyra. It was
River Plate's 28th Argentine championship . . . Nottingham Forest's
purchase of Stern John paid off almost immediately as he scored in
the sixth minute of his first game in England last month. John, 23,
who led the MLS in scoring in his two years with the Columbus Crew,
converted an even more important goal Saturday. This time, John's
goal was the game's only score as Nottingham Forest edged Crewe
Alexandra to take over 19th place. Coach David Platt's position was
becoming precarious as Forest was slipping toward the relegation
zone . . . Pachuca, Mexico's oldest club, won its first
professional league championship Sunday. Los Tuzos had to travel to
Mexico City for the second leg of the final, and took the victory
over Cruz Azul two minutes into overtime as Argentine Alejandro
Glaria scored the only goal of the game. Glaria had converted twice
in a 2-2 tie in the first leg at Estadio Hidalgo. Pachuca coach
Javier Aguirre had assembled a team of mostly anonymous players.
The squad included Mexican national team veteran Marcelino Bernal,
Baltimore-born Gerardo Mascareno, and Argentine goalkeeper Nacho
Gonzalez. Cruz Azul's season concludes Tuesday when it meets CD
Guadalajara in Los Angeles in the final of the Copa Estrella . . .
In century rankings of the world's best players, the International
Federation of Football History and Statistics listed Fall River's
Billy Gonsalves sixth in the CONCACAF region. Gonsalves, who played
in the 1930 and '34 World Cup finals, was the only US player in the
top 10. The top-ranked player was Hugo Sanchez, a five-time scoring
champion in Spain. The top goalkeepers were: Antonio Carbajal
(Mexico), Luis Conejo (Costa Rica), Kasey Keller (US), Jorge Campos
(Mexico), and Henri Francillon (Haiti), who is now head coach at
Emerson College. Joe Kennaway, who played for the Fall River
Marksmen and Glasgow Celtic, ranked seventh among goalkeepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
