<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-HOLLEYCOLUMN-ART-     12-21 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S EXAMINE PATRIOT REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A game of 20 Questions with the Pro Football
Coroner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, what caused the death of the 1999 New England Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, there were a lot of factors involved. I'll tell you,
this has been one of the most bizarre autopsies I have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Initially, I examined this team and didn't find a heart. So I
thought that was the cause. But I changed my diagnosis when I
leaned closer to the corpse and found scant remains of something.
Now there is no doubt that blood once coursed through these
lifeless veins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're crazy. This highly paid, 7-7 team was whipped _
literally and metaphorically _ by a third-string quarterback named
Koy Detmer. Did you see what he did to them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yep. Saw everything. I saw his suggestive, 25-cent Peep Show
dance and I saw his three touchdown passes. But if you think their
problems began with Detmer and the Philadelphia Eagles, you
probably also think Michael Bishop should have played earlier in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You play dirty. We'll talk about Bishop later. But let me ask
you: If the Patriots had heart _ which I doubt _ what didn't they
have?
</P>
<P>
   A: Organizational honesty. From the owner, to the personnel
department, to the coaching staff, to the players. They didn't know
whom they were and it killed them. They were delusional and it
affected the way they managed, the way they drafted, the way they
dealt with their free agents, the way they viewed the competition,
the way they disciplined themselves, the way they held themselves
accountable, the way their fans talked about them . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: Hold on. One at a time. Who was most at fault for all this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Throw out some names and I'll tell you where they went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   A: Forget about all this Bill Parcells hysteria. That wasn't the
mistake. The big fella is from New Jersey and there was no way he
was going to retire here. Kraft's biggest error was that he and the
men who work for him thought more like football guys than baseball
guys. In baseball, most people go for veterans over untested
prospects. They also go for ``locker room presence'' guys. Kraft
did the opposite. He picked prospects over veterans and _
unintenionally or not _ sacrificed the soul of his team. Ever
notice that every major league baseball team has one or two guys
who aren't really that good? Those are your ``presence'' guys.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did Kraft allow this to happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: He made the mistake a lot of executives make: he thought the
people who worked for him were replaceable. They may have been on
paper, but there were some distinct quirks about Curtis Martin, Sam
Gash, and even Corwin Brown that endeared them to teammates. All of
them were effective players and terrific people. Brown and Gash
used to keep the locker room pulsing by playing chess. They were
thinkers. Martin, one of the most sincere men you'll ever meet,
used to shadowbox with Jimmy Hitchcock (also traded for a
third-round pick). They were good guys who didn't easily accept
losing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Kraft make a mistake by hiring Pete Carroll?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope. You've got the order reversed. Carroll made the mistake
of choosing the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Huh?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pay attention. Didn't I tell you this team died because it
didn't know itself? Carroll thought he was taking over a thriving
Super Bowl team when he took the job in 1997. He wasn't. He was
taking over an enigma. He took over the second- or third-best team
in the AFC, a team that lost the Super Bowl by 14 points. He took
over a team that was 11-5 in '96 and 6-10 in '95. He took over a
team that was in transition, shifting its personnel power from
Charley Armey to Bobby Grier. He took over a team in flux.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And that was a mistake?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, because he should have known that if things went wrong
_ and they did _ he was going to be the public face of the
collapse. That's what happened. He'll lose his job soon. He'll find
another one because he is respected by coaches such as Mike
Shanahan and George Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You feel sorry for him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really. He was too polite with these guys. Just
yesterday, he said he was ``on the verge'' of saying something
nasty about his team in Philly but resisted. Hey, Pete. Get nasty,
my brother. These players have disrespected you all season and
you're holding back? Terry Glenn didn't hold back when he was late
for those team meetings and team buses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I think Glenn is one of the finest receivers in the league.
Wouldn't trade him for anyone. Do you agree?
</P>
<P>
   A: What, did you go to Ohio State or something? If I ran the
Patriots when they were alive, I would have called the Cleveland
Browns and offered them Glenn for their first pick. I'd call
Philadelphia, too. Glenn is, maybe, the fifth best receiver in the
AFC. I'd rather have Keyshawn Johnson, Marvin Harrison, Jimmy
Smith, and Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm confused. Weren't the Patriots supposed to be talented?
</P>
<P>
   A: They were. But they didn't have enough warrior in them. They
always gave you the feeling that they were relaxing in the
Carribbean, even when they were in Foxborough. I told you: They
were delusional. And soft. Kraft and Grier tinkered with this team
when they should have been overhauling it, especially on the
offensive and defensive lines. Max Lane is my boy (we once did a
show together) but he shouldn't have been given big money. Same
with Todd Rucci.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   A: Will never make the Pro Bowl again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ex-Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   A: I heard that he is not ready to run the offense and that he
doesn't do so well in the team's weekly quarterback quizzes. Looks
like he needs to do his homework.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Bruce Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   A: He criticized the Carroll/Ernie Zampese play-calling on
Sunday. Whoa. I've learned that if you criticize a man's music,
religion, shoes, or play-calling, you're in for a fight. My
goodness. Death from delusion. Wait until I tell my assistant about
this one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Wait, wait. Before you go. One more thing. Please?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We're planning a Patriots funeral and need the perfect
selection for the dirge. Any recommendations?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Certainly. These Patriots should be buried to the sounds
of one of my favorite groups, a group that is _ appropriately _
from Philly. They are called the Roots. The essential song?
``Things Fall Apart.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
