<HEADLINE>
A LOOK BACK AT GOING EVERYWHERE ... AND ANYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGBOAT KEY, Fla. _ What's Christmas without a tree?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a palm tree,'' says my crony, Murray the Wrench, the
Buffalo, N.Y., orthodontist, who once more has snatched victory _
escape to a balmy, palmy Florida shore _ from the jaws of
juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yessir, their teeth puts bite in my bankroll, and here we are
again. A mini-wrench is my Yule tool. The only white I dream of for
Christmas is this sand,'' he says, rearranging himself in the rays
beside the blue-and-green splattered Gulf of Mexico at the Colony
Beach &AMP; Tennis Resort. ``Forget Bing Crosby and sleigh bells. I'll
take buoy bells.'' So will his lady, Susie, a refugee from the pale
perils of Canadian winter.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and I have been meeting at the Colony for a couple of
decades to admire the pelicans, egrets, and other birds, wash the
bah-humbug out of our systems with salt water and Wild Horse pinot
noir, as well as ponder the passing and coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're big losers this time,'' he says. ``We're dropping not
just a year but a millennium plus my 20th century _ three for the
price of one jug of . . . champagne at midnight the 31st. I hate to
see them go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you said about rumble seats, boogie-woogie, white
bucks, nickel phone calls, and doctors' house calls,'' Susie
reminds him. ``But you got past it. And why is this your century?
Because you've been around for most of it? The champagne will ease
your sense of loss.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no sense of loss about travel because you keep the
memories. Sometimes expensive, usually priceless. At a distance in
time I can even admire the artistry of a double-teaming Ecuadorian
pickpocket team that nailed me in a Quito cathedral. One bumped me
on the left, apologizing profusely while his partner on the right
dipped profitably with a claw as educated as a Florida stone
crab's.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch beckons. We move in the direction of the dining room where
adroit maitre d'hotel Alberto Mastromano and venerable waiter Ron
Craze deliver stone crab, the succulent creature from these Gulf
waters that sacrifices regenerative claws but not its life.
Intriguing beasts, they're the stars of the Colony's annual October
Stone Crab Festival presided over by chef John Dutton. Put together
by Katie and Michael Moulton, the hotel's respective general
manager and food manager, it's a cookout for chefs who descend from
numerous pots of call to try their hands with crabs and other
native seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Among the yummy treats were: crab fried in seaweed by Paul
Albrecht, once king of numerous superb kitchens in Atlanta, who has
opened a new restaurant, Chez Paul's, up the West Coast at Panama
City Beach; corn and oyster fritters with tamatillo avocado sauce
by Melissa Kelly from Primo in Rockland, Maine; sauteed shrimp and
sausage with stone-ground grits by Don Barickman of Magnolia's in
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   As we munch, Murray says he's returning in February and March
``to treat myself to more crab and the Sarasota Opera across the
bay.'' Seafood and sopranos, a satisfying blend, especially since
that fine company's 2000 season will include Bizet's ``The Pearl
Fishers'' and Wagner's salty ``The Flying Dutchman'' as well as
Rossini's ``Barber of Seville'' and Verdi's ``Alzira.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he asks me, the road-tripper, to distill from all the
millennial etcmileage and baggage those 20th-century journeys that
pop quickly to the surface of my neural mush. So I give him this
dozen, chronologically:
</P>
<P>
   --Hello Florida _ First visit as a summer-vacationing
schoolchild with my parents and sister in a cramped 1937 Chevy. It
took days on two-lane roads from northern Ohio, but we were in no
hurry. Burma Shave signs provided roadside doggerel, and the
mountains of Tennessee loomed strange and thrilling. Tourist cabins
(predecessors of motels) with outhouses were a novelty away from
our accustomed beds. Harsh revelations of a different country
called Dixie were the chain gangs in zebra-striped outfits working
Georgia roads, chaperoned by shotgun-carrying guards. And Jim Crow:
separate drinking fountains, toilets, and, we learned, everything
else for ``white'' and ``colored.'' The Atlantic was a grand new
sight along Florida's east coast. ``Whoa, we're going in!'' said my
grinning father, pulling over next to a deserted beach. We changed
in the car, then delighted in a salt-water baptism.
</P>
<P>
   --Niagara Falls, 1938 _ It was a prize, and I felt like I'd won
a million on a quiz show. Nothing that enriching, but I had
outlasted the field in a third graders' spelling contest for the
Cleveland area, sponsored by a newspaper, the doomed Press.
All-expenses-paid for two over a weekend. As the Depression raged,
it seemed all the more unimaginably plush: a Pullman sleeper from
Cleveland to Buffalo, then a limo with driver and guide taking my
mother and me to the falls, depositing us in a ritzy hotel. All
that rushing water was overwhelming, especially up close in a boat
called Maid of the Mist, and, I assume, still is. For me the
toughest words in the spell-down were ``faucet'' and ``chauffeur,''
seeming appropriate in retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe Ho! _ A college boy's rookie look was taken at the end
of a nine-day New York-England voyage on an ex-troop ship. Why did
those people talk so funny? But it was English. Sort of. French was
tougher. In that pre-TV-saturation day, everything my friend, Bob
Beach, and I had read about _ Westminster Abbey, Stratford, Notre
Dame, Dutch windmills and canals, Brig o' Doon _ stood out as
though newly minted (in a pre-aged motif, of course). With
stringent food rationing yet austerely enforced in an England
unrecovered from World War II, we were always famished. It was
different on the Continent, victuals abundant. And as francs were
numerous at 300 to the dollar, staying well fed in France was easy,
even on a tight budget.
</P>
<P>
   --Tanzanian Safari _ A Hemingway mystique blanketed this
movement through the Great Rift Valley, plotted and led by Papa's
youngest son, Dr. Greg Hemingway, who had apprenticed as a
professional hunter. It was a big game looking for big game. Though
I wouldn't go on a gunning safari again _ the concept is passe _
the stalking of dangerous beasts is undeniably exciting (is that
elephant tooting at me?). Tramping and camping in lush terrain
abounding with them was exhilarating. Hamisi, a professional
tracker, initiated us in the art of palming a tall mound of
elephant dung: If it's warm, the depositor is in the neighborhood.
Hard to beat rising at 4:30 amid showers of stars, walking most of
the blue-sky day, dining wearily at the campfire with good company.
When my hardy pal, Bwana Jack, won out after hand-to-paw combat
with a husky lion, he casually reported, ``Leo had bad breath.''
</P>
<P>
   --Vietnam, Parts I and II _ Scared to death every minute the
first time, covering the war for a couple of months. The reprise 25
years later was an improvement from mindlessness to mildness: a
beautiful country with beautiful, congenial people pleased to see
Americans. Hanoi is a beguiling city surrounding a lake into which
John McCain crashed. Beaches are waiting to be resortified. A side
trip into a Cambodian jungle revealed the haunting temples and
overpowering sculpture of Angkor Wat and Angkor Tom.
</P>
<P>
   --The Taj Mahal _ No building can live up to such a spectacular
reputation, I thought. Wrong. India's Taj does, and it should be
seen at various times of day and night (moonlight's terrific) to
get the full effect. My first visit, our driver roared nonstop the
50 miles from New Delhi to Agra, never releasing the horn. ``I have
to keep blowing to warn people,'' he said. ``I don't want to hit
anybody. But if I do, we don't stop. They would kill us.'' The
second visit was coupled to the mystically compelling Varanasi,
where Hindus go to die, if they are lucky. Or their bodies are
carried there for cremation, the ashes spread across the sacred,
teeming River Ganghes.
</P>
<P>
   --China '77 _ So rare were Westerners then that we were followed
_ quietly, politely _ by gatherings of curious in Shanghai and
Beijing. The citizenry blended together, dressed similarly in
Maoist drab. However, young children somehow were allowed to flaunt
colors. The Wall was indeed great, although it may be plastered
with advertising now. Nobody had a car. Life was primitive and
hard, extremely laborious, but the people fascinating, friendly. I
need to take another look one of these days.
</P>
<P>
   --Senami Onsen, Japan _ Picked it by chance off a map because
it's on the Sea of Japan, connected by excellent trains to Tokyo.
(Why oh why does the United States lag so far behind Japan and
Europe in the best form of transportation, rail?) Swimming in the
sea was splendid, the rural vistas pleasant. Food at the inn was
fine except that there was no way to order. It just arrived at the
room. The catch was that only one man in town spoke English. After
the embarrassed innkeeper produced that guy, life got better, more
understandable _ even if we were the lone non-wearers of kimonos.
</P>
<P>
   --Tibetan Trek _ Because the Chinese guides were so secretive
and unprepared, nobody knew where the hell we were, other than it
was marvelous mountainous country where yaks moved surer than we.
Because the cook, fittingly named Pan, was a star we didn't starve
though caught in a blizzard. Sleeping bags prescribed by the
Globe's Tony Chamberlain saved our skins, and yak herders shared
their fires. When it stopped snowing, we found ourselves at the
foot of a handsome peak in the Da Wa Range, Mount Siguniang _ I
think. Uncertainty ruled. Eventually we walked back to a village
where a van awaited for a springs-threatening drive over
rut-and-roll mud to Chengdu in China.
</P>
<P>
   --Across Australia _ With my friend, Aurelio, at the wheel, we
drove west-east, transcontinental, from Perth to Melbourne, close
to 3,000 miles. Few do. It's not so hazardous as a few years ago
when the road was unpaved. There were few roadhouses, and running
out of water probably meant death. Aussies thought we were bonkers,
rating the Nullarbor Plain as must-miss barren, monotonous. Not
really. Meeting so many interesting, resourceful folks in tiny
settlements and on vast ranches along the way, we thought it
restful and amusing. Like finding the entire population, 28, in the
lively pub at Salmon Gums, Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
