<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FOOTBALL FIELD AND IN POLITICS, LEADERSHIP'S THE KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After his players shut down rather than compete during their
costly loss Sunday to the Philadelphia Eagles, Pete Carroll, the
New England Patriots head football coach, was asked the obvious:
What happened?
</P>
<P>
   They ``squatted,'' he replied. The analogy has a sexist tinge to
it _ it seems crudely to imply something along the lines of ``they
played like girls.'' But at this point, feminist concerns are the
least of Carroll's problems. I bring them up because this debacle
of a Patriots season raises interesting issues beyond football.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is not what happened, but why? Why did this
team quit? Why does one group of athletes or workers rally and pull
together to achieve greatness and another group give up?
</P>
<P>
   The answer involves that elusive quality we call leadership.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to sports talk shows, Carroll's leadership
deficiency is largely attributed to a general feeling that he is
``too nice.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the jock crowd, he's too California and too mellow,
which seems to be male code for saying he isn't macho enough.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier during his tenure in New England, Carroll had to deny he
surfed, as if surfing somehow signals a lack of manliness. But
leadership, I think, means more than being ``manly,'' even to a
professional football player.
</P>
<P>
   A nice person can be a leader, when sometimes even the toughest
guy in a crowd will never be one. Women clearly can be leaders. Why
else do all those big, bulky football players say ``Hi, Mom,'' when
they get into camera range?
</P>
<P>
   Fear alone does not inspire people to excel _ on a football
field or in a newsroom. The strength of a coach like Bill Parcells
is not just his ability to scare professional athletes, but to
scare them into being the best they can be.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, coaching athletes takes a nasty and, again, decidedly
sexist turn. Remember when Parcells referred to Patriots wide
receiver Terry Glenn as a ``she''?
</P>
<P>
   Yet nastiness in itself doesn't motivate, either. A coach like
Parcells is at the height of his leadership potential when he is
able to make a player confront his weaknesses in order to build
upon his strengths and then work not just for individual glory but
for the glory of the team. (Parcells' style didn't work well with
Drew Bledsoe, although the quarterback might appreciate it more now
than he did in the past.)
</P>
<P>
   Carroll lacks that basic ability to motivate, at least with this
specific football team. It is true that he is not the one dropping
the passes. The athletes are making the actual on-field mistakes.
But Carroll, a seemingly nice man, is not succeeding at his job,
which is this: to make the players believe they can win, to inspire
them to try, and to care if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, that is what leadership is all about, whatever the
playing field. And in politics, business, or sports, leadership is
a know-it-when-you-see-it kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Some people simply exude it _ Arizona Senator John McCain is an
example. Some people have it and lose it, because they lose moral
authority _ President Clinton comes to mind. Some people never have
it, despite prestigious job titles and other accoutrements of
power, such as money. The jury is still out, for example, on Texas
Governor George W. Bush and, for that matter, Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders execute a plan in one place, then decide to take it
somewhere else, like New York. That's what Parcells did and what
former Governor Bill Weld is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are leaders without portfolio. They have no titles
or trappings, but when they speak, others listen and instinctively
follow. Some people yell, scream, rant, and rave. But no one will
ever follow them anywhere, because they know there is nothing
behind the noise. Some people are more public in their leadership,
while others make things happen quietly, in their churches,
schools, or in their own back yards.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot lead without a plan people consider worth following.
That is a problem for someone like Governor Paul Cellucci, who has
chosen to take a stand on too many things people consider
irrelevant while taking a pass on more important matters.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad to see a leader fail. But when it happens, it's over.
Voters won't vote for you. Employees won't work for you. Football
players won't play for you. You just can't get anywhere, because no
one understands where you want to go or how to get there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
