<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTANT THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee met this week in Washington.
Nobody expected anything more than a furrowed brow from Alan
Greenspan, in the form of one sort of cryptic statement or another,
addressing bond-buyers' fears of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term rates were raised slightly in November. Raise them
again? ``They have done everything but promise they won't,'' said
Frederick Breimyer, chief economist for State Street Bank and
Trust. The Fed policy-makers will wait at least until their next
meeting in early February to see whether that tap on the brakes was
enough. It probably wasn't, he added.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the century, the American economy is ticking along
very nicely indeed _ soon to become the longest business expansion
ever. The holiday spending season is contributing solidly but not
spectacularly, said David Wyss, an economist who narrates the
economy like a play-by-play announcer for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a
subsidiary of McGraw Hill.
</P>
<P>
   At least three factors are now at work, Wyss said. Wealth is not
growing as quickly this year as in the recent past; the S&AMP;P 500
index is up only 19 percent this year _ compared with an annual
rise of 27 percent for each of the past four years. The slowdown
may have a dampening effect. ``As long as Americans consider
themselves rich, they feel they do not need to save more for
retirement or other purposes,'' Wyss said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, consumers have learned that store prices fall as Dec.
25 approaches. ``Retailers have trained customers to wait for the
last minute before buying their gifts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The busiest shopping day last year was the Saturday before
Christmas, he said. The Friday after Thankgiving ranked a lowly
eighth in sales volume. Electronic commerce may reinforce this
trend, Wyss said. Internet purchases are growing phenomenonally.
They roughly tripled last holiday season; they may have doubled
again this year _ maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet _ and this is the point _ Internet shopping is still a tiny
fraction of all consumer spending _ 0.1 percent, according to DRI,
perhaps as much as half a percent of retail. Throw in catalog sales
and it may be 1 percent, and growing. Americans may be strapped for
time and tired of looking for a parking place. But they're still
going to the stores.
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce boom is clearly in its infancy. No wonder, then,
that the Congressional Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce
is hearing from a growing chorus of store owners and their
political representatives that tax-free status of e-commerce could
become an unfair edge in the battle for consumers' dollars, with
traditional shops that pay sales taxes that vary widely depending
on the state and city. The commission has been holding hearings in
different cities around the country. It is charged with analyzing
the issues surrounding the taxation of Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real problem,'' Wyss said. ``Retailers are worried. So
are politicians. They are worrying about it on fiscal committees of
state legislatures, too, because it's a revenue leak.''
</P>
<P>
   There are limits to the power of the Internet to evade taxation,
of course. Commodities that are delivered locally are still taxed
easily when the owner takes possession. Automobiles, fuel oil, food
_ all will remain comfortably within the power of the tax
collector, even though they may be ordered on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alchoholic beverages are a special problem. I know because I
just tried to order wine to send to a niece. They are not permitted
to deliver to Indiana. You can't ship alcohol into Massachusetts,
either. It is something the liquor wholesalers arranged,'' Wyss
said.
</P>
<P>
   Few tax economists think that e-commerce should be taxed
differently than retail. But many think that the Internet should be
permitted to grow unfettered for a time. Prominent is Austan
Goolsbee, professor of economics at the graduate School of Business
at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons, he said, why the Internet should be
exempted while it grows: compliance costs, information problems,
bandwagon effects. At first, the revenue losses to states and
cities would be small.
</P>
<P>
   But these factors are becoming less important over time. And
once the Internet becomes an established retail channel, it
shouldn't be treated differently than anyone else. The distant
thunder you hear is coming from the bricks-and-mortar merchants who
agree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His e-ail
address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
