<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIAL GOAL: PROSPERITY FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America created prosperity for 30 years after World War II, and
the federal government should repeat many of those same policies
for at least the first 30 years of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, America maintains the same economic polices of the
last 20 years, the new millennium will not be for everyone to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The rich will get richer. The poor will get poorer. And
middle-class incomes will continue a backward slide.
</P>
<P>
   This is what folks are saying at United For A Fair Economy, a
Boston-based think tank that focuses on economic inequality.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, the U.S. economy boomed, and so did people's
incomes. From 1945 to 1979, all Americans saw their incomes
virtually double. Almost everyone, except most African-Americans
before the civil rights movement began, benefited from the new
prosperity, said Betsy Leondar-Wright, of United for A Fair
Economy.
</P>
<P>
   As she explained it, so many Americans prospered because it was
``the deliberate policy of the US Government to create a middle
class'' by implementing programs such as the GI Bill of Rights,
home-buying plans, antipoverty programs, civil rights legislation,
and other programs dsigned to put more money into the hands of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that this was good for American business,''
said Leondar-Wright, giving consumers the ability to buy new homes,
new cars, new appliances. This is what the government wanted, what
business wanted, and what returning GIs wanted.
</P>
<P>
   And until the last 20 years, that is what most Americans got.
</P>
<P>
   From around 1979 to 1999, the richest Americans gained
enormously from a robust economy. Meanwhile, for middle class to
poor Americans, things got worse. Net income of the top fifth of
Americans increased by 38 percent, but the bottom fifth lost 5
percent of their incomes, when corrected for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, for example, the United States had 66 billionaires,
while 31.5 million Americans lived below the poverty line. In 1999,
the number of billionaires rose to 268, while 34.5 million people
lived in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the middle class continued to slide.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the median household, after adjusting for
inflation, had a net worth of $54,600. In 1997, according to the
latest available statistics, the median household had a net worth
of $49,900, a drop of almost $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why this occurred, Leondar-Wright said, ``It's no
mystery.'' In the 1980s and '90s, she said, the government pursued
a policy of supply-side economics, putting a lot more money into
the hands of the wealthy on the theory it would ``trickle down'' to
the rest of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first part happened,'' she said. The policies put money in
the hands of major corporations and wealthy individuals. But the
second part, ``the `trickle down' part, never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, she said, the supply-side policy was more of
``a reward to major campaign contributors'' than sound economics.
</P>
<P>
   But as the millennium approaches, the government can begin to
change these policies to benefit the middle class and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it coul raise the minimum wage, as Democrats in
Congress are trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government also needs to do something to directly give
people assets,'' she added, such as implementing
government-sponsored individual development accounts for low- and
middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The government can also get back into home building programs and
educational funding, to help give people a savings cushion,
something to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   ``All government needs, '' said Leondar-Wright, ``is the will to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
