<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT DIZZYING SPEED, OLD YIELDS TO NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we come to the end of the century and the decade, a great
deal is being written about how much the world has changed in the
last 100 years or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the stock market, what is remarkable is how
much has changed in just the past year. It is not an exaggeration
to say there has been a revolution, as a new order has overthrown
the old one with breathtaking speed. The barbarians are not just at
the gate. They are inside the palace.
</P>
<P>
   One need look no further than Massachusetts to prove the point.
Consider: At the end of the first quarter, less than nine months
ago, we published a list of the 10 Massachusetts public companies
with the greatest market value. The list had a lot of familiar
names.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette ranked first, as it had for most of the decade,
although it was already being challenged for the lead by EMC, the
data storage company in Hopinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the list were Raytheon, Fleet Financial Group,
BankBoston, State Street, the retailer TJX, and Boston Scientific,
which makes medical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to today and take another look.
</P>
<P>
   EMC is number one, having left Gillette in the dust. EMC is
worth $98 billion, compared to $43 billion for Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   More amazing are the changes a little further down the list. In
fourth, fifth, and sixth place, respectively, are CMGI, Akamai
Technologies, and Sycamore Networks.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, of Andover, operates and invests in Internet companies. At
the end of March, its stock was worth $8.5 billion; today it is
worth $26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai and Sycamore weren't even public companies in March.
Akamai, the Cambridge company whose technology eases bottlenecks on
the Internet, had its initial public offering in October; Sycamore,
a Chelmsford maker of telecommunications gear, went public in
October. Neither makes money. Neither has much in the way of sales.
Together, they have a market value of $45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI loses money, too. In its most recent quarter, it reported a
loss of $117 million. Even so, CMGI's stock is worth nearly as much
as Fleet's. Fleet earned $430 million in the most recent quarter.
Fleet purchased BankBoston earlier this year, bringing the state's
fourth- and eighth-largest companies together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have no profits, you have no way to measure,'' says
Frederick Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Corp. ``There
simply isn't an established way of coming up with a value.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently have no such problem. They see great things
ahead for these companies. How else do you explain the astounding
market capitalizations?
</P>
<P>
   The traditional companies on our list _ those not fortunate
enough to be in the Internet business _ have not fared as well.
Nearly all of them have lost value since March. In some cases, the
losses have been dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's value has gone from $65 billion to $43 billion;
Raytheon's from $33 billion to $9 billion. Boston Scientific was
$16 billion; now it's $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   State Street went from $13 billion to $11 billion, Staples from
$15 billion to $9 billion, and TJX from $11 billion to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the new world, the winners win big _ and the losers lose big.
</P>
<P>
   ``The divergence between the haves and have-nots is as extreme
as it has ever been,'' says Thomas O'Neill, chief investment
officer at FleetBoston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the momentum in the market feeds on itself. In
other words, the better tech stocks do, the more money they
attract. Conversely, the worse traditional stocks do, the faster
money flows out of them.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, O'Neill says, there has to be a day of reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies with strong franchises will get recognized,'' he
predicts. And those speculative enterprises that don't live up to
the hype? ``There will be some massive shakeouts,'' O'Neill saysd.
</P>
<P>
   When will this happen? Will it happen? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway Solutions, a Boston e-consulting firm, has become the
latest company to enter the venture capital business.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway says its new venture fund, Breakaway Capital LLC, will
invest primarily in the firm's clients, many of them emerging
dot.com businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way of aligning our goals with our customers,'' said
Gordon Brooks, chief executive. Breakaway was already working on
four deals, he said, none of which have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway also said it made an equity investment in Katalyst, a
Philadelphia company that provides management services to
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway had its initial public offering in October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-21 1860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LONGBOAT KEY, Fla.: ... Western Australia.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   --New Zealand _ You might paraphrase Gertrude Stein's acerbic
line about Oakland (``There's no there there'') and transpose it to
New Zealand as ``There's nobody there there.'' But it wouldn't be
uncomplimentary. Wherever you can find the slight-of-number and
widely distributed people who call themselves Kiwis, they will be
as welcoming as the lovely countryside and coastlines. North
Island, South Island _ it doesn't matter. NZ is just a relaxing
nice zone. You'll find any number of beaches filled with privacy.
Strip and dip. Matai Bay, a double horseshoe at the north end of
the north is my peach of a beach.
</P>
<P>
   --Italy's Feet-challenging Five _ Along Italy's Ligurian coast
in the northwest they lie: Cinque Terre (five lands). Although but
a few miles apart, these remote high-and-low mountain villages _ at
seaside, on crags _ seemed five different, almost inaccessible
countries in the Middle Ages when they could be reached only by
boat or scaling steep, twisty paths. Now a train connects
Riomaggiore, Manarola, Corniglia, Vernazza, and Monterosso with
each other and the nearest city, Levanto. The right idea is to do
one of them per day. But, of course, friend Aurelio, whose family
tree undoubtedly harbored mountain goats, insisted we de-train at
Riomaggiore and clamber, clomp, and cloud-bust through all five in
a 12-mile, 10-hour strain back to Levanto.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived that recital, Murray the Wrench exclaims,
disappointed, ``You didn't mention Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in the next century, or the next life,'' I reply about
the town that Doug Flutie made semifamous. And recalling that a
runaway, the artist Jeremiah Goodman, has described it as ``a place
where both sides of the tracks are the wrong side.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the season of good will to most, and I shouldn't let
another 60 years go by before dropping in on Buffalo again to
devour a singular roast beef sandwich at Charlie the Butcher's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love buffalo,'' cries Aurelio. ``But I mean the East African
kind. Meanest of African critters. Good to shoot _ but with a
camera. Not a gun,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, ever the gallant, says she deserves equal time for her
century's dozen-to-die-for. Absolutely. Aurelio's choices:
</P>
<P>
   --Tibet and Nepal _ ``A gorgeous mountainous journey over land,
by vehicle and foot, through primitive, sparsely inhabited country,
past silent, virginal peaks from Lhasa through Shigatse to
Katmandu, included an Everest trek up the Tibetan north face to
Base Camp I. But a strip search at the Tibet border by obnoxious
Chinese guards _ crude, bored guys amusing themselves _ did not
endear the People's Republic to me.''
</P>
<P>
   --Cambodia _ ``Angkor Wat is truly magnificent, haunting, but I
was charmed by a neighborhood gem, Ta Prohm, a small temple
fighting for its existence against rogue invaders _ persistent
strangler fig trees. They are locked in a timeless grapple.''
</P>
<P>
   --Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula _ ``Dramatic Uxmal, an 8th- century
Mayan city sequestered in deep jungle. What I relished _of course _
was climbing the steep-sided pyramid on precipitous steps. The
nearby city, Chichen Itza, is wonderful, too, with its deep well
into which virgins were dropped as sacrifices to the gods. I left
before the custom was revived.''
</P>
<P>
   --Mount Kilimanjaro _ ``Tanzania's attic, the highest mountain
in Africa (19,340 feet) is a sturdy climb made by many. However,
few go beyond Gilman's Point, the rim of the crater. The summit,
Uhuru Peak, is another mile and a half and 700 feet in altitude
farther. That's the hard part. I kept remembering David Breashears,
the mountaineer, counseling me, `You'll be mad at yourself if you
get as close as Gilman's and don't go all the way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --Great Barrier Island _ ``An unspoiled New Zealand dot 50 miles
from Auckland. It has everything for a getaway: sensational
beaches, mountains, bush walks, views, hot springs. Not many
people. No electricity or running water, but there are generators,
rain-catchers, and limited places to stay. It has my favorite
airport of all at Claris. The terminal is a shack, the landing
strip grass. You just walk to the plane and get on. What a soothing
departure from the huge malls-with-runways and lines of passengers
we encounter in most cities.''
</P>
<P>
   --Tasmania _ ``Australia's almost-forgotten island state. Plenty
of wilderness. Endless untrammeled beaches from which penguins
march to their maritime dining rooms. Hobart, a bottom-of-the-world
city, is up high in friendliness, restaurants, nice places to hang
out, and a mountain called Wellington.''
</P>
<P>
   --Rome _ ``OK, so it's old and decrepit. It has been for
millennia. But you can't beat experience. That's what Rome's got _
and it's a wondrous experience to experience that experience,
wrapped in so much history. Regardless of how many times you visit,
there's always something new to the eyes of a walking explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   --Monument Valley, Utah _ ``The Western movie couldn't exist
without this monumental cowboys-and-Indians desert playground of
pinnacles, peaks, mesas, boulders, sagebrush, cactus. You've seen
it innumerable times on the screen, but . . . surrounded by it . .
. you're as overwhelmed as John Wayne by Claire Trevor in the
original `Stagecoach.' Sunrise and sunset, enlivening the rock
formations, are dramas of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   --Ha Long Bay, Vietnam _ ``Off Haiphong, this stretch of sea is
punctured by rocky cones, magical uninhabited islands that seem
sculpted by angels, each different and beguiling. These sights
required a long boat trip and a night on Cat Ba island at a hotel
unbeatable in its standards of grunginess _ but worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Tanzanian camping _ ``Too bad they don't allow overnights at
Ngorongoro Crater anymore. We were lucky to tent there in '88 as
elephants, lions, zebras, and tree hyrax wandered about us in the
moonlight. On the same trip, the Serengeti Plain, a majestic herd
of 70 elephants emerged from a grove of acacias to hospitably
parade for us, not even prompted by the local chamber of
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   --New Mexican pueblos _ ``The Indians have tried to preserve a
distinguished culture, and it hasn't been easy. To me the seasonal
dances are very spiritual. Especially the Corn Dance _ in the hope
of a good harvest _ at Santo Domingo Pueblo, not far from Santa Fe.
As a girl I danced with the tribe there, and I cherish the memories
of the ritual beneath vast skies and continents of clouds. An
outsider wouldn't be permitted to participate now, other than as a
spectator, but we were neighbors and my father was a friend of
tribal leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   --Angel Falls _ ``It's a heavenly spigot all right. Except for
rain, no water drops straight down from higher, about 3,000 feet
into a Venezuelan jungle. You can get up close in a small plane as
we did. But most of my Venezuelan time in the Peace Corps was spent
in Caracas where home-sweet-homes for way too many folks were
wooden crates in the barrio.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray says, ``My room is an improvement on that. I think we're
pretty lucky to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   And then some. To be anywhere. You might agree with the
philosophy of Boston's own Teddy Green, the renowned (unauthorized)
withdrawer of bank funds, who used to say, ``A room is a room is a
room.'' Of course, most of his had bars on windows and doors at
stopovers like Alcatraz.
</P>
<P>
   As hotel-roomers most of the time over the years, Aurelio and I
have gone the A-to-Z route _ admirable to zany _ and she has a
``fond memories'' half-dozen: the Lake Palace in Udaipur, India;
Hayman Island Resort, Australia; the Cavallieri Hilton in Rome; the
Oriental in Bangkok; San Domenico in Taormina, Sicily;
Hilton-on-the-Park in Melbourne, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Situated on its own small island in the lake, built around a
lush garden, the Lake Palace R _ for romantic _ great,'' she says.
``Hayman has everything _ beaches, pools, six fine restaurants,
wilderness, access to the Great Barrier Reef. On a hilltop, the
Cavallieri gives you bustling Rome at your feet, but in a relaxed
atmosphere. Its swimming pools, indoor and outdoor, are splendid,
the spa fit for the most sybaritic Roman emperor. Longtime staff
members like Grace Rettondini and Lynn Knudsen, concierge Italo
Fort, doormen Antonio Franitto and Salvatore Mirarchi greet you
like old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the string quartet in the lobby to service supreme, plus
the vista of frenetic river traffic, the Oriental is a dream. San
Domenico, a tastefully restored ancient monastery, is chaperoned by
Mount Etna, the Aegean Sea, and elaborate gardens. Aussie good
spirit abounds at that Hilton where Anita Gromotka oversees a new
world-class spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also-likes include: Sails in the Desert at Ayers Rock,
Australia; the Rittenhouse in Philadelphia; the Hyatt in
Birmingham, England; the Metropoles in Moscow and Hanoi; Dolphin
Square in London; Prince de Galles in Paris; Marina Cay in the
British Virgins; Silver Sands on Key Biscayne, Fla.; Four Seasons
in Seattle; UN Plaza (for its pool) in New York; Boca Raton (Fla.)
Resort and Club; the Peninsula in Hong Kong; Norma and Des Fallon's
Queensland Outback ranch, Avington, south of Barcaldine, Australia
_ no jollier B &AMP; B hosts could be found.''
</P>
<P>
   And the zany? The prize goes to the Colonial Motel in Gallup,
N.M., where a bold burglar crawled in through the bathroom window
at 2 a.m., scared us awake, then fled through the door clutching
his prize _ my toothbrush. No reward has been offered.
</P>
<P>
   Murray wants to know, ``Do you people ever go home to Boston?''
</P>
<P>
   We visit. ``You should try it. It's a marvelous city,'' says
Aurelio. ``Both of us are immigrants from way west of Dedham, but,
having lived in The Bean for several decades, we may yet be
approved by Mayor Mennino for green cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston brings music to our ears like no other city _ the
outpourings of classical and jazz on Stations WHRB, WGBH, WBUR,
WHRB. On the road we miss all-rounder Ron Della Chiesa with his
``Morning Classics'' and ``Jazz Song Book'' on WGBH where the
brilliant piano player, Virginia Eskin, hosts ``A Note to You'' on
Sundays (although at 6 a.m.! Are programmers trying to hide Eskin
out in Whitey Bulger style?)
</P>
<P>
   We were fortunate to catch John Williams's composition ``For
Seiji,'' his tribute to Maestro Ozawa's silver anniversary at the
helm of Seiji's Big Band (a.k.a. the Boston Symphony Orchestra).
The same afternoon, Ozawa conducted Richard Strauss's ``Death and
Transfiguration'' so movingly that it made death seem appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The death of a year, a century and a millennium are coming up as
we are about to be transfigured into . . . what? For you, cherished
reader, we wish Holiday Huzzahs, egg nog (straight or enhanced to
your taste), laughs, good health, and avoidance of the Y2Kukoo bug
anywhere you go, as well as those ghastly unmentionable automated
phone systems on which a human voice is as rare as a lovable robot.
</P>
<P>
   Whether millennial malaise or merriment awaits, the advice here
is to close your eyes, hold your nose, say a prayer, and take the
21st-century plunge.
</P>
<P>
   See you anywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
