<HEADLINE>
ALL I WANT FOR CHRISTMAS IS... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
Dear Santa, 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, I know it's been a long time. How's it goin'? Are
you taking a hit from the Internet shopping boom? I wouldn't worry
too much about it _ at least you know your deliveries will be there
Christmas morning. As for me, I think it's been about 30 or so
years since I last dropped you a line, and if I remember correctly,
I wanted a basketball, right?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's been a pretty good year, and I've already gotten a
number of things I wanted such cancellation of ABC's
``Wasteland''; a host of smart, challenging and provocative films
like ``American Beauty,'' ``Being John Malkovich,'' ``Boys Don't
Cry,'' and ``Election''; a new Nine Inch Nails album, ``The
Fragile''; and a two-year break from performing by Celine Dion.
But, of course, there are a few more wouldn't mind finding under my
tree come Christmas. So, here's my wish list:
</P>
<P>
   --After the failures this decade of dramas with predominately
African-American casts such as Fox's ``413 Hope St.'' and ``South
Central,'' ABC's ``Gabriel's Fire,'' and CBS's ``Under One Roof,''
pleasepleaseplease let CBS's upcoming new hospital drama, ``City of
Angels,'' which premieres Jan. 16, be not only good, but
successful.
</P>
<P>
   --Better sales for Macy Gray's ``On How Life Is,'' Mos Def's
``Black on Both Sides,'' Me'Shell Ndegeocello's ``Bitter,'' and
Fiona Apple's ``When the Pawn. . .''
</P>
<P>
   --Fifty more years of ``Peanuts'' and Charles Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   --Movie trailers that can entice an audience without revealing
every single plot twist.
</P>
<P>
   --No more posthumous albums ``by'' Notorious B.I.G., like the
dreadful ``Born Again,'' which is little more than a crazy quilt of
Biggie rhymes and snippets sewn onto beats and guest-star turns.
Hey Puff, stop rolling Biggie's corpse in hopes that a few more
coins will fall out of his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   --A steel-cage, no-holds-barred, pay-per-view beatdown between
singer/actress/occasional nuisance/Kurt Cobain widow Courtney Love
and Dave Grohl, current Foo Fighter and former Nirvana drummer. The
marvelous catfighting between these two _ La Love recently lit
Grohl up on ``The Howard Stern Show,'' and ``Stacked Actors'' on
the Foos' latest is rumored to be a shot at Courtney _ is just
endlessly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   --An end to lousy ``time-slot'' hits like NBC's ``Jessie'' and
``Stark Raving Mad,'' which succeed simply because they reside in
the comfy cushion between ``Friends'' and ``Frasier,'' and
``Frasier'' and ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   --If the Latin pop trend is to be believed, then how about major
crossover success and full star treatment for the great Celia Cruz
or the Afro-Cuban All-Stars?
</P>
<P>
   --An Academy Award nominating committee that does not follow the
miscue of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association (the Golden Globe
people) in overlooking the wonderful performance of Wes Bentley in
``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jewel to stick to her folkie-yodeling thing (such as it is),
and write books of poetry _ like the ridiculous and embarassing ``A
Night Without Armor'' _ no more.
</P>
<P>
   --Fred Durst of Limp Bizkit to finally acknowledge that
performing ``Break Stuff'' before the increasingly volatile throngs
at Woodstock '99 last summer was a remarkably stupid thing to do.
Like, dude, what were you thinking?
</P>
<P>
   --No more Woodstocks. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   And, come to think of it, I never did get that basketball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
