<HEADLINE>
A SKI GUARANTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will it snow on Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   While the kids may be concerned that Santa won't arrive unless
his sleigh has snow to ride on, skiers have no concerns. At least
skiers who head for six of New England's top areas this holiday
season. They're guaranteed snow if they reserve a ski vacation
between now and Dec. 24 for the period Dec. 25-Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have snow,'' says Les Otten, American Skiing Co. chief
executive officer. ``Our resorts have the most advanced snowmaking
systems in the nation, and we expect to be wide open. But if we
can't give our guests at least 70 percent of their mountain, we'll
activate our guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   The guarantee gives guests a 25 percent price reduction on their
next vacation this season and a voucher worth up to $500, which may
be used toward a future ski vacation at The Canyons in Utah or
Steamboat in Colorado. And, guests who choose to may cancel
reservations at no cost on the planned day of arrival if that
threshold has not been met.
</P>
<P>
   The resorts with the guarantee are Killington, Mount Snow, and
Sugarbush in Vermont; Sunday River and Sugarloaf in Maine; and
Attitash Bear Peak in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And, in addtion to snow, Otten says the resorts will have lots
of other activities as well as festive New Year's Eve parties for
all ages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One big hug
</P>
<P>
   What better way to bring in the new century than one giant
festive hug of people from many nations around the Dead Sea, the
lowest place on earth? The Millennium Great Embrace on New Year's
Eve is a communal effort by the State of Israel, the Hashemite
Kingdom of Jordan, and the Palestinian Authority. Its purpose is to
be a ``universal declaration of dedication to peace and the
conservation of nature for children,'' said Arie Sommer, Israel
commissioner for tourism in North America. More than 100,000 people
of all ages are expected to join hands around the sea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow train
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Bay Railroad Enthusiasts will be running their
annual Snow Train to Vermont Feb. 26. The one-day trip will leave
from Boston and continue to Brattleboro and Bellows Falls. Optional
side trips include a sleigh ride, country inn luncheon, covered
bridge tour, and a 26-mile round-trip ride on the Green Mountain
Railroad. Fares are $70 adult, $40 children 12 and under. Stops
will also be made at Wellesley, West Natick, and Worcester. For
more information, call 617-489-5277 or www.Massbayrre.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Need a nanny?
</P>
<P>
   Families visiting Aruba can now have the services of a nanny.
The Aruba Sonesta has begun an ``Island Nanny Program'' that
provides a nanny for the duration of the family's stay. The service
costs $120 a day from 8 a.m. to midnight for two children. For
information on the nanny program, call Coleta Zschuschen at
011-2978-36000. For reservations, call 800-SONESTA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
