<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GETS ITS JOLLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas was once banned in Massachusetts and didn't become a
legal holiday in the state until 1856. My, how times have changed:
Nowadays, Massachusetts _ and especially Boston _ is filled with
fa-la-la. And those who take Boston's Holly Jolly Holiday Trolley
Tour not only view the glory of the city at Christmas but learn a
lot about the holiday as well. Among the fascinating facts:
</P>
<P>
   --Charles Dickens gave the first reading of ``A Christmas
Carol'' in the United States at Tremont Temple in 1867, performing
all the parts in different voices. (These days the marvelous
musical ``Black Nativity'' is presented at the temple during the
holiday season.)
</P>
<P>
   --The city's two principal Christmas trees are gifts. The Boston
Common tree is from the children of New Brunswick, and the tree at
the Prudential Center is from the people of Nova Scotia. Decorating
the Pru tree, incidentally, takes more than 3,200 hours to hang 4.5
miles of wire and 17,000 lights.
</P>
<P>
   --America's first Christmas cards originated in Boston in 1874.
</P>
<P>
   --Newbury Street has everything a shopper could want, including,
it is said, the items mentioned in the ``Twelve Days of Christmas''
song. But to get everything (buying a partridge in a pear tree,
renting eight maids to milk, etc.) would cost $55,086.26.
</P>
<P>
   --The big metal teddy bear outside F.A.O. Schwartz is believed
to be the world's largest. In any event, it weighs 6,112 pounds, is
12 feet tall, and eight feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   (The Holly Jolly Holiday Trolley Tour is presented by Old Town
Trolley Tours. Remaining dates are Dec. 22, 23, 26, and 27.
Trolleys depart at 6:15 p.m. from the Old Town Trolley Stop on
Cambridge Street at City Hall Plaza. The two-hour, fully narrated
tour includes admission to the Enchanted Village on the plaza,
cocoa and cookies while watching the skaters on Boston Common Frog
Pond, sights that range from the candlelight of Beacon Hill windows
to the festively decorated USS Constitution, and a lot of singing
along to recordings by everyone from Sinatra to the Partridge
Family. The cost is $25 for adults and $12 for children. For
reservations or more information, call 617-269-7150.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Where did a certain bishop named St. Nicholas live
about AD 300? &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: There is a Christmas, Ariz., Christmas, Fla., and Santa
Claus, Ind. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Put some memories in your travelin' bag/ and miles upon
your shoes'' _ sound advice from folksinger Bill Staines.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred pronunciation: El Dorado, Ark., is pronounced with a
long ``A'' to rhyme with tornado, and not the Spanish way. (With
thanks to Henry Taves of Lecompte, La.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
How's that again? Instructions on some Chinese-made Christmas
lights: ``For indoor or outdoor use only.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Asia Minor, most of which is known today as
Turkey, just as St. Nicholas is known today as Santa Claus. Merry
Christmas!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
