<SLUG> BC-MCGROROY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT ON THE RITZ AT MY PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News bulletin: Florida couple pays $100,000 for the Boston
Ritz-Carlton ``Ultimate Millennium Experience'' package on New
Year's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That thrilling rumor being celebrated in Boston society circles
this holiday season is absolutely true. I've decided to rent out my
apartment for New Year's Eve, and it promises to be a weekend that
my lucky guests will not soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know what you're thinking. The unabashed elegance, the
exotic fabrics, the European-trained staff, the vintage wines _ how
can we, the public, ever afford to take such a place of honor in
your cherished home?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the short answer is, you probably can't.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who can, be assured that no expense will be
spared, no detail overlooked, no luxury stinted in an attempt to
make this the most resplendent weekend of your important lives. And
allow me to earn your trust. Never, ever, would I gouge on prices
amid all this crass and commercial millennial hype, even among you
tardy last-minute party planners. Not me.
</P>
<P>
   What's the competition? This Ritz-Carlton ``Ultimate Millennium
Experience?'' Ultimate schmultimate. That hotel hasn't been
renovated in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   And their package, which is already booked, barely goes beyond
the usual fare, with the typical chauffeur-driven Jaguar, a few
nights in the presidential suite with a butler, a magnum of
Taittinger champagne and couple of Baccarat crystal flutes,
matching Bulgari watches, Bulgari perfume. Remember, Bulgari rhymes
with vulgarity, almost.
</P>
<P>
   And, ho-hum, you get dinner in their wine cellar, breakfast in
bed and entry to their so-called New Year's Eve party, where blue
hair suddenly looks like a fashion trend.
</P>
<P>
   And their point is?
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine yourself sashaying into the inviting environs of my
one-bedroom apartment. Set the thermostat at whatever temperature
you'd like. Help yourself to the holiday M&AMP;Ms piled high in a
festive Crate &AMP; Barrel bowl. Walk the dog as often as you desire,
and feel free to give him his anti-itch pills precisely at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Choose from hand-selected wines in both red and white. Kick your
feet up on the genuine wooden coffee table and partake in your
favorite television show (use of remote control included). Sprawl
out on the recently laundered sheets of my double bed.
</P>
<P>
   Staff? My Aunt Nanny will iron your tails and gowns for the
enchanting evening ahead. My nephew waits outside in his 1993 Dodge
Caravan, ready to whisk you as far as your imagination might go,
provided he has enough gas.
</P>
<P>
   And I am personally at your beck and call, available and eager
to tend to your every need, whether it be pushing my soiled clothes
into the corner of a closet or helping you unclog the stubborn
bathtub drain. If I've fallen asleep on the couch, I encourage
guests to show no hesitation whatsoever in waking me up. Just be
warned that on rare occasions I've been heard to shout nonviolent
obscenities in my sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts? Make liberal use of the Old Spice cologne left on the
bathroom vanity. Lather yourself in an array of Ivory soaps and
Breck shampoos. Wrap your cleansed body in the softened warmth of a
cotton-poly blend towel.
</P>
<P>
   And as you leave, as a memento of the times past and the
wondrous stories you'll carry ahead, take a keepsake glass ashtray
engraved with the words, ``Days Inn/Hartsfield Airport.'' These are
the memories that will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   And dinner will bring your millennial experience to an entirely
different level, which in this case is actually the basement, where
you will dine on a genuine white tablecloth in a setting
reminiscent of the Ritz wine cellar. Notice, for instance, all the
pretty bottles in the nearby recycling bin.
</P>
<P>
   Choose from an array of Asian delicacies from the menu of a
local Chinese take-out restaurant, all as my friend, Eduardo,
thrills you with your favorite polkas mastered on his accordion.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, for the special enjoyment of our guests, we've
arranged for a massive, complimentary fireworks display over Boston
Harbor at the stroke of midnight. Kindly tell the uniformed police
officers that you're the guest of honor and they'll no doubt leave
you to your personal joy.
</P>
<P>
   And all this, ladies and gentlemen, for exactly half the price
of that Ritz package. Yes, you read that right. No gouging here,
not like all those other establishments in town that charge so much
for so little. And the leftover Chinese food? It's yours to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
