<HEADLINE>
BRUSH UP YOUR BIBLE, START QUOTING IT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidential candidates have decided not to hide their light
under a bushel this campaign season. They're letting their light
shine before men, playing the faith card, though how far they'll go
in applying the Golden Rule to their rivals remains to be seen. But
the rhetoric bears watching, and not just on grounds of
appropriateness and sincerity. When it comes to misquotation and
misapprehension, the Bible is probably running neck and neck with
poor Shakespeare, and we want to hold would-be leaders to a high
rhetorical standard.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's true, misquotation is a venial sin: Shakespeare
wrote ``To gild refined gold, to paint the lily,'' but it's usually
condensed to ``gild the lily''; Churchill spoke of ``blood, toil,
tears, and sweat,'' but we like it better as ``blood, sweat, and
tears.'' The biblical proverb says ``Pride goeth before
destruction, and an haughty spirit before a fall''; in popular use,
it's ``Pride goeth before a fall.'' But these modifications remain
true to the spirit, if not the letter, of the originals.
</P>
<P>
   Our collective editing is not always so benign, though. Reader
Eric Naticchioni of Chelmsford, for one, is mightily vexed by the
common misusage of the Bible's ``suffer the children'' as if it
meant ``the children are suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   As Naticchioni notes, the biblical scene _ he quotes from the
King James version, Mark 10:13-16 _ has the disciples trying to
keep visiting children away from Jesus. ``But when Jesus saw it, he
was much displeased, and said unto them, Suffer the little children
to come unto me, and forbid them not: for of such is the kingdom of
God.'' ``Suffer'' here means simply ``allow,'' and though that
meaning is now called archaic, it was in use a mere century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The worst offenders in the ``suffer'' department are not
reporters, in fact, but headline writers, who can't resist slapping
``Suffer the children'' onto editorials about families in poverty
or feature stories about child abuse. These headlines (and the Pat
Benatar song title, too) are all misquotations _ though the writers
may not know they're quotations at all. I suspect some of the perps
do know their rendering is wrong, but think readers don't care; Mr.
Naticchioni is here to testify that they do care, and so should
editors.
</P>
<P>
   None of the presidential candidates is likely to quote ``Money
is the root of all evil,'' but if John McCain ventures onto that
ground _ with ``Soft money is the root of all evil,'' say _ the
opposition's defense is the correct quotation: ``Love of money is
the root of all evil.'' After all, even a guy who's filthy rich can
deny that he actually loves the loot _ except, maybe, Donald Trump,
who revels in the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But ``filthy rich'' may be an inappropriate description of The
Donald, with his hygiene obsession; he should be appealing to the
cleanliness-is-next-to-godliness constituency. Would he be
surprised _ and would they _ to learn that the maxim comes from a
sermon by that pillar of Protestantism, John Wesley? And that he
borrowed it not from the Bible, but from the Talmud?
</P>
<P>
   As for that Golden Rule _ ``Do unto others as you would have
others do unto you'' _ it doesn't appear in the Bible in that form,
either; it's a distillation of Jesus' words from two of the
gospels. (The similar sentiment, ``Love thy neighbor as thyself,''
appears first as an Old Testament injunction.) And ``God helps
those who help themselves'' is no more biblical than ``Win one for
the Gipper''; it's from Aesop, though his gods were plural.
</P>
<P>
   God tempers the wind to the shorn lamb? Perhaps, but not in the
Bible. The English novelist Laurence Sterne stole it from a
16th-century French version. And that lamb isn't lying down with
the lion to keep warm, either. In the original, full-length
version, Isaiah's vision is that ``The wolf also shall dwell with
the lamb, and the leopard shall lie down with the kid; and the calf
and the young lion and the fatling together.'' But the lion and the
lamb make a natural alliterative pair, and a much more reassuring
image for a holid. (Here too, folklore has trumped fact; a
lion is far more dangerous than a wolf, but try telling that to
Little Red Riding Hood.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as we watch the ``Peanuts'' gang stage its final
Christmas pageant, here's a timely tidbit: The Bible doesn't tell
us that there were three kings, or wise men, who came to Bethlehem
from the East _ only that they brought three kinds of gifts. For
all we know there were two dozen, wise enough to pool their
resources for a gift basket of gold, frankincense, and myrrh. But
ignorance, in this case, may be bliss: ``We 14 kings of Orient
are'' just wouldn't have the same ring, would it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
