<SLUG> BC-LUNAR-EVENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMIC FORCES CREATE A SOLSTICE WORTH CELEBRATING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put aside millennial madness for a moment. For a year-end event
with a little cosmic clout, consider Wednesday, the first day of
winter, coincides with a full moon and the lunar perigee, the point
at which the moon's orbit is closest to the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the moon is approaching its nearest point to the
sun, all of which adds up to a somewhat rare confluence of cosmic
events. Though you may not even notice it, the full moon will be a
little larger and a little brighter than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Where skies are clear and there is snow and ice on the ground
the effect could be quite magical. Given this celestial setting,
new age devotees have been planning celebration rituals for months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, professional astronomers are not particularly excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solstice, the full moon, and the lunar perigee all occur
within a few hours of each other. So what?'' says Brian Marsden,
director of the planetary science division of the
Harvard-Smithsonian Center of Astrophysics in Cambridge, Mass.
``The moon is always high and bright in December and January.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers generally find full moons boring, Marsden says.
``You can't see the stars well or tell what's happening on the dark
side of the moon,'' he explains. ``Full moon nights are good ones
for astronomers to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   But astrologers, neo-pagans, Wiccans, and practioners of Native
American shamanism attach a great deal of importance to all full
moons and changes of season. `
</P>
<P>
   `The moon mythically represents our unconsciousness, and a full
moon on the solstice at the end of the century is very
significant,'' says Karen Thorne of Lincoln, Mass., a professional
astrologer.``I don't think that there will be any one dramatic
occurrence, but there could be profound changes in our collective
unconsciousness that will bring new insights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagan and Wiccan spirituality is earth-centered and its
holidays correspond with changes in the environment,'' explains
Chistopher Giroux, manager of the Unicorn Bookstore in Arlington,
Mass., which specializes in new age literature and serves as a
resource center for the local neo-pagan community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate the winter solstice as `Yule,' the rebirth of the
sun. The summer solstice and the vernal and autumnal equinoxes are
also holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The winter solstice, when the sun is farthest south of the
celestial equator, falls on the shortest day of the year. But it
won't seem very short to Cheryl Masson of Rehoboth, Mass., a
priestess in the Church of Wicca and chairwoman of the Witches
League for Public Awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very long day,'' says Masson. Beside the
customary Wiccan rituals associated with a full moon and solstice,
Masson says, she will participate in the dedication of the site of
a new temple for the congregation she has cofounded in Dighton with
Laurie Cabot of Salem, Mass., dean of the area's self-declared
witches.
</P>
<P>
   Masson is also a local coordinator for ``Goddess 2000,'' an
international project involving Wiccan and neo-pagan groups all
over the United States and in 32 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witches and others will gather around the world to celebrate
the solstice,'' Masson says, but also ``to focus their energy to
create awareness in the coming millennium of what we call `the
goddess,' the feminine element of the universal life force.''
</P>
<P>
   Because this year the solstice falls midweek, many new age
organizations held combination ritual and social events over the
weekend; members will observe the actual seasonal change on their
own. ``We had a Yule celebration, with a ritual circle, at the
bookstore on Saturday and a couple of dozen people took part,''
says Giroux.
</P>
<P>
   Many pagans and Wiccans also prefer to keep a low profile and
observe their holidays in the privacy of their homes. ``The winter
solstice is an important holiday but my husband and I are solitary
practitioners of Wicca,'' says Lynn Dube of Haverill, Mass. ``We'll
just have a little party, light candles, and maybe do something a
bit special in the way of ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   The big moon solstice has also touched off a buzz on the
Internet: exchanges of e-mail messages and electronic chain
letters. Many people were first alerted to the event by a
hyperbolic Old Farmer's Almanac article, which even speculated
wildly that the moon could get so bright ``even your car's
headlights may seem superfluous.''
</P>
<P>
   Be advised, say scientists and highway safety experts: The moon
never gets so bright that it's safe to turn car headlights off at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Marsden says that what is of rare note is that the three events
_ the winter solstice, the perigee, and the full moon _ take place
in such quick succession this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1866, the solstice, full moon, and lunar perigee occurred
over 20 hours,'' he says. ``But this time it will be over 10 hours,
with the solstice at 12:42 p.m., the perigee at 4 p.m., and the
full moon at 10:32 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you could say,'' Marsden adds, ``that ours will be even
better than the last one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
