<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SOLDIER-SILENT-NIGHT-     12-21 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLDIER-SILENT-NIGHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHRISTMAS CAROL THAT CONQUERED THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Vincent de Liberto is a freelance writer based in New York.)
 &HT;    
 By VINCENT de LIBERTO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Nearly 40 years ago I passed my first Christmas in Germany as a
19-year-old American soldier. I had arrived at a small U.S. Army
base outside the town of Herzogenaurach, so deep in the snowbound
month of December that I lacked an immediate duty assignment.
Luckily, I received a surprise 24-hour-pass to Christmas Eve.
 &HT;    I joined some other green-uniformed soldiers and we boarded the
regular military bus heading off base to explore the nearest big
city--Nuremberg.
 &HT;    We had seen a USO brochure describing Nuremberg as Germany's No.
l Christmas city. Nuremberg of the infamous war-crimes trials, the
Hitler rallies, the racial laws--Nuremberg, the setting of the Nazi
propaganda film, ``Triumph of the Will.''
 &HT;    Our bus stopped at the very Nuremberg streetcorner I would
recognize years later in the film, ``Judgment at Nuremberg.''
 &HT;    I paired up with an army pal and we headed for the Altstadt, or
Old City, the walled medieval center surmounted by a castle on a
hill.
 &HT;    First, of course, we made sure to stop in one, two, or
three--and probably four--Stammlokals (or taverns) along the way;
we needed to test the local Franconian brews.
 &HT;    I knew something of Nuremberg's notorious history under the
Nazis -- I had seen the 1930s newsreels of torchlit Nazi rallies in
the Altstadt. Allied bombers later flattened the half-timbered
medieval center. In 1945, in a single night, 600 bombers rained
down tons of explosives, killed thousands and rendered tens of
thousands homeless.
 &HT;    We finally made our way into the Altstadt, behind the restored
medieval walls, and found the Hauptmarkt, or central market square.
 &HT;    For hundreds of years, each Christmas season the market square
has hosted the Christkindelsmarkt, or Christchild Market.
Nurembergers set up dozens of booths and stalls--festooned with
strings of lights--and sell regional handicrafts, dolls, puppets
and tin soldiers.
 &HT;    We caught a smokey whiff of a foodstand offering Nuremberger
specialties--warm pretzels and sizzling sausages. Immediately, we
reached for the Nuremberger pretzels that go so well with the
Franconian brews, then the small, dark, sizzling bratwursts, served
up with steamy scoops of onions on a hard roll. And there was
Schnapps, of course.
 &HT;    Suitably fortified against the biting night air, we moved
through the market throngs to the Shoenerbrunner, or Beautiful
Fountain, a medieval masterwork. We found the fabled brass ring
hand-wrought seamlessly into the iron grillwork, spun it, but could
not work it loose. We greeted sparkling frauleins in the spirit of
the season as they passed us by.
 &HT;    By now, it had surprised me to see no signs of war damage. In
Frankfurt, our embarkation point into West Germany, lingering
damage was still evident in bombed-out ruins in side streets. Now,
in Nuremberg, in the heart of the most heavily bombed city in West
Germany, singled out for special attention as a Nazi symbol of
rancor and exterminationist hatred of the Jews, the Altstadt
seemingly had risen to a new life to celebrate the birthday of
Christ.
 &HT;    As commercial activity began to slow in the Christkindelsmarkt,
the crowds were moving toward the Frauenkirche, or Our Lady's
Church. It too had risen from the ashes of destruction -- postcards
on sale in local shops showed it as a smoldering ruin in 1945. Now,
the doors were flung open to a Christmas service under way.
 &HT;    A celestial melody floated out into the market square,
accompanied by angelic voices. It was ``Silent Night,'' but it took
me a moment to catch on to the original German lyrics, ``Stille
Nacht, Heilige Nacht.'' They floated in the night air like a balm
to soothe my private images of World War II destruction.
 &HT;    In 1960 the German language was mainly familiar to me through
the filter of World War II movies--''Achtung!'', ``Jawohl!'' or
``Heil Hitler!'' Now I heard it renedered beautifully in a
Christmas night, and I went on in later years to memorize the
German lyrics, preferring them to the English.
 &HT;    In fact, I started to collect them in the languages of countries
where I would pass the holidays in the ensuing decades--France,
Spain, the Netherlands.
 &HT;    I recently managed to revisit Herzogenaurach and Nuremberg. I
did so through the magical transport of the Internet and the World
Wide Web. I glimpsed this year's Christkindelsmarkt by ``live
cam.'' And my cyberspace visit sparked the memory of my 1960
footsoldier's tour and the deathless tones of ``Stille Nacht,
Heilige Nacht'' soaring in that frigid market square that had once
been smashed into ruins.
 &HT;    Later, I focused my Web search engine on ``Silent Night.'' To my
surprise, the master site was not in Germany or Austria but in
South Africa. The Web page (http://silentnight.web.za/) collects a
hundred translations of Silent Night in a hundred languages,
literally from A to Z--including versions in American Sign Language
and Delaware Indian.
 &HT;    Then again, maybe it is fitting that we should find ``Silent
Night's'' healing words featured in South Africa--a country that
has also known more than its fair share of rancor and racial hatred
in this century. So this 1999 season the Afrikaner sings, ``Stille
nag, heilige nag''--and the Zulu, ``Busuku obuhle.''
 &HT;    The Christmas carol that conquered the world.
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Vincent de Liberto
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-JAPAN-FACES-BOS &LR;      12-21 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FACES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING JAPANESE TO PUT ON A HAPPY FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Put a pair of chopsticks between your teeth, and bite
down. The corners of your mouth should rise above the horizontal
line of the chopsticks. No? Then you need some smile therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshihiko Kadokawa is happy to help out. With his company, the
Smile Amenity Institute, and his book, ``The Power of the Smile,''
he has a tidy little business going teaching the Japanese how to
grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to always keep the mouth up, it creates a good
face,'' Kadokawa said. And it is a lesson many Japanese badly need,
added the smile specialist, who bemoans his people's lack of facial
expressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Hired mostly by businesses that want their salespeople to put on
a good face to attract customers, Kadokawa has more work than he
can do teaching eye contact, cheek movement, and how to massage the
face to give it a softer, more pleasant expression.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, putting on a good face in Japan meant doing
nothing at all. For centuries, the face has been a social mask more
than a tool for individual expression. Even talking about it was
considered taboo.
</P>
<P>
   But like so much in Japan these days, much of the old way of
life is being flipped on its head _ including the face.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, whether it is a raised eyebrow or muscular control,
facial expression is the subject of books, academic study,
television shows, and a museum exhibition touring the country.
Scientists, business executives, and ordinary Japanese are deciding
that despite all the communication tools at their disposal _ from
the Internet to mobile phones _ the face has an important role to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese predisposition to keep a blank face does not suit
the modern world, said Hiroshi Harashima, director of the Academy
of Facial Studies in Tokyo, whose 700 members include
psychologists, cosmetologists, physiologists, anthropologists, and
forensic scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of expression is changing because of
international society. It is important not to be misunderstood,''
said Harashima, an engineer who founded the academy, which is said
to be the only one of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Harashima became interested in the face in the 1980s when
videophones began to be developed. He began working on computer
techniques to alter facial expressions and make faces more
pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   The academy helped sponsor a popular interactive museum show
called Dai-Kao-Ten (Big Face Exhibition) to which hundreds of
thousands are flocking.
</P>
<P>
   During the show's run in Tokyo, more than 300,000 people crowded
the National Science Museum to ponder the faces of celebrities,
politicians, historical figures, even animals. How to read the
face, and how emotions of surprise and disgust are registered _
these are just some of the issues the exhibit explores.
</P>
<P>
   With much of the exhibition interactive, visitors can examine
and remold their faces with odd-angled mirrors and computer
simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Susumu Kiyoko and his wife said they came away from the exhibit
realizing that the face is more than just a social tool. It can
affect how you feel about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep an angry face, it can make you angry. I don't want
that to happen so I have to be careful to keep smiling,'' said
Kiyoko, a 51-year-old dollmaker.
</P>
<P>
   After watching exhibits on how to control eye muscles, one young
man positioned himself in front of a large round mirror to learn to
raise one eyebrow. He got nowhere at first, but he was determined
to practice until he succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create a more vivid facial expression, I want to
make it funnier, so it's an enjoyable face,'' said Tsuyoshi Nakano,
32, a computer software programmer.
</P>
<P>
   Countless Japanese expressions reflect the era when any kind of
exaggerated movement of the face was considered unseemly and the
ideal was a mask-like face, from ``The face cannot be seen'' to one
that pretty much declares that smiling or any lively expression a
no-no: ``Man moves only half a cheek in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nakano balked at the suggestion that Japanese have little or
no facial expression. ``We do have our own, it's just that our
movements are tiny and small, so foreigners don't see it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The best illustration of the subtlety _ not to say immobility _
of Japanese facial expressions is the stylized tradition of Noh
theater, which features actors wearing painted masks. Changes in
emotion are conveyed by the slightest movements of the head.
Tilting the face forward conveys sadness; tilting it slightly
upward signals a more desperate anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologist Yakinari Kohara said there are physical reasons
for the slight facial expressions of the Japanese. Kohara, who has
studied the faces of Americans, Japanese, and the Ainu, Japan's
indigenous population, found that the Japanese find it very hard to
wink. That in turn means less eye motion, and eye mobility is what
gives the face its greatest expression, says Kohara.
</P>
<P>
   While there are both physical and cultural reasons for the
Japanese penchant for impassive faces, Kohara said that over the
years, Japanese have developed a more expressive facial repertoire.
Kohara, a 70-year-old with a wide grin and crinkly cheeks, said he
is very happy about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to feel tight inside because I couldn't show my
emotions. But now it's OK, and I feel as if I've been released
somehow,'' he said laughing, his mouth open wide enough to show his
fillings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
