<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BO     12-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM GEAR ISN'T FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retailers have served up plenty of cheesy holiday platters in
our time. But this year's promotion of splashy millennium
memorabilia is off the charts. Talk about white elephants.
</P>
<P>
   There are baseball caps adorned with working electronic
countdowns to 2000. ``Tiny Bubbles'' necklaces have pendants shaped
like champagne bottles ``corked'' with a gadget through which the
wearer can blow bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the high heels, multicolored sweaters, formal
evening tops, T-shirts, neckties, socks, and handbags embellished
loudly with millennium motifs, sequins, beads, and phrases like
``Celebrate 2000,'' ``I'm OK, Y2K,'' and ``Happy Millennium.'' And
this is all just at Lord &AMP; Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart has 01-01-00 hats in bucket, ski, and baseball styles, as
well as mittens with a 10-9-8 countdown on the fingertips. Filene's
has polyester and cotton shirts and vests embellished with, among
other things, sequins, party hats, and the number 2000. Bailey
Banks &AMP; Biddle has a ``millennium ring'' _ a solitaire with
``2000'' inscribed by laser within the diamond. Inside the band is
a ``2'' inscribed alongside three inlaid diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these items aren't cheap. Beaded evening tops at Lord &AMP;
Taylor are $59. Its slingback 2000 heels are $99. The Bailey Banks
&AMP; Biddle ring is $1,995 for 1/2 carat, $4,995 for 1 carat.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean they aren't selling. Says Lavelle Olexa,
senior vice president of fashion merchandising at Lord &AMP; Taylor,
``We really felt there would be a lot of interest in . . .
memorabilia going into the new millennium. That has proven to be
correct.'' The multicolored sweaters and beaded evening tops have
been ``good sellers,'' she says. A spokeswoman for Bailey Banks &AMP;
Biddle says it expects to sell out its stock of 2,000 millennium
rings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest question for shoppers is: What does one do
with the mementos after January 1? Sure, some of the goods could be
collector's items. Some can be worn throughout 2000. But in
reality, the countdown hats, sparkly sweaters, and embroidered
handbags are most likely destined for the back of the closet. Look
out, Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural to wonder just what people will wear in the
future. In ``Millennium Mode,'' authors Roberta Wolf and Trudy
Schlachter surveyed 40 top designers from around the world _
including Donna Karan, Miuccia Prada, Issey Miyake, Domenico Dolce,
and Stefano Gabbana _ for their predictions. The results make the
book a worthy read.
</P>
<P>
   Is society ready for nakedness? New York designer Daryl Kerrigan
(Daryl K) thinks it's the ultimate fashion statement of the future,
based on the current physical fitness and health crazes. ``While
this concept is obviously not widely accepted right now,'' she
said, ``it's possible that society could embrace such an idea in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sprouse, of New York, said he would love to see clothes
that ``pour'' on. ``Just get in the shower and press the clothing
sprocket. You dip yourself in the clothes and they're hot-wired to
computers to keep you warm or cool, change colors, whatever.
Clothes that respond to you. Eventually, you probably won't need
designers. You'll just need the right cable company.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rennie, chief designer for Escada in Germany, thinks work
will be obsolete in the future, thanks to robots and computers. So,
as people dedicate their time to leisure, home, and travel,
comfortable fabrics will be key, he said. ``It's conceivable that
people will create their own fabrics and fashions over the
computer. This `computer couture' could make designers obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Todd Oldham isn't so hooked on technology. He
predicts that despite technological breakthroughs, computers won't
be the key to moving fashion forward _ humans will. ``You can
streamline machinery, but in the end, the sewing maching that was
invented in the 18th century is pretty much the same one we're
using today. . . . I use computers only in the print process. I
don't design with a computer. Hands have to do that. We're
designing for the human form. It's very instinctive where to place
a seam _ computers can do it, but it won't be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest companies on the planet are using computers to
design and you can see it in the clothes. In the end, I think
people will turn away from that. The success of design is making it
look like humans touched it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
