<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-CUISINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE TEXAS INMATES TO FEAST ON A MEAL FIT FOR A PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When inmates at the Trinity County Jail sit down for
their Christmas meal this year, the daily fare of frozen TV dinners
will give way to a gourmet meal fit for, well, a president.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Hurt, a 21-year-old recent transplant from Seattle and
the new chef at Baroque Restaurant in Houston _ which counts former
President Bush among its occasional visitors _ is whipping up a
holiday feast for jail inmates and staff during her off-work hours.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Day, her ``guests'' will dine on a tossed salad in red
pepper cups dressed with roasted garlic vinaigrette alongside
assorted fresh fruits with cranberry-infused whipped cream. The
entree will consist of ham in a rum-spiked orange and brown-sugar
glaze accompanied by roasted garlic mashed potatoes, green beans
almondine with bacon and red onions, and butter-top rolls. For
desserts, she is serving Bailey's Irish Cream cheesecake with
chunks of white and dark chocolate and a raspberry swirl, baked in
an Oreo cookie crust. Warm cinnamon-apple and cherry pies, served a
la mode, also will be on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tradition in our family to adopt people who don't
have families,'' Hurt said, explaining in part how she got involved
in cooking a holiday meal for the nearby Trinity County Jail, which
is about 90 miles north of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the second time Hurt has prepared such a feast for
the jail; she and her father also cooked a lavish dinner for
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that just felt right to do,'' she said. ``We
would have been cooking anyway, and it's just as easy to cook for a
large group as for one.''
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to any harried host or hostess this season who is
fretting over how to handle the increased cooking chores and party
fare.
</P>
<P>
   But Hurt, a graduate of the Western Culinary Institute in
Portland, Ore., who also has studied at Le Cordon Bleu in Paris,
Scuola di Artes Culinaria in Rome and the Culinary Institute of
America in Napa, Calif., began cooking family meals at age 11,
catered her mother's wedding reception for 85 at age 12 and began
catering meals and special occasion cakes and pastries at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   A former chef with the Doubletree Hotels in Portland and Seattle
and at two trendy Seattle-area restaurants, Hurt moved back to
Texas from Seattle earlier this year to get reacquainted with her
father, Chuck Hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents divorced when she was 7, and, after her dad was sent
to prison as a sex offender, Hurt lost all contact with him except
for one visit she made to the Texas Department of Criminal Justice
when she was 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom disapproved, and it was very hard for me to communicate
with him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, after seeing her mother struggle with the death
of her own parents from whom she had been estranged, Hurt decided
to move back to Texas to get to know her dad, who was paroled
several years ago and works as a paralegal for Huntsville-area
attorney Bill Habern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just realized how much I didn't know about him,'' she added.
``I haven't known my father in the past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father has become a surrogate father to a young man, Tim
Beaver, who is serving time in the Trinity County Jail. They met
while both were in prison and Chuck Hurt had become sort of a
counselor to Beaver. He continued that role after both were
paroled.
</P>
<P>
   And when Hurt and her father began talking about the bleak
Thanksgiving Beaver faced in jail and how they might brighten it,
they came up with the idea of taking him a meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about taking him a plate of food for Thanksgiving
dinner, but that didn't seem very festive or fair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she and her dad decided to cook for all the inmates and
staff at the jail. That is not as cumbersome a task as it might
seem at first, because the jail has only eight inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Brent Phillips said he welcomed the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a small jail, and we don't have much of a budget for
food,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Families of inmates often ask him if they can bring food on
holidays to their relatives behind bars. Because the jail is so
small, Phillips has a policy that if one person gets a special
meal, all the prisoners must get the same treat.
</P>
<P>
   With such a small jail population, Phillips said, morale would
suffer if one prisoner got a home-cooked meal and the others were
left with the frozen fare.
</P>
<P>
   At Thanksgiving, Hurt and her father also tried to promote the
idea of families and organizations volunteering similar holiday
meals in small jails around the state. Ray Hill, who does a Friday
night prison radio show from Houston, promoted the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Inmate Family Association took up the cause, but
executive director Linda Reeves said sheriffs in a number of other
counties rejected the offers from TIFA members to prepare meals.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt admits that putting together the Christmas meal will be a
little more hectic than it was cooking the Thanksgiving feast. She
had not started work at Baroque when she cooked the Thanksgiving
meal.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, she's overseeing the Christmas Eve dinner at
Baroque. Once through there, she will dart to the Huntsville area
where she and her dad will begin cooking. She'll finish up
Christmas morning and the father-daughter team will deliver the
meals to Groveton, where the jail is located, by noon.
</P>
<P>
   It's not everybody's idea of how to spend Christmas Eve and
Christmas Day, but Hurt shrugs it off with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to cook,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-NATO-ANTIAMERICANISM-     12-21 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANTIAMERICANISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EUROPEAN FORCE, US FEARS A LOSS OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Just days after the European Union pledged to create
its own rapid-reaction force so it would not have to rely always on
the American military, officials from Hanscom Air Force Base went
to an airbase in rural England.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts-based team was there for ceremonies last
Wednesday marking a key milestone in a project to upgrade the Royal
Air Force's fleet of AWACS aircraft, flying command posts packed
with advanced electronics for communication, battlefield
surveillance, and electronic warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The visit underscored the fact that in their quest to operate
more independently of the US military, the Europeans will need the
help of Americans to narrow the technological gap that became
glaringly obvious during the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It also showed the fine balance that the United States seeks to
strike as it urges its European allies to spend more on defense,
but not so much that they won't need the Americans at all anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The vaguely anti-American rhetoric that has come out of some
European capitals recently has US officials worried that the
American-dominated NATO alliance could be undermined by a more
robust and independent European military.
</P>
<P>
   But while talk is cheap, improving technology and military
capability is not. And that is the main reason that US military
figures seem less troubled than American diplomats by the European
Union's formal decision to create a 60,000-member rapid reaction
force by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, military officials and analysts suggested that
European governments are neither politically nor culturally
prepared to make the cuts in social welfare programs that would be
needed to pay for a military infrastructure capable of making NATO
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those same officials and analysts say it would be wrong to
dismiss the genuine desire of Europeans to assume more
responsibility for military decisions, and the resentment over what
some say is the propensity of the Americans to dictate to them.
</P>
<P>
   The British government, which with France has led the push for
asserting Europe's military independence, spent $100 million to
upgrade its seven AWACS, or Airborne Warning and Control System,
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   US Air Force Colonel Brad Butler heads the AWACS program at the
Electronic Systems Center at Hanscom that oversaw the British
upgrade, and he sees Britain's investment as underpinning rather
than undermining the future of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this strengthens the alliance, not sets the tone for
division,'' Butler said in an interview here. As he explained it,
upgrading the radar systems on the AWACS aircraft makes it easier
for the allies to exchange information quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This increases the capability to be interoperable, and to
deploy and be ready to fight together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans have made it clear that they want to be able to
deploy soldiers to hot spots like Kosovo without relying on
American forces, and especially on the US Congress, which they see
as increasingly isolationist. The Europeans believe that a
homegrown rapid reaction force could intervene in conflicts such as
Bosnia and Kosovo before they escalate to full-scale wars.
</P>
<P>
   As the European communique issued in Helsinki Dec. 11 put it,
the 15-nation European Union pledged to ``develop an autonomous
capacity to take decisions and, where NATO as a whole is not
engaged, to launch and conduct EU-led military operations in
response to military crises.'' The goal is 60,000-member force that
is able to deploy within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Strobe Talbott, the US deputy secretary of state, met with NATO
foreign ministers in Brussels last week, and said the United States
welcomed the European decision. But Talbott said the new force
should not supplant NATO and must take into account the security
concerns of NATO members who are not in the EU _ the United States,
Canada, Norway, Iceland, and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting in Brussels underscored the differences between
the Americans and their European allies. Talbott briefed the allies
on a proposed anti-missile defense system for the United States, an
updated version of the ``Star Wars'' project of the 1980s that
never took off. Many of the European allies are opposed to the
so-called missile shield, saying it violates an arms control treaty
with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO is a 19-nation alliance, by law its military
operation must be headed by an American general, and American
superiority in air power and technology gives the United States
disproportionate influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it both ways,'' admitted a senior US diplomat posted
in a European capital, speaking on condition of anonymity. He meant
the United States wants Europeans to increase their defense
spending, but not in a way that would undermine NATO. Right now,
the United States spends 3.2 percent of its gross domestic product
on defense, while the French spend 2.8 percent and the British 2.6
percent. Germany, which has Europe's biggest army, spends only 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Eichenberg, a professor of political science at Tufts
University who has studied the issue, says public support for a
single defense policy that would make Europeans less dependent on
NATO has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear, however, is whether Europeans are willing to pay
for a defense structure that would make NATO irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public support for that is still low, but it has been growing
in recent years,'' said Eichenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Gilles Andreani, a French military analyst and senior fellow at
the London-based International Institute of Strategic Studies, said
the State Department is more worried about the European plans than
the Pentagon. Pentagon officials, he said, see the force for what
it is _ a relatively small operation of 60,000 troops taken from a
pool of 2 million European soldiers. Pentagon officials also
remember that without French and German cooperation, the US would
not have been able to deploy nuclear missiles in Germany in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with longer-term vision are pretty relaxed over what
the Europeans are doing,'' he said. ``The guardians of the temple
are from the State Department, and they have exaggerated suspicions
of the French.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials, notably President Jacques Chirac and Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine, have complained openly that the post-Cold
War United States has gone from superpower to hyperpower.
Unchallenged on the world stage, the Americans too often dictate
rather than treat their allies as partners, they say.
</P>
<P>
   While the French have long wanted to rely less on the Americans,
it was not until last year, when British Prime Minister Tony Blair
joined Chirac at a British-French summit at St. Malo, that Paris
had the ally it needed to push the European Union to create its own
intervention force. Blair, Washington's most steadfast ally, has
repeatedly reassured the United States that the NATO alliance will
not be undermined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French are more explicit about the need for autonomy and a
more balanced dialogue,'' said Andreani, the analyst. ``The British
are more explicit about this not being pursued in a manner that
affects NATO integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   There are different motivations at work, Andreani says. The
French and the Germans, who have already established a small
bilingual force, see it as a way to strengthen European
integration. The British, always the most skeptical about such
integration, ``see this as a way they can lead in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But in their statements at Helsinki, the various European
leaders said they needed to be able to act when NATO cannot or will
not.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, whose research center at Hanscom has produced some of
the technology that gives the US military its huge edge over its
allies, was stationed in Europe during the 1980s and calls talk
about weakening of the American-European alliance exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo showed that we and the Europeans have shared values as
much as shared interests,'' he said. ``The cooperation we had with
our European allies on this AWACS project was typical. We don't
have the market cornered on the best ideas. I come away from this
more encouraged about the alliance, not more worried about its
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
