   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ For decades, political pundits have
promoted campaign debates as the best way to inform voters about
the virtues and failings of presidential candidates. But when Al
Gore proposed two debates a week with his rival, Bill Bradley, in
return for abandoning all primary TV advertising, Gore was
ridiculed and Bradley was praised for refusing to go along. The
secret is now out. Campaign debates are boring. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
