<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MILOSEVIC-BOS &LR;      12-21 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MILOSEVIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHATTERED MAN OR MALEVOLENT RULER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MILOSEVIC 
Portrait of a Tyrant 
By Dusko Doder and Louise Branson 
Free Press, 284 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At last! A biography that skips the saint-or-sinner debate.
</P>
<P>
   As Dusko Doder and Louise Branson abundantly document, Slobodan
Milosevic, almost from the start, epitomized the Balkan-variety bad
seed. The child of parents who both committed suicide, Milosevic
aligned himself with a woman who hungered for power to avenge the
ignominious death of her mother. Milosevic betrayed a college
classmate, a mentor of two decades, and his next-door neighbor in
lunging to the top of Yugoslavia's diseased post-Tito political
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Milosevic: Portrait of a Tyrant'' traces how he encouraged
_ and later sacrificed _ thugs and political aspirants, urging them
to remain king of Belgrade's hill even as he led his nation down a
path of political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Branson, Washington correspondent for The Scotsman, and Doder, a
native Montenegrin and a longtime journalist (he has covered the
Balkans for The Boston Globe and The Washington Post), deftly
explore two perplexing questions that have surrounded Milosevic: Is
he the root of all recent Balkan evil, as Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright and other US policymakers contended before
this year's costly NATO campaign to wrest Kosovo from his clutches?
And how could such a man remain in power for so long?
</P>
<P>
   It is a mistake, the authors argue, to view Milosevic as
omnipotent and (despite his background) premeditatedly malevolent.
His signal speech a decade ago in Kosovo, in which he promised
ethnic Serbs that they would never again be victimized by the
Albanians who were an ethnic majority in the southern province,
came on the cuff, only after jeers greeted his standard
conciliatory government message. After the rapturous welcome given
that speech, Milosevic, according to Doder and Branson, became
addicted to exploiting ethnic divisions to rise to power.
</P>
<P>
   But he also recoiled at the worst excesses of Bosnian Serb
atrocities in Bosnia, he was eager to portray himself as
indispensable to peace to Western negotiators such as Richard
Holbrooke, and he sold out 200,000 ethnic Serbs in the Krajina
region of Croatia rather than prolong a confrontation there (and
buttress Serb rivals).
</P>
<P>
   Despite Albright's contentions, the authors argue, he is no dark
Machiavelli or Clausewitz. ``There was no hard center to his rule;
no strategy,'' the authors write, their use of the past tense
reflective of their view of the tenuousness of his rule today. ``He
lived from day to day. The only discernible pattern was perpetual
mayhem. . . . He promoted conflicts _ in Slovenia, in Croatia, in
Bosnia, in Serbia itself _ to enlarge his power and to keep his own
people distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation by Albright and other US policymakers to use
overwhelming force against him in Kosovo was based on a tragic
misreading of the man, the authors argue. Although Milosevic backed
down in Bosnia, he did so as much to undercut increasingly
independent Bosnian Serb rivals as to respond to the West's
stiffening spine. Kosovo, where he first made his mark, would have
to be taken from him, at whatever cost to his shrinking nation.
</P>
<P>
   The biography's most painful moments arise as the authors
chronicle the series of missed opportunities, by Washington and by
internal opponents, to truncate Milosevic's rule. Twisting state
media with the skill of a Nazi propagandist, Milosevic, whose only
clear-cut electoral victory came in 1990, silenced his critics. He
fixed elections, or disregarded them if he lost. He unleashed his
police, secret agents, and terrorist freelancers against meddlesome
opponents such as nationalist Vuk Draskovic, beaten so severely in
1993 that his mental faculties since have come into question.
</P>
<P>
   Doder and Branson assert that inflexible US diplomats
short-circuited a true internal challenger, the Serb-American Milan
Panic, whose platform in 1992 elections became the removal of
Milosevic. Advised by a former US ambassador to Yugoslavia, Jack
Scanlan, Panic could not coax a commitment from the outgoing Bush
administration that economic sanctions would end if he ousted
Milosevic. While he was wildly popular, Panic's lack of US
influence kept Milosevic's lieutenants from defecting, and it left
the propaganda and electoral mechanisms in Milosevic's hands.
Today, with beatings and arrests of Serbian opponents to Milosevic
on the rise again, Washington yearns for a counterweight as strong
as Panic was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   As this biography makes clear, many Belgrade residents gave up
on Milosevic long before the NATO warplanes rained down bombs on
them last spring. In 1997, derisive crowds besieged Milosevic in
1997 as he and his megalomaniac wifepassed through Belgrade in the
Mercedes 600 of the former Yugoslav leader, Josip Broz Tito. ``The
partners in power were in for a shock,'' Doder and Branson write.
``The crowds pelted their limousine with old shoes, a message that
the couple were not fit for the shoes of the old dictator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
