<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MILLENNIUM _ JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government's
religious ministry has asked that hotels keep Christmas trees
behind closed doors to avoid offending the locals. The government
started preparations for the expected crowds years late. A look
around Jerusalem finds no signs or decorations about the event to
come. After all, in the Jewish calendar it's not 2000, it's 5760,
and the Jewish state is a reluctant host to the Christian
milestone. In fact, the Palestinians nextdoor may steal the
millennial show. A few Israelis have been openly anxious about the
influx of the Christian masses. Most are indifferent, but their
knowledge of Christianity is limited. A Gallup Poll released
Tuesday shows that most Israelis do not know the date of Christmas.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   XMAS-TRAVEL _ With Christmas only a few days away, travellers
are already packing traines, planes and automobiles to get away.
AAA association, already logging reports of heavier-than-usual
traffic on I-75 and I-95 along Ga and Florida, is predicting lots
of vehicles on road in the Southeastern U.S. as people make their
holiday get-aways. Greyhound bus officials also bracing for more
passengers. We account for this and try to talk to a few people who
are on the move at Hartsfield and Amtrak station. (Charles, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
