<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5369 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BIOWARFARE-SCIENTISTS     12-21 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOWARFARE-SCIENTISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOLOGICAL WEAPONS EXPERTS LEARN TO PUT SKILLS TO PEACEFUL USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. _ Just a few years ago, Dr. Vladimir Bugreyev
was making deadly biological weapons in the secretive ``closed
city'' of Stepnogorsk in the Kazakhstan region of the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   His potential target: The United States and other military foes
of the U.S.S.R.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bugreyev is working with American scientists at the U.S.
Department of Energy's Pacific Northwest National Laboratory in
Richland, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In October, he and three other colleagues _ from among the
60,000 or more former biowarfare scientists from the Soviet
``Biopreparat'' _ concluded weeks of work at PNNL learning to put
their skills to peaceful and commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an assistance program of sorts for their scientists and
engineers,'' said Dr. Richard Weller, the lead scientific liaison
between the researchers and the Richland laboratory, now operated
for the government by the private firm Battelle.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the retraining effort is the fear that scientists who
once worked for the now dismantled Soviet biowarfare program will
market their talents to rogue nations or terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Recent revelations of how extensive the Soviet Union's
biowarfare research program was _ including reports of deaths
caused by the accidental release of anthrax at Sverdlovsk in 1979 _
have prompted an urgent international effort to reduce the threat
and learn how to defend against an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Young, former commissioner of the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration and now director of the National Disaster Medical
System, said last month at a scientific forum that a biological
warfare attack on the United States is almost inevitable. Young
warned that the country is not prepared to rapidly identify such an
attack, much less defend against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat is very large and it's true we're not ready for
it,'' said Dr. Tam Garland, a veterinary scientist at Texas A&AMP;M
University and an expert on animal-based biowarfare agents such as
anthrax and plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biologicals are the most worrisome weapons of mass destruction
because they are so easy to acquire and transport,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With the breakup of the Soviet Union, American and former Soviet
officials recently decided to work together to minimize the chances
that weapon-making skills might fall into the wrong hands, said
Patricia Godoy-Kain, manager of PNNL's international biological
weapons non-proliferation program.
</P>
<P>
   The Tri-Cities, home of the Department of Energy's Hanford
Nuclear Reservation, has spent decades learning how to shift away
from a government-run weapons program to a more diversified and
commercialized economy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Russian officials first focused their efforts on
preventing the spread of nuclear weapons technology. Attention soon
turned to biological and chemical weapons as well, and PNNL was
selected to lead the effort aimed at preventing the proliferation
of bioweapons because of the Richland lab's established expertise
in molecular biology.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, groups of former Soviet biowarfare researchers have
been coming to the Richland lab. Bugreyev, his wife and scientific
partner, Dr. Nadezhda Bugreyeva, Dr. Ekaterina Nikitina and Dr.
Vladimir Berezin were the most recent visitors to the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Another group is scheduled to arrive in February.
</P>
<P>
   Most are from Stepnogorsk or other cities in the newly
independent state of Kazakhstan, where the Soviet Union had
concentrated much of its work on anthrax and plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepnogorsk demonstrated our ability to wage biological
warfare on a scale matched by no other nation in history,'' Ken
Alibek, a former deputy chief of Biopreparat, revealed in his book
``Biohazard,'' published earlier this year. ``Needless to say, we
didn't advertise our accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the Cold War, however, American officials soon
learned of the massive Soviet scientific system that had been
dedicated to biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first level of engagement is scientist to scientist,''
said PNNL's Weller, who recently visited the Kazakhstani scientists
back home to help them in their shift toward developing biomedical
research projects.
</P>
<P>
   Weller said the goal is to help them identify practical and
commercial applications for the work previously dedicated to
weapons development. It's not as much of a stretch as you might
think, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the basic molecular biology and the lab techniques are
the same,'' Weller said.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage that many former Soviet scientists have over their
American colleagues, he said, is that most U.S. researchers are
heavily dependent on high-tech equipment and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in the former Soviet Union, Weller said, had less to
work with and were forced to become more creative.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dr. Evguenia Rainina is a biochemist from Moscow
who came to PNNL a year ago and stayed. Rainina now sometimes
serves as a liaison between the Richland scientists and her former
Soviet colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, she had developed a system for rapid detection of
bacterial toxins and other pathogens _ something of critical
importance if attacked by a biological weapon.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, Rainina didn't engineer any genes or develop some
high-tech instrument.
</P>
<P>
   She used fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son and his friends grew up catching fireflies,'' Rainina
said, noting that her research project back then even had a tilt
toward capitalism. ``We paid the kids for each firefly they
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   What she got from the fireflies was an enzyme responsible for
the bugs' luminescence known as luciferase. Rainina found that the
enzyme luciferase could be visibly triggered by very small amounts
of a common metabolic chemical _ ATP, adenosine triphosphate _
found in all living cells.
</P>
<P>
   Further research allowed her to discriminate between types of
living cells, which allowed identification of different microbes.
The presence of even a minute amount of an organism's ATP can
produce a visual flash of light. All this is valuable if troops are
exposed to an unknown bioweapon.
</P>
<P>
   But Rainina's work with the firefly enzyme may also be valuable
for medical diagnoses and detection of bacterial contaminants in
food.
</P>
<P>
   Through her work with researchers at PNNL, where the project
also pairs up the foreign scientists with commercial firms, Rainina
is now working with a medical equipment manufacturer in Maryland to
develop a highly sensitive pathogen detector that may be used first
for food safety inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Weller said the company, New Horizons Diagnostics, plans to
develop an inexpensive ``illuminator'' detection device that simply
alerts the user to the presence of a bacterial contaminant. Further
research, he said, is aimed at creating detectors that can
distinguish types of organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects with the Kazakhstani scientists include work on
an experimental hepatitis C vaccine based on a natural
immunity-stimulating compound refined by Berezin and an antifungal
medication based on a unique strain of strep bacteria Nikitina
isolated from soil.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these health-oriented projects are based on accidental
discoveries that can trace their roots back to research looking for
new bioweapons or for antidotes to these weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the exchange of information also benefits the United States,
Weller said, by bringing us new commercial opportunities and novel
scientific approaches to problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a win-win situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M's Garland, who also helps operate an Internet-based
independent database called ProMED that reports on disease
outbreaks worldwide, said another likely but unstated benefit of
the PNNL program is to gather defensive information about the
former Soviet biowarfare program.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, she said, should be for the U.S. scientific,
medical and public health communities to come together with a
well-defined response plan in the event of an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Limited attempts at bioterrorism may have already taken place
that have gone unrecognized, she said. The recent outbreak of West
Nile encephalitis in New York City that sickened at least 50 people
and killed seven, she said, fits the profile of such an attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it was (an act of bioterrorism) but it's an
extremely odd virus that's not been seen in the U.S. before,''
Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York illnesses were initially misdiagnosed by medical
doctors as St. Louis encephalitis and attributed to a common virus.
The rare virus was discovered and eventually linked to the human
outbreak by a Wildlife Conservation Society veterinary pathologist,
Tracey McNamara, who had been examining dying birds at the Bronx
Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Garland said that episode, whether it was an act of bioterrorism
or not, demonstrates the need for a better system to recognize and
respond to biological weapons. The PNNL program is a good step in
that direction, she said, but it's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to biological weapons it's not a question of if,
but when,'' Garland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
