A5371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-BROADDRICK22-     12-21 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BROADDRICK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON RAPE ACCUSER SEEKS RECORDS FROM ADMINISTRATION
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The woman who alleges that President Clinton raped
her more than 21 years ago is suing the White House and Justice
Department to obtain any records held by the Clinton administration
about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to know if there's a file there,'' Juanita
Broaddrick said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas nursing home executive made accusations against
Clinton that were made public early this year by The Wall Street
Journal and NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   Broaddrick said in a brief interview Tuesday that the White
House rejected a request she made in October for files kept about
her.
</P>
<P>
   She has hired Larry Klayman, the head of Judicial Watch, an
attorney who has filed numerous suits against the Clinton
administration. The court papers cite rights under the Privacy Act
in seeking to have the White House turn over records.
</P>
<P>
   In an Oct. 27 letter responding to the request, the White House
legal office said the Privacy Act did not apply to the president's
personal staff.
</P>
<P>
   Broaddrick said that she had hoped the lawsuit would not
generate publicity. However, a CNN television news team was at the
federal district courthouse here for the filing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the rape allegation was first aired last February, Clinton
issued a denial through his lawyer, but he has not personally
responded. Since then, Broaddrick has returned to her private life
in rural Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy resurfaced last week when a woman at a New
Hampshire forum asked Vice President Al Gore if he believed
Broaddrick's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had not seen the televised interview, but said, ``I
guess I'm like a lot of people in that I think that enough is
enough. I do not know how to evaluate each one of these individual
stories. I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
