<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-MOON-SPI &LR;      12-21 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MOON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAUFMAN STORY ENTERTAINING YET EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-time Oscar-winning director Milos Forman accomplished a
minor miracle three years ago with ``The People vs. Larry Flynt,''
a film biography of a somewhat despicable pornographer that managed
to be an authentically moving tribute to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In its follow-up, ``Man On the Moon,'' Forman tries to do
something like the same trick with a biopic about another offbeat,
highly outrageous and, in many ways, prototypically '70s character:
TV comedian Andy Kaufman (``Taxi,'' ``Saturday Night Live!'').
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, it's often hilarious, and it also offers a
reasonably strong, A-level star vehicle for Jim Carrey. But it
offers no special insights into its subject, it doesn't connect on
any higher level, and it left me feeling vaguely dissatisfied and
let down.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a script by Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski (who
also wrote ``Larry Flynt''), it opens with a clever title sequence
in which Kaufman (Carrey) addresses the audience, then dramatizes a
random moment from his affluent Long Island childhood before
zipping to his first days as a struggling L.A. stand-up comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Though he seems a spectacularly inept comic, an important agent
(Kaufman's ``Taxi'' co-star, Danny DeVito, who also co-produced)
quickly notices something original and brilliant in his strange
impersonations and sketches, which have no obvious punchlines and
are often esoterically obscure or blatantly sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, he's a semi-regular on ``SNL'' and a crazy mechanic
on ``Taxi,'' where his bizarre humor is finally fully appreciated
and fawning network executives are catering to his every whim.
(DeVito has reunited the cast of ``Taxi'' for these scenes, and
it's a mistake, because they're all rather glaringly 20 years older
than we remember.)
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie deals with his growing contempt for and
rebellion against his success, his inexplicable obsession with
wrestling, his love affair with one of his ring opponents (Courtney
Love, in a fairly nondescript role), and his brief battle with the
lung cancer that will quickly take his life.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly for Forman, it's kind of an MTV-style movie _ all
high points, omitting scenes that might ``explain'' Kaufman's
unique, self-destructive drive. The film views his life as a series
of outrageous stunts and hoaxes in which the comedian and his
faithful companion and writing partner, Bob Zmuda (Paul Giamatti),
are ultimately shown to be putting on everyone around them.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain refreshing honesty in this _ an acceptance
that all human beings are basically unknowable (``There is no
you,'' the Courtney Love character tells him at one point) _ but
it's also frustrating and negates Kaufman's importance as a
cultural figure. The only conclusion we can draw from the movie is
that Kaufman was a complete nut-case.
</P>
<P>
   Since Forman and the writers clearly don't know what to make of
Kaufman, Carrey's impersonation is not really a performance. But it
still holds the movie together nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey has a seductive screen presence; he is always both
surprising and entertaining (more entertaining, for sure, than the
real Andy Kaufman), and it's basically the kind of eye-bulging,
face-twisting, mug-fest role at which he has no equal.
</P>
<P>
   Man on the Moon. Directed by Milos Forman. Written by Scott
Alexander and Larry Karaszewski. Cast: Jim Carrey, Danny DeVito,
Courtney Love, Paul Giamatti. Universal. 118 minutes. Rated R for
language, sex scenes and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
