 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; WEDNESDAY &LR; , Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on Carl
Lewis and Jesse Owens and both men's place in the athletic history
o0th century. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GAMEPLAN (Undated) _ To follow a NFL coach from Monday to
Sunday is to witness a numbing succession of meetings, statistical
analysis, critiquing of video tape along with lengthy after-dinner
skull sessions when the scheming of plays and defenses are debated
and ultimately agreed upon. It's an exercise removed from anything
athletic, a chess match of anticipated moves on a gridiron with
300-pound game pieces. The art of deception is the skill prized
above all others as opponents' tendencies are examined and their
weaknesses weighed. The goal is to play your game with your players
but to look completely different doing it. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-RAPTORS (Toronto) _ The N.J. Nets at Toronto, 7 p.m.
EST start.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
