<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5382 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-MOTHER-SPI &LR;      12-21 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MOTHER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMODOVAR'S `MOTHER' COMBINES DARKNESS AND COMPASSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spanish director Pedro Almodovar has run the gamut from good to
ugly in his wildly flamboyant films.
</P>
<P>
   From the misanthropic ``Kika,'' to the histrionics of ``The
Flower of My Secret,'' to the crazy vibrance of ``Woman on the
Verge of a Nervous Breakdown,'' ``Tie Me Up, Tie Me Down'' and
``Dark Habits,'' Almodovar has traipsed all over the emotional map.
</P>
<P>
   So it's lovely to note that ``All About My Mother'' is as dark
as a Greek tragedy yet it has a vibrance and joie de vivre that
can't be contained by grief.
</P>
<P>
   The film pays loving tribute to actresses and that genre of
movies familiarly called ``women's films'' and Almodovar has merged
three _ Bette Davis in ``All About Eve,'' Gena Rowlands in
``Opening Night'' and Romy Schneider in ``L'important c'est
d'aimer'' _ into a buoyant homage to the female sex, ``women who
act'' and ``actresses who have played actresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuela (Cecilia Roth) is a nurse and single mother who is
raising her son, Esteban (Elor Azorin), a bright, curious teenager
who wants to be a writer. On his 17th birthday, his mother
surprises him with tickets to a stage production of ``A Streetcar
Named Desire'' starring the great actress Huma Rojo (Marisa
Parides) as Blanche Dubois.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban has asked his mother for only two things on this special
day: to finally tell him about his father and to wait with him by
the stage door in the pouring rain so he may ask Rojo for her
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   But tragedy strikes and the boy is killed in a freak car
accident. Consumed by grief, Manuela returns to Barcelona to find
Esteban's father, who has never known his son, and tell him of the
death.
</P>
<P>
   Manuela's journey becomes remarkable when three extraordinary
women enter her life; Rojo, pregnant nun Sister Rosa (Penelope
Cruz) and the transvestite Agrado (Antonia San Juan), who is
Manuela's old friend and the keeper of the secret of Esteban's
father and his true identity.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar has painted this story of gender, loss and the slow
process of healing with his signature palette of color, camp and
chaos. But ``All About My Mother'' brims with a compassion that
gives the story great dignity despite its wild array of characters.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, who worked previously with Almodovar on ``What Have I Done
To Deserve This?'' and ``Dark Habits,'' is wonderfully thrilling
and chilling in her grief as the primally wounded Manuela. Her face
carries both the pain and the capacity for reason and forgiveness
though her heart is broken. San Juan creates a character who
lovingly bounces off life's sadness with a survivor's humor and the
humanity of a woman who has reinvented herself (literally).
</P>
<P>
   The result is a dizzying, marvelously acted rush of a movie that
may, after more than 20 films, finally give Almodovar a wider
crossover appeal. He's already won the best director prize at this
year's Cannes Film Festival and ``All About My Mother'' swept the
best foreign film of the year awards from the National Board of
Review and the New York, Los Angeles and Boston film critics
groups.
</P>
<P>
   All About My Mother. Directed and written by Pedro Almodovar.
Cast: Cecelia Roth, Marisa Paredes, Penelope Cruz, Antonia San
Juan. Sony Pictures Classics. 101 minutes. Rated R for sexual
themes. In Spanish with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
