<HEADLINE>
ALLEN'S `SWEET AND LOWDOWN' WINDS UP DOWN AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all these years and all his troubles, it still can be fun
to see the annual Woody Allen movie. It's usually a letdown, but it
always contains some good stuff and invariably involves an element
of surprise: You never quite know what you're going to get.
</P>
<P>
   In this 1999 edition, ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' Allen exercises his
well-known fascination for ethnomusicology with a lighthearted,
semicomedic exploration of the life and legend of a fictitious jazz
guitarist of the '30s named Emmett Ray (Sean Penn).
</P>
<P>
   The thing about Ray is that he's a thoroughly despicable human
being. The opening scenes establish him as a pimp, a thief, a
coward and a self-obsessed, gun-toting braggadocio whose idea of a
good time is a midnight excursion to shoot rats at the city dump.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also a sublime musician, second at his instrument only
to the great French Gypsy guitarist, Django Reinhardt, whose
mystical superiority so haunts the insecure Ray that the movie's
running gag is that he can't stop talking about the man.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's script roughly takes the form of a documentary, with the
dramatic scenes introduced by a series of Ray experts, including
Allen, his former writing partner Douglas McGrath, and a succession
of fatuously tongue-in-cheek jazz authorities, including critic Nat
Hentoff.
</P>
<P>
   It largely traces Ray's life in terms of his two most important
relationships: his affair with a ``half-witted'' mute woman
(Samantha Morton) who appreciates his music and accepts him for
what he is, and the shallow society dilettante (Uma Thurman) he
marries.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Allen movies of the '90s, ``Sweet and Lowdown'' never
tries to be a laugh riot, and aims more at maintaining a consistent
level of irony and whimsy. It's entertaining, but somewhat trivial
and underwhelming, and you do finally get tired of it before it's
over.
</P>
<P>
   The film is, however, a real showcase for Penn, who seems to
positively delight in playing a slimy, hateful character that most
stars would not go near. Never has it seemed clearer that this
endlessly rebellious actor intends to be the Robert Mitchum of his
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet and Lowdown. Directed and written by Woody Allen. Cast:
Sean Penn, Samantha Morton, Uma Thurman, Anthony LaPaglia, Gretchen
Mol, John Waters. Sony Pictures Classics. 110 minutes. Rated PG-13
for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1454EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
