<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUNDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANY GIVEN SUNDAY' GIVES UP YARDAGE IN TIRED OLD TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a football movie carries the names of Oliver Stone and Al
Pacino in its credits, one might reasonably expect it to be an
imaginative examination of the prototypical American institution,
with possibly some of the devastating power and insight of ``Wall
Street'' or ``The Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   But the duo's near-three-hour gridiron extravaganza, ``Any Given
Sunday,'' is one more sports film about a talented hot-shot rookie
who learns to be a team player and appreciate the traditions of the
game _ a plot that was a groaning cliche even in the Silent Era.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino plays Tony D'Amato, the veteran head coach of the
fictional Miami Sharks, a troubled franchise with attendance
problems, a 38-year-old quarterback (Dennis Quaid) held together by
scar tissue, and, as the film opens, two humiliating losses in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   In a desperate moment, Tony has to use his third-string
quarterback (Jamie Foxx), and the kid comes through, and even shows
signs of being the miracle the team needs. The trouble is he won't
obey the game plan, he has no team spirit and he insists on doing
things his way.
</P>
<P>
   But he makes touchdowns, and the young team owner (Cameron Diaz)
insists that Tony use him. So the story goes on a collision course
_ Tony, his loyalty to the game and his aging quarterback pal on
one track; the arrogant upstart player and the money-grubbing owner
on the other.
</P>
<P>
   As always with Stone, the film has some gritty performances and
a certain likable audacity. Pacino commands the screen with his
usual slouchy magnificence, and Diaz holds her own as his
yuppie-scum nemesis. Several of the game sequences also are fairly
compelling, even if you know nothing about football.
</P>
<P>
   But far too much of the film is taken up with tiresome and
confusing scenes of unidentifiable men violently crashing into each
other, and Stone's nervous, hand-held visual style _ half a tribute
to the competition movies of Michael Ritchie (``Downhill Racer''),
half to ``The Blair Witch Project'' _ is mostly uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also is too darn long. Like nearly every other major
film of this holiday movie season, it's just shy of three hours _
which in this case means it has an extra hour of locker-room excess
and unnecessary and annoyingly repetitive battle scenes tagged onto
its very thin plot line.
</P>
<P>
   Any Given Sunday. Directed by Oliver Stone. Written by Stone and
John Logan. Cast: Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz, Dennis Quaid, James
Woods, Jamie Foxx, LL Cool J. Warner Bros. 170 minutes. Rated R for
language, violence and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1458EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
