<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A PAY RAISE FOR ALL BUT THE WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Ed Lucas was at the east end of the concourse
beneath the Empire State Plaza at lunchtime the other day, in a
gray suit and red tie, just like New York Gov. George Pataki wears
so often. Clearly, he was enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's a tall, rangy guy who looks vaguely like the governor _
although not so much that you really would mistake either of them
for the other. In stage makeup designed to age him _ Lucas is 15
years younger than the governor _ he was in character as Pataki. As
state workers hustled by, he stopped them and offered them their
Christmas bonuses _ lumps of coal in gift boxes. As state workers
got the idea, they played along.
</P>
<P>
   They would moan to the ``governor'' about how desperately they
want a contract, how much they need a few extra bucks, how wounded
they are that the governor got his 20-plus percent raise, along
with his commissioners, and that the state legislators gave
themselves a 38 percent bump fully a year ago, but the
rank-and-file workers still can't get anything out of the state of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   It was all street theater cooked up by the Public Employees
Federation (PEF), one of the state employee unions. Lucas is a PEF
divisional president responsible for 1,200 members. In real life,
for more than 20 years, he has been a civil engineer for the state
Department of Transportation. He was having a fine time yesterday
playing George Pataki and poking fun at the Republican governor.
But the unions won't be so good-natured Jan. 5, when they gather at
the Capitol as Pataki delivers his State of the State Message.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the state workers plan to have thousands of
protesters on hand, waving signs, chanting, doing whatever they can
think of within the limits of the law to dramatize their dismay
over stalled contract talks. You can probably expect a chorus line
of Pataki look-alikes, kicking up their heels like Jay Leno's
dancing Judge Lance Ito during the O.J. Simpson trial. Actually,
the possibilities for bad taste and rowdiness here are virtually
limitless.
</P>
<P>
   The state workers will be right on the merits of this, too.
They've been without a contract since April. They've gone four of
the last eight years with no raises and with only minor increases
in the years in which raises did come through. Meanwhile, as
salaries stagnated, they've been called upon to pay more on their
health insurance. In general, a state government with a surplus
totaling billions _ with Wall Street cash washing like a tidal wave
into state coffers _ is treating the people who make government
work day-to-day like dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas isn't a bad example. He lives in a modest house in an
older section of Niskayuna. He has two young kids. His specialty is
concrete. He evaluates the stability of concrete structures, does
work on bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing sexy; nothing exciting. It's merely the workaday
business of government that keeps buildings from falling in on
people and bridges from tumbling into rivers.
</P>
<P>
   For this work, we taxpayers pay Lucas $40,000 a year _ or, to
put it another way, we pay him not quite twice the size of the
raise the legislators gave themselves. In total, we pay him only
$10,000 a year more than the raise the governor got and signed into
law last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy my work,'' Lucas said. ``I save the taxpayers a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, if anybody in this state's political leadership
appreciates that, they sure have a funny way of showing it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, though, the outrage festival slated for Jan. 5 will get
their attention.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1502EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0111 </DOCNO>
