<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIBERTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVINSON REVISITS BALTIMORE IN `LIBERTY HEIGHTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his bittersweet 1990 family saga ``Avalon'' _ the third of
his autobiographical ``Baltimore'' movies _ director-writer Barry
Levinson traced the subtle disintegration of an extended, once
close-knit Jewish family in the post-World War II era. It was the
best of the three and a far cry from its more comedic predecessors
_ ``Diner'' (1982) and ``Tin Men'' (1987) _ but its melancholy
story and downbeat vision seemed to turn off audiences, and the
film died at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, for his fourth installment in the series,
``Liberty Heights,'' Levinson returns to the same '50s territory in
a much more positive frame of mind. The film is a valentine to the
roots of a big change-for-the-better that is about to consume '50s
America.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the titular Northwest Baltimore Jewish neighborhood in
1954, the film traces a year in the life of the Kurtzman family:
Nate (Joe Mantegna), his wife Ada (Bebe Neuwirth), and teenage sons
Van (Adrien Brody) and Ben (Ben Foster).
</P>
<P>
   The script weaves three parallel story lines:
</P>
<P>
   _The problems that arise when Nate, who owns a cheesy burlesque
house that's mostly a front for the numbers racket, is financially
busted by the big numbers win of a small-time black gangster.
</P>
<P>
   _The romance between Ben, Nate's sweet-spirited youngest son,
and Sylvia, the first black student in the Liberty Heights high
school after the courts officially desegregated the Baltimore
school system that year.
</P>
<P>
   _The impossible love affair between Van, Nate's oldest son, and
the beautiful-but-alcoholic and probably doomed blonde WASP
princess (Carolyn Murphy) he meets at an upper-crust Gentile
Halloween party.
</P>
<P>
   All three stories take place in a world that at first seems more
innocent and simple than ours, but is gradually revealed to be
wracked and compartmentalized by racial prejudice _ white for
black, black for white, Gentile for Jewish, Jewish for the whole
threatening world outside their immediate community.
</P>
<P>
   The subtext of the movie is that the changes about to engulf
this world _ the Civil Rights movement, rock music (the advent of
which we see in the form of a James Brown concert), and the great
counterculture of the '60s _ are going to shake it, and leave a
more diversified and better place in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   As always with Levinson, it's well done. The dialogue is funny
and the cast is flawless _ especially Mantegna, who creates a
semi-gangster character of genuine nobility. And it's as warm and
uplifting a portrait of a family that will somehow survive these
changes as ``Avalon'' was the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is marred by the broad strokes with which Levinson
paints his picture of mid-'50s prejudice. Were the characters
really so obsessed with race in 1954 that it's their only topic of
conversation? Did Baltimore's top country club really have a
gigantic sign at its entrance stating: ``No Jews, Dogs or
Coloreds''?
</P>
<P>
   It's also annoying that the film is a sloppy catalog of
anachronisms. Levinson has a major reference to the ``Perry Mason''
TV show that would not debut until 1957. Van refers to himself as a
``beatnik'' even though the term wasn't coined until 1958. And so
on.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the film is in so many ways, it also altogether rings
a bit false and contrived _ in the way that many highly
autobiographic works of cinema do, as their artists grow older and
wealthier and less emotionally connected to the lost eras that
inspired them to be artists.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Heights. Directed and written by Barry Levinson.
Produced by Levinson and Paula Weinstein. Cast: Joe Mantegna,
Adrien Brody, Bebe Neuwirth, Ben Foster, Rebekah Johnson. Warner
Bros. 122 minutes. Rated R for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1506EST &QL; 
