<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-NEURALGIA-RELIEF-HNS &LR;      12-21 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEURALGIA-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PHYSICIANS SAY PAINFUL NERVE DISORDER STILL NOT NDERSTOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ His pain is so intense, the Rev. Paul Tartaglia
can't chew, talk, brush his teeth or even touch his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me right above the eye,'' said the semiretired
Albany priest. ``It's like someone with a golf cleat smashing into
the eye area and then electrifying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians say those who suffer from attacks of trigeminal
neuralgia aren't exaggerating. This nerve disorder is so
excruciating that some people have been known to commit suicide
rather than endure it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst pain in the world,'' said Dr. Peter Jannetta, a
neurology professor at the University of Pittsburgh and a pioneer
of a controversial surgical treatment of the condition, known as
microvascular decompression.
</P>
<P>
   Tartaglia traveled last week to New York University Medical
Center to undergo the operation in hopes of stopping the pain that
has dogged him over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to such medical advancements, most people diagnosed with
trigeminal neuralgia can find some relief. Over the past three
decades, researchers have come up with new ways of treating this
condition, from oral medications to minimally invasive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Yet trigeminal neuralgia is still not widely understood, even
among some physicians. ``When I tell people I have this, they've
never ever heard of it,'' said Tartaglia, who works in the Chancery
office of the Albany Roman Catholic Diocese. ``I initially thought
it was an eye problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Others sometimes confuse the pain with a severe toothache
because of the location of the trigeminal nerve. It's not unusual
for neurologists to see patients with trigeminal neuralgia who have
had several teeth pulled before their condition was accurately
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is the largest of the nerves in the head, the
trigeminal nerve is responsible for much sensation in the face,
from chewing to blinking.
</P>
<P>
   Without the nerve, the face would feel numb, like after a trip
to the dentist. Imagine not being able to feel a light breeze, a
soft kiss or a wisp of hair on the face, and the important role of
the trigeminal nerve becomes easier to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nerve endings in the face are the most concentrated in the
body, even more than the fingertips,'' Jannetta said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one theory as to what causes the pain associated
with trigeminal neuralgia, and attacks can be caused by anything
from smiling to going outside on a windy day. Because people with
the condition live in fear of triggering it, some doctors have seen
patients who won't even talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have patients coming to my office smelling like a stinking
pig because they can't brush their teeth,'' said Dr. Ramesh Babu, a
neurosurgeon at New York University Medical Center. ``You have to
see it to believe how painful it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of specialists believe that the protective covering
of the nerve, known as the myelin sheath, deteriorates, either as a
result of another condition, such as aging, multiple sclerosis or
because of pressure from a nearby blood vessel or tumor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, regular nerve transmissions are interrupted, much
like static in a phone line. The sensation is pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible, terrible pain,'' said Isabelle Peete, 84, who
also suffers from trigeminal neuralgia. ``When you have those
pains, you can't open your mouth, you can't eat. It's like
electrical shocks,'' said Peete, who lives near Plattsburgh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Trigeminal neuralgia affects about one in every 25,000 people
and is slightly more common in women than men. This year alone, the
Trigeminal Neuralgia Association estimates that 15,000 new cases
will be diagnosed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In cases that can't be linked to multiple sclerosis or a tumor,
the first line of defense is medication such as Tegretol, an
anti-convulsant drug also commonly used to treat epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet such drugs may not work for everybody or they may lose their
effectiveness over time. Tartaglia didn't want to risk the
potential side effects, such as kidney and liver problems, because
of other underlying health problems.
</P>
<P>
   His search for relief brought him to the New York University
Medical Center recently, when he underwent a three-hour operation
to pull a tiny blood vessel away from his trigeminal nerve, a
procedure that's still a matter of dispute among some
neurosurgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's controversial, but it works,'' said Dr. Marc Schwartz,
one of two neurosurgeons who perform the delicate operation at the
Albany Medical Center. ``There are different ways of treating this,
the controversy is, who's data do you believe?''
</P>
<P>
   Jannetta, who pioneered microvascular decompression in the
1960s, said the procedure has become more widely accepted in recent
years as long-term data show it offers a more permanent solution
and involves fewer side effects than other techniques, including
cutting the nerve or injecting it with glycerol to damage the pain
receptors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, fewer than 10 percent of all neurosurgeons perform
microvascular decompression, in part because it can be difficult to
find the tiny blood vessel that's responsible. And, as with any
surgery in the head, there are risks, including meningitis or
hearing damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced this procedure is the best way to treat
trigeminal neuralgia,'' said Babu, the neurosurgeon at the New York
University Medical Center who operated on Tartaglia last week.
</P>
<P>
   The key, however, is finding a neurosurgeon with a lot of
practice at finding a blood vessel much smaller than a hair. Once
that blood vessel is identified, the surgeon inserts a tiny piece
of Teflon to buffer it from the nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest critics of this procedure are the ones who can't
locate a 50 micron blood vessel,'' Jannetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Tartaglia was hopeful the surgery will bring him the relief he's
been seeking. Although he's been suffering from trigeminal
neuralgia since the early 1990s, the attacks recently become more
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since a year ago October, there is no time I haven't known I
have this condition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after surgery and still in the hospital, Tartaglia
was optimistic. Although he still felt pain from the incision, he
didn't feel the trigeminal neuralgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely on Cloud Nine,'' he said. ``I have total
confidence at this stage. It's very encouraging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
