<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      12-21 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTY CURRY IN ONE POT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a relatively standard Indian dish of cauliflower and
potatoes whose flavors I have long loved. I even have a 30-year-old
Indian cookbook _ one that cost me all of 95 cents _ with a
dog-eared page to prove it. But over the years, I found myself
making the dish with just cauliflower because the potatoes seemed
too starchy, especially since the curry practically cries out for
white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, I substituted boneless chicken for the
potatoes, in roughly equal quantity. This turned the dish into a
one-pot meal even nonvegetarians could appreciate. The chewiness of
the chicken, as opposed to the mealiness of the potatoes, gave the
dish an added dimension.
</P>
<P>
   I made the flavor slightly more complex by adding a fair amount
of cumin seeds, which contribute not only taste, but also crunch.
And now I can serve this curry with flatbreads or over rice without
feeling as if I'm eating a crate of carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, this dish can be little more than onions,
cauliflower, curry powder and water. But there are many ways to
vary it. A tablespoon or even more of minced ginger added to the
onion as it cooks will enhance the flavor even further, as will a
teaspoon or two of minced garlic; a little cayenne or some chilies,
fresh or dried, are other options. I like to use chopped tomatoes
with their juice for liquid, but you can use a little stock
instead, or just rely on water.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarians will want to revert to something closer to the
original recipe, with potatoes instead of chicken. Use a waxy
variety, like new potatoes, peeled and cut into one-half-inch dice,
and cook along with the cauliflower until tender. And two cups of
cubed eggplant cooked with the cauliflower is a great addition,
whether you're using chicken or potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED CAULIFLOWER AND CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 2 tablespoons neutral oil, like canola or grape seed
</P>
<P>
   { cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 head cauliflower, about 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons curry powder, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 or 6 canned plum tomatoes, with juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless chicken, cut into {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Minced cilantro or parsley for garnish, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put the oil in a 12-inch skillet, and turn the heat to high;
add the onion, and cook, stirring occasionally, until it begins to
brown. While it's cooking, trim the cauliflower and cut the florets
into {-inch-thick pieces.
</P>
<P>
   2. When the onion has browned a little, add the cumin seed and
curry powder and cook about 30 seconds. Add the cauliflower, and
stir, still over high heat, for another minute. Cut up the
tomatoes, and add them to the pan along with their juice, \ cup
water and a generous sprinkling of salt and pepper. Cover, and turn
the heat to medium-low.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook 10 minutes, stirring once or twice. Add the chicken,
stir, cover the pan again and cook 6 to 8 minutes longer, or until
the chicken is cooked through. (If the sauce appears to be drying
up at any time, add a little more water.) Stir in the lemon juice,
taste and adjust seasoning. Garnish if you like, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
