<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUBBLES ON A BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(af) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fizzing sound you will no doubt hear on Dec. 31 will not be
the air going out of the Y2K balloon but millions of bottles of
sparkling wine being uncorked. For Champagne producers, that's the
kind of payday that comes along, oh, once every thousand years. For
consumers giving large parties, it's a substantial investment.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to pay for a Champagne ball, there are
alternatives beyond California sparkling wine, which now has both
critical acclaim and the prices that go with it. One possibility is
cava, the Spanish sparkling wine, which is relatively inexpensive
and eminently likable.
</P>
<P>
   Cava _ the word means cellar in Spanish _ is probably most
familiar to Americans as Freixenet Cordon Negro. But there's a
world beyond Freixenet's black bottles, and because the cava
industry is booming, other producers are getting easier to find.
</P>
<P>
   Good cava is produced using the traditional Champagne method,
but with different grapes. Instead of the red-and-white blend used
for Champagne _ pinot noir, pinot meunier and chardonnay _ cava has
historically been made of three white Spanish grapes: macabeo,
parellada and xarel-lo. Some of the better makers now add
chardonnay. Cavas are usually lighter bodied and less acidic than
Champagnes, and they lack their richness but can be fresh and
lively.
</P>
<P>
   Cavas are aged a minimum of nine months; reservas are aged
longer. The wine is in contact with yeast sediments as it ages, so
older cavas have a yeasty, toasty character typical of wines made
by the Champagne method. These six cavas are listed in order of
preference. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEGURA VIUDAS BRUT, RESERVA HEREDAD $17 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mildly toasty, very fine bubbles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAUME SERRA, CRISTALINO BRUT $9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Light-bodied with a lovely fruit aroma. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALLFORMOSA BRUT $9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yeasty aroma, tastes of apples and pears. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAUL CHENEAU, BRUT GRANDE RESERVE 1994 $15 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caramel aroma, fuller bodied than most. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HUGUET, BRUT NATURE GRAN RESERVA, 1995 $18 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fruity aroma, light-bodied and austere. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTEL DE VILARNAU, BRUT $14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yeasty aroma with a citrus flavor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices are those paid in various Manhattan wine shops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
