<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SICILY-SWEETS-2TAKES-     12-21 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICILY-SWEETS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA DOLCE VITA, SICILIAN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODICA, Italy _ Viewed from the cosmopolitan cities of the
north, like London and Paris, the southeastern corner of Sicily is
a remote part of Europe. But in a Mediterranean context, it lies at
the very heart of things. It stands sentinel between Iberia and the
Middle East, closer to Tunisia in North Africa than to Rome and
Naples in the boot of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Geography has shaped Sicily's history, and history has shaped
its traditions, including its eating habits _ most of all, the
sweets that Sicilians adore. It was a Sicilian, Francesco Procopio,
who in 1670 opened the first ice cream parlor in Paris (long since,
alas, converted into a mediocre restaurant). And here in the
southeast, in the fine old Baroque cities of Noto and Modica,
skilled confectioners practice the ancient arts brought to the
island by the Arab conquerors in the ninth century and by the
Spanish in the 15th.
</P>
<P>
   For a man with a sweet tooth, this is the promised land. For a
man on a diet, it's a nightmare, an unceasing series of sugary
temptations called peccatucci, or little sins.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish imported the prickly pear and saffron, among other
things, but their most important gift was chocolate, whose delights
they had learned from the Aztecs of Mexico. The Arabs, often
referred to by modern-day Sicilians as Saracens, taught the locals
how to mix snow from Mount Etna or elsewhere with flavored syrup.
They called the result ``sharbat'' or ``sciarbat''; it was the
granddaddy of today's gelato (ice cream), sorbetto (sherbet) and
granita (water ice). Most important, the Saracens planted the
ancestors of the almond and citrus trees that now blanket this area
and provide flavoring for cakes, candies and frozen sweets, and
they introduced sugar cane, a far more versatile sweetener than the
honey previously used.
</P>
<P>
   Today, every town and every season have their specialties, made
for the most part in pastry shops. A fig- and nut-filled ring
called a buccellato heralds Christmas in Palermo, but in Modica,
figs are combined with walnuts and almonds and enclosed in thin
pastry shells, which are bent into S shapes before baking. The
little cookies, called nucatoli, taste like fig newtons gone to
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Other holiday specialties are citrus based. Grated citron is
heated with honey and formed into hard, sausage-shape rolls, from
which bits are broken off to nibble as an aid to digestion after
the Christmas feast (an acquired taste, I'm afraid, from my point
of view). Peels from the uniquely perfumed local oranges are
candied with sugar. Orange peels are cooked for at least two or
three hours with honey to form balls called aranciati.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Betsey, and I watched at a Modica shop called the
Antica Dolceria Bonajuto as a short, cheerful, muscular man named
Giorgio Turla stirred a copper vat full of orange peel with a
paddle at least twice as tall as he. In December, that is his
chore, all day, every day. At the Bonajuto sweet shop, a bastion of
tradition, they do these things by hand.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is the domain of a gentle, dignified man named Franco
Ruta, who has a passion for preserving all that is best in this
fragrant Island of the Sun, as Homer called Sicily. We met him
through the intercession of Piero Selvaggio, owner of one of
California's most esteemed Italian restaurants, Valentino in Santa
Monica. Selvaggio was born in Modica, once one of the seats of
Spanish power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand poverty and donkey carts and the Mafia as
symbols of Sicily,'' said Ruta, a medical technician who retired a
decade ago to take over the shop, which was founded in 1880 by his
father-in-law's father-in-law. ``I want our people to appreciate
our history and our patrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   One important legacy, in his eyes, is chocolate, and he and his
half-dozen workers make chocolate of astonishingly pure, powerful
flavor. Using semiprocessed cacao from the Ivory Coast, which
contains all the cocoa butter that makes the end product rich, they
combine it with vanilla or cinnamon and heat it until it turns
soft, at about 100 to 120 degrees. Industrial chocolate, Ruta said,
is made at much higher temperatures, which harm texture and taste.
</P>
<P>
   Pierpaolo Ruta, Franco's son, told me that his research, carried
out with the help of the Internet, suggests that only in Oaxaca,
Mexico, and in certain Catalan towns in Spain is this old process
still used.
</P>
<P>
   When the chocolate comes out of the pan, it looks like brownie
mix. It is next rolled between the hands of the confectioner and
dropped into long aluminum loaf pans. The pans are placed in wooden
trays, which are banged briskly (and loudly) on marble worktops,
expelling air bubbles and leaving a satin-smooth surface atop the
deep brown chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting it, said Sicilian gastronome Leonardo Sciascia, ``is
like reaching the absolute, the archetype'' _ and I most heartily
agree. It is dense, fudgy and full-flavored. Because of the low
temperatures involved, the sugar granules remain intact, leaving a
slight, pleasant graininess.
</P>
<P>
   The Ruta family's chocolate can be used in a hot drink, in the
Aztec style, or eaten as a sweet. But Modican tradition views it as
a food rather than a candy. So the Dolceria makes 'mpanatigghi,
ravioli stuffed with mincemeat and chocolate _ the name is related
to the Spanish empanada _ and liccumie, another pastry stuffed with
eggplant and chocolate, and even chocolate bonbons flavored with
more than a hint of chili pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the Corso Umberto I, Modica's main street, at the
sleekly modern Fattoria della Torri, recently anointed as one of
Sicily's two best restaurants by the Gambero Rosso guide, they
serve rabbit with a sauce (wait for it) made of chocolate. Had I
not known, I would have thought I was eating a wine sauce with some
mystery ingredient, perhaps rabbit liver.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, all this sounds preposterous, even if very
vaguely reminiscent of the mole sauce served in Mexico. But not a
single one of these savory chocolate creations tasted a bit weird.
All were perfectly delicious.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As were Corrado Costanza's gelati, even though both of us winced
a bit before tasting them. Rose ice cream? Jasmine? Ricotta cheese
ice cream? One bite of each, however, is enough to demonstrate why
Costanza, now 70, has been chosen again and again as Sicily's
gelato and granita king. The rose and jasmine tasted the way those
flowers smell at their peak; eating them was a walk in a summer
garden. The ricotta, unctuous and sweet but with sour undertones,
is superb, too; it is made with a kind of cottage cheese and plenty
of cinnamon, which has long been a favorite Sicilian spice.
</P>
<P>
   But Costanza's masterpiece, it seemed to us, was the gloriously
fragrant tangerine sorbet _ just fresh tangerine juice with pure
water and sugar. It occurred to me that it would make a perfect
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   We tasted them all at his shop, an unassuming place with yellow
striped awnings, down the street from the cathedral in Noto. We
tasted them with traditional Sicilian ice cream spades, which used
to be seen in old-fashioned American ice cream parlors, too. We
tasted them while Costanza, who has visited New York twice, held
forth on things he did not like in the United States, including
air-filled, factory-made American ice cream. ``Gelato gonfiato,''
he called that, meaning puffed-up ice cream. ``Not real, no good.''
California citrus, said Costanza, a jolly man with a white brush of
a mustache, was OK. But Sicilian oranges, he added, ``have a lot
more'' _ and here, his English having run out, he pantomimed a
punch.
</P>
<P>
   None of that good-natured railery should be construed as a
suggestion of arrogance. Costanza is a humble man. When I noticed a
certificate, signed by the president and prime minister of Italy,
making him a cavaliere, or knight, he shot me a disdainful look and
commented: ``That doesn't matter. What matters is whether you think
my ice cream tastes good or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ruta's, Costanza's workshops, next door to his cafe and
shop, contain some reassuringly elderly equipment, but a lot of
modern tools, too, including automated ice cream machines. Some, he
hastened to show me, wouldn't work unless safety screens were in
place to guard against the loss of a finger. Old-fashioned he may
be; a Luddite he certainly is not.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, he also makes granita from lemons, tangerines, black
mulberries and other fruit, as well as coffee. Ricotta fills the
crisp little tubes called cannoli and the celebrated cake called
the cassata.
</P>
<P>
   But the superlative local almonds are Costanza's secret weapons;
scoop a few from a bin, blanched but unsugared, and they have a
remarkable sweetness. He makes torrone, or nougat, with them, and
fashions miniature fruits and vegetables from hand-painted almond
paste, or marzipan. That word, too, is Saracen in origin, stemming
from the Arabic ``martaban,'' but the Sicilians call it martorana,
after a Palermo convent where it was once made.
</P>
<P>
   There is one more important almond product _ the sugar-coated
nuts that we call Jordan almonds and the Sicilians call confetti.
Mary Taylor Simeti remarks in ``Pomp and Sustenance'' (Ecco Press,
1998) that ``food in Sicily shares in what I have come to regard as
the terrible density of Sicilian culture, an insular culture
compacted by centuries of foreign conquest and domestic
oppression,'' and confetti is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we Americans throw our paper confetti at brides and
bridegrooms, Sicilians sometimes hurl almonds. The custom
originated in the far-off epoch when brides were kidnapped by the
groom's friends, and the bride's defenders often threw stones or
other missiles at the captors. Confetti throwing, or so Waverly
Root reports in ``The Food of Italy'' (Vintage Books, 1992), is
simply the present-day ritualization of those long-forgotten
battles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
