<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WAS BRADLEY-MCCAIN SHOW SUPPOSED TO ACCOMPLISH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing like a little dog-and-pony show to liven up a
boring political campaign _ or to help a couple of underdog
candidates grab some headlines and free TV time.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more gullible among the media tried to palm it off
as historic, or at least important, but Thursday's joint appearance
by Democrat Bill Bradley and Republican John McCain to talk up
campaign finance reform was barely more than a run-of-the-mill
publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   It was different, we can give 'em that. A candidate seeking his
party's presidential nomination doesn't usually go on television
with a would-be nominee from another party _ which might be why Ted
Koppel figured that the Bradley-McCain encounter deserved exclusive
treatment on ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   What it really deserved, of course, was a giant yawn _ and
probably got it, seeing as how most public-opinion polls suggest
that voters are about as interested in campaign finance reform as
they are in Monica Lewinsky's latest diet.
</P>
<P>
   No fair-minded voter should find fault with these guys for
availing themselves of the opportunity to hype their campaigns and
take potshots at their intraparty opponents _ and to do it while
sharing the authoritative spotlight commanded by Koppel.
</P>
<P>
   But the stunt does raise a question: Exactly who was it supposed
to impress?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is obvious enough where Bradley is concerned.
Campaign finance reform is a popular issue among liberal Democrats,
who are perennial also-rans to conservative Republicans when it
comes to fund-raising. But McCain?
</P>
<P>
   McCain must know that rank-and-file Republicans and conservative
activists have no use for most of the proposals to reform campaign
finance because they are rigged to favor Democrats and punish the
GOP. Besides, conservatives generally believe that contributing
financially to a political campaign is tantamount to free speech _
and therefore that stringent restrictions on such contributions are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   So. What was a candidate for the ``Republican'' presidential
nomination trying to accomplish by participating in that
Bradley-to-McCain-to-Koppel double play?
</P>
<P>
   Best guess: He was scrounging for independent votes in New
Hampshire, where independents apparently are interested in campaign
finance reform _ and where residents can vote in either party's
primary. McCain might be gambling that independents can help him
defeat front-runner George W. Bush in the Feb. 1 primary, and that
a win in New Hampshire will give him so much momentum that he'll be
able to overtake Bush in later primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain keeps insisting that voters really do care about
campaign finance reform despite polls indicating otherwise, he
seems to be basing his strategy on the cynical assumption that
Republican voters care so little about the issue that his
anti-Republican position won't dissuade Republicans from supporting
him in party primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Give him credit for chutzpah, if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Bush is right when he says that campaign finance
reform is a scam designed to neutralize the GOP's fund-raising
advantage _ and most Republican voters agree with him. Faced with
choosing between a presidential candidate who represents their
thinking (Bush) and one who is determined to sell out to the
Democrats (McCain), GOP voters won't have to think twice before
voting for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   All this is academic, anyway, because McCain's big surge in New
Hampshire is a mirage. Even if he wins that primary, he's going
nowhere. A win in New Hampshire will no more propel him to the
Republican nomination than it propelled Pat Buchanan to the
nomination when he upset Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a one-issue candidate. And his one issue, campaign
finance reform, doesn't even appeal to the voters whose support he
must enlist if he expects to give Bush a run for his, uh, money,
much less win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's headline grab with Bradley was good theater. It was not
good politics _ unless McCain hopes to be Bradley's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
