<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-R-SWEET-SYRUPS-ART-NY     12-21 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SWEET-SYRUPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUL OF THE GRAPE, DROP BY DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 repeating to add art note (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what they say about necessity. Centuries ago, when
refined cane sugar was a luxury for aristocrats only, the common
folk made sweeteners by concentrating the juices of grapes and
other fruit into dark, viscous syrups with a touch of acidity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these age-old, often homemade sugar substitutes have
acquired culinary cachet. Chefs across the country are using them
to enrich marinades and sauces and drizzling them around braised
cabbage and pork, over sharp pecorino cheese or on creamy panna
cotta or berries. They are imported mainly from the Emilia-Romagna
region and, in the south, Apulia.
</P>
<P>
   Odette Fada, the chef at San Domenico in Manhattan, has used
fruit syrups for years. ``I get mine from a friend in Italy who
makes her own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, these sweeteners are made from wine grapes and go by
regional names like saba, sapa, vin cotto or mosto cotto. Vin cotto
means ``cooked wine'' though it is made from unfermented grape
juice, or must, and has no alcohol. In southern Italy, vin cotto is
sometimes made from figs.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro Mafrici, the chef at I Trulli, uses vin cotto from Apulia
as a glazing dip for fried Christmas cookies and to sweeten an
apple and almond cake. At Babbo and nearby Po, saba is used in
sauces and dressings. The chef, Mario Batali, said he discovered it
when he lived in Modena. ``They often make it from the grapes they
thin from the vines before the harvest, so they don't go to
waste,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Turkey, a syrup called pekmez is made from grapes or
pomegranate juice (sold as pomegranate molasses) and is more acidic
than saba. Similar concentrates are found in parts of North
America, especially in New England, where boiled cider has been a
sweetener since the Colonial era.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dark brown, intensely apple-flavored sweetener, it has at
the same time a definite snappiness that keeps it from being too
cloying,'' writes Ben Watson in ``Cider, Hard and Sweet''
(Countryman Press, $19.95). Cider mills in Vermont and Sally
Schmitt's Apple Farm in Philo, Calif., sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar is thought to have evolved from saba, said
Lynne Rossetto Kasper, the cookbook author. Both start by boiling
down the must of trebbiano or lambrusco wine grapes. ``The syrup
might have been stored in vinegar barrels, and that's how balsamico
came about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fada said she often uses saba like balsamic vinegar, as a
finishing touch for butternut squash soup. It is also delicious on
grilled radicchio or baked peaches.
</P>
<P>
   Aging gives true balsamic vinegar its complexity, and its steep
price. But add a touch of good red wine vinegar to saba or vin
cotto, and you'll have something closer to traditional $100
artisanal balsamic vinegar than the harsh industrially produced
vinegars in most stores. And you're better off spooning saba over
next spring's strawberries than using less than top-of-the-line
balsamico. At $10 to $25 for 17 ounces, saba and other syrups now
cost more than sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottled imports don't fit our budget, so we're making our
own interpretation,'' said Mark Ladner, the chef at Lupa in
Greenwich Village. He crushes red grapes, cooks the juice down with
some red wine vinegar and sugar, and adds semi-dried grapes to the
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kasper notes in ``The Italian Country Table'' (Scribner,
$35) that farmers in Italy still make vin cotto or saba, though
sugar is now cheap. One farm woman told her: ``Sugar sweetens. Vin
cotto flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAKED PEARS WITH SABA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Splendid Table'' by Lynne Rossetto Kasper
(William Morrow, 1992)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours, plus cooling
</P>
<P>
   6 bosc pears, peeled, cored and halved
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 large lemons, and grated zest of one
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1} cups saba or vin cotto.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 375 degrees. Toss pears in a bowl with lemon
juice. Butter a 10- or 11-inch round or 9-by-13-inch baking dish.
Arrange pears in dish. Sprinkle with lemon zest and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bake about 1 hour, basting every 20 minutes with 1/3 cup
saba. Remove from oven. If pan juices are runny, spoon into a
saucepan, and cook down until syrupy.
</P>
<P>
   3. Serve pears warm or cool, with pan juices and remaining saba
drizzled over them.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARTELLATE WITH VIN COTTO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from I Trulli
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 1 hour resting
</P>
<P>
   4 cups all purpose flour, more for rolling
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   2 cups vin cotto or saba
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put flour in mixer. Add oil, 1 cup water and salt, and beat
at low speed until dough forms. Wrap in plastic, and set aside 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Divide dough in half. On large work surface lightly dusted
with flour, roll it paper-thin into a rectangle. Cut in strips 1\
inches wide and 12 inches long. Fold each strip in half lengthwise
without pressing it down, then roll into a pinwheel about 2 inches
in diameter, pinching ends closed. Repeat with remaining dough.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat oil to 350 degrees in a large saucepan to a depth of 2
inches. Fry pinwheels until golden brown. Drain on absorbent paper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heat vin cotto, sugar and \ cup water in saucepan until sugar
dissolves. Dip fried cookies in syrup; drain. Arrange on platter.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALMOND, APPLE AND VIN COTTO CAKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from I Trulli
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons melted unsalted butter, plus butter for pan
</P>
<P>
   \ cup cake flour, plus flour for pan
</P>
<P>
   6 tart apples, peeled, cored and each cut in 16 slices
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   { cup vin cotto or boiled cider
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups almond flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon confectioner's sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. Butter and flour a 10-inch
springform cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place 1 tablespoon butter in large skillet over medium heat.
Add apples, and sprinkle with 3 tablespoons sugar and { teaspoon
vanilla. Saute 4 to 5 minutes, until starting to soften. Spread on
baking sheet to cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Beat yolks with { cup sugar in large bowl until very light.
Fold in remaining butter and vanilla, \ cup vin cotto and cake
flour.
</P>
<P>
   4. Whip egg whites until firmly peaked. Gradually beat in
remaining sugar until glossy. Fold egg white mixture into egg yolk
mixture. Fold in almond flour.
</P>
<P>
   5. Spread half the apples in pan. Add half the batter. Repeat
layers. Sift confectioner's sugar over top. Bake 40 to 45 minutes,
until browned. Cool, remove from pan and serve with vin cotto
drizzled on each portion.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
