<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Unhappy birthday, dear impeachment
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first anniversary of Bill Clinton's impeachment came
dribbling by the other day with precious little celebration.
Nothing more stale, I suppose, than old non-news warmed over.
</P>
<P>
   The usual suspects seemed to be working their customary sides of
the street. Monica Lewinsky was appearing as a witness in the
Maryland wiretapping trial of the pathetic Linda Tripp, who may
have the peculiar distinction of being the only participant to do
time. Impeachment managers were still insisting on the rectitude of
the enterprise. The public, which thinks more poorly of Bill
Clinton, was still yawning. Special prosecutor Ken Starr admitted
he made some mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes up to which Starr owned were merely failures to
explain himself clearly enough to the public. Starr does not still
realize that explaining is what got him in trouble in the first
place. Superior spin would have made things worse.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's less than startling admission is a valuable indication,
however, as to what it was all about in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
