A5504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WEIR-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-     12-21 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIR-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEIR COOKING': NEW RECIPES WITH A FAMILIAR WINE COUNTRY FACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Italy)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (Eds: A recipe appears at end of review.)  (DW) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cookbook becomes a keeper when you want to take it into the
kitchen after you flip through it once. Usually, the attraction is
not the book's new culinary horizons but comfortable yet alluring
recipes that do not demand hours of work. Joanne Weir's cookbooks
are like that. They have a familiar feel and offer the best advice
for any home cook: prepare dishes made with the finest ingredients
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weir Cooking: Recipes From the Wine Country'' (Time-Life
Books, $27.50) outlines California cooking with an eye on the
Mediterranean. As Ms. Weir points out, both regions share a similar
climate and ingredients, like olives, and she fills her first
chapter with dishes fortified with their briny tang. Her excellent
mock puff pastry for an olive tart could be put to wider use.
</P>
<P>
   The book moves on to more substantial fare, like polenta cakes
with mushroom ragout, seared salmon showered with oil-infused
herbs, asparagus cheese puffs and a dessert tart with a nubbly
cornmeal texture.
</P>
<P>
   Root vegetables were excellent roasted with a splash of Marsala.
Ms. Weir did not specify whether it was to be dry or sweet: I'm
glad I had dry on hand. In a recipe for spicy shellfish stew, she
did not say what kind of clams or scallops to use. If I had good,
thick rib-eye steaks, I would grill them instead of going to the
trouble of butterflying them, filling them with a vegetable
stuffing and braising them.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where in the town of Recco, on the Ligurian coast
of Italy, she ate the famous focaccia col formaggio, a kind of huge
double-crusted cheese pie made with very thin dough. But her
recipe, calling for a yeast dough, misses the mark. It's tasty but
not the real thing. Only those who had been to Recco might know the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   WARM OLIVE AND CARAMELIZED ONION TART
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Weir Cooking''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ hours, plus one hour's freezing
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour, plus more for work surface
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cake flour
</P>
<P>
   12 tablespoons butter, cut in {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   5 medium onions, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled, seeded, chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 anchovy fillets, soaked in cold water 10 minutes, patted dry,
mashed
</P>
<P>
   { cup imported black olives, pitted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1. Combine flours in bowl, and freeze 1 hour. Freeze butter
cubes 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a bowl or food processor, mix frozen flour with { teaspoon
salt. Add butter, and cut with pastry blender or pulse until butter
is size of peas. Add up to \ cup ice water, just until mixture
holds together (if using food processor, transfer mixture to bowl
first). Turn onto lightly floured surface and pat into shape of
small rectangle. Chunks of butter will show. Roll out dough, making
rectangle about 5 by 7 inches, { inch thick. Fold narrow ends
toward center so they meet. Fold in half again to make 4 layers.
Give dough quarter turn, and repeat rolling and folding. Repeat
another time. Roll dough again, but this time fold it in thirds
like a business letter. Wrap in plastic, and refrigerate 45 minutes
to 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, heat oil in large skillet over medium-low heat.
Add onions, garlic, thyme and rosemary, and cook, stirring
occasionally, until onions are soft and golden, 50 to 60 minutes.
Add tomatoes, increase heat and cook until almost dry, 10 to 15
minutes. Add anchovies and olives, season and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. On floured surface, roll dough
to make rectangle 9 by 13 inches, \ inch thick. Crimp edges, and
transfer to baking sheet. Cover dough with onion mixture to within
{ inch of edge. Bake until crust is golden, 30 to 40 minutes. Cut
in portions or small squares, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings, or 24 hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
</TEXT>
