u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-Y2K-H     12-21 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. SAYS Y2K GLITCHES WON'T AFFECT SOCIAL SECURITY  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 44 million Americans who receive Social
Security retirement benefits will get their checks as usual on Jan.
3 _ even in the event of a Y2K-related computer failure or power
outage, the federal government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who depend on us can rest assured that their
payments will arrive on time,'' Social Security Commissioner
Kenneth Apfel told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The agency that runs the nation's Social Security retirement
system began addressing the Y2K problem in 1989 _ several years
before the rest of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security has done a wonderful job in dealing with its
own systems,'' said John Koskinen, the White House's Y2K czar.
``Social Security has been a leader in the federal government in
terms of Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Apfel said Social Security has been issuing checks for more than
a year using computers that have been fixed to overcome any 2000
problem. If computers are not fixed they may misread the digits
``00'' as 1900 and malfunction, potentially wrecking havoc in the
nation's air traffic control system, the power grid or the
financial sector, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Treasury Department has already printed the paper
checks that will be received by 11 million Americans next month.
Those checks will be delivered to U.S. post offices on Wednesday,
Dec. 29 _ one day earlier than usual _ to ensure they are received
by Monday, Jan. 3. Social Security benefits are always paid out on
the third of each month.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, Social Security officials will have forwarded the
electronic files to the Treasury Department of the 33 million
Americans whose Social Security payments are automatically
deposited into their bank accounts. The Treasury Department will
forward those files to the Federal Reserve, which in turn will
forward the files to various banks by Dec. 30. The banks will have
until Jan. 3 to electronically deposit the money into the accounts
of individual recipients.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 30, the six million Americans who receive supplemental
Social Security disability checks will receive their benefit
payments. Those payments are normally made on the first of each
month, but because Jan. 1 is a federal holiday, the supplemental
payments are being made early and will be unaffected by any Y2K
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case there are some Y2K glitches, Apfel said the
agency is taking several steps to deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will operate a 24-hour command center at its
headquarters in Baltimore from Dec. 30 to Jan. 7. Shortly before
midnight on New Year's Eve, Social Security's main computers there
will be switched to a backup generator powered by jet fuel in case
the city's power fails. If Social Security officials receive word
that there was no disruption to the regular power supply, the
computers will be plugged back into the Baltimore power grid.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1 officials at more than 1,300 local Social Security
offices will be assigned to check all phones and computers to make
sure they are working and report into the national headquarters. If
there are any problems _ which are not expected _ the computers
will be fixed Jan. 1 and Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event a bank cannot receive electronic deposits,
Social Security will have the Treasury Department issue and mail
paper checks within five days. If people are unable to wait for
that check, they can go to their local Social Security office to
have the check issued immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;  (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
