<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JUNEAU-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     12-21 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNEAU-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PASSAGE TO JUNEAU': A SOLITARY SEAMAN'S VOYAGE WITH A PRICE TO
PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do we travel, especially when the reviews on leaving home
are so mixed? Blaise Pascal's aphorism that all human evil comes
from ``man's being unable to sit still in a room'' rings a clear
alarm about the hazards of restlessness. But then there is what
Jonathan Raban in ``Passage to Juneau,'' his latest book of travel,
calls ``the Romantic solitary wanderer,'' like the figure in
Shelley's first major poem who left ``His cold fireside and
alienated home/To seek strange truths in undiscovered lands.''
</P>
<P>
   Raban, in sailing alone from Seattle to Juneau, Alaska, did not
discover any undiscovered lands. There are no undiscovered lands
anymore, though certainly the Inside Passage from Washington state
to Alaska, even if heavily used by cruise liners, fishing boats and
fortune seekers, is remote by most people's definition. In his last
book, ``Bad Land,'' the British-born Raban explored the meaning of
remote landlocked regions, so it made sense that he try a kind of
watery counterpart, and the goal was more defined by Shelley than
Pascal: to pursue strange truths, or perhaps truths, even if not
strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant to go fishing for reflections and come back with a
glittering haul,'' Raban writes early on, meaning reflections on
the sea as a zone of meaning, as a mirror of human vanity, as an
imminent danger, as a place where history happened and cultures
collided. ``Other people's reflections, as I thought then,'' Raban
continues, before hinting at a tragic disclosure to follow, ``I
wasn't prepared for the catch I eventually made.''
</P>
<P>
   Raban is perhaps our most literate and literary travel writer.
His books are not, as are those of many other travel writers,
essentially entertainments based on encounters with oddball
characters met on route, though a few such characters certainly do
appear on Raban's itinerary. ``Passage to Juneau'' brings its
readers through a complicated maze of physical description, of
solitary sailing tribulations and of historical-cultural
ruminations. It is a rich, even overly rich melange, showing an
author with a mind always at eloquent work but with some confusion
as to its central theme.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually his narrative is taken over by emotionally laden
personal matters: the death of his father, strains on his marriage.
These matters of private life are moving but seem distant from the
subject at hand, the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage to Juneau'' in other words is a highly intelligent and
lushly written repository of products created by a meditative and
adventurous sensibility. It has much that is brilliant, including
many passages of fine descriptive writing; it is also a caldron
overflowing with too much stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Raban boarded his 35-foot, library-equipped sailboat on April
Fool's Day, saying goodbye to his wife and the 3{-year-old daughter
whose annoyance at his temporary abandonment tinged his journey
with sadness from the beginning. As Raban navigates northward, he
establishes himself as an unillusioned observer, one attuned to
beauty but not rhapsodic about it or about nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motoring through the sound, watching for deadheads, I sailed
through a logjam of dead literary cliche,'' he writes in a passage
about scenery and Romantic poetry. ``Snowcapped peaks above,
fathomless depths below, and, in the middle of the picture, the
usual gaunt cliffs, hoary crags, wild woods, and crystal
cascades.'' And later: ``I felt that entering a landscape like
Desolation Sound was uncomfortably like wandering over a famous
battlefield left over from someone else's war. That it had been a
scene of such heightened emotion in the past only made me feel more
keenly my own absence of feeling in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Along his way Raban gives a savory history of a geographically
identical journey though the Inside Passage taken by the ships and
crew commanded by Capt. George Vancouver, whose unhappy surveying
voyage of 1791 to 1795 gave many of the islands, promontories, bays
and mountains of the Northwest Pacific their names. And so Raban's
own account of heavy tides and fog is interspersed with tales from
Vancouver's afflicted voyage, which included frequent floggings,
one grounding, many tense encounters with Indians and an
undercurrent of late-18th-century British class warfare. Raban
reflects on many other matters as well: on the impossibility of
knowing what the original native culture was; on anthropologists
like Franz Boas and Claude Levi-Strauss; on landscape painting,
Romantic poetry, even Mozart at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Raban marvelously describes the perilous unpredictability of
tides and currents. He ties up at forlorn spots where the canneries
have closed and the tourists have not yet arrived, giving a picture
of profane, unhappy men sitting in bars and cursing their fates. A
lover of nature, he distinguishes himself from a certain kin of
prayerfully reverential environmentalism associated with writers
like John Muir that in Raban's view represented a maudlin variation
on ravished-by-nature 19th-century Romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lopez's version struck me as improbably tidy and benign,''
Raban writes, Lopez being Barry Lopez, whom Raban groups with other
Northwest nature writers. ``A `design inherent' in nature implied a
designer, in whose existence I had no faith at all. `Logic' was, I
thought, a useful word so long as it  &UR; meant &LR;  logic, not some
vapory, intuited life-force.''
</P>
<P>
   The sea, in other words, like nature, may have its meanings to
some, but Raban associates it more with the chaos, the terrifying
whirling abysses that he remembers in the paintings of J.M.W.
Turner, about whom he discourses learnedly. Wildness is not
friendly, but then, it turns out, neither is human life. In the
end, Raban identifies the price he pays for his own inability to
sit quietly in a room. It would be unfair to disclose here exactly
what that price is, but it is one that gives Raban's entire account
a melancholy gloss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage to Juneau'' in a sense turns out to be a kind of
anti-travel book, a refreshingly counter-sentimental antidote to
the notion of travel as continuous adventure, quantum-leap
self-discovery. The very capaciousness of Raban's interests gives
his account a dense and tangled quality, but within every thicket
there is the kind of intellectual precision that makes going along
on this unromantic adventure very worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PASSAGE TO JUNEAU: A Sea and Its Meanings'
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Raban
</P>
<P>
   435 pages. Pantheon. $26.50. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
