<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHEERLEADERS MOBILIZE FOR HOLIDAY ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders usually work along the
sidelines, but this week they are on the front line for another
American team _ U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mission with one delightful holiday twist: When they
fall in on European stages wearing their trademark blue blouses,
white vests and white pants trimmed with stars and rhinestones,
they will cheer a team that _ unlike the Cowboys football team _
can't lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's clearly the Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders' mission
to give back to the troops that help keep us free and safe at
home,'' choreographer Shelly Roper-McCaslin said Monday. ``And it's
bringing a little bit of home to them.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the idea of this year's Defense Department-USO holiday
tour to the Balkan region of Europe. Among those making the trip
are NFL Hall of Fame quarterback Terry Bradshaw, ``Saturday Night
Live'' alumnus Al Franken, Grammy-winning country singer Mary
Chapin Carpenter and supermodel Christie Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Roper-McCaslin and six other Cowboy cheerleaders headed east,
where they will open hourlong shows in the former Yugoslav republic
of Bosnia-Herzegovina; in Kosovo, the disputed province of Serbia;
the Republic of Macedonia, another former region of Yugoslavia; and
Italy. They will entertain about 15,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen more headed to Okinawa and South Korea, continuing a
Cowboys tradition Roper-McCaslin said began in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to me to be able to go over and touch
someone's life at Christmastime,'' cheerleader Alice Phillips, 32,
said. ``It gets you warm and fuzzy inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Chief Master Sgt. Jim Finch, the service's top
enlisted man, would not doubt that after seeing smiles from the
cheerleaders that could melt a Bosnian snowbank.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest overseas holiday event Finch, 43, has seen in his
25-year career was in 1977, when an Air Force band played before
300 service personnel at a Royal Air Force base 60 miles west of
London.
</P>
<P>
   This tour will be far better, he said, and predicted the
cheerleaders would be a big hit with the American forces
participating in peacekeeping duties in Kosovo and
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be a big treat for the troops,'' he said.
``In many cases they're young folks and have not had Christmases
away from home before, and so to have someone come out here and
entertain them makes them feel like they're somebody special and
somebody cares.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
