A5513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUNDAY-FILM-REVIEW-NY     12-21 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` ANY GIVEN SUNDAY': END ZONE AS WAR ZONE ... HUT! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end.) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a cinematic flasher of not-so-secret mass culture fantasies,
Oliver Stone is Hollywood's R-rated answer to P.T. Barnum. Instead
of clowns, aerialists and lion tamers, he parades his own
hyper-macho vision of modern American life as a primitive
bread-and-circuses carnival of power, greed, lust, fame and
violence (especially violence). And in ``Any Given Sunday,'' his
viscerally charged, razzle-dazzle ode to professional football as a
blood sport, he comes up with some quintessentially zany Oliver
Stone moments.
</P>
<P>
   Take the scene in the locker room of the Miami Sharks in which a
heavily muscled naked football player with a mammoth sexual
endowment is placed directly in front of the camera. The shot is
held for an extra half-beat as if to say: ``Look at it. We all know
that this is what football is really about: colliding superstuds
whose bedroom conquests we would like to imagine are the erotic
equivalent of their stadium feats.''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene in which the Sharks' head coach, Tony D'Amato
(Al Pacino), lectures the hotshot young quarterback Willie Beamen
(Jamie Foxx) on being a team player, the movie lards in clips of
the climactic chariot race from ``Ben-Hur.'' In case we haven't
already gotten the movie's blatant message about football being the
home-grown equivalent of a Roman gladiatorial circus, here it is
spelled out again. Later the movie actually trots out Charlton
Heston for a cameo appearance as the moralizing commissioner of the
Associated Football Franchises of America. It should be no surprise
that Stone is as gleefully at home inside a football stadium as he
is on the battlefield, since his new movie portrays professional
football and wartime combat as variations of the same experience.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most exciting scenes take place in the bone-crushing
thick of the fray, and they provide about as acute a sense of
straining muscle and excruciating collision as a football movie
could hope to give. Like battlefield casualties, injured players
are rushed off the field on stretchers. And at halftime, the locker
room resembles a hospital emergency ward where players who are not
too badly injured are frantically sewn up and shot up with
painkillers, then sent back into battle.
</P>
<P>
   Encasing all this action, the director and his collaborators
John Logan and Daniel Pyne have erected the shell of a story that
is a crude morality play in the style of Stone's ``Wall Street.''
The biggest struggle pits the old school of football philosophy
against the new. That old school is exemplified by the battle-weary
D'Amato and the Sharks' loyal but fading star quarterback, the
legendary Jack Rooney, known as Cap (Dennis Quaid), who at 39 is
nearing the end of his career. Tony and Cap represent a cooperative
team-player ethic that is being undermined by big money and the
star-making power of television.
</P>
<P>
   The new school is embodied by the gifted but arrogant and
relatively inexperienced Willie, who catapults from third-string
quarterback into the Sharks' resident superstar. In a matter of
months, Willie has also scored a chart-topping rap hit and landed
some lucrative television commercials. But Willie is so green that
he throws up before every game. Not groomed to be a team player, he
infuriates Tony by calling his own shots in the huddle. But when
his spontaneous decisions win games and the Sharks' sagging
fortunes start to reverse, Tony's old-school philosophy is
increasingly called into question.
</P>
<P>
   Willie's flash is backed by the Sharks' ruthless owner,
Christina Pagniacci (Cameron Diaz), who, with her alcoholic mother
(Ann-Margret), inherited the team from her football legend of a
father, who was also Tony's mentor. Other moral conflicts pit the
Sharks' coldbloodedly pragmatic orthopedist, (and Dr. Feelgood)
Harvey Mandrake (James Woods), who risks the lives of the players
to keep them in the game at all costs, and its young internist,
Oliver Powers (Matthew Modine), who is appalled by Mandrake's
reckless decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the movie, the kinetic furor of the game sequences
helps camouflage the weaknesses of a screenplay that is a
mechanically contrived series of power struggles, each of which has
an issue attached to it. But as the movie develops into a kind of
mega-``Rocky'' with an end-of-game sequence that stretches nine
seconds of play into many minutes, the strains begin to show.
</P>
<P>
   Those strains extend to some crucial performances. Quaid appears
several years too old (and not in good enough shape) for his role,
and Ms. Diaz, who can be such a winning comedian, is not up to the
dramatic demands of her unsympathetic character. But Pacino's Tony
is a solid if well-worn variation on a familiar Pacino type, a
weather-beaten not-so-young true believer stretched beyond his
limits and forced to re-evaluate his entire life. The movie's
revelation is Foxx's Willie, who gracefully embodies the internal
conflicts of a talented, insecure athlete. Embittered by years of
racial discrimination and tempted by the rewards of instant
celebrity, he struggles not to lose his humanity amid the hoopla.
It's a subtle performance in a movie that has nothing else subtle
about it.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Stone's attitude toward the frenzy he has conjured is
wildly ambivalent. ``Any Given Sunday,'' like so many other Stone
films dealing with violence, embraces the visceral Dionysian thrill
of professional football with the ecstatic eagerness of a
scaredy-cat who has conquered his fear of skydiving and become
addicted to jumping out of airplanes. At the same time it is also
an expose of professional football and its sins and the mad,
mindless excesses of greed, power-mongering, exploitation and
phallic worship it enshrines.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the movie cops out. Although the story presents many
opportunities for tragedy (some situations practically beg for it),
``Any Given Sunday'' turns ludicrously upbeat as it hastily ties
all its strands together. P.T. Barnum liked happy endings too.
Circus lions are in the ring to be tamed, aerialists are expected
not to fall. The final message of ``Any Given Sunday'' is one big
thumbs up: Let the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Any Given Sunday'' is rated R. It has profanity,
sexual situations and lots of playing-field violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ANY GIVEN SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Oliver Stone; written by John Logan and Stone, based
on a screen story by Daniel Pyne and Logan; director of
photography, Salvatore Totino; edited by Tom Nordberg, Keith Salmon
and Stuart Waks; production designer, Victor Kempster; produced by
Lauren Shuler Donner, Clayton Townsend and Dan Halsted; released by
Warner Brothers. Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Al Pacino (Tony D'Amato), Cameron Diaz (Christina
Pagniacci), Dennis Quaid (Cap Rooney), James Woods (Dr. Harvey
Mandrake), Jamie Foxx (Willie Beamen), L.L. Cool J (Julian
Washington), Matthew Modine (Dr. Oliver Powers), Charlton Heston
(the Commissioner), Ann-Margret (Margaret Pagniacci), Aaron Eckhart
(Nick Crozier) and John C. McGinley (Jack Rose).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
