<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATSBY-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GREAT GATSBY': MUSIC CATERING   TO THE WORDS   OF FITZGERALD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One came away from ``The Great Gatsby'' at the
Metropolitan Opera on Monday night thinking not so much about Daisy
Buchanan, Nick Carraway or even Gatsby himself, but of what a nice
man John Harbison must be. His new opera has many responsibilities
to serve and much to live up to, and Harbison's sense of duty is
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the obligations incurred: a handsome commission from
the Met; a gilt-edged cast; an elegant staging by Mark Lamos,
Michael Yeargan and Jane Greenwood; the ministrations of one of the
world's great opera conductors, James Levine; voluminous
pre-premiere publicity; and finally an F. Scott Fitzgerald novel of
iconic stature.
</P>
<P>
   In 3 hours and 15 minutes this composer serves his several
masters with all the imagination at his disposal. When original
dramatic effects are required, Harbison is there with his thudding
percussive strokes. When scenes cry out for music of the Jazz Age,
combos and megaphoned pop singers materialize onstage performing
convincing syntheses of 1920s popular style. Everywhere is the
spirit of accommodation. Every need is tended to, promptly and
caringly.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful opera, on the other hand, may be more than doing the
right thing. I have long gone along with the idea that success in
this field means the judicious blend of music and words. ``The
Great Gatsby'' makes me wonder. Powerful opera may well start with
the monstrous musical ego: cruel to literature and contemptuous of
everything around it. A friend suggested to me that opera ought not
to be allowed near great writing, which ``Gatsby'' certainly is. I
would alter that to say that opera should not be allowed to treat
great writing with too much respect.
</P>
<P>
   For minutes at a stretch Harbison's music patiently accompanies
operatic narrative and conversation that an Alban Berg would have
squeezed mercilessly into seconds. One inches along these dreary
passages waiting for the bursts of interest that occasionally
appear. The composer tries to fill up long stretches with
interesting music, but legato singing lines played against a busy
movement in the orchestra results too often in mutual
nullification. I wish there were more rhythmic and metric life in
Harbison's music, but the tamely uniform sequential patterns simply
do not rouse the ear.
</P>
<P>
   To compare Harbison's music with Verdi's would be manifestly
unfair, but manner and approach are another matter. Verdi's love of
Shakespeare did not prevent him from pouring acid over the skin and
viscera of magnificent prose-poetry and writing operas using only
the skeletal remains. Harbison's own libretto (with song lyrics by
Murray Horwitz) extrudes and compresses, but it may be too
respectful of Fitzgerald for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Gatsby'' is in two acts and 10 scenes, the latter
bridged by orchestral interludes. Harbison ends with Gatsby's
funeral, omitting Nick Carraway's final encounter with the
Buchanans. This is sound theater in the big-finale tradition,
although Fitzgerald's final sigh of despair might have been an
updated, domesticated version of Mussorgsky's Idiot at the end of
``Boris Godunov.'' The Long Island decor, backed by sheer, silken
curtains, is elegance itself, and Ms. Greenaway's costumes, both
men's and women's, are a constant delight.
</P>
<P>
   The opera catches fire twice, both times in the party scenes.
Here music and dance do what they should be doing, overwhelming
everything around them. Robert La Fosse's choreography glitters
with frenetic energy and great charm. The cast is splendid. Dawn
Upshaw and Susan Graham are Daisy and Jordan and could scarcely be
better. Dwayne Croft's baritone as Nick is in luxurious condition,
and Mark Baker is a forceful Tom Buchanan. Jerry Hadley takes the
title role. His slightly overworked top register is probably an
acquired taste (though one not in my possession). The Wilsons _
Lorraine Hunt Lieberson and Richard Paul Fink _ provide the needed
rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in ``The Great Gatsby,'' partly buried, lies an
effective opera. Harbison is beholden to perhaps too many elements
of this enterprise, but every so often his musical imagination
rises, hearteningly, in revolt. His opera may also be the victim of
the inflated expectations surrounding it. With a little less star
treatment, ``The Great Gatsby'' might have passed quietly and
benignly into our lives.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREAT GATSBY'
</P>
<P>
   Opera by John Harbison, words by the composer, after the novel
by F. Scott Fitzgerald, with popular song lyrics by Murray Horwitz;
conductor, James Levine; production by Mark Lamos; sets by Michael
Yeargan; costumes by Jane Greenwood; lighting by Duane Schuler;
choreography by Robert La Fosse. At the Metropolitan Opera in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Dawn Upshaw (Daisy Buchanan), Jerry Hadley (Jay Gatsby),
Susan Graham (Jordan Baker), Lorraine Hunt Lieberson (Myrtle
Wilson), Mark Baker (Tom Buchanan), Dwayne Croft (Nick Carraway),
Richard Paul Fink (George Wilson), Jennifer Dudley (Tango Singer),
Matthew Polenzani (Radio Singer, Band Vocalist), William Powers
(Meyer Wolfsheim), Frederick Burchinal (Henry Gatz) and LeRoy Lehr
(Minister).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1708EST &QL; 
