<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yummy appetizers come to fore at this most festive time of year
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the French decreed in the 17th century that hors
d'oeuvres should be served before a meal, we are, after all,
approaching the 21st, and times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   After a holiday season of preparing sumptuous, sit-down feasts,
it may be the perfect time to alter the pace, take appetizers off
the sidelines and put them into the spotlight of your New Year's
celebration. Indeed, a buffet table brimming with trays of savory
morsels and a crystal bowl of sparkling punch can be perfectly
suited for a relaxed and festive evening of revelry.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to be a professional caterer to create
awesome appetizers, either. Most are simple, fun to prepare and
allow for unlimited creativity in presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and cold meats, fish, cheeses, fruits and vegetables can be
mixed and matched, stuffed, rolled, dipped and wrapped in unlimited
ways to create unexpected tastes and textures. Better yet,
quantities can be easily adjusted to serve two or 200. And best of
all _ for the host or hostess _ most appetizers can be made ahead
and frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most difficult part of putting together an
appetizer buffet is deciding what will grace your table. Help is
out there. The Larousse Gastronomique devotes no fewer than 15
encyclopedic pages to hors d'oeuvres, and the Internet has many
times more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nobody will miss a sit-down dinner of turkey or ham when
presented with a lovely display of antipasto kebabs of salami,
peppers, zucchini, olives and cherry tomatoes drenched in oil,
lemon juice and minced garlic. It's but one of hundreds of
appetizer ideas you'll find at
www.ichef.com/ichef-recipes/Appetizers/table-g.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If it can be stuffed, rolled, dipped, spread or made into a
log, you'll find it among the recipes at
sunsite.auc.dk/recipes/english/cat10
</P>
<P>
   .html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a variety of gourmet appetizers with lots of cheese and
vegetarian choices, see
www.ama-assn.org/insight/genhlth/gourmet/recapp.htm and
www.thebodygourmet.com/recappet.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making appetizers ahead of time and freezing them guarantees a
fun evening for the host. Crab Bites, Blue Cheesecake, Sausage
Spinach Balls, Baked Clam Loaf, Sausage Cheese Bites, Cajun Clams,
Bacon Wrapped Shrimp, Teriyaki Stuffed Pepperoncini, Savory Clam
Balls and Tortilla Pinwheels are a few of the surprisingly simple
recipes you can make ahead and freeze. See
busycooks.about.com/library
</P>
<P>
   /weekly/aa120699.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And then there are dips, which present a separate array of
taste-bud tempters. Put aside containers of prepared ranch and
French onion dips _ this is, after all, the millennium. Check out
the excellent links at
cheese.about.com/home/cheese/msub7.htm?REDIR404
</P>
<P>
   &QC; yes&AMP; for fantastic collections of dips, spreads, sauces, easy
mousses and salsas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When choosing dips, don't think chips _ think fine British
crackers, crusty rounds of French bread, pita wedges or bagel
thins. Check out the import section of the grocery and see what you
can come up with. Go all out and save the chips for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Punch your party up with 10 fabulous punch recipes and advice
from Epicurious. See food.epicurious.com/ddrinking/d03punch
</P>
<P>
   /punchintro.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finally, ``The Art of the Buffet,'' at food.homearts.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /thoughts/enter/c7enta36.htm, provides excellent tips on putting
together the perfect holiday buffet.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Caponata on Crostini
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 cups (20 slices) Preparation time: 55 minutes Cooking
time: 1 1/4 to 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 large eggplant, cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   6 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pimento-stuffed green olives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup red wine or cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 baguette, about 20 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a large enameled or stainless steel pot, combine eggplant,
onion, green pepper, tomatoes, olives, garlic, olive oil, vinegar,
salt, sugar, oregano, basil and capers. Mix well. Bring to a boil.
Reduce heat to medium-low and cook uncovered, stirring
occasionally, about 1 hour to 1 hour and 15 minutes, or until
mixture is soft and all liquid has cooked away. Cool to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   As mixture cools, preheat oven to 400 degrees. Brush bread with
remaining olive oil and place in oven for 12 minutes or until
lightly brown. Cook about 5 inches from top of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Top bread with Caponata. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Caponata will keep in the refrigerator for a week and may
be frozen up to 2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Per slice: 163 calories, 3 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 49), 19 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 312
milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
