<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP22-COX     12-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key lime juice puts some bite into wafers
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Louise Gay of Blairsville, Ga., wrote for cookie
recipes using bottled Key lime juice, I thought of Key Lime
Squares. Since that recipe was published in this paper several
years ago, it has become one of my favorites for cookie trays,
providing a welcome alternative to chocolates and vanillas, pecans
and peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   We published her request, though, hoping to get some more ideas.
This recipe for Lime Meltaways, originally published in Martha
Stewart Living in 1995, was sent in by Billie Boswell of Roswell,
Ga., who added a disclaimer that she is no fan of Stewart's and it
was a ``fluke'' she came across the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we're glad she did. These bite-size wafers are a snap to
make, and they hold just the right balance of sweet and tart.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Lime Meltaways
</P>
<P>
   Makes 120
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-15 minutes per batch
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) unsalted butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Key lime juice or freshly squeezed lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 2 limes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups plus 2 tablespoons
</P>
<P>
   all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cream butter and 1/3 cup confectioners' sugar
until fluffy. (Place remaining confectioners' sugar in a plastic
zip-top bag and set aside.) Add lime juice, zest and vanilla,
beating until incorporated (some of the juice may not be absorbed
completely).
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, stir together flour, cornstarch and salt.
Add to butter mixture and beat on low speed until combined.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough in half. On countertop or board lightly floured or
sugared, roll each half into a 1 1/4-inch-diameter log. Wrap in
parchment paper or plastic wrap and refrigerate at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to prepare, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line baking
sheet with parchment. Slice dough logs into 1/8-inch-thick coins.
Place rounds on sheet, about 1 inch apart.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 12 to 15 minutes, until barely golden. Transfer cookies to
a wire rack to cool slightly, about 5 minutes. While still warm,
place cookies, a few at a time, in plastic bag with confectioners'
sugar to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Store cookies in airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 22 calories, trace protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 48), 3 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 5 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Key Lime Squares
</P>
<P>
   Makes 36
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons Key lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated lime
</P>
<P>
   or lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Combine butter or margarine,
confectioners' sugar, 2 cups flour and salt. Mix with a pastry
blender or two knives until well-blended. Pat evenly into a
15-by-10-by-1-inch jellyroll pan and bake 20-25 minutes, or until
very lightly golden.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs lightly. Stir in granulated sugar, 6 tablespoons
flour, lime juice and zest. Mix well and spread over baked crust.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25 minutes longer, or until topping is set and edges are
golden. Watch carefully during last few minutes of baking, as the
crust can quickly become too brown.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and sift confectioners' sugar over the top. Let
cool on wire rack, then cut in squares.
</P>
<P>
   Store in airtight container between pieces of waxed paper.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 133 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 39), 19 grams carbohydrates, 24 milligrams
cholesterol, 109 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
