<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTY BOOP HAS QUITE A FEW YEARS ON BARBIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Barbie turned 40 this year. How old is Betty Boop?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.B.M., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Boop is pushing 70 _ she was created in 1930 by Fleischer
Studios for a series of short animated films.
</P>
<P>
   The character was originally a dog who sang cabaret and served
as sidekick to another canine named Bimbo. She quickly became the
most popular character in the cartoons and was transformed into a
human, appearing in more than 100 films in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The expression ``boop boop a doop'' came from Helen Kane's
version of the song ``I Wanna Be Loved by You.'' Mae Questel
provided Betty's voice.
</P>
<P>
   There's an official fan club that publishes a quarterly
newsletter with memorabilia articles, collecting tips and other
information. To join, send $10 to Betty Boop Fan Club, 6025
Fullerton Ave., No. 2, Buena Park, CA 90621-2345.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is Fort Benton out west?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.H.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Fort Benton is located on the Missouri River in northern
Montana about 40 miles northeast of Great Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Home to the oldest building in Montana, Fort Benton was
established as a fur trading post in 1846 and was a thriving
steamboat port from 1860 to the 1880s. The fort was sold by the
American Fur Company to the U.S. military in 1869 and abandoned by
1881.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the city of Fort Benton has 1,600 residents and a Lewis,
Clark and Sacagawea statue commemorating their 1805 expedition
through the area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I buy a crusher for garlic cloves?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.Z., Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you can't find one at a local cookware store, you can
order a Susi garlic press from Garlic World, a specialty store in
Gilroy, Calif. The retailer sells $11.50 and $14.50 presses along
with garlic peelers, slicers and graters.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 537-6122 or visit the Web site
www.garlicworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
