<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ORGANIZING23-COX     12-21 1583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANIZING23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to organize your home
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 23.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders and Alma Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough's enough.
</P>
<P>
   That realization made Kimberly Harrison seek professional help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem I'd been working on for a while, but I finally
just needed someone to help me get a handle on things,'' says the
Woodstock homemaker and mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison suffers from one of today's most common addictions _
stuff. The excess of the '90s, heaped by a lack of time for
organizing it, has snowballed into an avalanche of clutter that
leaves homeowners like her chronically frustrated. That is, until
this month when Harrison hired a professional organizer to help her
and her family get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a new person now,'' she says. ``It is such a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as consumers brace for Saturday's delivery of even more
``stuff'' while eyeing the new year as a time for changing habits,
masses of others will seek relief as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their biggest resolutions each New Year's are to get healthy
and to get their closet organized,'' says Jim Stockstill, a trainer
for the Container Store in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer is among a growing number of storage businesses
targeting the time-pressed consumer's weakness for disarray. And
for those too busy or too overwhelmed by organizational products to
shop, there are hundreds of experts willing to unravel a mess for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization industry is just booming,'' says Judith
Kolberg, president of the 50-member Georgia chapter of the National
Association of Professional Organizers. ``People are just wired to
the max and looking for an antidote for simplifying their lives.
There's also the recycling consciousness. People don't want to
waste anything _ and especially their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some professionals specialize in business organization, while
others concentrate on homes, says Kolberg, whose own niche is the
``chronically disorganized.''
</P>
<P>
   The pantry was the starting point when Harrison hired Charlotte
DeMarco to make sense of her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge walk-in pantry that had become a storehouse for
lots of toys, lots of kids' clothes _ everything but food,'' says
Harrison, whose children are 3 and 1. ``We couldn't find a thing in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco removed everything from the pantry and created labels
for organizing the shelves by category. She then placed tiered
units on the shelves so that the labels on all canned goods could
be seen. Baskets and a turkey basting pan became instant storage
bins. ``I didn't have to buy a plethora of things,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco moved seasonal housewares, such as Christmas and picnic
items, to a new home in cabinets over the fridge, the least
accessible yet most practical place for such seldom used things.
</P>
<P>
   By simply purging the pantry of other items, Harrison was left
with two large bags filled with garbage and two giant boxes of
giveaways. The job, which cost about $200 for seven hours of work,
also left her with a lesson she won't soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to organizing, DeMarco taught her to think of
every item in the house as either ``friend, acquaintance or
stranger.'' Friends are called on all the time, acquaintances are
needed only some of the time, while strangers aren't allowed in the
house. The message? Store each accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that,'' Harrison says. ``This morning, as I
walked through rooms, I started asking myself, `Do I really need
this anymore?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bedroom Closet
</P>
<P>
   One of the home's most disorganized areas is the bedroom closet,
so once in order, it provides a sense of satisfaction few can deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is make everything where you can see it and
access it easily,'' says Lance Stadmiller of California Closets in
Atlanta, which designs and installs storage systems. ``Once you
have a place for things, you don't have to think about it. You know
where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Organize a closet by:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taking inventory of everything you would like to store in the
closet. Separate items by season and store noncurrent ones in
another part of the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Donating articles you rarely wear to charity or storing them
in a box for a future garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Removing the clothes-hanging bars so that you can more easily
visualize the amount of space. Measure the floor-to-ceiling space
and, if adequate, install double-hung bars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Purchasing a storage system that can be reconfigured as your
needs change or if you move.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Protecting your belongings. ``A lot of people invest in
clothing but don't protect it,'' said Jim Stockstill of the
Container Store. Choose quality products that won't damage
clothing, such as plastic hangers, clear plastic shoe boxes,
tie/belt racks, hanging accessory organizers and pest-protection
items, including cedar blocks and sachets. &QR;  Storing
special-occasion shoes in clear boxes on high shelves to save space
for everyday wear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Standing purses upright between vertical shelf dividers so
they are easy to see and retain their shapes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taking advantage of space under the bed for long-term storage
of items, placed in clear containers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using the back of the door for hanging racks and bags for
shoes, belts, ties, scarves, jewelry and other accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Adding a trash can for holding dry-cleaning bags and wire
hangers.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen/Pantry
</P>
<P>
   No area contains more items than a kitchen, so don't let an
organization job there overwhelm you. Always start small, with a
drawer or cabinet, Stockstill says.
</P>
<P>
   Start by:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Considering one of the variety of storage systems on the
market for maximizing the space inside your cabinets and pantry.
The most practical ones can be expanded by adding shelves, drawers
and doors as needs change.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making spice jars easy to see by placing them on tiered units
on shelves. Spices tend to prefer a dark area, so don't leave
frequently used jars on counters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Placing a step stool in the pantry that can be hung on the
back of the door or wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using deep drawers for bulky potato chip bags or cereal boxes,
and shallow ones for napkins and placemats.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using turntables in hard-to-get-to corner cabinets and in
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing opened boxes of cereals and grains in clear containers
for saving space and avoiding bugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Repairing or discarding small appliances that are broken.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using dividers to organize utensils.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Placing tiered units on top shelves so that items can be seen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using vertical space in cabinets but not placing items on top
of things, such as stacks of plates. Instead, use racks to elevate
items.
</P>
<P>
   bathroom
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge in organizing a bathroom is counter space.
Maximize it by:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using jewelry trays and valets for holding keys and change.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing cosmetics in clear acrylic containers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Placing soaps, shampoos and conditioners in shower totes or on
wall racks attached with suction cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using rolling carts, wall-mounted racks and over-the-door
racks for holding toiletries.
</P>
<P>
   children's rooms
</P>
<P>
   Few things create more clutter than toys because kids rarely
return them to their neat boxes after playing with them. Make toy
storage fun by:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choosing brightly colored stackable bins for holding
odd-shaped toys.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing them in groups of like items.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Creating a bulletin board to which wooden cutouts and other
small items can be attached with Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Providing deep clear plastic chests.
</P>
<P>
   holiday items
</P>
<P>
   Who hasn't felt the frustration of untangling a string of
Christmas lights or wrestling with crumpled gift wrap? Avoid
compounding your holiday stress by:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing ornaments in compartmentalized bins and boxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wrapping tree lights around cardboard dividers and storing
them in a box.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing rolls of gift wrap, along with bows, ribbons, scissors
and tape, in a flat, compartmentalized box or plastic bin.
</P>
<P>
   10 TIPS TO GET ORGANIZED
</P>
<P>
   Here are some general tips for organizing your home, according
to the Container Store, Target, California Closets and the National
Association of Professional Organizers:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Edit belongings for items that can be thrown away, donated to
charity or sold in a garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decide which items need to be accessible and which can be
stored.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visibility, flexibility and accessibility are the keys to
storage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get in the habit of putting things away immediately and not
letting them stack up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Designate one central location in the house where all mail,
including bills, magazines and junk mail, can be sorted. Give all
family members a box, with their name labeled on it, for holding
their mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Throw out junk mail and magazines after tearing out anything
of interest for future reference.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create a tickler file for papers with dates and deadlines that
require attention later. Include files for each month and one
labeled ``current'' with dividers marked 1-31 for each day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get rid of any box, except for ones holding memorabilia and
keepsakes, that you haven't looked inside in two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're planning a yard sale, designate a box for collecting
the items.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get rid of clothes and accessories you haven't worn in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders and Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
