<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Dec. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exceptionally dry weather pattern will cover most of the
nation for the next several days. Unusually strong high pressure
centered near the Northwest coast will expand across the Plains
into the East suppressing moist air far to the south over southern
parts of Florida and the Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cold air will continue to spread gradually through the East
Coast states as breezes from the northwest import Canadian air.
Wednesday will begin with clouds near the coast from the Carolinas
to southern New England as low pressure moves quickly out to sea
off the Northeast coast. Patchy rain will linger much of the day
near the Middle Atlantic coast, but farther north, clouds will
break during the afternoon. Much of the interior Northeast will
have ample sun, although patchy clouds and snow showers will occur
near the eastern shores of the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   A moisture-starved disturbance will produce patches of clouds
and a few flurries near the central Mississippi Valley and northern
Ohio Valley. Otherwise, the Middle West will be dry and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will expand from the southern Rio Grande Valley to the
mountains of eastern New Mexico and western Texas. Patchy snow will
occur in the higher terrain, while a few light showers dampen lower
elevations. Farther north, areas of clouds and snow showers will
linger near the central and northern Rockies, particularly along
north-facing slopes. West of the Rockies, sunshine will be
plentiful as very strong high pressure remains nearly stationary
over the region.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Direct Connect &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 15 inches of snow fell Saturday at Yakutat, Alaska, as
a south-to-north channel of moisture originating over Hawaii
connected the two states. As a general rule, weather moves from
west to east, but, on occasion, particularly in winter, there are
transitions to patterns in which weather moves nearly parallel to
longitude lines rather than latitude lines. Such a pattern, with
cold air flowing far south and warm air far north, often results in
great storminess. Currently, however, there has been no potent
disturbance to touch off a chain of events leading up to a big
storm. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
