<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-PATENT-NAT     12-21 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-PATENT-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        Agencies get cyber 
 &HT;     By Tania Anderson and Jonathan Lipman  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 21 -- Two federal agencies launched online
databases Tuesday that are expected to make life easier for small
business owners. The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office is making it
easier to check progress on patents and the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corporation is making its survey of bank and thrift
deposits accessible in an online database.
</P>
<P>
   The Patent Application Information Retrieval (PAIR) system will
make it possible for applicants or their attorneys ``to get
up-to-the-minute information...without compromising the
confidentiality or security of pending or abandoned applications,''
a Commerce Department release said. Users will be able to download
information such as whether a filing date has been recorded, the
current status of the application, and the examiner's name and
contact information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our customers will appreciate the ease of using
PAIR as more and more of the agency's products and services become
available on the Internet,'' said Q. Todd Dickinson, Commissioner
of Patents and Trademarks, in the statement. ``It should be
particularly helpful to small businesses and small inventors as it
makes it more convenient to check the status of pending
applications,''
</P>
<P>
   Since patent data is private by law, businesses interested in
using the computer system will have to obtain free software from
the patent office in order to receive encrypted data from the PAIR
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation posted its most recent
deposit survey of all insured bank and savings institution offices
on http://www2.fdic.gov/sod. The FDIC's Summary of Deposits shows
the address of each of the more than 84,000 insured bank and
savings institution offices throughout the nation, plus the amount
of deposits reported by each office.
</P>
<P>
   The summary typically is used to evaluate market share for each
financial institution operating offices in any state, county or
city. Holding company market-share data at the state level also are
available. The website includes tables and graphs reflecting
aggregate national statistics for the industry, as well as data for
each state, county and metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   These online services come soon after the White House sent memos
to each federal agency head to make government information more
accessible on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has the potential to enhance civil society as
well as to boost commerce,'' said President Clinton in a statement.
``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
