<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POMPIDOU-CENTER-2TAKE     12-21 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POMPIDOU-CENTER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS' POMPIDOU CENTER UNEARTHS THE MUSEUM WITHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For its 20th birthday in 1997, the Georges Pompidou
Center got a much-needed paint job that made the polychromatic
neo-industrial building in eastern Paris look more like the
cultural fun palace it was designed to be. Then it shut down for 27
months to allow its insides to be torn apart and thoroughly
reorganized. Now, on the inevitable date of Jan. 1, France's most
visited arts institution finally reopens to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The results are impressive. Its permanent collection of modern
and contemporary art has been given 50 percent more space. The
public information library, one of its main attractions, has been
brought up to date and expanded. The main foyer has been
redesigned, and the basement has four theaters for dance, cinema
and theater. At long last, the center will even have a top-class
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying this ambitious $90 million makeover, a perhaps more
fundamental reflection has been taking place about the center's
future role. With some 150 million visitors in its first 20 years,
the Pompidou Center was undeniably a success, but its original
multifaceted mission was gradually lost in the crowds. Now its plan
is to reopen with a clearer purpose and a fresh creative spirit.
And perhaps fewer visitors.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is one likely consequence of denying free access
to its sixth-level glass-paneled viewing platform. Until 1997, 20
percent of the center's 8 million annual visitors _ in the main
foreign tourists _ rode the escalators up the outside of the
building to the platform for the sights. They spent nothing, saw no
art and added to wear-and-tear. ``The center had become a machine
for looking out at Paris,'' said its president, Jean-Jacques
Aillagon. ``Some tour operators even charged for the visit when it
was free.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in January, then, while admission to the center's
cavernous foyer will remain free to the public, admiring Paris from
the platform will require a $4.50 ticket. The view is intended as
bait to lure people to the fourth and fifth levels of the center,
where with the same ticket they can visit the National Museum of
Modern Art and its extraordinary collection of 20th-century works.
In fact, a crucial objective of the ``new'' center is to focus
attention on that museum.
</P>
<P>
   It has been housed in the center since 1977, but its name is
little known (and often confused with the Museum of Modern Art of
the City of Paris in the Palais de Tokyo), and its identity has
been obscured by that of the center, which is in turn widely known
in Paris as the Beaubourg (the name of one street that runs by it).
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the museum does not have a single iconic work, like
``Mona Lisa,'' to ensure its automatic inclusion on bus tours of
Paris. Thus while the center always draws good crowds to its
temporary shows (``Matisse'' in 1993 attracted 735,000 visitors),
the museum has been surprisingly overlooked, with just 700,000
visitors annually compared with 6 million or so for the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the center is not about to abandon blockbusters.
So ``Picasso Sculptor'' will be a major exhibition from June 7 to
Sept. 25, ``The Pop Years'' is planned for early 2001, and a
Dubuffet retrospective will open in the summer of 2001. Also on the
schedule are smaller shows dedicated to the photography of Nan
Goldin, the architecture of Jean Nouvel and the artworks of Daniel
Buren.
</P>
<P>
   To Werner Spies, the museum's director, its 20th-century art is
matched only by that of the Museum of Modern Art in New York. And
if in the past it was not always presented as a living collection,
its reorganization, he says, should now make it more appealing to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reopening of the Pompidou Center is perhaps the true birth
of the museum because never before has our collection been seen
with such impact,'' said Spies, who has supervised the display of
some 1,600 works from the museum's 45,000-piece collection. ``In
the past, there were people who didn't even know there was a museum
here. I would hope that the Pompidou Center will now become
synonymous with the National Museum of Modern Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Spies has done his bit. Until 1997, people taking the escalator
to temporary shows or to the viewing platform on the sixth level
could enter the museum on the fifth level. Then they visited the
modern galleries, which show art from 1905 to 1960, but rarely
bothered to include the contemporary collection, covering the
period since 1960, on the fourth level.
</P>
<P>
   Now the museum's entrance is on the fourth level, leading
visitors first to the contemporary collection, starting with Jean
Tinguely's ``Requiem for a Dead Leaf,'' Claes Oldenberg's ``Giant
Ice Bag'' and Warhol's ``10 Times Liz.'' ``In the past, people
didn't go down to the contemporary galleries,'' Spies said. ``In
museums, it's a bit pejorative to go  &UR; down &LR; . Now they climb toward
jubilation.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before they do, however, the expanded contemporary floor looks
better than ever, with some rooms dedicated to such key movements
as Pop Art, Arte Povera, Op Art, Fluxus and the like, and others to
individual artists, among them Beuys, Dubuffet, Gerhard Richter,
Christian Boltanski and Annette Messager. And for the first time,
design and architecture are treated as contemporary art. Over the
last two years, the museum has also bought works by Oldenberg, Ms.
Messager, Sophie Calle, Christo and others.
</P>
<P>
   The staircase to the modern galleries on the fifth level ends at
Picasso's sculpture ``Little Girl Skipping Rope'' and Le Douanier
Rousseau's painting ``La Guerre.'' Dozens of galleries then lead
off a broad ``avenue'' that runs the length of the building, again
with some dedicated to movements, starting with Fauvism and Cubism,
and others highlighting and contrasting works by 20th-century
masters, from Picasso, Braque, Brancusi, Kandinsky and Matisse to
Miro, Dali and Max Ernst. Picasso's ``Mercure,'' a large painting
on cloth, has been restored for the occasion, and Francis Picabia's
``Dresseur d'Animaux'' is among the new acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Another novelty is that the museum's contemporary display will
be rehung every 18 months and its modern galleries every year, both
to make use of its vast stored collection and to create mini-shows
of different artists or movements. Two new fourth-level spaces, the
Museum Gallery and the Graphic Art Gallery, will feature individual
artists or special projects. Yet another space will house the
museum's new media collection.
</P>
<P>
   Below the museum, with all administration offices moved to an
adjacent building, two entire floors are now given over to the
public information library, which remains open to the public
without charge and has traditionally accounted for 40 percent of
visits to the Pompidou Center. In hindsight, this is perhaps a
strange place to put a library, but it was part of French President
Georges Pompidou's idea of founding a multicultural institution
with an interdisciplinary vocation. And the written word was
included.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, however, interdisciplinary activities faltered.
There was cinema, dance, theater, architecture, industrial design,
music (through the Institute of Research and Coordination of
Acoustic Music, better known as Ircam) and of course the visual
arts, but each went its own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived here four years ago, the center had become a
`cultural hotel' in which each art form locked itself in its own
room,'' Aillagon recalled. ``I remember saying, `If you're just
going to share a building, you might do well to plan your own
buildings.'''
</P>
<P>
   With the reopening, then, Aillagon has used his position as
president not only of the center but also of the library and Ircam
to promote cross-fertilization of the arts, something other museums
are trying (the Louvre, for example, now has theater, concert and
movie programs) and the Pompidou Center is already well equipped
for.
</P>
<P>
   For the center's first temporary show, ``Le Temps, Vite,'' an
exhibition about time that runs Jan. 13 through April 17, German
composer Heiner Goebbels has been commissioned to write a score to
accompany visitors, while Ircam will echo the show's theme in six
concerts. In addition some 50 writers will participate in a public
reading of Proust's ``Remembrance of Things Past.''
</P>
<P>
   With space for temporary shows now available in three galleries
on the sixth level, two on the fourth level and one on the first
level, the center will also be able to present very different
exhibitions at the same time with the hope that visitors will be
encouraged to pass from drawings to architecture, from sculpture to
video art. And to remind readers where they are, large sculptures
by Frank Stella and Dubuffet are being stationed at the entrance to
the library.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, then, as it comes of age, the Pompidou Center as a
whole is starting life afresh. During its first 20 years it not
only helped gentrify the surrounding neighborhoods of Les Halles
and Le Marais, with its sloping plaza alive with street performers
and artists, but it also encouraged other European cultural
institutions to diversify their approach to the arts. Now it wants
to return to its founding principles and demonstrate that it is
still a pioneer. It may remain the Beaubourg to Parisians, but in
the future it wants to be known as a museum with a difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ISRAEL-MILLENNIUM-122     12-21 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MILLENNIUM-1222-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEELINGS MIXED IN ISRAEL ABOUT HOSTING MILLENNIUM
 &HT;    750 and adds
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM_ This is the year 5760 according to the Jewish
calendar. But, the Jewish state finds itself playing the ambivalent
host to the Christian millennium.
</P>
<P>
   As one rabbi puts it, Israelis feel like they are letting
outsiders use their house for a party they do not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any discussion in Israel about what the
millennium means to Christians,'' said Rabbi Donniel(cq) Hartman,
an advocate of religious pluralism at the Shalom Hartman Institute
in Jerusalem. ``The whole country has just sort of been asleep
about the whole issue. Just not even there. And our preparation
shows as a result of it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than $90 million worth of preparations _ paving roads and
walkways, building new police stations, adding security cameras _
are still underway to accommodate expected crowds at tourist sites.
Still, tourism industry officials criticize Israel's preparation as
sluggish. And at one point the country's religious affairs ministry
asked hotels to keep Christmas trees, the most recognizable image
of the Christian holiday season, behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Christians want to remind the Israelis that their country
includes many of Christianity's holiest sites. Jerusalem's Church
of the Holy Sepulcher is where many believe Christ was crucified.
Nazareth's Basilica of the Annunciation is where it is believed an
angel informed the Virgin Mary she would give birth to Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Christians urge Israelis to face up to their obligations as the
keeper of these holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Father Peter Vasko, a member of the Franciscan board that
oversees holy sites in the Middle East, takes exception with
Hartman's party-in-the-house analogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity is part and parcel of this land, whether people
like it or not,'' said Vasko, once a travel agency executive in
Atlanta. ``It's not just their house. It's the house of Christians,
too. It is shared by both.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone poll of 479 people conducted by Gallup Israel two
weeks ago and released Tuesday showed that Jewish Israelis know
little about Christianity. The margin of error was plus or minus
4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only 27.2 percent knew that Dec. 25 was a date of significance
and 44.1 percent said Dec. 31 this year has no special meaning to
them.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, most American Christians probably could not
recognize the date of a Jewish holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, as on most issues, Israelis are split about the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The majority lead secular lives and are indifferent or
unbothered by the turn of the western Gregorian calendar, which
many of them follow.
</P>
<P>
   Though New Years Eve falls on the Friday night sabbath, when
most stores and restaurants must stay closed, there are parties
planned in the cork-popping, midnight-kissing traditions of the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Most Israelis view the millennium as at least mildly interesting
and a boon to tourism in a sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important, but it's interesting,'' said Israeli Ike
Kedm(cq), 54, a labor union treasurer in Jerusalem. ``If you don't
have a lot of tourists, the city starts to get boring.''
</P>
<P>
   But, there have been cries of concern from leaders of the
ultra-Orthodox Jewish community, comprising about 10 percent of the
country. They stress the historically rough relationship between
Christians and Jews. They are suspicious about the missionary
intentions of Christians coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Yaakov Sabag, kosher supervisor for the Ministry of Religious
Affairs, which issued the Christmas tree ruling, said trees in
public could conjure up images of the violent Holy Land Crusades of
the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   A Christmas tree, Sabag told Cox Newspapers, would hurt an
Israeli's feelings, ``like the Swastika hurts peoples' feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the anticipation that cities display when hosting
a Super Bowl or Olympics, decorations for the millennium seem
light. There are banners stating ``Welcome to Jerusalem 2000'' on
street lights in Jerusalem, but little other fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The media focus has been on security concerns about Christian
fanatics. There has been little written about the significance the
millennium holds for the vast majority of the peaceful pilgrims
expected.
</P>
<P>
   What Rabbi Hartman calls Israel's ``polite silence'' is
accentuated by the festivities next door in areas controlled by the
Palestinian Authority. Palestinian President Yasser Arafat has
himself been involved in planning the celebrations taking place in
Bethlehem, which is located in a Palestinian-controlled sector of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his opening address to the parliament in July, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak could not have made the millennial ambivalence
any clearer, as he awkwardly tried to draw on some millennial
inspiration: ``In the entire world, there is great anticipation of
the coming millennium. The Hebrew calendar does not recognize this,
and for most of us the change of date between 31 December and 1
January is not a day of celebration. But we are part of the world,
and this new government will cross the line into the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials maintain that they are making all the
necessary preparations, but that the celebrations are not their
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a state event. It's a Christian religious event,''
said Uri Mor, the Israeli government's liaison with Christian
communities. ``The Christian community directs the events. The
government takes it on its shoulders to help implement the event.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Jewish state includes more than 100,000 Christian
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, they will be supplemented by Christians who are
expected to make up the bulk of the 3.2 million visitors to the
country _ almost 30 percent more than the previous high. One
expected visitor is Pope John Paul II, planning his first visit in
March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poll released Tuesday showed that about 53 percent of
Israelis view that visit positively.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based International Fellowship of Christians and
Jews, a group that raises money for Israeli Jewish charities,
sponsored the poll. The group's leaders stressed that most Israelis
think this year's influx of visitors will help Israel ``prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   But, 16.7 percent Israelis said that the more American
Christians coming to visit, ``the bigger the threat posed to
Israel's Jewish character.'' That number was heavily weighted by
respondents who considered themselves ultra-Orthodox, a significant
share of the population of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, Israel office director of the Anti-Defamation
League, said ultra-Orthodox Israelis tend to focus more on history
than other Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But, he decried a nearly complete lack of Christian studies in
the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   That has slowed Jewish-Christian understanding, he said, and it
is showing up in Israeli ignorance about Christianity at the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little understanding of the practices and
teachings,'' he said. ``The year 2000 is a great opportunity to
start the process of righting the wounds of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
