country. They stress the historically rough relationship between
Christians and Jews. They are suspicious about the missionary
intentions of Christians coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Yaakov Sabag, kosher supervisor for the Ministry of Religious
Affairs, which issued the Christmas tree ruling, said trees in
public could conjure up images of the violent Holy Land Crusades of
the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   A Christmas tree, Sabag told Cox Newspapers, would hurt an
Israeli's feelings, ``like the Swastika hurts peoples' feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the anticipation that cities display when hosting
a Super Bowl or Olympics, decorations for the millennium seem
light. There are banners stating ``Welcome to Jerusalem 2000'' on
street lights in Jerusalem, but little other fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The media focus has been on security concerns about Christian
fanatics. There has been little written about the significance the
millennium holds for the vast majority of the peaceful pilgrims
expected.
</P>
<P>
   What Rabbi Hartman calls Israel's ``polite silence'' is
accentuated by the festivities next door in areas controlled by the
Palestinian Authority. Palestinian President Yasser Arafat has
himself been involved in planning the celebrations taking place in
Bethlehem, which is located in a Palestinian-controlled sector of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his opening address to the parliament in July, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak could not have made the millennial ambivalence
any clearer, as he awkwardly tried to draw on some millennial
inspiration: ``In the entire world, there is great anticipation of
the coming millennium. The Hebrew calendar does not recognize this,
and for most of us the change of date between 31 December and 1
January is not a day of celebration. But we are part of the world,
and this new government will cross the line into the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials maintain that they are making all the
necessary preparations, but that the celebrations are not their
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a state event. It's a Christian religious event,''
said Uri Mor, the Israeli government's liaison with Christian
communities. ``The Christian community directs the events. The
government takes it on its shoulders to help implement the event.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Jewish state includes more than 100,000 Christian
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, they will be supplemented by Christians who are
expected to make up the bulk of the 3.2 million visitors to the
country _ almost 30 percent more than the previous high. One
expected visitor is Pope John Paul II, planning his first visit in
March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poll released Tuesday showed that about 53 percent of
Israelis view that visit positively.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based International Fellowship of Christians and
Jews, a group that raises money for Israeli Jewish charities,
sponsored the poll. The group's leaders stressed that most Israelis
think this year's influx of visitors will help Israel ``prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   But, 16.7 percent Israelis said that the more American
Christians coming to visit, ``the bigger the threat posed to
Israel's Jewish character.'' That number was heavily weighted by
respondents who considered themselves ultra-Orthodox, a significant
share of the population of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, Israel office director of the Anti-Defamation
League, said ultra-Orthodox Israelis tend to focus more on history
than other Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But, he decried a nearly complete lack of Christian studies in
the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   That has slowed Jewish-Christian understanding, he said, and it
is showing up in Israeli ignorance about Christianity at the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little understanding of the practices and
teachings,'' he said. ``The year 2000 is a great opportunity to
start the process of righting the wounds of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
