<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx14;  BC-MOON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-21 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'MAN ON THE MOON': EXPLORING THE OUTER LIMITS OF AN ODD COMEDIC
UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Kaufman's mind games with his audiences played on an
element of the unknown. Whether he was treating everyone in
Carnegie Hall to milk and cookies or spewing abuse in his corrosive
Tony Clifton mode, it was crucial that the viewer never know
whether to laugh or squirm. Kaufman's precocious genius for ironic
detachment seemed extreme, to the point where his death in 1984
struck even his loved ones as a possible put-on. But time has
turned Kaufman into a hugely influential avatar of confrontational
comedy. Jim Carrey, to name just one spiritual descendant, would
not be possible without him.
</P>
<P>
   Now Carrey delivers an electrifying homage in ``Man on the
Moon,'' Milos Forman's vivid re-creation of Kaufman's too-short and
enduringly strange career. (The film takes its title from R.E.M.'s
ghostly musical tribute to the Kaufman spirit.) In a film that
summons its subject's most memorable creative inventions as a
series of greatest hits, Carrey makes a flawless, uncanny
impersonator. It's all here: the timid, wide-eyed Foreign Man, the
sneering wrestling matches with women, the reading of ``The Great
Gatsby'' in its entirety to a dumbfounded college audience, the
priceless pantomime of the ``Mighty Mouse'' theme song.
</P>
<P>
   But what is missing here, though it might have been the first
thing expected from an ostensible film biography, is an answer to
the simplest question: Who was Andy Kaufman, and how did he get
that way? ``Man on the Moon,'' which takes the form of a
surprisingly straightforward show business rise-and-fall story,
isn't telling. Whether this is a strictly artistic choice or an
indication that the generous treatment of Kaufman's agent,
girlfriend and immediate family make this a somewhat authorized
version, it limits the film's ability to give Kaufman three
dimensions. That's a dramatic liability even if you believe, as
perhaps the filmmakers do, that Kaufman was no more of a cipher to
audiences than he was to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' is another big, vibrant collaboration
between Forman and the screenwriters Scott Alexander and Larry
Karaszewski. Together they brilliantly evoked the world of ``The
People vs. Larry Flynt'' in all its absurdity and unlikely
gravitas. But their new film remains more opaque, perhaps because
Kaufman was such a self-conscious figure in the first place. Unlike
Flynt or Ed Wood (whom the writers also summoned so wonderfully in
Tim Burton's film), Kaufman does not offer the creative leeway of
an unexamined life.
</P>
<P>
   Hamstrung as it may be, ``Man on the Moon'' is still a
formidable piece of work. As it dutifully revisits the milestones
of the Kaufman career, the film benefits enormously from Carrey's
way of channeling his character.
</P>
<P>
   Artfully distilled, the Kaufman happenings (that's what they
were) are rendered faithfully yet made tighter and funnier. Without
losing Kaufman's penchant for letting an audience twist in the
wind, Carrey adds his own stamp to the material by making it
brighter.
</P>
<P>
   Fleshing out the story of how Kaufman progressed from a
middle-class upbringing in Great Neck, N.Y., to the crowd-baiting
outer limits of the comedy frontier, the film needs to give him a
succession of sounding boards. These include Danny DeVito (one of
the film's producers) as the agent George Shapiro, who is given a
``Eureka!'' moment when he is first made privy to a Kaufman put-on,
and who later becomes Kaufman's staunch protector.
</P>
<P>
   Also used here in a similar capacity is Bob Zmuda (played
likably by Paul Giamatti), the writing partner and co-conspirator
who helped Kaufman create his boorish lounge-act alter ego, Tony
Clifton. The unapologetic ugliness and aggression of the Clifton
character is, like Kaufman's avid delight in wrestling women
(Courtney Love appears as one of them), a kink that the film leaves
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Man on the Moon'' is rated R. It includes profanity
and sexual situations involving prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   MAN ON THE MOON
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Milos Forman; written by Scott Alexander and Larry
Karaszewski; director of photography, Anastas Michos; edited by
Christopher Tellefsen and Lynzee Klingman; music by R.E.M.;
production designer, Patrizia Von Brandenstein; produced by Danny
DeVito, Michael Shamberg and Stacey Sher; released by Universal
Pictures. Running time: 118 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jim Carrey (Andy Kaufman), Danny DeVito (George Shapiro),
Courtney Love (Lynne Margulies) and Paul Giamatti (Bob Zmuda).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FULL-MOON-HNS &LR;      12-21 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FULL-MOON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FULL MOON BREEDS PREDICTIONS OF GLOOM, DOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The world probably won't end Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the sky should be a bit brighter, and the Earth's
inhabitants may act a little goofier.
</P>
<P>
   While some police officers, ambulance medics, bartenders and
cabbies swear it is true, there is little scientific evidence to
support the common belief that people really are crazier during a
full moon.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sun, moon and Earth are in a rare alignment, unseen
since 1866, it will be one of the brightest when an unusual amount
of sunlight will be cast on the lunar surface Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could count how many arrests we make,'' said Officer
Sherman Ackerson of the San Francisco police. ``It would be
interesting if it makes the jails fill up.''
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of years, the full moon has been said to influence
human and animal behavior. It has been linked to everything from
sleepwalking and sexual potency to seizures and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the full moon has reputedly increased the number
of murders, robberies, bar brawls and car crashes. That notion has
been repeated by word of mouth, amplified by the Internet and
supported by at least one 1978 book, ``The Lunar Effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout history there has been this notion that the moon
can make you crazy,'' said Alan Dundes, an anthropologist, folklore
expert and professor at the University of California at Berkeley.
``The only real evidence is that if you keep repeating that a
certain thing makes you act crazy, then it probably will. The power
of suggestion is effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the moon could toy with the human mind was first
recorded in the latter years of the Roman Empire, when many people
maintained that worshipers of the moon goddess Luna were insane.
That led to the word ``lunatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the police, emergency workers and others who see aberrant
behavior up close, the ``lunar lunacy'' is an axiom that is often
repeated but never proved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it the werewolf effect,'' Ackerson said. ``When I
started out as a cop 27 years ago, everyone said a full moon was
always the worst night _ that everyone acts a little crazier than
usual. I never saw proof, but a lot of people who work the street
assume there is some truth to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The superstition about the full moon is not just limited to
emergency workers in California. In a database search on the topic,
constables and 911 dispatchers were quoted saying similar things in
newspapers from Scotland to Singapore and India to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   But there also are a lot of skeptics on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an urban myth,'' said David Fleming, an assistant nursing
manager at San Francisco General Hospital, who works the swing
shift in the emergency room. ``It's a great story, fascinating for
conversation. But I've never seen a study that backs it up.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes his own.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming recently looked at hospital admissions records on full
moon nights and compared them to other shifts that were similar in
every aspect _ except the lunar cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full moons really don't show an increase in the number of
people we see in emergency rooms,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   Several researchers agree with Fleming. More than one report
suggests that people are more likely to remember a full moon than a
crescent one.
</P>
<P>
   So if a killing were to take place when the moon is a
fog-shrouded sliver, the theory goes, no one would take note. But
police officers called out to a crime scene under a clear, full
moon, might note that detail in their nightly log or talk about it
in the squad room.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the full moon becomes associated with the crime, even
though similar events occur at other times of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's moon should be one to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be able to read by the light of the moon if it
isn't cloudy,'' said Bob Strom, a scientist at the Lunar and
Planetary Institute in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   For about 10 hours beginning around 4:15 p.m., the Earth will be
at its closest point to the sun and the moon. The result will be an
unusually bright full moon, made so because it reflects so much
light from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The moon becomes full every 29.5 days. This month's full moon
happens to fall on the Northern Hemisphere's winter solstice, the
longest night of the year. It's an event that happens on the winter
solstice only once every 19 years. It puts the moon 17,000 miles
closer than its average distance of 230,000 miles during its
off-center orbit of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Earth is also nearing its closest approach to the sun. The
Earth will make its closest pass to the sun, 91.4 million miles, on
Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Those stellar pieces have not fallen into place like that for
133 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 21, 1866, under the full, bright moon, the Oglala Sioux
lured U.S. Army troops into a deadly trap in what was then the
Idaho Territory. The Sioux, led by Crazy Horse, surrounded and
killed all 80 soldiers in what became known as Fetterman's
Massacre, after commanding officer Capt. William Fetterman. Next to
Little Big Horn, it was perhaps the biggest defeat suffered by U.S.
troops in frontier days.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe some of the e-mails circulating cyberspace,
Wednesday night to early Thursday could have even bloodier portent
than Fetterman's Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   But then some of these same folks probably believe that the
world's going to end on New Year's Day 2000 as well.
</P>
<P>
   There were those predictions on Friday, March 13, 1998. That
Friday the 13th coincided with a full moon and a lunar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the world did not come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does (Wednesday), call me back for a quote,'' laughed
Dundes, who has written a half-dozen books on folklore and urban
myths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
