<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-MARKETING-ART-NY     12-21 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-MARKETING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN VOUVRAY IS `MELLOW YELLOW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 10-page wine list at Maritime, a new Manhattan seafood
restaurant, includes a Chassagne-Montrachet Morgeot, an Hommage
cabernet from Clos Pegase, a Grande Cuvee Krug. These fine wines,
priced from $60 to $200, appear under the headings ``The Light Red
District'' ``Red Hot Mamas'' and ``Et Tu, Brut.''
</P>
<P>
   Perusing the list at Fressen, wine drinkers are presented with
groupings like ``Mellow Yellow'' and ``Heaven Scent.'' And at
Thalia, the categories read like excerpts from the Wine Spectator:
``Sophisticated, chic with depth and passion. ...''
</P>
<P>
   What ever happened to Red/White, France/Italy,
Burgundy/Bordeaux? At many New York restaurants the old
color-country-region system has been dumped in favor of oenophile
lingo, cute gimmicks and bad puns.
</P>
<P>
   Just as stuffy sommeliers have been replaced by 20-something
``wine guys'' who tell you that a 1995 Barolo  &UR; rocks,  &LR; wine lists
have undergone a makeover. In some cases (Union Square Cafe), this
means the convenience of wines listed by style and weight for
today's more curious, knowledgeable customers. Elsewhere, the new
lists get goofier and, in some cases, end up sounding even more
obscure and pretentious than the old.
</P>
<P>
   The new lists want to  &UR; evoke,  &LR; to  &UR; relate  &LR; to customers in a way
that might make a traditionalist wince.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to move wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selling lots of pigato from Liguria,'' said Jerri Banks,
the beverage director at Fressen, who put this full-bodied Italian
white alongside an Austrian furmint and a Menetou-Salon from the
Loire Valley under Seafood Specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to lighten it up more,'' said Ms. Banks, who has
been in the wine business for 22 years, including a stint at Cellar
in the Sky. ``Groups of young women giggle their way through the
list.''
</P>
<P>
   That a high priestess from this temple to the grape, which
specialized in hard-to-find wines, should now be doing a rock 'n'
roll wine list in the meatpacking district suggests a new era when
wine, like everything else in life, is being marketed within an
inch of its shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency of the average American wine drinker is to order a
wine he or she has heard of, Ms. Banks said. The thinking behind
rewriting wine lists by style of wine or according to what foods
they will compatibly wash down is to get people to sample, say, a
South African shiraz or Oregon gamay that might have scared them
before.
</P>
<P>
   The movement to demystify the complexities of wine has taken
some restaurateurs and wine consultants to the opposite extreme: a
sort of ``Wine for Dummies'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Best Cellars chain of wine stores has reduced its entire
stock to eight adjectives: fizzy, fresh, soft, luscious, juicy,
smooth, big or sweet. The stores take user-friendliness to new
highs (or lows) by limiting their selections to about 100 wines,
almost all under $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is so tradition-bound that most people who work in the
business have a hard time imagining it classified any other way
than by grape type or country of origin,'' said Joshua Wesson, one
of the founders of Best Cellars, which has expanded from its base
in Manhattan to Boston and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Wesson, who says he is registering these adjectives as
trademarks, has licensed them to the Xando chain of coffee and wine
bars. Rammy Harwood, national marketing manager at Xando Cosi Inc.,
said wine sales were up sixfold since it licensed Best Cellars'
labels seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The way Harwood sees it, ``If I go in and say, `I want a bold
wine' and I see `bold' on the menu, it makes it a lot easier. It's
educational.'' Previously, wine was not even on the Xando menu. It
appeared on cardboard ``table tents,'' Harwood said, and the
selection consisted of ``a couple of reds and a couple of whites.''
</P>
<P>
   To aid the educational process, little icons appear on the Xando
menu. Next to ``luscious'' (a Cartlidge &AMP; Browne chardonnay) is a
pair of lips. There's a lollipop next to the port and sherry, which
are described as ``sweet'' _ once a banned word in wine circles, in
favor of the more elegant-sounding ``fruity.''
</P>
<P>
   The new generation of wine guy sees his simple adjectives and
icons as the antidote to generations of snobbery. The manager at
Maritime, Andrew Newhouser, unabashedly declares: ``Wine is grape
juice. It's grape juice! I've never understood this huge mystique
behind it. It should be a lot more easy and fun than people make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouser attributes his whimsical list with its Rubenesque Reds
and Pisces Meets Libra whites to Ted Davidson, the former sommelier
at Maritime, who was, he said, ``a very whimsical guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much whimsy, though, can be as unhelpful as too little.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Olson, a wine consultant and self-described ``wine geek,''
who devised the list for Typhoon Brewery, said he has seen wines
described on menus as ``sexy'' and ``obtuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine language has ``evolved to the point now where some of it is
pretty trite and doesn't work,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early rebels was Daniel Johnnes, the wine director at
Montrachet and for Drew Nieporent's Myriad Restaurant Group.
Montrachet's collection, which includes a vast repository of
Burgundies, is listed the old-fashioned way, by country and then by
region.
</P>
<P>
   But when Layla opened five years ago, Johnnes made ``What would
be the best wine if you were stuck in the desert?'' a category.
</P>
<P>
   Anything to ``encourage a dialogue with the consumer,'' Johnnes
said. Most diners, he pointed out, still read the wine list from
right to left. And frugal readers will notice new euphemisms for
expensive and cheap.
</P>
<P>
   At Fressen, if the wine costs more than $60, it falls into the
``classic'' category. At Quantum, a new place in Manhattan that
bills itself as a ``progressive American restaurant,'' the words
``Light and Crisp'' introduce the relatively inexpensive rieslings
and pinot grigios, whereas the ``Rich, Full and Classic'' reds
include $80 cabernets and a $212 Pomerol.
</P>
<P>
   If you're unwilling to have your wallet rocked by a classic,
there's always the Homer Simpson method: just order the
second-least-expensive bottle on the menu and hope you get lucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
