<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NUTCRACKER-BALLET-REV     12-21 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTCRACKER-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NUTCRACKER': RITE OF PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dancing the three lead roles in George Balanchine's
production of ``The Nutcracker'' can be a rite of passage at the
New York City Ballet, and such was the case at the Saturday and
Sunday matinees.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Janie Taylor brought her usual endearing spunkiness
to the demanding choreography of Dewdrop. Nerves did not diminish
the beauty of her fully shaped dancing, held arabesques and
controlled abandon.
</P>
<P>
   In other newly acquired roles on Saturday, Antonio Carmena
balanced the exotic acrobatics of the Tea divertissement with humor
and an easy, expansive attack. Jeroen Hofmans looked perfectly at
home with the prances and jumps, some through hoops, in the Candy
Cane divertissement. And Eva Natanya glowed graciously in ``Hot
Chocolate,'' performed with Jason Fowler. Yvonne Borree and Peter
Boal were the Sugarplum Fairy and Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastien Marcovici took on the role of the Cavalier on Sunday
afternoon. Watching the ballet's culminating grand pas de deux,
performed with Jenifer Ringer, was a terrifying experience.
Marcovici has a uniquely lush, almost lupine quality. But the
Cavalier demands clean classical dancing and strong, confident
partnering. Neither was forthcoming, and Ms. Ringer deserves a
medal for valor.
</P>
<P>
   She was a first-rate Sugarplum Fairy, blending musical phrasing,
a keen sense of dramatic detail and a radiant aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's child leads were among the best in a long time. Zakary
Yermolenko's Little Prince was a touchingly solemn, well-mannered
boy who seemed far older than his years but who came into his own
in miming that was elegantly larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Score made Marie a sweet-natured girl with unexpected
gumption and an amusingly mouselike walk. And Shimon Ito's Fritz
was such a lovably eager, pensive and naughty child that one wanted
to pluck him offstage and bring him home as a stocking-stuffer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1751EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
