<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JUILLIARD-COMMERCIALS     12-21 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUILLIARD-COMMERCIALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SYMPHONY OF CLASSICISM AND MAD AVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICE D. SAMUELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Grace Huang, a 23-year-old viola student at the
Juilliard School, was chatting with two classmates and a professor
in Room 524 recently about her latest composition: a jazzy score to
a mock television commercial for Ethan Allen, the furniture maker
and retailer.
</P>
<P>
   A classical musician studying TV commercials? At Juilliard?
</P>
<P>
   As recently as five years ago, a class on how to score
commercials and film would not have been offered at the prestigious
school, which trains top-flight classical musicians. These days,
however, what was once the domain of Madison Avenue jingle writers
has become an outlet of musical expression, and income, for the
most talented young musicians in every genre of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so much fun is that the kids come into class and
discover parts of their musical personality,'' said Edward Bilous,
a composer who began teaching the course at Juilliard three years
ago. ``By the end of each year, a few students are considering a
whole new life path.''
</P>
<P>
   Even composers, who used to shun commercials as an enterprise
too crass for their art, are being drawn to them. Michelle DiBucci,
38, a classical composer and teacher of music theory at Juilliard,
for example, gave up waiting tables at night and made the leap to
television commercials as a way to support her opera compositions,
both financially and, she says, artistically.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last eight years, Ms. DiBucci has written commercials
for sponsors ranging from the Olive Garden restaurants to Nissan to
New Jersey Transit. She often meets with the client and composes
and produces a commercial in less than a week, earning more in a
few days that she does in six months with a classical commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do I earn money,'' she said. ``I work with the best
musicians in the world and get inspirations for my operas.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, inspiration for operas from supervising the production of a
commercial. For the snappy, often sappy jingle of the past has been
replaced with sophisticated scores to express the mood and energy
the advertiser wants to project. In a Cachet perfume commercial,
for example, Ms. DiBucci mixed the sounds of a Japanese shakuhachi,
or flute, as well as a Lebanese tambourine, a classical cello, an
Indian vocalist and electronic music to illustrate morphing
animated images of women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DiBucci was lucky: Prince Matchabelli, which makes Cachet,
had a rich budget of $2.5 million for this commercial, allowing her
to bring performers together. More typically, scores these days are
produced by computers and synthesizers.
</P>
<P>
   That is the unhappy flip side of the new opportunities for
composers: The explosion of electronic music, combined with a
growing use of golden oldies and other previously released music,
has decimated the livelihood of the studio musician who once made a
living performing for commercial scores.
</P>
<P>
   With studio jobs disappearing, young performers like Ms. Huang
are increasingly looking for work in commercials as a higher-paying
alternative to giving private lessons or waiting tables.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, four members of Bilous' scoring class formed a
production company, Trifecta Music for Film. They will have plenty
of competition; according to Theresa Piti, managing editor of The
Shoot Directory, a trade publication, the number of such houses has
grown from a handful in the early 1980s to an estimated 600 today.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of cable television stations and the Internet
revolution have created the advertising boom that is fueling that
growth. At the same time, the availability of cheap recording
equipment has lowered the economic barriers to entering the
industry for classical musicians, not known for having lots of cash
on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   As opportunities have opened up and old ones have vanished, a
jack-of-all-trades mentality is taking hold among many classical
musicians. Younger performers who grew up on pop music don't view
it as an inferior art form and are less willing to limit their
careers to academia. ``Composers no longer want to write just for
other composers and colleges,'' said Frances Richard, vice
president for concert music at the American Society of Composers,
Authors and Publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rice, 32, a bass player with a master's degree in
orchestral performance from the Manhattan School of Music, said,
``For me right now, it is all about adapting.'' He earns a living
playing reggae music and its predecessor, ska, three nights a week
in downtown Manhattan clubs like the Knitting Factory and the
Cooler. He also spends hours each week at Cliff Schwarz Music
Production as an unpaid intern designing audio and sound effects
for TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Appleton, 32, is one of the army of beeper-clad musicians
making ends meet with a melange of freelance jobs. A guitarist with
his own band, he has produced CDs for Nickelodeon and American
Express, created music for Web sites and produced the sound effects
for a CD-Rom soccer game. ``Until recently no one thought of
putting sound on the Internet,'' he said. ``It was the silent movie
of the computer age.'' So far, however, the most he has earned on a
single project was $5,000, and that was a flat fee, with no
provision for royalties.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change. Marc Morgenstern, executive vice
president of Ascap, said 1,500 Web sites had registered with the
trade group, indicating that the Internet could become a major new
stream of royalty revenues for composers and artists.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Subotnick, a composer, lecturer and revered
electronic-music guru, say he believes the Internet is the
profession's future. Subotnick recently developed a software
program called Making Music that allows children to create
compositions on the computer, and he is developing a Web site for
the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you had to drive a taxi, or at best give
private lessons,'' he said of classical composers. ``Now the
opportunities are so great, you can put together a living through
music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
