<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-BRESSON-2TAKES-A     12-21 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BRESSON-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BRESSON, MOVIE DIRECTOR, DIES IN PARIS AT 98 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Robert Bresson, the acclaimed French movie director
whose best-known films, among them ``Diary of a Country Priest''
and ``Pickpocket,'' reflected a strongly aesthetic and spiritual
approach to cinema, died on Saturday. He was 98 and lived in Paris.
He made his last film in 1983 and had been unwell for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson, a slim man with a shock of white hair that made him
immediately recognizable, was very much a loner, keeping aloof from
both fellow directors and journalists, interested neither in
becoming a celebrity nor in following cinematic fashion. Rather, he
pursued his own vision slowly and meticulously, making just 13
films in a 40-year career. But they earned him a special place in
cinema history.
</P>
<P>
   In visual terms, his films were often described as ``purist''
because he tried to reduce his images to almost abstract
simplicity, stripping them of all sentimentality. When possible, he
avoided using professional actors, or at least those whose stage
work had made them, in his view, too theatrical. ``His cinema is
closer to painting than photography,'' Francois Truffaut once
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson nonetheless posed complex emotional and spiritual
problems in his movies, some of which he wrote himself, often by
confronting tragic lives and situations with a distant hope of
redemption. At times seemingly struggling with his own faith, he
was known to some French critics as ``a dark Catholic.'' But he
rarely favored them with an explanation: Once he had completed a
movie, he preferred it to speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you see my film?'' he asked one interviewer in 1983. The
journalist answered affirmatively. ``Then you know as much as I
do,'' he replied. ``What do we have to talk about?''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, he published ``Notes sur le Cinematographe'' in 1975,
but they were neither memoir nor primer. Rather, they contained a
series of maxims that served as his guides, like ``it is not a
question of directing someone else, but directing yourself'' and
``there can be no marriage between theater and cinema without
mutual destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most quoted ``note'' reflected his obsession with
internalizing his dramas: ``A film is not made for you to promenade
your eyes, but for you enter it and become entirely absorbed by
it.'' This effect was achieved principally in the editing room.
``To edit a film is to link people to each other and objects
through their looks,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson's films reflect a deep stoicism preoccupied with
redemption and atonement, predestination and spiritual favor, like
the triumph of love over hate and of grace over sin. They are
marked by an austerity that the critic Andre Bazin described as
``almost unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bresson was born in Bromont-Lamothe, a small town in
central France, on Sept. 25, 1901. His father was an army officer,
and the family moved frequently while he was young. Drawn to the
arts at an early age, he worked first as a painter and then as a
photographer before testing his hand as a screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, he made his first film, a satirical short called
``Public Affairs.'' It includes a ship-launching scene in which a
Champagne bottle remains intact and the ship's prow splits in two.
</P>
<P>
   He then became a co-writer of several scripts, including ``Pure
Air'' for Rene Clair. When Germany invaded France in 1940, he was
among the tens of thousands of French soldiers who were captured,
and he was held in a German prison for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson's first feature film, ``Les Anges du Peche,'' did not
come until 1943. Made during the German occupation, it tells of a
secluded order of nuns who dedicate themselves to rehabilitating
women from prison, in this case one Therese, who is unrepentant.
Hailed as a remarkable debut, the film already announced Bresson's
theme of salvation.
</P>
<P>
   In his next film, ``Les Dames du Bois de Boulogne,'' released in
1945, revenge and sexuality take the place of salvation. ``There
was no doubt about `Les Dames du Bois de Boulogne' being a landmark
in cinema history,'' observed the critic and film historian David
Thomson. The work was ``taken from Diderot's `Jacques le
Fatalisme,' with dialogue by Jean Cocteau,'' Thomson said. ``The
literary transposition was less important to Bresson than the
first, triumphant use of abstraction in photographing people.'' He
added, ``Here, plainly, outward appearance was a formal shell for
emotional and intellectual identity.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1950 Bresson returned to spirituality in ``Diary of a Country
Priest,'' one of his finest films, in which a young priest dying of
cancer suffers even more from his failure to save souls until he
mysteriously assumes a state of grace that releases him from his
torment. Adapted from a novel by Georges Bernanos, the film won the
Grand Prix at the Venice Film Festival in 1951. Truffaut, calling
it Bresson's best, said that ``every shot is as true as a handful
of earth.''
</P>
<P>
   His next film, ``A Man Escaped,'' a true story of a Resistance
fighter's escape from the Gestapo, was not made until 1956 (winning
him the award for best director at the 1957 Cannes International
Film Festival). Critics have remarked on his focus on the
prisoner's face in his narrow cell, the prisoner's growth of faith
and the way the ritual of prison life subtly fades into religious
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1959, Bresson made ``Pickpocket,'' one his most
celebrated works, in which he follows a young man's erotic
obsession with pickpocketing as it alienates him from those who
want to help him. In the film's final minutes, the pickpocket is
redeemed by a woman's love. Paul Schrader, an American director and
writer influenced by Bresson, echoes these minutes in his film
``American Gigolo.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Bresson's work seems to have been unaffected by the
New Wave that was sweeping French cinema in the late 1950s and
early '60s. The spiritual undertone of many of his films evidently
irritated some critics, but he continued to make the films he
wanted to make, including ``The Trial of Joan of Arc'' (1962), in
which he contrasts the serene transcript of her testimony with the
brutal way she was treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who detests Christianity cannot be interested in `Les
Anges du Peche,' `Diary of a Country Priest' and `The Trial of Joan
of Arc,''' Roger Boussinot wrote in his French-language
``Encyclopedia of Cinema.'' ``Anti-clerics, rationalists and
surrealists have not missed a chance to ridicule the commonplaces
of Bresson's admirers.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Balthazar,'' made in 1966, Bresson uses the story of a
brutalized donkey as an allegory for human cruelty and love. In the
same year, in ``Mouchette,'' another adaptation of a Bernanos
novel, a teen-age peasant girl driven to suicide epitomizes human
suffering. Three years later, in his first color film, ``A Gentle
Creature,'' starring Dominique Sanda, then a 17-year-old model, the
director again tackles suicide, but this time seen through the
angry and guilt-ridden eyes of a surviving husband.
</P>
<P>
   His final four films were ``Four Nights of a Dreamer'' (1971),
``Lancelot of the Lake'' (1974), ``The Devil, Probably'' (1977) and
``Money'' (1983). In the last one, an expression of his distaste
for unrestrained materialism, the forgery of a 500-franc note
begins as a schoolboy prank and ends up a catalyst for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson's first marriage, to Leidia van der Zee, ended in
divorce. He is survived by his second wife, Marie-Madeleine van der
Mersch.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bresson, then 77, had difficulty raising funds to make ``Money''
and was helped by the French culture minister, Jack Lang. The movie
went on to win the best-film award at the 1983 Cannes festival.
</P>
<P>
   To the end, Robert Bresson remained a true auteur who controlled
every facet of his work, who managed to work independent of
commercial considerations and who made movies that are instantly
recognizable as his. Although he was too iconoclastic to inspire a
school of filmmakers to follow him, he did have a legion of
admirers, becoming, as Jean-Luc Godard put it, ``to French cinema
what Mozart is to German music and Dostoyevsky is to Russian
literature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ETOUR-COX     12-21 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ETour seeks exposure after money
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A little over a year ago, 29-year-old Roger Barnette
was just another Web geek.
</P>
<P>
   He had nothing more than a business plan, an Emory University
business degree and an idea for a company that would deliver Web
sites to registered users based on their interests and preferences.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnette's days of struggle are quickly fading. This week
the company, now called eTour, received another $25 million in
funding from a group of broadcast outlets and still more money from
Atlanta-based investors including iXL's Bert Ellis and WebMD's Jeff
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast outlets include Jefferson Pilot Corp., Susquehanna
Broadcasting, Barnstable Broadcasting and Beasley Broadcast
company. NeoCarta, a Boston-based venture fund, led the funding.
</P>
<P>
   The new infusion of cash comes only five months after Barnette
received $10 million from Atlanta investors. The money has helped
Barnette lift his company up onto the national radar. In addition
to new, spacious offices, there are also offices in New York and
San Francisco. He has increased his staff from 15 to about 80 with
plans to hire still more employees early next year.
</P>
<P>
   New York ad agency Fallon McElligott, the same folks who do
those ``MindSpring loves me'' ads, have done a series of equally
quirky ads touting eTour with the tag line ``surf without
searching.'' And then there is Mahir.
</P>
<P>
   Mahir is the hapless Turkish guy whose lonely hearts home page
is written in fractured English with the headline ``Welcome to my
home page! Kiss
you!!!!!!!(members.xoom.com/XOOM/primall/mahir/index.html) has made
him the darling of the online world. Mahir is now looking for a lot
more than love on the Net, he's looking for money. He's selling
merchandise and touring the United States on a whirlwind media
blitz sponsored by Barnette and eTour.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet media have been eager to jump on the Mahir
bandwagon, its sponsor has been virtually ignored. In a bubbly
Salon article called ``I Kissed Mahir,'' Internet writer Janelle
Brown described every detail of her encounter with Mahir but left
the party somewhat puzzled about eTour.
</P>
<P>
   Of Mahir's stop in San Francisco, Brown writes: ``Our host,
eTour, has provided meatballs and brie and Thai chicken on skewers,
plus all the free cocktails you can drink ...eTour has plastered
the walls with its logos and Mahir posters ... I can only wonder
what it costs to wine and dine this crowd of strangers _ none of
whom, incidentally, have been able to tell me what exactly eTour
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette just shakes his head and laughs quietly when he hears
the Salon story. He's certainly not surprised that eTour got lost
in the hoopla. That's been his company's most pressing problem all
along, describing itself and what it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is radically different from anything else out there
on the Web. We need to get the word out, and that's what all the
money is for. There's really nothing like eTour that lets users see
Web sites they've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette says eTour is a quick and easy way to see what's out
there on the Web, in addition to the dozen or so sites the average
Web user frequents. ``Old timers go to the same sites over and over
again. The appeal of searching is gone,'' he says. ``There are
millions of sites out there. We are absolutely a service. People do
want to see sites they've never heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a service has to make money. A staff of editors selects
sites for each of eTour's categories, but most of eTour's income
comes from Web sites that pay to be part of the eTour rotation.
About 20 percent of the sites eTour users see have paid for the
privilege and the number will not go higher than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Barnette also says that users won't see the paid site _ or any
other site _ more than once a month. (The average eTour user logs
on about 8.5 times a month.) ``Every day the experience should be
different,'' he says. ``You won't see the same Web site more than
once in a month. What a site pays for is the eyeballs of people who
have said they have an interest in the products or services or
content that site has, whether it's auctions or food or golf.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an effort to convert editorial picks into paying
customers, although Barnette maintains there are other ways to make
money without compromising the customer experience.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his mother as an example of the perfect eTour user. A
newcomer to the Web, Barnette's mom surfs the Web using eTour,
without even realizing she's surfing. But no matter how wonderful
or relevant eTour is, or how many people are willing to invest in
Barnette's ``surf without searching'' Web venture, if no one knows
about eTour, eTour is through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring more eyeballs to the site,'' Barnette
acknowledges. ``And describing what we do has always been our
biggest challenge. There's no real world corollary or even an
online corollary.''
</P>
<P>
   He says even his hip TV ads are a gamble. ``It's hard to get the
message across in 30 seconds. We've done a good job (on TV) of
getting the message out. We actually show people the Web site _ not
a lot of Web sites do. Most of them are just out there advertising
for shock value.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the money is rolling in and the users are signing
up, Barnette knows there's plenty of work ahead. ``I spent two
years getting a lot of blank stares,'' he says. ``It's hard to do
this on a tight budget. We need the money to get to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
