<HEADER>
A5573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GENERAL-MILLS-COX     12-21 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-MILLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    General Mills could be made to ante up for charity
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Mills Inc. could owe $4.5 million in new
charitable contributions to breast cancer research if other states
follow a formula Georgia imposed after investigating a recent
yogurt marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The company had promised on the outside of specially marked
Yoplait yogurt lids to donate 50 cents to breast cancer research
for each returned lid.
</P>
<P>
   A statement on the inside of the lid said the company's donation
would be limited to $100,000. But consumers had to purchase the
yogurt and open it before they could read the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers nationwide returned 9.4 million lids to General Mills,
far more than expected. The company would have had to donate $4.7
million to keep the promise on the outside of the Yoplait lids. It
donated $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Cathy Cox found that the campaign deceived
Georgia consumers. ``We must make sure Georgia consumers are not
misled by sales promotions that feature a charitable component,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Cox said Georgia planned to share with charity
regulators in other states its formula for calculating how much
extra General Mills should contribute. The formula is based on a
projection that Georgians purchase about 1.32 percent of all
Yoplait yogurt sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have created a template for other states'' to use in
calculating breast cancer research donations required on behalf of
their citizens, said Cox spokesman Chris Riggall.
</P>
<P>
   To settle the matter, General Mills has agreed to pay an
additional $63,000 to cover donations that should have been made on
behalf of Georgians who returned lids.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills spokesman Austin Sullivan said the company was
``frustrated with Georgia's stance. We felt we had acted in good
faith and were forthcoming in every respect.'' Settling with
Georgia for $63,000 was ``a fairly easy business decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said General Mills had no indication the lid-mailback
campaign was an issue outside Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will contribute more than $1 million to
breast cancer research this year and is currently conducting
another Yoplait lid-return campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the new campaign, the company promises to donate 10 cents per
lid to breast cancer research, with a $500,000 minimum donation and
up to $500,000 more depending on how many lids are returned. Those
terms are shown on the outside of yogurt container.
</P>
<P>
   The Breast Cancer Research Foundation expressed support for
General Mills and other companies that engage in ``cause-related
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate campaigns such as General Mills' not only generate
important financial support for breast cancer research, but also
raise awareness about the dangers of breast cancer and what can be
done to deter or prevent it. It's hard to put a price tag on that
kind of contribution _ but it's invaluable,'' Susan Hirschorn, the
foundation's executive director, said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the initial Yoplait lid campaign was General
Mills' first venture into cause-related marketing. ``In all things
you do for the first time, you learn a few things,'' he said. ``We
were bowled over by the response.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Sullivan said, the campaign did not cause a spurt in
Yoplait sales. He said the company hopes the program will help
typical yogurt consumers _ women between 18 and 45 _ associate one
of their key concerns with the Yoplait brand over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mantius writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
