A5575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-S-ONE-COX     12-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S-ONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most signs are ripe for S1 success
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo and eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Both are well-known Internet companies. Each dominates their
market. Each stock is in the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Now S1 founder James S. ``Chip'' Mahan, and some analysts, think
you can add S1 to that list.
</P>
<P>
   It has the potential. S1 holds a dominant position in an
emerging industry. S1, formerly Security First Technologies, sells
software and services so banks can let their business and consumer
customers manage their money online. Banks, citing concern over
Year 2000 issues, have not pushed online banking services to their
customers. But that reluctance is expected to change next year.
</P>
<P>
   S1 also has size to capitalize on the emerging market. S1's
technology powered the first Internet bank, Security First Network
Bank. Last year, Mahan sold the Internet bank to Royal Bank of
Canada and focused on peddling the tools and the expertise that
made the online bank possible.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May, S1 said it was buying Edify and FICS, two of its
largest competitors. In September, S1 said it was buying
VerticalOne, an Atlanta firm with a technology to let users access
all their online accounts with one password. In four months, the
firm grew from 250 employees to 1,600. The deals closed in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan, S1's chief executive, also says he thinks the timing is
right. The repeal of parts of the Glass-Steagle Bank Act of 1933 is
expected to bring massive change in the financial services
industry, allowing banks and insurance firms to offer each other's
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the precise time all the walls are falling between these
industries is the precise time that broadband Internet access is
upon us, which is the precise time that people want access to
information that had been locked away on mainframe systems,'' said
Mahan. ``Why wouldn't a company like this be a really big, $100
million market capitalization company?''
</P>
<P>
   Last week S1 hosted an analysts conference to tell Wall Street
its story. Analysts apparently liked what they heard. Since the
meeting, three analysts have issued S1 ``strong buy''
recommendations, three have issued buy ratings.
</P>
<P>
   S1 shares hit a 52-week high of $89 Tuesday, before closing at
$85, down 25 cents. S1 shares are up 457 percent for the year, more
than 76 percent for December.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Baker, of SunTrust Equitable Securities, said he thinks S1
shares should be trading at $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``S1 is the industry leader and has little, if any, direct
competition,'' Baker wrote in his research note. ``We believe 2000
will be a pivotal year for financial service technology companies
as traditional and non-traditional finance companies begin to
aggressively market their electronic services. As a result, we
believe S1 is one of the financial service companies that is
strategically positioned to take advantage of this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he based his $200 price target on the valuations of
other companies that dominate their markets, such as eBay, Yahoo,
Inktomi and Verisign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is no competition for S1,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was the first time analysts and investors had a
chance to hear about how S1 had absorbed its acquisitions, said
Jeff John, an analyst with Robinson-Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better than I expected,'' he said. ``They are targeting
the top 200 global financial institutions as customers. And they
are well on their way. S1's main competition are the banks that
build the software on their own. S1 owns the high-end of the
market. There doesn't appear to be anyone really challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   John has a target price of $120.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray's Steve Franco said S1 is positioning
itself to be a multi-national, very large software company selling
to the largest financial customers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts know Mahan as a deal-maker. Mahan said S1 might forge
some alliances, but he said he does not expect to make any
acquisitions anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have the software to do what we need to do,'' he
said. ``Now we can be a little more selective in how we feed the
engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
