u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-21 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: UNCORKING GOOD CHEER AT THE LAST MINUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You. Yes, you with the panic-stricken look. Stop cringing.
Straighten up, and throw those shoulders back. Yes, you still have
gifts to buy. No, the Internet cannot save you now; it's a bit late
to click your troubles away. But be of good cheer: there is someone
who can.
</P>
<P>
   Who? Why, that friend to the dilatory, that last resort of all
last resorts, your local wine merchant. When all others have
failed, or closed up and gone home, he stands ready, up to the very
last minute, to lighten your holiday burden. Your wallet, as well,
but in truth, when it comes to gifts, there are probably more
bargains on the wine-shop shelves than just about anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Wine is one gift that flatters the giver and the recipient. Even
someone who doesn't know beans about wine is delighted to know that
you think he or she does. In fact, it's an area where neither of
you has to know very much.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking of a really superb gift I spied in one of the shops
the other day: a wooden case containing three bottles of Dom
Perignon Champagne from three great vintages: 1966, 1975 and 1978.
The cost: $1,050. Now, before you gulp at the price, consider this:
Some names transcend their metier. People who know nothing about
baseball know about Joe Torre. People who know nothing about wine
have heard of Dom Perignon, Moet &AMP; Chandon's top-of-the-line brand.
For a wine fan, such a gift is doubly welcome, because Champagne is
made to be drunk soon after it is bottled, and even Champagne
lovers rarely have a chance to taste older vintages. Here is that
chance.
</P>
<P>
   For more modest tastes _ and pocketbooks _ a single bottle of a
good Champagne is always a welcome gift. Especially this year, when
it can be opened to bring in the new year, new century and new
millennium. Veuve Clicquot, dressed up for the holidays in its
special sack, is a perfect last-minute gift, at about $5.
</P>
<P>
   Just as festive, and quite a bit more wine, is a case of Georges
Duboeuf's Beaujolais nouveau, released a month ago and now at its
peak. It's difficult to think of a more compelling gift for about
$70. If you know you are buying for a true Beaujolais fan, think of
Duboeuf's 1998 Morgon, a bigger and better Beaujolais, for about
$120 a case.
</P>
<P>
   Port is a wonderful wine for cold winter nights. A roaring fire
and a faithful old dog are the perfect accompaniments, but none of
the wine shops I know carry them. Vintage port is the most
discussed of all the port styles, and for the port expert on your
list, it's the ideal gift. For anyone else, I'd choose a tawny,
which has been aged in wood for many years. A Taylor Special
20-year Tawny sells for about $45, a 30-year version for about $90.
Tawny refers to the amber color the wine assumes during its long
life in oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing less than a vintage port will do, a wise choice would
be a bottle of Cockburn's from one of the finest vintages of the
last century, 1963; it will go for around $200. A Quinta do Noval
from 1970, another fine vintage, sells for about $80.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive of all wine gifts is the big bottle.
Even a magnum, which is just a double bottle holding a liter and a
half of wine, is quite a sight on the dining table. Think of the
impact you will make when you bestow a double magnum, which equals
four regular bottles, or an imperial, which holds the equivalent of
eight bottles of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of these outsize gifts can be reasonable. A magnum of
the 1996 Chateau Gloria can be had for about $60; Chateau
Phelan-Segur, a favorite of mine from St.-Estephe, is also $60. The
1996 Lafite-Rothschild, in magnum, is $1,100, but the same-size
bottle of 1995 Chateau Canon-Moueix, an attractive property in
Fronsac owned by Christian Moueix of Petrus fame, is only about
$38.
</P>
<P>
   In a double magnum, I like Chateau Malmaison 1995 from Moulis.
This is a second property of the late Baron Edmond de Rothschild,
now managed by his widow, Nadine. Not a complex wine but a most
attractive Bordeaux nonetheless. And at about $80, it makes a
spectacular gift.
</P>
<P>
   As for those imperials, the 1986 Petrus will set you back about
$10,000, but the 1996 Carruades de Lafite, the second label for
Lafite-Rothschild, is only around $375, and Chateau Talbot, from
the same vintage, is about $400. If you buy one of these monsters
and it's too late to have it delivered, bring a strong friend to
help carry it.
</P>
<P>
   A note of caution: Wine shops are filled with wine artifacts
this time of year: books, openers, stoppers, racks, glasses and
others. Some are interesting; many are junk. Avoid packages pairing
a bottle of wine with two glasses. The glasses are usually cheap
but add considerably to the price of the wine. Assume that whoever
is getting the gift already has glasses, and just buy the wine.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a wine gift to end all wine gifts? Well, you could buy
someone a chateau in Bordeaux or a winery in Napa, but we're
talking last-minute stuff here; buying a chateau might take a day
or two. Here is something you might pick up on your way home from
work tomorrow: a set of three magnums _ those double bottles _ of
Romanee-Conti from the 1996 vintage. Romanee-Conti, from the
Domaine de la Romanee-Conti in Burgundy, is by far the most
prestigious of all French wines, surpassing even the great Bordeaux
like Petrus, Margaux and Haut-Brion.
</P>
<P>
   Romanee-Conti routinely sells for about $1,000 a bottle at the
vineyard, a price that escalates quickly because so little is made
each year _ around 700 cases _ that wealthy collectors vie to own
just a few bottles. Park Avenue Liquor Shop, in Manhattan, which is
making this offer, is charging about what you might pay for a new
Honda: $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   Happy down-to-the-wire shopping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CENSORED-$ADV2     12-21 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CENSORED-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN DEMOCRACY FAILS SCREEN TEST AS FILMMAKER BATTLES
ATTEMPTED CENSORSHIP
 &HT;    1000 and add
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It's fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But never before, during 70 years of one-party domination, has a
Mexican filmmaker dared to use this country's ruling party as the
undisguised villain in a movie about abuse of power. Mexico's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI, is the explicit running
joke in ``Herod's Law,'' a newly-finished black comedy set in rural
Mexico in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is good enough to have won screenings in January at
Robert Redford's prestigious Sundance Film Festival in Utah. But a
short-lived debut in Mexico has prompted a national scandal that
belies the current PRI government's image as more respectful of
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixture of political clumsiness and evil,'' said
37-year-old filmmaker Luis Estrada, reflecting on alleged attempts
to censor his movie, which still hasn't been released in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought things like this didn't still happen in this
country,'' Estrada added. ``Surprise, surprise, surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The film represents the first time a filmmaker here has broken
through a veil of self-censorship and state control to create
unsavory characters clearly identified as members of the PRI _
right down to their membership cards and campaign buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, magazines and non-fiction books take aim at the
PRI's failures and flaws with greater vigor now than when the party
ruled more supremely. But movies and television are the final
frontiers, even when it comes to a fictional treatment of the party
set 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada obtained more than 60 percent of his $1.45 million
budget for the film _ his fourth _ from the government-run Mexican
Cinema Institute. Filmmakers rely heavily on the agency because
private financing is so difficult to obtain here. A committee
reviewed the script in 1995 and approved funding and agreed to take
on distribution of the movie in partnership with Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to tell a story about power in this country,''
Estrada said. ``And it doesn't say anything new. The bad guys
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada said some colleagues were taken aback by the audacity of
his script for ``Herod's Law,'' but he felt secure that times had
changed enough in Mexico that the film couldn't be repressed.
</P>
<P>
   In an opening scene, a top aide to a Mexican governor pins a
button emblazoned with the PRI logo on the main character's lapel.
From then on, the pin becomes a supporting character in a madcap
descent into corruption and betrayal set against an infectious
mambo soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, we owe everything to the party,'' the aide tells the
protagonist, Juan Vargas, a swindler whose dream is to rise to a
lucrative position in Congress from his appointment as mayor of a
miserable desert hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is told to bring ``modernity and social justice'' to the
troubled village. But most of all, the party brass want control of
the townsfolk at any cost until after an upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's movie lampoons one of Mexico's main opposition parties
_ the National Action Party, or PAN _ as well as the Catholic
clergy and greedy gringos. But the antics of PRI politicians, who
pack pistols and consort with thugs with names like ``Sharkey,''
appear to be what ultimately terrified government bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to a 1992 reform that forbids it to censor content, the
film institute gave Estrada ``complete freedom'' while he produced
the movie, he said. After it was completed in September the
institute's directors saw it and congratulated him on its high
quality and humor.
</P>
<P>
   But when ``Herod's Law'' was scheduled for a French-sponsored
film festival in Acapulco in November, the institute tried to block
it from screening. Although it remains unclear who ordered the
muzzling, Estrada said it was obvious the institute showed the film
to someone in a powerful position who became upset.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Gonzalez Rubio, a novelist and committee member, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A functionary sees the film and panics about what he thinks
could be a problem for the party in an electoral period,'' Gonzalez
said, relating the story as if it were the plot for its own movie.
``A comedy of errors begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican newspapers leaped on the dispute and members of the
Acapulco audience began chanting ``freedom!'' in French. The
institute relented and the film was shown.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada began to negotiate with the institute, offering to buy
the agency's stake in the film and find an independent distributor.
He said the institute wanted to buy his share and dump the movie in
a can until at least 2001 _ well after Mexico's July 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of talks, Estrada opened up a newspaper in early
December and discovered two Mexico City theaters were screening his
film with minimal publicity, no opening event and without his
permission.
</P>
<P>
   People who saw the film told him the copies shown for several
days were either blurry or constantly interrupted by projector
problems. Estrada suspected a cheap attempt to further sabotage the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Enraged, Estrada demanded the film be pulled. The institute told
him he was free to sue for beach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   The institute wanted him to get tangled up in a lawsuit, Estrada
alleges, because it knew legal action would probably shelve the
film for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada turned to an opposition member of Congress who
threatened to make the conflict a legislative issue. Mexico's
top-ranking culture secretary stepped in and a settlement was
reached. Estrada assumed $900,000 from the institute's investment
in the film's $1.45 million budget and agreed to pay the debt from
the film's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently looking for a distributor interested in the
film's money-making potential and brave enough to take on a what he
calls a ``hot potato.'' He wants to show the film in Berlin and
already has been invited to events in Montreal, San Antonio, and
San Diego, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada also hopes to show the movie in U.S. cities where
Mexican immigrants are concentrated. He believes they'll embrace
the film as a ``little vengeance'' because so many immigrants blame
the PRI for their having to leave Mexico to seek better lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some here have questioned Estrada's decision to use government
funds to make a film criticizing the party with the most power.
``The funds are everyone's. They don't belong to the government,''
Estrada bristled in response.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the deal was struck releasing the institute from
its partnership in the film, the agency's director was fired for
committing the ``error'' of trying to squelch the movie, according
to Rafael Tovar y de Teresa (CQ), president of Mexico's national
arts council.
</P>
<P>
   When the agreement with Estrada was struck, Tovar y de Teresa
announced publicly that ``freedom of individual creation and
artistic talent in Mexico is guaranteed.'' But he declined repeated
requests to discuss the matter further.
</P>
<P>
   The film institute's new director also declined to talk about
the dispute. And since he was removed, the previous director hasn't
been available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   An aide in President Ernesto Zedillo's office said the Mexican
leader, respecting the autonomy of the institute, didn't get
involved in the imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   The aide acknowledged, however, that the attempt to block the
movie ``contradicted'' Zedillo's emphasis in speeches that Mexicans
should enjoy freedom of expression. It was Zedillo who championed
the PRI's first primary presidential election in November as a show
that his party was becoming more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist in Mexico City's Reforma newspaper recently reported
that on Nov. 26 a powerful group convened for a private screening
of ``Herod's Law.'' The group included Mexico's interior secretary,
whose ministry rates movies, Tovar y de Teresa and the former film
institute director.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Diodoro Carrasco reportedly thought the film
was funny and reflected a PRI of 50 years ago that no longer
exists.
</P>
<P>
   When Mexicans finally get a chance to see the film, Estrada
said, ``Each person can ask himself that question. Is it a PRI that
no longer _ or still _ exists?''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss can be reached by e-mail at:
susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
