<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-21 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME, THAT WHICH CAN'T BE BOTTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (Eds: Lisa Belkin's e-mail address is Belkin(at)nytimes.com. Please
note that the word AT in parentheses is used instead of the symbol,
which is not transmittable to many newspaper systems.) (DW) 
 By LISA BELKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Birthdays do not make me feel nearly as old as I feel
come New Year's Eve. I think it's the communal countdown in the
final seconds, then weeks of miswriting the date on checks because
I'm still living in the past, that make me acutely aware of the
passage of time. I've had 365 days, my psyche whines. Where did
they all go?
</P>
<P>
   In college _ back when I thought I was busy _ I spent some spare
time reading Ionesco. ``We haven't the time to take our time,'' he
wrote, and I copied that down and tacked it to my bulletin board,
my justification for sloppy work and rash decisions. I now know, of
course, that I couldn't have been all that busy since I had time to
read a Romanian playwright who wrote in French.
</P>
<P>
   Then I graduated and began my first job. Talk about busy. In
those early years I came to the newsroom early, left late, skipped
vacation and stopped in for at least a few hours most weekends. But
my mental scrapbook also contains snapshots of brunch. Hours spent
reading the whole of the Sunday paper. Along the way I married and
I shared those brunches and that paper with my husband, Bruce _
before each of us headed off for a few hours of work.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until I had children that I understood what busy was.
Bruce and I had never fought during our first four years together,
but when our first son was born, I found myself picking fights
about something I'd always taken for granted. No, not sleep. Time.
``The devourer of all things,'' was how Ovid described it (yes, I'd
once had time to read him, too), and now that I was trying to give
100 percent of myself at work and 100 percent of myself at home,
the lack of time was threatening to devour me.
</P>
<P>
   The nadir came one afternoon when I drew up an elaborate chart,
with separate columns for the amount of time, to the minute, that
we had each spent alone, together, working, playing and caring for
the baby, over the weekend. That it didn't prove the dramatic
imbalance I'd set out to prove only fueled my rage more. I maturely
ripped the chart to pieces, tossed it all at my husband and stormed
out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Life (and time) being relative (no, I never read Einstein), some
people would see it as a luxury to have time to make a chart in the
first place, and even more of a luxury to have a partner to throw
it at. I have been writing this column for three months now, and
readers have been writing back. Most of the mail is about time (and
guilt, which, given the context, is the same thing), and much of it
is from people who are balancing work and life and children on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a single parent,'' says Jennifer McGregor, who runs a
Manhattan consulting company that specializes in public art
projects, ``I'm dependent on complex, fragile arrangements that
include an excellent after-school program, the health of my two
girls, the availability of my parents who live 250 miles away, and
the good will of the children's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she says, the house of cards tumbles, like the day
she was at a meeting in Philadelphia and realized she had forgotten
to leave a key for the sitter who was supposed to pick up the
children from a friend's house and take them home.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Laing has only recently come to see her life reflected
in such moments. Until last year she was a professional
photographer in Midland, Texas, a job she loved for its creativity
as well as its flexibility. Every Christmas season, she would hold
an elaborate party, where dozens of neighborhood children would
bake and ice hundreds of cookies and then deliver them to homeless
shelters. She would also create a masterpiece of a Christmas card.
Once she rented a trampoline and placed it against the backdrop of
a cloud-filled sky so she could photograph her children as if they
were flying.
</P>
<P>
   But now she is divorced, working 50 hours a week at a job with
benefits and a steady paycheck. There will be no cookie party this
year, and no Christmas card, not even a store-bought one. ``It's an
acknowledgment that I have limits and can only do so many things,''
she said during a teary phone call. ``I just ran out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't managed to send holiday cards this season, either. The
ones I have received wish me peace and love and joy, and computers
that continue to function after midnight on the 31st. I wish you
all those things, and one thing more. I wish you the time to enjoy
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
