<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-CROSTINI-SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 3602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSTINI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Toast of the Town: A few easy toppings turn simple bread
slices  into delectable crostini   By Tilde Herrera 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Crostini have long been Italy's rustic answer to
the French canape. Less refined than the crackers and toast points
that are the bases _ literally _ for classic canapes, these
``little toasts'' are perfect for holiday entertaining.
<P>
   In the classic tale of American culinary trends, the ``little
toasts'' traveled from Tuscany to the U.S. and inevitably crossed
cultures to suit a variety of tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Crostini are thin slices of day-old baguette, crust intact,
toasted in the oven and brushed with olive oil. Then they can
assume a variety of guises, depending upon what's laid upon them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they sport silken squares of French foie gras, zesty
mounds of Latin chiles or slices of seared ahi tuna dolloped with
Japanese-inspired wasabe creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   These toppings _ or the likes of porcini and roasted poblanos
from Do &LR; n &LR; a Tom &LR; a &LR; s' Do &LR; n &LR; a Savitsky or ``forest'' crostini from
Bistro Ralph's Ralph Tingle _ are colorful, delicious and most
importantly, many can be prepared quickly for last-minute
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Crostini look appealing, are easy make and to serve _ which is
why they've emerged as a secret weapon of the catering business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chefs like crostini because they can use different kinds
of bread with olive oil, fresh herbs and hundreds of topping
varieties to suit any taste or color scheme,'' says Jane Hammond of
Jane Hammond Events in San Francisco. ``Even if we make thousands
of them, they don't suffer because we can make them ahead of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Teri Menchini of La Bocca Fina Catering in Hayward has been
serving crostini throughout her 18 years in business. ``Crostini
are so varietal, easy to eat and offer so many non-meat options,''
she enthuses. ``People like to have a taste of everything and this
allows them to sample different flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why crostini are especially suited to the last holiday
season of the century. We have collected 10 crostini recipes from
Bay Area chefs and food professionals that are sure to spoil your
guests _ and with very little time and preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Just two or three different types are fine for a small
get-together, and none of them requires more than a handful of
ingredients. The choice of toppings is as endless as your
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Crostini Pointers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are ways to ensure top-notch crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Use the right bread and slice it thinly.  &LR; Crostini should be
sliced no thicker than 1/4-inch. Italian and French baguettes (not
sourdough) are the best choices, although other breads such as rye
and pumpernickel may be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Use day-old bread if possible because bread that is too fresh
may not be able to withstand the weight or moisture of certain
toppings.
</P>
<P>
   The slices should be small enough to be eaten in 1-2 bites. They
are traditionally cut straight down but bias cuts are very
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Brush the slices with olive oil.  &LR; Don't use too much oil or
your guests will end up with oily, messy fingers. Sprinkle with a
dash of salt and pepper, if desired. They can be rubbed with garlic
as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Toast the bread.  &LR; Place the sliced bread on a cookie sheet in
a 400 degree oven for about 10 minutes or until lightly golden.
Cook slightly less if you plan to reheat with toppings. Remove and
let cool. If making ahead of time, seal in a plastic airtight
container or storage bag after they have cooled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Choose toppings with care.  &LR; The toppings should be neat and
compact so that they don't fall off the crostini as they are being
passed around or bitten into. Garnish with fresh herbs for color.
Arrange on a serving tray and pass. Some crostini may be assembled
and refrigerated hours in advance if the toppings won't make the
crostini soggy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Plan the correct amount.  &LR; Expect that most people will eat
2-3 of each hors d'oeuvre. Each baguette will yield approximately
36-40 toasts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Topping Options &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More crostini topping ideas:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Tapenade With Roasted Peppers and Basil.  &LR; Top with a thin
layer of good commercial olive tapenade. Garnish with strips of
canned roasted peppers and a leaf of fresh basil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Smoked Salmon With Cream Cheese and Dill.  &LR; Blend 11/4 cups of
softened cream cheese with 1-2 tablespoons of chopped fresh dill
and salt to taste. Cut slices of store-bought smoked salmon and
roll into small cigars. Place a salmon cigar diagonally across a
crostini and garnish with a few capers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Seared Ahi Tuna With Wasabi Creme Fraiche. &LR;  Season a 1-inch
by 1-inch by 5-inch strip of ahi tuna with salt and pepper. Heat a
tablespoon of olive oil in a large saute pan over high heat until
almost smoking. Place ahi in the pan, searing evenly on all sides
until brown but not cooked all the way through. The center should
remain bright pink. Drain and place on cutting board. Cut slices
1/8-inch thick and set aside. Mix 1 cup creme fraiche with prepared
Japanese wasabi to taste. Arrange ahi on crostini and garnish with
a small dollop of creme fraiche. Tuna may be chilled or served
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Smoked Chicken With Roquefort and Toasted Walnuts.  &LR; Sprinkle
1 cup crumbled Roquefort cheese over toasts, followed by a thin
layer of chopped, toasted walnuts. Slice thin shreds of 6 ounces of
prepared smoked chicken and place on crostini. Finish with a
crumble of Roquefort. Place under broiler briefly, until melted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Chicken Liver and Anchovy.  &LR; Chop 8 chicken livers finely and
mix with 1 tablespoon minced parsley. Saute in butter or olive oil
for 5 minutes. Add 3-4 diced anchovy fillets and saute for 1 minute
more. Deglaze pan with a splash of sherry and remove from heat.
Season mixture with salt and pepper and spread on toasts. Garnish
with chopped parsley. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; What is Bruschetta? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Crostini resemble their Italian cousin, bruschetta. But the
Italian toasts are generally thicker and made from heavier-crusted
bread. They're traditionally used to show off the quality of a good
olive oil _ the slices are first rubbed with whole garlic cloves,
then grilled and lastly drizzled with the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, bruschetta began to bear toppings as well _ most
notably, ripe tomatoes showered with slivers of fresh basil. Today,
bruschetta is often toasted in the oven, but no matter how it's
made the outside should be crispy or even charred around the edges
while the center remains slightly soft.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, crostini are brushed with olive oil before being
toasted in the oven, are crisp all the way through and support a
huge array of topping combinations. Crostini should never be sliced
more than 1/4-inch thick while bruschetta can be as thick as
3/4-inch. If cleverly planned, bruschetta can even serve as a meal;
crostini are specifically snacks. Ideally, crostini should be eaten
in 1 to 2 bites and can be served warm or cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SMOKED TROUT, ASIAN PEAR AND HORSERADISH CREAM CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   A creamy spread spiked with horseradish and pecans gives a
pleasant kick to this crostini from Jennifer Cox of Montage
restaurant in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped toasted pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt, fresh ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 Asian pear, peeled, cored and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, juiced
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces smoked trout
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced tarragon
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Whip the heavy cream with the sugar in a mixer to firm peaks.
Fold in the horseradish, pecans, lemon zest, garlic and apple cider
vinegar. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place Asian pear slices in a small bowl and toss with the lemon
juice to keep them from browning.
</P>
<P>
   Flake trout into a small bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the horseradish-pecan cream in a thin layer on each
crostini. Top with a slice of the Asian pear and a small amount of
the flaked smoked trout. Garnish with tarragon and sprinkle with
more fresh ground pepper, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the rest of the crostini and topping ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 56 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate,
3 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 12 mg cholesterol, 51 mg sodium, .3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ROASTED PEPPER, ANCHOVY AND BLACK OLIVE CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Zubicaray and Bernat Dones of Pintxos restaurant in San
Francisco blend classic Spanish elements into this little bite.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 green bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 yellow bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   36 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   18 pitted black olives, halved
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil for drizzling
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons parsley, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Place the peppers in a shallow
baking pan, brush with oil and sprinkle with salt and pepper. Wrap
the onion in foil and place in the oven. Roast the peppers until
the skin blisters, about 40 minutes. Roast the onion for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Put the peppers in a bowl and cover with plastic wrap. When they
are cool enough to handle, peel and seed each pepper, then cut the
peppers into julienne strips, keeping each color separate. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   When the onion is cool enough to handle, peel and cut it into
julienne strips; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 strip of each color pepper, 1 strip of onion, 1 anchovy
fillet and 1 piece of olive on each baguette slice. Season with
salt and pepper, drizzle with olive oil and garnish with chopped
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 53 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate,
3 &LR;   &LR; g fat (.5 g saturated), 6 mg cholesterol, 208 mg sodium, .6 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUINCE AND CHEVRE CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Rossi of Oakland's Citron restaurant uses quince,
which tastes like a cross between a pear and an apple, for a
seasonal flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 large quince, peeled, cored and cut into eighths
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces good-quality chevre
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cream
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place quince and sugar in a non-corrosive pot. Cover with water
and bring to a simmer. Cook until the quince are tender, about 12
minutes. Remove the pot from the heat, lift the quince from the
syrup and, while still warm, cut the quince into thin slices.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the chevre and cream together in a small bowl to form a
soft spread.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the chevre mixture on each baguette slice and top with
two slices of quince. Sprinkle with freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 60 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 5 mg cholesterol, 72 mg sodium, .2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SHRIMP AND BACON CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   From Marsha McBride of Cafe Rouge in Berkeley. Undertoast the
baguette slices since they will toast further when the crostini are
finished in the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   36 medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces bacon, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Butterfly the shrimp by slicing halfway
down from the head to the tail. Place the shrimp in a bowl and toss
with 2 tablespoons of the olive oil and a pinch of salt; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bacon, garlic, Parmesan-Reggiano, rosemary and parsley
in a food processor. Pulse to a smooth paste, adding the remaining
tablespoon of olive oil while the motor is running.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the paste on each baguette slice and top with 2 pieces of
shrimp. Transfer the crostini to a sheet pan and broil until the
shrimp are cooked, about 3 minutes, watching to make sure they
don't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 55 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate,
3 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 15 mg cholesterol, 101 mg sodium, .1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ARTICHOKE AND YUKON GOLD POTATO CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   From Kirk Webber of Cafe Kati in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 large artichokes
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Sauvignon Blanc
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Small Yukon Gold potatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 smashed cloves of garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Gorgonzola, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped rosemary
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Remove the outer leaves of the artichoke until you get to the
yellow center leaves. Cut crosswise through those leaves about 1
inch from each stem. Use a paring knife to cut off all of the dark
green leaves, leaving only the tender leaves. Scoop out the chokes
with a teaspoon and place the artichokes in water mixed with the
juice of 1 lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the olive oil in a skillet. Add the onion
and saute briefly. Add half of the Sauvignon Blanc and continue to
cook until the onions turn a deep brown color, stirring regularly
once the onions start to color. When the onions start to stick on
the edges, add the rest of the wine to the pan and boil until the
onions caramelize and the liquid evaporates. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the potatoes into eighths and place them in a large pot with
the artichokes. Add water to cover, the smashed garlic and the 1
tablespoon salt. Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer and cook for
about 10 minutes, or until the vegetables are tender. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Place the potatoes in a bowl and mash with the half-and-half, 2
tablespoons olive oil, 5 teaspoons Gorgonzola, the rosemary and
salt and pepper to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the outer three-fourths of the artichoke stems. With
stem pointed up, cut the artichoke in quarters. Slice thinly with
stem still pointed up. Each artichoke heart should yield
approximately 20 slices.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining tablespoon of olive oil in a skillet. Add the
artichoke slices, season with salt and saute until slightly golden.
When they are done, dip them briefly in a bowl with the juice of
the second lemon. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Spread the potato-Gorgonzola mixture onto
the toasted baguette slices. Put 2-3 slices of artichoke on top,
followed by a thin layer of carmelized onions. Top with a small
crumble of Gorgonzola. Repeat with the remaining crostini.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the crostini to a baking sheet and broil for a few
seconds, until the cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 68 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate,
3 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 3 mg cholesterol, 109 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SHRIMP CROSTINI WITH THAI BASIL AND KAFFIR LIME SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   The Thai basil and Kaffir lime leaves called for in this recipe
from Alexander Ong of Xanadu Restorasian Cuisine in Berkeley are
available at specialty produce markets and at well-stocked Asian
grocers.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound raw medium-size shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt, freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons thinly sliced Thai basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced Kaffir lime leaves
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil into a saute pan and heat over medium heat. When the
oil is hot, add the ginger and garlic, and saute until aromatic,
about 30 seconds. Add the shrimp and saute until the shrimp are
almost cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Add the lime juice to the pan and cook until it evaporates. Add
the coconut milk and cook until the mixture is slightly reduced,
1-2 minutes. Season to taste with salt and freshly ground black
pepper. Add the Thai basil and lime leaves, and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place one shrimp on each crostini, then drizzle
lightly with the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 47 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 15 mg cholesterol, 58 mg sodium, .2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TECOMATE AND CHILE POBLANO CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  This recipe from Dona Savitsky of Dona Tom &LR; a &LR; s uses fresh
porcini mushrooms. If they are unavailable, use either
reconstituted dried porcini or another high quality fresh mushroom.
Epazote can be found at specialty produce stores or some Hispanic
food stores. If you can't find it, simply leave it out.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds  &LR; tecomates &LR;  (porcini mushrooms), thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cup  &LR; crema &LR;  (creme fraiche)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons chopped epazote
</P>
<P>
   Salt, freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   2 poblano chiles, roasted, peeled and cut into 1/4-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Put the oil and the butter in a skillet and heat over medium
heat. Add the mushrooms, and saute until tender. Stir in the crema
and epazote, and season to taste with salt and pepper. Cook 1-2
minutes to combine the flavors. Cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the topping onto the baguette slices and top with the
chile strips.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 42 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 5 mg cholesterol, 47 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FOREST CROSTINI
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Tingle of Bistro Ralph in Healdsburg calls on the
earthiness and of mushrooms for this recipe. Garnish with braised
or sauteed duck, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove of garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches escarole (leaves only)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh chanterelles (or mushrooms of your choice)
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Parmesan-Reggiano or other hard grating cheese
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Rub the fresh garlic clove once across each piece of cooled
toasted baguette.
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely chop the escarole leaves into 1-inch bite-sized pieces.
Pull the chanterelles apart by hand into bite-sized pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the olive oil into a large saute pan and set over
medium-high heat. Once the oil is close to smoking, add the butter,
the mushrooms and the sherry vinegar. Stir over high heat for 3-4
minutes, then add the chopped garlic, thyme and escarole. Stir
together until the escarole has softened, about 30 seconds. Season
with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the mixture between the crostini and sprinkle with the
grated Parmesan-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 39 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 2 mg cholesterol, 54 mg sodium, .5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHITE BEAN CROSTINI WITH DUCK CONFIT
</P>
<P>
   The duck confit in this recipe from Christopher Fernandez and
Morgan Brownlow of Stars Bar &AMP; Dining in San Francisco can be
purchased at a specialty grocery store or butcher shop, or you can
make your own. You may also substitute canned cannellini beans
instead of cooking them from scratch although some flavor witll be
sacrified. If you use the canned beans, rinse them and add enough
liquid (half water, half stock) to just cover them. Add the sage
leaves and simmer for at least 30 minutes before pureeing.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cannellini beans, soaked overnight in water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 small stalk of celery
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   6 sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves of roasted garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 legs of duck confit, meat pulled off the bone and shredded
</P>
<P>
   36 toasted slices of baguette (see instructions elsewhere on
this page)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Drain the soaked beans and set aside. Heat the olive oil in a
medium-size stockpot and add the onions. When the onions are
translucent, add the drained beans, the celery, carrot, sage
leaves, bay leaf, chicken stock and water. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat and simmer, uncovered, for 1-11/2 hours, or until the beans
are soft. Add additional stock and water as needed to keep the
beans submerged in the liquid. Season with salt and pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the beans, reserving 4 tablespoons of the cooking liquid.
Remove the celery, carrot, bay leaf, sage leaves and half of the
onions.
</P>
<P>
   Puree the beans, approximately 1/4-1/2 cup of the reserved
onion, and the roasted garlic in a food processor. Add 2-4
tablespoons of the reserved cooking liquid to the processed beans
to a make a slightly thin, spreadable puree. Add the extra virgin
olive oil. Adjust salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the bean puree on the crostini and garnish with the
shredded duck confit.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen crostini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CROSTINI: &LR;   &LR; 63 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (.5 g saturated), 7 mg cholesterol, 108 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
