<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANIA-OUTLOOK-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 YEARS AFTER REVOLUTION, MANY ROMANIANS FEEL WORSE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASOV, Romania _ Ten years ago, the Romanians rose up against
communist rule and the grinding dictatorship of a personality cult.
But the prosperity that had vanished under Nicolae Ceausescu's
regime now seems more remote than ever.
</P>
<P>
   This often-overlooked country of 22 million, bigger than most of
its East European neighbors, is going through harder times than
most of them. The average wage has slipped to $80 a month, and
one-third of the country lives on less than $2 a day.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn in Bucharest, the capital, groups of children emerge
from the sewers to beg, just as they do in the capital of Angola.
While Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and even tiny Estonia are
a jump away from joining the European Union, Romania lingers with
the underachievers, proud to be invited to qualify in a later
round.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mihai-Cristian Grigore, 32, a citizen of Brasov, an industrial
city in the Carpathian Mountains, knows Western-style
reorganization from the sharp end. A high school dropout, he was a
machinist in a factory that made hardware for doors before the 1989
revolution. That could have been a job for life. But in 1990,
Grigore recalled, ``our boss bought it from the state, dismissed
everybody and hired his own family.''
</P>
<P>
   His next job lasted five years and ended with a layoff. Six
months later, he found work at a screw factory where his mother
spent her career. But it was shrinking, and he was laid off again.
He wound up tiling sidewalks for a pittance. But that winter was
snowy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Grigore lives on $15 a month from temporary welfare, help
from relatives and the $14 a month that his wife makes selling
fruit on the street.
</P>
<P>
   He took a truck-driving course, but the police officers who
administered the exam were in a hurry at the end, and no one in his
class finished. Now he, too, hopes to obtain a license to sell
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying all I can to improve my life,'' Grigore said. ``But
this is the way we live now. If I could go overseas, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Romanians are bitter. In November, in a poll that stunned the
government, 61 percent said that life was better under Ceausescu,
who along with his wife was so hated that they were tried and shot
on Christmas Day in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Life then was lousy. Apartments were heated less than four hours
a day. Food shortages were so bad that people lined up for hours
and literally fought one another over rare supplies of chicken
parts with almost no meat, and television was two evening hours
simply glorifying the ruling couple.
</P>
<P>
   But the unemployed remember that everyone had jobs under
Ceausescu, despite his North Korean-style tyranny. A visitor
constantly hears this refrain: ``Then we had money, but there was
nothing to buy. Now the shops are full, but we have no money.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the government nor President Emil Constantinescu,
elected in 1997 with great hopes for change because it was the
first peaceful transfer of power in Romanian history, is planning a
nationwide celebration of the 10th anniversary of the revolution on
Wednesday. They fear that any spark could set off rioting.
</P>
<P>
   The government itself, a fragile, bickering multiparty
coalition, is in turmoil, accused of corruption and bungling the
economy. In what a local political commentator called ``a typical
Romanian circus,'' Constantinescu dismissed Prime Minister Radu
Vasile on Dec. 14, after most of his cabinet had resigned. Vasile
was defiant, saying the president had no such power, then
succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by Mugur Isarescu, an economist who had run the
central bank since 1991 and is in no political party. Isarescu is
highly regarded. He was reported to have taken the job reluctantly
and to have asked Parliament to guarantee him his old job back
after the elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   Violent strikes reminiscent of the dictator's waning days have
returned, and some marchers have taken to carrying Ceausescu's
picture. On Nov. 1 in Brasov, angry workers from the Roman truck
factory invaded and vandalized a government building. Their plant,
which once supplied much of the Soviet bloc, has shrunk, to 9,100
workers from 21,000 in 1990. The Tractorul tractor plant did the
same, and feels stabbed by both East and West. The NATO blockade of
Yugoslavia hurt sales just as the Soviet collapse did.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By some lights, the truck factory is where the 1989 revolution
began. In 1987, workers furious at working on Sundays for no pay
cut the electricity and marched on the building, where they found a
groaning buffet table set out for a Communist Party fete. They
rioted. For two years afterward, the factory floor was full of
security police officers in workers' clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The spies are gone. Hard times are not. A union president, Gabor
Fanica, said his members spent 90 percent of their salaries on
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no possibility to buy new clothes or keep up your
apartment, to allow yourself to make phone calls, let alone to go
away on vacation,'' Fanica said. The laid-off go to soup kitchens
or move in with rural relatives and eat what they grow.
</P>
<P>
   Aged pensioners have it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother's pension amounts to 7 pizzas a month,'' said Mircea
Irimie, 58, a retired railway engineer in the western city of
Timisoara. ``Who can live on that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``These beautiful buildings?'' he added, waving at the town's
Orthodox cathedral with an odd German roof. ``They're all a facade,
my friend. Romania used to export wheat to the world. Now it
exports only prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
