</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This round-up column will make practical sense
of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering
offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your
plate. &HT;       
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: Crustacean's Harvest Leaves Fishermen Crabby  By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; After a very slow start, the Dungeness crab season
is picking up a little steam. But the crabs at seafood markets in
the Bay Area are underweight, with shells that fishmongers say are
still too soft.
<P>
   That means higher retail prices and crabs that aren't as meaty
as in years past.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the average size is about 13/4 pounds. ``A crab from up
north might be two pounds plus but a lot will be water rather than
meat,'' said Steve Kingsley, a partner in San Francisco's Morgan
Fish. ``The crab that are out there haven't matured enough. They're
just not full of meat like you'd want.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabbers and fish wholesalers attribute the slow start to
various causes, all of which boil down to one thing: the vagaries
of mother nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is late this year. Steelhead are a month late,''
says Paul Johnson, president of Monterey Fish.
</P>
<P>
   A round of bad weather earlier this month didn't help local
supplies. Still, the slow start can't all be blamed on the storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we go out there in good weather and the ocean's like
glass, there just aren't any crab,'' says John Minaidis, Jr., owner
of Half Moon Bay Fish Market. ``I think it's just going to stay the
way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 700 crab boats ply California's waters searching for crab
between mid-November, when the season opens, to the end of June
when it closes. In a good year, crabbers will pull more than 4
million pounds of crab from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   This year doesn't look like it will be particularly good for
local crabbers. But for crab lovers, hope is coming from the north.
Earlier this month, the first shipments of crab from Washington and
Oregon started pouring into the Bay Area, sending prices down and
selection up. Their numbers will likely outweigh the local crab
catch for much of the season, sellers predict.
</P>
<P>
   The quality and amount of the northern catch can affect prices
day to day in the volatile crab market. Monday, prices for live
crab dropped to under $6, although it was up near $10 at a few
markets. Cooked crab was much cheaper Monday. Safeway, which
doesn't sell live crab, had cooked crab for $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   But in the up-and-down world of crab pricing, ``That may change
in heartbeat,'' Kingsley says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
