<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods.  BEST WAY: Homemade Sugar Cookies  
   
 By Rebecca Markowitz  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  One of my most treasured memories from childhood
is how my brothers and sister and I would decorate the holiday
sugar cookies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mom would make the dough, roll it out, cut the cookies and place
them on the cookie sheet. Then we let loose our artistic abilities
in the form of tie-died trees and purple reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't begun baking for the holidays, don't fret, this
recipe can be prepared in an afternoon. It will help occupy the
kids on those long school free days, and may create treasured
memories for your family as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the season, the Chronicle's Food staff ventured
to find what makes the best sugar cookie. We began by comparing
several recipes and found that most varied in the type of fat
specified and slightly in technique. We settled on a basic recipe
from The Chronicle's Baker columnist Flo Braker, then varied the
fat. We baked three batches _ one with all shortening, all butter,
and half butter-half shortening. With each batch, we noted how the
fat affected the mixing, rolling out and final flavor and texture.
We also checked which batch was best after several days' storage.
</P>
<P>
   We found that the recipe using butter only produced a rich
tasting but very soft cookie. In baking, the high amount of butter
also caused the cookie to brown quickly and unevenly. However, it
baked in the shortest time _ just 10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The half butter-half shortening cookie was crispy on the outside
and slightly soft on the inside. The edges browned slightly and
evenly, but the cookies took slightly longer to bake _ 13 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The shortening-only dough was the easiest to roll out but the
most difficult to transfer to the baking sheet. The resulting
cookie was extremely crisp. Many tasters thought this cookie tasted
bland, but one staffer enjoyed the contrast of the sweet and salty
flavors. Although it took the longest to bake _ 15 to 17 minutes _
it never browned.
</P>
<P>
   Using the half butter-half shortening cookie recipe as our
favorite, we tested how long the dough should be refrigerated
before rolling out. Chilling the dough makes handling the dough
easier. If the dough is too warm, it will stick to everything.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 minutes in the refrigerator, the dough was still too
soft to work with. After one hour, it was better but still
difficult to use. We could cut a few cookies, but within a couple
of minutes the dough warmed up and began to stick. It was too soft
to re-roll.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours in the refrigerator, the dough was able to be
re-rolled more than once. The cookies were also easy to cut and
move. Almost all of the dough was used before it became too warm to
work with.
</P>
<P>
   Chilling the dough for 24 hours made it easiest to work with. It
could be re-rolled until it was all used up. However, the baked
cookies weren't as appealing as those made with the two-hour dough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The half butter-half shortening cookie, with the dough
refrigerated between 2 and 8 hours, makes the best holiday sugar
cookie. It is ideal for decorating.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STORING SUGAR COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We reserved half of each batch of baked cookies and stored them
for one week in a sealed plastic bag to see if there was a
difference in how each held up.
</P>
<P>
   Both the shortening- and butter-only cookies tasted stale and
were soggy. The half butter-half shortening cookie lost little
texture, but didn't taste stale at all. So not only is the
half-and-half cookie the best tasting, but it keeps the best, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OLD-FASHIONED SUGAR COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   These cookies may be sprinkled with decorating sugar before
being baked, or leave them plain, or ice the baked and cooled
cookies with a favorite frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces shortening
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour, baking powder and salt onto a sheet of wax
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the butter, shortening and sugar in a large mixing bowl.
Using an electric mixer, beat until well blended. Beat in the eggs
and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   With the mixer on low speed, add the flour mixture and beat just
until thoroughly blended.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough in half and roll out each portion between 2
sheets of wax paper to form a 151/2 x 11-inch rectangle, about 1/8
inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the dough rectangles between the sheets of wax paper,
stack them on a baking sheet and refrigerate until firm, at least 2
hours, or up to 3 days; or freeze, well wrapped, up to 1 month.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust rack to lower third of oven; preheat oven to 350 degrees.
Line a baking sheet with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Remove 1 dough package from the refrigerator. Peel off the top
sheet of wax paper, replace it loosely on top, and flip the entire
package over. Peel off and discard the second sheet of wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   Using a large star or other shape cookie cutter (about 41/4
inches across), cut out cookies and set them about 1/2 inch apart
on the baking sheet. (If the dough softens, return it to the
refrigerator for 5 to 10 minutes to chill.)
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with second dough package. Scraps of dough may be
rerolled. Bake 1 sheet at a time for 10 to 12 minutes, or until the
cookies are pale golden around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 20 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE &LR; : 220 calories, 3 g protein, 28 g carbohydrate, 11
g &LR;   &LR; fat (4 g saturated), 34 mg cholesterol, 94 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
