<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics.  WINE POTPOURRI: Gift Twist: Give Whisky Not Wine  
   
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Still looking for gift ideas? You're not alone.
The same old gift of wine won't do this year. What you want is
something different, especially for those few people whose names
are still on your holiday gift list.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look no further. Single malt whisky is the answer. That's right,
single malt Scotch whisky is the ideal gift-with-a-difference for
the wine lover on your list. Like wine, single malts offer variety
of style and character, with major regional differences and more
subtle nuances by the different distilleries.
</P>
<P>
   A single malt is a grain whisky from a single distillery. The
only ingredients in malt whisky are malted barley and pure water.
Blended Scotch, like Johnnie Walker, contains up to 35 single
malts, and grain spirits, usually corn. Fans of blended Scotch
should love Johnnie Walker Blue Label, $160, a special blend
faithful to the recipe John Walker used in 1820 to create his first
bottle of blended Scotch.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 100 single malt distilleries in Scotland,
located in the Highlands, Lowlands and islands. In general, Lowland
whiskies are the lightest, Highland malts the most traditional and
island whiskies the heaviest. There are, of course, regional
stylistic variations; Islay whiskies, for instance, can be heavy
and peaty like Ardbeg and Laphroaig, or more moderately peated,
like Bunnahabhain. The fun is in trying a dram of each and
comparing the single malts, the same as you would do with wine.
</P>
<P>
   Every single malt distillery has a standard line, traditionally
based on age, or the time the whisky spent in oak barrels. In
recent years, a trend among whisky distillers has been to age their
whiskies in barrels that previously held different types of wine.
Glenmorangie, a northern Highland distiller, has a range of single
malts in Sherry, Madeira, Port and the latest, Claret wood.
</P>
<P>
   The new limited First Growth Claret Wood Finish Single Malt
Scotch Whisky, $250, was first aged in American oak barrels and
then transferred to barrels previously used for aging a first
growth Bordeaux from Pauillac. There's also a Limited Edition Fino
Sherry Wood Finish, at $90. Glenmorangie's other wood-finished
single malts, my favorite is the Port Finish, are more modestly
priced at about $40.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenlivet, considered by whisky drinkers as the
quintessential Highland malt, has a set of five vintage-dated
single malts _ 1967, 1968, 1969, 1970, 1972 _ in 200-ml. bottles,
selling for $299, or $199 for a 750-ml. bottle of each. Vintage
dating single malts is a new trend, since traditionally, malt
whisky distillers have never used a vintage date as with wine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular single malts is The Macallan, a
Highland-Speyside malt aged in Spanish oak Sherry casks. The
Macallan's 12 Year Old, $37, and 18 Year Old, $79, are the
standards. Now, The Macallan has added a special cask-select Gran
Reserva, $140 and The Macallan 1946, a collector's single malt,
priced at $2,500, distilled with more peat character than the
standard Macallan. During World War II there was a coal shortage,
requiring the kilning of the barley to use more peat to fuel the
fires.
</P>
<P>
   From the northern island of Orkney comes Highland Park, an
elegant single malt that ranks as one of the best made in Scotland.
Highland Park 12 Year Old, $32 and 18 Year Old, $70, are the
standards. Now, they've added a smoky, deeply flavored Vintage 1977
Reserve, aged 21 Years, for $100.
</P>
<P>
   Other single malt whiskies to consider for the holidays include:
the Sherry-finished Aberlour 15 Year Old, $45 and the newly
released 21 Year Old, $75; Ardbeg smoky-peaty-briny Islay Single
Malt 17 Year Old, $75. There is also a collection of different
single malts, called Defenders of the Malt, that includes
Glendronach 15 Year Old Highland-Speyside, $43, Scapa 12 Year Old
Orkney, $37 and Laphroaig 10 Year old Islay, $40. For a broader
range, look for the six-bottle Classic Malts of Scotland that
includes Talisker from Skye, Lagavulin from Islay, Glenkinchie, a
Lowland malt, Oban from the West Highlands, Dalwhinnie from the
Highlands and Gragganmore from the Highlands-Speyside. &QL; 
 &UR; Whisky Magazines &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know more and keep up with the latest whisky news
and releases, there are two excellent magazines to read.
</P>
<P>
   Malt Advocate Magazine reports on all malt beverages, including
whisky and beer. Subscription information for the
Pennsylvania-based magazine can be obtained by calling (800)
610-6258.
</P>
<P>
   Whisky Magazine, a bi-monthly published in the United Kingdom,
is available by subscription and on newsstands in the United
States. Dedicated exclusively to whisky, the attractive magazine
costs $41.70 for a year's subscription. Visit the website at
 &LR; www.whiskymag.com &LR;  or write to: Whisky Magazine Subscriptions,
RD1, Box 812, Landisburg, PA 17040-9797.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When a wine has a distinct, flat off-odor and taste, it is
usually described as oxidized. Oxidation occurs when a wine is
exposed to the air, is in a bottle with a faulty cork, or has had a
prolonged stay in a barrel or bottle. Browning, an enzymic
oxidation, can occur simultaneously with over-oxidation, but it is
more a factor of enzymes combining oxygen with tannins.
</P>
<P>
   Certain wines, such as sherry, are oxidized wines, with excess
oxidation giving sherry its unique flavor and character. Advanced
oxidation is often called Madeirization (Marsalato in Italy,
</P>
<P>
   for the brown Marsala sweet wine) for the brown sweet wine of
the island of Madeira.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
