<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5610 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FLAVORS-SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAVORS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 FLAVORS OF HOME: Desert Harvest for Ramadan   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 DALY CITY, Calif. _  Young Amel Guettatfi had been sneaking looks
at the clock for a good half hour. But the last few minutes, she
didn't take her eyes off the slow-moving hands. When they finally
showed 4:57 p.m., she shouted, ``break time.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   A familiar school scenario? No. The setting was her parents'
Daly City apartment. And the break had nothing to do with classes
but rather the moment the sun went down and her family could break
its daily dawn-to-dusk fast, observed by Muslims all over the world
during the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-year-old was lucky that this year, Ramadan falls in the
middle of winter (December 9 to January 7) when days are short.
Because the Arabic lunar calendar has 354 days, Ramadan, the ninth
month of the Arabic year, coincides with different months of the
Gregorian (Western) calendar.
</P>
<P>
   When Ramadan falls in the middle of summer, the hours of fasting
are longer. Actually, Amel is not obligated to fast because of her
age, but, say her parents, Abdel-Kader Guettatfi and his wife,
Houria, she is eager to do it because it's a grown-up thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends at school are fasting,'' Amel says, confirming
the opinion that there is prestige attached to no longer being an
infant who doesn't have to fast (nor do the elderly or infirm). The
school she refers to is the Granada Islamic School in Santa Clara,
where her mom, who has a Ph.D. in computer science from McGill
University, is a teacher. The two of them commute together _ at
least until Amel's baby brother or sister arrives in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary, the family breaks the fast with a snack of the
foods that sustained the prophet Mohammed in the desert, according
to 1,400-year-old tradition: dates and milk (buttermilk is the
Guettatfis' choice, its tartness provides a pleasant counterpoint
to the intense sweetness of the dried fruit).
</P>
<P>
   The California dates she purchases are fine, Houria Guettatfi
says, but they are not as delicious as the Deglet Nour dates of
their homeland, Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   There are other North African foods that don't quite have their
equal in America, she says, among them herbs like parsley and mint
(``the flavors are less intense here''); phyllo sheets that are not
as paper-thin as the ones available in this country, and
larger-grained couscous which is favored for certain dishes.
</P>
<P>
   A thoroughly practical woman who has to reconcile a heavy
teaching schedule with family obligations, she has found solutions
to these problems.
</P>
<P>
   She makes do with the fine couscous found in local natural food
stores (the couple visits Berkeley Bowl when time permits), using
it even for the relatively thin couscous with raisins and butter
that is a favorite breakfast food.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than battle the super-thin phyllo (``it's so brittle that
it's hard to work with''), she finds Chinese egg roll wrappers an
acceptable substitute for dishes like bourek, the tubular,
meat-filled fried pastries served with such soups as lamb broth
lightly thickened with barley that started one of her Ramadan
dinners last week.
</P>
<P>
   An avid cook, Guettatfi bases her cooking on recipes she learned
from her mother, with minor adjustments like the use of the egg
roll wrappers. She has every intention to pass her family recipe on
to her daughter, who already loves to help in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims have few dietary restrictions, and none specific to
Ramadan, she explains. Aside from alcohol, the one food strictly
prohibited is anything derived from pigs, so a lot of staples of
the American diet are shunned. Most snack and convenience foods are
forbidden because they might contain pork or pork byproducts (even
gelatin is suspect), as are such items as flavorings that may
contain small amounts of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Not having access to mixes and other convenience items,
Guettatfi has invented a number of shortcuts that enable her to get
dinner on the table within a brief time of returning from work.
</P>
<P>
   To shorten the long cooking time required by garbanzo beans _ a
staple of the Algerian diet _ she soaks a big batch overnight,
drains them in the morning and then freezes them. The combination
of soaking and freezing, she explains, softens the legumes
sufficiently so they take no longer to cook than the meats they
frequently accompany (as in the  &LR; mderbel &LR;  recipe below).
</P>
<P>
   And when she has the time, she makes a big batch of  &LR; bourek &LR;  and
freezes them before frying _ her home-grown version of fast food.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOUREK
</P>
<P>
   Houria Guettatfi uses Chinese egg roll wrappers in place of the
heavier Algerian phyllo she can't get here. She often makes these
in quantity and freezes them for a quick-fix addition to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch flat-leaf parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   20 Chinese egg roll wrappers
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a medium-sized skillet. Add the chopped onion
and ground beef, breaking the mixture up with a wooden spoon, and
saute until the meat is no longer pink. Add parsley and salt and
pepper to taste. Transfer the mixture to a bowl and cool. When
completely cooled, add the egg.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 heaping tablespoon of the mixture on 1 egg roll wrapper
and roll up, forming a cigar shape. Moisten the edges to adhere or,
if you want to be sure of a tight seal, mix a beaten egg with 1
teaspoon water and brush this solution on the edges. Repeat with
the remaining wrappers and meat.
</P>
<P>
   If these will not be served right away, wrap them tightly in
plastic wrap and overwrap with aluminum foil or more plastic wrap
for extra protection, and freeze. When ready to cook, remove as
many boureks from the freezer as needed. Leave on a plate for a
short time to start defrosting.
</P>
<P>
   To cook, pour vegetable oil to a depth of about 1 to 2 inches
into a heavy skillet, and heat over high heat. When the oil is
shimmering, add the boureks without crowding, reduce the heat to
medium and cook, turning frequently, until crisp and golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Serve boureks alongside soup or as an appetizer with lemon
wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER BOUREK: &LR;   &LR; 94 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, 6
g &LR;   &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 32 mg cholesterol, 34 mg sodium, .1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MDERBEL OF CAULIFLOWER (FRIED CAULIFLOWER WITH A LAMB SAUCE)
</P>
<P>
   Other vegetables such as zucchini can be used in place of
cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Lamb
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds bone-in leg of lamb, cut into 8-12 pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Big pinch saffron
</P>
<P>
   1 cup presoaked garbanzo beans (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   The Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   1 medium head cauliflower, separated into florets, tough stems
discarded
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch flat-leaf parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Big pinch of cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   1 russet potato, peeled and sliced 1/8-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Additional parsley for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prepare the lamb: &LR;  Heat the oil in a heavy skillet and add the
lamb, turning occasionally, and cook until lightly browned. Add
onion and continue sauteing and turning until onion is translucent.
Add garlic and cook a couple more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add a generous amount of salt and pepper, the saffron and the
garbanzo beans. Stir to mix, then add enough boiling water to
cover. Reduce the heat to low, cover the skillet and simmer about
11/2 hours, until the lamb and beans are very tender, checking and
adding more boiling water if the mixture is not covered.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prepare the vegetables:  &LR; Steam the cauliflower florets until
they are firm-tender, and set aside; do not overcook. This can be
done several hours ahead of finishing.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the egg, milk, chopped parsley, green onion, cinnamon, salt
and pepper in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 to 2 inches of vegetable oil in a heavy pan until
shimmering. One by one, dip the florets in the egg mixture and then
add to the skillet without crowding (do in 2 batches if needed).
Fry, turning frequently, until crispy brown. Drain in a colander
and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Add the potato slices to the skillet, adding more oil if needed,
and fry, turning once, until crisp-brown. Drain on paper towels and
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Place fried cauliflower on a warm, rimmed serving
dish. Place the lamb and garbanzos on top, spooning on the sauce.
Top with the potato slices and additional chopped parsley, if
desired. Accompany with quartered lemon to squeeze on top. Serve
with French bread for sopping up extra juices.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   To shorten the garbanzos' cooking time, soak them overnight in
cold water to cover, then drain and freeze in meal-sized batches.
You can also use canned garbanzo beans: Drain them well and add
during the final half hour of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 730 calories, &LR;   &LR; 79 g protein, 50 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 24 g fat (8 g saturated), 257 mg cholesterol, 221
mg sodium, 15 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
