<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCE-GREEN-SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-GREEN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders.  AT THE SOURCE: Fill Your Belly Full of Greens  
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Fir branches, holly and ivy are not the only
greens that delight us this time of year. The sturdy greens of the
winter garden are wonderful in the kitchen.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They look great (put them in a bowl on the table for a couple of
hours before using them), they are chockful of vitamins and
minerals, and they are eminently suited to the sturdy food _ soups,
stews, braised dishes _ we crave when evenings turn gloomy and
cold.
</P>
<P>
   These greens, especially the various kales, are stars in
farmers' market bins this time of year. And they are one of the
crops harvested now through at least February at a unique farming
venture in Yolo County. Full Belly Farms has all manner of kale,
including red Russian (no political reference); tender, long-leafed
Dino; and Karinate, a deep green vegetable with especially sweet
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all kales have a certain sweetness, says Melinda
Baker, the farm's office manager. Full Belly was started in 1984 by
Dru Rivers and Paul Muller, who were later joined by Judith Redmond
and Andrea Brait. The four co-owners' commitment to organic farming
took root on 170 acres in the tiny community of Guinda (near
Woodland). Today, it has a pretty impressive client list: Chez
Panisse and Oliveto restaurants; Monterey Market in Berkeley; Whole
Foods and Real Foods markets, as well as the Thursday Civic Center
Market in San Francisco, the Tuesday Berkeley Farmers' Market and
the Palo Alto Farmers' Market on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, working through the Community Supported Agriculture
organization, Full Belly delivers boxes of produce to individual
customers in the East Bay, Davis, Woodland and Sacramento. (Don't
rush to the phone. The farm can't handle more than the roughly 550
boxes packed each week and has a substantial waiting list.)
</P>
<P>
   Aside from kales, Full Belly's winter greenery includes salad
and braising mixes, spinach, broccoli and cabbage. Kale, a member
of the cabbage family, has been cultivated since ancient times. It
thrives in cold climates as well as moderate ones, a fact which, at
least in part, accounts for its great popularity in central and
northern Europe. A mixture of coarsely mashed potatoes and kale is
a specialty in Germany's Rhine area, often served as a side dish to
pork, and at one of Ireland's most luxurious hotels, Dromoland
Castlecq &LR; , pheasants are served on a bed of kale cooked with bacon
and onions.
</P>
<P>
   There is one caution about kale: It is best cooked within a few
days of being harvested. Not only do the leaves (which are the only
edible part _ the stems are too tough) wilt rather quickly, but the
vegetable loses some of its wealth of vitamins A and C by the hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
