<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-TERRY-COX     12-21 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-TERRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terry tries to defy rookie curse
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After three months, Lenny Wilkens figures he has a
pretty good handle on his protege, Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the mental capacity, the size, the skills to be a
terrific player in this league, and he will be. Believe me,''
Wilkens said. ``But, you know, this is such a difficult position
for rookies in the NBA. There's so much going on out there, and
sometimes, well, sometimes, Jason goes a little brain dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be alarmed, said the man who made the Basketball Hall of
Fame for his skill at the point guard position Terry occupies and
for his acumen and longevity as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Stephon Marbury his rookie year. There was a time
when he couldn't do anything right. Terrell (Brandon), the same.
Mark Price, the same. Hey, I went through it in St. Louis, but I
was lucky. Bob Pettit and my coach, Paul Seymour, helped me get
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens says, ``I'll get Jason through this. He'll be so much
better next year, you won't believe it, because he's such a smart
player. He remembers everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ordeal of his first NBA season, Terry remains an
engaging young man, full of fun, optimistic, steadfastly refusing
to be weighed down today by the mistakes of yesterday. ``I'm the
type player (who says), 'Last night is over. I'll take it to them
the next time,' `` he said. ``I'm not going to dwell on past
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   After general manager Pete Babcock dealt Mookie Blaylock to
Golden State for the No. 10 pick and Bimbo Coles, it was a foregone
conclusion that he would select a point guard. The draft offered an
unusually large crop of good ones: Steve Francis to Vancouver, and
then on to Houston, at No. 2; Baron Davis to Charlotte at No. 3;
Andre Miller to Cleveland at No. 8; Terry to the Hawks; and William
Avery to Minnesota, No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   All have struggled. And while Francis is flamboyant and Davis
has been both electrifying and steady, the Hawks say they have no
regrets about Terry. ``We would have been satisfied with any of the
others,'' Babcock said. ``And we have a lot of confidence in Jason,
just as Jason has a lot of confidence in himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry, All-American and Pac-10 player of the year as a senior,
is averaging 9.1 points in 22 minutes a game, but his assist
average is a low 2.8 and the 3-to-2 ratio of assists to turnovers
would be unacceptable for a veteran and is only tolerable in a
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   But he still is young, an ebullient kid with a quick smile that
entirely splits narrow features.
</P>
<P>
   His world is a maze of timing and selecting plays. He is trying
to deal with the emotions, desires and varying range of skills of
those around him.
</P>
<P>
   Three months past his 22nd birthday, the father of a 2-year-old
daughter, Jasionna, he also remains committed to his Play Station,
often playing several hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Terry clings to his superstition of wearing at least four pairs
of socks when he plays, one pair hiked to his knees. ``Sometimes I
wear five,'' he says. ``It depends on how my feet are.'' He also
eats the same pregame meal, a chicken sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, for all concerned, he no longer insists on sleeping in
his uniform the night before games. Thatapparently was over when
his four-year tour ended at Arizona. Given the frequency of road
trips and the packed calendar of the NBA, it might have been his
easiest adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Terry acknowledges that he can be his own worst enemy. ``I
thought I would be feeling comfortable right now,'' he says. ``But
after three, four minutes in the game, I find I'm not comfortable.
It's my mentality that changes. Not the other team's. I guess
that's the confidence factor. I've got to get more confident with
everything I can be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry says the active point guard he most admires is the one he
watched as a high school star in his own town of Seattle, Gary
Payton. ``I model my game after him. He's a great leader, very
intense.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Marbury of the Nets and the Bucks' Sam Cassell,
because ``they have no conscience,'' Terry says. ``When they've got
it going, they don't worry about, 'Should I pass or what?' They
keep doing what makes their teams successful.''
</P>
<P>
   When Terry came to grief Saturday night against Utah's John
Stockton, he said he was defeated by his reticence to attack rather
than Stockton's defensive wizardry. ``He played off me, but I felt
it was time for me to pass the ball, and he stole it twice,'' he
said. ``But with him playing off me, it was there for me to take
him, and I didn't do it, not because he's the great John Stockton,
but because I didn't use my natural skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens seizes on that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, Jason understands, but the problem is getting him to be
that assertive, to feed on success,'' Wilkens said. ``I tell him,
'Look, it's there for you to go to the basket, so take them. Don't
be shy. Don't worry about your teammates. If they have a problem,
let me be the bad guy, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Terry is learning to become an NBA point guard
and he realizes that he's in a great situation with Wilkens and the
Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's a great town, I have wonderful teammates, the best
possible coach for me,'' he said. ``Give me a little time. They
drafted me to be their point guard. It's gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
