<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NATGEO-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-21 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NATGEO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ADVENTURES IN TIME': TAKE HUNDREDS OF EPOCHS AND DIGEST IN TWO
HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and channel are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So if you're in need of another millennium-season fix, here's a
two-hour special from good old reliable National Geographic.
``Adventures in Time,'' made up mainly of material that fans have
seen before, offers little by way of fresh ideas or incisive
thought, but it is a picturesque grab bag. The notion of packaging
billions of years of happenings in two hours is a television
conceit, so don't take too seriously the pretense that the program
has much to do with time, except the timeouts for commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The viewing family may enjoy these quick looks at some favorites
like the 80-million-year-old fossil of an Oviraptor, ``that
fearsome carnivore of the Gobi.'' So much for dinosaurs, and it's
briskly on to the water chevrotain, an ancient flower eater related
to antelopes and pigs that can resist the horned lizard, which in
turn owes its survival to its ability to squirt a nasty stream of
blood into the face of a predatory coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, the program has reached primates, those new
arrivals, in the form of the famous skull discovered by Louis and
Mary Leakey of a young male creature who lived in Africa about 2
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator makes a strained segue from primitive life to an
obsession with death as evidenced by the ancient sarcophagus
discovered not long ago near the pyramids of Giza. If you conclude
that the subjects are driven by the available pictures, you are
onto something.
</P>
<P>
   The camera speeds from New Guinea to the Indian subcontinent to
central Borneo, ostensibly for glimpses of the ways different
peoples see or ignore the passage of time. Although it's a random
collection, the material has its fascination. As much cannot be
said for the familiar references to 20th-century explorers,
including Robert Peary and Matthew Henson, Richard Byrd, William
Beebe and Otis Barton. And then for no particular reason except the
photographs there's an interlude devoted to the perennially popular
pastime of climbing Mount Everest: ``You don't conquer it, you
survive it.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for Earth. Suddenly we are transported to outer space, a
slightly discouraging journey considering the recent failure of the
latest Mars probe.
</P>
<P>
   But the narrator holds out the hope of establishing an outpost
on Mars by 2050, by which time, some expert assures us, gene
research should be producing humans without cavities or colds or
inherited disease who will live almost forever. That is, of course,
if the millennium does not live up to the expectations or wishes of
people who are planning on an end to the world.
</P>
<P>
   But National Geographic is no more a proponent of miraculous
expiration than of creationism. The fears with which the program
leaves us are of ``a doomsday asteroid'' that could strike almost
anytime or global warming or depletion of ocean life or pollution
or overpopulation; you name it. Happy millennium.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Special
</P>
<P>
   `Adventures in Time'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Wednesday on NBC (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Kevin McCarey. Nicolas Noxon, executive producer;
Nicholas Stein, producer; Emmanuel Mairesse, co-producer and
editor; Teresa Koenig, senior producer. Music by Jay Chattaway.
Barry Nye, series supervising producer and editor; Andrew Carl
Wilk, executive vice president, programming and production; Tim
Kelly, president; C. Richard Allen, president and chief executive,
National Geographic Ventures. John Lithgow, narrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
