<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Dec. 22 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-ARREST (Montreal) _ Folo on the arrest in Canada of a
suspected terrorist and details about his past. By John Kifner and
others.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT10, 11.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ A look at the Democratic Party's
strategy for seeking soft money. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   MALL-DECLINE (Mountain View, Calif.) _ The enclosed shopping
mall was not born in California. But this seems to be where people
are digging its grave, at least in its present form. At a time of
record prosperity and robust retail sales, dead malls litter the
landscape, from the old Naugatuck Valley Mall in Waterbury, Conn.,
to the icon of Valley Girl culture, the Sherman Oaks Galleria in
Southern California. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIA-OUTLOOK (Brasov, Romania) _ This often-overlooked
country of 22 million people, bigger than most of its Eastern
European neighbors, is going through harder times than most of
them. Ten years after the overthrow of the Ceausescu dictatorship,
on Dec. 22, 1989, freedom is here but prosperity is not. By Donald
G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING (New York) _ It was a boom year for companies
going public on Wall Street, but last spring one investment firm,
Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, mysteriously scrubbed its plans for a
public offering and refused to say why. On Tuesday, the mystery was
solved when the former chairman of the firm, James J. McDermott
Jr., was charged with insider trading in a bizarre case in which he
was accused of leaking information about billion-dollar bank deals
to a pornographic movie star he was dating. The actress was also
charged in the case. By Benjamin Weiser and Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   BELL-LONG-DISTANCE (Undated) _ Bell Atlantic Corp. is expected
Wednesday to get Federal Communications Commission approval to sell
long-distance service in New York state, becoming the first
regional phone company to enter a $90 billion U.S. market. William
Kennard, the FCC chairman, will announce the agency's decision at
11 a.m. EST Wednesday. (Summary from wires) By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOUSING-CUOMO (New York) _ Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo
said Tuesday that the Giuliani administration could not be trusted
to fairly distribute federal funds for homeless services in New
York City and that the Department of Housing and Urban Development
would now take direct control of a program that provides about $60
million a year to local social service organizations. By David M.
Herszenhorn.
</P>
