<SLUG> BC-Y2K-VIRUSES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE OF Y2K VIRUSES EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BOB NORBERG   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ As the calendar rolls over to the New Year,
a new wave of malicious computer viruses that can corrupt data or
erase hard drives is expected to be released, say authorities and
software makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of weeks, we've seen an increase in the
number of viruses released,'' said Carey Nachenberg, chief
researcher for Symantec's Norton AntiVirus program in Santa Monica.
``We do expect that people will release some new viruses for the
new year.''
</P>
<P>
   One New Year's virus already has been discovered. Mypics will
deliver its destructive package Jan. 1, disguising itself as a Y2K
computer problem, but then erasing data on the hard drive,
Nachenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, software engineers saw a variant of the
Worm.Explore.Zip, which masquerades as an e-mail from a friend and
mails itself to those listed in the Microsoft Explorer address
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received 40 calls on it last week,'' said Scott Gaidano,
president of Drive Savers, a Novato company specializing in
retrieving lost data.
</P>
<P>
   And virus researchers are scrambling to find others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work going on in research and development at
all of the major anti-virus companies,'' said Patrick Hinojosa,
president of U.S. operations for Panda Software, a Madrid, Spain,
software company.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses are computer programs that are usually spread by e-mail
attachments. When the attachments are opened, the viruses set up
programs that hide deep within a computer operating system.
</P>
<P>
   There are 200 to 300 known viruses that are now in circulation,
and virus researchers find 10 to 20 new ones a week, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, viruses are being written to spread by going into the
computer's Internet browser and using the address book to send
itself out. The virus can thus look like it is coming from a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the viruses are simply mischievous, such as the Music
Bug, which slows down the computer while it plays a short tune.
</P>
<P>
   Others can be destructive, corrupting data in spreadsheets and
files or causing all data on a hard drive to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to combat viruses is for computer users to have
good anti-virus software and update it frequently by loading new
software from the software-maker's Internet site. Most makers
update their software weekly, although Panda is now updating its
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Virus software looks for viruses by ``definition,'' scanning
hard drives for program language that matches known virus program
language, and also looks for program ``behavior'' that matches
virus behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Software officials also warn computer users to not open any
e-mail attachments that don't come from friends, and even then not
to open it unless it was expected.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several high-profile viruses during the past
year, in which there have been a record number of virus attacks
reported to the Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie Mellon
University, , the U.S. clearinghouse for virus information.
</P>
<P>
   The Chernobyl virus attacked on May 26, marking the 13th
anniversary of the Chernobyl nuclear disaster in Ukraine, writing
over a portion of the operating system on a computer hard drive,
stopping the computer from booting up and often causing a loss of
all data on the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   That outbreak was scattered throughout the United States, Europe
and Asia and wasn't as bad as it could have been only because
computer users had already suffered from attacks from three other
malevolent viruses _ Melissa, Papa and Happy 99 _ earlier in the
year and were prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus attacked computers by sending itself out on
all the e-mail addresses in a user's Web browser, which had the
effect of overwhelming the e-mail programs on computer networks,
causing the servers to crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm.Explore.Zip virus, which used the same principle to
travel around the world within three days, also attacked and
disabled Microsoft Word, Excel and Powerpoint documents.
</P>
<P>
   Through September, CERT had received 6,844 reports of virus
attacks, compared to 3,734 in 1998, 2,134 in '97, 2,573 in '96,
2,412 in '95, 2,340 in '94 and 1,334 in '93.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa of Panda Software, which has its research headquarters
in Bilbao, Spain, also fears that beginning Jan. 1, computer owners
and network system administrators faced with computer problems
might look for Y2K problems and overlook a virus infection.
</P>
<P>
   CERT spokesman Bill Pollock said it is only speculation that
there will be new and more viruses for the New Year. But
regardless, CERT researchers will be watching, many will be on duty
and others will be on-call.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are viruses that are timed to deliver their payload on
any day of the year, and Jan. 1 is no different,'' Pollock said.
``We don't want to give the impression that people need to gear up
for Jan. 1 and then not be ready for Jan. 2 or 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson, an FBI spokesman in San Francisco, said the
bureau is not issuing warnings, but computer specialists are
prepared and will be working.
</P>
<P>
   Gaidano said Drive Savers has a staff of 30, which will be
working or on-call on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Norberg writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
