<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALKED BY PHONE, SHE WINS RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Dec. 28)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end it was like getting rid of an old lover, someone
she'd broken off with years ago but who couldn't believe it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent one, in this case, was the phone company trying
to woo back Kit (for Kathleen) Carson.
</P>
<P>
   You know these dinner-time calls.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of them come from phone companies. How could you leave?
Please come back. Just listen to what I will give you if you come
back.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after doing business with AT&AMP;T for 20 years, Kit
switched to another phone company and then later exchanged it for a
third.
</P>
<P>
   The calls began shortly after and lasted for three years. They'd
come at night, usually around 7 p.m. Kit has severe asthma and goes
to bed early, especially in the winter. By 7 p.m. she's pooped, but
she doesn't turn off her phone because she has a daughter who lives
in Australia and Kit wants to be available if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Kit started out, like most gentle people, not wanting to be
rude. Then, after the phone company refused to quietly go away, she
stopped being nice. But it didn't matter. The calls continued.
</P>
<P>
   We all know about switching phone companies. We do this for
various reasons. We are seduced by free air mileage, special
international calling rates, $100 checks to switch companies. We
are fickle, and maybe if you are a phone company that has been
dumped you think that we will dump the next one, too, and
eventually come back. That is one way of thinking, I suppose, but
when has badgering ever rekindled the flame?
</P>
<P>
   Kit is not easily flapped. She's worked in public relations,
television production, as a junior college instructor. She has a
sense of humor, and fortunately for her stress level, a fair amount
of patience with the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first when they called me and asked why I dropped them I
answered all their questions. They'd send mailings and I'd read
them all.''
</P>
<P>
   No thanks, she said, but they kept up anyhow. Over those three
years she estimates she got more than 50 nighttime phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Each time she would say, ``Please don't call me again'' and
later, ``Don't ever call me again.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't get it. Perhaps they thought she was being coy.
Perhaps they thought when she said no she meant yes.
</P>
<P>
   Often on the following mornings she called AT&AMP;T and would ``work
my way up the hierarchy to talk to a supervisor,'' who would assure
Kit the matter was settled. Then the calls would resume.
</P>
<P>
   She told them she was disabled. She told them she had a
breathing problem and that their calling made it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't shake these people,'' says Kit. ``I was getting
hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she heard a radio program mention the Telemarketer Consumer
Protection Act. Something could be done, but how to go about it?
She called the California attorney general's office and was advised
to tell AT&AMP;T to put her name on the ``do not call'' list.
</P>
<P>
   Kit calls those ``the magic words.'' Those were the ones that
broke the code when other pleadings failed. Previously she had said
to phone company supervisors, ``What do I have to do to get you not
to call me ever again?'' She even offered suggestions: Perhaps they
could put an asterisk after her name, draw a line through her name.
She said no one at AT&AMP;T ever mentioned the existence of a ``do not
call'' list.
</P>
<P>
   But when she asked to go on it and for AT&AMP;T to please send her a
confirmation letter to that effect, things started happening. The
rule is that if companies continue to solicit people who are on a
``do not call'' list, they can be fined.
</P>
<P>
   Kit was notified that she made the list in March. The calls
continued, not as often but enough to make her finally go to Small
Claims Court and charge the phone company with harassment. In
September she won her case and received a $2,000 check for her
troubles. But she says, ``The money outcome was never the purpose.
The purpose was to make them stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding not unlike the dazed survivor in an alien movie, she
sighs and says, ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she backs up and recalls a laughable moment. After Kit sued
AT&AMP;T she got a letter from company headquarters saying they'd like
to discuss the matter but would she please call them because they
didn't have her phone number. It's unlisted.
</P>
<P>
   There are efforts to make things a little easier than what Kit
went through. In California a ``Do Not Call'' bill has been
introduced in the Legislature that would allow consumers to
register with the attorney general's office to be removed from all
phone solicitation lists. There's also a petition for a ballot
measure being circulated that would control telemarketing.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
