<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GT-CAMPBELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech's Campbell gets OK to play in Gator Bowl
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Tech wide receiver Kelly Campbell, arrested last week on
a misdemeanor marijuana possession charge, was cleared Tuesday to
play in the Gator Bowl after a drug test proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad to say the drug test came back negative,'' Campbell
said Tuesday at a news conference. ``I have proclaimed my innocence
from the beginning, and I maintain my same innocence now.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell would not take questions because the charges are still
pending. A court date has been set for March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech sophomore was a passenger in a car stopped Dec. 17 by
Cobb County, Ga. police. A cigar stuffed with marijuana was found,
and police alleged that Campbell was observed stuffing the cigar
between his seat and the car's console. Police also found a bag of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell denied knowledge of the marijuana and told coach George
O'Leary that the driver informed police the marijuana was his. As
per team rules, O'Leary ordered the drug test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have an accusation leveled against a player . . .
in the program, we have a procedure,'' O'Leary said. ``I'm very
happy with the findings of the procedure we went through. Kelly
Campbell is a member of the football team, and will remain a member
of the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might add that Kelly has steadfastly maintained his
innocence in this incident from the beginning. Any further action
by me will be dependent on the resolution of his court hearing on
the legal charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was accompanied by his mother, Belinda Campbell, but
she did not want to comment. Tech players were not available to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said that, because the incident happened at 4:30 p.m.
and did not involve a curfew violation, he has not imposed any
restrictions on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Tech will practice today before breaking for Christmas. The team
will convene in Jacksonville, Fla., on Dec. 26 to prepare for their
New Year's Day game against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
