<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOO MUCH OF A GOOD THING? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For decades, political experts have lobbied for
televised campaign debates as the best way to inform voters of the
comparative personalities and policies of our presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   These verbal matches have been promoted as so important that the
candidates routinely spend weeks carefully negotiating the
positioning of the podiums, the nuances of lighting, the design of
the setting. Typically, the fellow who is leading stalls around and
tries to keep the number of debates to a minimum while the
challenger demands more and tries to get as much exposure as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1960, when Sen. John F. Kennedy bested Vice President
Richard M. Nixon in the first televised presidential debates, the
common wisdom has held that such face-offs are central to the
enlightenment of the electorate. But the drama has faded.
</P>
<P>
   Both verbal fluffs and soaring rhetoric have become increasingly
rare, as politicians have mastered manipulation of the dialogue,
rehearsed their words carefully and hid behind their standard stump
speech as often as possible. Over the years, campaign debates have
deteriorated into dull, self-serving recitals of political mush.
</P>
<P>
   A truly memorable moment such as 1988 Democratic vice
presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen's famous putdown of his GOP
rival, Dan Quayle, is the exception rather than the rule. (After
Quayle compared himself with Kennedy, Bentsen intoned: ``Jack
Kennedy was a friend of mine. You are no Jack Kennedy.''
Unfortunately, the top of the Democratic ticket was Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, a disastrous candidate whom Bentsen could not
save with quips or anything else.)
</P>
<P>
   If the candidates are reasonably well matched, voters often
learn little from the debates.
</P>
<P>
   So when Vice President Al Gore carried the concept to absurd
extremes on Sunday by proposing two debates every single week in
exchange for abandoning all primary television advertising, he was
immediately trashed from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, by contrast, was
praised for bluntly declining Gore's offer of a handshake on the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   So what is going on here? Have the pundits finally acknowledged
the dirty little secret that debates are boring, boring, boring and
that we are sick of them, no matter how good they are supposed to
be for us?
</P>
<P>
   But why would anyone prefer the repetitious, dumbed-down
30-second advertisements that Gore would cashier, which are already
driving New Hampshire voters nuts? How much can folks learn from a
brief sound bite anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that neither man was particularly
public-spirited here. Both were acting in their own self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has raised more money than Bradley but in a general
election would be at a distinct financial disadvantage against
George Bush. The Texas governor has raised more than $60 million,
and his campaign treasury will presumably be greater than that of
either Democrat. Gore would prefer not to spend lavishly on his
tight contest with Bradley but instead wants to husband his funds
for what he hopes will later be a race against Bush. Debates would
amount to free air time, whereas commercials are costly.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, is less known than Gore and feels he
can most effectively spread his message through paid TV ads. First
things first with Bradley. His immediate problem is to catch up to
Gore in the primaries. While the two are about even in New
Hampshire, Gore is now beating Bradley in Iowa, which holds the
first primaries, by a score of 48 percent to 27 percent in a new
CNN-USA Today poll. Underdogs don't have the luxury of worrying in
advance about general election spending.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gore was denounced for pulling a stunt, Bradley
didn't come out of the exchange looking very good either. He had
just pulled his own stunt urging campaign finance reform in tandem
with Republican contender John McCain. His refusal to abandon
expensive TV ads seemed to undermine the sincerity of that
particular publicity pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and McCain pledged, should they win their party's
nomination, to give up the so-called soft money that comes in
unlimited amounts and is essential to pay for such ads. Bradley
conditioned his pledge on a reciprocal act by the Republican
nominee, which means he need not fear financial consequences if the
GOP picks Bush, who has every intention of spending every penny he
has raised.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has made campaign finance reform the centerpiece of his
campaign, but it has never been a big issue with Bradley, who has a
record of raising huge contributions with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats have already debated three times and the five
Republican candidates three times as well. There will be more such
confrontations on both sides. But it's just as well that Gore's
proposal didn't fly. It would create an excess of dubious riches.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
</P>
<P>
   means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
