<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ REGISTERS BIGGEST ONE-DAY POINT GAIN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two broad stock market gauges leaped to records
Tuesday, with the bulk of the gains coming after the Federal
Reserve left short-term interest rates unchanged and kept its
neutral stance toward future increases.
</P>
<P>
   The gains were particularly pronounced in the technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index, which registered its biggest one-day point
gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which was up early in the session, jumped an
additional 30 points after the Fed announced that it was not
raising interest rates and that it was remaining neutral about a
further increase.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Internet companies like CMGI and Yahoo, the Nasdaq
continued to climb, broke through the 3,900 barrier for the first
time and closed at 3,911.15, a gain of 127.28, or 3.4 percent. With
Tuesday's gains, the Nasdaq is now up 78.4 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a clue why this is happening, and everyone is
amazed by it,'' said Steven C. Witt, a managing director at
Firsthand Funds in San Jose, Calif., which has about $2.3 billion
invested in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there will be a correction at some point, but interest
in technology has spread to a much, much broader audience than
previously. What is going on is more than momentum investors piling
into stocks that have worked in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo Birinyi, who runs his own stock research firm, echoed
those comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a mania, because it is so broad and so deep,'' he
said. ``This is more than that, even though I don't know how to
classify it.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Birinyi forecast that the Nasdaq would peak at
2,800 in 1999, a prediction that most on Wall Street viewed as
wildly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's decision to stand pat also helped to fuel gains in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, the Dow Jones industrial average
and the Russell 2000 index of smaller company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The S.&AMP; P. 500 climbed 15.34 points, or 1.1 percent, to a record
1,433.43, led by Microsoft and General Electric, the two largest
companies by market value.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which was lower early in the day, rallied after the Fed
announcement and closed at 11,200.54, up 56.27 points, or 0.5
percent. And the Russell 2000 index had a solid day, gaining 8.60
points, or 1.8 percent, to 475.79.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, the Internet holding company, and Qualcomm were two of the
Nasdaq's biggest stars.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI catapulted 47 13/16, to 270, after Henry Blodget, an
analyst at Merrill Lynch, initiated coverage with an ``accumulate''
rating.
</P>
<P>
   And Qualcomm, a phone and semiconductor maker, gained 20 1/16,
to 496~. The stock was lifted by optimism that Motorola or Nokia
would buy its wireless phone unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are making a bet that analysts are going to be raising
fourth-quarter earnings estimates early next year,'' said Michael
Molnar, a managing director in sales and trading at Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rising interest rates will be the catalyst of a correction,
and that will become more and more of an issue in the second
quarter. But the prospects for the first quarter are great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
