<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 26,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-ERA-SONGS (Undated) _ Here's a little post-holiday exercise
for your amusement: grab pen and paper and jot down your 10
favorite songs dating from 1955 to now. Ponder carefully, or don't,
depending on whether you think music should be judged by the brain
or the gut. Call five friends and read them your list. Set up a
date to argue about it, to spin CDs and scream and shout. When
you've done that, you will have helped shape the canon of rock 'n'
roll. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FILM (Hollywood) _ Norman Jewison is not Hollywood
hip. At the age of 73, the director of such films as
``Moonstruck,'' ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' ``A Soldier's Story,'' and
``In the Heat of the Night,'' (which won an Academy Award in 1968
as best picture) is hardly on the current A-list of trendy
directors pursued by studio executives and producers. In fact,
executives at Universal Pictures, which is releasing Jewison's
newest drama, ``The Hurricane,'' were skittish about hiring him to
direct the somber drama about Rubin ``Hurrican'' Carter, the boxer
wrongfully accused of murder (portrayed by Denzel Washington.) The
film will open on Wednesday in New York, Los Angeles and a few
other cities in order to qualify for Academy Award consideration.
By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MR.-DEATH-FILM (Undated) _ ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of
Fred A. Leuchter Jr.,'' Errol Morris' new film, opens Wednesday.
Fred A. Leuchter Jr., is an earnest dweeb with a thick
Massachusetts accent and a fondness for death chamber technology,
who drinks 40 cups of coffee and smokes six packs of cigarettes a
day, meets his wife-to-be at the local Dunkin' Donuts and then jets
off with her to Auschwitz, and is partial to comments like, ``Every
time there's a gas execution, it's an accident waiting to happen.''
By Peter Applebome. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FILMS (Beijing) _ These are exhilarating, and perhaps a
bit frightening, times for Zhang Yuan, 36, who is increasingly
described in international film circles as perhaps the most gifted
and original filmmaker of his generation, even though his movies
have not been widely seen at home or abroad. His past films,
including ``Beijing Bastards'' (1992) and ``East Palace, West
Palace'' (1996), were banned in China because they dealt with
hidden subjects like alienated youths and furtive homosexual
encounters. But Zhang's seven feature films, including fiction and
documentaries, have become favorites on the international art-house
and film-festival circuit. Known for years as an intriguing
underground filmmaker, he is now swamped with invitations to appear
at festivals and seminars. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-PLAYS (New York) _ A look at an assortment of Broadway
shows this year that firmed the theater's distinctive role in the
arts, plus one major downer, standing in (alas) for many other
productions of the same sensibility. By Ben Brantley. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARIAN-DANCE-TROUPE (New York) _ The Budapest Ensemble calls
its touring folk dance program ``Csardas: The Tango of the East.''
A producer of the show readily volunteers comparisons with the
popular Irish revue ``Riverdance.'' Clearly, a few bets are being
hedged here. But scratch the surface of the marketing campaign and
genuine passion and pride are quickly evident. The csardas is not
only the Hungarian national dance, it seems, but an embodiment of
Hungarian soul and the country's respect for dance in all forms.
``Csardas'' opens its monthlong tour of the United States and
Canada on Jan. 14 at the State Theater in New Brunswick, N.J. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-CHOREOGRAPHERS (Undated) _ BlAck choreographers,
especially a younger generation, stepped into the spotlight as a
group this year. All had an individual stamp, but many shared an
attraction to African dance movement that they stylized and
absorbed into a personal vocabulary. By Anna Kisselgoff. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-YEAREND (Undated) _ The year took its time before
delivering its best. The delay is understandable, given the
millennial nature of the moment. Some of the best experiences came
from abroad: from the Salzburg Festival and from festive reopenings
at the Theatre du Chatelet in Paris and the Royal Opera House in
London. But New York may have ended up with the prizes. By Bernard
Holland. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC (Undated) _ One thing the 20th century has left
us with is electronic music. The first electrical machines for
making sounds were built just before, but lasting possibilities of
producing music by electronic means arrived and grew during the
century now ending. In the 1920s and '30s came the earliest
electronic instruments that would survive: some are still in
occasional use, including the theremin and the ondes martenot, both
generating the weird effect of voicelike sounds coming from
inexplicable sources, and the electronic organ. By Paul Griffiths.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUBINSTEIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ RCA Red Seal has released Arthur
Rubinstein's entire discography in a deluxe boxed set, ``The Arthur
Rubinstein Collection'': 94 CDs in 82 volumes, more than 106 hours
of music, making it the biggest and most expensive special
collection yet issued. (Retail cost is about $1,300.) Everything is
here: the early HMV recordings; many RCA recordings that have long
been absent from the catalog; all of the many chamber and concerto
performances; recordings of live concerts that were released
commercially; and some items that have never previously been
issued. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC-1999 (Undated) _ Some remniscences of popular music in
1999. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-SHOWS (Undated) _ The year's handsomest shows of old art, by
medium: bronzes by the sculptor Adriaen de Vries at the Getty,
drawings and paintings by Ingres, and photographs by Carleton
Watkins, both at the Metropolitan. The biggest surprise of the
year: Frank Hurley's photographs, at the American Museum of Natural
History, from Ernest Shackleton's epic 1914 expedition to
Antarctica, one of the great stories of modern exploration, which
turned out to have produced remarkable pictures of the end of the
earth. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ For too long, the architectural art
form has been riding on the coattails of architectural preservation
_ coasting on the past, that is to say, instead of generating the
forward movement on which a great city's vitality depends. This
year, however, brought a few welcome signs that New York's
architecture may be rousing itself from its Sleeping Beauty coma.
By Herbert Muschamp. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ART (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Rome was ever Rome, and thus
counts as eternal. Istanbul bears a more recent name, but its
history as Constantinople and Byzantium goes back just as far. By
comparison, New York was born yesterday. Which may account for the
uproar over Chris Ofili's ``Holy Virgin Mary'' at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art's much-scrutinized and reviled show ``Sensation.''
Could the same thing have happened on the Bosporus? As it happens,
Ofili was among the 56 artists from 32 countries invited to the
sixth International Istanbul Biennial this fall (Sept. 17-Oct. 30).
His hip, jazzy pieces gave the catalog its most eye-catching pages.
By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOONLGHTING (Undated) _ It was a match made in hell: she with
the cool gaze and the silky long legs, he with the rhythm-and-blues
soul and that incessant smirk. And from the moment Bruce Willis
called Cybill Shepherd a rude five-letter name and she returned the
compliment with a quick hand across his face, viewers were smitten
by the bickering sweethearts and their television love nest,
``Moonlighting.'' Fifteen years later, their chemistry seems as
potent as ever. Which is exactly what Bravo was banking on when it
acquired 65 episodes of the ABC series and annointed them ``TV too
good for TV,'' an honor already bestowed on 1980s classics like
``Max Headroom'' and ``Brooklyn Bridge.'' Next Sunday at 1 p.m.,
Bravo will introduce its newest addition with a mini-marathon of
the first seven episodes before adding ``Moonlighting'' to its
weeknight lineup at 7 p.m., beginning the next day. By Kathryn
Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   TV-YEAREND (Undated) _ Doesn't it seem ``The Sopranos'' has been
around forever? And that the Barbara Walters-Monica Lewinsky
interview became part of pop-cultural history long ago? The
revealing detail about this year's most significant television
events is how quickly they have become absorbed, a testament to the
sound-bite speed of television and the ever-quickening pace of the
world it chronicles and shapes. By Caryn James.
</P>
