<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT JAPANESE POLITICIAN QUITS AMID SEX-ASSAULT SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In what is being seen as a major victory for women's
rights, the top official of Japan's second largest city resigned
Tuesday, as prosecutors filed charges against him for molesting a
21-year-old campaign worker.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of the once-popular governor of Osaka, Isamu
Yamada _ a former comedian who still goes by his stage name, Knock
Yokoyama _ ended several months of determined efforts by the
politician to make the brewing scandal blow away.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Yokoyama's tactics, which involved publicly
calling his accuser a liar while agreeing to pay a large civil
settlement, failed woefully. The outcome provided a rare,
high-profile instance of encouragement to women, who have
traditionally been reluctant to bring sexually related complaints
to court.
</P>
<P>
   Yokoyama comfortably won re-election in April. But public
opinion swiftly turned against him after the young campaign worker
won a settlement in a civil suit. She contended that three days
before the April election, he had draped a blanket over himself and
the student in the back seat of a campaign vehicle and had groped
her.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded he had draped the blanket over the two of them but
contended it was because she was sick and he was cold. He denied
any improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Local groups, angered at the apparent contradiction between his
strong denials and his quick agreement to pay $107,000 in the civil
suit, mobilized to demand his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Yokoyama was forced to pay a large amount of money, most
people weren't sure whether to side with the governor or the young
woman,'' said Mizuho Fukushima, a member of Parliament's upper
house. ``But once he paid up, most people in Japan concluded that
he was guilty, and public opinion shifted against him strongly.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the mass media felt pressure to treat this more
seriously. Now he has quit, but he still hasn't admitted his crime.
So I think the prosecutors had to file a criminal case, and I hope
that he has to face the truth and admit it before the court.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yoriko Madoka, another member of Parliament's upper house who is
also a prominent feminist, said: ``This indictment must be
considered a major step forward for women's rights in Japan. In the
past in Japan, sexual harassment and rape victims typically ended
up being treated like the accused.''
</P>
<P>
   The university student will probably remain an anonymous hero
for many women because the courts systematically shield the victim
from public exposure.
</P>
<P>
   But she was quoted as saying that she was left frustrated by
Tuesday's outcome. ``Fundamentally, I am not satisfied with his
manner of resignation,'' she said in a statement published by the
Sankei Shimbun. ``For me, I wanted him to apologize earlier,
reflect on what he had done, and then resign.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, the student's lawyer, Eri Shimao, said
her client's case had been helped immeasurably by her
forthrightness. ``I think the person who filed the lawsuit had
compelling testimony,'' she said. ``There were no contradictions in
her statement, and that gave her high credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Yokoyama has been unavailable for comment since checking into an
Osaka hospital late Monday, soon after police raided his offices.
In previous interviews, though, he has always insisted on his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Several women's groups and lawyers who deal frequently with
sexual harassment issues said the case would provide powerful
encouragement to other women to step forward and bring charges
against men who have harassed them.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``sexual harassment'' entered into usage in Japan only
10 years ago, after a famous case was brought in Fukuouka. Since
then, until recently, women have only very slowly begun to feel
secure enough to come forward to make harassment complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last couple of years, for reasons not entirely clear,
that has begun to change, and lawyers who specialize in such
matters say the numbers of women going to court over harassment has
been growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Rising public attention to the issue has also brought legal
changes. In April, the labor ministry introduced sweeping new rules
affecting discrimination against women and harassment in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Public pressure from a letter-writing campaign to the
prefectural assembly, which censured Yokoyama last week, and the
prosecutor's office were seen as helpful in creating pressure to
take the complaint seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A civic group called Watchguard wheeled into action after the
civil suit was settled on Oct. 4, sending over 1,500 postcards to
the prosecutor's office demanding that a case be brought against
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's attitude was not only neglectful of women's
rights, but of the law,'' said Yoneko Matsuura, 62, a member of the
group. ``So on the 8th of October, we decided to demand his
resignation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
