<SLUG> BC-XCELERA-HP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD BUYS 3 PERCENT OF XCELERA.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xcelera.com Inc. is getting help from Hewlett-Packard Co. in its
effort to gain a foothold in the business of speeding up Internet
content delivery.
</P>
<P>
   HP will invest $32 million for a 3 percent stake in Xcelera.com,
and will help the Woburn, Mass. company deploy a worldwide network
of Internet data caches built around HP computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Xcelera.com's Mirror Image Internet subsidiary is one of several
businesses that seek to speed up the performance of the Internet by
deploying large data storage caches at key points worldwide. Data
requested by Internet users is sent to them from the nearest cache,
instead of coming all the way from the actual Web site. ``By
storing a lot of content intelligently, close to end-users, we
deliver the content faster,'' said Xcelera.com chief executive Alex
Vik.
</P>
<P>
   Mirror Image Internet already has deployed its data caches in
Frankfurt, London, St. Louis, and Washington, with another under
construction in San Jose, Calif. Eventually, the company plans to
build 32 sites worldwide. Each will be located at a key Internet
access point, where many Internet backbone networks come together.
</P>
<P>
   Xcelera.com is going into the same business as high-flying
Akamai Technologies of Cambridge, Mass. That company already has
deployed hundreds of servers worldwide for speeding up Internet
service, and has done deals with CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass. and
the RoadRunner high-speed Internet system to further expand its
reach.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Akamai is currently one of the hottest of all
technology stocks. The company went public in late October at 26 a
share, and closed Tuesday at 301 7/8 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig White, senior vice president of Hewlett-Packard
Technology Finance, said the Mirror Image Internet technology is
superior to Akamai's. ``If you look at this segment,'' said White,
``we think they are going to be the leader, and emerge as the
dominant player.''
</P>
<P>
   Xcelera.com Inc. jumped 18 to 85 on the American Stock Exchange,
while HP closed up 2 23/32 at 108 3/4 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
