<HEADLINE>
HUSKEY PLACED ON FREE-AGENT LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In July, the Red Sox felt they needed Butch Huskey's
bat to make a run at the Yankees, and jumped at the chance to bring
him in from Seattle. Now they've decided he's no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey, 29, was one of three Red Sox players whom the club
decided to grant free agesday by refusing to tend them a
contract. Also gone are catcher Shea Hillenbrand, who batted .269
in 62 games with Pawtucket before suffering a torn anterior
cruciate ligament, and pitcher Julio Santana, acquired from Tampa
Bay in July. Santana did not pitch last season because of a sore
arm.
</P>
<P>
   Obtained just before the trading deadline, Huskey started fast
and hit a respectable .266 in 45 games for the Red Sox, with seven
home runs and 28 RBIs. Even though there are two spots available on
the 40-man roster, the Red Sox apparently feel they can receive
better production from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of outfielder Carl Everett from Houston and
the expected promotion of Michael Coleman from Pawtucket, Huskey,
an outfielder/designated hitter, would have been in a fight for a
starting job. Barring injury, veterans Darren Lewis and Trot Nixon
might platoon in right, unless one can beat out Troy O'Leary in
left. Mike Stanley and Brian Daubauch will likely platoon between
first base and DH. Wilton Veras could be the extra righthanded bat
and/or backup third baseman. Facing those odds, Huskey simply
became the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of competition for jobs,'' said team
spokesman Kevin Shea. ``And it might be difficult for him to be in
a situation where he is not a full-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey was obtained for Pawtucket lefthander Robert Ramsay, who
was promoted to Seattle in less than a month and made six
appearances, three as a starter. Despite his 0-2 record and 6.38
ERA, he is still considered a strong candidate for the Mariners'
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Sox general manager Dan Duquette said the team's No. 1 priority
remains pitching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
