<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-FRAGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 77, A FORMER FRANCO AIDE SERVES ON IN SPAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Brazil, Britain)  By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO DE COMPOSTELA, Spain _ Manuel Fraga Iribarne, Francisco
Franco's propaganda chief in the 1960s, is the only veteran of the
old fascist dictatorship who still holds high elected office in
democratic Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Fraga has been president of his native Galicia in northwest
Spain for nearly a decade, but as he turned 77 in November a fierce
battle to succeed him was brewing here in the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
   On the inside track are conservatives in Spain's governing
Popular Party, which Fraga himself founded in 1989 after repeatedly
failing to win election as prime minister after Franco's death in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside are upstart progressives, who for the first time
won control of most of Galicia's big cities last June. They say
that despite Fraga's latter-day democratic credentials, which
include helping to write Spain's Constitution of 1978, he rules
relatively poor Galicia like a fief.
</P>
<P>
   To all, Fraga's steely gaze and sly grin send a message not to
expect a disappearing act. He shows every indication of seeking a
fourth consecutive term in the regional elections due by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``My succession has come up, logically, because of my age and my
years of service,'' Fraga told Spain's largest-circulation
newspaper, El Pais, recently. ``But it has been made clear that my
succession is not open.''
</P>
<P>
   A top aide, Jesus Parga Lopez, put it more succinctly: ``He is
his own successor.''
</P>
<P>
   Galicia's fiery opposition leader, Xose Manuel Beiras, is
convinced that Fraga ``wants to continue and die with his boots
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may not surprise many people in this rainy, hilly corner
of Spain near the Atlantic. Fraga's staying power recalls other
leaders with Galician roots. The region produced Franco, who ran
Spain for 36 years, and it was also the birthplace of Fidel
Castro's father, who emigrated to Cuba, which his son has run for
nearly 41 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Castro and Fraga may be ideological opposites but
they have celebrated their shared Galician heritage during visits
to to each other's territories.
</P>
<P>
   As Galicia's president, roughly equivalent to a governor in the
United States, Fraga has traveled to 28 nations to promote his
region and is sometimes treated like a head of state.
</P>
<P>
   His aides say that these trips, criticized by the opposition,
have produced huge gains for Galicia's fishing, agricultural and
industrial companies. But Fraga's economic counselor, Jose Antonio
Orza, conceded that his department had never actually calculated
the financial benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fraga is not the longest-serving of Spain's 17 regional
government leaders; his counterparts in Catalonia, Extremadura and
New Castile have held office longer. But Fraga is unique for his
link to Franco, whom he served as minister of information and
tourism and later as ambassador to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The Franco connection hampered Fraga's four bids to become prime
minister, and the job of moving the Spanish right toward the
political center finally went to his protege, the current prime
minister, Jose Maria Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   Fraga retreated to Galicia, a region of 2.7 million people, and
has been elected three times with comfortable majorities. He has
presided over increasing prosperity for Galicia at a time when
Madrid has given it, and other regions, more home-rule powers in
areas like education and health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraga is incredibly efficient at image-making,'' said Emilio
Perez Tourino, secretary general of Galicia's Socialist Party. ``He
has been capable of making himself the symbol of this changing
Galicia.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Socialists and Beiras' leftist Galician Nationalist Bloc
have buried their differences recently to form a joint threat to
Fraga, like pooling their resources to wrest control of the big
city halls.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential successors come from within the Popular Party,
where analysts say that a longtime Fraga aide, Jose Cuina, heads a
faction strong in rural Galicia, while Madrid's conservatives are
pushing an aide to Prime Minister Aznar, Mariano Rajoy, who
represents the urbane, better-educated Galicians.
</P>
<P>
   Rajoy, the minister of education and culture, announced in
November that the national government would soon invest nearly $1
billion for long-sought railroad improvements in Galicia.
</P>
<P>
   Rajoy's news conference did not include Fraga, who was preparing
to leave for another overseas trip, to Brazil. But the next day, a
new opinion poll said Fraga was still the best-rated leader in
Galicia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
