<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FED-UNCHANGED-BOS &LR;      12-21 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-UNCHANGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED STANDS PAT ON RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to maintain calm as the world approaches the new
millennium, the Federal Reserve Board has made no changes in its
policy on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   As was widely expected, the Federal Reserve Open Market
Committee agreed not to rock expectations and not to raise the 5.5
percent federal funds rate.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring a desire as the world's largest central bank to
preserve certainty and liquidity in financial markets during the
days leading up to Jan. 1 _ when computers around the globe may
have difficulty recognizing the year 2000 _ the policy-setting
committee stated that it also would remain neutral toward the
future direction of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The message from the Fed Tuesday was ``Have a nice holiday and a
Happy New Year, and we'll see you in February,'' said Glenn
Migliozzi, managing director of fixed income for Fleet Investment
Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Fed vote against a rate increase, analysts said it
is more _ not less _ concerned about inflation and has not ruled
out a rate hike, possibly at its next meeting on Feb. 1-2. Some
analysts noted that Fed members said they ``remain concerned with
the possibility'' that the economy would continue growing too fast,
which could spark a pickup in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Three one-quarter-point Fed rate hikes this year each have done
little, so far, to slow the economy, and analysts detected a
heightened tone of concern about the red-hot economy in the Fed's
statement. After the Nov. 16 rate increase, the Fed policy
committee said its actions so far this year ``should markedly
diminish the risk of inflation going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Fed said, it ``remains concerned with the
possibility that over time increases in demand will continue to
exceed the growth in potential supply, even after taking account of
the remarkable rise in productivity growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed continued: ``Such trends could foster inflationary
imbalances that would undermine the economy's exemplary
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the booming economy was everywhere in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government reported that retail sales accelerated
in November. Gross domestic product expanded at a 5.5 percent
annual rate in the third quarter, the fastest pace since last year;
forecasts put growth for all of 1999 at about 4 percent, just a tad
below the blistering growth of the two previous years. Tight labor
markets and low (4.1 percent) unemployment have given rise to the
possibility of higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring high-tech stocks are also a continuing concern of
Greenspan. Fueled by the surge of investment interest in Internet
stocks, the Nasdaq stock index has soared 78 percent this year,
adding another 127.28 points Tuesday, or 3.36 percent, to close at
a record 3,911.15. Other major stock-market indexes moved slightly
higher, with the Dow Jones industrial average gaining 56.27 points
to close at 11,200.54, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index
rising 15.34 points to close at a new record level of 1,433.43.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has said in the past that ``asset inflation'' _ the
rising values of people's homes and stock portfolios _ can
contribute to increased demand for consumer goods and lead to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the Fed is focused primarily on getting
through New Year's, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   On the potential Y2K threats, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan has
expressed confidence the banking system is prepared to handle the
century date change without any major computer failures. The Fed
also has made sure the financial system has ample currency reserves
to meet unexpected demands for cash from customers withdrawing
extra cash from their banks in the event that financial
institutions have computer glitches that would prevent people from
gaining access to their money.
</P>
<P>
   A boost in interest rates this close to the Y2K switchover would
have added another disruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very concerned about the Y2K issue,'' said Pierre
Ellis, senior international economist for Primark Decision
Economics. ``They don't want to contribute to any problems that
might develop _ not just in the US but abroad where there are
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
