<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS SLIP AS MARKET REMAINS ANXIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Government bond yields were down moderately on
Tuesday, still hovering near their two-year highs even as the
Federal Reserve decided to leave interest rates unchanged and its
stance neutral.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond slipped 8/32, to 95
21/32, while the yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose
to 6.46 percent, from 6.44 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   William Hornbarger, fixed-income strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Sons, said the bond market's performance on Monday was the worst
one-day decline since February, and indicated that the market is
afraid of more interest rate increases by the Fed. The lack of
liquidity at year-end most likely exaggerated the recent weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be noted that the yield spread between the two-year
note and the 30-year bond continues to narrow and is currently at
26 basis points. A more restrictive monetary policy tends to
produce a narrower yield spread,'' Hornbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the week's biggest event was Tuesday's meeting of the
Federal Open Market Committee of the Fed. ``Coming into the meeting
it was highly unlikely that the Fed would alter monetary policy''
as the year 2000 neared, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street consensus was that the Fed would adopt a tightening
bias, which they didn't,'' Hornbarger said. ``A change in the bias
would not have meant that a tightening was a foregone conclusion.
It simply would have meant that the Fed views the risks as
unbalanced and that they are more likely to tighten than to ease
going forward.'' He noted that the Fed has adopted a tightening
bias, favoring higher interest rates, 22 times this decade and only
tightened after six of those bias changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the recent weakness, we still feel that bonds
represent good values at these levels. Discounting the rise in
energy prices, inflation remains well in check and there are signs
that the interest-rate-sensitive areas of the economy continue to
slow. A Fed tightening remains a big worry, but the flattening of
the yield curve leads us to believe that further moves won't hurt
long-term rates too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point one has to look past the immediate impact of
tighter policy and at the long-term effects of multiple moves in
the federal funds rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornbarger believes that if the Fed moves again, it will slow
the economy and keep inflation in check, which is ultimately good
for bonds. ``In the near term, we look for yields to continue to
hang around recent levels, but we still feel that looking into the
first half of 2000, yields will fall from current levels to under 6
percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
