<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     12-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright San Francisco Chronicle 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUE LOVE MEANS LIVING IN LUXURY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vicki Liviakis &LR; , travel reporter for KPIX's ``Evening
Magazine'' and ``Travel Update'' anchor, was lured aboard a
Southwest flight from Oakland to Los Angeles last week, where her
boyfriend proposed. They had met seven years before on the same
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sweet and sentimental moment,'' says Liviakis, and
when the betrothal was announced to the other travelers, they burst
into applause. And then the flight attendants treated each and
every passenger to an extra bag of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LITERARY HATE CHAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Salon's  &UR; Craig Offman  &LR; reports on a critical do-si-do of fiction
writers:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Updike  &LR; wrote in the New Yorker that  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; 's book,
``A Man in Full'' is ``entertainment, not literature.'' In the New
York Review of Books,  &UR; Norman Mailer &LR;  said that ``Reading the work
can even be said to resemble the act of making love to a 300-pound
woman. Once she gets on top, it's over. Fall in love, or be
asphyxiated.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparently retaliatory interview in a Charleston, W.Va.,
newspaper, Wolfe called Mailer and Updike ``two old piles of
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   When informed of this by a Canadian TV interviewer,  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Irving &LR;  jumped into the fray, saying he's unable to read Wolfe
``because he's such a bad writer.'' Irving called Wolfe's novels
``journalistic hyperbole described as fiction. ... He's a
journalist. ... He can't create a character. He can't create a
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wolfe asked about Irving, ``Why does he sputter and
foam so? Because he, like Updike and Mailer, has panicked. All
three have seen the handwriting on the wall, and it reads: `A Man
in Full.' ... Irving needs to get up off his bottom and leave that
farm in Vermont or wherever it is he stays and start living
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Soap opera star  &UR; Susan Lucci  &LR; was to open in the New York
revival of ``Annie Get Your Gun'' December 23, her birthday, but
the opening was postponed last week because the producers said she
had missed some rehearsals because of illness. The New York Post
said she didn't want to open on her birthday because everyone would
be asking her age, which, according to different Web sites, is
either 51 or 53. Lucci says only that she started playing her soap
opera character, in 1970, ``as a 15-year-old girl.''
</P>
<P>
   _Eighty-two members of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association
received $400 Coach watches from the makers of ``The Muse'' in the
name of  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR; , while considering nominating her for a
Golden Globe award for her work in the movie. Stone's publicist
said the watches _ provided free by Coach ``because it gets their
name out'' _ were sent by the film company. ``We were touched by
her generosity,'' association President &UR; Helmut Voss &LR;  said of Stone,
``but this is definitely a no-no.'' The watches were retrieved and
returned to Stone, he said. They are now in the offices of USA
Films.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOUSE CHOOSES A NEW CHAPLAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the House of Representatives have nominated the Rev.
 &UR; Charles Wright, &LR;  a Presbyterian, as chaplain of that body,
rejecting Father  &UR; Timothy O'Brien, &LR;  a Catholic, who had been
recommended by the 18-member selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   According to Roll Call, some members of the committee think
O'Brien was rejected because of his religion; he would have been
the first Catholic to hold the office. Rep. &UR; Steve Largent &LR; ,
R-Okla., told fellow members of the committee he was worried that
O'Brien's Roman Catholic priest's collar might cause divisiveness
in the House. Among those who said she was disappointed was Rep.
 &UR; Anna Eshoo &LR; , D-Atherton, who served on the committee. ``As a
Catholic,'' she said, ``I'm resentful and offended as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The full House has to vote on the nomination in January.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``In geologic time, everyone now present on Earth will be dead
in a few milliseconds. What a toll! Only through the diligent use
of sex, and you guessed it, food, can we further ourselves, hurling
our puny `I ams' into the face of 20 billion years of mute, cosmic
history. With every fanny glance or savory bite, you are telling a
stone to take a hike, a mountain that you are alive, a star that
you exist.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Jim Harrison &LR; , in an essay in ``The Adventure of Food; True
Stories of Eating Everything,'' edited by &UR; Richard Sterling &LR; 
(Travelers' Tales; $17.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
