 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright San Francisco Chronicle 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUE LOVE MEANS LIVING IN LUXURY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vicki Liviakis &LR; , travel reporter for KPIX's ``Evening
Magazine'' and ``Travel Update'' anchor, was lured aboard a
Southwest flight from Oakland to Los Angeles last week, where her
boyfriend proposed. They had met seven years before on the same
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sweet and sentimental moment,'' says Liviakis, and
when the betrothal was announced to the other travelers, they burst
into applause. And then the flight attendants treated each and
every passenger to an extra bag of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LITERARY HATE CHAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Salon's  &UR; Craig Offman  &LR; reports on a critical do-si-do of fiction
writers:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Updike  &LR; wrote in the New Yorker that  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; 's book,
``A Man in Full'' is ``entertainment, not literature.'' In the New
York Review of Books,  &UR; Norman Mailer &LR;  said that ``Reading the work
can even be said to resemble the act of making love to a 300-pound
woman. Once she gets on top, it's over. Fall in love, or be
asphyxiated.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparently retaliatory interview in a Charleston, W.Va.,
newspaper, Wolfe called Mailer and Updike ``two old piles of
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   When informed of this by a Canadian TV interviewer,  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Irving &LR;  jumped into the fray, saying he's unable to read Wolfe
``because he's such a bad writer.'' Irving called Wolfe's novels
``journalistic hyperbole described as fiction. ... He's a
journalist. ... He can't create a character. He can't create a
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wolfe asked about Irving, ``Why does he sputter and
foam so? Because he, like Updike and Mailer, has panicked. All
three have seen the handwriting on the wall, and it reads: `A Man
in Full.' ... Irving needs to get up off his bottom and leave that
farm in Vermont or wherever it is he stays and start living
again.''
</P>
