<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-KEARSE-COX     12-21 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEARSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Kearse wows NFL
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville, Tenn. _ Tennessee Titans defensive end Jevon Kearse
has a wingspan of 86 inches _ nearly the height of Hawks center
Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse's hands are huge _ he can hold the ends of a 12-inch
ruler between his little finger and thumb _ and he wears size 14
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   During a workout before April's NFL draft, Kearse ran the
40-yard dash under 4.5 seconds, speed usually reserved for very
fast running backs, cornerbacks and receivers.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder teammates, coaches and opponents call him ``The
Freak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy is physically very unusual. He can do some pretty
amazing things,'' said Denver Broncos receiver Travis McGriff, who
played with Kearse at the University of Florida. ``The guy is 260
pounds, with a 40-inch vertical leap. There's not too many people
walking this earth like that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Few NFL rookies have created such a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, 6 feet 4, leads the AFC in sacks with 13 1/2. He broke
the league's rookie sack record with two in last week's 30-17
victory over the Falcons. Today, Kearse probably will become the
first rookie defensive end from AFC named to the Pro Bowl since the
AFL-NFL merger in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Kearse said, ``(teammates and coaches) say, 'Man,
how did you do that?' It just comes naturally. Sometimes, I can't
believe it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen other NFL teams didn't think it would come so
naturally. Kearse, who began his college career as a safety before
moving to outside linebacker, fell to the middle of the first round
in the draft. Some NFL scouts were concerned that he was too big to
play linebacker; others said he was too small for defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they just didn't want to take a chance on taking a
'tweener' like me,'' Kearse said with a grin. ``I was moved around
a lot in college. I think other teams saw me as just a big,
athletic guy. Some thought I had to play outside linebacker. Others
thought I was just a pass rusher and not an every-down player.
Teams didn't want to take a chance, and that motivated me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team that passed me up may not play us, but they can
pick up the paper, see our record and my stats.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse's loss was the Titans' gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that everybody had a good feel for his gifts, his
talent and his athletic ability prior to the draft,'' Titans coach
Jeff Fisher said. ``We were extremely surprised he fell (to No.
16). Starting with about the sixth pick, we tried to trade up to
get him. We were unsuccessful, and then obviously he fell to us.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kearse leading the way, the Titans (11-3) have clinched at
least a wild-card berth to end their six-year absence from the
playoffs. Tennessee can move within one game of first-place
Jacksonville (13-1) in the AFC Central by beating the Jaguars in
Nashville's Adelphia Coliseum on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy might be the best athlete I've ever seen,'' said
Titans safety Blaine Bishop, a three-time Pro Bowler. ``I'm scared
to race him in the 40. I told him, 'If you pass me chasing someone
from behind, I'm retiring.'''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past eight games, Kearse has 10 1/2 sacks, 41 tackles,
nine quarterback pressures and seven forced fumbles. With four
sacks in their final two games, the Titans can break the team
record of 52, set in 1993 when the Houston defense coached by Buddy
Ryan led the NFL in sacks and run defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we didn't know about (Kearse) were the instincts,
the passion, the discipline, those kinds of things,'' Fisher said.
``He has been more than what we expected. He plays very, very hard.
He's extremely instinctive. He's not the biggest (defensive end),
but he separates off blocks. He understands the running game,
primarily because of the instincts. He's a gifted athlete. He's not
satisfied easily.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Titans wanted to find out about Kearse's heart and
determination, they had only to look at what he'd overcome in the
past. Kearse was one of seven children raised by a single mother in
Ft. Myers, Fla. His father, Joseph Kearse, was shot and killed in a
pool hall eight months before Jevon was born.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, his half-brother, Jermaine ``Rocky'' Green, was
killed at 17 in a drive-by shooting outside the family's apartment.
A grandfather and uncle also were murdered. Kearse's older brother
``J.J.'' is serving a prison term for armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the field, I tell myself that the guy lining up
across from me could be the guy that shot my brother,'' Kearse
said. ``Sometimes, I ask myself what my life would be like now if
I'd grown up with a father. Maybe my younger brother would be
alive. Maybe my older brother wouldn't be in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, if I had grown up with a father, I may not have
pushed myself to be where I am right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Kearse already is one of the top pass rushers in the
NFL, and he might be the best rookie defensive player since
linebacker Lawrence Taylor entered the league in 1981. Tennessee
fans are dancing to the song ``Le Freak,'' and they're cheering
for, of all things, a former Gator.
</P>
<P>
   ``In training camp, there was a play where Chris Sanders, one of
our fastest players, ran a slant pattern from the receiver position
on the opposite side of the field,'' said Titans cornerback Anthony
Dorsett, son of former Dallas running back Tony Dorsett. ``Jevon
was rushing the passer, was in the backfield, turned and ran
upfield and 30 yards downfield caught Chris and was in on the
tackle. We all said to ourselves, 'Man _ that's why he's the
``Freak.'' ' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``We all think he can have the impact like a Lawrence Taylor,''
Dorsett said. ``Think about it: This is his first year, so he's
going off raw ability. Just wait until he gets some (pro) smarts.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Titans defensive coordinator Gregg Williams wanted to
acclimate Kearse cautiously. When Kearse first became a defensive
end in April, he didn't know which hand to put on the ground in a
three-point stance. Early in the season, he played only left end.
But opponents started loading up that side, using tight ends to
help the right offensive tackle double-team him. Teams also keep
running backs in the backfield to chip-block him, making every
effort to keep Kearse away from the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to account for him,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said.
``He's one of those Lawrence Taylor types, where you have to make
sure you take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher says Kearse's best games lie ahead. The team has hired a
nutritionist from Vanderbilt University to add some weight to his
sculpted body. Kearse said his weight has dropped as low as 245
this season. He would like to be at 265 to 270.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher envisions using Kearse's power and quickness to create
mismatches. iKearse has enough speed to drop into the secondary and
cover receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's just scratching the surface as far as playing the
defensive line,'' Fisher said. ``We've put him in one position,
rather than moving him around, so he becomes familiar with one. . .
. I really believe that if Jevon keeps the same work habits and
stays healthy, he can be as good as he wants to be. And he wants to
be the best _ ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
