<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-REBUILD-C     12-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REBUILD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Look for new _ hopefully improved _ Falcons team in 2000
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons general manager Harold Richardson might make a
great used car salesman.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, he showed a sense of humor when asked about the
monstrous job of re-building the Falcons in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   He remarked that of the 57 players currently either on the
active roster or injured reserve, about 42 are signed or are the
exclusive property of the Falcons at least into the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which, if you look around the league,'' he said, ``is probably
about average.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's numbers are about right.
</P>
<P>
   But like a guy who wants his customer to look at the shiny paint
job without looking under the hood, he fails to acknowledge a few
key points.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the unsigned players were starters in last Sunday's 30-17
loss at Tennessee, and nine can become free agents. If right guard
Gene Williams were healthy, he'd have started, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but some of the players signed beyond this season
won't be around by the time the NFL draft rolls around in April
because they haven't played very well, or will be too expensive
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: If you see some Falcons players shopping tonight,
be nice. It's the holiday season, and besides, a lot of them will
be unemployed soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I really haven't got used to at this level,''
said second-year linebacker Keith Brooking, who will definitely be
back. ``You have to accept it. It's part of the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of all these unsigned players is that the Falcons
have about $15 million to spend under next season's projected $61
million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   That's rare, and good news for a team that had to trim its cap
last offseason by waiving wide receiver Tony Martin (also partly
for legal reasons) and linebacker Cornelius Bennett, and
re-structuring the contract of quarterback Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are the Falcons will go after after a top-notch wide
receiver with size, but plenty of parts will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Even Richardson acknowledged that having that much money to
spend is akin to holiday shopping with a new credit card.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a necessity,'' he said. ``If you're going to add
components, you have to have the resources available.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most curious potential missing faces next season
could be 13-year veteran middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle
</P>
<P>
   He's played well, despite missing two-and-a-half games with a
strained left patella tendon, but will be 35 next season. Still, he
wants money similar to what he's making now -- a salary of about
$2.9 million, and a salary cap charge of about $3.85 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rush on anything,'' he said. ``I think I can play
at a high level again next year. I want to try to end this thing at
15 years, and try to end as an Atlanta Falcon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I' in a position to try to say, `OK, I'll play
for less money.' I don't think my skills have slipped to that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the only starter to become a free agent was strong
safety William White, who the Falcons made no attempt to re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, you try to get those negotiations done
before free agency starts (a few weeks after the season),''
Richardson said. ``There are exceptions. It's a fluid situation.
They're looking (at free agency); we're looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
