u a BC-DEAD-MOTHER-BOS &LR;      12-21 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD EXONERATES TEACHER IN DEAD MOTHER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. _ The School Committee agreed in a closed
emergency session Monday night not to punish the first grade
teacher whose student, seven-year-old Lydia Hanson, came to school
two weeks ago saying, ``My mom is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Internal school incident reports that explain the morbid tale
indicate that Lydia sent mixed messages about her mother's health
to adults, including her teacher, Janet Makar, 57, according to a
source familiar with the documents.
</P>
<P>
   The child apparently failed to confirm that her mother was dead
after other students alerted Makar, the report said, and Lydia
later told another adult that her mother was merely ill. The child
took the school bus home, where she spent a night sleeping in her
dead mother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Several school committee members said it would be unfair to hold
Makar and other Kiley School staff members responsible for not
taking more decisive action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tragedy initiated by an act of God,'' said school
committee member James K. Liacos. ``We feel badly for the family,
the teacher and the counselor, but we believe you have to really go
on the judgment of the individuals involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lydia's grandmother, Sharon Tucker, did not have a strong
reaction to news of the panel's decision, which is to be made
public Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have mixed feelings about that. I don't know what to
say,'' Tucker said. ``I have my granddaughter, I just lost my
daughter, and that's all I'm focusing on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Hanson, a 33-year-old single mother, was a diabetic and
died of an enlarged heart, according to Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   School Committee members read incident reports describing the
events of Dec. 9 from the points of view of Makar, the guidance
counselor she consulted about Lydia, Kiley School Principal John M.
Murtagh, Superintendent Louis Perullo and the neighbor who drove
Lydia to school on the fateful morning.
</P>
<P>
   The documentation suggests that Makar handled the situation
appropriately, said School Committee member David D. McGeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the teacher did a very good job,'' McGeney said.
``For whatever reason, this girl did not reach out to any adults,
although she was in contact with several. The only adult that
picked up on any clues was her teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, the incident reports contradict what
Lydia apparently told Tucker and her husband, Richard Tucker, after
Richard Tucker found the child with her mother's body on the
morning of Dec. 10. Sharon Tucker said Lydia told Makar her mother
had died, but the teacher responded, ``You shouldn't say things
like like,'' and sent her back to her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Makar testified in her statement that boys in her class
approached her saying Lydia had told them her mother was dead,
according to the source, who described the documents on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   When Makar asked Lydia if she had said such a thing, the little
girl did not respond at all.
</P>
<P>
   Makar then asked, ``Is that an appropriate thing to say?'' Lydia
answered ``no,'' according to the source, who was paraphrasing the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school had not been contacted about any death and
Lydia had said nothing to the neighbor who gave her a ride to
school, Makar assumed that Kimberly Hanson was not in fact dead,
but still felt alarmed. ``Her experience told her that that's not
right; a kid wouldn't say that,'' said the source.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Makar, a 35-year veteran teacher, then told a
guidance counselor she wanted to speak about a student, but did not
specify the problem. The guidance counselor did not get back to
Makar until Lydia had left for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the teacher didn't leave it at that,'' the source said.
``She continued to monitor the girl's activities. She took a test,
she did well on the test. She ate lunch, she ate a good lunch. She
went to recess and played happily with the other kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tuckers said that Lydia could not call for help once she got
home from school because she did not know how to use her mother's
new cordless phone.
</P>
<P>
   However, the incident reports say that Lydia answered the phone
when a neighbor called to ask why the little girl did not show up
after school, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   When the neighbor asked if she was coming over, Lydia answered,
``No, my mother is sick,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was yet another adult she didn't reach out to,'' said the
source. ``I'm not a psychologist, but it seems that she hid the
fact that her mother had died from adults. I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee's decision to exonerate Makar and the Kiley
School was unanimous, said member David C. Gravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody made the decisions based on the information they
had,'' Gravel said. ``There was no flaw in the decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the panel said they would continue to examine the
city's policies and procedures for handling emergency situations.
Such policies are up-to-date, Liacos said, but he added, ``you
can't possibly think of everything that might arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Makar has suffered profound sadness over Lydia's loss as well as
her night alone with Hanson's body, said school committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's common nature that when someone is injured, particularly
a child, you want to find a villain,'' McGeney said. ``But there
are no villains in this case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
