A5663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STOCK-COX     12-21 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke, CCE given lower debt ratings
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Concern about higher debt and weak operating
performance prompted Standard &AMP; Poor's on Tuesday to lower its
ratings on the creditworthiness of Coca-Cola and two of its major
bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased debt levels, along with weaker-than-expected
operating performance at Coke and its key bottlers in 1999 due to
weak global economies and European product recalls, have weakened
creditor protection measures for the system below ranges considered
appropriate for the former ratings,'' S&AMP;P said in a release.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P's corporate credit rating on Coca-Cola Co.'s long-term debt
was lowered to ``A+'' from ``AA-,'' and the rating on its
short-term debt was lowered to ``A1'' from ``A1+.'' The ratings on
Coke's senior unsecured debt and shelf registration debt was
lowered to ``A+'' from ``AA-.'' The rating on commercial paper was
lowered to ``A1'' from ``A1+.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings on Coca-Cola Enterprises' and Coca-Cola Amatil's
long-term and senior unsecured debt also were lowered, from ``A+''
to ``A-.'' Coca-Cola owns 40 percent of Atlanta-based CCE and
around 37 percent of Coca-Cola Amatil, which is based in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The actions were not a surprise. In September, S&AMP;P put
Coca-Cola's senior debt on its credit watch ``with negative
implications.''
</P>
<P>
   The downgrades could make it more expensive for Coca-Cola and
the bottlers to borrow money. Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch,
however, said Coca-Cola is confident it will have access to lending
rates that are ``only slightly higher'' than the company has been
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch added that while the company was disappointed in S&AMP;P's
actions, ``we will continue to maintain an open dialogue with them
so they will continue to have a clear understanding of how our
business is operating.''
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P's highest ratings are ``AAA,'' meaning a company's ability
to meet its financial obligations is ``extremely strong,'' and
``AA,'' which means it is ``very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The third-highest rating, ``A,'' means a company's capacity to
meet its obligations remains strong but that the company has become
more susceptible to the ``adverse effects'' of changes in business
conditions, such as troubled markets or costly acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about $6.3 billion of total debt was outstanding at
Coca-Cola and about $11.2 billion was outstanding at CCE as of
Sept. 30, S&AMP;P says.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, ``Standard &AMP; Poor's does not believe credit
measures are likely to improve to levels consistent with the
previous `AA-' minus rating for Coke or the previous `A+' rating
for CCE and CCA over the next two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola shares closed Tuesday at $58.43 3/4, down $1.12 1/2.
CCE rose 25 cents to $18.37 1/2. Coca-Cola Amatil's American
depositary receipts closed at $4.75, down 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Seward writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
