<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-CLEAN-AIR-(TR     12-21 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CLEAN-AIR-(TRIMS)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNVEILS STRICTER CLEAN-AIR RULES TO LITTLE INDUSTRY
OBJECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 has been being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Striking a political balance that limited public
criticism, President Clinton on Tuesday announced the costliest
environmental regulations of his presidency: new air pollution
rules that will require automakers to build cleaner vehicles and
oil companies to refine cleaner gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The president's original proposal, issued last spring, was
modified in three ways to make it more palatable Tuesday to
automakers, oil companies and environmentalists. With Republican
and Democratic presidential candidates trying to portray themselves
as friends of the environment, the new rules have also won support
across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has the enthusiastic backing of
the oil and auto industries, set the political tone earlier this
month when he said in a debate in New Hampshire that he supported
the Environmental Protection Agency's plans for tougher rules. He
then asked Texas regulators last week to tighten state rules on
auto pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, Bush's leading rival for the Republican
nomination, said through a spokesman that he supported the new
rules, provided that they did not turn out to impose unacceptable
costs on consumers. Both candidates for the Democratic nomination,
Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, have long
advocated tighter auto pollution rules.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A year of political balancing by the Clinton administration, a
few last-minute adjustments to the regulations and a split within
the auto industry produced an extremely rare chorus of support
Tuesday for the regulations _ or at least acceptance of them _ from
automakers, oil companies and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, the lobbying arm of the oil
industry, said that while oil industry officials still disliked
some details of the plan, they would comply. ``This is going into
effect, and we're going to do our part to make it work,'' said
William Hickman, a spokesman for the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers also said Tuesday that they were not planning to
block the new regulations. Officials at General Motors Corp., which
has lagged rivals in reducing pollution from sport utility vehicles
and pickup trucks and which had lobbied against the new rules, said
Tuesday that they had decided against filing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the rule is there, we have to get on with the job of
meeting the standards,'' said William Noack, a GM spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists were the most enthusiastic. ``This rule was
No. 1 on our Christmas wish list,'' said Angela Farleigh, an
activist at the U.S. Public Interest Research Group, which inflated
a 15-foot-high, red balloon shaped like a sport utility vehicle
outside the elementary school in northeast Washington where Clinton
announced the plans. The group has lugged the inflatable vehicle,
dubbed the Exterminator, to protests in two dozen cities this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Tuesday at an elementary school in a low-income
neighborhood of northeast Washington, Clinton presented the new
rules as necessary for public health as Americans drive ever more
miles and increasingly buy sport utility vehicles, which produce
several times more pollution per mile than cars. He said the new
rules would prevent 4,300 premature deaths a year and 173,000 cases
a year of asthma and other respiratory illnesses among children.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma has become a scourge of inner-city children, for reasons
that are not entirely clear but seem to be linked to air pollution.
Gloria Hickman, the nurse at the elementary school, said that 25 of
the school's 315 students suffered from the ailment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They come in frightened, short of breath, scared,'' she said
in an interview. ``It tugs at my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of sport utility vehicles, which tend to pollute the most,
have leveled off at about 17 percent of the market over the last
three years, but are still climbing as a percentage of vehicles in
use, from about 8 percent now. Automakers are working on car-like
models that look like sport utilities, like the Subaru Forester,
but do not have the environmental and safety problems of
traditional, pickup-based sport utilities; General Motors, Ford
Motor and DaimlerChrysler all plan to introduce such vehicles next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimated that automakers and oil companies would spend
$5.3 billion complying with the new rules over the next few years,
but that cleaner air would reduce the nation's medical bills and
other health-related costs by $25.2 billion. That would make the
clean air rules the biggest of the Clinton presidency in terms of
costs and benefits by a wide margin, EPA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs will be so widely spread that opposition to the
rules never really coalesced. The EPA said that the rules would add
$100 to the price of a car, $200 to the price of a sport utility
vehicle and a couple pennies to the price of a gallon of gasoline.
The new rules will reduce allowable pollution from cars by 77
percent in the 2004 model year and then require so-called light
trucks _ sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and minivans _ to
meet car standards in the 2007 to 2009 model years. Light trucks
currently emit several times as much pollution per mile.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress from oil-producing states had posed the
biggest political threat to the new regulations, threatening last
spring to block the new rules through legislation. But the
administration tempered that criticism Tuesday by giving small
refineries two extra years to produce cleaner gasoline; Sen. James
Inhofe, R-Okla., who had led previous criticisms of the plan and
held hearings, welcomed the changes Tuesday, although he said that
he still had some misgivings about the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution rules on large sport utility vehicles were made even
more stringent than under the original proposal. The very largest
models, like the Ford Excursion, will be counted as family vehicles
for the first time instead of medium-duty trucks. This delighted
environmentalists, who had sent more than 100,000 postcards and
letters to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also postponed until sometime next year any
action on diesel vehicle pollution, to the relief of automakers,
who nonetheless remain worried about the possibility of tighter
regulations someday. Automakers want to start equipping more sport
utility vehicles with fuel-efficient diesel engines so as to meet
federal fuel-economy regulations. But environmentalists want much
stricter emissions rules on diesels, because some research has
suggested that the emissions may be carcinogenic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
