<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION CHIEF'S PAY LINKED TO STUDENT TEST SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Taking accountability to a new high at a time when
students, teachers and principals are under intense pressure to
boost test scores, Massachusetts will tie the state education
commissioner's pay raise to MCAS results.
</P>
<P>
   The move is believed to make the Commonwealth the second state
in the country -- Illinois is the first -- to link a state
education chief's pay even partially to student gains on a
standardized test.
</P>
<P>
   After voting to grant Education Commissioner David P. Driscoll a
6.75 percent pay increase to $149,450, Board of Education chairman
James A. Peyser suggested Driscoll's future pay hikes should take
into account improvement on students' MCAS scores.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll immediately agreed, joking that he would take a
vacation in May ``to run around all the schools urging the kids
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Details on exactly how much students have to boost scores still
have to be worked out, and Deputy Education Commissioner Alan
Safran said it would be up to the board to set those parameters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, however, raises questions over how far up the
education chain responsibility should extend for test results and
whether an education chief like Driscoll has any direct influence
over individual MCAS scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the key accountability questions: Who should be
accountable and for what?'' said Mary Fulton, a policy analyst for
the Education Commission of the States, a non-profit group
dedicated to improve public education across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises the question over what should be reasonable and
fair. Should you be accountable for something you have no control
over? We have to look at what makes sense and it's the same
question we are asking about students, teachers, schools and local
administrators,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher unions across the country have vehemently protested
tying teacher bonuses or pay hikes to student performance. They
insist it is unfair to hold teachers solely responsible for student
test scores because so many variables affect a child's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, education officials -- from Texas to Florida -- have
combatted with reams of research showing that a class' performance
and gains on a standardized test may be a good indicator of a
teacher's ability. In Florida, teachers get special bonuses if
their students perform particularly well or make significant gains
on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Lynn school officials won't give principals more
money until their students show a 10 percent improvement on the
Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, education officials had mixed responses to Peyser's
suggestion, with some saying it was only fair and others
questioning if such an incentive could somehow result in higher
test scores for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair,'' said Board of Education member Bill
Irwin. ``Everyone has to be held accountable; the students, the
teachers, the administration and even the Department of Education
and the Board of Education.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, along with fellow board member Roberta Schaefer and
Peyser, based Driscoll's current pay increase on three criteria:
effectiveness in building support for board policies; effectiveness
in supporting the board's work and effectiveness in managing the
state Department of Education. Driscoll's pay raise will take
effect in January.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll was appointed education commissioner March 10 1999,
after serving as interim chief for eight months. This is his first
raise.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said the recommendation to link test scores and
Driscoll's future pay ``sounds like an interesting idea, but I have
not thought through the ramifications of it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members did not vote on the issue or discuss it at great
length partially because Driscoll readily agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   How the board determines what is an acceptable gain will be
important, observers say. In Illinois, for example, state education
superintendent Glenn W. ``Max'' McGee's contract says test scores
are ``one of the factors that is going to be looked at,'' said
spokesman Lee Milner, but doesn't mention specific goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
