<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTSON, RECOVERING FROM BROKEN FOOT, PRACTICES WITH TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Danny Fortson will not be expected to solve all of the
Celtics' problems when he returns for their visit to the Los
Angeles Clippers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Fortson's recovery from a broken right foot is an
encouraging sign as the Celtics take a six-game losing streak into
Wednesday's game against Atlanta. Fortson participated in his first
full practice at Brandeis University Tuesday since being injured in
the second game of the exhibition season. His foot has completely
healed, but he will need more conditioning before playing,
according to coach Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have struggled against opposing frontcourts and were
simply overmatched against Los Angeles' Shaquille O'Neal in a 99-90
loss Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won against L.A.,'' Fortson said. ``We've had a
couple of games like that. It was frustrating for me in the
beginning to watch and not be able to help out. But the more and
more I work out it's not so bad. I've learned to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to just go out and win, simple as that. Nobody is
going to feel sorry for you in the NBA. But we are a young team and
we are making progress. If we were a veteran team and we were
losing games we would have major problems. But we're still young
and coach Pitino is pointing us in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics have lately been moving in a negative direction,
with three wins in their last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers are playing with a lot of confidence, Shaq is a
dominant player, and they believe they can beat the world right
now,'' Fortson said. ``But L.A. is beatable. And we can have that
same kind of confidence as long as we don't read the papers, just
come here and focus on beating teams on the court. It shouldn't
become a psychological problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' visit to Los Angeles marks the start of a
three-game road trip. And the Celtics have a nine-game road losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling rebounding and (Fortson) gives us another
physical presence,'' said Paul Pierce, who remains out with a
sprained left ankle. ``He is one of the best rebounders in the NBA.
And rebounding is the key. The other team can't get second shots,
and it gets our transition game flowing, everything flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's return has not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not rushing things,'' Pierce said. ``I want to make sure
I'm 100 percent. I'm anxious to get back out there and whhen the
doctors and trainer say it's time, I'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating. You never want to be the guy on the
sidelines when you know you could help the team so much. But I've
been learning a lot by watching, learning the strengths and
weaknesses of my teammates and different ways I can fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to find ways to get wins, to get more offensive
consistency, consistency everywhere. We say every day that in order
to be a playoff team we've got to win road games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
