A5669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE-COX     12-21 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preacher fields gift, Holyfield queries
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Creflo Dollar of World Changers Ministries says he
gave Fulton County police $100,000 to help financially strapped
officers, not to buy favor.
</P>
<P>
   And Dollar, speaking on a video, said he won't participate in
the Evander Holyfield divorce case because divorce violates his
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time the leader of the 20,000-member church
has publicly commented on the two controversial cases. He explained
his position in videos that his lawyer released Tuesday morning to
reporters after a court hearing in Fayetteville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar said he gave $1,000 checks to 100 Fulton County police
officers last month as a way of showing his support for law
enforcement officers. He said he empathized with police because his
late father was a law enforcement officer who often worked extra
jobs to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never the intention to make it look like we were trying
to buy the police,'' Dollar said. ``I want to apologize for it
being taken completely the wrong way. It was an act of kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollar said the checks, handed out in November at an
appreciation breakfast in south Fulton County, had no connection to
two traffic tickets he received in October. Those tickets were
downgraded to warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar said that ``$100,000 for a $150 ticket, that would not be
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton County Ethics Board in Atlanta voted last week that
officers must give the money back to Dollar and the church.
</P>
<P>
   Money is a major element in the second controversy Dollar
addressed, the high-stakes divorce case of Janice and Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar does not want to answer questions from Janice Holyfield's
lawyers about how much money the former heavyweight champ donated
to Dollar and the church. Janice Holyfield's lawyer estimates it's
$7 million. Dollar has been ordered to give a deposition, but
refuses to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is against my religious convictions to participate in the
divorce proceedings of Evander and Janice Holyfield,'' Dollar said
on the video. ``I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollar said the Bible orders him to keep people married, not
help them get divorced. He said he'd lose his freedom of religion
if he had to answer questions about counseling the Holyfields.
</P>
<P>
   When Dollar didn't show up for a court-ordered deposition
Tuesday morning, Fayette County Superior Court Judge Ben Miller
found Dollar in contempt and ordered the minister jailed until he
agreed to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar's lawyer, Lecora Bowen, immediately appealed to the
Georgia Court of Appeals, thus keeping Dollar out of jail. Miller
has said some communications between Dollar and the Holyfields,
such as confessional statements, were privleged.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal usually takes several months. John Mayoue, one of
Janice Holyfield's lawyers, didn't know if that would delay the
Holyfield divorce trial, which is scheduled to start April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar is a leader in the ``prosperity gospel'' movement, which
teaches that God promises wealth and health to the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Ellis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
