<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Dec. 22, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-DEATHS (Undated) _ The asbestos-tainted ore that killed
and sickened hundreds of miners and their families in Libby, Mont.,
didn't stop there. Millions of pounds of the ore were shipped from
a mine near Libby to at least 60 processing plants throughout the
United States and Canada, causing workers at many of those plants
to become ill and die, a Post-Intelligencer investigation has
found.
</P>
<P>
   with:
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-DEATHS-JOIREMAN (Undated) _ You don't have to spend an
entire career shoveling asbestos for it to kill you. Lee Joireman
was 21 and trying to get money for college. He worked as a laborer
hauling tons of tremolite-laced vermiculite ore from the boxcars to
the ovens at the Western Vermiculite Co., a Zonolite processing
plant in Spokane. Thirty-six years later, the 23 months he spent on
the dusty job killed him.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Stories will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BIOWARFARE-SCIENTISTS (Richland Wash.) _ Just a few years ago,
Dr. Vladimir Bugreyev was making deadly biological weapons in the
secretive ``closed city'' of Stepnogorsk in the Kazakhstan region
of the former Soviet Union. His potential target: The U.S. and
other military foes of the USSR. Now, Bugreyev is working with
American scientists at the U.S. Department of Energy's Pacific
Northwest National Laboratory to learn to put his skills to
peaceful and commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MOON (Undated) _ ``Man on the Moon'' is often hilarious,
and it also offers a reasonably strong, A-level star vehicle for
Jim Carrey. But it offers no special insights into its subject,
Andy Kaufman, it doesn't connect on any higher level, and it left
me feeling vaguely dissatisfied and let down.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MOTHER (Undated) _ Spanish director Pedro Almodovar has run
the gamut from good to ugly in his wildly flamboyant films. So it's
lovely to note that ``All About My Mother'' is as dark as a Greek
tragedy yet it has a vibrance and joie de vivre that can't be
contained by grief.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SWEET (Undated) _ Like most Woody Allen movies of the '90s,
``Sweet and Lowdown'' never tries to be a laugh riot, and aims more
at maintaining a consistent level of irony and whimsy. It's
entertaining, but somewhat trivial and underwhelming, and you do
finally get tired of it before it's over.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SUNDAY (Undated) _ When a football movie carries the names
of Oliver Stone and Al Pacino in its credits, one might reasonably
expect it to be an imaginative examination of the prototypical
American institution. But the duo's near-three-hour gridiron
extravaganza, ``Any Given Sunday,'' is one more sports film about a
talented hot-shot rookie who learns to be a team player _ a plot
that was a groaning cliche even in the Silent Era.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LIBERTY _ With ``Liberty Heights,'' director-writer Barry
Levinson returns to the '50s in a valentine to the roots of a big
change-for-the-better that is about to consume '50s America.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Mets GM, fearing charges of
tampering, warns his players not to call Ken Griffey Jr. to try to
talk him into OKing that trade. Here's what such a phone
conversation might sound like.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Indianapolis) _ Seattle SuperSonics travel to
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
