<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5673 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-XMAS-TRAVEL-COX     12-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-TRAVEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Tis the season to hurry up and get there
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the Pakula family, visiting relatives this holiday
season meant bundling up their 3-year-old toddler and packing their
belongings for an overnight train trip to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, Laura and Louis, and their son, Frank, made the trek
south from Baltimore along with 135 other passengers on a packed
Amtrak train that arrived Tuesday morning. Laura's mother, Norma
Barnes, is glad they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have your children around you during the holidays makes it
special,'' Barnes said with a smile while playing with her
grandson, who raced around the train station laughing and playing.
``He's my youngest grandson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakulas are among nearly 45 million Americansexpected to
travel by planes, trains, buses and automobiles over the holidays,
according to estimates by the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport are
predicting the Thursday before and Sunday and Monday after
Christmas will be among their busiest travel days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia and throughout the Southeast, close to 9 million
motorists are expected to hit the highways for holiday visits. It
will likely be slow going in many places.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be in heavy, heavy, heavy traffic,'' said
Teresa Hildebrand, regional director of the AAA's Atlanta office.
</P>
<P>
   She said her agency is hearing reports of growing congestion
along Interstates 75 and 95, vital north-south routes. ``They can
expect longer delays and more cars on the road,'' Hildebrand said.
</P>
<P>
   No universal rules ensure travelers reach their destinations in
time to unwrap presents with the family and sip egg nog by the
fireplace come Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But travel industry executives say passengers can increase the
odds that their trip will go without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   For example, AAA's Hildebrand said motorists should be sure
their cars have emergency equipment, including a spare tire and
hazard reflectors.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested fuel tanks be topped off because stop-and-go
traffic is likely. Drivers also should make sure their cars are up
to the journey because a mechanic will be hard to find. ``It is
going to be more difficult to limp to the next exit and find
maintenance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AAA believes more motorists will choose to drive this year
because there have been fewer discounted airfares and many people
will stay closer to home with the Y2K uncertainty surrounding the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   At Hartsfield, the biggest crush will occur on the days just
before and after Christmas, with passenger volumes each day
expected to average 230,000 travellers.
</P>
<P>
   The next peak occurs Jan. 3, when more than 245,000 passengers
are forecast to pass through Hartsfield. Airport crowds likely
won't approach those of the Thanksgiving holiday because the
Christmas-New Year's period occurs over weekends, said John
Kennedy, a Delta Air Lines spokesman. ``We are saying the bookings
are 'soft,' because we have two two-day holidays and it's more
spread out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials said passengers can ease the bumps in their
travel experience by arriving early for check-in, by having photo
identification and tickets readily accessible and by calling to see
whether parking lots are open before driving to the airport.
Greyhound Bus Lines said it expects to carry a record 1.3 million
people this holiday season. ``We're doing exceptionally well,''
said spokeswoman Kristin Parsley. She credits a surge in ridership
to low fares, new bus terminals and added buses for routes with
high ridership.
</P>
<P>
   Bus riders should arrive at least an hour early to check in,
Parsley said. And, ``Bring anything that's going to make you
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials declined to predict their passenger loads this
holiday season. But rail officials suggest passengers arrive at
least 30 minutes prior to their train's departure. Officials at
Amtrak's Buckhead office said Tuesday they are expecting large
crowds, especially as Christmas draws near.
</P>
<P>
   For Louis Pakula, traveling by train is the only way to go. ``I
used to travel by train while growing up,'' he said while waiting
to collect his family's bags. ``I prefer it over flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Charles writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Gary Hendricks contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
