<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILMS-REINVENT-$ADV26     12-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-REINVENT-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING FRESH WAYS TO SEE AND TO SELL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The major film motif of 1999 was reinvention, both on and off
the screen. Characters and filmmakers alike found significant ways
to renew themselves. Rekindled careers (Robert Altman's with
``Cookie's Fortune,'' Spike Lee's with ``Summer of Sam''),
revisionist notions of storytelling (``Run Lola Run'') and the
jump-starting of an entire genre (animation with ``Princess
Mononoke'' and ``Toy Story 2,'' not to mention the wicked ``South
Park'' musical).
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood even found a way to put aside the usual playbook and
make this Christmas season virtually formula-free.
</P>
<P>
   The grass-roots marketing triumph of ``The Blair Witch Project''
sent the message that here, too, was an opportunity for reimagining
the familiar. (The single smartest ``Blair Witch'' brainstorm: ads
that cropped the terrified face of Heather Donahue &UR;  &LR; so that this
did not appear to be the kind of low-budget indie film that would
let the camera linger indefinitely on her running nose _ even
though it was.)
</P>
<P>
   The fact that so much of moviegoing America responded to the
interactive, Internet-driven ``Blair Witch'' siren song means that
the usual ways of attracting film audiences are growing outmoded.
And the imaginative salesmanship may pave the way for more
rewarding idiosyncrasies on screen.
</P>
<P>
   These are the 10 best films of 1999, with their shared
fascination for phoenix-like transformation:
</P>
<P>
   `TOPSY-TURVY' Mike Leigh's gloriously witty and literate foray
into music appreciation. In Leigh's account of how the popular team
of Gilbert and Sullivan escaped their creative doldrums and
concocted ``The Mikado,'' the portrayal of a theatrical world is
immensely clever. And this film's delightful homage to the artistic
process is art in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY' Within the tabloidy tale of a young woman's
gender-bending masquerade, Kimberly Peirce's film found an
essential American tragedy and a terrifying vision of barren,
small-minded life. But her film's vast reserve of hope and beauty
was its great surprise.
</P>
<P>
   As played unforgettably by Hilary Swank, without whom the film
might not have succeeded, the character of Brandon Teena became a
touching emblem of freedom: the chance to reach beyond the
limitations of circumstance and bravely shape a different destiny.
</P>
<P>
   `ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER' Pedro Almodovar, himself no stranger to
the idea of flamboyant reinvention, showed dazzling new ambition
and wisdom in his most mature work yet. Dedicated to film stars who
have played actresses onscreen, this bold, passionate melodrama
brought out the noble heroine in each and every one of its
characters, regardless of gender.
</P>
<P>
   In a newly sweeping, generous style, and with ever more striking
visual sophistication, Almodovar created a group of fabulously
resilient feminine types. The hilarious centerpiece: Antonia San
Juan, as the film's resident transsexual, cataloging all the
womanly perfection that money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   `THE STRAIGHT STORY' Somehow it took David Lynch to lead
audiences past the ultimate frontier: into a G-rated parable of
spirituality and decency, seen from the unfashionable vantage point
of old age. Lynch accomplished the unthinkable by putting Richard
Farnsworth, in a devastatingly real and rock-solid performance, on
a lawnmower at 5 mph and still building enough drama and emotion
for a great chase.
</P>
<P>
   Burned out on the surreal and the grotesque, Lynch faced down
inevitable realities about aging and conscience. In yet another
story of a character who radically redefines himself, he made the
most touching and quietly eloquent film of the year.
</P>
<P>
   `THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY' In a richly nuanced, elegantly
inventive adaptation of Patricia Highsmith's bone-chilling story of
stolen identity, Anthony Minghella beautifully demonstrated that
the exquisite acuity of ``The English Patient'' was no fluke. He
reached beyond the story's criminal particulars and touristy
ambience to explore the psychosexual shadings and socioeconomic
game-playing inherent in its central murder. Minghella was once
again adroit in shaping a first-rate literary adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   `BEING JOHN MALKOVICH' In this jubilant funhouse of a debut
feature, Spike Jonze made a great display of wild, idiosyncratic
humor as he captured the essence of life on the seventh-and-a-half
floor. Never mind the film's curious stooped-over characters and
their strange elevator stop: What Jonze really caught better than
any other film this year was the mind-boggling sensation of a world
bursting with wild new technological possibilities. Portals into
famous brains? Exit routes to the New Jersey Turnpike? ``Being John
Malkovich'' had a giddy new elasticity, a high-tech sense that
anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER' Finally connecting with material to suit his
sleek, impressionistic style, Michael Mann fused agile technique
with a hard-hitting corporate parable. With Russell Crowe
outstanding as a tobacco company man turned whistle-blower, this
glossy, expertly crafted drama framed a moral dilemma for a
ruthlessly business-minded world.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN MOVIE' This funny, beguiling documentary introduced a
would-be independent filmmaker hell-bent on making horror movies.
And then it artfully revealed why, for him, filmmaking was a life
or death proposition. The essence of game, wishful independent
filmmaking could not be captured more honestly _ or entertainingly
_ than this.
</P>
<P>
   `EYES WIDE SHUT' Stanley Kubrick's posthumous dreamwalk, a
voyage into sexual mistrust and the uneasy balance between id and
propriety, elicited the year's most disastrous hype. But it remains
one more brilliantly unnerving nightmare from a filmmaker who never
lost his fascination with the dissolution of man's civilized
veneer.
</P>
<P>
   `THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS' In this emotionally raw and astute
French film about two young women and their friendship, questions
of power, loyalty and sexual manipulation figured effortlessly into
a naturalistic drama. A haunting coming of age tale, exemplary for
the rare force and purity of its vision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
