<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BLACK-CHOREOGRAPHERS-     12-21 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-CHOREOGRAPHERS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLACK FLOWERING AND A BURST OF BIG SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26)  
 (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black choreographers, especially a younger generation, stepped
into the spotlight as a group this year. All had an individual
stamp, but many shared an attraction to African dance movement that
they stylized and absorbed into a personal vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   This very new fusion of idioms makes for work that is abstract
and avant-garde. There was no mistaking the cumulative impact of
recent pieces by, notably, Garth Fagan, Ronald K. Brown, Jawole
Willa Jo Zollar, Donald McKayle, Bill T. Jones, Judith Jamison,
Reggie Wilson (a relative newcomer) and Dwight Rhoden (his
``Twist'' was delivered with dazzle by Dance Theater of Harlem).
</P>
<P>
   It was also a year of blockbuster events. The New York City
Ballet held a mammoth 50th-anniversary celebration. Lincoln Center
Festival '99 carved out a major place for dance. The Kirov Ballet
offered a behemoth of a ``Sleeping Beauty.'' The New Europe '99
Festival added pep with witty surprises in three boroughs. As other
highlights suggest, the best also came in smaller packages.
</P>
<P>
   HERBIN (TAMANGO) VAN CAYSEELE A tap dancer, he is both
sensational and a well-kept secret to most of the dance public. A
cult audience is nonetheless familiar with his astonishing elegance
and virtuosity, a blend of swaying curved form, lightning speed and
skimming floor rhythms. One is tempted to call him the best dancer
of any kind around.
</P>
<P>
   Van Cayseele hails from French Guiana by way of Paris and the
world is visibly his stage. Thanks to the Kitchen, the Manhattan
performance space, his multicultural production ``Urban Tap'' gave
him wider exposure. The musicians and dancers from several
continents that he gathered for this occasion included Max Pollak,
a Cagneyesque tapper, and Eijo, a prancing Artful Dodger. A magic
show led by a wizard.
</P>
<P>
   RONALD K. BROWN ``Grace,'' created for the Ailey company, put
this choreographer over the top as a major talent, although his new
works at the Joyce Theater for his own company, Evidence, presaged
the fireball intensity that ``Grace'' received from the magnificent
Ailey cast at City Center. Telly Fowler, an extraordinary dancer in
Evidence, remains the paragon of the explosive energy and liquid
fluency with which Brown's work has been identified since his
sojourn in the Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY BALLET The company's 50th anniversary bash, with
100 ballets spread out over two seasons at the New York State
Theater, got better and better. Fresh insights flowed from the
``Balanchine Black and White Celebration,'' a concentrated dose of
the modernist works that make this company unlike any other. Love
it or hate it, Peter Martins' full-length ``Swan Lake,'' with
splendid sets by Per Kirkeby, cleared away old-fashioned clutter.
Maria Kowroski, a dancer of the 21st century, was the most stunning
Swan Queen.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder other choreographers used her in premieres: Martins'
``Them Twos'' and the rollicking suite of jazz ballets ``Duke!'' by
Robert La Fosse, Fagan and Susan Stroman. Add Christopher
Wheeldon's delightful ``Scenes de Ballet'' plus a thrilling revival
of George Balanchine's creepy ``Ivesiana,'' and it turned out to be
a happy birthday after all.
</P>
<P>
   MERCE CUNNINGHAM Lincoln Center Festival '99 presented a
smashing tribute to a choreographer who has changed the way we look
at dance. Cunningham more than returned the compliment with
splendid New York premieres and revivals at the State Theater.
``Biped'' was the production spectacular, integrating live dancers
with striking animated figures that Paul Kaiser and Shelley Eshkar
had generated through ``motion-capture'' technology. Cunningham's
unfettered originality was seen in the equally haunting ``Pond
Way,'' a subtle nature piece.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EUROPE '99 A three-week showcase of cutting-edge work from
Europe revealed a range of aesthetics that thankfully had more
creativity than coherence. The big hit was Felix Ruckert's
``Hautnah,'' an exploration of audience-performer boundaries at
Joyce SoHo, obliging the viewer to be shut up alone with one
dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sasha Pepelyaev's brand of physical theater at Dance Theater
Workshop showed how dramatically things have changed in Russia. At
the Brooklyn Academy of Music, Jan Lauwers' Needcompany, with
choreography by Carlotta Sagna, confirmed that Belgium remains a
hotbed of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   France was represented by Jose Montalvo's technological wizardry
at the Joyce Theater and by the Compagnie Kafig, which turned
hip-hop into a mesmerizing visual symphony at Hostos Center for the
Arts in the Bronx. A message to David White of Dance Theater
Workshop and his fellow organizers: Encore.
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA GRAHAM DANCE COMPANY What is there to say about Graham,
the mother of it all, except that at her most hermetic, she is
often at her grandest. ``Herodiade'' and ``Dark Meadow'' are among
her enigmatic works, and they were led this year with superlative
power by Terese Capucilli and Christine Dakin. Graham's legacy has
been loyally and beautifully preserved by Ron Protas, the company's
artistic director. Thanks to this season at the Joyce Theater, a
generation of young audiences discovered Graham's genius and
clamored for more.
</P>
<P>
   MOISEYEV DANCE COMPANY Igor Moiseyev turned 93 during the
national tour of his famed folk company from Moscow. Of course, no
folk ever danced like these astounding virtuosos who brought down
the house at Carnegie Hall. Among the premieres, ``Jewish Suite,''
an ingenious vignette about a wedding in Czarist times, and
``Bashkir Dance,'' lyrical in its mystery, testified to Moiseyev's
continuing innovations as a choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL TAYLOR'S ``OH, YOU KID!'' In this small suite to ragtime,
Taylor created an American parable. For all the sepia glow and faux
nostalgia of the hilarious boardwalk imagery, dark forces were
evoked and got the Taylor treatment. The Ku Klux Klan became a a
mincing chorus line, and Lisa Viola, in a knockout contortionist
performance, was the exploited cooch dancer, a stereotyped vision
of people from foreign climes. Behind the laughter, pain. Thanks go
to the American Dance Festival and the John F. Kennedy Center for
the Performing Arts for commissioning the piece.
</P>
<P>
   AFTERIMAGES Marcel Marceau, face painted white but persuasively
turning green with seasickness at the Kaye Playhouse; Damien Welch,
the heartthrob of the revitalized Australian Ballet at City Center;
the bravura and artistry of American Ballet Theater's male stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
