<HEADLINE>
SHIP SALVAGES MORE HUMAN REMAINS FROM FLIGHT 990 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising hopes that relatives of EgyptAir crash victims might
claim some remains of their loved ones, a deepwater salvage ship
returned to a Rhode Island port Tuesday with aircraft wreckage and
body parts retrieved from the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Smit Pioneer docked at Quonset Point at 6 a.m. and began
unloading 16 large containers, each about the size of a commercial
trailer, for distribution to hangars at the former Navy base. The
human remains will be sent to a morgue set up there by the state
medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-foot-long piece of EgyptAir Flight 990 was the largest
wreckage plucked from the bottom during 750 deployments of a
clamshell bucket dropped from the ship. The piece's location on the
plane had not been identified, according to Ted Lopatkiewicz, a
spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Other items brought back by the Smit Pioneer, a Dutch ship
leased by the Navy, included passenger seats, seat covers and other
parts of the cabin interior. Clothes and personal items belonging
to the victims were also found during the ship's 10 days at sea.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, the NTSB chairman, said Tuesday he did not know how
much of the Boeing 767ER-300 had been retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, our investigators believe that parts from all areas
of the aircraft have been recovered, most of which are very small
due to the extreme fragmentation of the aircraft fuselage,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the jetliner wreckage will be laid in a hangar to dry,
then examined for clues about the cause of the Oct. 31 crash off
Nantucket that killed all 217 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   The process will take several weeks, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   No information about the nature or amount of recovered human
remains, which will undergo DNA testing, was disclosed by the NTSB
or the state medical examiner. Nearly all the previously discovered
remains, retrieved in the first days after the crash of the Boeing
767, had broken into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatkiewicz said no decision had been made whether the Smit
Pioneer will return to the wreckage field. Over the next two weeks,
the Navy will send a submarine to survey the 270-foot-deep area to
determine whether more work is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, crews recovered an 8-foot section of the aircraft
with three windows, and a nose wheel before high waves forced the
salvage effort to cease for about a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was quite a bit of wreckage where we felt there was
going to be,'' NTSB spokesman Keith Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the crash, underwater robots retrieved the cockpit
voice recorder and flight data recorder.
</P>
<P>
   While the newly found wreckage is sorted, catalogued and
examined, investigators will continue their probe into what caused
the jetliner, en route to Cairo from New York, to plummet into the
ocean at near-supersonic speeds after a terrifying dive and climb.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that a co-pilot might have crashed the aircraft
purposely followed news leaks that the cockpit voice recorder
contained part of an Islamic prayer just before the fatal dive.
</P>
<P>
   US and Egyptian investigators reportedly have been at odds.
However, Egyptian Ambassador Nabil Fahmy said last week at a
gathering of the Boston-based World Affairs Council that the
investigation has been progressing well, and that the public knows
only 1 percent of what has been a cooperative effort overall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
