<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-TERROR-GROUP-BOS &LR;      12-21 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-GROUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS WEIGH ALGERIANS' POSSIBLE LINK TO BIN LADEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Algerian men are behind bars _ one in
Washington state suspected of trying to smuggle a truckful of
bomb-making materials into the United States, the other in Vermont
who was in a car with possible traces of explosives in its right
rear fender.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, the government's corridors are abuzz
about the end-of-the-year terrorism threat from UBL _ the acronymn
for Osama bin Laden (US officials spell his first name ``Usama'').
</P>
<P>
   What's the connection between bin Laden, believed to be hiding
out in an Afghanistan cave, and two Algerians trying to sneak into
the United States?
</P>
<P>
   Those knowledgeable about counterterrorism said it could be a
link that reaches back to the early 1980s when bin Laden led a
brotherhood of Arab fighters in Afghanistan, giving him well-armed
friends throughout the Arab world, including in the Algerian Armed
Islamic Group. Or there could be nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the hunger for information on bin Laden, and on the
Algerians, is growing by the day, as the year comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scare is on,'' said Hussein Ibish, communications director
of American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee in Washington.
``Unfortunately, you could see the scare began even before the
arrest of the Algerian in Washington state, emerging in the
warnings and cautions given by the State and Justice departments.
When they mentioned the millennium, they said a particular cause of
concern was the holy month of Ramadan, as if it were a dangerous
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan is a month of spiritual reflection and fasting for
Muslims, not a particularly violent time historically, with the
notable exception in recent years in Algeria, where massacres were
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, though, violence in Algeria has dropped
significantly, and President Abdelaziz Bouteflika's amnesty plan
for Islamist fighters has appeared to split the armed resistance
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But those who study terrorism in general and bin Laden in
particular say if there is a link between the arrest of the
Algerians and bin Laden's Feb. 23, 1998, declaration of holy war
against Americans, it is unlikely to be driven by internal Algerian
developments.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, parts of bin Laden's Al Qaeda network, a loose group of
Islamic militants from Indonesia to Algeria, could be activated by
word of mouth after an order is given from bin Laden, a member of a
Saudi Arabian family that has made billions in construction
projects, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can assume there is a plan to attack Americans, either
abroad or in the United States, or both,'' said Boaz Ganor,
director of the International Policy Institute for
Counter-Terrorism in Israel and a former top adviser on terrorism
issues to the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure the GIA (the Algerian Islamic group) would
target the United States, but I do think it's possible that
specific people in the GIA who have connections with bin Laden
could try to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's worldwide advisory for Americans living
or traveling abroad to exercise caution until after the New Year
was based on specific information that came from the arrests of 11
Jordanians, an Iraqi, and an Algerian who were plotting attacks on
Christian pilgrimage sites in Jordan, said officials there. The
group was funded by bin Laden's close associate, Omar Abu Omar,
Jordanian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, US intelligence specialists were first alerted
to a possible bin Laden terrorism plan targeted for Western Europe
when Turkish authorities said six members of a reported bin Laden
commando unit had infiltrated Turkey. The six, still at large, are
four Iranians and two Algerians. Two weeks ago, Turkey police
detained six Libyan men suspected of planning an attack on the
American Embassy in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-American sentiment in the Middle East has its roots in
the Gulf War coalition against Iraq, the nine years of sanctions
against Iraq, and the perceived pro-Israeli bias in peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US government is hated,'' said Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi in an interview Tuesday with CBS' ``The Early Show.'' ``All
the people in the world are against it, therefore, there is a
threat. I hope it will not happen in this new year. I have no
knowledge about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, in his 1998 statement urging holy war against
Americans that he and four other Islamic militant leaders signed,
claimed that America was eager to ``destroy Iraq'' and occupy the
holy Arabian peninsula with its troops.
</P>
<P>
   The statement then declared, ``The ruling to kill Americans and
their allies _ civilians and military _ is an individual duty for
every Muslim who can do it in any country in which it is possible
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials have linked bin Laden to the two East Africa US
embassy bombings last year that killed more than 200 people;
terrorist training camps in Afghanistan and Sudan; and a group that
tried to bomb American servicemen in Yemen in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But in Vermont Tuesday, US Attorney Charles Tetzlaff said there
was no evidence linking the two arrested Algerians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm skeptical,'' said Ibish of the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee. ``I don't doubt that a wealthy man
can arrange things, even nasty things if he wants. But he sort of
has assigned this role to himself, in which he spends a lot of time
giving blood-curdling interviews. In the Arab world, the man is
widely regarded as a crank and a dangerous fanatic.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, which has posted a $5 million reward
for information leading to bin Laden's arrest, spokesman James B.
Foley tried to strike a balance in describing the nature of the
threat to Americans in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the American public that this is a yellow light.
It is not a red light,'' Foley said. ``We are urging Americans to
be vigilant and cautious as they travel, but we are not
recommending to Americans that they change their plans and that
they not travel overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about Americans at home?
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is meeting do discuss the issue. The
FBI continues its investigations on the Algerians. Customs
officials have put an extra 300 guards on duty, and all their
border posts on high alert.
</P>
<P>
   And top officials, including Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright, General Henry H. Shelton, and CIA Director George Tenet,
met Monday at the White House. But after two hours of discussions,
they decided not to make public any of their drafted statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to take this day by day,'' Foley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
