<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-RATES-380&AMP;ADD-NYT     12-21 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED LEAVES RATES UNCHANGED, BUT HINTS IT MAY RAISE THEM IN
FEBRUARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve on Tuesday voted to leave
interest rates unchanged, but warned that it might raise rates
early next year to head off inflation if the economy continues to
grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank stopped short of adopting a formal policy
signaling the likelihood of a future rate increase, saying that it
did not want to risk throwing the financiats off balance in
the weeks leading up to the Year 2000, given the possibility of
fallout from the associated computer software problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed's policy-setting committee issued a statement making
clear that it was only the potential for Y2K disruptions to the
markets and the economy that kept it from formally putting
investors on notice that a rate increase might come as soon as its
next meeting on Feb. 1 and 2. And the practical effect of the
statement was nearly the same in any case, emphasizing the Fed's
willingness to consider a rate increase if the economy continues to
run so hot that it generates inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed may formally be neutral, but you don't even have to
read between the lines to see that they're biased towards
tightening policy,'' said James Glassman, an economist at Chase
Manhattan in New York. ``A new chapter of Fed tightening is
certainly on the table for the February and March meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed almost never raises rates in the weeks before Christmas,
and given the added concerns over Year 2000 computer problems,
analysts had long ago concluded that the central bank would not
push rates up Tuesday. On Wall Street, investors read the Fed's
decision not to adopt a formal bias toward raising rates as good
news, sending stock prices modestly higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 56.27, closing at
11,200.54. Bond prices fell, sending up interest rates. The yield
on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 2 basis points, or
hundredths of a percent, to 6.46 percent, its highest level since
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is little evidence that inflation might be taking
root, despite economic growth this year of about 5 percent, a level
that economists once assumed would set off broad-based increases in
wages and prices, especially with unemployment as low as it is now
_ 4.1 percent in November.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The economy's remarkable performance has led to wholesale
re-evaluations among Fed officials and economists generally about
the relationship between growth and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe the economy is now capable of substantially
higher levels of noninflationary growth base their case on the huge
investments by American business in computers and other technology
and the associated pickup in the growth rate of productivity, or
the amount that a worker can produce in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But in raising its short-term federal funds target rate three
times this year to 5.5 percent _ and through its statement Tuesday
_ the Fed has stressed that even a more productive economy can bump
up against inflationary pressures that needed to be squelched
before they can endanger the long expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee ``remains concerned with the
possibility that over time increases in demand will continue to
exceed the growth in potential supply, even after taking into
account the remarkable rise in productivity growth,'' the central
bank's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such trends,'' it continued, ``could foster inflationary
imbalances that would undermine the economy's exemplary
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it was nonetheless maintaining its current
neutral policy stance to emphasize that its focus in coming weeks
``must be ensuring a smooth transition into the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   At its upcoming meeting in February, the statement said, ``the
committee will assess available information on the likely balance
of supply and demand, conditions in the financial markets and the
possible need for adjustment in the stance of policy to contain
inflationary pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the economy has retained its considerable
momentum as it heads toward the new year. Some of the robust growth
may come from companies' stockpiling goods and supplies as a
protective measure in case the economy is disrupted by widespread
computer problems starting Jan. 1. But most of it continues to stem
from strong consumer demand and a buoyant stock market, heavy
levels of business investment and a rebound in many foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Many forecasters say the economy is likely to slow next year but
not right away and probably not until the Fed pushes the federal
funds rate up by at least half a percentage point, to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do expect a slowdown, but I don't think it will be
sufficient to ward off more Fed tightenings, and I don't think it
will be apparent in the first month of the year,'' said Marilyn
Schaja, an economist at Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette. ``We'll see
at least two more Fed tightenings with the potential for a third if
the economy does not slow.''
</P>
<P>
   As the prospects grow for a series of rate increases next year,
so does the likelihood that the Fed will become a political issue
in a presidential election year. But the White House reiterated its
support Tuesday for Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, whose term expires
in June. President Clinton is widely expected to nominate Greenspan
to a fourth four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes he has done a good job, has a lot of
respect for the job he's done and likes him personally, and when
we're ready to announce a decision, we'll announce a decision,''
said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan and his colleagues are likely to face some
difficult decisions about how much leeway to grant the economy,
given the absence of inflation, the benefits of low unemployment
and robust job creation and the wealth being created by the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Robert DiClemente, an economist at Salomon Smith Barney in New
York, said the Fed might even consider a half-point rate increase
in February if domestic demand and the stock market remain strong.
The Fed has not raised rates by half a percentage point since
February 1995, at the end of a tightening cycle that saw the
central bank double the federal funds rate to 6 percent in the
course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems facing the Fed is that higher rates so far
have done little to restrain Wall Street, whose continuing rise is
seen by most economists as a key driver of consumer confidence and
spending.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also indications that even sectors of the economy
that traditionally have been most sensitive to rising rates, like
housing, have so far remained relatively robust. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
