<HEADER>
A5684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABERNATHY-GUILTY-COX     12-21 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABERNATHY-GUILTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abernathy III convicted of theft, other charges
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It will be the new millennium before a judge decides
whether former state Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III will serve
anything from a maximum of 150 years in prison to a minimum of
probation for stealing state money with false expense reports.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 hours of deliberation, the second jury to try Abernathy
returned with a verdict Tuesday that found him guilty of 18 of the
28 counts against him _ 5 of theft by taking involving $5,700, 5 of
false swearing, 5 of violating his oath of office, 2 of forgery and
1 of influencing a witness.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no lone holdout, refusing to even consider
convicting an Abernathy, to cause a hung jury, which is what other
jury members said happened in his first trial in September.
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy spent much of his time during the jury's deliberations
studying two Bibles and making notes from them. The verdict seemed
to come as no surprise to him or to his mother, who spent every
moment of both trials in the courtroom. When the judge finished
reading the verdict, Abernathy turned to his mother with a glum
smile. He, his mother, former state Rep. Hosea Williams and other
supporters formed a prayer circle, holding hands across the bar.
Abernathy remained silent while Williams and Mrs. Abernathy prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that not only Ralph but every one of us has fallen
short,'' she prayed. ``We pray, oh God, that this does not mar our
Christmas season.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy refused to speak with reporters. Attorney General
Thurbert Baker, accused by Abernathy's supporters of mounting a
vendetta against him, said ``it is always a sad day when any public
official violates his trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, looking weak and ill from recent surgery but still
combative, complained that Abernathy ``would have been better off
if he'd been tried by the Ku Klux Klan.'' Abernathy, he insisted,
did nothing that other legislators don't do.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, a core member of the group that worked
with Ralph David Abernathy Sr. and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
during the 1960s, said he is ``deeply saddened'' and hopes the
conviction won't stand.
</P>
<P>
   He added, in a written statement, ''Even though Ralph felt that
he was simply behaving as others around him did, we cannot always
act like the Romans, even when we are in Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that in three instances from 1994-1998 while he
was a member of the state Senate, Abernathy got aides or assistants
to sign vouchers saying they had received specific amounts of money
for services rendered, although in fact they had not. Then
Abernathy signed the vouchers _ which included an oath that the
information it contained was true and accurate _ turned them in to
the legislative fiscal office and was paid. But the aides who were
supposed to get the money got little or none of it.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, he obtained $1,200 to pay a telephone bill, of
which a maximum of $700 was paid.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth and most damning case, he signed the name of Zee
Bradford, his public relations consultant, to two vouchers for a
total of $2,700, never gave her a nickel of it, and then, when the
GBI began investigating his actions, was tape recorded in two
conversations begging, cajoling and bullying her to lie and say she
had signed the vouchers and received the money. She refused, and
testified for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Senior Superior Court Judge L.A. McConnell ordered a
pre-sentencing investigation by probation authorities and indicated
he would not decide on a sentence before mid-January. Asked what
kind of sentence he would seek, Baker said mildly that ``We think
all these felony counts are deserving of jail time.'' Assistant
Attorney General Stacey Hydrick, who prosecuted both trials,
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Tyrone Brooks charged that Baker is ``using the
Abernathy family as a political football.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy's career has been in a tailspin since 1994, when he
led East Point, Ga. police on a high-speed chase because, he said,
he was late for a speech before some elementary school children. He
drew a fine for that. Six months later, a female state employee
said Abernathy barged in on her and refused to leave while she was
inside a Capitol restroom.
</P>
<P>
   A GBI investigation is still ongoing into the interception of
the lunch-bound jury in September's trial by Mrs. Martin Luther
King Jr., members of her family and other civil rights luminaries.
Martin Jr. was the only member of the family to show up during this
trial, and he did not enter the courtroom while the jury was
present.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, customs authorities caught him coming into the
country at Hartsfield International Airport with marijuana in his
underwear. That cost him a $500 fine and a sanction from the
Senate. Last year, he lost his seat when his $400 qualifying check
bounced and the Democrats refused to put him on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Gita M. Smith contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
