<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-AD-COLUMN- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING:  PITCHING  TO WOMEN WATCHING PRO FOOTBALL GAMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES- NYT  
 (ATTN: Colo., Minn., Wis., Fla., Mass., N.J., Texas)   By COURTNEY KANE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After decades of televised professional football,
some advertisers are finally catching on that women watch the games
too.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers that include an airline, a credit card company and
even the National Football League itself have aimed more pitches at
women during the games. Some see it as an unconventional way to
reach their target audience, while others regard it as a unique
option to cut through the advertising clutter. Others are just
simply taking advantage of the increase in female viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, the new efforts show marketers now realize
that women are not only a significant part of football's fan base,
but, more importantly, that they have buying power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have been part of our audience for some time, but
they've clearly evolved from detached and less knowledgeable to far
more involved and connected,'' said Howard Handler, senior vice
president for marketing and fan development at NFL Properties in
New York, the league's in-house marketing unit.
</P>
<P>
   The league says more than 20 million female fans consider
themselves to be avid and approximately 45 million female fans in
general _ about 40 percent of the total 113 million viewers who
constitute the NFL's weekly television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a significant portion of the audience is female,
most ads during football games are dominated by marketers of
products that mainly appeal to men like shaving accessories, beer
and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a steady progression of more and more advertisers
finding many different segments of our audience to market to,''
Handler said. ``As more and more audiences become fragmented and
sponsors strive to find places where they can talk to an entire
family, you're going to see more and more of a broad range of
advertisers and sponsors associated with our games.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is partly responsible for some of the other marketers'
decisions to focus on women. As part of the league's own fan
development campaign, Handler said that the NFL had started sharing
more of its fan-base research and brand expertise with its
advertisers. ``Our partners were really astonished by this in some
ways,'' he said, adding that ``I think that we did a good job of
planting some seeds in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   A commercial from the NFL that is aimed at women, introduced
earlier this month, features the coming of age of the female
football fan. The humorous spot, which spans the decades from the
1960s until today, shows a couple watching football together;
gradually, the woman becomes more knowledgeable about the game than
the man. The commercial, the third installment of the NFL's ``Feel
the power'' fan development campaign, was a collaboration between
the advertising and design group at NFL Properties and Sally
Jenkins, an author who wrote the commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines was one of the NFL's first sponsors to
recognize the league's female fan base. Last year, the airline
began a campaign, ``Must be football season,'' that featured women
as football fanatics in two of its four spots. This year, three of
four commercials will portray women as passionate fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting women in ads appeals to a group of people that are
often ignored in sports campaigns,'' said Melanie Jones, a
spokeswoman for Southwest in Dallas. ``These days, a lot of women
are really sports fans and they watch those games. And they're our
customers too and we wanted to reach them.''
</P>
<P>
   One commercial in the campaign, created by the GSD&AMP;M unit of
Omnicom Group in Austin, Texas, takes place in a gift shop. A woman
grabs a crystal vase, spikes it and does a victory dance. Another
spot features a woman standing in a movie theater line when a man
in front of her drops something and he bends over to pick it up:
she assumes a quarterback's stance behind him and starts shouting
signals.
</P>
<P>
   Visa USA has run an ad in response to the NFL research. The Visa
spot, created by BBDO New York, another unit of Omnicom, features a
pregnant woman and husband in a paint store seeking a very specific
shade of orange _ presumably for a nursery. But the woman is shown
at a Denver Broncos game, her face painted orange and blue _ the
team's colors _ cheering heartily. The spot ends with the tagline,
``Visa. Everywhere NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Silver, senior vice president for advertising and
brand management at Visa in Foster City, Calif., said developing
the commercial was a ``very easy step'' after seeing the NFL's
research.
</P>
<P>
   For Campbell Soup Co.'s Chunky Soup brand, an ad created by
Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York, features Terrell Davis, the
Broncos running back, along with an actress portraying his mother.
</P>
<P>
   John Faulkner, a spokesman for Campbell in Camden, N.J., said:
``We certainly recognize that the NFL is an environment where both
men and women consumers enjoy watching the NFL games. While Chunky
is primarily thought of as a men's soup, the reality is that a lot
of women eat Chunky as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best evidence of how much appeal football has to
women and the marketers who court them is Super Bowl XXXIV on Jan.
30, where one longstanding NFL sponsor and two brand-new ones are
willing to pay enormous rates to broadcast spots that pitch to the
female fan. A commercial for the Miller Brewing unit of Philip
Morris Cos., created by Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis, is part
of the Miller Lite campaign in which two celebrities debate what
makes Miller Lite taste great. This spot features Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos, the model, and Jimmy Kimmel, the comedian, debating
the greatest Super Bowl teams of all time. Kimmel acts as if he is
a football expert but consistently fumbles on the nicknames of
classic teams and Ms. Romijn-Stamos corrects him.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bussen, a spokesman for Miller in Milwaukee, said the ad
supported the Miller Lite Super Bowl promotion in which consumers
select the greatest Super Bowl team of all time. He said the
company's objective was to appeal to both sexes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
