<HEADER>
A5692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOOTBALL-AD-COLUMN-2N     12-21 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-AD-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: both sexes. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oxygen Media in New York, a World Wide Web site and cable TV
network aimed at women, is hoping to draw attention with its first
national television commercial during the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the Oxygen spot, created by Mullen Advertising in
Wenham, Mass., part of the Lowe Group unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos., were not disclosed. But Linda Ong, senior vice president for
marketing at Oxygen said that ``We want to claim the territory,
crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous opportunity,'' she added. ``It's the largest
viewing audience of women on television. Women have been there all
along, watching with families, friends, boyfriends, husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana Products in Bradenton, Fla., which traditionally
advertises during female-oriented programming, is also advertising
during the Super Bowl for the first time to introduce a new
campaign that stresses the nutritional benefits of orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl has transcended from being a sporting event to
a real social event,'' Roger Berdusco, senior vice president for
marketing at Tropicana, a division of PepsiCo, said. ``We're
reaching a very broad audience in one fell swoop.'' Details of the
commercial, created by the New York office of the FCB Worldwide
unit of True North Communications, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The league clearly hopes more advertisers follow this trend.
``What we believe,'' Handler of the NFL said, ``is that Visa,
Southwest, Miller and Campbell are going to open up a lot of other
people's eyes to see that certainly the NFL is a place to look for
men _ but women are hearing and responding to these messages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
