<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GAMEPLAN-ART-780(     12-21 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GAMEPLAN-ART-780(TRIMS)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL GAME PLANS ARE A CHESS MATCH WITH 300-POUND GAME PIECES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Sean Payton, in stocking feet and a gray
Giants sweatsuit, charged into the darkened room excited and
talking fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one for you,'' said Payton, the Giants' assistant
coach who now calls the team's plays. ``We'll call it Tiki
Special.''
</P>
<P>
   It was early last week in a conference room beneath the Giants
Stadium grandstand and Payton, who had interrupted a meeting of
Giants' defensive coaches, hastily began to sketch small black
circles on a white plastic board.
</P>
<P>
   To the whirl of a film projector and the crunching of sunflower
seeds, he scribbled slashing lines, dashes and arrows _ a football
hieroglyphic _ until every coach in the room easily understood.
</P>
<P>
   It was a new, trick play for the Giants' game against the St.
Louis Rams last Sunday _ a faked handoff to running back Tiki
Barber, who would amble away from the flow of the play as if a
decoy, until the last moment, when quarterback Kerry Collins would
throw back to him streaking up the left sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll buy that,'' said John Fox, the defensive coordinator
whose job it is to shoot holes in any new play.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, Payton's diagram came to life as Barber, at a
pivotal juncture of the third quarter, caught a 22-yard pass to the
Rams 2-yard line. The Rams had been duped; Tiki Special had worked.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of hundreds of plays the Giants coaches devised
in a painstaking week of preparation for what turned out to be a
discouraging 31-10 loss to the Rams. The play's inception accounted
for just 10 minutes out of seven days of intensive plotting to play
three hours of football.
</P>
<P>
   To follow an NFL coach from Monday to Sunday is to witness a
numbing succession of meetings, statistical analysis, critiquing of
video tape, along with lengthy after-dinner skull sessions when the
sche plays and defenses are debated and ultimately agreed
upon.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exercise removed from anything athletic, a chess match
of anticipated moves on a gridiron with 300-pound game pieces. The
skill prized above all is the art of deception, as opponents'
tendencies are examined and their weaknesses weighed. The goal is
to play your game with your players but to look completely
different doing it.
</P>
<P>
   When it is done, an average game plan, bound neatly in a blue
spiral notebook with plays and explanations produced by computer,
is more than 125 pages thick.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just for the offense. The defensive game plan is
another 100 pages.
</P>
<P>
   All this work is done to try to control the outcome of a game
played with an oblong ball pointed at both ends that takes wildly
unpredictable bounces. And as the Giants would soon find out last
Sunday, all their planning can be undone by the simplest misstep.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays after Barber's catch, on another new play designed
specifically for the goal line situation the Giants were in, guard
Ron Stone, the team's best lineman, stepped on the foot of Collins
as the play began, tripping him.
</P>
<P>
   It was meant to be a pass to fullback Greg Comella, a play the
Giants discovered while dissecting the video tape of a Rams game
from six weeks ago. In a meeting room last week, the Giants'
offensive coaches had run the tape of the play, a Lions touchdown
against the Rams, back and forth 16 times to be sure they had
captured every nuance.
</P>
<P>
   This new play would have worked, too. Comella was breaking open
in the end zone as Collins stumbled to the ground, where he was
tackled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God,'' a coach yelled into Fassel's sideline headset as
other coaches added more saucy comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up,'' Fassel yelled. ``Next play. Kick the field goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Which the Giants did. But instead of cutting a 10-0 Rams lead by
7 points, the Giants never threatened again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the realism of this job just hits you,'' Fassel
would say in his office the day after the game, laughing ruefully.
``It's the right situation, right defense, right call and it
doesn't matter because somebody steps on the quarterback's foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a week earlier, in the midst of the weekly 17-hour
strategy marathon known as game plan Tuesday _ the day when NFL
coaches design the offensive and defensive attack for that week's
opponent _ Fassel paused to relate a conversation he once had with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kitty said to me, `What are you doing there all day and
night?' `` Fassel said. ``And I explained the whole day down to
every last detail. I said: `Amazing, isn't it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Told there might be other words for the seemingly endless work
hours in the average week of a NFL coach, Fassel snickered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``Stupid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' coaching staff arrives each weekday before sunrise,
never later than 6:30 a.m., and when they arrive on Monday morning
_ sometimes less than 12 hours after a big victory or defeat _
there are 25 to 30 video tapes of the next opponent set in a row
neatly across their desks.
</P>
<P>
   At the computer screen on an adjacent credenza, with a few
clicks of a mouse, they can also view virtually any play the
opponent has run during the season _ and they can find it easily
because the plays are categorized by down and distance, by quarter,
even by what players, or groups of players are on the field. If
they see a play that intrigues them or might be useful to another
coach, they can send it to him via the fiber optic cables
connecting the offices.
</P>
<P>
   But first, they would give the play a name, in code, because
everything inside a football office is in code. A play that begins
with the number 12 means a one-back formation with two tight ends.
A play beginning with 21 is the inverse, since the first number
refers to the number of backs on the field and the second the
number of tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the name of the play can have seven different terms,
something like 10 Split Load Left Dig Zany Oscar Eagle 44. Late
last Tuesday, near 11 p.m. of a workday that began 17 hours
earlier, the offensive coaches spent four minutes discussing where
to insert the word ``shift'' in the terminology of a new play.
</P>
<P>
   It does matter. The 11 players on the field are supposed to move
in unison, and each code word in the play's name gives them
complicated rules to follow should the defensive formation change,
which is likely, or should the defense blitz, which is common. If
everybody follows the rules together, every play is technically a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, listening to the coaches debates in their meetings is
like trying to eavesdrop on a conversation in a foreign land where
you don't speak the language.
</P>
<P>
   If a coach says a receiver is going to ``bus ticket,'' it means
he's taking off on a deep pass route. If a lineman ``pops,'' he's
pulling wide of the formation. If a defender ``dogs,'' he's coming
after the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   And they never refer to the players by the positions football
fans know and recognize. The quarterback is the ``q,'' the wide
receivers are ``x'' and ``y,'' and the linebackers have four names
based on where they line up: Will, Mike, Sam and Buck.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all high-tech. On Tuesday morning last week, Fassel
was having his first cup of coffee just past 6 a.m. when offensive
line coach Jim McNally bolted into the room. He wanted to show the
head coach a new blocking scheme he had designed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Soon McNally was aligning two blue swivel chairs to mimic
defensive linemen, a bookcase was a defensive end, the couch the
other end. The red, holiday Pachysandra on Fassel's desk was
apparently out of play.
</P>
<P>
   But McNally made his point and Fassel agreed that's how the
guard should line up against that defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel smiled as McNally left the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody does this unless they love it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that is the same about the Giants' offensive and
defensive meeting rooms, which are no more than 20 feet apart, is
that each has a bottle of Tabasco sauce and a bottle of
Worcestershire sauce in the middle of the main conference table.
There is apparently agreement on the condiments needed when dinner
is delivered by a catering firm.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive room is bright, with coaches continually jumping
up to draw prospective plays or formation adjustments on the white
plastic board that's replaced the conventional black chalk board
from Knute Rockne's day. Sometimes two or three coaches will be
diagramming the same play, drawing lines and circles as they
dispute certain details until the whole board becomes an
indecipherable mess resembling a transit system map.
</P>
<P>
   They wipe if off with an eraser and start over.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive room, meanwhile, is usually dark because the
coaches are watching video tape. They are constantly searching for
clues, ways the upcoming opponent might tip off what play they plan
to run, or what part of the field they plan to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes though, the coaches fly by the seat of their pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, they're going to score points so we're going to
have to take some chances,'' Fassel said Wednesday evening in the
third-down meeting.
</P>
<P>
   So two long pass plays were included as surprises for a third
down-and-short situation. Three new plays for the fleet wide
receiver Brian Alford were added to the package. After weeks of
practicing a reverse option pass by receiver Amani Toomer, the
Giants decided to try it.
</P>
<P>
   (When run in the game, it succeeds in getting a pass
interference penalty on the Rams, but a 31-yard gain is nullified
by a Giants penalty.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I get out of here, sit in my backyard with a cigar
and think about what we ought to try,'' Fassel said of the game
plan later in the week. ``You can't let these four walls narrow
your thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   When John Fox went home two Fridays ago _ on his only night off
in the week _ he found himself in his living room watching football
tapes for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was watching an entire season of youth football, played by
sons, Cody, 7, and Mark, 9. Their games were Tuesday nights when
Fox is inside Giants Stadium. His wife, Robin, taped the games.
John watched them all in one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see them running around,'' Fox said. ``Usually
I only see them asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday night, the Fox family, which includes another son,
Matt, went out to dinner with Payton and his wife, Beth, and
daughter, Meghan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean and I will get away with talking a little shop at
dinner,'' Fox said. ``We'll compare notes on the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the things Fox and the other coaches detected in their
diligent study of the Rams: a minute tick in the stance of the Rams
left tackle Orlando Pace.
</P>
<P>
   When Pace lined up with his left foot in back of his right foot,
with the heel slightly raised off the ground, the Rams were going
to pass. When Pace's left heel was touching the ground, the Rams
ran the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just looking for details in that dark room,'' Fox said. ``It
doesn't hit you all at once. You go, `Hey, look at that. Look at
his heel.' &UR; '' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were hoping to get an edge with their stealthy
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Pace's stance was a fairly accurate predictor, until he
was ejected from the game for a late hit early in the second
quarter. Since Pace hadn't missed a game, the Giants knew little
about his replacement, a converted center, Ryan Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   As Pace left the field, departing with him was any advantage to
the hours of preparation for playing against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you wonder if we should just line up and play,''
Fassel said in his office Monday afternoon, a day after all the
best-laid, highly-intricate plans  &UR; _ &LR;  including many that worked
 &UR; _ &LR;  resulted in a 21-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, it ain't going to matter. But you have to put your
players in the best position to win and hope it helps them execute.
As coaches, this is what we do. &UR;  &LR; And in a little while, I'll start
watching tape of the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't think about last week again,'' Fassel said. ``I've got
a week now to figure out how to beat Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
