<HEADER>
A5698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ALABOWL-COACHES-C     12-21 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALABOWL-COACHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowl brings together pair from past
 &HT;    By Alan Wooten
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ East Carolina's Steve Logan and Texas Christian's
Dennis Franchione have known each other for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   As small college coaches in Kansas, Franchione often came by to
recruit Logan's junior college talent.
</P>
<P>
   But the duo didn't speak to each other for a long time. The
reason was simple enough _ both are from the Midwest and while
Franchione stayed there and in the southwestern part of the U.S. as
a coach, Logan came to the East Coast 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been on the other end of the world,'' Logan said. ``It's
just one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   They renewed acquaintances earlier this week when they arrived
for the inaugural Mobile Alabama Bowl. Tonight, for the first time,
they send teams against each other when Logan's East Carolina
Pirates meet Franchione's Texas Christian Horned Frogs in
Ladd-Peebles Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis has done a fine job, everywhere he's been,'' Logan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two remember a pretty good relationship when they were
working in Kansas in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   For Logan, this match-up against his friend will be a far
different day on the sideline as compared to his last. In that, the
Pirates beat N.C. State 23-6 to finish the regular season _ and
finish the head coaching tenure of a head coach, Mike O'Cain, for
whom he had a good deal of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, I want to win every game that I coach, but
two years ago when Mike O'Cain won the football game, I had a great
deal of joy for him because I knew they weren't going to fire him
that day,'' Logan said of a season-ending 1997 loss at N.C. State.
``The same thing, you flip it two years later, the incident that
happened out here, again, the empathy and compassion I had for him
. . . I just had a bad, bad feeling about what could happen and, of
course, it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in their right mind would take any joy in that.
Somebody that is of a sick mind would probably have a good time
with that. That is not where I want to live and it isn't where I
live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan and Franchione trace their relationship back to 1981.
Logan was the head coach at Hutchinson (Kan.) Junior College in
1981-82, the same two years Franchione was at Southwestern (Kan.)
College. It was the first head coaching stops for both _ each of
whom had started in the high school ranks and had a brief stint at
a major Division I program.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern was one of more than a half a dozen
church-affiliated, NAIA Division II programs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year after the real-deal recruiting had been over with,
he would always stop by and see what we had,'' Logan said.
``Kansas, K-State, Nebraska _ all those people would come in and
see what we had, and whatever was left, all those church schools
would come by and see if they could get a player or two.''
</P>
<P>
   And he usually found something he liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always looking for the diamonds in the rough, the ones
bigger schools looked at and didn't find something they liked,''
Franchione said. ``You're always looking for players that are
near-misses.''
</P>
<P>
   After Franchione left Southwestern for Tennessee Tech as
offensive coordinator in 1983-84, he had a chance to return to his
alma mater _ NAIA Division I perennial national title contender
Pittsburg State (Kan.). He hinged on making the move, but finally
did and spent 1985-89 coaching the team to five conference titles
and three national semifinal-round appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Pittsburg State, in some ways, was a tough decision. But
a conversation with a friend convinced him his time at Pittsburg
State had lasted long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a point, we had been there five years, and sometimes
you take winning for granted,'' Franchione said. ``I'll never
forget. We had been in the national playoffs, ranked number one
twice, and the year before my last year in June, I had someone come
up and ask me who I thought we'd play in the playoffs. And we
hadn't won a game yet. And that stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the '89 season, Southwest Texas State had posted five
straight losing seasons and was in need of a head coach. Franchione
was the man pegged for the job. Two years later, New Mexico was
searching, then finding Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends in coaching said you don't want to go there, it's a
deathbed,'' Franchione said. ``There were things there that
intrigued me and I did it. They had 11 straight losing seasons, and
the year before I got there, they lost 94-17 (to a Jim
Sweeney-coached Fresno State team) and 60-7 (to a Jim
Wacker-coached TCU team).
</P>
<P>
   ``The next year, my first year at New Mexico, our first game was
TCU and (new head coach) Pat Sullivan and we beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lobos went on to climb into a bowl game by Franchione's
sixth, and final, season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that Dennis has always done, he's always been an
option coach,'' Logan said. ``He's always been real creative with
the option.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Mexico hadn't won in a million years, and he went out
there and built a program _ 3-8, 6-5, 5-7, 4-7, 6-5, 9-4. Now, TCU,
they've been down. They were 1-10 when he got in there. He took
them to a 6-5 first year and beat Southern Cal in a bowl game with
the option. Southern Cal, they were clueless with superior athletes
and lost the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, going through the ranks to the top rungs of Division
I-A means head coaching stops, as it was with Franchione. For
others, it means going through jobs as an assistant, as it was with
Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione assures he could have remained at Southwestern for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be the head coach, to be in charge _ I liked
that,'' Franchione said. ``I was not hung up on any particular
level I was at. Some coaches would rather be on the D-I level, but
that didn't matter to me. I enjoyed coaching whether there were
5,000 people in the stands or 55,000. I'm just a ball coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way was good for me, and I had some good years. I was
fortunate. I had the opportunity to move up from time to time, and
if I had not have moved up, I don't think it would have been that
big of a deal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference, of course, is compensation and exposure.
There was little of either at Pittsburg State despite the success,
and there's plenty coming at TCU. The pay range is about 10-fold _
somewhere between $75,000 and $80,000 to the more than $700,000 he
earns with the Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been real caught up in the money,'' Franchione
said. ``I'm always telling people I wouldn't want to be two things
_ real rich and real poor. I'd be lying if I said I don't enjoy
what I have.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my motivator has always been opportunity. To do something
that hasn't been done in a while. To see that there are people
committed to doing those things well. That's far exceeded my
excitement level about a job more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan is much the same.
</P>
<P>
   He embraced the challenge of building a program _ and succeeded.
His eight-year tenure is the longest of any ECU coach in 30 years,
and his 51 wins are the most in school history.
</P>
<P>
   But he rarely gets wrapped up in the match-up of coaches. He'll
enjoy this one, mind you, but it won't cloud his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to go out there and focus on what we can do
well, and what are we going to do for us,'' Logan said. ``We coach
that way all week long. I'm concerned somewhat about Texas
Christian's lead option, but I'm more concerned about us
enthusiastically getting to the ball, taking care of the lead
option scheme with a lot of hustle and enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Wooten writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
