<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO CLOSE TO REGAINING CONTROL OF PRIZED SIBERIAN OIL FIELD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ BP Amoco PLC, one of the biggest foreign investors in
Russia, has tentatively reached an agreement with a Russian oil
company to resolve a long-running conflict that threatened to
destroy the petroleum giant's half-billion-dollar investment in the
country, people close to the negotiations said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which could be announced as early as Wednesday,
BP Amoco would regain authority over a prized Siberian oil field
sold in a questionable bankruptcy auction to the Russian company,
Tyumen Oil.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco's dispute with Tyumen has come to symbolize problems
that foreign investors have confronted in Russia. If the agreement
holds, it would mark an important if rare victory for BP Amoco,
which had not ruled out the possibility of leaving Russia out of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday night whether the deal was directly
related to broader pressure on Russia from the United States.
Earlier Tuesday in Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright ordered the U.S. Export-Import Bank to suspend approval of
$500 million in loans to Tyumen because of Russia's faltering
economic reforms, corruption and military action in Chechnya. The
agency left open the possibility that the loans could be approved
later.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, BP Amoco has plowed most of its Russia
investment into a 10 percent stake in Sidanko, a onetime oil
conglomerate that formerly owned some of the most valuable energy
assets in Russia, notably the Chernogorneft field in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, production subsidiaries of Sidanko have been
pushed into bankruptcy and sold off under controversial
circumstances, essentially leaving the parent company as an empty
shell.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen bought Chernogorneft at a fraction of its value. BP Amoco
and others have accused Tyumen, which is nearly half-owned by the
Russian government, of tampering with the courts to influence the
bankruptcy proceedings and liquidation sales.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen acknowledges it was interested in acquiring
Chernogorneft, but denies using questionable methods.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the expected agreement, Tyumen would return
the Chernogorneft oil field to Sidanko, and in return receive an
equity stake in Sidanko of 25 percent plus one share, people close
to the deal said. BP Amoco, a British-based company with major
American assets, would keep the 10 percent stake it owns in
Sidanko, but its voting rights would be the same as Tyumen's. Such
holdings are known as ``blocking stakes,'' giving both companies
seats on the Sidanko board and sufficient leverage to influence the
company's business activities.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco would also get managerial authority over Sidanko and
its subsidiaries, essentially giving it control of the
Chernogorneft field.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the negotiations said it was still possible that
the agreement could fall apart. Spokesman for Tyumen, BP Amoco and
Sidanko declined to comment on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unclear if the acrimony between BP Amoco and Tyumen
could be quickly put aside so as to allow Sidanko to resume
functioning properly. All involved in the talks appear interested
in building the Chernogorneft field, situated in northwestern
Siberia, more than 1,500 miles east of Moscow, and adjoining other
Tyumen property.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism it has endured over the Sidanko dispute,
Tyumen Oil is considered a strong company that has worked hard to
develop its fields and refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think that Tyumen's push to refurbish its aging,
Soviet-built assets may have been one reason why it decided to
negotiate a settlement. And the Export-Import Bank loans to Tyumen,
whenever approved, would allow the company to overhaul an important
refinery and improve production at a major oil field.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. Ex-Im keeps postponing the loans, and they're very
important to Tyumen,'' said Dmitri Avdeyev, oil analyst with the
United Financial Group, a Moscow brokerage firm. ``And they
probably realized that with the reputation they had gotten, foreign
capital markets would be closed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen Oil appears to have agreed to a solution that gives them
a stake in Sidanko worth far less than the Chernogorneft field.
``Twenty-five percent is too low for giving up Chernogorneft,''
said Ivan Mazalov, an oil analyst with the brokerage firm Troika
Dialog. ``Chernogorneft accounts for half the value of Sidanko.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people who have followed the BP Amoco-Tyumen struggle said
the Russian government might have brought pressure on the rival
parties, in light of the damage that has already been done to the
country's reputation as a place for investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight wasn't just bad for Sidanko,'' Avdeyev said. ``It
was bad for the whole market. And so any fair compromise will help
restore sentiment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
