<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MOON-REVIEW-LADN     12-21 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MOON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARREY BRIGHT BUT `MOON' WANING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' opens with a loopy five-minute prologue that
promises a movie that would positively delight its subject, the
late oddball comedian Andy Kaufman. Nervously facing the camera,
Jim Carrey's Kaufman (it might as well be Kaufman, the performance
is so completely encompassing) welcomes us to his movie,
apologizing (in a way, rightly so) for it being ``stupid'' and
``terrible.'' The end credits then roll and Carrey leaves the
screen, only to return shortly afterward to ask: ``What are you
still doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   What are we doing here, indeed? Well, we're not learning
anything about Kaufman, that's for sure. In bringing their latest
eccentric to the screen, writers Scott Alexander and Larry
Karaszewski (``Ed Wood,'' ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'') have
decided to let Kaufman's ``art'' speak for itself, making no
attempt at any point in the movie to get inside Kaufman's head. But
the film's shapeless script, combined with some surprisingly
listless direction from Milos Forman, renders Kaufman a complete
cipher. Ultimately, this is a movie that's remarkable only for
Carrey's uncanny channeling techniques.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, ``Man on the Moon'' seems unconventional by its very
conventionality. Instead of evolving like a standard, three-act
biopic, ``Moon'' leaps almost directly into Kaufman's career, never
stopping for a moment to consider how he arrived there. Of course,
with Kaufman, one must wonder: Was there a there?
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the film, Kaufman complains to his girlfriend
(Courtney Love, more or less playing her public persona) that ``you
don't know the real me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a real you,'' Love retorts.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman's reply? ``Oh, yeah. I forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly a legitimate point of view, but it doesn't make
for much of a movie. ``Man on the Moon'' plays like one long
performance reel of Kaufman's greatest bits: singing ``The Mighty
Mouse'' theme on ``Saturday Night Live,'' playing Latka on
television's ``Taxi,'' wrestling women on ``The Merv Griffin Show''
and indulging his alter ego, the obnoxious lounge singer Tony
Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman's ``Taxi'' co-stars are on hand for some pretty creepy
scenes (Kaufman looks the same; everyone else _ despite valiant
makeup work _ is 20 years older) and Danny DeVito steps out of
character for some yeomanlike work as Kaufman's manager. But this
is Carrey's movie and he makes the most of what he can with the
thin material.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly there are some priceless bits of comedy here, but
aside from the movie's opening moments, the whole thing is played
too straight. Despite its strained attempts to portray Kaufman as a
comedy outlaw, ``Moon'' comes across as a rather tame, shallow
portrait of an enigmatic man of dubious talent. Kaufman, whatever
you think of him, deserves better. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Man on the Moon'' (R; language, brief sexuality and
nudity). &QL; 
The stars: Jim Carrey, Danny DeVito, Courtney Love. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Milos Forman. Screenplay by Scott
Alexander and Larry Karaszewski. Released by Universal Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 58 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
