<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5730 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-MUSIC-GATSBY-REVIEW-S     12-21 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GATSBY-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARBISON`S `GREAT GATSBY': CEASELESSLY INTO THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &LR;   &LR; _ ``You can't repeat the past,'' Nick Carraway sings
in Act 2 of John Harbison's new opera ``The Great Gatsby'' _ to
which Jay Gatsby replies, in all his thrilling, tragic myopia,
``Can't repeat the past? Of (set ital)course(end ital) you can!''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the crux of Harbison's well-made but futile
adaptation of F. Scott Fitzgerald's classic 1925 novel, which had
its long-awaited world premiere Monday night in a splendid
production at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   If it were possible for Fitzgerald's self-made protagonist to
reclaim the lost love of the alluring Daisy Buchanan, his chosen
method _ lavish displays of wealth combined with a little emotional
arm-twisting _ would probably be the right one. But as generations
of high school English students have learned, Gatsby's romantic
dream of self-invention and renewal turns out to be a chimera.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if the traditional models for opera had any life left
in them _ if a composer could still craft a powerful dramatic work
through shapely arias, intricately woven ensembles, canny
orchestral writing and all the rest of the historical apparatus _
Harbison would be the one to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Setting his own libretto, Harbison has compressed and slightly
rearranged Fitzgerald's narrative with a sure sense of pacing. The
score is studded with lyrical numbers of arresting beauty, and the
skill with which he interweaves the sounds of the Jazz Age into the
musical texture is nothing less than astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Monday's heralded premiere _ with the eyes and ears of the
whole musical world focused on the last new opera of the 1900s _
only confirmed Nick's unheeded reminder. Harbison's lavish
creation, like one of Gatsby's extravagant lawn parties, felt like
an attempt to recapture an unreachable past, when the
tried-and-true methods of writing an opera still worked.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``The Great Gatsby'' is simply an exercise in
pastiche-laden archaism, like the echoes of Mozart and Rossini that
coursed through an earlier Met commission, John Corigliano's
``Ghosts of Versailles.'' In fact, the strains of 1920s popular
music that run through the score probably constitute its most
fascinating feature.
</P>
<P>
   Between Gatsby's parties _ two of which feature prominently in
the opera _ and music streaming from radios, there's a constant
backdrop of fox-trots, two-steps, tangos and rumbas that do as much
as Jane Greenwood's costumes to establish the piece's period tone.
</P>
<P>
   The songs themselves are Harbison's own, with lyrics by Murray
Horwitz, and they're dazzlingly good exercises in period style
(Horwitz, in a program note, compares the process of writing these
songs to making antiques). Better still is the way the composer
grafts his character's sung dialogue onto those Jazz Age rhythms
and harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   The precedents are the ball that ends Act 1 of Mozart's ``Don
Giovanni'' and the opening scene of Verdi's ``Rigoletto,'' and
Harbison's effort belongs in that company _ especially in the
opera's most powerful scene, the party that begins Act 2.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time that Daisy, who has just reconnected with
Gatsby after their aborted romance five years earlier, comes to
Gatsby's house for one of his extravagant bashes. While the
assembled guests dance a lively fox-trot, Daisy's husband, Tom,
vents his suspicions about Gatsby to the perpetual onlooker Nick
(just as faceless here as in the novel), and Gatsby and Daisy
inhabit a world apart, where the strains of the party can only just
be heard through the gauzy mist of their forbidden love.
</P>
<P>
   It's a display of remarkable virtuosity, and it's not the only
one. The overture, written in 1985 as a stand-alone orchestral
piece, captures the emotional essence of the piece with brilliant
efficiency. The tender lyricism of some of the set pieces _ Daisy's
first soliloquy, Gatsby's final reverie recalling the magic of
their first love, and even Nick's oddly minimalist evocation of a
winter train ride through Wisconsin _ can be heart-wrenching in its
power.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the whole enterprise feels deeply familiar.
The arias announce themselves too brazenly as such (sometimes
drawing the proceedings to a sudden halt), and the audience can see
them coming well in advance. ``Gatsby'' is full of affecting
moments, but never the ghost of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's production, nimbly staged by Mark Lamos and conducted
with panache by music director James Levine, at least makes a
committed case for the piece (it'll travel to the Lyric Opera of
Chicago next season). Michael Yeargan's sets, dexterously lit by
Duane Schuler, are impressively clutter-free yet convey the
requisite air of ostentatious wealth through high ceilings, broad
vistas and just a few well-placed sticks of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The cast, too, turned out to be well-chosen in nearly every
case. In the title role, tenor Jerry Hadley gave eloquent voice to
Gatsby's romantic fantasies, singing powerfully in the ensembles
and with clarity in his solos.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal difficulty that plagued him so recently in September's
San Francisco Opera production of Charpentier's ``Louise'' raised
its head only briefly, in the form of some labor-intensive high
notes; otherwise, he managed Harbison's sinuous melodic writing
with alluring ease.
</P>
<P>
   As Daisy, soprano Dawn Upshaw managed to pack her character's
unearthly allure into her singing, producing a stream of
resplendent, brightly focused sound that drew listeners into her
aura.
</P>
<P>
   The star of the evening, though, was San Francisco's own
Lorraine Hunt Lieberson, making an incendiary Met debut as Tom
Buchanan's smoldering, lower-class mistress, Myrtle Wilson.
Myrtle's earthy eroticism is Fitzgerald's clich &LR; e &LR; , but the
unstoppable vibrancy and force of Lieberson's portrayal made it
instantly believable.
</P>
<P>
   Mezzo-soprano Susan Graham was nearly as entrancing as Daisy's
friend, Jordan Baker, in a performance that caught the character's
supercilious charm perfectly, and Mark Baker brought fearless
assurance to the heldentenor role of Tom Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Only baritone Dwayne Croft as Nick, with his bland tone and
inaptly Italianate diction, struggled to make an impression. But
there were strong performances by Richard Paul Fink as Myrtle's
cuckolded husband, Matthew Polenzani as the band vocalist at
Gatsby's parties and William Powers as the gambler Meyer Wolfshiem.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it's fitting that ``Gatsby'' will go into the history
books as the last new opera premiered in the 1900s. It is an expert
compendium of most of the operatic techniques that have been
mastered and digested during the past century and more, and in
terms of skill and resourcefulness, it is hard to fault. But now,
perhaps, it might be time for something new.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
