<SLUG> BC-U.S.-U.N.-DUES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAKES LAST-MINUTE DUES PAYMENT TO UNITED NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs to delete `R-Del.' in 6th graf, correcting to `Sen. Joseph
Biden of Delaware, the committee's ranking Democrat...') 
(mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With barely a week to go before the United
States would have lost its vote in the General Assembly for falling
too far behind in paying its back dues, the Clinton administration
came through Tuesday with a check for $51 million, the United
Nations said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, despite several recent payments totaling $247
million, a minimum of about $8 million remained to be paid by the
United States, the organization's spokesman, Fred Eckhard, had said
earlier in the day. The last-minute payment was consistent with a
pattern in recent years in which just enough money was found by the
United States to save its General Assembly vote. The Security
Council vote is not affected.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations calculates the total outstanding American
debt at still more than $1 billion. The United States does not
accept that figure because of congressional decisions to lower
payments. Both sides agree, however, that a minimum of $255 million
had to be paid by the end of this year. Tuesday's check cleared
that mark comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Richard Holbrooke, the U.S.
representative at the United Nations, praised a budget agreement in
Washington that finally freed $926 million for the United Nations.
He called the decision a ``terrain-changing event'' for the United
States here, where resentment against Washington for essentially
bankrupting the organization has been mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our judgment from the beginning that if we didn't get
the Helms-Biden bill passed,'' Holbrooke said, referring to the
budget agreement, ``the next year here in New York would have been
very unpleasant, and America's influence not only in the United
Nations but in all sorts of important issues around the world could
have been severely eroded. It was important to get this behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Helms-Biden compromise, agreed to by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and
Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware., the committee's ranking Democrat,
set the $926 million total for U.N. payments.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke is now faced with the task of putting some
congressional conditions to the test here. The money is being
released by Congress in installments, with the condition that
members of the United Nations agree to reduce American
contributions to 22 percent of the organization's budget from 25
percent. Congress has already unilaterally lowered contributions to
the peacekeeping budget to 25 percent from 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many other benchmarks are attached to the payments, but
Holbrooke says they are manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hays, an American diplomat with ambassadorial rank, has
joined the U.S. mission here to take on the budgetary and dues
negotiations. Holbrooke said the United States would like to
broaden the debate on dues to review not only American
contributions to the organization, but also those of many other
nations that are perceived to be paying too little or too much.
</P>
<P>
   Except for adjustments two years ago that lowered the rates of
membership for the smallest and poorest countries to $10,000 from
$100,000 annually, a readjustment of dues had not taken place for
more than a quarter of a century, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-six new nations have joined the U.N. since then,'' he
said. ``Some get richer, some poorer. Some nations have told us
privately that as part of a package they will increase their
contributions. Some nations said they would like to reduce. We are
calling for a general revision, not just a diktat from
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said the organization needed to find only $38 million
annually to make up for the United States' reduction in payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
