u f BC-STATES-BORDER-NAT     12-21 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BORDER-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SOUTH TEXAS BORDER ON ALERT FOR TERRORISTS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 21 - U.S. law enforcement officials along the
border between Texas and Mexico are beefing up security inspections
to varying degrees in a ``heightened state of alert'' for possible
terrorists seeking to enter the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of several alleged terrorist activities, including
the announcement Tuesday of the arrest of an Algerian in Vermont
smuggling bomb-making materials across the Canadian border, South
Texas customs officials said they are moving personnel and asking
inspectors to work overtime in case of a terrorist entry there.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and border patrol inspectors are also on the look
out, but so far have not moved or added staff.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official who focuses on terrorism said while
there is no direct evidence of terrorist activity in any area of
the country, stepping up security just in case is a ``prudent
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the alert sent out by immigration and border agencies,
South Texas customs officials are likely to do twice as many
security inspections than usual in the area from Del Rio to
Brownsville, said Maria Reba, director of field operations in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Reba said customs officers started shifting administrative staff
into inspections roles this week, and have asked inspectors to work
double their normal working day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be a lot more vigilant,'' Reba said. ``We have
a heightened sense of alert.''
</P>
<P>
   There will also be extra security measures, such as using two
dogs to sniff for drugs where one would normally be used, Reba
said. They are doing more preliminary inspections of vehicles
before they arrive at the first checkpoint - and doing more
searches inside and under the hoods of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Reba said those crossing the borders may find delays due to the
heightened security. ``We ask that people realize this is for
safety, we thank for their understanding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. customs officials Monday said they were adding 300
inspectors to work at various customs points around the country.
South Texas does not have plans to bring inspectors from other
precincts to its ten points of entry, Reba said.
</P>
<P>
   But those points, which employ 1,084 people, may need to add
more personnel because there are limits to how many extra hours
inspectors can work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Services, which checks
documentation of those entering the country at official entry
points, may decide to move personnel from one center to another,
and may ask employees to work overtime, but has no plans to deploy
additional officers, said Nicole Cheulick, spokesperson for INS
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Art Moreno, spokesman for the INS in Harlingen, Texas, said his
office had received the alert. ``They've been told to keep their
guard up,'' he said. ``There will be no operational changes [and]
it's going to be maintained at same integrity as far as
inspections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande Valley's Border patrol, which sweeps for illegal
entry to the U.S. in Starr, Hidalgo, and Cameron counties, is
looking out for suspicious people, but it's ``business as usual''
said Harry Bell, assistant chief patrol agent of the Valley's
patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he doubted any terrorist from the Middle East or
Europe would try to enter the Southwest border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to draw suspicion immediately,'' Bell said.
``Antennas and red flags are going to go up all over the place
along the Southwest border,'' he said. ``It's pretty easy for us
because the majority of our traffic is Mexicans, and someone from
Europe sticks out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
