A5739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HOLIDAY-DRESS-COX     12-21 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-DRESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Have yourself a dressy little Christmas
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On her way through a local department store Dec.
10, the colorful Christmas sweater caught her eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had tickets to have brunch with Santa at the Racquet Club
the next day and my children were going to dress in holiday
clothes,'' recalls Jackie Williams. ``When I saw the sweater I
thought it would be fun for me to wear.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that time of year when folks get the urge to cover
themselves with candy canes and reindeer, sleighs filled with
presents and wreaths, nutcrackers and angels. Some don
battery-powered twinkling lights. Others opt for pins on their red
and green turtlenecks. Men take out their Christmas ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Scrooges among us assert that holiday garb looks more like
billboards than clothing and doesn't flatter anyone. But that
doesn't dissuade devotees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start wearing them right after Thanksgiving and wear
them through Jan. 1,'' says Peggy Cornwell, manager of the Acorn, a
Kettering, Ohio, women's shop that specializes in novelty sweaters.
This year her store in the Town &AMP; Country Shopping Center sold a
``Twelve Days of Christmas'' sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell says customers of all ages buy the festive holiday
sweaters _ some even collect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a Grinch sweater by Michael Simon that teachers really
liked,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Christmas attire, this year there's the added
attraction of millennium garb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done well with it and it's like a memento so people can
really wear it past the 2000 year,'' says Cornwell.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bukey, vice president/regional director of stores for
Elder-Beerman, says sales for holiday-motif clothing build every
year and that millennium merchandise also has been selling very
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that lot of people are doing it for the novelty of
it and having a lot of fun with it,'' he says. ``This year is so
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Williams _ whose cardigan boasts a Christmas tree, teddy
bear and presents_ says the sweater will be perfect for her
family's Christmas Eve celebration and that it brings smiles to
those who see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have business casual at work every day, wearing
holiday sweaters is a nice break from everyday business casual
dress,'' says Williams, who works at Reynolds &AMP; Reynolds. ``When I
wear it I feel a little more in the spirit of Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
