<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-CARREY-FEATURE-L     12-21 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CARREY-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARREY CHANNELS THE ELUSIVE KAUFMAN IN `MAN ON THE MOON'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' may be the strangest movie biography ever
made. That's partly because of its subject and partly because of
the man who plays him.
</P>
<P>
   The film is, ostensibly, about the life and times of Andy
Kaufman, the guerrilla performance artist who masqueraded as, among
other things, a stand-up comedian in the 1970s and '80s. A put-on
specialist of the highest order, Kaufman didn't care if he made his
audiences laugh or not _ heresy in the comedy biz _ and even
actively provoked hatred with his quixotic ventures into wrestling
women and readings of ``The Great Gatsby,'' in full, to people who
thought they had bought tickets to a laugh party.
</P>
<P>
   But since Kaufman died suddenly in 1984 (some, quite naturally,
still believe he faked that, too), leaving a perplexing legacy of
unbroken poses rather than the usual accumulation of clues as to
what he was really like, his story could only honestly portray the
masks, not the man behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that stopped ``Moon's'' star, Jim Carrey, from
virtually channeling Kaufman. The superstar funnyman _ whose
trademark antic schtick is about as far from Kaufman's poker-faced
surrealism as two acts can get _ remained in character for the
entire shooting schedule, interacting with director Milos Forman
and cast and crew members exclusively as Andy. Or, on the really
freaky days, as Kaufman's abrasive lounge singer character, Tony
Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to consume me because it consumed Andy,'' an apparently
saner Carrey explains. ``I wouldn't work in that way for any other
project, I don't think. But Andy was that way, Andy was a person
who opened his eyes in the morning and the circus began. You didn't
go 'Action!' and Andy suddenly went into character. He came as the
character, and he was the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so committed, in fact, that people thought he was sick.
So, I thought, I'm a comic, and to do anything less than commit
like he did would be disrespectful or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Respect for Kaufman among big-time Hollywood players such as
Carrey, multiple Oscar winner Forman and producer/co-star Danny
DeVito was what got this decidedly quirky project off the ground.
Forman and DeVito, who had worked together more than two decades
ago on ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' reunited five years ago
at a birthday party for that film's producer, Michael Douglas,
where their mutual interest in Kaufman became the main topic of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito, of course, was a veteran of the hit TV sitcom ``Taxi,''
on which Kaufman played the lovable foreign mechanic Latka Gravas.
For his part, Forman had fond _ well, maybe distinct is a better
word _ memories of a live Andy performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Andy for the first time _ and the last time _ live at
the the Improv in, I believe, 1974,'' says Forman, the Czech-born
director of such diametrically different biopics as ``Amadeus'' and
``The People vs. Larry Flynt.'' ``I was fascinated and, at the same
time, irritated. But I remained fascinated since.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski, the off-the-wall biopic
specialists who wrote ``Flynt'' and ``Ed Wood,'' had also been
fascinated by Andy. They were, naturally, the writers Forman and
DeVito turned to for their script, so with the entree to Andy's
friends and intimates the big names provided, Scott and Larry set
out to write the definitive Kaufman screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Which they did. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``This script was a nightmare to figure out,'' Alexander admits.
``We were trying to get a clean and simple bead on who Andy was,
but after four or five months of interviews we couldn't get a
straight answer. Plus, we also couldn't figure out how to tell the
story and be true to Andy. Then we hit upon the idea of there is no
real Andy, then we hit upon the idea of doing the film as a series
of puzzles.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but what does that tell us about Kaufman?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a weird sense, what I think is interesting about Andy and
that keeps him interesting all these years later is that he is not
explainable,'' Karaszewski offers. ``That he is an enigma and that
he was a person who was not happy unless he was wearing a mask,
either on stage or off. If you went out to dinner with Andy, I
would say that seven times out of 10 he would talk to the waiter
with a German accent. He was all about performing, and every time
you thought that you'd gotten into the inner circle, whenever you
thought you were finally seeing the real person, you realized that
you were just being messed with again.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVito, who plays Kaufman's patient (if not always
understanding) manager, George Shapiro, in the movie, reveals that
even after working for five years with Kaufman, he had little
notion of his friend's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a very respectful and, genuinely, I thought, a
good guy,'' DeVito recalls. ``But honestly, my take on it was that
what he was doing as a little boy _ magic shows, sing-alongs, that
kind of solitary fantasy life that he led _ stayed with him. I
mean, really stuck; and this young man grew into an adult who loved
doing the same exact things he did as a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others involved in making the film, DeVito refers questions
about the real Andy to Shapiro and the late comedian's girlfriend
Lynne Margulies, who is played by Courtney Love in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a constant put-on artist, except in private life,''
Margulies more or less explains. ``But it's difficult to describe
what his private life was like. He was just a quiet, shy,
intelligent, you could almost say boring guy. He was almost, kind
of, not there. He wasn't cinematic in the slightest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In real life, I could have a conversation with Andy for three
or four hours,'' Shapiro, an executive producer of the film,
reveals. ``Totally rational, intelligent, he'd tell me what he
enjoyed doing in his life. And I enjoyed being with him,
one-to-one, as a person, talking about what his dreams were and
what he loves.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody cared much for the obnoxious Clifton persona, however.
DeVito recalls Clifton showing up on the ``Taxi'' set _ the cast
was told he was a friend of the absent Andy's _ and totally
insulting everybody. The incident was re-created for the movie with
many of the original ``Taxi'' actors playing themselves (though
DeVito noticeably was not among them). Only this time Carrey
appeared in full Tony garb and bray, and with a coating of stinky
cheese all over him for good measure. He particularly enjoyed
hugging visiting Universal Studios executives that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very surreal, but when I saw what dedication Jim had
for this part, I felt blessed,'' notes DeVito, who can say that,
since he wasn't around for a Limburger embrace. ``I had a lot of
responsibility here because, first of all, I loved Andy and I'm
very good friends with George Shapiro and my company produced this
movie. I am thanking God that Jim totally, totally immersed himself
in that character. Jim himself only came to the set twice in, like,
four or five months, so everybody was able to do exactly what they
were doing back at the time when Andy was around.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kaufman was doing his thing, Carrey was a poor Canadian kid
just starting to struggle in the competitive comedy game. He
eventually succeeded beyond his wildest dreams, applying his
plastic-muscled ingenuity to the decade's most successful run of
comedy films _ ``Dumb and Dumber,'' ``The Mask,'' ``Liar Liar,''
the Ace Ventura pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even though Carrey turned into a kind of ultimate
crowd-pleaser, he credits Kaufman as a key influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just opened up the doors,'' Carrey says. ``First of all,
you don't have to be funny _ whew! _ second of all, you just have
to be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a period when I stopped doing impressions and
wanted to explore other avenues,'' Carrey continues. ``There were
six months of my life when I went to the Comedy Store every night
and decided not to repeat something that I had said the night
before, and it was deadly. I mean, sweat was pouring down my face.
But when you saw people like Andy Kaufman taking the chances that
he took, (you realized that) failure was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a Golden Globe nomination and talk that he might be up
for the Oscar nomination that eluded him for ``The Truman Show''
last year, Carrey is still somewhat possessed by the Andy spirit
that so thoroughly consumed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever did win an Oscar or something, I wish that Andy
would run up and grab it out of my hands,'' Carrey says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
