<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-AID-(TRIM     12-21 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-AID-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT BLOCKS AID TO RUSSIAN OIL COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Tuesday
ordered the Export-Import Bank to reject a $500 million loan for
Russia ``for the time being, '' arguing that the state-affiliated
oil company for which the loan was intended was an example of
resistance to economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of frantic meetings in which Albright tried
unsuccessfully to persuade the independent agency to defer
consideration of the loan guarantees, she invoked a rarely-used law
to block the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The bank met behind closed doors late Tuesday afternoon after
receiving a letter from Albright, and did not proceed with its
previously planned approval of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said Albright's concerns were
entirely focused on questions about the rule of law in Russia and
had nothing to do with the country's military campaign in Chechnya,
though senior aides to President Clinton noted that the secretary
only became deeply involved in the loan issue after Russia's
attacks in Chechnya intensified.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of reports and allegations that raised
questions about the use of bankruptcy laws in Russia and about
shareholder and creditor rights,'' said Al Larson, the
undersecretary of state for economic affairs. ``This is
particularly important given the importance of promoting rule of
law, something we have discussed for many years, and particularly
in the past few months.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The denial of the loan will mean little for the Russian economy.
It simply stops American firms from selling oil-drilling and
environmentament to Tyumen Oil, a company that is 49.8
percent owned by the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   But the symbolism is far greater. The action comes at a crucial
time in both Russian domestic politics and U.S. relations with
Moscow. Moreover, it reflects a hardening of the U.S. stance toward
the benefits of ``economic engagement'' with Russia during its
rocky transition to a market economy. In addition, American
companies considering doing business in Russia could easily be
scared off if they think it will become more difficult to obtain
guarantees from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have already been assailing Vice President Al Gore
for his leading role in the Russian aid packages of the past seven
years, charging that the taxpayer-supported economic assistance has
done little good. While the Clinton administration has defended its
approach, it has also slowed the money to a trickle while insisting
on major changes in the Russian economic and legal systems.
</P>
<P>
   Aid from the International Monetary Fund, for example, has been
strung along for months, with the administration insisting that
Russia first carry out its promised reforms.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Export-Import Bank, James Harmon, a former
investment banker at Goldman Sachs, had turned the loan into a test
of the administration's stomach for continued economic engagement
with Russia. He angered many in the administration by refusing to
read the political tea leaves, and insisting that the loan should
go ahead if it met the bank's criteria _ which are economic in
nature, not political.
</P>
<P>
   But from the start, the loan guarantees were politically
troublesome. Tyumen Oil has been in the midst of several nasty
commercial battles in which it was accused of fraud in dealing with
BP Amoco, with investor George Soros and with the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco and Soros both retained powerful lobbyists to plead
their case, and Amoco used the loan issue to negotiate a deal
resolving its long-running dispute with Tyumen. That agreement is
expected to be announced this week, and its resolution might begin
to clear the way for the lifting of Albright's order, officials
suggested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement that will reportedly be signed Wednesday,
Tyumen will surrender a valuable oil production unit that it
obtained through a quickly-executed bankruptcy action from a
company called Sidanco. BP Amoco owned 10 percent of Sidanco and
originally believed that its investment was lost, leading to its
complaints to the Clinton administration. Now, under the agreement
reached hours before the Export-Import Bank's board was meeting, it
will control a quarter of the voting rights in Sidanco, making it
an equal partner with Tyumen.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether that will be enough to lift the order that
Albright issued Tuesday under the 1978 ``Chafee Amendment,'' named
for the late Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I. The amendment empowers the
secretary of state to override any action by the bank that the
secretary determines is not in ``the national interest.'' The law
uses a country's human rights record as an example of a concern
that could lead to canceling a loan; it makes no mention of reform
of a nation's commercial legal structures.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the administration says motivated it to suspend
the loan, administration officials conceded Tuesday that the action
will be interpreted in Moscow as retaliation by the Washington for
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's refusal to back off from the
Chechnya campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This may really be all about promoting rule of law in
Russia,'' one of Clinton's economic aides said late Tuesday. ``But
I wouldn't bet that the Russians are going to read it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days and hours leading up to Albright's letter to the
bank Tuesday afternoon, Harmon came under extraordinary pressure to
back away from the loan. Lobbyists on both sides of the issue
cruised the halls of the Ex-Im bank, across Lafayette Park from the
White House. A series of senior administration officials broadly
hinted that Harmon should become more attuned to the political
difficulties of lending to Russia at a moment when Chechnya was
raging and Moscow was still resisting some of the reforms advocated
by the IMF, according to officials familiar with the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   But Harmon said that by the criteria his bank was to apply _
putting together financing that will aid American workers with
loans and guarantees to creditworthy foreign firms _ the oil
project should be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted today that the order was
temporary. ``We have issues to work through,'' one senior official
said, ``and when that happens this arrangement will be able to go
forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
