<HEADLINE>
DAVID AND MADDIE, SO YOUNG  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a match made in hell: she with the cool gaze and the
silky long legs, he with the rhythm `n' blues soul and that
incessant smirk. And from the moment Bruce Willis called Cybill
Shepherd a rude five-letter name and she returned the compliment
with a quick hand across his face, viewers were smitten by the
bickering sweethearts and their television love nest,
``Moonlighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, their chemistry seems as potent as ever.
Which is exactly what Bravo was banking on when it acquired 65
episodes of the ABC series and anointed them ``TV too good for
TV,'' an honor already bestowed on 1980s classics like ``Max
Headroom'' and ``Brooklyn Bridge.'' Next Sunday at 1 p.m., Bravo
will introduce its newest addition with a mini-marathon of the
first seven episodes before adding ``Moonlighting'' to its
weeknight lineup at 7 p.m., beginning the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ```Moonlighting' was ahead of its time, a natural,'' said
Frances Berwick, Bravo's senior vice president for programming, who
praises its ``crisp humor, inventive story lines'' and its stars'
lasting appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producer and writer, Glenn Gordon Caron, dreamed up
the series as a comeback vehicle for the model-turned-actress Ms.
Shepherd. ``Moonlighting'' created in her image an alter ego named
Maddie Hayes, a former cover girl left high and dry when her
accountant skips town with her liquid assets in tow _ leaving her
stuck with a money-losing detective agency headed by a
smart-mouthed charmer, David Addison, played by Willis in his first
big role.
</P>
<P>
   Maddie tried to get rid of him. Honestly, she did. But by the
end of the pilot, when David tossed down a blanket on the office
sofa and wagered that she might prefer spending the night at his
place, the audience was betting he wasn't far off the mark. And it
spent the next four years wondering, through sparkling banter, sly
innuendo and a weekly cat-and-mouse game, Would they ever?
</P>
<P>
   By the time they did, in a highly rated 1987 episode, the series
was deemed by critics the best thing to hit television that decade.
The Directors Guild of America, in an unprecedented occurrence,
nominated one episode for best comedy and another for best drama.
Willis won an Emmy. Both stars won Golden Globes.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are better left undone. When the sexual tension
waned, so did the audience's interest, and two seasons languished
beneath desperate plot devices, including a pregnancy for Maddie.
Then, in what felt like a heartbeat, they were gone. Ms. Shepherd
eventually played another version of herself in another sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Willis became one of Hollywood's biggest box-office draws. And
this season, Caron returned with ``Now and Again,'' a series about
a middle-aged man whose brain is transplanted into a young hunk's
body.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of viewers may find relevance in Maddie and
David's capers, a tale of love between two people so perfectly,
wonderfully wrong for each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
