<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-ART-$     12-21 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STARTS TO LOOK BEYOND ITS PAST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Arkansas state flag was run up the pole at
city hall this summer, New Yorkers were finally forced to
acknowledge the fact that our mayor is campaigning against the city
he was elected to serve The campaign has continued with assaults on
neighborhood parks, the Brooklyn Museum of Art and the right to
exercise free speech on the steps of city hall.
</P>
<P>
   This hostility toward creative life _ the soul of New York _
could have the effect of a wake-up call. Our long day-dream of
complacency, our willingness to take culture for granted, could be
coming to an end. This would have a major impact on the city's
architecture. For too long, this art form has been riding on the
coattails of architectural preservation instead of generating the
forward movement on which a great city's vitality depends.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, brought a few welcome signs that New York's
architecture may be rousing itself from its Sleeping Beauty coma.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH TOWER The most important building to be completed in New
York in years. The French architect Christian de Portzamparc
reinvents the spirit of Art Deco for those who imagine that
repeating the 1920s ziggurat motif will bring back Jazz Age
glamour. The building, on East 57th Street near Madison Avenue,
isn't weighted with undue philosophical meaning. It's a pousse-cafe
with changing colors that wash across a faceted crystal facade. A
nos amours!
</P>
<P>
   PENN STATION
</P>
<P>
   Carved out of the interior of the Beaux Arts General Post Office
(James A. Farley) Building on Eighth Avenue, David Childs' design
features a glass and metal space frame arcing over the arrival hall
and waiting areas arrayed on platforms that cascade down to the
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK PRESBYTERIAN CHURCH
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyside, Queens. Designed by Greg Lynn, Doug Garofalo and
Michael McInturf, who belong to a coming generation of designers
one might call the Polymorphs. Faced with the threat that advanced
computer technology will deliver architecture over to the world of
virtual reality, these designers are harnassing animation software
to shape real spaces of surprising free-form contour, like the main
sanctuary of this church.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPE STARCK
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the Internet has not shattered the appeal of
physical proximity. Even computer companies like to gather in
Silicon Valley. And Stark's relocation from Paris to New York has
already given the local design scene a boost.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN CENTER FOR ARCHITECTURE PRIZE FOR THE DESIGN OF CITIES
</P>
<P>
   The first in a series of urban design competitions to be held
every three years in a different city around the world. Of the five
finalists, Cedric Price of Great Britain produced the most
surprising entry. A fusion of historic preservation, sustainable
design and public space, Price's design called for minimal
intervention in a 20-block site on the west side of midtown
Manhattan: a concrete platform encrusted with small glass spheres.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO CITY MUSIC HALL
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frightening moments of the year occurred at the
opening of the newly restored entertainment palace, when Ann
Margret came onstage and took credit for saving it. The theater
itself, completed in 1932, has been renovated with great fidelity
to detail by Hugh Hardy and now stands revealed as one the
century's greatest spaces.
</P>
<P>
   RIVER HOTEL
</P>
<P>
   Architecture don't get no respect around here. Community
opposition and a flawed master plan helped doom an exemplary design
by the French architect Jean Nouvel for a boutique hotel and
cineplex beneath the Brooklyn side of the Manhattan Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MATRIX''
</P>
<P>
   Computer-generated virtual sets turned Larry and Andy
Wachowski's sci-fi action movie into a classic urban study in the
tradition of ``Metropolis,'' ``Alphaville'' and ``Blade Runner.''
In this digital twist on City Beautiful design, beauty and city are
both in the eye (and brain) of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   350 MADISON AVENUE
</P>
<P>
   Another one bites the dust. Roger Duffy's stylish para-building,
a vertical addition to an existing midtown office block, took an
important step toward a new design vocabulary for a built-up city.
The design won a Progressive Architecture Award, an honor played up
in ads by the building's developers. Alas, only a fraction of the
design is being built.
</P>
<P>
   CITY HALL PARK
</P>
<P>
   Paranoid-schizoid urbanism at its creepy best. With gas lamps, a
two-tiered fountain and period-piece benches, the park resembles a
Currier and Ives print as interpreted by Tommy Hilfiger for a
Christmas window at Macy's. But this $30 million adventure in theme
park picturesque is actually camouflage for more of Mayor
Giuliani's security installations. Fences, gates, guardhouses and
who knows what manner of tough-guy hardware is buried beneath the
Victorian frou-frou. Nighttime lighting courtesy of Alcatraz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-YEAREND-$ADV26-NYT     12-21 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-YEAREND-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH DRAMA, REAL LOSS AND QUIZ MADNESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doesn't it seem ``The Sopranos'' has been around forever? And
that the Barbara Walters-Monica Lewinsky interview became part of
pop-cultural history long ago?
</P>
<P>
   The revealing detail about this year's most significant
television events is how quickly they have become absorbed, a
testament to the sound-bite speed of television and the
ever-quickening pace of the world it chronicles and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's impeachment didn't make this list because it
already seems like last year's story. And though the final
impeachment vote happened in 1999, in television terms it
(italics)was(end italics) passe; the long unfolding in 1998 was the
television story, not the deflated result.
</P>
<P>
   In entertainment, it took no time for ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' to raise ABC's fortunes and alter the entire
television landscape, which was desperate for change, any change.
But the copycat quiz shows arriving soon already seem behind the
curve.
</P>
<P>
   And if the most important television events seem distant,
imagine how quickly our collective amnesia will take care of the
non-events. In the new year everyone can be grateful for this: we
can say goodbye to all those tedious millennium wrap-ups (did
anyone stay awake through a single hour?), quietly hoping no one
plans to rerun them next year at this time. Here, in descending
order of their impact, are the most influential events of the
television year:
</P>
<P>
   `WHO WANTS TO BE A MILLIONAIRE'
</P>
<P>
   The cheap little show that came out of nowhere as a summer
replacement is, let's face it, retro and cheesy. But there is no
doubt about the quiz show's appeal, based on a feel-good
philosophy: families can watch together and everyone can sound
smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' gained the kind of humongous ratings a network
show rarely achieves anymore, in this era of splintered audiences
and dozens of cable choices. On the surface, it did nothing more
than unite the country around a dopey catch phrase (``Final
answer?''), but it also sent a message that audiences are hungry
for comfort shows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COVERAGE OF JOHN F. KENNEDY JR.'S PLANE CRASH AND FUNERAL
</P>
<P>
   In the doldrums of a summer weekend, when John Kennedy's plane
disappeared, the all-news cable channels leapt in, followed by the
networks. For a full week, television went around the bend. A
legitimate, tragic story was covered as if it were a national
crisis; a promising but unfinished life was inflated to heroic
proportions; television crossed a significant line, creating the
story far more than it covered it, and raising questions about the
future of journalism. Will a celebrity-driven cable approach steer
all the news from now on?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BARBARA WALTERS-MONICA LEWINSKY INTERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few people paid attention when the impeachment vote
was televised, but the Lewinsky interview drew an incredible
audience of 70 million and is already an iconic event. We can all
see her in our minds, with her slicked-back hair and giggle,
talking about her boyfriend the president. Ms. Walters allowed the
guest to reveal herself in all her self-delusion, and so made this
the ultimate (though not the final) word on everything Monica. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE SOPRANOS'
</P>
<P>
   The year's towering achievement and the most talked-about series
in years, ``The Sopranos'' deserves all the attention. It is that
rare thing, a work of art that is tough, intelligent and daring
enough to generate sympathy for a coldblooded killer. When the
original series begins running again Sunday night on HBO, it offers
a chance to appreciate how nuanced the story of Tony Soprano and
his families, nuclear and Mafia varieties, really is. The second
season begins on Jan. 16, facing insanely high expectations.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COM COMMERCIALS
</P>
<P>
   Television has become flooded with commercials for Internet
companies. Some are ordinary, with celebrity shills. William
Shatner urges viewers to buy everything from plane tickets to
groceries online. (``No deliveries,'' he cheers, as if that's a
good thing.) Others are mini-shows, like Amazon.com's campy
musicals for Christmas, with a chorus of men in Andy Williams
sweaters assuring us that the Internet is a cozy site for
old-fashioned holiday shopping. The inescapable dot-com ads are
harbingers of the changing world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COVERAGE OF THE COLUMBINE HIGH SCHOOL SHOOTINGS
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the shootings, television became an ambiguous
force on the scene. Students who witnessed the killings were
quickly put on camera, and the spectacle eerily moved back and
forth across a line separating catharsis from self-aggrandizement.
</P>
<P>
   The instant analysis made the entertainment industry the easy
scapegoat once more, as pundits shied away from the more difficult
issue: the difference between entertainment as a direct cause of
violent behavior, and as simply one factor among many. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE WEST WING' AND THE RISE OF DRAMAS
</P>
<P>
   With its acerbic view of politics and its textured depiction of
life among the White House staff, ``The West Wing'' has become the
season's best, most absorbing, most ambitious series (despite an
unrelenting mushiness in the form of its sappy fictional president,
played by Martin Sheen).
</P>
<P>
   Other dramas have filled the networks, too: the engaging
``Judging Amy'' has consistently improved, while ``Once and Again''
and ``Now and Again'' have floundered (so maybe you never will have
to tell them apart). And as dramas have risen, sitcoms have
crashed; not a single new comedy made any impact this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE MORNING SHOW WARS
</P>
<P>
   ABC's sinking ``Good Morning America'' brought on Diane Sawyer
and Charles Gibson as co-anchors and unveiled a dazzling new studio
with a view of Times Square. And though NBC's ``Today'' remains at
the top of the ratings, the revitalized ``GMA'' now seems fresher
and livelier than its competition. Meanwhile, CBS built a new
morning show and extravagant studio around Bryant Gumbel and nobody
cared, as ``The Early Show'' at times tumbled in the ratings below
the scarcely watched version it had replaced.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AN AMERICAN LOVE STORY' (PBS) AND `STRANGE JUSTICE' (SHOWTIME)
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Fox's 10-hour PBS documentary about an interracial
family and Showtimes' fiery drama based on the Clarence
Thomas-Anita Hill sexual harassment hearings offered new
perspectives on both race and sex. These lively, accomplished works
prove that serious issues don't have to be treated in a deadly,
earnest way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NAACP BOYCOTT THAT WASN'T
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP had an excellent point about the lack of black actors
in leading roles this season, but the group seemed weakened when
its loudly threatened boycott of a-network-to-be-announced never
happened. Still, the networks scrambled to sign minority producers
and stars to contracts, offering at least the possibility of a more
equitable future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
