<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NEWYEAR'S-TERROR-(     12-21 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEWYEAR'S-TERROR-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SEES A SAFE TIMES SQUARE AT NEW YEAR'S
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to rising concerns about possible
terrorist acts on New Year's Eve, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Tuesday that there was no evidence of any specific plot against New
York City and outlined painstaking plans to maintain order in Times
Square, where up to 2 million people are expected to ring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said there was no reason to avoid millennium
celebrations in Times Square, despite comments to that effect by
some law enforcement experts, most notably Jim Kallstrom, the
former head of the New York office of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In television interviews and in an article in the New York Post
on Tuesday, Kallstrom said that he would avoid Times Square,
because terrorists gravitate to crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the New Year's Eve celebration, Giuliani said, ``I
think everybody but Jim Kallstrom is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Giuliani said, the city ``will be as safe on New
Year's Eve as it is on any other day of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that bomb-sniffing dogs would patrol tunnels
beneath the streets, workers who need to traverse the side streets
around Times Square would be required to have passes, and 7,000
uniformed and undercover police officers would mingle with the New
Year's Eve crowds, a duty usually handled by 4,800 officers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spoke at a news conference at City Hall that was
intended to spell out the work the city had done to cleanse its
computer systems of vulnerability to the Year 2000 computer
problem. He was flanked by his police and fire commissioners and
representatives of the city's power and telephone companies, all of
whom spelled out precautions being taken to keep things running.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that the city, after spending more than $350
million, had finished checking its hundreds of computers, 11,000
traffic lights and other equipment for malfunctions and said he was
confident that power, phones, elevators and the rest of the city's
electronic and electrical underpinnings would work.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said every
city computer had been checked three times. ``We could test things
again if we need to, but it would just be testing for testing's
sake,'' Lhota said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Questions at the news conference focused on whether the arrest
last week of an Algerian man, Ahmed Ressam, who was carrying
bomb-making materials as he tried to enter Washington state from
Canada, raised concerns about possible attacks on the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we live in a dangerous world and that
terrorism is a reality,'' Giuliani said. ``But I really think
people should not allow themselves to get overexcited about this.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said: ``We're in constant
contact with our federal partners. There's absolutely no indication
of any specific threat against New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   James G. Natoli, Gov. George Pataki's director of state
operations, said that investigations of possible movements of
terrorists from Canada into this country were noteworthy, but had
not led to any greater level of alert in New York state than
already existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think terrorism has certainly been something on our radar
scope,'' he said. ``That's part of prudent planning. But we're not
really concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the state and city would be in continual contact in the
hours before and after New Year's Eve with state troopers at the
city's police and emergency management command centers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expected crowds, Times Square would make a poor
target for terrorism, said Brendan Sexton, president of the Times
Square Business Improvement District, one of the groups organizing
the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police start checking people a couple of blocks away,'' he
said. ``They are looking for alcohol, so people get a visual
once-over. Once you finally get here, there are more cops than
civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Kallstrom echoed that view and said that his
earlier remarks were not intended to indicate that he knew of
specific threats to New York City. ``I wouldn't go to Times Square,
and I wouldn't go to downtown Philadelphia, but that's not because
I have some specific information,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City is one of the best protected and best policed
cities in the world,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In parallel preparations, officials at the Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey said its entire police force of 1,250 officers
would be deployed around New Year's Eve at the city's airports, at
Port Authority bridges and at other vulnerable spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our police will be on duty, and extra civilian personnel
will be on hand to ensure that everybody has a safe and happy New
Year's Eve,'' said Robert E. Boyle, executive director of the Port
Authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
