<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5759 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MAN-ON-MOONREVIEW-COX     12-21 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-ON-MOONREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To makers of 'Man on the Moon': Thank you very much
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Kaufman would have loved the opening of ``Man on the
Moon,'' director Milos Forman's compelling film biography of the
late comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, whose performance is so spot-on that he looks to be
channeling Kaufman, appears as Andy's ``foreign man'' character and
shoos the audience out of the theater. It's absolutely hilarious
and perfectly captures Kaufman's anarchic spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Best known as Latka on television's ``Taxi,'' Kaufman was an
innovative, eccentric comic who eschewed traditional setups and
punchlines in favor of off-the-wall routines that would have him
mouthing the words to the Mighty Mouse theme _ just the refrain,
mind you _ or leading the audience in a nonsensical
call-and-response sing-along.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're insane, but you may also be brilliant,'' his manager,
George Shapiro (Danny DeVito), tells him shortly after their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, who died in 1984 at age 35 from a rare form of cancer,
could be considered the first performance artist or ``alternative''
comedian. He seems an unlikely subject for a feature film, but so
did Z-grade moviemaker Ed Wood and porn publisher Larry Flynt,
whose lives also were sharply translated to the screen by writers
Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski as the acclaimed dramas ``Ed
Wood'' and ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   Forman, an Oscar nominee for the latter film and two-time winner
for ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' and ``Amadeus,'' presents
Kaufman's story in a highly entertaining manner _ thanks in no
small part to Carrey's astonishing performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' is funny, sad and unsettling _ much like
Kaufman's career _ and it stays with you long after you leave the
theater. Unless, of course, you exit at the comic's behest before
the movie begins.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet Kaufman as a television-obsessed youngster from
Long Island, N.Y., singing a children's song to his little sister.
Cut to a comedy club, where an adult Andy performs the same tune to
a dumbfounded audience as part of his act.
</P>
<P>
   The story unfolds in vignettes, re-creating career high and low
points with such actual participants as David Letterman, Lorne
Michaels, Jerry Lawler and the cast of ``Taxi'' playing themselves.
Paul Giamatti, who co-starred with Carrey in ``The Truman Show,''
portrays Kaufman's best friend and writing partner, Bob Zmuda.
Courtney Love, a Golden Globe Award nominee for ``The People vs.
Larry Flynt,'' plays girlfriend Lynn Margulies.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman enjoyed provoking people on and off stage, rarely
breaking character or letting his friends and audiences in on the
gag. Often he would carry a joke too far, as with his boorish
alter-ego, lounge singer Tony Clifton, and his bad-boy wrestling
persona.
</P>
<P>
   When Kaufman tells his inner circle that he has cancer, Shapiro
responds: ``That's in terrible taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey immerses himself in the role, impersonating Andy's
voices, expressions and mannerisms while more deeply conveying the
comic's fearlessness and passion. His wholly convincing performance
is sure to bring him an Oscar nomination for best actor,
compensating for last year's snub by the Academy for his fine work
in ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey develops nice chemistry with DeVito, who co-starred with
Kaufman on ``Taxi'' and produced the film. The role of Shapiro
allows DeVito to play a nice guy for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' doesn't give us a sense of what inspired
Kaufman's bizarrely amusing and often confrontation style, nor does
it convey who he was off stage. But then, his life was a
performance, and few people probably saw who he was inside. As
Margulies says, ``There is no real you.''
</P>
<P>
   The bittersweet finale lends credence to those who suspect that
Kaufman's death was just another elaborate put-on. Wherever Andy
may be, he's certainly laughing.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW _ B+
</P>
<P>
   Man on the Moon
</P>
<P>
   Director: MILOS FORMAN; Starring: JIM CARREY, DANNY DEVITO,
COURTNEY LOVE, PAUL GIAMATTI; 118 minutes; Profanity and brief
sexuality/nudity.
</P>
<P>
   GRADING SCALE:
</P>
<P>
   A _ Excellent
</P>
<P>
   B _ Good
</P>
<P>
   C _ Fair
</P>
<P>
   D _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   F _ Abysmal
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: davelarsen(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
