NYT-12-21-99 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-SHOWS-ART-$ADV26-     12-21 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SHOWS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREWORKS IN VENICE, AND ICE IN ANTARCTICA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get the lists out of the way first. The year's handsomest
shows of old art, by medium: bronzes by the sculptor Adriaen de
Vries at the Getty, drawings and paintings by Ingres, and
photographs by Carleton Watkins, both at the Metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise of the year: Frank Hurley's photographs, at
the American Museum of Natural History, from Ernest Shackleton's
epic 1914 expedition to Antarctica, one of the great stories of
modern exploration, which turned out to have produced remarkable
pictures of the end of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The most dutiful survey: the American Century exhibitions at the
Whitney. The best contemporary sculpture show: the same Richard
Serras that looked great in New York and Los Angeles last year
looked greater still in Bilbao, Spain; his ``Torqued Ellipses''
found their perfect home in the big ``fish'' room of Frank Gehry's
Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   The year's most peculiar and extravagant new work of art:
naturally, Matthew Barney's fourth and next-to-last installment of
his ``Cremaster'' film series, ``Cremaster 2,'' a highly personal
saga linked loosely to the story of Gary Gilmore, the murderer from
Utah, that caused the usual number of heads to be scratched while
confirming that Barney is, if nothing else, still very much
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hands down, the exhibition of 46 Cezanne watercolors at
Acquavella Galleries in New York was the local gallery show of the
year: a museum-quality display, which reminded everyone why
Cezanne, who died at the beginning of the century, at the end of
the century is still the most astonishing modern painter of
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   He could somehow make the white of a blank page evoke the
southern French countryside in springtime and turn a bunch of lumpy
rocks in the woods into the stuff of erotic dreams.
</P>
<P>
   A few shows made the world seem a little bigger and better:
``The Experimental Exercise of Freedom'' at the Los Angeles Museum
of Contemporary Art (it's still on view through Jan. 23), which
features Latin American avant-gardists of the '60s like Lygia Clark
and Helio Oiticica, and the current retrospective at the New Museum
in Manhattan of Cildo Meireles, the Brazilian artist, who followed
their lead. And Cai Guo-Qiang, the Chinese artist living in New
York who won a prize at this year's Venice Biennale, set off
fireworks over Vienna for a show that left a brief but indelible
mark in time.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Venice, the organizers of the Biennale finally
figured out how to deal with the circus atmosphere of the big
international survey: accept it. No summing up of the state of art
in the world. The new strategy is to cater to the appetites of
people who want to snack among hundreds of different works, people
who might prefer to be contemplating a steaming bowl of spaghetti
with clams or drinking a pink Bellini at Harry's Bar.
</P>
<P>
   The result: user friendly, quickly digestible, easily forgotten
videos, installations and sculptures. Video ruled because moving
images are attention magnets, but in all sorts of media the
biennale made clear that festival art, the late 20th century's last
hothouse art phenomenon, has become a peculiar kind of genre in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   This may turn out to mean nothing, but did you notice that in
mid-November, Jeff Koons' ``Pink Panther'' sold for $1.8 million
and a Martin Kippenberger painting of a man in boxers fetched
$717,500 at Christie's? An intoxicated art market suddenly seemed
as if it were reprising that moment just before the crash a decade
ago, when crazy people were paying crazy amounts for what turned
out to be crazy investments, and shortly ended up losing fortunes.
One dealer at this auction suggested that there is ``just too much
money around.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn and ``Sensation'': enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Although, while we're on the subject of collectors' collection
exhibitions, the best show of the kind this year: ``The Eye of
Duncan Phillips,'' in Washington (through Jan. 23), a celebration
of a man who first thought modern art was a sham, then was
converted to it and became one of the most passionate, articulate,
perceptive and generous collectors in American history. Phillips
loved painting especially, and the show, like his museum, which was
the first in the country dedicated to modern art, conveys his lyric
and joyous sensibility. Phillips proves that that it always pays to
keep your eyes, and mind, open.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, two deaths: Paul Mellon, who died in February, was one
of the last, and the greatest, of the patrician patrons of the
postwar period in America, a man who quietly gave nearly $1 billion
over the years to what he loved and what he also thought would
benefit the country: to the National Gallery of Art, which had been
founded by his father, to the Yale Center for British Art, which he
had founded himself, to the restoration of Monticello, to various
libraries, to the Bollingen Foundation to publish literature, and
to many other serious projects.
</P>
<P>
   He never wanted his name carved on a building, figuring that no
one else would want to give money to something that said Mellon on
the outside of it, but also because he valued privacy almost as
much as he loved paintings and race horses. He was a gentleman who
turned benefaction into an art, and his death, at 91, ended an era.
</P>
<P>
   An era also ended with Leo Castelli's death at 91 in August. He
helped to put American Pop, Minimalism, Post-Minimalism and
Conceptualism on the international map, and did so with style _ a
certain suave, calculating, late Austro-Hungarian Empire style _
which is to say he was a cunning businessman as well as a believer
in the new.
</P>
<P>
   He had an eye, but more to the point, he had good ears,
listening to what people were talking about. The ultimate
cosmopolite, he was the supreme salesman in this country of and for
contemporary art who became the most coveted dealer among artists
because he treated them with the respect he also gave to
collectors. At a time when it was nearly unheard of, he put artists
on stipends, buying their loyalty (at least for a while) and
letting them be productive even if they weren't selling.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Trieste, trained as a lawyer in Milan, Castelli worked
for an insurance company in Bucharest and as a banker and then an
art dealer in Paris until World War II, when he served in the
United States Army, after which he took his time before opening a
gallery in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, Roy Lichtenstein, Richard
Serra and Frank Stella were a few of the obvious reasons his place
became a magnet and lightning rod. It stayed that way during some
of the most important and tumultuous years in the third quarter of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``One does not have to like it, but one cannot discard it,'' he
said about the work he represented. ``One can lament a certain
fashion, but one ... just cannot say: `This is not art, it will go
away.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
