<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GEOGRAPHIC-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC'S `ADVENTURES' IN POINTLESSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wonder of wonders _ a National Geographic special on NBC that's
practically unfettered by point or purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Some would call that perfect TV.
</P>
<P>
   The program, airing Wednesday, is ``Adventures in Time: The
National Geographic Millennium Special'' (8 p.m. on Channel 4) and
yes, it's an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   It's an adventure in the way that emptying the fridge, tossing
the contents into a casserole dish and serving the thing with great
fanfare would be an adventure. Mmmmm, leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC calls its special a ``fast-paced and visually captivating
... look at the march of time.'' You'd call it something like that,
too, if you had no mortal clue what the show was about.
</P>
<P>
   But it's true in a sense. We watch dozens of clips culled from
past National Geo specials and, sure enough, time marches. The
clips were actually filmed in the same millennium, if that'll
suffice for a theme.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers are reminded yet again that our sun is ``an unremarkable
star.'' They should stop saying that on TV. It's a common
misconception.
</P>
<P>
   Our sun is a most remarkable star. People remark about the sun
constantly. You might have remarked about the sun already this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, there are willy-nilly shots of foul animals devouring
each other, great white sharks out in the Farallon Islands,
lizards, polar bears, chimps, turtles, lions, tigers and strange
rodents. Some of the rodents will be hosting their own syndicated
talk shows in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Egyptian mummies are being opened and great mountains
climbed. Primitive people whoop it up in Papua New Guinea, and
there's a neatly edited sequence of folks dancing all over the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Then organs are cloned, genetic diseases conquered, and we're in
the next century, in spirit. Geologist Roger Bilham predicts
catastrophic earthquakes destroying great cities in the next few
decades, and merry Christmas to him, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Inasmuch as the program has extended itself into the
21st century, it's out of recycled clips. Say buenos noches and
bring on ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A PBS special later Wednesday does have a purpose. It's to
reminisce about TV Sundays before pro golfers and the NFL swiped
Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omnibus: Television's Golden Age'' celebrates the weekly
program ``Omnibus'' (born 1952, died 1959), which, as its name
suggested, was about everything _ music, dance, drama, science,
comedy, even politics and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Omnibus'' host, Alistair Cooke, and others chat about a
program that was a commercial TV anomaly even during TV's eclectic
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The old clips are inhabited by Leonard Bernstein, Jonathan
Winters, Mike Nichols and Elaine May, Frank Lloyd Wright, Hume
Cronyn, Jessica Tandy, Eartha Kitt, Gene Kelly, Benny Goodman,
Sugar Ray Robinson, Les Paul and Mary Ford, John F. Kennedy and
Victor Borge.
</P>
<P>
   It's Borge, seeing music as his comic foil, who observes that
``Clair de Lune'' translates into English as ``Clear the Saloon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Omnibus'' didn't just make smart choices. Its secret was to
make inventive use of its choices. It was a program about process.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein visits Beethoven's mind as he wrote his Fifth
Symphony; he eliminated the flute, ``a delicate lady at a club
smoker,'' from the symphony's famous opening. Kelly constructs a
dance from the movements of pro athletes. Paul and Ford demonstrate
their pioneering recording technique.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's documentary also makes a donation to the
Ronald Reagan trivia bank. Seems that CBS, early on, wanted to
replace the urbane mid-Atlantic Cooke with the unmistakably
American Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omnibus'' producer Robert Soudek held firm. Reagan went to
``General Electric Theater'' instead to bone up on television.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
