<HEADLINE>
U.S. BORDER, AIRPORTS ON ALERT AMID TERRORISM FEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal law enforcement agencies Tuesday ordered
heightened security at U.S. airports, borders and docks amid fears
of increased terrorist activity home and abroad during the holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, in an effort to discourage
terrorists, said it will increase the number of inspectors and
bomb-sniffing dogs at U.S. airports and will be more diligent in
checking passengers for explosives. The Customs Service said it
already has added 300 inspectors at various ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Border Patrol also said they will increase their
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Sparking the government's apprehension is the coming of the new
millennium and the recent arrest of a foreign national suspected of
sneaking into the United States with bomb-making equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, Customs Service, FBI and Border Patrol, though
acknowledging their personnel increases in key areas, declined to
provide specific numbers or tactics, citing the need to keep
security measures confidential.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton's spokesman Joe Lockhart
downplayed any immediate domestic threat posed by the Dec. 14
capture of a suspected Algerian terrorist in Washington state.
Lockhart said law enforcement officials had not yet found any
specific threat against a particular American target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a scare mode,'' he said. ``We're not
advising people to change their plans and not follow through on
what they've planned to do for their millennium celebrations,
whatever that might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said a State Department advisory remains in effect for
people traveling abroad. The United States has received credible
information, from arrests made in Jordan, about potential terrorist
attacks overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made clear that there is a travel advisory, people
should exercise caution, and if people are planning to travel, they
should be in touch with the consulate or embassies, wherever
they're planning to go, to get further information,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Foley echoed Lockhart's
comments in urging Americans traveling overseas to be careful but
not unreasonably afraid of the terrorism threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a yellow light; it is not a red light,'' Foley said of
the department's travel advisory. ``We are urging Americans to be
vigilant and cautious as they travel, but we are not recommending
to Americans that they change their plans and that they not travel
overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the Defense
Department last week cautioned U.S. military commanders about
terrorist threats against Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide advisories provided ``information'' relevant to
the security of U.S. forces, Bacon said, declining to be more
specific. ``We're taking appropriate action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, besides adding inspectors and dogs, also called for
strict local enforcement of parking rules near terminal buildings
and greater caution by travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All passengers are encouraged to be alert for any suspicious,
unattended bags, parcels or other items, and report them
immediately to airport personnel,'' the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers can avoid inconvenience by not gift-wrapping items
they are taking with them,'' the agency added. ``While the FAA does
not expect the increased security to cause delays, travelers should
check in for their flights at least one hour early for domestic
flights and two hours early for international flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs Service chief Raymond Kelly declined to state
specifically where additional agents would be stationed, saying
only that they would be positioned at ``remote ports.''
</P>
<P>
   At the FBI, bureau spokesman Bill Carter said agents had already
taken steps to increase security in light of federal concern that
terrorists might strike at U.S. interests at the dawn of the new
millennium
</P>
<P>
   The moves by U.S. law enforcement followed a meeting Monday at
the White House among a handful of top administration officials,
who discussed the terrorism concerns and how to respond to them.
Among those at the two-hour meeting were Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William Cohen and CIA
Director George Tenet.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart would not confirm details of the session, saying only
that a group of people who work to combat terrorism meet regularly
to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as we lead up to the millennium and the issues that
brings on, and with some of the things that have been in the news,
the group, you know has been meeting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spurring the increased federal attention to the terrorism
concern was the Dec. 14 arrest of an Algerian national, Ahmed
Ressam, whom Custom Service agents caught in Port Angeles, Wash.
Law enforcement officials said they found nitroglycerin and other
potential bomb-making equipment in his car.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian police are seeking another man who is believed
to have stayed with Ressam in a Vancouver, B.C., motel before the
Algerian's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in Beecher Falls, Vt., Border Patrol agents Monday
arrested another Algerian national, Bouabide Chamchi, who allegedly
tried to sneak into the United States from Canada using a fake
passport.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are investigating whether the two men are
connected and whether either is linked to a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas and a critic of U.S. efforts to stem
illegal immigration, said the Washington state and Vermont episodes
should serve as a warning to U.S. and Canadian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is the best wake-up call that either Canada or the
U.S. (is) going to get about our porous, shared border,'' said
Smith, who chairs the House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration
and Claims. ``We have twice arrested individuals who entered the
U.S. from Canada with the apparent intent to commit acts of
terrorism. How many near misses can we tolerate?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRI) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, whom the United States has also
accused of promoting terrorism, said Tuesday that he was unaware of
any attack planned on Americans. But Gadhafi, interviewed on
CBS-TV's ``The Early Show,'' said ``the U.S. government is hated.
All the people in the world are against it, therefore there is a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will not happen in this new year,'' Gadhafi said.
``I have no knowledge about this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
