<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ELECTRONIC-MUSIC-ART-     12-21 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-MUSIC-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNPLUGGED DECADE FOLLOWS AN ELECTRONIC AGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing the 20th century has left us with is electronic music.
The first electrical machines for making sounds were built just
before, but lasting possibilities of producing music by electronic
means arrived and grew during the century now ending.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and '30s came the earliest electronic instruments
that would survive: some are still in occasional use, including the
theremin and the ondes martenot, both generating the weird effect
of voicelike sounds coming from inexplicable sources, and the
electronic organ.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the '40s, Pierre Schaeffer in Paris opened the
door to a fully electronic music with his musique concrete, made by
recording sounds on disk, playing them back in some unorthodox
manner, and re-recording the result. The spread of the tape
recorder, soon after, increased the range and convenience of such
processes, and the development of computer technology, especially
from the mid-'60s to the early '80s, brought another widening and
acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, though, most of the leading composers now working in the
Western classical tradition make little or no use of electronic
means, and electronic music has become a separate culture, of
composers creating and exchanging their music without need of any
larger audience.
</P>
<P>
   The increased power of computers, putting all the facilities of
a 1970s electronic music studio onto a couple of square feet of
desk space, has furthered the rise of this culture, and the
Internet is doing more. But in the public world, it is almost as if
electronic music had never been invented.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the outstanding pieces of the last decade, for instance,
have been for that great 19th-century institution, the symphony
orchestra. Olivier Messiaen, in his huge last achievement,
``Eclairs sur l'Au-Dela,'' used a vast assembly of instruments,
with whole ensembles of flutes and clarinets, to communicate
``visions of the beyond,'' where heaven transmutes the sounds of
earth: mountainous chorales for the wind group, long adagios in
which strings are idealized human voices, noises of wind and water,
and everywhere the calls and songs of birds. The sounds are in a
sense recorded, but this is musique concrete made entirely without
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Other composers in the '90s used a regular symphonic outfit and
still found the means to make new sounds. John Adams' Violin
Concerto starts with the violin singing against rippling
backgrounds that keep timbre and tonality in perpetual fluctuation,
and the finale creates the same kind of magical puzzles with
rhythm, in a hoedown.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Ades' ``Asyla'' is a lustrous symphony, having places of
beauty _ high-register cavortings, laments above exotic percussion
_ and also of danger, with the frenzied third movement reaching
simultaneously up to elation and down to mindlessness: ecstasy or
Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Harrison Birtwistle's piano concerto ``Antiphonies'' is,
like all his longer pieces, rugged, but it is also delicate, like a
giant reaching down to pick a flower. The piano, a dreamer, resists
the efforts of the orchestra to interrupt her dreaming but finally
has to realize that it is the orchestra on which her imagination
draws, and that the orchestra has dreams of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Carter's ``Symphonia'' is a symphony for the end of the
century by a composer who has lived through most of it: a big
statement of enthusiastic energy, multiplicity, diversity and new
sonic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Still other composers of the last decade have found new things
to do with the piano. Like many beginning pianists, Gyorgy Ligeti
sees the instrument as a recalcitrant machine _ but on a virtuoso
level. His Etudes are based on rather simple figures in rather
simple processes of imitation and movement up or down in register,
except that the extreme densities and speeds of events throw up
contradictions, and the mechanical surfaces erupt, explode or
dissolve in poetic confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Babbitt's ``Preludes, Interludes and Postlude,''
contrastingly complex on the surface, nevertheless sparkle with a
similar elegance and oddity. The piano sounds new in its sharp
attacks, at once unpredictable and exact, its characteristic
wobbles of repeated notes and its electric activity in the top
couple of octaves.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s was also a good period for quartets and solo string
pieces, especially in the output of Gyorgy Kurtag, and for choral
music. Heinz Holliger's ``Scardanelli-Zyklus,'' for chorus and
small orchestra, is as beautiful, delicate and poignant as frost.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Bach Passion for the present time, in chorales and
canons that sing on through deflation and exhaustion, and with the
protagonist now Friedrich Holderlin, whose late, mad poetry
provides the texts. At the same time, the oldest instrumentalist
figure of all, the solo percussionist, found a decisive
reincarnation in Steven Schick, and in music written for him by
Brian Ferneyhough and David Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Beside all these, electronic masterpieces of the last decade
were few, though they would certainly include Pierre Boulez's ``...
explosante-fixe ...'' for electric flute and small orchestra. Like
Ariadne in a labyrinth of mirrors, the solo flutist follows paths
amid distorted images of herself, these coming from the orchestra
while her own voice is magically and beautifully transformed by a
digital system. Eventually she reaches the way out, through
gateways of cadences.
</P>
<P>
   They are perhaps also gateways to the future, pointing to the
electronic music of the 21st century. Or perhaps the real musical
function of electronics has been to make the music of instruments
and voices more widely available, for all the wonderful music
described above is electronic music in another way, to be heard at
the spin of a CD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
