<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-POP-MUSIC-CENTURY-$AD     12-21 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-CENTURY-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKING TIME AS DUKE'S CENTURY WOUND DOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for POP-MUSIC-1999)  
 (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Popular music was running out the clock throughout 1999. No one,
it seemed, wanted to squander an original idea this year, lest it
be tossed out with the entire passe 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop's dominance was incontestable; it's as pervasive now as
the blues was in the 1960s. Although hip-hop's musical vanguard is
no longer its commercial front line, its rhythms and strategies are
now at the core of all best-selling popular music except country.
</P>
<P>
   Boy bands lead their audiences in hip-hop chants; hard rock
bands use hip-hop cadences and sound effects. Instead of the
ingenious wordplay and textural dementia of the best hip-hop, most
borrowers have taken the easy stuff: limited melodies, unlimited
egos and aggressive bad-boy poses, including a newly unbridled
misogyny.
</P>
<P>
   Women joined the renewed battle of the sexes in 1999, but with
more wit than their antagonists. There were other promising
directions this year, particularly the surge of Latin music.
</P>
<P>
   But the major changes were about marketing. Old styles were
gussied up in bright colors and big smiles to be sold to ever
younger consumers in the form of kiddie-pop, aimed directly at the
population of unjaded 8-to-15-year-olds. Behind the curtain, newly
consolidated recording conglomerates were frantically making deals
and alliances to position themselves for sale of music over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Technology departments scrambled to control whether recordings
could be copied. But in the front offices, no one has figured out
how to reverse the increasing disposability of current pop.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 reminiscences of popular music in 1999: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HORMONE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Testosterone. It was a man's year, full of backlash against
female authority. With Limp Bizkit leading the charge, never have
so many tattooed, pumped-up rock songwriters yelled so loud and
felt so sorry for themselves, while placing all the blame on ``The
Nookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Gangsta rappers like DMX and Jay-Z celebrated male bonding
through mayhem while Eminem and Kid Rock clowned their way through
raps that alternated self-mockery with crass chest-thumping. The
male preening of video-friendly boy acts _ Ricky Martin, the
Backstreet Boys, N'Sync, 98 Degrees _ was a different display of
testosterone, but just as commercially effective. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTIVE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Women's rhythm 'n' blues. Leaving male performers to their
fantasies of gangsta machismo and conspicuous consumption, women
followed through on Lauryn Hill's ambition: to reclaim the old
soul-music alchemy of honesty, fun and uplift. Mary J. Blige, Macy
Gray, Destiny's Child, Angie Stone, T.L.C., Me'shell Ndegeocello
and others delivered songs that were heartfelt, grounded in
realism, musically ingenious and unafraid to be deep. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BANDWAGON OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   The Latin tinge. It took Ricky Martin's grin and Jennifer
Lopez's rump to make radio stations and mainstream listeners pay
attention to salsa. The demographics of a growing Spanish-speaking
population helped. And in a year when American hitmakers were
determined to sacrifice all subtlety or grace, it was well past
time to notice the cornucopia of Caribbean rhythms one more time
and to recognize the romantic fervor of Spanish-speaking singers.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, this latest Latin wave _ which also brought a
comeback for Santana and an English-language hit for Marc Anthony _
will open more North American ears to the madcap hybrids of rock en
espanol bands like Cafe Tacuba and Los Fabulosos Cadillacs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPARITIONS OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilson, fighting his stagefright and backed by pop
scholars who recreated ``Pet Sounds'' arrangements, emerged for his
first tour without the Beach Boys; the partnership behind it has
already collapsed into lawsuits between singer and producers. Tom
Waits made his first tour since 1987, proving he's still his own
best character. Jesse Winchester quietly re-emerged after a decade
of writing songs for other performers.
</P>
<P>
   Most unlikely of all were the Monks, a band formed by former
American soldiers in Germany, who released one album, in 1966, of
clattery, dissonant, astringent, howling protopunk songs, complete
with feedback and antiwar lyrics. The original lineup, electric
banjo and all, finally made its United States debut, with its first
performances since 1967. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUFFERING ARTIST OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Trent Reznor. For five years the man who is Nine Inch Nails
procrastinated, produced other bands, sank into clinical depression
and worried about whether his next bass line would save rock. And
he holed up in the studio until he came out with ``The Fragile,'' a
marvel of solitary despair on which every sound is made to wound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EMINENCE GRISE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Max Martin. Behind the smiling faces and multimillion sales of
kiddie-pop are catchy songs, and Max Martin, ensconced in Sweden,
keeps cranking them out as writer and producer. He's the master of
the ambiguous ``it'' who came up with the Backstreet Boys' ``I Want
It That Way'' (along with most of their ``Millennium'' album) and
Britney Spears' ``... Baby One More Time.'' Lately, breaking the
age barrier, Celine Dion recorded one of his songs. Abba should
brace for competition.
</P>
<P>
   MOST D TRADEMARK OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Buena Vista Social Club. The Cuban musicians who got together on
the 1997 album reappeared in Wim Wenders' documentary film, then
fanned out with their own albums and tours. Ibrahim Ferrer, Ruben
Gonzalez, Omara Portuondo, Eliades Ochoa, Compay Segundo and
Barbarito Torres gave United States audiences a chance to separate
out the urban and rural styles that were entwined on the album and
listen more closely. Americans rightly grabbed the opportunity.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOST TARNISHED TRADEMARK OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock Festival. The Woodstock name will no longer be
automatically associated with the peace, love and cheerful chaos of
the original 1969 festival. At the 30th-anniversary version, the
chaos was hostile, with male aggression boiling over from the mosh
pit and ending up in rapes, vandalism and fires.
</P>
<P>
   There's blame aplenty to be divided: ineffective security,
resentment over high prices and fans who took rowdy music as
excitement. Will anyone take a chance on Woodstock 2004? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDEAD STYLE OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Grunge. Flannel shirts have been laughed out of fashion, and all
the leading Seattle bands except Pearl Jam are gone. But down-tuned
guitars and weight-of-the-world brooding still made their way to
No. 1 for Creed and Korn.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDING SPIRIT OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington. A century after his birth in 1899, Ellington
received well-deserved tributes: a year of punctilious programs
from Jazz at Lincoln Center, the CD release of his entire RCA
Victor recordings, continuing scholarship and performances that
sought to recreate the letter of his music or extend its spirit.
Both musicians and listeners rediscovered music that entertained as
it experimented, that anticipated countless ideas, and that merged
grand ambition, musicianly camaraderie and lapidary detail. It was,
after all, Ellington's century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
