<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-QUARTER-MINT-SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUARTER-MINT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COIN ON A ROLL: TREASURY MAKING A MINT ON COMMEMORATIVE QUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By SAM WHITING  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ There are 325 oak branches on the new
Connecticut quarter, and Irene Wu is checking each one with a 7x
magnifying glass. Wu is a coin press operator at the San Francisco
Mint, where precision is expected because a collector may be
checking this same coin with a 100x microscope, searching for the
slightest blemish.
</P>
<P>
   Since President Clinton signed the 50 States Commemorative Coin
Program Act into law on Dec. 1, 1997, quarters have become a coin
to save, not spend. According to a Mint survey, 15 million American
kids are collecting the quarters.
</P>
<P>
   By early next year, an estimated 60 percent of the American
population will be involved in the hunt, making the 50 state
quarters ``the hottest collectible product in several
generations,'' says Philip Diehl, director of the U.S. Mint in
Washington, D.C. ``We've sold 100 times the number that Pokemon
cards have.''
</P>
<P>
   The heads side of the new quarters is still George Washington,
though his hair has been textured as if there were gel in it.
Replacing the eagle on the tails side are designs submitted by each
state and produced five a year in the order in which the states
were admitted to the union, starting with Delaware last winter and
ending with Hawaii in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia and Connecticut,
quarters were issued this year. Next year, coins honoring
Massachusetts, Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire and Virginia
will be added.
</P>
<P>
   The state quarters program has put a shine on the San Francisco
Mint, the gray granite fortress that looms above Market Street.
Running at low idle since it ceased production of circulation
currency in 1981, San Francisco is the only mint entrusted with
pressing the commemorative quarters that come sealed in proof sets.
</P>
<P>
   These coins, marked with an ``S,'' represent ``the peak of coin
artistry,'' according to Diehl. They are subject to much more
careful workmanship and scrutiny than the general-circulation state
quarters minted in Denver and Philadelphia and marked with a ``D''
or ``P.'' The state designs will completely replace the eagle until
the program ends in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   To meet demand for the 1999 proof set of the first five states,
production at the San Francisco Mint has already doubled to 36
million coins and will rise to 50 million when the new Sacagawea
golden dollar is rolled out next year.
</P>
<P>
   The quarters-only proof sets, available in regular copper-nickel
for $13.95 and all silver for $31.95, are expected to sell out. The
coins are sealed in plastic for the numismatists who will not keep
a coin that has been touched by a human.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program has given new life to the Mint in San Francisco,
the (U.S.) Mint in general and coin collecting,'' says Diehl. ``It
was considered a dying hobby until this year. A hundred million
Americans would consider themselves new recruits to coin
collecting.''
</P>
<P>
   On average, each new collector has 12 quarters, according to a
Mint survey. To get them out of dishes and drawers, the Mint also
sells a handsome fold-out map for $24.95 with a slot for each
state's quarter, and historical and geographical information about
the states and the Mint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bringing a tremendous number of new people into coin
collecting,'' says Ritchie Clay, manager of the Coin Broker in Palo
Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Farino of Portola Valley, Calif., bought five albums,
including one each for her kids. ``They're always looking for the
different states,'' Farino says. ``It's hard to make sure each
child has one of each.'' The kids, ages 10, 7 and 4, are always
snooping in her coin purse, but Farino doesn't mind. ``I think it
ties into the history of the country and learning how to collect
and take care of something,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The financial point of the program is to make money for the U.S.
Treasury: Each state quarter costs the Mint just 4 cents to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Each state's coins are minted for 10 weeks, and that is it. For
the first three _ Delaware, Pennsylvania and New Jersey _ about 750
million of each were put into circulation, and they are already
disappearing. Production was doubled for the last two _ Georgia and
Connecticut, and that's why pocket change is lousy with them.
Pennsylvania seems to be the scarcest out West.
</P>
<P>
   The quarters can also be bought at face value in bags of 100 or
1,000 from the Mint's Web site. In October, when the Connecticut
quarter was launched, 7 million quarters sold out in 4 1/2 hours.
This level of commerce has moved the Mint into the top 25 retailers
over the Internet, and it has expanded into ancillary products like
quarter-based jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   But buying in bulk over the Internet is a passionless way to
collect, like buying a full set of baseball cards in a binder. It
takes the sport out of it. It is more rewarding to collect them in
change, and more rewarding still to collect them in the state they
honor. There is satisfaction in, say, getting a Pennsylvania
quarter in change from a pumpkin and cider farmer in the
Pennsylvania Dutch country.
</P>
<P>
   Over the life of the program, a conservative estimate is that
the 50 state quarters will earn the Treasury between $6 billion and
$8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's real money that goes in and lowers the deficit,'' says
Diehl. ``It's just like tax money but a lot less painful to
raise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
