<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JEWISON-FILMS-2TAKES-     12-21 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISON-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VETERAN DIRECTOR STILL FIGHTS THE GOOD FIGHT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for HURRICANE-FILM)  
(af) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Norman Jewison is not Hollywood hip. At the age of
73, the director of such films as ``Moonstruck,'' ``Fiddler on the
Roof,'' ``A Soldier's Story'' and ``In the Heat of the Night''
(which won an Academy Award in 1968 as best picture) is hardly on
the current A-list of trendy directors pursued by studio executives
and producers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, executives at Universal Pictures, which is releasing
Jewison's newest movie, ``The Hurricane,'' were skittish about
hiring him to direct the somber drama about Rubin (Hurricane)
Carter, the boxer wrongfully accused of murder (portrayed by Denzel
Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said, `Go young with this movie, find some MTV
director, find some new young guy and bring a youthful,
contemporary, stylish point of view to this story,' which is a
period piece set in the '70s,'' said Armyan Bernstein, one of the
screenwriters and chairman of Beacon Communications, which produced
the film. ``I said: `This is one of the youngest guys I've ever
met. His fire hasn't gone out. In fact it's blazing.'''
</P>
<P>
   At an age when many of his contemporaries are no longer working,
Jewison is facing the odd prospect of a career resurgence in a
business notorious for its obsession with youth. A trim,
bespectacled and restlessly enthusiastic man, Jewison said he would
probably work in films as long as he could stand. ``I know I'm
getting old,'' he said with a laugh, seated in his office at a
production facility in west Los Angeles. ``But I also know that
it's worth it to keep going, worth it to keep fighting and
hammering away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian-born filmmaker, who first won notice in the United
States as a television director, has been hammering away for 50
years, often driven by old-style liberal convictions that have
shaped some of his most noted films. Racial prejudice and racial
issues stir Jewison. In fact, Jewison said, he views ``The
Hurricane'' (which opens on Wednesday in New York, Los Angeles and
a few other cities in order to qualify for Academy Award
consideration) as his third movie of a personal trilogy about race.
</P>
<P>
   The first was ``In the Heat of the Night,'' about a black
Philadelphia policeman helping to investigate a Mississippi murder;
next came ``A Soldier's Story'' (1984), about a black officer at a
Southern military base in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   His fascination with racial issues dates back to the time when
he first crossed the Canadian border to visit the United States.
``I hitchhiked through America when I was 17, 18,'' he said. ``I
went down to New Orleans, to Mississippi, Tennessee. Alabama,
Louisiana, Arkansas. I couldn't believe what I saw. It was
apartheid. People couldn't get a cup of coffee or a Coke at
Woolworths. They couldn't drink from a fountain on the street. Had
to sit at the back of the bus. I was kind of shocked. I was so
naive, this kid from Canada. It always stayed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The current film, written by Bernstein and Dan Gordon, is based
on two books: ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,'' by Sam Chaiton and
Terry Swinton, and ``The 16th Round,'' Carter's own account of his
dream of winning the middleweight boxing title and how it was
destroyed when he was arrested, along with a young fan, John Artis,
for murdering three people in a New Jersey bar.
</P>
<P>
   The boxer was convicted and sentenced in 1967 to three life
terms in prison, where he channeled his despair into writing and,
essentially, isolated himself from the outside world. The case
became a cause celebre briefly during the 1970s, inspiring
demonstrations and a Bob Dylan song used in the movie's soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The film depicts how four people who were convinced of the
boxer's innocence _ an alienated black American teenager living in
Canada and his three social-activist guardians _ helped spark a
full-scale campaign to free Carter from prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, federal Judge H. Lee Sarokin overturned Carter's second
trial conviction after finding the prosecution committed ``grave
Constitutional violations.'' Sarokin said the convictions were
based on ``racism rather than reason, and concealment rather than
disclosure.'' Carter spent nearly 19 years in prison. ( Artis, who
also maintained his innocence, had been released from prison in
1981 after serving 15 years).
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's involvement in the Carter story began in the 1980s,
after he read a Sports Illustrated story about the boxer and began
discussing a project on his life with the producer, David Picker.
The project foundered, because of financing issues. Four years ago
Bernstein and Beacon stepped in. (The film cost about $30 million
and was made mostly in Toronto.) ``I'm glad they called me,'' said
Jewison.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Denzel Washington played an important role in hiring
Jewison. It was Jewison who saw the then unknown actor on stage in
Charles Fuller's Pulitzer Prize-winning drama, ``A Soldier's
Story,'' in the early 1980s and cast him in the film version.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a simplicity about his direction,'' Washington said.
``He knows what he wants. When I worked with him 15 years ago on
`Soldier's Story,' I was young and wasn't aware of how good he was.
He's a real actor's director.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has sought to play Hurricane Carter for nearly a
decade, and endured a sometimes grueling physical regimen for 18
months, including a weight loss of 35 pounds. ``This is an
extraordinary story and it's obviously a great part,'' said
Washington. ``And Norman was the perfect director. Not just for his
talent but his stance on racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison and his wife, Dixie, now spend most of their time on a
big farm, with 100 head of cattle, near Toronto. (They have three
grown children). Although the couple have a home in Los Angeles,
Jewison said that living in Canada has served to shield him
somewhat from the pressures of Hollywood and enabled him, unlike so
many directors who live in L.A., to distance himself from the
town's obsession with box office and what's hot.
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's own career, while enduring and very successful, has
had some off moments. (``He remains unpredictable, a gadfly among
directors,'' wrote David Thomson, in ``A Biographical Dictionary of
Film.'') A successful television director on CBC in Canada in the
1950s, Jewison was invited to New York and became an even more
successful, and Emmy Award-winning, director of such variety shows
as ``Your Hit Parade'' for CBS, and ``The Andy Williams Show,'' as
well as special shows featuring Harry Belafonte, Danny Kaye and,
most notably, Judy Garland.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jewison directed and-or produced at least a dozen Judy Garland
shows _ and he keeps several pictures of Garland and him in his
office. Jewison says that even in the final years of her career,
Garland was a mesmerizing talent who was exploited by managers and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had such a good sense of humor about herself that no
matter how difficult things got for her, with her husband and her
family and her problems and her health and addictions, there was a
personal courage about her that I admired,'' he said. ``I became
very protective of that talent. I don't know what it was. It's hard
for me to describe. I wasn't in love with her. I mean, I was her
director. She trusted me. And sometimes I think I was the only
person to tell her the truth, not lie to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's debut as a film director came with the successful 1963
comedy ``40 Pounds of Trouble,'' with Tony Curtis. This was
followed by three more comedies at Universal, including two with
Doris Day. Jewison then co-wrote and directed ``The Cincinnati
Kid'' (1965), a drama about card sharks starring Steve McQueen. And
then came movies like the satire ``The Russians are Coming! The
Russians are Coming!'' and ``... And Justice for All,'' with Al
Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Jewison also directed the stylish caper ``The Thomas Crown
Affair'' (1968) with McQueen and Faye Dunaway. He said he could not
bring himself to see the recent remake. ``I tried _ I got right up
to the door, I had my Cineplex pass out and I couldn't do it,'' he
said. ``I went to see another movie. Can you understand that?''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison's political commitments altered his life in 1970. He
packed up his belongings in Los Angeles and moved his family to
London. ``I kind of lost my confidence in the American dream,'' he
said. ``I was losing my sense of humor. I had marched. The war was
going on. Bobby Kennedy had been assassinated. Reagan was governor.
Nixon was president. I handed in my green card and moved.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Europe for about eight years, Jewison made the
successful screen versions of Broadway's ``Fiddler on the Roof''
and the rock opera ``Jesus Christ, Superstar.'' He also made the
futuristic ``Rollerball.'' In recent years, Jewison's films have
included ``Agnes of God,'' ``In Country'' and ``Other People's
Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison, who has made 23 feature films, has been nominated four
times for an Oscar, and his movies have received 45 nominations and
12 Academy Awards. At last year's Oscar show he won the prestigious
Irving Thalberg award for his directorial achievement.
</P>
<P>
   (His disappointments included ``F.I.S.T.,'' a 1978 drama
starring Sylvester Stallone as a Jimmy Hoffa-style labor leader,
which he blames partly on Stallone's efforts to revise the script
written by Joe Eszterhas.)
</P>
<P>
   Jewison said he hoped his next film would be a musical, although
he declined to discuss the details. ``I'm working at it,'' he said.
``I'm trying to convince people to give me a shot. I even liked
Woody Allen's musical, that everybody didn't like. I loved it. I
just don't think he knows how to make musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison, walking from his office to a nearby restaurant at
lunchtime, said with a laugh that, yes, he yearned for the old
days. ``The decision to make `Moonstruck' was made between Alan
Ladd Jr. and myself,'' he recalled, of the former MGM studio chief.
The movie went on to win three Oscars, including best actress and
best original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him a price of what I thought I could do the film for,
and told him I was going to go after Cher to play the lead. No
other major stars. And he called me up and said, `OK.' And I never
saw him again, until I told him that the film was finished and I
wanted him to see it. That doesn't happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first came to Hollywood, Jewison was mentored by great
filmmakers like Fred Zinnemann, George Stevens, Billy Wilder and
William Wyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember Willie Wyler when he was dying of emphysema
and I went to see him and I asked him, `When's it all over,
Willie?''' recalled Jewison. ``And he says, `It's all over when
your legs give out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jewison laughed heartily. ``My legs are pretty good,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
