<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BELL-LONG-DISTANCE-2N     12-21 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-LONG-DISTANCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to go.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the old AT&AMP;T agreed to spin off its local phone operations
as the seven Baby Bells in 1984, the Bells were prohibited from
selling long-distance services, which could have enabled them to
use their local monopolies to extend into a new market.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act, however, said that the Bells would
be allowed into the long-distance market on a state-by-state basis
as they persuaded the FCC that they had opened their local networks
to competitors. The Bells are required to sell access to parts of
their networks, notably the copper lines that run into homes,
because it would be next to impossible for any new local phone
company, no matter how well heeled, to fully replicate the systems
the Bells have spent decades building.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Bell local phone companies, like GTE, which has agreed to
merge with Bell Atlantic, and Southern New England
Telecommunications, which has been acquired by SBC, are also
required to sell access to their systems. But because those
companies were never part of AT&AMP;T, they have been allowed to sell
long-distance services without facing the tests the Bells must
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, no Bell has passed. New local phone companies and the
long-distance giants have consistently maintained that the Bells
have hindered their ability to sign up and serve local customers.
Under Hundt and his successor, William Kennard, the FCC has agreed
with that assessment, denying applications in Oklahoma, Illinois,
Louisiana and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic has appeared to go far beyond the other Bells
in taking the steps to open its network in New York. For at least
18 months, the New York Public Service Commission has pressed the
company to open its systems; the negotiations between the company
and the New York regulators delayed Bell Atlantic's federal
long-distance filing for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some legislators who passed the Telecommunications
Act, and even some who voted against it, have voiced impatience
with the FCC for what they see as the slow pace of results from the
act (aside from mergers). They have pressed the FCC to begin
allowing Bells into the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's long-distance aspirations took an unexpected
blow last month when the Justice Department, which has an advisory
role in the application process, said the company had not yet
completely opened its network. The Justice Department said the
commission could approve the application subject to conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to the process said Tuesday that it was not
likely that the commission would apply major conditions. Instead,
they said, the commission was poised to outline heavy fines that
would be imposed on Bell Atlantic were the company to slow or
reverse its progress in opening its systems.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman and FCC spokeswoman declined to
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said that Bell Atlantic's success in New York
could become a template for the other Bells. But Hundt, the former
FCC chairman, said Tuesday that New York could prove to be a
special case.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many consumers in New York may not be aware that
they have a choice of local phone provider, AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom
have recently begun to expand their push into the local phone
market in New York. Business customers in New York, especially in
New York City, already enjoy a wide range of options for local
communications.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Bell Atlantic has already paid much of the price
for opening its network. Other Bells in states where competitors
have not already made much progress may have less of an incentive
to open their systems, some analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as important, the long-distance market in New York is
especially lucrative because a large amount of the nation's
international communications begin or end in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear that the other Bells, or even Bell Atlantic
outside New York, will want to make the same effort,'' Hundt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the quick pace of consolidation, coupled with the
crumbling of regulatory barriers, may all but ensure that the
communications market of the future is dominated by a handful of
behemoths that compete across myriad markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will have been in everybody else's markets,'' Hundt
said, ``and competition will be self-policing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
