<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBANS-DETAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBANS FREED   FROM U.S. JAIL   RETURN HOME   TO NEW PRISON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Cuban government has jailed six Cubans who
returned home as part of a deal with the United States that led
them to end a hostage standoff at a Louisiana jail last week,
Clinton administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans, the officials said, were taken off an American
government jet at Havana's international airport in handcuffs and
chains on Monday night and driven to prison. Administration
officials said they had no information on what charges, if any,
might be brought or how long the six might be incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Fidel Castro said in a statement that it had
agreed to the unusual deal with the United States, which has no
formal diplomatic ties to Cuba, to avoid ``a bloody outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   A seventh Cuban who was involved in the hostage incident,
Roberto Villar Grana, 31, was not returned to Cuba, though his
mother had served as a go-between in the negotiations that ended
the six-day siege at the jail in St. Martin Parish, La.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say Villar, who was originally supposed to
join the others on the flight to Cuba, was detained in Louisiana
after a female inmate who was among the hostages said he had raped
her.
</P>
<P>
   Villar is awaiting sentencing Jan. 6 elsewhere in Louisiana for
the attempted murder of a police officer and for cocaine
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials were eager Tuesday to make
clear that the six Cubans who were returned, far from being granted
their freedom, simply faced another jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   Local prosecutors in Louisiana said the Cubans inmates should
have been prosecuted for kidnapping, not granted free passage from
the United States. The prosecutors said the deal between Washington
and Havana could encourage other Cubans being detained in American
prisons to consider uprisings as a way to win freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The six Cubans came to the United States in 1980 during the
Mariel boatlift, which included hundreds of criminals freed from
jail by the Castro government and allowed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Many who arrived in the boatlift were later convicted of crimes,
which made them subject to deportation. The Castro government has
allowed them to be returned to Cuba case by case, a process that
has kept many in prison in the United States for more than a
decade, awaiting the flight home.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service has identified the
Cubans who returned to Cuba on Monday as Jorge Ramirez Acosta, 45;
Lazaro Orta Elisalte, 48; Jonne Ponte Landrian, 28; Mario Mora
Medina, 32; Gerardo Santana Morales, 26; and Juan Miranda Salot,
45.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had no intention of following
up on the treatment of the six by the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not American citizens and never were,'' one official
said. ``They are subject to the laws of Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   An eighth man, a Bahamian whose name has not been released by
the immigration service, was also involved in the prison uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that the man's deportation to the
Bahamas was not required under terms of the agreement reached with
the Cubans, and that he would be returned to the Bahamas under
routine procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
