<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-YEAREND-ART-$AD     12-21 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YEAREND-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A SLOW START, MOST EVERYTHING BUT CHOPIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year took its time before delivering its best. The delay is
understandable, given the millennial nature of the moment. Some of
the best experiences came from abroad: from the Salzburg Festival
and from festive reopenings at the Theatre du Chatelet in Paris and
the Royal Opera House in London. But New York may have ended up
with the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   There was the new production of ``Tristan und Isolde'' at the
Metropolitan Opera, an event that might become a landmark. Marked
as well was the beginning of a Carnegie Hall season extraordinary
for its concentration of the best the passing century has had to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the special events was Pierre Boulez, who in his 70s
has ripened into one of music's more rewarding polymaths: teacher,
composer, theorist, conductor. I didn't hear all of his concerts
and workshops last month, but what I did hear deeply affected me.
</P>
<P>
   Operas experienced in Paris and London during the fall brought
splendid music surrounded by sights one did not always want to see.
Robert Wilson's brilliance extends uneasily to the special problems
of operas of a certain age, but what a revelation to hear Gluck on
successive nights and to savor in large doses the wonderful
directness of this music.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Graham Vick's conception of Verdi's ``Falstaff'' was
vivid and unfailingly cute, but it looked equally uneasy next to
Bryn Terfel's quiet, subdued, astonishingly effective re-creation
of the title role.
</P>
<P>
   I liked Busoni's ``Doktor Faust'' in Salzburg because of, not
despite, its plainness. New Yorkers will have a chance to judge for
themselves; the production and its excellent principal Thomas
Hampson are headed for the Met. Also well remembered is Salzburg's
extravagant fantasy in its production of ``Les Boreades'' by
Rameau, beautifully conducted by Sir Simon Rattle.
</P>
<P>
   `TRISTAN UND ISOLDE' AT THE MET
</P>
<P>
   Jane Eaglen and Ben Heppner are the new hopes for two of
Wagner's demanding title roles. The opera's celebration of the
spirit and the flesh has seeped into the corners of every music
lover's sensibility. So overwhelming is its music that it is often
better remembered or dreamed about. But what a joy, after a long
absence, to have ``Tristan'' onstage just to reassure us that it
really exists.
</P>
<P>
   James Levine was a deliberate yet inspired conductor. Dieter
Dorn's production solved many problems with grace and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   GLUCK IN PARIS
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its renovation and reopening, the Theatre du
Chatelet hit on the clever idea of doing ``Orfeo ed Euridice'' and
``Alceste'' in their French versions. Thus satisfied were
patriotism, history and the desire for beautiful music. Sir John
Eliot Gardiner conducted both operas, combining his big musical
heart and his finicky attentions to period practice.
</P>
<P>
   None of the principals were real stars, but the melody flowed
almost without end for two consecutive nights. Recreating Wilson's
sense of gracefully suspended time is really an art in itself.
Opera singers approach it awkwardly, or, at least, most did here.
</P>
<P>
   `DOKTOR FAUST' IN SALZBURG
</P>
<P>
   Busoni worked endlessly on this opera; and though he is not
ultimately a man of the theater, he invests the orchestra part with
a dramatic life that one can almost see. Hampson was splendid in
the title role, and the Salzburg Festival's dark, dingy, ominous
production, with its railroad tracks and handcars, underlined the
inner turmoils that the opera contemplates.
</P>
<P>
   `LES BOREADES' IN SALZBURG
</P>
<P>
   It was a riot of shiny surfaces and glittery decor and costumes.
Given was less Rameau's work from start to finish than an essay on
the elements of Baroque opera. The dances listened to the music and
rethought Baroque style in their own modern terms. Under Sir
Simon's baton, the Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment played
with great joy. A happy evening.
</P>
<P>
   `FALSTAFF' AT COVENT GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   Here was another reopening and another celebration of
renovations just completed, at the Royal Opera House in London.
Vick's production of Verdi's opera created a colorful and
topsy-turvy world with occasional sly touches. But with Terfel's
dignified and restrained portrayal of Falstaff himself, all the
acrobatics and sight gags seemed a little out of place. Terfel was
a wonder: clear, unforced singing and a total immersion in the
part.
</P>
<P>
   `ARIODANTE' AT THE CITY OPERA
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Opera can now put on sophisticated productions
of Handel operas and supply the singers to do them with style.
``Ariodante'' was given a simple, stately staging by John Copley.
An American contingent of singers led by Bejun Mehta, Amy Burton
and Lisa Saffer was strong, but it was the phenomenal English
mezzo-soprano Sarah Connolly, in the title role, who caught the
imagination. The voice is dark and true, remarkably flexible and
filled with the required heat.
</P>
<P>
   BOULEZ CONDUCTS SCRIABIN
</P>
<P>
   Scrupulous care and rationality from a great French conductor
have made clear the sensual if somewhat mad beauties of a Russian
composer in a recording from Deutsche Grammophon. The paradox is
delicious, but there it is nonetheless, in Scriabin's ``Poem of
Ecstasy,'' Piano Concerto and ``Prometheus.'' Boulez keeps the
excesses of the Chicago Symphony in check. The excellent pianist is
Anatol Ugorski.
</P>
<P>
   `MOSES UND ARON' AT THE MET
</P>
<P>
   I may dispute the ultimate greatness of Schoenberg's only big
opera, but the Met's production, conducted by Levine, was an
important event for lovers and nonlovers. The opera lives in its
chorus parts, and they are difficult and wearing indeed. The Met's
ensemble singers did wonderfully, and an important piece of history
is firmly in the company's repertory.
</P>
<P>
   `RADIO CITY CHRISTMAS SPECTACULAR' No blast of sheer pleasure
could be more welcome after a year of pondering the verities of art
and music. The precision and swiftness of this two-hour review are
astonishing, and I am afraid the Rockettes have snatched my heart
forever. Note, especially, the small army of dancing Santas. This
will be on my list next year as well.
</P>
<P>
   CHOPIN: NOTHING
</P>
<P>
   The silence at the 150th anniversary of Chopin's death has been
surprising but perhaps salutary. There have been a few recitals,
often in the context of local music schools and conservatories.
What are we to do otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   Chopin is among the most original, accomplished, beloved and
performed of all composers, and music celebrates his presence
continually, regardless of memorials by the calendar. I am happy to
commemorate the anniversary by wishing Chopin the blessing of
silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
