<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5784 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-FUNDRAISING-2TAK     12-21 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ADOPT GOP TACTIC TO SKIRT REGULATIONS ON `SOFT MONEY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., La., Mich., Fla., Mo., Calif., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic Party has established a half-dozen
committees to channel large, unregulated contributions to Senate
candidates, hoping to circumvent bans on using such money for
individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The party has created so-called ``victory funds,'' similar to
committees established for some Republican Senate candidates, to
collect unrestricted ``soft money'' donations for Senate races in
New York, Massachusetts, Louisiana, Michigan, Florida, Missouri and
California. While the funds were ostensibly created to aid
state-level Democratic campaigns, the so-called joint committees
are all incorporated at the party's national headquarters in
Washington and run by national Democratic officials.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said the funds, which seek to collect
millions of dollars, are intended to circumvent Federal Election
Commission rules that limit the size of contributions to individual
candidates and bar the national parties from raising and spending
soft money contributions on specific campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee said
the funds are legal and do not attempt to disguise their purpose,
although they made no effort to publicize them when they were
created over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joint committees allow us to fully comply with FEC
regulations. They provide our donors with a convenient vehicle for
contributions and help the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee
with administrative ease and simplification,'' said David
DiMartino, a spokesman for the Democratic Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who first devised this type of fund-raising
committee two years ago, have set up two such funds this year, for
Senate candidates in Pennsylvania and Missouri, said Stuart Roy, a
spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is no fund for New York City Mayor Rudolph . Giuliani, who
is expected to seek the Republican senatorial nomination, but
national party officials did not rule out establishing one next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The fund set up for Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is seeking the
Democratic nomination, has collected ``several hundred thousand
dollars,'' DiMartino said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Election law experts said that the committees themselves are
probably legal, but could run afoul of federal election law if the
spending is too closely coordinated with individual candidates or
if donors are somehow deceived about the purpose of their
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not illegal for a candidate to raise money for a soft
money account of the party, and then if that money finds its way
back into the state committee apparatus and is spent consistent the
rules,'' said Kenneth Gross, an election law specialist in
Washington. ``The jeopardy is greater on the spending side, but the
Federal Election Commission has shown a great deal of latitude on
spending by state parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The committees permit individual donors to contribute more than
the $2,000 limit that federal law allows for so-called hard money
donations from individuals to political candidates in the primaries
and general election. A corporate or union political action
committee can contribute up to $10,000 per election cycle and a
party committee, such as the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, can give $17,500 in direct assistance to a candidate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new state-level victory funds can take in much larger
donations outside the limits of the federal election law. For
example, if a contributor wants to give $100,000 (or even $1
million) to Mrs. Clinton's New York Senate campaign, the donor
cannot give a check of that size directly to the campaign. The
donor would instead be steered to an entity called Victory in New
York 2000, a soft-money account that can accept unlimited
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   That committee _ incorporated at national committee headquarters
in Washington and run by the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee _ will then apportion the funds under terms of a tacit
agreement with the Clinton campaign, officials of the party's
senate committee said. A formal agreement to earmark the money
solely for the Clinton campaign would be a violation of federal
campaign finance law that bars spending soft money on individual
candidates, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, Victory in New York 2000 takes in the
contribution, and then sends some of it back to the Clinton
campaign as hard money. Some of the money may be sent to the New
York Democratic Party, some may be used for television advertising
in New York or nationally and some may be distributed to other
states with competitive Senate races.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows you to have a donor write one check,'' said a
Democratic official involved in the process who explained the
program on condition his name not be published. ``The joint
fund-raising committee serves as kind of a shell, it takes the
money and divides it out to the different committees.''
</P>
<P>
   The committees are obligated to disclose contributions of $200
or more and must file reports every six months; the first filings
are due in mid-January. DiMartino said that in addition to the
money raised for Mrs. Clinton in New York, there are several
hundred thousand dollars in the accounts of the other six
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the Democratic party had never before used
this mechanism for raising and spending political money.
</P>
<P>
   The first fund-raising committee of this type was created by the
Republicans on behalf of Matt Fong, the unsuccessful Republican
candidate for Senate in California in 1998, a Republican official
said. The Republicans used a variant of the joint fund-raising
system in several states in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning from them,'' DiMartino said.
</P>
<P>
   The development comes soft money comes under attack in the
presidential campaign and as Senate contest have become increasing
expensive. Each side in New York's U.S. Senate race, for example,
is expected to spend as much as $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the current system of financing political campaigns
said the fund-raising committees operate in a legal gray area
because they clearly are designed to funnel unregulated soft money
into campaigns for individual candidates. Federal law allows such
contributions only to be used for so-called party-building
operations such as get-out-the-vote drives, polling and voter
education programs. But the Federal Election Commission, which has
a relatively weak enforcement record, could have difficulty closely
monitoring the spending of state political groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Cooper, a former senior FEC official who now runs a
campaign-finance watchdog group called Public Disclosure Inc., said
the committees are a new wrinkle in the old game of collecting
unrestricted money at the state level, routing it through a federal
committee and then sending it back to the states with instructions
on how it is to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the newly crafted version,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that recent FEC filings illustrate how the system
works. In October, one fund-raising entity for Mrs. Clinton
transferred $200,000 in soft money contributions to the Democrat
Senate committee. Shortly thereafter, the national committee
transferred $100,000 to the New York Democratic Party, which paid
for an advertising campaign on behalf of Mrs. Clinton in November,
the federal records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably legal,'' Cooper said. ``But it's still a
scheme.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
