<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BROADWAY-PLAYS-ART-$A     12-21 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-PLAYS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIERCE `WOOLF,' JOYOUS `CONTACT,' CLASSIC `SALESMAN'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An 80-year-old actress sheds decades to become a
fierce middle-aged tigress with unsheathed claws; classic dramas
shed decades of accumulated tarnish to glimmer like newly polished
silver, and even the American musical sheds its decades-old status
as an endangered species, with shows that instead reflected its
singular role as a mood elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Below, an assortment of uppers that affirm the theater's
distinctive powers of self-rejuvenation in the last year of the
century, plus one major downer, standing in (alas) for many other
productions of the same sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   `WHO'S AFRAID OF VIRGINIA WOOLF?'
</P>
<P>
   Edward Albee's masterpiece rematerialized, like a Brigadoon
built of fire, for just one night, in a benefit for the HB
Playwrights Foundation and Theater. And, oh, what a night it was.
Uta Hagen brilliantly reclaimed the role she created nearly four
decades ago _ of Martha, the cannibal earth mother _ with a pro's
authority and a neophyte's zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pryce and Mia Farrow (who should both take up permanent
residence on Broadway), plus the ever-game Matthew Broderick,
helped Ms. Hagen turn what was nominally a staged reading into the
year's most dazzling evening of theater.
</P>
<P>
   `CONTACT'
</P>
<P>
   And you thought they didn't make 'em anymore. Susan Stroman's
three-part ode to the redemptive powers of dance is indeed a
real-live newborn musical. And unlike most new offerings in the
genre, which tend toward dourness and dissonance, this one is
unabashedly joyous. Along with ``James Joyce's `The Dead''' _ a far
more imbalanced but equally original work _ ``Contact'' happily
demonstrates that the American musical, which had been looking as
stunted as a bonsai, still has room to grow.
</P>
<P>
   `KISS ME, KATE'
</P>
<P>
   The big, flashy revival that got the formula right. Michael
Blakemore (director), Kathleen Marshall (choreographer) and a
justifiably self-delighted cast led by Brian Stokes Mitchell and
Marin Mazzie bring a pulsing immediacy to Cole Porter's classic.
Theatrical ham, it seems, never spoils if it's properly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   `DEATH OF A SALESMAN,' `THE ICEMAN COMETH' and `NOT ABOUT
NIGHTINGALES'
</P>
<P>
   The three productions that made this the best season for vintage
drama that Broadway has known in many a year. Two mythic salesmen,
Arthur Miller's Willy Loman and Eugene O'Neill's Hickey, were
reincarnated in the formidable persons of Brian Dennehy and Kevin
Spacey, while Elizabeth Franz's Linda Loman brought electric
complexity to a character long dismissed as a human doormat.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Nunn, in the meantime, achieved a glorious act of
resurrection in his passionate but delicate direction of
``Nightingales,'' a long-lost study in heartbreak by the young
Tennessee Williams that deserved a longer run than it got.
</P>
<P>
   `THE WEIR' and `THIS LIME TREE BOWER'
</P>
<P>
   Two deeply felt, intricately structured studies in the
impossibility of separating the teller from the tale, from the
young Irish playwright Conor McPherson. Seen both on Broadway
(``Weir,'' in an exquisitely acted import from London) and Off
(``Bower,'' in a more awkward domestic incarnation), these plays
established McPherson as an irresistible force in contemporary
drama, while reminding audiences of the distinctive powers of
theater as a vehicle for storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   `HOUSE/LIGHTS'
</P>
<P>
   The Wooster Group, the venerable experimental theater troupe
directed by Elizabeth LeCompte, took its mixed-media style to new
heights of sophistication with a show that translated Cubism into
flamboyantly theatrical terms. With an ensemble led by the peerless
Kate Valk, as the automaton spirit of modern times incarnate, the
production blended a Gertrude Stein opera libretto about Faust with
a hokey but sinister 1960s cult movie to consider the dehumanizing
deals contemporary culture has made with the devils of technology.
</P>
<P>
   `VIA DOLOROSA'
</P>
<P>
   David Hare, the most widely represented playwright on Broadway
this spring (``The Blue Room,'' ``Amy's View''), courageously
turned actor for his fascinating one-man show about the Gordian
knot that is the Middle East. Oddly enough, this first-person piece
of reportage was steeped in a provocative ambiguity lacking this
season in Hare's fictional dramas. And with the help of the
director Stephen Daldry, Hare ingeniously made a compelling
theatrical style out of his very stiffness and self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   `BETTY'S SUMMER VACATION'
</P>
<P>
   The triumphant return of Christopher Durang to the ranks of
America's most incisive living playwrights and a vivid testament to
the fact that satire, shaped with enough idiosyncratic charm, can
sear like no other form. Directed by Nicholas Martin, this surreal
comedy of television, tabloids and domestic homicide brought a
whole new spin to the idea of a culture that is entertaining itself
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Also heeding the muse of satire with exceptional flair: David
Lindsay-Abaire, who made a spectacularly promising debut with
``Fuddy Meers,'' a memorable comedy of amnesia, and the redoubtable
Dame Edna Everage (aka Barry Humphries), currently giving Broadway
a lesson in what it means to be a star.
</P>
<P>
   AUDRA MCDONALD
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Marie Christine,'' the highly anticipated musical
by Michael John LaChiusa, failed to enchant, its star once again
showed herself to be a theatrical sorceress of the first order.
Playing a late-19th-century Medea-like woman scorned, Ms. McDonald
parlayed her remarkable fluency in assorted musical vernaculars
into a breathtaking character portrait, all the more compelling for
its implicit contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   `SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER'
</P>
<P>
   The year's most resounding example of everything wrong with the
contemporary Broadway megamusical. A literal-minded retelling of
the 1977 movie, this dreary show managed to eliminate every vestige
of the rebellious energy and sensuality that made the film a hit,
while turning the show's dance-loving characters into an assembly
line of lead-footed androids.
</P>
<P>
   As a lesson in dehumanization, it's on a level with
``House/Lights,'' though this could surely not have been what the
creators of ``Fever'' had in mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
