A5808 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HIS, HERS, OURS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I'm flipping through the Neiman Marcus catalog. The
store's Christmas book has always been a wonderful anthropological
document, defining standards of extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   In this gilded IPO age, in this week in which Time magazine has
decided that the most important man of 1999 was the one who started
Amazon.com, in this season in which the New York auction houses are
breaking records every 20 minutes or so, I am curious about the
outer limit of conspicuous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Neiman's has offered such outlandish his-and-hers
big-ticket items as a pair of Beechcraft airplanes, a pair of
diamonds cut from a single rough stone totaling 77 carats,
his-and-hers hot air balloons, a matching Jaguar coupe and jaguar
coat, Chinese junks, submarines, dirigibles, camels, Egyptian mummy
cases, Chinese Shar-pei puppies, ermine bathrobes, robots,
windmills, buffalo calves, Hummers and chunks of adoptable rain
forest.
</P>
<P>
   How over-the-top would its top-of-the-line present be in this
fin to end all siecles?
</P>
<P>
   I eagerly turn to the last page, ``1999 His &AMP; Hers: A Lasting
Legacy.'' And underneath _ could I be seeing things? _ a picture of
the Clintons! In the fetching photo in front of the White House
Christmas tree, Bill has on his Christmas tie and Hillary has on
her red-and-green plaid frock.
</P>
<P>
   It had finally happened. After all these frantic years of
borrowed money, funny money, soft money, hard money, owed money, no
money, the Clintons had been forced to put themselves on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich in history and holiday tradition, the Clintons are living
heirlooms,'' the Neiman's blurb reads. ``You've admired them. Now
you can help the federal government support them. If you purchase
the Clintons, even quiet family dinners would be an event. Think of
the unique experience of seeing these two `interacting.' No party
could resist an ice-breaker of such memorable proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golden couple of politics is now available to take home,
if you have enough gold. Why settle for a Waterford millennium bowl
($3,500, p. 134) or an original copy of the beloved 1822 poem ``The
Night Before Christmas'' by the Rev. Clement C. Moore ($795,000, p.
38) when you can have the ultimate luxury goods?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let others dally with the politics of authenticity. We can
FedEx you the politics of cupidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider some of the things that make this offering so
deliciously irresistible. The arc of the Clintons' lives, their
transformation from hicks to the most expensive couple in American
political history, is truly remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a saga of unsurpassed his-and-hers chutzpah. Hillary's
nascent New York campaign and jaunt to Israel have been happily
placed on the public tab. And over the weekend, the Clintons
floated a priceless trial balloon suggesting that they might
actually seek reimbursement from the federal government for their
$5 million in legal fees in the Monica Lewinsky mess. Now that's
moxie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton has a finely tuned eye for trompe l'oeil,
creating inventions worthy of the Old Masters. This is your chance
to become a true patron of the black arts, to underwrite the lie
that cost more people more money than any other lie in history!
</P>
<P>
   ``This special purchase comes with an exciting bonus: free
advice from the president's bankroller/best friend, Terry
McAuliffe, who will be grateful to you for lifting from his
shoulders the Herculean burden of filling the Clinton money pit.
Before this unprecedented offer, McAuliffe was the sole proprietor
of the first couple, raising more than $275 million for the
president's library and the Clintons' campaigns and legal bills,
and guaranteeing $1.35 million for their first mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But McAuliffe is, after all, only one man. And Hollywood is,
after all, only one well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why spend a fortune on Di's dresses and Marilyn's nighties
when you can have a living, breathing, conniving piece of
Americana?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a gift to future generations. Do you really
want the American public to have to pay $5 million on top of the
$47 million Starr investigation and on top of hundreds of thousands
in reimbursements for the legal fees of Clinton aides _ just
because Bill Clinton couldn't admit in a timely fashion that he
fooled around with an intern?
</P>
<P>
   ``A gift that will keep on taking, for a mere $200,000,000,000.
Allow eight weeks for delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
