<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: EXIT RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem said no emergency exit would be
opened in the Holy Sepulcher Church, despite Israel's request for
such an exit. The sects who share the site ``did not come to an
agreement and the Israeli government said OK,'' the patriarch,
Michel Sabbah, said. He also said the decision to build a small
mosque next to the Basilica of the Annunciation in Nazareth is
being reconsidered, despite the recent laying of a cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT: PYRAMID PLANS REVERSED
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has abandoned a plan to place a golden capstone atop the
largest pyramid at the height of millennium celebrations.
Opposition newspapers have described the capstone as a Zionist
symbol; archaeologists fear the cap could damage the structure.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: FUJIMORI MAY RUN
</P>
<P>
   The election board accepted the application of President Alberto
Fujimori's coalition Peru 2000 for a place on the ballot in April,
allowing him to run for a third term. Fujimori is expected to
announce his candidacy next week. Fujimori has dismissed several
judges who stood in the way of a re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: POLITICAL MANEUVER
</P>
<P>
   In a move aimed at benefiting Gerry Adams, president of Sinn
Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army, the
government will introduce a law permitting politicians in the
British Parliament and the Northern Ireland Assembly to run for
seats in the Irish Parliament in Dublin. Adams is a member of the
Belfast assembly and of the British Parliament, though he has not
taken his seat because of the need to pledge allegiance to the
queen.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FAYED WINS LIBEL SUIT
</P>
<P>
   A London jury found that Mohamed Al Fayed, the owner of Harrods,
did not libel Neil Hamilton, a former Conservative member of the
House of Commons, when he said he had made cash payments to
Hamilton in exchange for parliamentary favors. Hamilton, who lost
his seat in 1997 over the charges, must pay $1.6 million in court
costs.
</P>
<P>
   MOLDOVA: NEW PREMIER
</P>
<P>
   Parliament elevated the deputy economic minister to prime
minister, breaking a political deadlock dating to Nov. 9, when
legislators ousted the reform-oriented Ion Sturza in a
no-confidence vote. The new leader, Dumitru Braghis, 42, faces an
economic crisis that has led international lenders to suspend aid.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: POLICE FOIL BOMB ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a routine traffic stop foiled a huge bomb attack
by the armed Basque separatist group ETA in Madrid. The police
discovered a ton of explosives and a timing device near Calatayud
in a white van that was on its way to the capital. The seizure came
three weeks after ETA ended its 14-month cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: REBELS GET A PASS
</P>
<P>
   About 173 separatist guerrillas in Assam have accepted a state
government offer allowing them safe passage for 10 days to meet
their families on New Year's Eve, officials said. Leaders of
militiant groups like the United Front of Assam and the National
Democratic Front of Bodoland rejected the offer, but some
guerrillas chose to accept it, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SECURITY ALERT
</P>
<P>
   Security in tribal areas in Gujarat, the scene of violence
against Christians this year, has been stepped up for Christmas, a
government statement said. Protection has been provided for 748
places in four districts, including churches and prayer halls, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NAMIBIA: UNITA FIRES BACK
</P>
<P>
   Angolan rebels fired mortars into Mbambi village, killing a
policeman and wounding three others, local news media reported. The
Unita rebels were apparently responding to Namibia's decision to
allow Angolan soldiers to use Namibia as a staging area for attacks
on the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
