<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANKONE-MARKETPLACE-N     12-21 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKONE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: MCCOY PAYS THE PRICE AT BANK ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ John McCoy, the chief executive who helped transform
Bank One Corp. from a regional bank into the nation's
fourth-largest bank holding company through big mergers, stepped
down Tuesday after a tumultuous year at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's board said that McCoy, 56, had decided to retire as
chief executive and chairman of the board effective immediately.
His duties will be assumed by Verne Istock, 59, the president of
Bank One, who will serve as acting chief executive until a
successor is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Bank One, which have been severely depressed for
months, soared on the news, climbing $3.375 to $33.375 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's decision to step down from Bank One, which is based
here, comes after a series of executive departures tied to a
yearlong earnings slide that was largely attributed to the
company's First USA credit card and consumer lending division,
which accounts for about one-third of the bank's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which surprised many on Wall Street, also underscores
the great difficulties that banks and other large institutions are
facing after a wave of expensive mergers and acquisitions that have
put increasing pressure on top executives to integrate diverse
corporate cultures and then create the kind of earnings growth that
would justify such deals.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said that McCoy had promised great things
from the new Bank One, which merged last year with First Chicago
NDB Corp. A year earlier, Bank One acquired First USA, one of the
nation's largest credit card issuers, with more than 64 million
customers and about $70 billion in assets in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   First USA was supposed to be the growth engine, helping to power
a big national bank. But First USA began sliding earlier this year,
partly because of increased competition but also because of growing
attrition rates, high penalty fees compared with rivals and poor
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The profit declines in the First USA division hit Bank One hard,
creating two quarters of disappointing earnings, and there have
been warnings from the company about more bad news to come.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price of Bank One is down about 50 percent from its
high of $64.875 in April 1998, and below the level it was before
the Bank One merger with First Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Dickson, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, says that
Bank One profit warnings have punished the stock. For 2000, profit
expectations have been cut by 32 percent, accounting for about $1.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, shareholders have taken a bath, analysts said, with
the bank losing more than $30 billion in market value. And there
have been rumors that the bank's stock collapse made it a possible
takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   A group of shareholders has already filed a class-action
lawsuit, saying that the company concealed earnings information,
and the board, which included at least one huge shareholder, grew
disenchanted with McCoy, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some on the board thought they had been sold a pig in a
poke,'' said Nancy Bush, a banking analyst at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``I
was told the move today cleared the logjam on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision came after a series of resignations and
shake-ups. Earlier this year, two vice chairmen retired and the
head of the First USA division resigned. In October, the board
reshuffled management duties, giving McCoy oversight of First USA
and Istock control over the day-to-day duties of most of the other
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the problems went far beyond First USA. There
were high expectations and failed promises, management missteps and
a clash of cultures between the ambitious, risky Bank One group and
the more risk-averse First Chicago executives.
</P>
<P>
   John Rau, the chief executive at Chicago Title Corp. and former
employee of First Chicago, said that the board of Bank One got
impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it said there are different skills necessary in
driving a series of community banks through a series of deals and
riding this big train,'' he said. ``They had this First USA deal
and it seems they hitched too much to that star.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, who was with the bank for more than 29 years and served
as chief executive for the last 15 years, retired without making
any statement. He got his start in Columbus, Ohio, where Bank One
had been based until this year. And he was the third member of his
family to head the bank. His grandfather was a bank executive in
the 1930s, and his father, John G. McCoy, created the Banc One name
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Istock, the former chief executive at First Chicago, is said by
analysts to be more averse to risk, and in the interim, while the
bank searches for a replacement, he may be exactly what the company
needs _ something steady. The bank said it expected to complete its
search for a chief executive in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Istock said he had to withhold comment
until January, when the bank plans to meet analysts to offer
details about its financial situation and the problems at First
USA.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the company might be considering a spinoff of
the First USA division or a sale or merger of the company, but the
consensus now is that the bank must right its ship first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
