<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EDITOR'S NOTE FOR WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 22
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: This editor's note will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-WEB-PATENTS-ART-NYT (moved on Friday, Dec. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 10,
about the rise in Internet-related patents referred to one recently
granted to LinkShare, a New York company. The article said the
patent gave LinkShare the right to block other Web sites from using
an arrangement in which they earn commissions from purchases by
users they refer to online stores. The article described the
LinkShare patent as a technique for doing business, a claim with
potentially broad implications, rather than a narrow technological
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The article should have attributed the description of the
patent's breadth to LinkShare. No legal claims have yet arisen, and
LinkShare's competitors say they feel the patent has a more limited
scope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RUBINSTEIN-MUSIC-2TAK     12-21 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBINSTEIN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE FILLED WITH THE SHEER JOY OF PLAYING THE PIANO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur Rubinstein was 42 and had long been famous when he made
his first recording, on March 9, 1929, at the studios of the
Gramophone Company, or HMV, in London. Before this he had disdained
existing recording technology, which, he said, made the piano sound
like a banjo.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of electrical recording, with its greater
fidelity, in 1925 changed his mind. When Rubinstein heard the
results of his first session, a performance of Chopin's Barcarolle,
he had tears in his eyes, he later recalled: ``It was the kind of
performance I dreamed of, and the sound reproduced faithfully the
golden tone of the piano. This was a very important day. A new life
had begun for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it had. Rubinstein continued making records, extensively,
almost compulsively, for nearly 50 years. He started recording in
1940 for RCA Victor, then an HMV affiliate, and became one of that
company's best-selling artists. Finally, in 1976, at 89, he made
his last recording (Schumann's ``Fantasiestucke'' and Beethoven's
Sonata No. 18) and retired.
</P>
<P>
   The same qualities that distinguished his artistry on the
concert stage made him ideally suited to the recording studio:
seemingly endless stamina; a keen intelligence, which enabled him
to commit a vast repertory to memory and keep it there; rich,
singing tone, which carried beautifully even in pianissimo
passages; a special combination of elan and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   No pianist of this century conveyed more sheer joy in playing
the piano, and few gave more concerts. You cannot imagine
Rubinstein plagued by stage fright or finger strain.
</P>
<P>
   He was even more relaxed in the recording studio. Max Wilcox,
one of Rubinstein's producers at RCA, has left a vivid account of
recording the pianist in all 14 Chopin waltzes at a studio in Rome
in 1963. On that breezy summer night, Rubinstein played the affable
host, as if for a evening of music at his home. His younger son,
the actor John Rubinstein, then 17, turned pages.
</P>
<P>
   RCA had scheduled sessions for several evenings. But on the
first night, the 76-year-old pianist started at 6:45 and, pleased
with the results, kept going, finishing the final waltz at 11:15.
``We were all limp _ but not Rubinstein,'' Wilcox writes. ``The
party on the Via Veneto lasted until 2:30 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Now RCA Red Seal has released the pianist's entire discography
in a deluxe boxed set, ``The Arthur Rubinstein Collection'': 94 CDs
in 82 volumes, more than 106 hours of music, making it one of the
biggest and most expensive special collections yet issued. (Retail
cost is about $1,300.) Everything is here: the early HMV
recordings; many RCA recordings that have long been absent from the
catalog; all of the many chamber and concerto performances;
recordings of live concerts that were released commercially; and
some items that have never previously been issued.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Rubinstein's legacy is clear just from looking at,
not to mention lifting, the collection, which comes in a gray,
clothbound, 15-by-20-inch case, with flaps that open to reveal two
crammed rows of CDs. All the recordings have been carefully
remastered.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Rubinstein was a major musician of this century.
Still, this collection raises nagging questions: What is it for?
Who is the target buyer?
</P>
<P>
   The set is not ideally organized for archives or libraries. The
recordings are generally presented in chronological order, though
many volumes offer mixed programs drawn from different periods.
Inexplicably, no index is provided. A 376-page accompanying book,
printed in three languages (English, German, French), offers essays
and reminiscences by colleagues, and lists the contents of each
volume. But there is no way to look up, for example, how many
recordings Rubinstein made of Chopin's Second Concerto without
leafing through the entire catalog. (The answer is four.)
</P>
<P>
   The collection could have provided a critical guide to the
discography, recording by recording, explaining the circumstances
under which each was made and giving an informed evaluation of the
results. The model for such a reference source is the critic John
Ardoin's book ``The Callas Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   RCA's deluxe limited edition, released in time for the holidays,
would seem to be a luxury purchase for moneyed consumers. It will
certainly attract attention in an owner's living room. But do even
Rubinstein's greatest admirers need to have, for example, all four
of his recordings of Brahms' Second Concerto?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is easy for a critic who got this set free to
forget how much pleasure it might bring to a music lover who must
pay a lot for it. There is a wealth of magnificent music-making on
these discs by an artist sometimes overlooked in debates about the
pantheon of 20th-century pianists.
</P>
<P>
   This collection should set that neglect right. I was surprised
to realize how many of these recordings were familiar from my
having grown up with them. In the interest of full disclosure I
should state that I have not listened to anything close to all 106
hours and probably never will. Still, my generous sampling, though
sometimes stupefying, was gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein's first recordings are particularly fascinating for
what they reveal about his subsequent development. Later in life,
he was candid about his young years as a prodigiously talented but
cocky and careless pianist.
</P>
<P>
   In the second volume of his memoirs, ``My Many Years,''
Rubinstein calls his childhood practice regimen a ``cheat and a
fake'': ``My technical facility allowed me to learn in no time a
concerto, a sonata or some shorter pieces, which I dared to play in
concerts with the greatest aplomb, covering technically difficult
passages with an intelligent use of pedal or with some dynamic
impacts which gave the innocent listener the idea I had played the
piece to perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks the pianist was exaggerating should listen to
his first recording of Brahms' Second Concerto, from 1929, with the
London Symphony Orchestra conducted by Albert Coates, the premiere
recording of the concerto. Rubinstein brings dash and brio to a
work often treated today like some weighty monument of the Germanic
repertory. The tempos are brisk, and the textures are light. The
account is exciting and sunny.
</P>
<P>
   But there are whole handfuls of wrong notes and audaciously
faked passages. It is not that Rubinstein lacked technique, as the
brilliance of his playing in a 1932 recording of Falla's ``Ritual
Fire Dance'' makes clear. But he didn't work hard enough here to
conquer the technical challenges of the unwieldy Brahms concerto.
In comparison, the Falla was a splashy work that he could dispatch
with his trademark fervor and panache.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, he wowed audiences with his arm-blurring
rendition of the ``Ritual Fire Dance,'' as he recalled in a 1969
French documentary about his life. Sitting with a self-satisfied
smile in his beautiful Paris villa, Rubinstein said: ``That piece
bought me this house.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, after a six-year courtship, Rubinstein married Aniela
Mlynarski, the 23-year-old daughter of a fine Polish conductor. In
the summer of 1934 their first child, Eva, was born, while they
stayed in a French mountain village. Becoming a family man in his
late 40s must have shaken him. He may also have been taken aback by
the increasing fidelity of recordings, which revealed his technical
shortcomings all too plainly. That summer he shut himself into a
stable room with an upright piano and worked maniacally on his
technique, up to nine hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged a transformed pianist, as recordings from that time
make clear. In his 1937 account of Liszt's Hungarian Rhapsody No.
10, he sounds like a technical phenomenon. The fingerwork is fleet
and crystalline, and the repeated octave passages are supple and
delicate. The performance is filled with color and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The recording of Chopin's First Concerto from the same year,
with John Barbirolli conducting the London Symphony, is also
splendid: rhapsodic, lyrical, with pearly passagework and crisp
rhythmic vitality. Barbirolli takes a huge cut in the long
orchestral exposition that begins the first movement, but such
practice was not uncommon at the time.
</P>
<P>
   There are other rarities to admire, like the 1947 recording of
Beethoven's Fourth Concerto, with Thomas Beecham conducting the
Royal Philharmonic. Rubinstein's playing is scintillating and
exciting. Interestingly, in the first and third movements he
performs cadenzas composed by Saint-Saens, which are almost
Lisztian in their Romanticism yet tasteful and effective. This
performance makes the Fourth seem as aristocratic as the mighty
``Emperor'' Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   There is no straying from Beethoven's score in a 1944 recording
of the Third Concerto with Arturo Toscanini conducting the NBC
Symphony Orchestra. Rubinstein is on his best behavior here,
playing everything scrupulously for the exacting maestro yet with
Classical refinement and lots of verve.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly numerous recordings of 20th-century works put
Rubinstein's relationship to his own time in perspective. As a
young man, he played and championed music by composer colleagues,
including Ravel, Falla, Albeniz, Villa-Lobos, Rachmaninoff,
Milhaud, Prokofiev and, especially, his beloved Polish countryman
Karol Szymanowski. He later kept these works in his repertory but
did not play new works by younger composers, a fact that led to his
being considered old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   I heard him intelligently challenge this simplistic
characterization in an interview late in his life. When he was
young, he said, he played music that was new, as young people are
wont to do. ``The music of today is for the young,'' he said, ``not
for me. I don't understand it. But I don't criticize it either. You
cannot criticize what you do not understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Rubinstein recordings, his numerous accounts of
Chopin's works are probably the most familiar. RCA has kept many of
these available, with good reason: Rubinstein set the standard in
this century for Chopin playing. In these performances he achieves
an uncanny balance between freedom and structure, between long-line
lyricism and harmonic color, between pianistic elegance and musical
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   He brings an almost Classical quality of restraint and
refinement to music often subjected to emotive distortions in the
name of rubato. There is a virile yet cool quality to his
expressivity, which somehow makes the music even more melancholic.
And his feeling for Polish dance rhythms is authentic and
infectious.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone ever played the 51 mazurkas better? Both the complete
recording from 1952-53 and the slightly more autumnal version from
1965-66 are landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The set includes three interviews that Rubinstein did in the
1960s but not my favorite conversation, which took place two
decades later on public television, when he was 90. The
interviewer, Robert MacNeil, remarked that though a famous bon
vivant, Rubinstein was now at an age when it was impossible to
resist facing mortality. MacNeil asked the pianist for his thoughts
on the matter. Did he, for example, believe in life after death?
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein answered that for him, as an intellectual man, this
was a concept he could not accept. Then, his eyes twinkling, he
said, ``Of course, if I am incorrect, I will be delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   He would no doubt be delighted to live on through ``The
Rubinstein Collection.'' Now I just have to find a place in my
apartment to put the thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
