 _ SF CHRON  
 AT&AMP;T Slams Pac Bell for Tactics to Snatch Back Local Customers  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
AT&AMP;T accused Pacific Bell yesterday of a ``systematic and
fraudulent campaign'' to monopolize California's telephone market
by illegally causing thousands of customers who picked AT&AMP;T for
local-toll call service to switch back to Pac Bell.
<P>
   In a formal complaint filed with the California Public Utilities
Commission, AT&AMP;T charged that Pac Bell and its parent, SBC
Communications, used scare tactics and other illegal methods to get
80,000 AT&AMP;T local-toll customers switched back to Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an unscrupulous effort to maintain a monopoly grip on
local-toll service, Pacific Bell has thwarted competitive choices
of thousands of California residents,'' AT&AMP;T Pacific Region
President president  &LR; Lois Hedgpeth said in a news release.
``SBC/Pacific Bell's actions demonstrate that it is not willing to
compete on a level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell, however, denied the allegations and fired back
charges that AT&AMP;T was guilty of the same practice of ``slamming,''
or switching customers without their permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of the pot calling the kettle
black,'' said John Britton, Pac Bell corporate communications
director. ``This industry and this company helped create the
fraudulent practice of slamming, and they've done it to many of our
local-toll customer.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is another skirmish in the battle to open up
California's lucrative local telephone market to competition. And
if proven, AT&AMP;T's accusations could sour Pacific Bell's upcoming
request to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC in May ruled that California phone customers could sign
up with any phone company as their local-toll carrier. Previously,
Pacific Bell was the main provider of local-toll calls, which are
calls made to regional numbers more than 12 miles away but not
long-distance. Until the May PUC ruling, customers who wanted to
use a different carrier for local-toll calls had to dial a
cumbersome seven-digit code before each call.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Costa, telecommunications research director for the
ratepayer advocacy group The Utility Reform Network, noted that
Pacific Bell has previously said it has recorded about 70,000
complaints of long-distance carriers illegally switching customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tries to make itself look like the good guy,'' Costa said.
``Pacific Bell keeps information on the behavior of other companies
but does not keep information on its own improper behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman Jame Peterson said his company was suspicious of
Pac Bell's claims and had its service representative begin
follow-up surveys of customer who had switched to AT&AMP;T and then had
switched back to Pac Bell for local-toll service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said it found evidence that Pac Bell switched customers
without their consent, used marketing representatives calls and
letters to scare or confuse customers into thinking their service
would be disconnected, and ``circumvented'' a third-party
verification system set up by the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Pac Bell tried to charge AT&AMP;T about $1 million to AT&AMP;T &LR; 
 &LR; to recover the cost of switching customers who had complained
about being slammed, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Billingsly, an analyst with the PUC's Office of
Ratepayer Advocates, said she had not seen the formal complaint or
the evidence gathered by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to doubt that this is happening, although I
have not personally seen any of the data on it,'' Billingsly said.
``It's the kind of behavior that we were worried about when we
devised the rules that governed how you handle customers changing
their service, especially the way Pacific Bell handles it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell has filed for PUC permission to offer long-distance
service, but first has to prove it has done all it could to open
the local market to competition.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T's allegations are true, ``it would cast an unfortunate
pall on (Pacific Bell's) attempts to show they really have done
everything they were supposed to do and are not trying to impede
competition,'' Billingsly said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
