<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CELL-CELL_SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-CELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Biotech Firms' Merger Plan Hits a Snag  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In an unusual case of seller's remorse, the board of directors of
Cell Genesys has advised shareholders in the biotech firm to vote
down a $350 million acquisition by Genzyme Corp. that it had
announced in October.
<P>
   Since October, Foster City's Cell Genesys has seen shares of its
publicly traded spin-off, Abgenix Inc. of Fremont, roughly triple
in value, giving Abgenix a market capitalization of $1.69 billion _
and making Cell Genesys' 22 percent stake in Abgenix worth more
than Genzyme's acquisition offer.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse announcement yesterday, Cell Genesys said it had
tried to renegotiate the deal but had been rebuffed by Genzyme.
Cell Genesys said it would hold a shareholders vote in February.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Cell Genesys spokeswoman, if Genzyme calls off
the merger before the vote, it can demand a $15 million
cancellation fee. But if it allows the vote to proceed and loses,
Cell Genesys walks away for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme, which is based in Massachusetts, refused to comment
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The merger tiff puts a spotlight on the recent success of
Abgenix, which was spun out of Cell Genesys in 1996 to
commercialize a new technology for making drugs based on human
antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Abgenix Chief Financial Officer Kurt Leutzinger explained the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Antibodies are a natural defense against disease. They act like
guided missiles, targeting and destroying specific bacteria or
viruses.
</P>
<P>
   But people's bodies don't always make the correct antibodies,
and in recent years, several biotech firms have assisted nature by
removing antibodies from mice and modifying these mouse antibodies
to fight human diseases. Drugs like the cancer-fighting agent
Herceptin are an example of this.
</P>
<P>
   Leutzinger said Abgenix has taken this strategy one step
further, by creating a special breed of mouse, called the
XenoMouse, that produces human antibodies rather than the mice
variety. Abgenix is now conducting early clinical trials to prove
that its XenoMouse human antibodies work better than the previous
generation of modified mouse antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Investors began to notice Abgenix in July, after the company
reported positive results in a test of its antibody drug for
psoriasis and began a clinical trial of an antibody to fight
several types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to developing its own remedies, Abgenix has licensed
its XenoMouse technology to firms like Pfizer and Amgen, and stands
to earn royalties on drugs they discover using its technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take years, but Abgenix has the technology to grow
into a top-tier biotech firm,'' said Richard van den Broek, an
analyst with Chase Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But van den Broek, a fan of Abgenix, questioned the ``crazy''
market valuations that has driven Abgenix's shares up from around
$20 in July. Shares of the Fremont firm gained $5.25 to close at
$112 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Cell Genesys, which has been overshadowed by its spin-off,
slipped 44 cents yesterday to close at $10.88. Genzyme gained $3.81
to end the day at $42.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
