<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDETRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BUSINESS TRAVEL: B &AMP; B's DRAW CORPORATE TRAVELERS; SURVEYS;(Duplication warning: also moved with `f' code.) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My own impressions of the bed-and-breakfast culture are limited
to a couple of scattered personal experiences reinforced by scenes
in movies like ``Groundhog Day,'' where Bill Murray is trapped for
eternity in one, and ``Flirting With Disaster,'' where the
overbearing proprietor denounces a hapless New York City couple,
Ben Stiller and Patricia Arquette, for disobeying a rule. ``You are
not B &AMP; B people!'' she hollers.
</P>
<P>
   B &AMP; B's don't usually turn up much in business travel
discussions. But in fact, a small but growing number of business
travelers are booking B &AMP; B's, said Eric Goldreyer, the founder and
president of BedandBreakfast.com, a company based in Golden, Colo.,
that lists information and provides an online link to book
accommodations at about 27,000 bed-and-breakfast inns, many of them
in or near major business centers.
</P>
<P>
   Goldreyer, himself a longtime B &AMP; B person, began the company in
1994 after he decided that comprehensive B &AMP; B information was
sparse and mostly available only in regional brochures of uncertain
vintage and reliability. Even assuming you found a place that
seemed right, booking a room was often a matter of making a phone
call and hoping someone would pick up.
</P>
<P>
   ``B &AMP; B information is usually out of date soon after it's
printed,'' he said. His idea to go online with a huge number of
national listings was successful enough that the company was
acquired last June by WorldRes Inc., an online travel network that
operates a booking engine that serves small hotels and resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The B &AMP; B site is easy to navigate and has very detailed
listings (www.bedandbreakfast.com). About two-thirds of the site's
registered users are women, Goldreyer said. This includes women who
travel on business who have little taste for skyscraper hotels with
the waterfalls in the atrium and the sales team roaming the lobby
in tasseled loafers and name tags.
</P>
<P>
   Melisa Harder, the company's marketing director and a frequent
business traveler, said that personal service was a main reason
some female travelers turned to B &AMP; B's. On one recent business
trip to Los Angeles, she said, an airline lost a bag that contained
an outfit she needed. ``I checked into a B &AMP; B worried about what I
was going to wear,'' she said. ``But the innkeeper personally
washed all of my clothes for me and returned them to me cleaned and
ironed while I waited in the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying Travel
</P>
<P>
   Four of every 10 business travelers are women, according to the
1999 National Business Travel Monitor, an annual survey conducted
for the travel industry by Yesawich, Pepperdine &AMP; Brown/Yankelovich
Partners. The survey suggests that the travel industry, especially
the hotel business, needs to pay more attention to serving women.
</P>
<P>
   When evaluating a business hotel, women place a greater emphasis
than men on such things as personal service, understated elegance,
secure electronic door locks, express check-in and check-out, a
selection of good in-hotel restaurants and free airport shuttle
service, the survey shows. Women are also considerably more hard
nosed than men about overall room price and such annoyances as
hotel telephone surcharges. Even when the company is paying the
bill, women resent it far more than men when a hotel tacks on a
75-cent or $1 fee every time they use the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels aside, men and women express roughly the same preferences
when it comes to airlines and car rentals: better service, a wider
range of personal choices and prices, reliable on-time performance,
dependability of brands, comfort and ease of making arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The current survey, incidentally, shows a sharp change in
attitude among business travelers about the prospects of life on
the road. In 1998, 70 percent of business travelers agreed that
innovations in technology would ``reduce business travel in the
future.'' This year, reality seems to have hit. Only 42 percent now
agree with that proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Another finding suggests that travel agents and online travel
companies alike need to think harder about how to provide
information that is considered credible and free of promotional
hype. Among business travelers, word-of-mouth _ anecdotal
information from friends and colleagues _ is the single most
important influence in choosing travel services. Travelers are also
increasingly inclined to go online to check travel recommendations
against the opinions of others in consumer-oriented travel chat
rooms. ``If the feedback is not positive, they are likely to move
to the next alternative,'' the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Side Trips
</P>
<P>
   Business air fares in the United States shot up 6 percent in
October over the comparable period in 1998 _ and were 49 percent
higher than in January 1996. That's according to American Express
Travel Related Services. In 2000, the National Business Travel
Association predicts, business air fares will take off again,
rising 7.7 percent over this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those fare increases, more workers are traveling on
business than ever before. In 1998, nearly 44 million Americans
took at least one business trip, a 14 percent increase over five
years, a survey by the Travel Industry of America finds. Other
findings: The duration of the average business trip was three
nights, and about one in five business travelers rented a car. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
