<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Overtime, Sick Leave Law Changing 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: What are the chief California legislative issues that will &LR; 
 &UR; affect small businesses in the new year? &LR;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: Two major changes in overtime and sick leave will go into
effect January 1. In addition, the Legislature is expected to
tackle major proposals for workers' compensation, unemployment
insurance and minimum wage, according to the California Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   First, the regulations that go into effect January 1:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Overtime &LR;  _ California returns to daily overtime in 2000. Overtime
will be paid after eight hours worked in a day rather than after 40
hours worked in a week. Time-and-a-half will be paid after eight
hours worked in a day and double time after 12 hours in a day.
</P>
<P>
   The new law does provide for makeup time at a regular rate of
pay for employees who work fewer hours one day and more time
another so long as the time is made up in the same week and the
employee works no more than 11 hours in a single day. Makeup time
also requires a written agreement between the employer and
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate work schedules, such as the four-day work week, are
also permitted as long as no more than 10 hours is worked in a day.
Alternate schedules must be approved by a two-thirds secret ballot
vote of the employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Sick Leave &LR;  _ Employers who provide paid sick leave must now allow
employees to use up to half of it for care of a sick parent, child
or spouse. Employees can use this sick leave for any family
illness, including colds and flu. Note: The new law does not
require employers to provide paid sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   The dawn of Y2K also means that employers must update their
employee handbooks and employee notices to reflect changes in state
disability insurance, COBRA, Cal/ OSHA information and
discrimination. The California Chamber, (800) 331-8877, sells
updated employment law kits for $189. You can also get information
at its Web site (www.calchamber.com). &LR; cq
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Turning to what happens beginning January 3, the second year
of the 1999-2000 legislative session, debate is expected on a
number of issues affecting employers. Here are three of the top
ones, according to the California Chamber:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Workers' Compensation _ &LR;  A bill that would have increased workers'
compensation premiums for employers by $2.1 billion was rejected by
Gov. Gray Davis earlier this year because he felt that the added
costs would seriously hurt the state's economy. It is expected that
labor unions and others will be back in 2000 with another bill to
substantially increase workers' compensation benefits. The chamber
and other employer groups want any benefit increases to be offset
by cost-saving reforms to help streamline the workers' comp system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Unemployment Insurance &LR;  _ A labor union-sponsored bill to increase
unemployment insurance was put on hold earlier this year. Senate
Bill 546 is expected to be taken up again when the Legislature
reconvenes. According to a Senate Appropriations Committee
analysis, the bill would increase employer unemployment insurance
taxes by more than $700 million a year. Employer groups oppose the
increase unless there are major reforms to the nation's largest
unemployment system, which is entirely financed by employers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Minimum Wage _ &LR;  Historically, California's minimum wage has been
set by the California Industrial Welfare Commission, which reviews
wage policy every two years. The commission met on December 15 in
Los Angeles to take public comment. Labor unions have made raising
the minimum wage, which is $5.75 in California, as compared with
$5.15 nationwide, a top priority. San Francisco and some other
cities are also looking at requiring a higher minimum wage for
businesses with whom they have contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing only on increasing the minimum wage as a way
to offset the increased costs of living in California, the
California Chamber would support programs to make child care,
housing and health care more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Home Office Tips &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a homeowner and use one room exclusively to do all the
administration work for my small business. However, I sell computer
components and do not meet clients at my home, so can I still
deduct the costs to maintain my office?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: You're in luck. For taxable years beginning after 1998, the
term principal place of business was amended and expanded to
include where the taxpayer does administrative or management tasks.
So long as you don't have another location where you do substantial
administration or management work, you can deduct the portion of
your costs associated with your home office. However, CPA Mary Jo
Murphy of M.J. Murphy &AMP; Associates in San Mateo notes some
limitations: Your deduction for the current year basically cannot
exceed the net income derived from the business conducted from your
home office. Any disallowed portion, though, can be carried forward
to subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy adds that an important consideration in deciding to take
the home office deduction is what happens when you sell your
principal residence. If you have claimed and depreciated your home
office, you will have to recognize a gain on any depreciation
adjustments in connection with business use of the residence after
May 6, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This can get complicated and you might want to consult a
professional. Suffice it to say that if you expect your income to
go up to a higher tax bracket and you think you may sell your home
at that time, you may want to reconsider taking the home office
deduction now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CREDIT CARD NOTE: In last week's column, I mentioned some business
credit card recommendations but gave a wrong name/Web address.
Check out www.cardweb.com. &LR; cq &LR;  Also, reader Larry Templeton
recommends the Quicken credit card for business, not because it's
the cheapest but because it allows him to download the details of
all credit card transactions directly into his Quicken accounting
program, thus easing the burden of bookkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
