<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5835 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PAWN-PAWN_SFCHRON &LR;      12-21 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAWN-PAWN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 An Unconventional Place for Holiday Shopping  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
As the Christmas clock ticks down, last-minute shoppers can go to a
mall or department store and battle their way to the cash register.
Or they can go online and take their chances.
<P>
   But for an alternative shopping experience, how about a festive
holiday lap dance? Or a tattoo? Or a visit to a pawnshop?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people come to pawnshops at this time of year,'' said
Paula Newhouse, manager of the Best Collateral pawnshop on San
Francisco's Mission Street. ``They know they'll get good value.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, visits to a number of downtown pawnshops revealed that
monthly sales rise by about 30 percent every December as customers
seek out bargain-priced jewelry, electronic goods, musical
instruments and other stuff to give as holiday presents.
</P>
<P>
   And, surprisingly, an increasing number of those sales are
taking place online.
</P>
<P>
   At Best Collateral, large red letters spelling out ``Merry
Christmas'' hang on the wall beneath a big red bow. Above the bow
is a neon sign promising ``Money Loaned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is always a good month,'' Newhouse said as customers
browsed among items such as an Aiwa stereo selling for $199.95, a
gold pocket watch costing $399.95 and a five-piece drum set priced
at $599.95.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though just about everything in the place goes for
something-ninety-nine-ninety-five. This isn't a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All prices are negotiable,'' Newhouse revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Pawnshops, in other words, are the Turkish bazaars of the U.S.
retail world. Haggling is customary, and only the most naive
shopper makes a purchase without first driving the price down as
much as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For those unfamiliar with the pawning process, it works like
this: A person brings in an item as collateral and receives a cash
loan. By law, the item must be held for four months and 10 days
before being put up for sale by the pawnshop.
</P>
<P>
   Interest is steep, starting at about 14 percent for the first
three months of a $100 loan, then tapering off. After four months,
a customer can either redeem or renew his or her loan, or can opt
to walk away and let the pawnshop take possession of the item.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small percentage of pawned items end up for sale.
Newhouse said most are eventually redeemed, and some remain in
storage for years, their owners using the pawnshop as a high-price
safe-deposit box by continually renewing the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner at Pacific Loan Co. on Sixth Street, owner
Michael Krasow said jewelry, DVD players and TVs are the hot
holiday gifts among his customers this year.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the shop are decorated with tinsel and Christmas
lights, and ``Happy Hannukah'' has been painted on the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``This month has been pretty good,'' Krasow said. ``But
generally, we don't see a big increase in sales until the last week
before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pawnshop patrons, he speculated, are among the worst offenders
when it comes to last-minute shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy is good, the pawnshop business is good
because people know they'll have money to get their stuff back,''
Krasow observed. ``And when the economy is bad, the pawnshop
business is still good because people need money.''
</P>
<P>
   One might think that the biggest threat to the pawnshop business
is the Internet. Customers who might have previously prowled
pawnshops in search of one-of-a-kind items and collectibles can now
turn instead to eBay and a host of other online flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   Krasow offered a sly grin. Rather than being a threat, he
explained, the Net actually has expanded his customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put all my best stuff on eBay,'' Krasow said. ``I average
five or six pieces a month, and I almost always get a better
price.''
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down at Midtown Loan Office, owner Ralph Kazanjian
agreed that eBay is one of the biggest advances to hit the pawnshop
trade in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some Disney animation cels recently,'' he recalled.
``Who's going to come down here for Disney cels? The Internet
allowed us to take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Midtown is celebrating the season with gold tinsel on the walls
and ``Happy Holidays'' painted on the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the sidewalk, the atmosphere is a bit less jolly. Things
may have been different decades ago, when about a half-dozen
pawnshops took root in the neighborhood. These days, Sixth Street
isn't the most welcoming part of the city for holiday shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, the Internet plays a role. ``If we can't get people
down here, the Net is a way for us to get to them,'' Kazanjian
said. ``It exposes us to a whole new market.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of exposure, over at the Crazy Horse Gentleman's Club
on Market Street, an employee who gave his name only as ``John''
said it's not uncommon for patrons to buy friends a complimentary
lap dance as a way of commemorating the season.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted that business falls off a bit at this time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to spend time with your family,'' John noted. ``You
don't want to be a horn-dog.''
</P>
<P>
   For truly alternative shopping, head down Market a few doors to
the Underground Smoke Shop, where Manager Al Salem will insist with
a straight face that sales of his products soar as Christmas
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a lot of T-shirts at this season,'' he said.
``Especially Grateful Dead shirts. And we sell a lot of Jerry
Garcia statues.''
</P>
<P>
   Other popular items include studs as stocking stuffers for
people with a pierced this or that, and big, fat skull rings for
those of a more heavy-metal bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And lava lamps, of course,'' Salem pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Across town on Haight Street, Muneer Hyat(cq) &LR; , a salesman at
Ashbury Tobacco Center, said sales of his wares are up as well. He
said this while standing in front of shelves stacked high with all
manner of ``water pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   Back when some of us were in high school, these things were
known as ``bongs,'' and they weren't used for tobacco. Times, and
laws, have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Hyat pointed to a big sign insisting that ``these are water
pipes and are intended to be used for tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   He cast his eyes over display cases full of other brightly
colored pipes, the kind that don't require water, as well as other
paraphernalia once more commonly associated with marijuana than
Marlboros.
</P>
<P>
   ``For tobacco,'' Hyat said with a slight smile.
</P>
<P>
   The big sellers this month are handblown glass bongs _ er, water
pipes _ ranging in price from $60 to $300. Hyat also pointed out
that smaller, handheld pipes make fabulous stocking stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone spends more than $500,'' he said, ``we give them a
discount card.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street at Mom's Body Shop, owner Barnaby Williams said
he issues quite a few gift certificates during the holidays. A
piercing, for example, will run about $25, while tattoos run $120
an hour, with more elaborate productions requiring as many as 30
hours of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, a gift certificate will be for a minor,'' Williams
said. ``A lot of parents will ask if their grades have been good
and will then get a gift certificate as a reward.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no Christmas decorations up in the small shop. But
Williams himself is rather jovially decorated on his arms and neck,
and undoubtedly elsewhere as well.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that business slows somewhat in the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the awareness of body,'' he explained. ``In the winter,
you're not looking so much at your arms and legs. You aren't
thinking about skin.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who are, though, small Japanese characters are popular
these days, as are retro renderings of pinup girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tattoo makes a good gift,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   And considering how hard it is to get the suckers off, they're
perhaps the one gift you know won't be immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
