<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-READING-THE-BIBLE-1ST     12-21 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READING-THE-BIBLE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE BEGINNING, A MAN IS READING THE BIBLE ALOUD WITHOUT STOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs to delete reference to winter solstice in 2nd graf.)
(ART ADV: A photo, NYT22, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 &HT;    (DW) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marshall Weber started reading the Bible Tuesday and
he just kept going.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn, Weber stood at the front of the city's oldest active
synagogue, took a sip of ginseng-gingko-ginger tea, adjusted his
flowing garments, opened a weathered, leather-covered volume to
Genesis and began the reading.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a nap upon completion of the Old Testament sometime
Wednesday night, Weber, a full-bearded, 39-year-old performance
artist and publisher of art books, does not intend to stop until
Friday at dawn. By then, he reckons, he will have read the entire
work _ all 66 books, 31,000 verses, 800,000-odd words. Plus the
Apocrypha.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Partly because it is there, and because Christmas and
Revelations' day of reckoning are just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I always wanted to do,'' said Weber, who has
read aloud Nietzsche's ``Thus Spoke Zarathustra'' (24 hours) and
Joyce's ``Ulysses'' (33 hours) and once read William T. Vollmann's
``The Rifles'' in 22 hours inside a 15-degree refrigerated truck at
a Canadian arts festival.
</P>
<P>
   But Weber, who considers himself a nontraditional Jew, said the
reading _ at the Orensanz Center for the Arts, housed inside the
150-year-old temple of the Shul of New York on the Lower East Side
of Manhattan _ was also a way to explore the place where the
secular and the religious intersect.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the act of devotion is really on a cultural and
literary level,'' he said in his apartment in Greenwich Village on
Monday night. ``But given the amount of mental and physical and
psychical energy this is going to take, I'm prepared for any kind
of spiritual experience in any form.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1:12 p.m. Tuesday, Weber had progressed to Exodus 21 _ the
often overlooked part just after the Ten Commandments that deals
with what to do if someone else's ox falls into your uncovered pit.
He had been temporarily banished to the building's drafty basement
because Modern Bride magazine had rented the ornate German-Romantic
sanctuary upstairs for a photography session. He read in a quiet,
almost boyish tenor, pausing occasionally to cough and blow his
nose.
</P>
<P>
   Other than two friends and a couple of reporters, there was no
one in attendance, perhaps because Weber was unable to raise money
to promote the reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religious people were scared that there might be some kind
of offensive component, and the art world was scared that there
would be some kind of offensive component that would backlash to
them,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   He does not consider his performance particularly radical. The
reading aloud of scripture is, after all, the basis of most
religious services. But the president of the National Bible
Association, Thomas May, said he had never heard of one person
reading the entire Bible more or less in one sitting. The
association, a nondenominational group based in New York, has
sponsored Bible-reading marathons for years, but those affairs are
relays involving hundreds of people reading a few pages each.
</P>
<P>
   While he expressed puzzlement with Weber's purpose and doubt
that he would be able to finish in the allotted time, May wished
him Godspeed. ``I don't think it's ever a bad thing to read the
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   As straightforward as Weber's project may seem, he has been
preparing for it for a year. He spent months searching for the
perfect Bible, settling on a folio-sized King James version printed
in 1873, illustrated by Gustave Dore. To cultivate the proper Old
Testament look, he said, he has not taken a blade to a hair on his
body since last December. For the last few days, he has tried to
sleep as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never lose my voice, because I modulate it very well,'' he
said, ``but after 30 hours, fatigue sets in, in terms of visual
hallucinations. When I was reading `Ulysses,' I had a hallucination
that I was at a copying machine, copying the pages as I read them,
and I asked myself, `Why am I copying them?' and it turned out I
wasn't. But it didn't interrupt the reading.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2:42 p.m., Weber read the last verse of Exodus and stood up
abruptly, knocking over a heater and his tea kettle. He had been
reading for seven and a half hours and was less than one-tenth of
the way through the Bible. His legs wobbled like a weary boxer's.
</P>
<P>
   But as he slurped down a container of chicken soup from Katz's
Delicatessen, he seemed to revive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more law coming in Leviticus,'' he said, ``but at
least we're done with the ark. It kind of gets more lyrical from
here on.''
</P>
<P>
   He blew his nose and sat down to Leviticus. A landscape of
blood, burnt offerings and lepers lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rocks,'' he said as he began to read. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
