<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     12-21 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THEIR FEATS ARE SIMILAR, NOT THE TIMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carl Lewis and I spoke recently about the passage of
time and the transformation of images. Specifically, we spoke about
Muhammad Ali and his canonization in the mainstream media over the
last decade. Ali was like a neighborhood once avoided, generally
disparaged, now home to trendy coffee shops and well-to-do
residents who boast of living in the ``inner city.''
</P>
<P>
   This was at the Chelsea Piers sports center in Manhattan, where
Lewis was taking part in a program with General Motors and the
United Auto Workers to give cars to 100 U.S. Olympic hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' name had come up earlier that morning at the New York
Athletic Club as an older generation of track stars gathered to
watch footage of Jesse Owens in conjunction with ESPN's announcing
Owens as its sixth-ranked athlete of the century.
</P>
<P>
   John Woodruff, Owens' teammate on the 1936 Olympic team and a
gold medal winner in the 800 meters, rated Paul Robeson, Jackie
Robinson, Owens and Joe Louis as his top four black athletes of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-year-old Woodruff said that Lewis, in many ways, was
better than Owens. ``When you compare what Jesse did back in his
time and what Carl Lewis has done, Carl is the better athlete,''
Woodruff said. Owens endures ``because of the times that he did
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling among some Owens supporters that Lewis does
not properly respect Owens. In 1985, Lewis won the Jesse Owens
International Amateur Athlete Award. In 1996, he skipped the Owens
dinner at which all living 100-meter gold medalists were honored.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how Lewis truly felt about Owens, an athlete with
whom he is inexorably linked. Each won four Olympic gold medals at
age 23 _ Owens in Berlin in 1936, Lewis in Los Angeles in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with all of his politics,'' Lewis said of Owens,
an evident reference to Owens' conservative stands on a wide range
of issues from student protests of the 1960s to activism among
athletes. ``It would have been interesting for me If I'd been
around Avery Brundage. You couldn't change things, but sometime I
wish that I could have been brought around earlier. After what I
had to go through on a different level with the media, it would
have been interesting to give me that forum to go against those
kind of situations. I do believe that no matter what, I would have
had a solid agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis earned millions after his Olympic performance. After the
1936 Games, while the rest of the U.S. team barnstormed through
Europe, Owens elected to go home to his family. The Amateur
Athletic Union suspended him from all further amateur competition.
The lucrative offers made in the heat of Owens' Olympic feats
disappeared. Owens, financially strapped, spent the next five years
racing for money against horses, dogs and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Owens did not rock the boat. He smiled, bore the burden and
burned inside. ``He didn't fight the system,'' Woodruff said. ``We
accepted it at the time. We went on and made the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt that Jesse was a little lost,'' Lewis said. ``I
never felt that he had that base that he could always fall back on.
My base is my parents, my coaches, my family; they have always been
a strong backbone for me. I didn't see that with Jesse, in Jesse.
So therefore when it came time to really be strong, I didn't see
him have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff said that competitive running was the base to which
Lewis referred. When the track establishment took that away, Owens
lost some of his resolve. ``I don't know what happened to Jesse,''
Woodruff said. ``Jesse was a highly conscientious athlete. It seems
as though when he got out of it, he was missing something, so he
started smoking and imbibing alcohol. That's what killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis fought for better drug testing and more money for
athletes. He promoted the sport with a bravado completely lacking
in the self-effacing Owens, an attitude not expected-or tolerated
from African Americans _ athletes or otherwise _ in previous
generations.
</P>
<P>
   At Chelsea Piers, Carl Lewis said that he would not remain close
to the sport, would not become a spokesman for the U.S. track
federation.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, he said, has left an indelible impression. ``Here's a guy
who was chastised by his sport,'' Lewis said. ``Everything was
taken from him, and now, the minute he drops, that very sport has
used his name left, right, up, down. in, out. And they're going to
tell me: ``We'll, you're like him, so you come too _ we're going to
do the same thing to you.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily,'' Lewis said, ``I had a vision, I know what's going
on and it's not going to happen twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
