u f BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      12-21 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS AT GOLDMAN SACHS WIDELY EXCEED FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Demonstrating how powerfully financial markets have
rebounded in a year, the Goldman Sachs Group said Tuesday that it
posted a record profit last quarter after suffering a slight loss a
year earlier, when much of the world was still feeling the effects
of financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, which went public in May, said it earned $723 million,
or $1.48 a diluted share, in its fiscal fourth quarter, which ended
Nov. 26. Its performance well exceeded the $1.25 a share expected
by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings of Goldman, one of Wall Street's foremost
investment banks, have been skewed in the last year by its
conversion from a private partnership to a public company. Adjusted
for that change, Goldman said, its earnings last quarter were $756
million, or $1.54 a diluted share, up from $8 million, or 2 cents a
share, in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's net revenue _ its total revenue minus interest
expenses _ came to $3.47 billion, up 280 percent from $915 million
a year earlier and 13 percent from the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Goldman sustained some big losses trading bonds and
commodities as the financial turmoil caused by Russia's summer
default on some of its debt rippled into Latin America and hurt
East Asian countries already in crisis. The value of all but the
safest of bonds sank fast, wiping out Goldman's profit from its
other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Like Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which reported surprisingly
strong earnings on Monday, Goldman has benefited this year from a
global boom in mergers and acquisitions and investors'
extraordinary appetite for new stock offerings. Goldman ranks first
in the value of mergers and acquisitions announced worldwide this
year and first in the amount of money raised through stock
offerings in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be the leader in the highest-margin
businesses,'' said David Viniar, the bank's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The profitability of Goldman's franchises in stock underwriting
and advising on mergers was evident in its 31 percent return on
equity, which is a key measure of profitability on Wall Street.
Goldman promises investors that it will earn at least 20 percent on
their equity almost every quarter; in the last three quarters, it
has outdone that by half, earning returns of at least 30 percent on
equity.
</P>
<P>
   Fees from advising on mergers rose 50 percent, to a record $622
million from a year earlier, though up just 1 percent from the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also showed big gains from its asset management
business, especially from deposits into its investment funds from
wealthy individuals. The firm's trading businesses recorded big
profits, though declines from the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good quarter for Goldman relative to
expectations,'' said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst with Merrill
Lynch. But Kraushaar added that the investment bank's profit had
been exaggerated last quarter by two unusual factors: a
lower-than-normal tax rate and lower-than-normal expenses for
paying its well-heeled employees. Goldman sets aside money every
quarter to pay year-end bonuses to investment bankers and traders,
who receive the bulk of their annual pay in a lump sum after the
end of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   It expects to pay out about half its net revenue to its
employees as compensation and benefits. This year, though, after
deciding how much to pay each employee, the firm had spent just
48.4 percent of its revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
