A5867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-DODGERS-BELTRE-NY     12-21 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BELTRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' DOMINICAN BASE CLOSED; BELTRE IS REFUSED FREE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding the Los Angeles Dodgers guilty of a foreign
transgression for the second time in six months, Commissioner Bud
Selig shut down their base of operations in the Dominican Republic
for a year on Tuesday, but allowed them to retain the good young
third baseman they had signed a year early.
</P>
<P>
   Selig did not declare the third baseman, Adrian Beltre, a free
agent because, he said, the investigation of the underage signing
turned up evidence that Beltre knew well before this year that the
Dodgers had falsified his birth date and that he himself had used
the falsified date on a variety of documents.
</P>
<P>
   A players association lawyer said the association would study
the ruling before deciding if it would challenge that part of the
commissioner's decision through a grievance. Besides closing the
Dodgers' highly rated baseball academy at Campo Las Palmas, a blow
to the organization's player development program, Selig prohibited
the Dodgers from scouting or signing first-year players who live in
the Dominican Republic. He also fined the club $50,000 and
suspended a current employee and a former one, both of whom have
been integral to the Dominican operation, for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's actions was yet another black eye for an organization
that under previous ownership portrayed itself as the epitome of
purity. Yet it was under that ownership that the transgressions
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Last June an investigation found that the Dodgers had illegally
scouted two players in Cuba, which is off limits to baseball
organizations, and spirited them from Cuba to the Dominican
Republic, where they said they had found and signed them. The
players were declared free agents and the Dodgers were fined
$200,000 and banned from signing foreign players for six months.
That period ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers signed Beltre on July 7, 1994. They listed his birth
date as April 7, 1978, which would have made him the requisite 16
years old when he signed. But Beltre was actually born a year
later, meaning he was 15 when he signed. Altered documents were
found in the Dodgers' files.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, Beltre's agent, contended that the player should be
declared a free agent, like other Latin players before him who were
found to have been signed prematurely. But Selig awarded Beltre
$48,500 ($33,000 plus interest) as the difference between the
$17,000 signing bonus he had received and the $50,000 he might have
received a year later. Boras has said that Beltre learned only last
March that he had been too young to sign with the Dodgers. But
Selig said documents uncovered in the investigation established
earlier knowledge and put Beltre well beyond the one-year statute
of limitations established in baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-page letter to Beltre, a copy of which was obtained by
The New York Times, Selig cited five specific documents that the
player filled out and signed on which he listed the falsified birth
date. They included a sports service questionnaire in 1996, two
club physical examination questionnaires in 1997 and 1998, and U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization forms in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``These documents,'' Selig wrote, ``demonstrate your awareness
that the Dodgers had falsified your birth date and that you, at
least at times, were cooperating in that deception.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Selig reminded Beltre of the representation he had
from his father and an amateur coach in negotiations or talks with
the Dodgers and other organizations, including the Yankees, in
1994. Those talks, the commissioner said, ``belie any naivete you
may claim toward the signing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras declined to comment on the ruling or the ``allegations''
of prior knowledge ``because this is going to grievance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gene Orza, the union's associate general counsel, was not
prepared Tuesday to say the union would file a grievance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read the opinion and I think it raises some questions
that require some analysis on our part,'' Orza said. ``We'll make
up our mind in the next 48 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers weren't challenging anything. They are ecstatic just
to be able to keep Beltre, who in his first full season in the
major leagues hit .275 and drove in 67 runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
