<SLUG> BC-NY-SEX-SHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY SEEKS WAYS AROUND RULING ON X-RATED SHOPS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a tree-lined residential street on Manhattan's
Upper West Side, just half a block from a Starbucks and Zabar's, is
a neighborhood video store decorated with Christmas wreaths and
lights, piped-in holiday jingles and shelves filled with features
like ``The Kermit and Piggy Story,'' ``Barney in Concert'' and
``Suzanne Somers' Thighmaster Exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   But customers at Les Hommes video store Tuesday afternoon were
not there for the family entertainment or even for the sprinkling
of Hollywood classics. Videos like ``Summer Sex Splash,'' ``The
Orgy in Budapest'' and ``In the Name of Leather'' are instead the
big sellers, a fact that infuriates Mayor Rudolph Giuliani but
which the state's highest court ruled unanimously on Monday was
perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling undermines a 1995 law that was supposed to
shut down most of the city's pornography-dominated stores,
particularly in residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the Court of Appeals ruled that the city was
being too broad in its enforcement of a guideline derived from the
law, which requires that stores in most of the city devote no more
than 40 percent of their business to pornographic materials. The
city has maintained that many stores have circumvented the law by
filling shelves with inoffensive and inexpensive videos they know
will not sell, in order to remain in business.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said Tuesday that they were looking for ways to
overcome the setback. One possibility, they said, was for store
sales and not just inventory to account for the 60 percent of
porn-free material.
</P>
<P>
   But civil libertarians and backers of the porn industry called
the decision a major victory in a battle that until now Giuliani
had been consistently winning. Since July 1998, when the U.S.
Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal of the zoning law,
allowing it to go into effect, 62 of the city's 144 sex-related
businesses have either been forcibly closed or gone out of
business, according to city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision should send Giuliani a message that the courts
are not going to stand for his intolerance and tyranny,'' said
Martin Hodas, the man who popularized peep shows in Times Square in
the 1960s and '70s and who is still an investor in sex-related
businesses in New York. ``Sex is not evil. It was given to us by
God to enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals decision came after the city tried to shut
down Les Hommes, one of dozens of outlets in the city that added
stocks of mainstream films and other nonsexually oriented
merchandise after the new zoning law went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The second-story shop at 217 West 80th Street has no obvious
street-level signs or other markings to indicate what is upstairs.
Sex toys are displayed in a glass case at the entrance, but most of
the store's compact sales floor is taken up by shelves filled with
dated Hollywood titles, karate films, sports videos and a large
collection of children's videos.
</P>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, a lawyer who represented the owner of
Les Hommes, said that the store did not have many of the latest
Hollywood films because it did not have the buying power of the big
video chains and could not afford to buy too many videos that did
not sell.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Xtremes video store, at 763 Eighth Avenue, near 46th
Street, an entire basement floor is dedicated to action, horror,
comedy, romance and children's films, with a sign on the main floor
vaunting the array of ``Kid Cartoons!!'' for $5.99. But the shelf
marked ``new releases'' carries such titles as ``Great Moments in
Basketball'' from 1988 and ``Romantic Comedy'' (1983) starring
Dudley Moore and Mary Steenburgen.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, all 17 customers pursuing the shelves at
Xtremes were upstairs in the adult sections, where movies with
titles like ``Candy's Girls'' and ``Samurai Fantasy Voyeur'' were
being rented or sold. A man who identified himself as the store
supervisor, but who declined to give his name, said the store was
scrupulously adhering to the 60 percent nonadult requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We comply with the law,'' he said. ``Giuliani asked for it. He
got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Haroules, a lawyer at the American Civil Liberties Union in
New York, said that any move by the city to expand the 60-to-40
rule by regulating the actual material the stores sell would not
stand up to a court challenge, since it would violate the
constitutional rights of owners and clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in and try to rewrite the guidelines or zoning
regulation, you open the door to a new round of constitutional
challenges,'' she said. ``You may have `101 Dalmatians' and it is
full of dust and over there you have `Debbie Does Dallas' and you
can't keep it in stock. But that is not at all relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Saffran, executive director of the Center for the
Community Interest, and city Councilman Walter L. McCaffrey, a
Queens Democrat who serves as chairman of the council's zoning
subcommittee, rejected Ms. Haroules' argument, noting that the
Court of Appeals judges had all but invited the city to revise its
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling notes that ``in the end, we must enforce the city's
administrative guidelines as written.'' But ``there may indeed be
situations where what a store is selling or renting cannot be
considered stock under the city's guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, in remarks to reporters Tuesday, said that the city
would make such changes.
</P>
<P>
   The court ``did not strike down the zoning change, thank
goodness,'' Giuliani said. ``The bad news is that we have to go
back and rewrite the regulation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
