<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KOZENY-INVEST-SUIT-NY     12-21 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOZENY-INVEST-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR ACCUSED OF FRAUD IN AZERBAIJAN VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ An investment promoter who made a fortune
from questionable stock dealings in his native Czech Republic years
ago has now been accused of fraud in an Azerbaijan venture that has
attracted $450 million from foreign investors. Some investors are
prominent Americans, including former Sen. George Mitchell and Leon
Cooperman, a Wall Street fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud accusation against Viktor Kozeny was contained in a
civil lawsuit filed Friday in London by one of the investors,
Marlwood Commercial Inc., a subsidiary of American International
Group, a diversified insurance company. The suit seeks $15 million,
the amount of Marlwood's investment.
</P>
<P>
   London's High Court sealed the suit, but some details were
disclosed Monday in a routine notification filed with the High
Court clerk's office. The filing alleged fraud and breach of duty
involving the long-stalled privatization program of Azerbaijan, an
oil-rich Caspian Sea nation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asserted that Kozeny fraudulently persuaded
investors that they could buy, among other properties, part of the
extremely valuable Azerbaijan state oil company, a concern that
Azeri officials say they never promised to sell. In addition, the
lawsuit asserted, Kozeny grossly inflated the price of
privatization ``options'' necessary for bidding on the properties,
charging investors $25 apiece when he paid as little as 25 cents
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the lawsuit said, some of Kozeny's clients believe their
investment has plummeted to less than 10 percent of its original
value, or a loss exceeding $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Richard D'Alessandri, a lawyer for American International Group,
said the company would not comment on its lawsuit, which has also
been filed in the Bahamas. Legal action was taken in London and the
Bahamas because Kozeny owns property in those places that
plaintiffs could move to seize.
</P>
<P>
   The group of about 30 American investors also included the real
estate billionaire Richard Friedman, who owns a Martha's Vineyard
estate where President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton have
vacationed, and Frederick Bourke, chairman of Dooney &AMP; Bourke, the
handbag company.
</P>
<P>
   With $180 million in investments from institutional and other
clients, Cooperman, chairman of New York-based Omega Advisors, is
thought to have the greatest exposure to the Azerbaijan venture.
Cooperman is not a party to the suit, though he said in a telephone
interview that ``it doesn't mean we can't be down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman said that he and Kozeny were no longer working
together. Cooperman also said that he was still trying to persuade
the Azerbaijan government to proceed with a significant
privatization. The Azerbaijan government recently said it would do
so, but would not yet include any part of the state oil company.
Diplomats have described the company as a lucrative source of cash
in a corrupt government that is unlikely to be sold anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viktor brought us the investment through a friend,'' Cooperman
said. ``We were not happy with his deportment. He became a
lightning rod of resentment in the country. So we went our separate
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Americans have described the Harvard-educated
Kozeny, 36, as a gifted, charismatic salesman. He has attracted as
much publicity for his spending binges as his investment
promotions, including a 1997 London meal on which he spent $20,000,
including $8,000 for a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny owns a mansion in London and a ski chalet in Aspen,
Colo., though he usually lives on the Bahamas island of Lyford Cay.
Several attempts to call Kozeny on Lyford Cay were unsuccessful.
His lawyer, Jacqueline Miller, did not return three phone calls to
her office in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Azerbaijan affair bears a resemblance to one earlier this
decade involving Kozeny in the Czech Republic, from which he
emigrated to the United States as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1991, Kozeny went on television and promised
enormous returns for Czech citizens who turned over their
privatization coupons _ every adult was entitled to them _ to the
company he then ran, Harvard Capital and Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 Czechs eventually did so. By 1996, Kozeny had
earned a fortune estimated to exceed $200 million, while his
clients' investment had plummeted. Some press articles called
Kozeny ``The Pirate of Prague,'' a moniker that endures there.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech government investigation resulted in a finding of
wrongdoing by his company, which was fined and ordered to reimburse
$6.8 million of investors' money improperly spent on advertising
and consulting fees. Kozeny was never criminally charged with
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Kozeny shifted his attention to Azerbaijan. That year
in Aspen, Kozeny threw a lavish party where, according to several
accounts, he delivered an extremely vivid account of a coming
windfall in Azerbaijan privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny said he intended to buy the gems of the Azerbaijan
economy _ the telecommunications company, the natural-gas
distribution company and, especially, the state oil company, known
by its acronym, SOCAR. With its refineries, pipelines and oil
fields, SOCAR is said to be worth well into the billions of
dollars. Those who heard the pitch told friends, and Kozeny
suddenly had much American investment.
</P>
<P>
   In Baku, Kozeny's company, Minaret Group, rented two floors in
the Landmark, one of the most expensive office buildings in the
then-booming Azerbaijan capital. Although Baku as yet had no stock
market, he built a computerized ``trading floor'' of computer
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who invested an undisclosed sum, appeared in April
1998 as Kozeny's marquee guest at Minaret's catered grand opening
at Baku's premier hotel. Mitchell's Washington law office said the
former senator was traveling Tuesday and was unavailable for
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Minaret Group established itself, Azeri
officials began delaying the privatization. Earlier this year,
Minaret abandoned much of its office space, and condensed its
operations into three rooms in the Landmark.
</P>
</TEXT>
