<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-RUBENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLEN IN '92, RUBENS PORTRAIT WORTH $3.1 MILLION IS FOUND IN NEW
JERSEY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A portrait painted four centuries ago by the
Flemish master Peter Paul Rubens and stolen seven years ago from
its owner in Belgium has been recovered from a New Jersey collector
who did not know it had been stolen, the authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The oil portrait, ``Unidentified Man Wearing a Ruff,'' was
painted by Rubens between 1600 and 1609, said Carey S. Chin,
special agent in charge of the FBI's Newark office. He said the
Belgian authorities valued the painting at $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The agency displayed the 20-inch-by-30-inch painting Tuesday in
the incongruous surroundings of a 15th-floor conference room, where
it was encased in a foam-padded wooden box standing on a metal
easel. The subject, a middle-aged man with a goatee, wears a dark
coat with a delicate white ruff, and a wide-eyed, slightly amused
expression. Agent Stephen Siegel of the FBI Newark Interstate Theft
Task Force, who retrieved the painting on Friday from the
unidentified collector, wore latex gloves to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Chin said the painting had not been authenticated by art
authorities since it was retrieved by the FBI. He said it was
stolen in Belgium in 1992 from a Brussels man, Dirck van Wylinck,
whose family had owned it since 1927. van Wylinck sought to start a
publishing house in Prague, and turned over the painting to two
people as collateral for a business loan, Chin said. But, he added,
they soon disappeared with it.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by Belgian law enforcement officials eventually
led them to a collector in New Jersey, who had bought the painting
in Belgium in late 1992 along with a group of drawings by other
well-known artists, Siegel said. He said the Belgian authorities
contacted the FBI's legal attache in Brussels, asking that agents
in New Jersey recover the painting. Chin said that agents in New
Jersey had no direct contact with the Belgian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Chin said the Belgian authorities are investigating the two
people who took the painting as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Chin refused to identify the collector or say whether he had
kept the painting in a home or gallery. The collector bought the
painting in good faith, apparently unaware of its value until he
had it appraised after he bought it, Chin said. He said the
collector had cooperated in the investigation and was not likely to
be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that Belgian authorities would come to Newark next
month to claim the painting and return it to van Wylinck.
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Maurice, deputy consul general at the Belgian
consulate, said he was told Tuesday afternoon of the painting's
recovery by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, of course, are happy that the American authorities were
able to find a valuable Belgian work of art,'' Maurice said.
``Especially because Rubens was one of Belgium's finest masters of
all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubens (1577-1640) was among the most prominent of the Flemish
and Dutch masters of the 17th century. His contemporaries included
van Dyke, a student of Rubens, and Rembrandt. Rubens' ``Head of
John the Baptist Presented to Salome'' sold last year for $5.2
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
