<HEADLINE>
KINGS WORK ON ROLE PLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three brutal losses followed by three days off
leaves the coaching staff with time to find a remedy, and Los
Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray attempted it do so with intense
practices and team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in less than 60 hours and the fourth time in
five days the Kings held a team meeting. This time it was to
discuss roles and to make sure everyone understood theirs heading
into tonight's game at San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went around the room and told every single player what we
expected of them,'' Murray said. ``So they know what a Glenn Murray
should being doing, what they can count on a Donald Audette for,
Rob Blake knows what he can count on Mattias Norstrom for. It's not
only a matter of that individual player knowing his role now. It's
a continuing of redefining and reinforcing roles.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems odd that 30 games into a season players can suddenly
forget their roles. But several players said injuries to marquee
players, and their subsequent return, caused players to drift from
the system that made the Kings the top team in the Western
Conference a few weeks ago. Instead, players were caught out of
position, particularly in the defensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people forgot their roles,'' Kings center Ian
Laperriere said. ``We're the same players, the same group of guys,
so what's wrong? Sometimes you try to do too much. Sometimes I
tired to do my winger's job. Sometimes the winger tried to do my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting strong: During the three-game losing streak the Kings
were outscored 13-1 in the first period, which contrasts to how
they played most of the season. The Kings outscored their opponents
28-17 during their 16-8-6 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware that we have to come out and play hard, but this
is also the time to show some mental toughness, that if we do get
down a goal we're not going to let it turn into something ugly
again,'' defenseman Mattias Norstrom said. ``I think to get out of
a slump like this, hard work is the way to do it. You change
systems, you can change this and that, but if you want to win bad
enough, you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Line tinkering: Murray said he wasn't planning any major changes
against San Jose, but added the coaching staff is taking a hard
look at it's ``energy line.'' Two-thirds of the Kings' fourth line
Jason Blake (post-concussion syndrome), Brad Chartrand (groin) and
Steve McKenna won't be available because of injuries. Murray was
unhappy with the Kings' lack of toughness Saturday against Chicago,
and he may opt to go with a burly line of McKenna, Dan Bylsma and
recently recalled Bill Huard, a physical presence from Lowell
(Mass.) of the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   Faceoffs: Murray said Jaroslav Modry would be the sixth
defenseman against San Jose. ...Jozef Stumpel was pain free after
practice and is expected to play for the first time in seven weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
