<SLUG> BC-EAGLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLE RESCUED BY HUNTER SOARS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bald eagle's heartbeat was strong; the doctor could feel it.
</P>
<P>
   A raptor once near death now perched on the arm of veterinarian
Tom Del Pico. But the eagle was stressed Tuesday on the drive to a
release point at Smithville Lake, making its heart pound and its
tongue wag.
</P>
<P>
   That the eagle was alive was a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Its life hinged on a deer hunter's keen eye and sure shot, a
wise conservation agent and a veterinarian who admires and treats
birds of prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope she flies,'' Del Pico said. ``I hope she doesn't crash
to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happened, the eagle would have to enter a rehabilitation
program, and the stress of travel and strange surroundings could
make its fate uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive to the lake, Del Pico momentarily lifted a towel
covering the bird. Eyes flashed fiercely. But wing strength was the
doctor's concern.
</P>
<P>
   The bird was rescued Dec. 12, when Bill Tott of Waldron was
hunting deer with a black powder rifle in the Missouri River
bottoms northwest of Parkville. From a distance, he spotted the
eagle dangling upside down in a cottonwood tree near the river.
</P>
<P>
   When Tott reached the cottonwood, the eagle was motionless, with
a wing snarled in limbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was dead,'' Tott said. ``Then I noticed its eyes
were green.''
</P>
<P>
   An eye blinked, and he knew the bird was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Tott hiked out of the bottoms, called authorities and returned
to the cottonwood with a more powerful rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Lying on his back, he fired at the tree limb and missed. He
switched aim to a bigger limb and fired again. The limb began
falling.
</P>
<P>
   As it did, the eagle slipped free and glided to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too weak to run or to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nichols, a Missouri Department of Conservation agent,
arrived as Tott was shooting down the limb. Together they
approached the eagle and placed a hunting vest over it to hold and
calm it. It was too weak to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a bald eagle tangled up in a tree before,''
Nichols said. ``I'd venture to say very few people have rescued a
bald eagle they found dangling from a wing.''
</P>
<P>
   An unusual twist of two limbs snagged the wing. Tott is saving
the limbs as a trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle would have died quickly from a lacerated wing,
dehydration and hypothermia, Del Pico said.
</P>
<P>
   Del Pico and his staff in Smithville treated the wing and began
force-feeding the eagle rainbow trout. At first the bird was bowed,
with few signs of pride.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next few days it became more active. A hunter
provided ducks for food, and the bird began to hold itself more
upright. Soon it was clucking and looking for an escape.
</P>
<P>
   So on Tuesday its rescuers and some onlookers gathered at a
parking lot near the Smithville Lake dam to release the bird.
</P>
<P>
   Del Pico lifted the towel from the white head. Wings thrashed
skyward, so the doctor set his patient free.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle promptly glided to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But wings flexed again, and in a creaky flight the eagle sailed
into the air and over a cove, scattering a flock of Canada geese.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it was over the main lake and climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, look at her go,'' Del Pico said. ``This is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Tott tracked the eagle through binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``Look at her climb. She's way up there
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
