<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES HELP ALMOST EVERYBODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's great inequality debate never lacks for serious
attention by those willing to ignore how statistics can be used to
support specious contentions.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst what's manifestly the most prosperous era in U.S.
history, some would have us believe Americans below the highest
income levels are worse off than they were a generation ago. Before
you buy into this pretext, however, ponder reality: Americans are
on track to spend about $6 trillion this year on personal
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there is substantial inequality if you measure such
concepts by the income gap between bosses and workers and the
amount of wealth controlled by the richest households. But to
equate such disparities with declining working-class fortunes is
pseudo-intellectual fatuousness.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite statistic in these circles shows the bottom fifth of
American families experiencing a small decline in real income over
the past two decades while the top fifth has enjoyed real-income
growth of nearly 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming accurate data, there are explanations that put this
development into economic perspective. One is that families at the
bottom of the ladder tend to be single-parent households much more
often than families at the higher levels. More household
bread-winners equal more income.
</P>
<P>
   When assessing real-income growth, those pursuing these studies
also should account for the damage done by rising payroll taxes.
These hit the first dollar earned and thus are especially
burdensome for low-wage workers. In 1979, the rate was only 6.13
percent on the first $22,900 of wages. Since 1990 the rate has been
7.65 percent, and this year's wage cap was $72,600 for Social
Security, with no limit on the Medicare portion. As a result of
these tax increases, more than three-quarters of taxpayers now pay
more in payroll taxes than income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the implication that those at the bottom live wretched
existences, some statistics provide strong mitigating arguments.
While life at the bottom may not be plush, even those below
government's officially decreed poverty line are not nearly as bad
off as the characterization suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Federal data show that some 40 percent own their own homes, 70
percent of poor households own cars (27 percent own two cars), 97
percent have a color television set (nearly 75 percent have a VCR),
two-thirds have air-conditioning, some 85 percent say their
families have enough to eat, and the average poor American has a
third more living space than the average Japanese and four times
more living space than the average Russian.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say some Americans don't have it rough. Like any
other human society, America has its share of serious material need
and want.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike any other society in history, however, America has
created a level of prosperity unmatched in human experience that
benefits most of society's members. Just because we aren't all
millionaires doesn't mean the system is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   This is merely the way the real world works. In 20th century
America, though, it has worked much better than it ever has before.
The holiday season is a much better time to count blessings than
bemoan cruel fates that often are either overstated or nonexistent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
