<SLUG> BC-NY-INJURY-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SAID TO SETTLE CAR-SEAT SUIT FOR $16 MILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to clean up lede graf)  By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family of a 7-year-old boy in Orange County, N.Y., who was
paralyzed after his car seat broke during an accident has settled a
lawsuit for nearly $16 million, their lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sum is believed to be the largest personal injury settlement
for a single plaintiff in state history, said the lawyer, Ed Souto
of Goshen, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The family of the boy, Jeremy Griffin, sued the manufacturer,
the Evenflo Co. of Vandalia, Ohio, after the seat broke during an
accident in which the car Jeremy was riding in collided head-on
with another on Sept. 30, 1993. Jeremy, who was seated in the rear
of the car, suffered spinal cord injuries when a harness broke on
the Ultara 1 model car seat. The boy was thrown head first against
the back of the front passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed in September 1996 in State Supreme
Court in Orange County, charged that Evenflo had failed to advise
consumers on the proper way to secure the seat and had known of
potential problems with the seat but did little to alert consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The back of the safety seat has three sets of slots through
which a shoulder harness may be routed. The bottom two slots are
not reinforced with metal, as they are designed for use with
infants and only when the seat is in the rear-facing position. A
problem arises, Souto said, when the safety seat is facing forward,
a position that requires the harness to be routed through the top
slots because they are the only ones reinforced with steel.
</P>
<P>
   The harness on Jeremy's seat had been routed through the middle
slots. The boy, who was a year and a half old at the time of the
accident, is paralyzed from the neck down.
</P>
<P>
   Souto said Evenflo did not recall the seat but altered the
design in later versions. A spokesman for the company could not be
reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Souto said the suit was settled for $15.7 million a few weeks
ago and the settlement was approved Dec. 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
