<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BELL-LONG-DISTANCE-1S     12-21 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-LONG-DISTANCE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC EXPECTED TO LET 1ST BABY BELL INTO LONG-DISTANCE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas, Mass., Pa., N.J., Okla., Ill., La., S.C.)  (SUBS to expand 1st three grafs into seven rewritten grafs,
including information on Mass., Pa. and N.J. Picks up original text
at `Even as the...' Adds New York dateline.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. TimesNews Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bell Atlantic oj Wednesday will become the first of
the Baby Bell local phone carriers allowed into the $80 billion
long-distance market, signaling a new era of competition in
telecommunications markets, people close to the decision said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the communications industry continues its torrid pace of
consolidation, the announcement expected Wednesday from the Federal
Communications Commission would allow Bell Atlantic, already the
No. 2 local phone company, to expand into a broad new market
covering long-distance services ranging from phone calls to
advanced data communications.
</P>
<P>
   Competition among the big long-distance carriers has decreased
in recent years, with MCI being acquired by Worldcom Inc. and with
the combined MCI Worldcom agreeing to acquire Sprint Corp. While
the announcement expected Wednesday would cover only New York
state, the approval could spearhead a broad invasion of the
long-distance business by other Bells, allowing consumers across
the country to buy local and long-distance services from the same
company.
</P>
<P>
   Approval would mark the first time since the breakup of AT&AMP;T 15
years ago that millions of consumers would be able to get both
local and long distance phone services from an offspring of Ma
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement expected Wednesday would allow Bell Atlantic to
sell long-distance services to the 6.6 million households it serves
in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Bell Atlantic said the company planned to
mount a big marketing campaign beginning the first week of January
to promote the company's long-distance service. The company intends
to offer long-distance calling plans with low per-minute rates but
without monthly fees, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has filed with Massachusetts regulators to offer
long-distance services in that state and could file a Massachusetts
application with the FCC within months. Executives close to Bell
Atlantic said Tuesday that the company expected to follow with
applications for Pennsylvania and then New Jersey, and that it
hoped to offer long-distance service in all three states by the end
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the communications business surges amid a flurry of
mergers, the explosive growth of the Internet and the
popularization of wireless phones, Bell Atlantic's long-distance
victory in New York would mark the beginning of a profound
reshaping of the industry's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, the FCC is expected to allow the Baby
Bells to enter the long-distance market in many states, presenting
AT&AMP;T as well as the other long-distance titans, MCI Worldcom Inc.
and Sprint Corp., which have agreed to merge, with powerful new
competitors who already enjoy relationships with tens of millions
of customers.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc., the largest local phone company, which
does business as Ameritech, Southwestern Bell and Pacific Bell, is
expected to ask the FCC as early as the first week of January for
approval to offer long distance in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bells and for regulators, Bell Atlantic's long-distance
approval in New York would mean the beginning of the end of a
regulatory system that emerged as the old American Telephone &AMP;
Telegraph shed its local Bell companies under court supervision in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, it would also represent a major success for the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, which Congress enacted largely to
break down regulatory barriers among communications sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dropping of the barrier keeping the local telephone
companies from the long-distance market is in fact the beginning of
the end of regulation,'' Reed Hundt, who resigned as chairman of
the FCC in 1997, said Tuesday in an interview. ``It's important,
the way that crossing the highest peak in any mountain range is
important. You're going down now, but you still have a long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the old AT&AMP;T agreed to spin off its local phone operations
as the seven Baby Bells in 1984, the Bells were prohibited from
selling long-distance services, which could have enabled them to
use their local monopolies to extend into a new market.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act, however, said that the Bells would
be allowed into the long-distance market on a state-by-state basis
as they persuaded the FCC that they had opened their local networks
to competitors. The Bells are required to sell access to parts of
their networks, notably the copper lines that run into homes,
because it would be next to impossible for any new local phone
company, no matter how well heeled, to fully replicate the systems
the Bells have spent decades building.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Bell local phone companies, like GTE, which has agreed to
merge with Bell Atlantic, and Southern New England
Telecommunications, which has been acquired by SBC, are also
required to sell access to their systems. But because those
companies were never part of AT&AMP;T, they have been allowed to sell
long-distance services without facing the tests the Bells must
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, no Bell has passed. New local phone companies and the
long-distance giants have consistently maintained that the Bells
have hindered their ability to sign up and serve local customers.
Under Hundt and his successor, William Kennard, the FCC has agreed
with that assessment, denying applications in Oklahoma, Illinois,
Louisiana and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic has appeared to go far beyond the other Bells
in taking the steps to open its network in New York. For at least
18 months, the New York Public Service Commission has pressed the
company to open its systems; the negotiations between the company
and the New York regulators delayed Bell Atlantic's federal
long-distance filing for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some legislators who passed the Telecommunications
Act, and even some who voted against it, have voiced impatience
with the FCC for what they see as the slow pace of results from the
act (aside from mergers). They have pressed the FCC to begin
allowing Bells into the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's long-distance aspirations took an unexpected
blow last month when the Justice Department, which has an advisory
role in the application process, said the company had not yet
completely opened its network. The Justice Department said the
commission could approve the application subject to conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to the process said Tuesday that it was not
likely that the commission would apply major conditions. Instead,
they said, the commission was poised to outline heavy fines that
would be imposed on Bell Atlantic were the company to slow or
reverse its progress in opening its systems.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman and FCC spokeswoman declined to
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said that Bell Atlantic's success in New York
could become a template for the other Bells. But Hundt, the former
FCC chairman, said Tuesday that New York could prove to be a
special case.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many consumers in New York may not be aware that
they have a choice of local phone provider, AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom
have recently begun to expand their push into the local phone
market in New York. Business customers in New York, especially in
New York City, already enjoy a wide range of options for local
communications.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Bell Atlantic has already paid much of the price
for opening its network. Other Bells in states where competitors
have not already made much progress may have less of an incentive
to open their systems, some analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as important, the long-distance market in New York is
especially lucrative because a large amount of the nation's
international communications begin or end in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear that the other Bells, or even Bell Atlantic
outside New York, will want to make the same effort,'' Hundt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the quick pace of consolidation, coupled with the
crumbling of regulatory barriers, may all but ensure that the
communications market of the future is dominated by a handful of
behemoths that compete across myriad markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will have been in everybody else's markets,'' Hundt
said, ``and competition will be self-policing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
