u a BC-NY-OFFICER-REINSTATED     12-21 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICER-REINSTATED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ORDERS A GUARD WHO FLEW THE NAZI FLAG REINSTATED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A corrections officer at a prison in upstate New York who was
suspended three years ago for flying a Nazi flag on his porch
should be reinstated with full back pay and benefits, the state's
top court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision, the state Court of Appeals in Albany
said that while the behavior of the prison guard, Edward M. Kuhnel,
43, was ``reprehensible,'' the state would have to abide by an
arbitrator's finding in Kuhnel's favor. State officials had agreed
to binding arbitration in the matter two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As abhorrent as Kuhnel's personal conduct is,'' Judge Richard
Wesley wrote for the court, ``judges cannot reject the factual
findings of an arbitrator simply because they do not agree with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhnel, who had worked as a state corrections officer for 18
years, was suspended on Dec. 12, 1996, from his job at the Eastern
Correctional Facility in Napanoch, a maximum-security prison, after
the Middletown Times Herald-Record published a photograph of the
swastika-emblazoned flag flying outside his home in Stone Ridge,
N.Y., about 60 miles south of Albany, said Richard Casagrande, his
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Kuhnel raised the flag on Dec. 10,
1996, the 55th anniversary of Hitler's declaration of war on the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhnel's union, the New York State Correctional Officers and
Police Benevolent Association, immediately contested his
suspension, Casagrande said. Based on the terms of the union's
contract with the state, the dispute was submitted to a binding
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, the arbitrator concluded that although Kuhnel's
behavior was not to be condoned, his off-duty conduct would not
disrupt his performance on the job and ordered that he be allowed
to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   State officials appealed the ruling in two lower courts in 1998
and earlier this year, although they paid Kuhnel his yearly salary
of $41,500 during the appeals process. The state contended that
Kuhnel had violated a regulation banning employees of the state
Department of Correctional Services from any behavior that would
reflect badly on the department and that his apparent neo-Nazi
leanings could incite racial problems in the prison. The state lost
in court both times; the appellate court upheld those rulings
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhnel, reached at his home Tuesday, would not discuss the
ruling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, said Tuesday
that the governor believed that it was ``absolutely absurd to allow
this type of hate-mongering in our prison system.'' McKeon added
that state officials would look into ``legislative and
administrative remedies,'' but refused to say what those remedies
might be.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner of corrections, Glenn S. Goord, will decide how
to reinstate Kuhnel after he reviews the court ruling, said James
B. Flateau, a spokesman for Goord. But Flateau added, ``The
arbitrator now carries the responsibility for ordering the
department to return an avowed Nazi to a position of authority in a
maximum security prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991221.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-INSIDER-TRADING-1STLD     12-21 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDER-TRADING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CHAIRMAN OF INVESTMENT BANK CHARGED WITH INSIDER TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change spelling of Marilyn to Marylin in 4th graf.) 
(mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER and PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last spring, in the midst of a boom year for
companies going public, the respected investment bank Keefe,
Bruyette &AMP; Woods abruptly scrubbed its plans for a stock offering _
and refused to say why.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the mystery was solved. Federal prosecutors in
Manhattan charged the firm's former chairman, James McDermott, with
insider trading in a bizarre case in which he was accused of
leaking information about potential billion-dollar bank deals to an
X-rated-movie actress he was dating.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 48, who lived in the world of sky-high Wall Street
salaries, is not accused of making any illegal profits himself. In
fact, all the suspected illegal profits were paltry indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The actress, Kathryn Gannon, was accused of illegally earning
$88,000 stemming from trades based on inside information provided
by McDermott about six bank mergers, all involving the firm's
clients. She was described by the government as an escort, exotic
dancer and actress in adult movies who uses the screen name Marylin
Star. The trades were made in 1997 and 1998, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gannon, 30, was also accused of passing information about
the deals to a New Jersey businessman, Anthony Pomponio, 45.
Pomponio was charged with making $86,000 in illegal trading
profits, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for someone of McDermott's generation, who lived
through the high-profile insider-trading cases of the '80s, to face
such a charge, said Thomas Newkirk, a high SEC official.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors revealed in the criminal complaint that Keefe,
Bruyette had canceled its offering in June after McDermott, who is
married, disclosed to its directors that a friend of his _ he did
not name Ms. Gannon at the time _ was under investigation by the
SEC for trading in stocks he had recommended to her.
</P>
<P>
   The offering was expected to raise $85 million, documents show,
and McDermott, whose salary was nearly $4 million, stood to
increase his stake to roughly $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott also resigned at the firm's request, and as part of
his severance agreement, both he and Keefe, Bruyette agreed not to
comment on his resignation, the complaint said. The firm said he
was leaving for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McDermott remained silent, entering no plea, as
federal Magistrate Judge Theodore Katz told him of his rights, and
ordered him released on $1 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, one of his lawyers, Denis McInerney, sharply
criticized the prosecution, saying that McDermott had been unaware
of the criminal investigation until Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McDermott is shocked by the government's action today,''
McInerney said. ``The government has never asked to speak to Mr.
McDermott, or reached out to his attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that the government chose to proceed in this fashion
without having the benefit of hearing from Mr. McDermott,''
McInerney continued. ``We will respond to the allegations in due
course, and are confident that Mr. McDermott will be exonerated
when the facts are known.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gannon, a resident of Miami, was believed to be in Canada,
where she is from, said the office of Mary Jo White, the U.S.
attorney in Manhattan. A warrant has been issued for her arrest.
Her lawyer did not respond to a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio, of North Caldwell, N.J., was released on $50,000 bond.
His lawyer, Thomas Dunn, said his client would plead not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint says that Pomponio told the SEC that Ms. Gannon
frequently boasted to him that ``she fraternized with individuals
who worked on Wall Street, and that her clientele included
high-powered investment bankers and lawyers on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said that McDermott's relationship with Ms.
Gannon lasted about 14 months, and that he had told her of six
upcoming deals. They involved Sun Trust, National Australia Bank,
Central Fidelity Banks, First Commerce, First Commercial and
California State Bank (West Covina).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gannon and Pomponio opened brokerage accounts, the
government said. She bought securities in advance of all the deals,
and he in five.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the complaint said, Ms. Gannon bought 1,800 shares
of the stock of Barnett Banks of Miami after she learned from
McDermott that Sun Trust was seeking to acquire it. A few days
later, on Aug. 29, 1997, Barnett stock surged 24 percent after it
was announced that it was being taken over by Nationsbank instead.
Ms. Gannon sold her Barnett stock for a profit of $30,400.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the investigation put an abrupt halt to Keefe,
Bruyette's ambitious plans, the new charges show.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, May 6, its executives and their investment bankers
were wrapping up plans to take the firm public. More than 4.7
million shares were scheduled to be priced the following Monday and
sold to investors before the market opened Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At a proposed price of about $18 a share, the offering would
have raised about $85 million for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But in a hastily called meeting that Thursday, McDermott told
the other directors that he had a personal problem that might
affect the offering. On Sunday, he told them more, the complaint
said, and the directors decided to cancel the offering.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that McDermott revealed that the SEC was
investigating stock trades made by a friend based on information he
had passed on. But, they contend, McDermott said that the
information was not confidential, and he described the profits the
friend had made as $20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever McDermott told the board that day was a closely guarded
secret for six months. Many people were curious about the unusual
last-minute cancellation and McDermott's subsequent resignation on
June 30 after 21 years at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the firm's other officials did nothing to squelch
speculation that the sale was withdrawn in favor of a plan to sell
the firm to another company.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Harry Keefe, one founder, knew why his former protege
left. Keefe, now in his 70s and long gone from Keefe, Bruyette,
said he hired McDermott as a bank-stock analyst and eventually
promoted him to director of research. Keefe said he helped make
McDermott one of the most-quoted bank analysts in the country by
insisting that only McDermott could field calls from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe said he found out about the charges when one trader at his
money-management firm read out a newswire headline that said
``Former CEO of Keefe Bruyette charged with insider trading.'' He
said he was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing more, he said: ``I'm heartbroken. My name's on the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation grew out of an SEC inquiry into trading of the
stock of Barnett Banks, said Newkirk, the SEC's associate director
of enforcement. The commission has already brought an enforcement
action against two young men who worked on Wall Street over their
trading of Barnett stock.
</P>
<P>
   That case reinforced the SEC's theory that the insider trading
of the 1990s was done by people too young to have learned the
lessons of the high-profile insider prosecutions of the 1980s. But
this case, Newkirk said, is an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody that was in this business in the 1980s should have
known better,'' he said of McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Newkirk said he found it ``shocking and dismaying'' that a chief
executive of an investment bank would get caught up in an
insider-trading case.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Keefe, Bruyette said, ``KBW has always
prided itself as having the highest ethical standards, and we have
long had strict policies in place regarding the handling of
confidential information.'' It went on to say, ``KBW has not been
charged with any wrongdoing and we are cooperating with the
authorities in their investigation of Mr. McDermott.''
</P>
<P>
   David Berry, a director, said that these events had not hurt the
firm's business. He said the firm has talked with other companies
that showed interest in buying Keefe, Bruyette but that no such
talks are going on now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might imagine when an IPO gets pulled, the phone does
ring,'' he said, but added, ``The firm is not trying to be sold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
