<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON CAUTIOUSLY OPTIMISTIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Extended winning streaks. A league-best record. An
MVP candidate. Dominance at home. Success on the road.
</P>
<P>
   To the world, the Los Angeles Lakers are looking a lot like NBA
championship material. Even now, in late December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not this week,'' coach Phil Jackson said of his team's
readiness to win a title. ``I think we've improved a lot, and I
think if we continue to improve in the next couple months, we're
going to be a pretty good team.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, they already are.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of seven-game winning streaks (with one loss sandwiched
in between) has given them a 22-5 record _ the Lakers' best start
since the 1985-86 team went 24-3. Through Monday's games, no other
NBA team had more than 18 wins.
</P>
<P>
   At this pace, the Lakers would win 67 games, and Shaquille
O'Neal would nearly be a shoo-in for MVP. A championship would be a
realistic expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a team that has that kind of ability,''
Jackson said. ``I'm still amazed at some players, like A.C. Green
and Rob Horry, doing a great job, kind of a tandem-team at the
(power forward), a spot where we're supposed to be weak. And we're
getting great performances out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm impressed with Glen Rice's every-night experience out
there. He has an occasional off night, but he's been great. And
Shaq and Kobe (Bryant) have been terrific, and we're finding a way
to make point guard with Harp (Ron Harper) and Fish (Derek Fisher)
work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a really good defensive team, simply because we
make teams shoot jumpshots, and we're cleaning up the boards.
Shaq's done a great job rebounding, and that's been a difference
for us. We're not giving up fast-break points a lot, except maybe
in turnover situations. That's been the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be really good later on. I don't know how good we can
be, but I think we're pretty stagnant at times.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they're not getting carried away with
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have any expectations, that's how were
playing,'' Bryant said. ``Our attitude is just taking it game by
game and that's all we're doing _ OK, we've got this game, knock it
down, then go into San Antonio, see if we can knock that down.
We're playing it one game at a time, that's all we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Down time: After playing four road games in five days and five
games in seven days, the Lakers get a bit of a break.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday, they go four days without a game before
playing the defending-champion Spurs on Christmas day at Staples
Center. They'll only practice every other day until then.
</P>
<P>
   After playing the Spurs, Dallas (Dec. 27) and Phoenix (Dec. 29),
all at Staples, the Lakers will get a five-day break. That means
they'll play just three games in a 14-day span. They won't travel
again until a Jan. 8 game at Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
