<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOBBY-BILL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AND ASSEMBLY DEMOCRATS COMPROMISE ON LOBBY LAW
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and the Democratic majority in
the state Assembly agreed Tuesday night on a measure to tighten the
state's lobbying law, forging an unusual alliance on an issue that
has put lawmakers on the defensive in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The measure features several new provisions, including a
requirement that lobbyists in counties and some municipalities
disclose their activities for the first time. But the two sides
declined to adopt major new restrictions on the gifts that
lawmakers can accept from lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The measure received a cool reception from the Republican
majority in the state Senate, whose members took a pledge last week
to refuse most gifts from lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also unanimously passed its own lobbying measure,
setting up a clash among the two houses and the governor that could
throw the regulation of lobbyists into disarray. The current law
expires at the end of the month. The propriety of accepting the
gifts has become a flash point in the talks over the lobbying law
because of reports about the extensive efforts by Philip Morris,
the cigarette giant, to win favor in the Legislature by treating
members to meals and other gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, lawmakers are prohibited from accepting gifts
of $75 or more if it can be reasonably inferred that the gifts were
intended to influence. The new measure would prohibit gifts of $75
or more, doing away with the need to determine intent.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between Pataki and the Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, represents a surprising turn of events because the
Republican governor typically works closely with the Senate
majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, an upstate Republican. But the
lobbying issue has created tensions between all three.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the provision regulating local lobbying, the
measure supported by the governor and Silver would give the state
lobbying commission the authority to conduct random audits of
lobbyists' records, increase penalties for violations of the law
and impore more disclosure requirements on lobbyists and clients.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would not require more reporting of lobbying of
state agencies, a move backed by Bruno but opposed by Pataki.
Pataki said in a statement that the measure represented ``real
reform that will build public confidence in our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said it would ``help restore the public's trust in
government.'' After the measure was announced, Bruno declined to
comment on its content, other than to say that the Senate would not
act on it at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner, an expert on the lobbying law and legislative
director for the New York Public Interest Research Group, called
the measure inadequate. ``The bad news is the stunning absence of
any agency lobbying and a gift ban,'' Horner said. ``We're shocked
that the Assembly refuses to give up the goodies from lobbyists,
and we can't understand why the governor doesn't want the public to
know who's lobbying the state agencies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The leaders of both houses had planned to renew the current weak
lobbying law without any changes, but they were pressured into
strengthening the law by the disclosures about Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   In July, The New York Times reported that a lobbyist for Philip
Morris had spent hundreds of thousands of dollars on gifts, like
expensive meals and theater tickets, for at least 115 current and
former legislators. The lobbyist, Sharon T. Portnoy, had failed to
report much of that spending to the lobbying commission, in
violation of state law. Philip Morris later agreed to pay a $75,000
fine, the largest in the commission's history, and Ms. Portnoy paid
a $15,000 fine and was banned from lobbying in New York for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was the first to respond with a plan, proposing a ban on
gifts worth more than $25, though with several exceptions and a
rule generally prohibiting lawmakers from accepting meals from
lobbyists. His plan also would have extended the disclosure rules
to lobbying of state agencies for contracts, an area of vast
expenditure that is now beyond public scrutiny, and to lobbying of
local governments.
</P>
<P>
   When Democrats questioned Bruno's sincerity in proposing his
bill, which Silver rejected outright, Bruno said the Senate
Republicans would voluntarily abide by its provisions, and even
make them the official rules of the chamber. The Senate Democrats
quickly followed suit, increasing the pressure on Silver and the
Assembly to take action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
