<SLUG> BC-DEAD-YALE-STUDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FOUL PLAY SEEN IN DEATH OF YALE SENIOR FOUND IN RIVER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Conn.)   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The death of a Yale University senior whose body was
found in the Harlem River last month was not the result of foul
play, university officials and the New Haven, Conn., police said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Norris, 21, an economics major from Omaha, disappeared
from the New Haven campus midway through the fall semester. After a
fruitless search in Connecticut, the authorities retrieved his body
on Nov. 16 on the Bronx shoreline. He was identified late last week
with dental X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case was being handled as a missing-person case, and now
that he has been identified it will be closed out,'' said Douglas
P. MacDonald, assistant chief of the New Haven Police Department.
``It is not being handled as a criminal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris was last seen on Oct. 31. Railroad workers in New Haven
reported early that morning that he was acting strangely in a train
station. They called the New Haven police, who arrived and found
him on the platform, apparently under the influence of either drugs
or alcohol, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers coaxed him into an ambulance that took him to
Yale-New Haven Hospital. He was treated in the emergency room and
checked himself out, said Kenneth Best, a spokesman for the
hospital. Best declined to elaborate on Norris' care.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Norris' family became concerned and notified the
university. ``His parents reported him missing when they couldn't
contact him,'' said Thomas P. Conroy, a Yale University spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In early November, the police searched in New Haven and at Yale,
interviewing students and faculty members. On Nov. 11, The Yale
Daily News, the campus newspaper, reported that Norris had left two
letters _ one for his ister, one for his parents _ in his
university suite before he disappeared. The contents of the letters
have not been publicly disclosed, and Norris' mother declined to
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   How and why Norris traveled to New York remained unknown
Tuesday. The police said only that his body was spotted by a
Metropolitan Transportation Authority foreman in mid-November and
retrieved from the river by the crew of a police harbor patrol
vessel. It remained unidentified in a city morgue for weeks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an open letter to the Yale student body on Monday, Richard H.
Brodhead, dean of Yale College, wrote that Norris' body had been
found. ``This is a grievous loss to our community,'' he wrote.
``I'm sure that you join me in extending our love and prayers to
Greg's family at this painful time.'' Although the New York medical
examiner's office said Tuesday that it had not determined the cause
of Norris' death, Brodhead's letter said that the ``police report
that there were no signs of foul play.''  &QL; 
ll
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
