<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-MAINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BEATS MAINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAIE, Hawaii _ The UCLA Bruins debuted Tuesday on Oahu's famed
North Shore, home of Sunset Beach and the Banzai Pipeline, and they
brought along a slew of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Barnes, rescued from academic suspension at the
last minute, made his first appearance of the season. Earl Watson
actually played like a point guard, passing first and shooting
second, and the Bruins unveiled dark blue, road-only uniforms with
a snazzy script ``UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise of all was their inspired play.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the opponent is Santa Clara or Vanderbilt, whether the
place is Maui or Anchorage, UCLA has a history of lethargic
performances in these early-season tournaments. (It hasn't won one
since the 1990 Great Alaska Shootout.)
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 18 Bruins were in fine form Tuesday, running and
dunking and overpowering Maine with a 83-62 victory in the first
round of the Pearl Harbor Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Steve Lavin) told us that UCLA has gone to tournaments
in Maui and Alaska and Puerto Rico and not played well,'' Bruins
forward Rico Hines said. ``We've been lackadaisical in the past,
and our junior class has never won a tournament. We stressed all
week that we had to come here and execute on offense and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins broke the game open with a 33-7 surge midway through
the first half. Reserve guard Ryan Bailey was the catalyst, just as
he was against DePaul. He checked in with UCLA trailing 12-10 and
immediately found Watson on an alley-oop. Ten minutes later, UCLA's
margin was 41-19.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bailey) gave us a real lift in the first half,'' Lavin said.
``I told him I would have gotten him more minutes (he played 17),
but with a comfortable lead I didn't want to push it with his
(tendonitis).''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey joined Watson and Ray Young to give the Bruins a
three-guard attack. They pressed and trapped and unleashed the fast
break. The Black Bears happily complied by shooting quick and
playing fast _ a style custom-made for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely today's opponent, Colorado State, will let the
Bruins play at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally took us out of anything we wanted to do with our
offensive structure,'' said Maine coach John Giannini, whose team
shot 32.1 percent in the first half. ``It was very difficult to run
our offense. I couldn't have been more impressed with their defense
in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half was another matter. With a 20-point lead, the
Bruins got sloppy. Their shooting deteriorated and their defense
wilted as Maine shot 55.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happened against Gonzaga,'' Lavin said. ``We're
trying to avoid that and get them to play with sustained intensity
for 40 minutes. We just lost concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   The sloppy second half failed to overshadow several impressive
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Maine power forward Nate Fox, who plays like Stanford's Mark
Madsen but looks like Steve Forbes, led all scorers with 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA forward Jason Kapono, who's one-fourth Hawaiian, made 3 of
4 shots from 3-point range and once again played a deft floor game.
When he's not on the court, it's noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Big men Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric dominated the smaller
Black Bears, combining for 29 points and 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes had eight points and a career-high 10 rebounds in 10
minutes, although his rebound total is debatable. (The local
statisticians, overwhelmed by the pace, initially credited Kapono
with 21 minutes played in the first half.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt exceeded my expectations in terms of how quickly he
appeared comfortable at both ends of the floor,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's makeover was remarkable. After poor decision-making and
horrendous shooting (4 of 24) against Gonzaga and DePaul, he
finally played like a point guard. The tempo probably helped _
Watson's always more comfortable in chaos _ and perhaps Bailey's
pass-first approach is resonating.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Watson did not attempt a shot until 3:44
remained in the first half, and he finished with 10 assists and two
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked in general terms about wanting to move the ball
quicker,'' Lavin said. ``As the point guard, Earl understands it
begins with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Watson does it against a disciplined team like Colorado
State _ not to mention Arizona and Stanford _ remains to be seen.
But for one balmy afternoon on the North Shore, the Bruins had
reason to smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
