<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-21 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RAPE-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      12-21 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RAPE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-STUDENT TO GET NEW TRIAL IN INTERNET SEX-ASSAULT CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An appellate court Tuesday ordered a new trial for a
Columbia University graduate student who was convicted in 1998 of
kidnapping, torturing and sexually abusing a Barnard College
student he had met over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the trial judge had wrongly invoked the state's
rape shield law to bar explicit e-mail messages the woman wrote to
the man before they met.
</P>
<P>
   The former doctoral student, Oliver Jovanovic, 32, has always
maintained that his encounter with the woman, then 20, was
consensual. He has served 20 months of a 15-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, who could appeal the decision to the state's
highest court, the State Court of Appeals, declined to comment on
the ruling Tuesday. It was unclear whether Jovanovic's accuser, who
spent six days on the witness stand in the trial, would be willing
to testify again. Legal experts said they had not yet had time to
review the decision and could not say what effect it would have on
the use of the shield law in other rape cases.
</P>
<P>
   Enacted in 1975, the law was intended to encourage rape victims
to come forward by restricting which aspects of their sexual
history could be made public by defense lawyers in a trial. For
example, the law states that evidence of an extramarital affair is
irrelevant at a rape trial. But other sexual conduct, such as a
prior sexual relationship between the accuser and the accused, can
be presented to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Judge David B. Saxe of the State
Supreme Court harshly criticized Justice William A. Wetzel's
decision to use the law to prevent the jury from seeing four e-mail
messages the woman sent to Jovanovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the highly intimate nature of some of this
information,'' Saxe wrote, ``the statements, as a practical matter,
should be viewed as the equivalent of `prior sexual conduct with
the accused.'''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was not meant to undermine the rape shield law, the
ruling said. But in a dissenting opinion, Judge Angela M.
Mazzarelli warned that the ruling would make it easier for defense
lawyers to sully the reputations of rape victims. He said the
ruling ``would only serve to turn the clock back to the days when
the main defense to any such charge was to malign the
complainant.''
</P>
<P>
   But the majority held that Jovanovic's trial had been unfair.
Saxe said the trial judge's failure to admit the e-mail messages as
evidence or to allow defense lawyers to ask the young woman about
sadomasochistic relationships she may have had, had an ``enormous''
impact on Jovanovic's ability to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling included the e-mail messages; in one, sent two
days before the attack, the woman wrote Jovanovic that she was
dating a sadomasochist. ``Now I'm his slave,'' she wrote, ``and
it's painful, but the fun of telling my friends `Hey, I'm a
sadomasochist' more than outweighs the torment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent e-mail, the woman responded affirmatively to a
question from Jovanovic about whether she was ``submissive.'' In
another, she used the slang term for a submissive partner in a
sadomasochistic relationship to describe herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the case stood, Jovanovic was precluded not only from
bringing out the degree to which the complainant seemed to be
inviting sadomasochism,'' the judge wrote, but from exploring the
possibility that she was ``a less-reliable narrator of events than
she appeared to be at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends of Jovanovic's, who have lobbied for a
reversal of his conviction, hailed the ruling as long overdue
justice. Sabina Jovanovic, his mother, said she had spoken with her
son Tuesday and hoped to have him home for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very much relieved, just relieved and happy that this
one stage is over,'' she said. ``It's been a trip to hell and
back.'' The case stirred debate about the safety of anonymous
meetings over the Internet. According to his accuser, Jovanovic
lured the woman on a date after an extended e-mail correspondence,
tied her to a futon in his Washington Heights apartment, and
tortured her for more than 20 hours. The woman said Jovanovic had
threatened to kill her, bit her until she bled, burned her with wax
and beat her with a stick. But Jack Litman, a defense lawyer,
accused her of making up a story about what was a consensual sexual
encounter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
