<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD NETS RESURFACE AGAINST TORONTO, SELFISH AND SOFT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Stephon Marbury was shaking his head as the horn
welcomed him back into what had ceased being a game, oh, about five
minutes after it started.
</P>
<P>
   Was he upset that Coach Don Casey had kept him out of action
from the end of the first quarter until there was only 4 minutes 23
seconds left in the first half of the Nets' 116-87 thrashing at the
hands of the Toronto Raptors? Or was he bothered that he had to go
back in to play what amounted to 28 minutes of garbage time, with
the Nets trailing by 24 points?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear; it didn't matter. After a stretch of decent
play against some lesser lights, the old Nets, the selfish, soft
ones, were back with a vengeance in Toronto Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played terrible tonight,'' a frustrated Marbury said
afterward. ``There's no excuse for tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he surprised that the ugly Nets had reared their heads again
after their recent run of six victories in eight starts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only won eight games,'' he said. ``We didn't win 15 in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury did not sound surprised at all by the turn of events.
``We beat teams coming off four games in five nights, teams that
were struggling,'' he said. ``We haven't beat a contender yet. We
haven't established ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly not. The Nets may be concerned that any of their good
work may have been undone. Casey had cause to keep Marbury, his
mercurial everything guard, on the sidelines for an extended
first-half rest. By the time Marbury had checked but in the first
place, the Nets were trailing by 43-24, their worst defensive
effort for one quarter this season.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Marbury had played out the second quarter, they were
down by 75-45 and had allowed the Raptors their best offensive
output for a half this season.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto (14-11) shot a stunning 65.2 percent for the half and
connected on four of five from beyond the 3-point line. Toronto's
Vince Carter had 24 points to lead all scorers, and Doug Christie
chipped in with 20 in only 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened to us,'' Casey said. ``But I know
they had a lot to do with it. They were in such a comfort zone,
they had a nice flow and a nice rhythm and we couldn't do anything
to disrupt it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' misery was shared across the box score. While Johnny
Newman managed 22 points off the bench, providing a brief spark,
and Jamie Feick continued his determined play, notching 12 points
and 12 rebounds, 6 of them on the offensive glass, the team
statistics were grim.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McIlvaine, the Nets' starting center, had to leave the game
after a collision with Carter's elbow early in the first quarter.
He was found to have a mild concussion and taken to Toronto Western
Hospital for observation, although it was not considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the lucky one,'' Casey said. ``He didn't have to watch
the massacre.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
