</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITHOUT HASEK, SABRES NO MATCH FOR PUNCHLESS RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the past, the Rangers could have blamed their
inability to defeat Buffalo on Dominik Hasek. Tuesday night the
Sabres demonstrated that it does not matter who protects their
goal.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12th consecutive time over three-plus seasons, the
Rangers proved no match for the younger, faster Sabres, who carved
out a convincing 3-1 victory at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie goaltender Martin Biron dominated this game from the
beginning of the second period to the end, making 28 saves. He was
helped by Curtis Brown's power-play goal midway through the second,
Miroslav Satan's tally at 7 minutes 8 seconds of the third period
and Dixon Ward's short-handed deflection two and a half minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo is 8-0-4 in its last 12 games against the Rangers and
5-0-2 in its last seven at the Garden. The Rangers have not
defeated the Sabres at home since Oct. 27, 1996, and they have not
beaten Buffalo at all since Dec. 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could not pick up any ground on the Sabres or the
rest of the Eastern Conference, mustering only Mike Knuble's
power-play goal with 5:35 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo, which has struggled this season in defending its
conference crown, was playing without Hasek, out indefinitely with
a severe groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that his team was losing control of the game, Rangers
Coach John Muckler used his only timeout 3:49 into the second
period. At the time, the game was scoreless and the move seemed
curious. But Muckler's feeling was correct; the momentum had
shifted to Buffalo. But no matter how loudly Muckler yelled at his
players during the timeout, the Sabres kept control all period
long.
</P>
<P>
   They outshot the Rangers by 14-6 in the second and scored the
game's first goal 12:08 into the period. It belonged to Brown and
came from the Sabres' power play that has been even more
ineffective than the Rangers'. Buffalo came into the game with the
worst unit in the National Hockey League, scoring at a rate of only
8.8 percent. The Sabres were 0 for their last 31, 1 for the last 47
and had not scored a power-play goal in their last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were already 0 for 2 Tuesday night when Jason Woolley
tossed a wrist shot on net from the right point with Mathieu
Schneider in the penalty box for holding the talented rookie right
wing Maksim Afinogenov. The penalty was the third whistled on
Schneider; the other two had negated Rangers power plays.
</P>
<P>
   This time, all Schneider could do was watch from the box as
Brown chopped at the puck just in front of Mike Richter's catching
glove. Brown's timing was perfect. He had eased himself behind Rich
Pilon, right in front of the goal mouth. Brown then deflected the
puck perfectly, straight down, right through Richter's legs. The
goal withstood a video replay to see if Brown's stick had been too
high when he touched the puck.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, and Buffalo led, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   That was the score after two periods. It easily could have been
1-1. But with the teams skating 4-on-4 midway through the first
period, Alexandre Daigle missed an open net after he had pounced on
a loose puck in the offensive zone. After Daigle deked Biron out of
position, he should have had a gimme. Instead, Daigle's uncontested
backhand from low in the slot went wide left. And the Rangers had
missed out on a golden chance at a goal.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was fairly even (Buffalo 11 had shots, the
Rangers 10) but in the second Buffalo had a decided advantage. The
score would have been far worse than 1-0 if not for the play of
Richter, who had 24 saves; the right post, which stopped a Brian
Campbell shot; and Pilon, who made a head-first save of a Satan
shot at the left post with Richter on his back and out of position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
