</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-ARREST-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED TERRORIST IS LINKED TO RADICAL ISLAMIC GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Subs for new 5th graf) (See also TERROR-BORDER) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11 are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 The following story was reported by Craig Pyes, John Kifner, John
F. Burns and Sam Howe Verhovek, and was written by Burns  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When U.S. customs officials arrested Ahmed Ressam near Seattle
last week after he came off a ferry from Canada in a car they say
was loaded with jars of nitroglycerine, timing devices and other
bomb-making materials, American intelligence officials knew little
about him.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrest set off alarms in France, where anti-terrorist
officials had been focusing on the 32-year-old Ressam because of
his connections to a radical Islamic group that French
investigators suspect had carried out in 1996 a series of attacks
on supermarkets, armored security vehicles and banks in northern
France.
</P>
<P>
   French officials declined to provide specifics and did not
suggest that Ressam himself was involved in those attacks, but one
senior French law enforcement official said that Ressam had links
to Fateh Kamel, an Algerian veteran of the Afghan war. The French
have implicated Kamel in the 1996 attacks, which left several
bystanders and several Islamic radicals dead and netted a cache of
high-powered weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the French identified Said Atmani, an
Algerian with a Bosnian passport who once roomed with Ressam in a
Montreal apartment, as another figure with links to Kamel. French
officials said they sent a delegation to Canada in October to
interview Atmani and Ressam, but neither man could be located.
</P>
<P>
   A French anti-terrorist official said that they briefed Canadian
and American officials about their interest in Ressam, including
his possible links to the financing of Islamic terror activities in
Europe and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Much about Ressam remains unknown as officials in three
countries trace his movements in an effort to learn what he planned
to do with the explosives he was accused of bringing into the
United States. But from interviews and a review of public records
in Canada, a picture is emerging of a man who moved easily from
country to country with falsified passports.
</P>
<P>
   At the modest, $85 per night hotel where he lived for two weeks
in Vancouver, British Columbia, workers recalled that he was
traveling with another man, who was lighter in complexion and spoke
English with no discernible accent.
</P>
<P>
   American officials now say they have unconfirmed intelligence
reports that Ressam had been seen in training camps used in the
1980s by Islamic militants fighting the Soviets in Afghanistan.
Ressam told Canadian authorities that he had been falsely accused
in Algeria of being an Islamic radical, and tortured, according to
immigration records.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials acknowledged on Tuesday that Ressam had taken
advantage of lax procedures and loose cooperation between the
police and immigration authorities to obtain his false papers.
Reviewing the case, one Montreal police investigator, Claude
Paquette, this week said that the loose rules had turned Canada
into ``a Club Med for terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's investigation into the affair has established, among
other things, that Ressam arrived in the country in 1994 with a
fake French passport in an assumed name. Later, after being ordered
arrested and deported, he went underground and obtained a Canadian
passport in a false name using only a Roman Catholic baptism
certificate, a procedure said to be common in Quebec. When arrested
in Seattle, Ressam was carrying a Canadian passport in the assumed
name of Benni Antoine Norris.
</P>
<P>
   The group to which French investigators have linked Ressam is
part of a new trend in Islamic radicalism in which small, loosely
linked bands of militants collaborate in attacks on Western
targets, often financing themselves by what the French call
``gangster-terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking French official who outlined what he called
``the globalization of Islamist terror'' said there were probably
20 to 50 Islamic groups that have planned or carried out terrorist
attacks worldwide in countries like Canada, France, Belgium,
Turkey, Malaysia and Australia, as well a dozen or more other
nations. Few of these groups, he said, belonged to a coherent
terrorist network, although many maintained loose links with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   What most of these groups have in common, French and American
officials say, is a heritage from the Islamic ``holy war'' against
Soviet troops in Afghanistan in the 1980s, when thousands of young
Muslims from across Europe, the Middle East and Asia were
indoctrinated with a militant brand of Islam, and trained in
weapons techniques and bomb-making.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Islamic terror groups are not centrally directed,
anti-terrorist officials in the United States and other Western
countries say they are linked by many things, including their
fiercely anti-Western system of Islamic beliefs and common
experiences and operating procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the leaders fought, or at least were trained, in
Afghanistan. Most see the United States, with its secular political
tradition, its military and economic power, and its backing for
Israel, as the prime target for terrorist attacks. Many radicals
use false passports, and work from the same terror-training
manuals, some of them adapted from CIA-supplied training materials
used in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are examining whether Ressam is linked to the most
notorious figure to emerge from that war, Osama Bin Laden, the
wealthy 42-year-old Saudi Arabian exile who lives in hiding in
Afghanistan. American authorities have identified Bin Laden as the
mastermind of the August 1998 bomb attacks on American embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania in which 220 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   One American official said there were reports that Ressam had
met with several people in Canada tied to Bin Laden. It was unclear
what significance, if any, these contacts had. French officials
have concentrated their recent investigations on Kamel, whom they
described as ``important in the world of Islamic terrorists'' and
as a frequent traveler to Bosnia, Syria, Turkey, Saudi Arabia and
Jordan among other places.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan on Tuesday, a high-ranking official of the Taliban,
the militant Islamic group that rules most of Afghanistan, scoffed
at American suggestions that Bin Laden may have continued to play a
role in terror attacks since the embassy bombings, which prompted
the FBI to place Bin Laden on its Ten Most Wanted list and post a
$5 million reward for information leading to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bin Laden doesn't even have access to a telephone or a fax,''
Sayed Mohammed Haqqani, the Taliban ambassador to Pakistan, told a
news conference.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rassem arrived in Canada's Mirabel Airport on February 20, 1994,
and claimed he was fleeing a government that had unjustly accused
him of arms smuggling and Islamic radicalism.
</P>
<P>
   His French passport bore the name of Tahar Medjadi, but he
readily admitted to authorities that the document and his birth
certificate were fake. He asked for refugee status and asylum.
</P>
<P>
   On his application form he stated the Algerian military
`'considered me to be nothing but an Islamic terrorist, even though
I have no connection to Islamic movements.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was tortured with rags, soap, ladders and a desk
drawer, made to sign false confessions, and held in administrative
detention for 15 months. After two years of legal wrangling,
Canadian officials rejected his claim for refugee status, and
ordered him deported.
</P>
<P>
   But at the time, his lawyer Dennis Buron said, the government
had a policy of not deporting anybody to Algeria because of the
harsh battles there between Islamic insurgents and the military
rulers. So he remained in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Charbonneau, a Canadian Immigration spokeswoman, said
that there was no grounds to hold Rassem. ``At that time, we had no
proof that he was linked to any terrorist group. If we had proof,
we would have kept him in detention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rassem then slipped from official view, living under two false
names, Benni Antoine Noris, and Mario Roig.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb 8, 1998, an arrest warrant was issued for Ressam, for
allegedly stealing a computer from a parked car. He served two
weeks in jail.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, a deportation order was issued for
Rassem, apparently on the basis of three outstanding criminal
arrest warrants, two for theft from cars, and one for breaking and
entering. In May 1998, a nationwide immigration warrent was issued
for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, last February Rassem sought and obtained a
government-issued Canadian passport in the false name of Benni
Antoine Noris. Even though he had been fingerprinted during his
refugee application, there was apparently no cross check with
police, immigration or intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Those fingerprints remained on file. And when Ressam was
arrested last week crossing the border into Washington, American
authorities lifted his prints and learned his true identity.
</P>
<P>
   France's interest in Ressam appears to have been prompted by the
arrest in Jordan this spring of Kamel, the Algerian-born Afghan
veteran who has been linked by French investigators to the group
that carried out a series of attacks in the Northern French city of
Roubaix.
</P>
<P>
   French anti-terrorist officials have said that they have
established that Kamel provided ``religious leadership'' to Islamic
groups, in France that carried out the robberies, which terrorized
the French city for three months in early 1996. In one attack, the
Islamic radicals shot dead a French Muslim who was slow in handing
over the keys to his Mercedes after the gang had bungled a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   According to the French investigation, the robberies netted the
gang only about 70,000 francs, a little more than $10,000, money
that the French say was used to finance the activities of the
Islamic groups Kamel is said to have led.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery spree ended with a shootout in the Roubaix suburb of
Alma in March 1996, in the course of which four gang members were
killed, two after fleeing across the border into Belgium. It is not
clear what direct evidence, if any, exists linking Kamel to the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest this year, Jordan extradited him to France and
Kamel has been held ever since under a French law providing for the
detention of suspects under investigation for alleged involvement
in a ``terrorist enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, following leads that arose from the Roubaix inquiry,
French anti-terrorist officials visited Canada, where they hoped to
question Ressam and Atmani, his former roommate in Montreal. A
French law enforcement official described both as ``lieutenants''
of Kamel in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians were unable to locate either man. Atmani had been
deported to Bosnia, where he had previously obtained his own
passport. Ressam had assumed his new identity and was living
underground.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian investigators did turn up evidence suggesting that the
Islamic groups with which Ressam and Atmani may have been
associated, in Montreal, were practicing their own, less violent
version of ``gangster-terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Canadians, police in Montreal arrested 11
Muslim men this fall on suspicion of stealing laptop computers and
cellphones from parked cars, and selling them in front of the
city's mosques.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ressam's arrest, the Canadians have said that they believe
the proceeds were funneled to Algerian-based Islamic groups,
including the Armed Islamic Group, a guerrilla organization that
has been responsible for many of the 100,000 deaths in the Algerian
civil war that began in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
