<SLUG> BC-BOMB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE YOU READY FOR Y2-CHAOS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - President Franklin Roosevelt once famously
proclaimed, ``The only thing we have to fear is fear itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he hadn't encountered the Great Millennium Scourge.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorist threats, power outages, apocalyptic cults, computer
glitches, solar sunspots - it's as if Steven King churned out a
horror novel while high on crank.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, persons unknown stole a bunch of explosives near
Flagstaff. And an Algerian man was arrested with bomb ingredients
at the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in drunken drivers and celebratory New Year's bullets
falling from Phoenix area skies, and it presages the worst
catastrophe since biblical plagues.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that common citizens have pegged this 2000 scare
as a futuristic version of the Chicken Little fable.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an Internet chat room for millennium stress is
empty.
</P>
<P>
   Operators at Phoenix's Community Information &AMP; Referral Hotline
have yet to hear from any Y2K panic victims.
</P>
<P>
   And Phoenix psychotherapist Carol Bettina says she has yet to
see a patient suffering from Y2K anxiety, despite an onslaught of
media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan ``Sully'' Sullivan, a 22-year-old Mesa writer, chuckles at
the sky-is-falling scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like how some people are a little freaked out about it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His emergency plans?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to store up on cigarettes and beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Macias, 36, of Phoenix, is convinced that the New Year
will bring more hysteria than havoc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets hyped out of proportion,'' Macias said. ``It seems
like people enjoy getting scared of things. I always wish the
doomsayers would look back on their record in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even have a bunker,'' said Debbie Haggarton, 31, a
Chandler homemaker. ``I haven't given it a second thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, city Y2K guru Gordon Cresswell said folks should,
at the most, plan for inconvenience similar to that during a major
storm. Still, the city announced this week that it will have 18
emergency communications centers ``should any unforeseen problems
occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Cresswell is so confident that none will, however, that he
hasn't so much as stocked up on canned food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done anything,'' he said. ``I'm not going to do
anything, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 11 people interviewed, not one was planning a suicide flight
to Hale-Bopp.
</P>
<P>
   Most denied having any trepidation about Y2K. They said dire
predictions will end up like Phoenix's New Year's bash: lots of
fizzle, no bang.
</P>
<P>
   Cinque, a 22-year-old Phoenix resident who uses one name, was
the lone alarmist.
</P>
<P>
   After reading about potential calamities, he decided the
millennium might fit a historical pattern: Every great empire
collapses eventually, and it could be America's turn. So Cinque has
stocked up on bottled water and canned food, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared,'' he noted confidently.
</P>
<P>
   That also seems to be the mantra of public and private officials
responsible for averting millennial chaos: They don't think
anything really bad will happen, but they're ready.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Susan Herskovits said the bureau has ``contingencies
in place that I can't talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely feel prepared,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Mike DeBenedetto, the Phoenix Police Department's emergency
planning coordinator, said ``millennium paranoia'' has actually
been good for public and private security.
</P>
<P>
   He said leave has been canceled for peace officers from next
Monday, Dec. 27 to Jan. 7. Even if Jan. 1 meets expectations as the
``biggest 911 night in Phoenix history'' DeBenedetto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very confident, and probably have never been more
confident, in our ability to provide public safety,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   At Sky Harbor International Airport, Sgt. Gerry ``Odis''
Brockman said Phoenix police already have gone on heightened alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be foolish not to at this time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That means that extra officers will patrol airport terminals
with bomb-sniffing dogs and that the ban on curbside parking will
be strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Aurelius, Phoenix's emergency operations coordinator,
said four years of preparation will be tested in the first few
hours of 2000. Contingency plans have been devised ``just in case
something goofy happens'' with water delivery systems, public
sewers, aviation equipment and emergency equipment that depend on
computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities and public utilities offered similar assurances.
</P>
<P>
   At Arizona Public Service, officials said that electrical output
and the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Plant are ready for the
changeover. Company spokesman Will Diaz said APS already passed a
pair of Y2K tests, adding that up to 500 employees will be at
substations around the state on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas B. Nixon, chief deputy with the U.S. Marshal's Office in
Arizona, said he couldn't discuss heightened security around the
federal courthouse but said that it's there.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Andy Vidaure, a DPS spokesman, said his agency will run
an emergency operations center from Dec. 27 until Jan. 3 to deal
with trouble arising with the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Vidaure said the Highway Patrol will assist local police
agencies on DUI task forces and will work to keep traffic flowing
after New Year's Eve parties in Tempe and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Sheriff Joe Arpaio said his deputies will pay special
attention to the Palo Verde plant while he offers free rides to New
Year's revelers who are too drunk to drive; they should call (602)
256-1661.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said his SWAT team will be on standby - with a tank.
</P>
<P>
   If such assurances don't calm millennial palpitations, help is
available on the World Wide Web (www.1-800-therapist.com/Y2K) or by
dialing 1-800-843-7274.
</P>
<P>
   If, that is, the computer and phone systems don't crash. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at &QL; 
dennis.wagner(at)arizonarepublic.com &QL; 
or at (602) 444-8874. &QL; 
Alexa Haussler contributed to this article. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-99 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
